          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Acidic yellow",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sharp cobalt",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Kelly green",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Chalky blue",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the beige-out: every piece at the same pale value looks unfinished rather than minimal",
          "fix": "rescue it with a graphite anchor piece or a bottle green accent, and let one texture change restore the depth"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let sharp edges lead your weekday choices. A stark navy worsted wool blazer provides the strict boundary required for a corporate setting. Your supporting elements do the subtle work. Exact cuts in an icy grey cotton poplin shirt build the foundation, while a single cool silver tie clip acts as your anchoring focal point. Remember that even a morning farmers' market run is a distinct occasion requiring exactness. A technical nylon trench over fine ribbed merino ensures you uphold your standards when buying produce. Keep your presentation entirely self-contained. Look for collars that stand crisp and trousers that hold a severe front crease. If an item collapses into a shapeless pile when you drop it on a desk, leave it at home.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the exact requirements of your working environment.",
      "tests": [
        "a farmers' market run is still a small occasion (Hearth)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In low light, let sharp edges lead. Dim venues obscure flat planes. Rely on stiff collars and crisp cuffs in stark navy poplin to carve out your silhouette. Avoid soft sweaters that blur your outline in the shadows. Keep your metals cool and highly polished. A white gold watch case or a sterling silver tie bar catches minimal light and turns it into clear intent. Treat a quick evening drink with the exact same strictness. A late meeting at a cafe remains a defined event requiring structure. Zip into a technical nylon shell over icy grey fine ribbed merino. Skip the relaxed fleece. Look in the mirror and check the neckline. If the collar sags, discard the knit. Strict lines must hold, even across a tiny table.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master low-light settings and small venues by applying strict visual discipline.",
      "tests": [
        "a farmers' market run is still a small occasion (Hearth)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Buying milk at the corner shop does not suspend your standard. An afternoon errand remains a discrete occasion requiring form. Reach for crisp cotton poplin rather than a soft jersey sweatshirt. Anchor every task in clean geometry + sharp edges + one polished signal. Keep the palette cool by relying entirely on stark navy and icy grey. Check the fall of your worsted wool pants. Lift the hem and observe the drop. If the fabric pools or loses its shape, discard it. Finish the look with a silver watch or a steel belt buckle. Require a matt surface on your main garments to let that single metal detail stand out. You do not need loud additions to stay self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Approach your everyday garments with absolute mechanical precision.",
      "tests": [
        "a farmers' market run is still a small occasion (Hearth)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Establish a cool baseline using {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Assess every zip, clasp, and watch by picking the item up. A bright surface can deceive the eye, but absolute physical mass tells the truth. If a piece feels hollow, drop it. Require sharp edges and a mirror-like shine to anchor your {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} garments. Hammered, antiqued, and artificially aged items create visual clutter against a present-tense look. Fix this by strictly committing to gleaming, unaltered metals. Veto {excluded_finish} outright. This protocol keeps your hardware functioning as an uncompromising structural tool.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select hardware that functions as a strict structural anchor.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Clean geometry demands absolute clarity in your hardware. Seek stones that capture cool light without scattering it. A structured {stone_1} or a deep {stone_2} provides the density your look requires. Copper, distressed brass, and artificially aged alloys introduce immediate visual static into a forward-facing wardrobe. Reject them entirely. Restrict your selections to high-shine silver, white gold, platinum, and mirror chrome. Enforce sharp edges across every bezel and link. Before committing to a piece, verify its substance. Ensure the object's heft matches its rigid boundary. Lift the item. If the physical mass falls short of the visual promise, leave it behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones and metals as structural components that must pass strict physical tests.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate your jewellery by picking it up before you commit. Visuals distort reality, but density offers a true measure. If an item feels lacking in substance, leave it on the tray. Protect your clean geometry from visual static. Any metal treated to look old will register as clutter against your worsted wool. Demand a cool finish. Stick to polished silver, white gold, platinum, or mirror chrome to maintain a strict, self-contained aesthetic. If you introduce {stone_1}, ensure its setting delivers that exact same substantial, unquestionable weight.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test the physical substance of your hardware before integrating it into your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories provide the final variable in your system. Build your clean geometry. Secure your sharp edges. Finish the equation with one polished signal. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start with eyewear. Look for a thin metal frame in a cool, polished silver. Before adding any hardware, apply the function test. Ask yourself if the object actually works as a tool. Fold the hinges and check for mechanical resistance. Put them on and step into direct sunlight. If the item fails to perform its primary physical job, leave it in the case.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hardware completes your formula, but only if it serves a distinct physical purpose.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin metal frame, polished silver"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Evaluate your bags strictly on structure and hardware. Choose a smooth leather crossbody over any slouching canvas style. Look for rigid lines that enforce clean geometry. The profile must retain its sharp edges even when empty. Inspect the zips. They must feature polished steel teeth and heavy pulls. Now test the utility. Sling the strap across your chest and attempt to open the main compartment using only one hand. If the leather caves inward or the zip catches, drop the item. A successful bag protects your independent routine. It secures your belongings without compromising its silhouette, bringing a cool metallic gleam against stark navy or icy grey worsted wool.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply rigorous functional standards to your carrying equipment.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather crossbody, polished zips"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your foundation with smooth leather footwear showing a clean gloss. Avoid heavy pebble grains or factory scuffed finishes. On your wrist, secure a watch featuring a steel case and a high polish. Trust the cold, dense weight of metal against your skin. Let this tactile feedback dictate your choices. Surfaces deceive, but physical gravity is absolute. Maintain strict clean geometry across these final additions. Before exiting, execute a mechanics check. If a buckle, strap, or subdial serves zero practical purpose, discard the item immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your hardware and footwear with strict rules of engagement, testing every item for true utility.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather, clean gloss"
        },
        {
          "name": "Watch",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "steel case, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Treat pattern as a strict, cool architectural tool. Tailored worsted wool garments demand exactness, so anchor them with {recommended_pattern_1}. Fluid layers require different handling. Choose {recommended_pattern_2} to build depth without disrupting your clean geometry. Since your approach adapts to changing contexts, scale your contrast accordingly. Keep tonal shifts subtle for quiet days, but push the contrast high when you need immediate visual focus. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} entirely because it destroys strict borders. Ensure any motif you select maintains visual discipline from afar. If the design becomes chaotic at a distance, leave the item on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate patterns purely on how well they reinforce your core architecture.",
      "tests": [
        "the desk test (read as clean texture at arm's length and a half)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the Desk Test to control your visual output. Drape the garment over a chair and step back exactly an arm's length and a half. Focus directly on the fabric. A valid {recommended_pattern_1} must lose its individual lines at this distance. It must blur into a unified, flat texture. If the print still fights for attention across an empty room, reject it immediately. You rely on clean geometry to build a strict silhouette. Any pattern that vibrates or distracts the eye breaks that structural discipline. Demand prints that resolve into a solid block of colour from a metre away. If the motif buzzes or refuses to settle down, leave it on the rack.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use the Desk Test to ensure every print acts with strict discipline.",
      "tests": [
        "the desk test (read as clean texture at arm's length and a half)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aquarius__moon_cancer__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean geometry + hidden depth + one polished signal",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on clean geometry + hidden depth + one polished signal.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Look for physical alignment when you assess a garment. Trust the drag and slide of the fabric against your skin. If the material catches, sags, or pulls unevenly across your shoulders, leave it on the rail. Your structural baseline requires exact tailoring. Picture a sharply cut blazer layered over a dense silk camisole, finished with a single reflective ring. That is clean geometry + hidden depth + one polished signal in action. The outer shape provides the structure. The inner layers offer subtle tactile weight. The final accessory acts as a deliberate focal point. Do not compromise on the fit to chase a trend.\n\nBuild your wardrobe methodically over time. Acquire pieces slowly to ensure perfect tailoring, but deploy them fast when the context demands a shift in formality. Apply the treaty test before you add anything new. Ask yourself if the garment negotiates a perfect truce between strict tailoring and cool adaptability. If the piece restricts your movement or collapses into shapelessness, the treaty fails. A successful garment serves as a neutral framework that allows you to shift gears without changing your entire outfit. Look for a polished surface that reflects light cleanly. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise these functional baselines to anchor your entire dressing process before you touch a single hanger.",
      "tests": [
        "the treaty test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Seek out fabrics that build clean geometry and maintain a cool, polished finish. Rely on {texture_good_1} for shirts that hold a crisp collar and defined boundaries. Build your foundational layers in {texture_good_2} to keep sharp lines close to the body. For trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing, select {texture_good_3}. Keep your outerwear agile with {texture_good_4}. Apply the two hands test to every piece. Grasp the fabric between both palms and pull gently to check its recovery. Rely on this physical feedback over visual appeal. Photography deceives. Tension tells the truth. If the textile warps or fails to snap back, reject it immediately. Prioritise these core materials.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your wardrobe on materials that hold their structure and support your movement.",
