    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Test material integrity at the hem. Grip the edge and stretch it outward. If {texture_bad_1} warps, discard it. It lacks the resilience required for a sharp silhouette. {texture_bad_2} fails similarly when it catches on dry skin or presents a flat, lifeless surface instead of a cool, dry hand. These textiles offer zero hidden depth. They merely hang like dead mass. Run your fingers across the warp and weft. If {texture_bad_3} feels hollow or slick, it will collapse over the collarbone. Measure a garment by the resistance in your fist. The eye ignores cheap construction. Gravity exposes it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify the materials that actively undermine your baseline.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your signature combination pairs {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Grip the first in your left fist and the second in your right. Rub your thumbs over both textiles. One hand registers strict, dry resistance. The other hand glides over a smooth, cool finish. This contrast builds clean geometry. Bring {texture_good_1} into the mix to anchor the outfit. If both materials slip, the combination fails. If both drag, the garments turn heavy. You need the firm tension of a matt surface countering a sleek, polished slide. Read this friction through your fingertips.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to calibrate your daily textile choices by putting the materials to work in your hands.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your temperature is strictly cool. Build the foundation with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}, employing {core_colour_3} whenever you need a white substitute. Anchor your worsted wool staples in {core_colour_4}. Deploy {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} to deliver one polished signal. Keep your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly near the face. Exclude mustard, rust, and warm olive green entirely. Beware the whiplash trap. Do not wear lightweight draped knits exclusively one week, only to pivot to head to toe technical nylon the next. Counter this by forcing the extremes to share space. Keep one opposing item in every look, always pairing a soft fine ribbed merino piece with crisp cotton poplin. Judge these combinations by touch. Mirrors mask poor fabric. The heft of the cloth reveals the truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Mastering your palette requires strict discipline and a firm grip on your structural foundation.",
