          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You have established clean geometry. You have integrated hidden depth. Now, accessories provide your one polished signal. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with silk scarves. Wrap a neat silk band tightly at the neck to cast a cool, soft glow against a matt weave. Assess the silk by crushing it in your grip. A crisp sound and smooth recovery indicate premium thread. Run the removal test. Stand at the glass and take off the final item you added. If the outfit loses its focal point, secure the scarf back in place. If the visual balance remains perfectly steady without it, leave the accessory in the drawer.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your finishing touches with strict, objective discipline.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk band, soft glow"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "For fine jewellery, demand a high polish finish. A thin platinum chain provides a precise glint against your matt collars. Test the necklace by letting the links slip through your fingers. The heavy, fluid drop of the metal against your skin acts as your true compass. Glare hides hollow segments, but the drag of solid links exposes them. Subject your choices to the subtraction rule before you leave. Face the mirror and unfasten any piece that obscures your clean geometry. Keep only the items that rest with absolute certainty against your collarbone.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your secondary accents through strict tactile and visual filters.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin gold chain, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your silhouette with a small structured bag. Demand a smooth leather crossbody that holds its rigid shape when empty. Run your thumb over the clasp to confirm it features polished fine hardware cast in a cool metal. Check the gussets. A firm base provides the clean geometry necessary to ground a heavy overcoat. Before stepping outside, audit your carrying capacity. Review your silhouette and detach any element disrupting your balanced lines. If a strap twists or a bulky pouch breaks your profile, leave it behind. Maintain absolute control over your precise shape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your accessories with rigid structure and apply a strict departure edit.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather crossbody, polished fine hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Your tailored pieces take their pattern from woven thread. Your fluid pieces take theirs from applied ink. Adapt your contrast to the setting. Choose tonal variations for subtle integration or sharp graphic precision when the context shifts. Seek out {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Apply the proximity check to every new acquisition. Suspend the piece at the end of your reach. It must read as a calm, even block of cool colour. Draw it near. The fabric must reward you with an intricate construction that delivers hidden depth. Skip chaotic novelties. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. True versatility relies on clean geometry, not visual clutter.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the exact scale and rhythm of the patterns you allow into your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Place the garment across the room and observe the overall effect. From the doorway, any {recommended_pattern_1} must project a solid, uninterrupted field of cool colour. Approach the item slowly. The woven structure should only become apparent to someone standing close enough to brush your sleeve. If the motif remains legible from across the street, abandon the purchase. Let physical space act as your absolute filter. If you can decipher the contrasting shapes before you can touch the cloth, the print is too loud. You require strict clean geometry from afar and intricate texture up close.",
      "sectionIntro": "Execute the arm's-length test to screen out loud graphics and guarantee structural subtlety.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aquarius__moon_aquarius__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean geometry + mobile layers + one polished signal",
    "closing": "Trust your physical instinct to map your wardrobe, letting every choice lock securely into clean geometry + mobile layers + one polished signal.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe by feeling for frictionless transitions. The garment must glide onto the body without catching the fabric beneath it or restricting your stride. Your baseline is clean geometry + mobile layers + one polished signal. Picture a crisp architectural coat worn open over a fluid woven shirt and meticulously tailored trousers, anchored by a single reflective cuff at the wrist. These pieces interact smoothly. You can strip the heavy coat away or add a dense knit underneath without losing the sharp shape.\n\nConstruct this modular system slowly, ensuring you can pull an outfit together in seconds on a dark morning. Maintain a cool visual temperature across every item to guarantee these rapid combinations always harmonise perfectly. When deciding whether to keep a new garment, run it through the flight test. Ask yourself if you could sleep in it on a transatlantic route and walk straight onto a train looking immaculate. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Restrictive weight and sudden creases do not.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your core operational logic, the physical baseline that dictates every purchase and combinations.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe demands materials that hold clean geometry while supporting mobile layers. Rely on {texture_good_1} for shirting that maintains architectural boundaries and pure separation. For close-to-body base layers, seek {texture_good_2} to ensure sharp lines and easy movement. Build your lower half with {texture_good_3}. This provides trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day. Finish with {texture_good_4} for lightweight outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little. Test the resilience of every new piece. Lift the garment by the shoulders and let it drop. If the fabric collapses softly rather than snapping back into its original shape, leave it on the rail. Rely on your hands to gauge structural integrity. A mirror flatters. Gravity exposes flaws.",
      "sectionIntro": "Let your hands filter your fabrics before you even look at the garment.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
