        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the hard shell: reaching for armour, technical jackets, and stiff utility layers when life speeds up",
          "fix": "swap the shell for a brushed cotton layer that moves just as fast and holds you besides"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At the desk, let clean geometry take the lead. Build your foundation with crisp cotton poplin and worsted wool. These firm fibres establish sharp edges. Support this structure with adaptable garments that shift easily as you work. Finish the outfit with a single polished silver focal point. Keep the palette strictly cool, relying on stark navy and icy grey to set a focused tone. Leaving the building for an afternoon errand does not excuse a drop in standards. Keep the poplin buttoned. Feel the garment to judge its worth. Reflections conceal cheap construction. Grasp the fabric before you put it on. If it feels flimsy or loses its crisp shape, leave it on the rack.",
      "sectionIntro": "Here is how to deploy your styling logic for business.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close quarters and dim lighting, clean geometry leads. Look for sharp, intersecting seams in worsted wool or fine ribbed merino. Avoid any silhouette that blurs your outline in the shadows. Pick up an item and assess its density. Rely on your immediate physical read of the material. The eye skips over poor construction, but the hand registers every fault. Even a late run for groceries provides no excuse to surrender your sharp edges to formless fleece. Keep the cut crisp. Anchor the look with stark navy and icy grey. Introduce a cool sliver of white gold or platinum near the collarbone to catch the candlelight.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is how you handle low light and close proximity without losing your structure.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A morning coffee run offers no reason to suspend your personal standards. Execute your exact baseline equation every time: clean geometry + mobile layers + one polished signal. Build this daily foundation using crisp cotton poplin over fine ribbed merino in icy grey. Add a stark navy technical nylon jacket for weather protection. Check the cut in the mirror. Rely on your tactile response to how the pieces shift when you reach for your keys. The construction either accommodates your frame or fights it. Reject anything that restricts your stride. Keep your hardware cool. A bright silver watch provides a sharp anchor for an ordinary morning.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish your daily baseline before you step out the door.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Focus your jewellery and functional hardware on cool, highly reflective materials. Build your collection entirely around {metal_1} and {metal_2}. Lift every watch, ring, or buckle before buying it. The gleam of a surface distracts, but sheer mass acts as a reliable gauge. Wait for the heavy drop of solid metal into your palm to confirm its quality. Avoid artificially aged clasps or fabricated vintage patinas. That sort of {excluded_finish} surface acts as visual clutter against your clean geometry. Stick strictly to a polished finish. A brilliant {metal_3} zip provides the precise sharp contrast you need to anchor your mobile layers.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your hardware as the crucial sharp edge of your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Assess your hardware by its light-holding clarity and structural density. Look for sharp, precise cuts in {stone_1} or {stone_2}. Test every piece by closing it in your fist. Rely on this direct contact. Sight creates illusions, while solid volume remains constant. Feel for a substantial, anchoring weight before you commit. Artificially aged brass, hammered copper, and tarnished finishes act as visual clutter against your clean geometry. Keep your settings restricted to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome. A dense {stone_3} requires a flawless, reflective foundation to amplify its cool temperature.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones by how they refract light and anchor your posture, not just how they look in a display case.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Hold the jewellery unclasped in your hand. Shine distracts from poor casting, but heft exposes true value. Rely on this physical substance to guide your choices. A substantial piece of {metal_1} anchors your mobile layers. Avoid antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged finishes. These distressed textures introduce messy interference to a cool, present-tense wardrobe. Keep strictly to polished silver, platinum, mirror chrome, or white gold. Smooth, highly reflective hardware supports your clean geometry.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate the physical density of your hardware before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your accessories provide the exact one polished signal needed to anchor the clean geometry and support your mobile layers. Keep strict limits. Build every outfit around one or two strong pieces per look. Start with silk scarves. Wrap a narrow silk band tightly at the neck to introduce a soft glow against a cool worsted wool jacket. Then apply the removal check. Stop at the mirror before you leave and take off the final item you put on. If the icy grey outfit holds together better without that extra addition, leave it on the table. Favour this physical instinct over visual evaluation. The reflection plays tricks, but the actual balance of the garments on your shoulders remains absolute.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your final details to lock the rest of your formula into place.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk band, soft glow"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Treat fine jewellery as a precise tool rather than an afterthought. Look for a thin gold chain with a high polish finish to sit close to the skin. This specific item provides a cool reflection that integrates seamlessly with mobile layers like worsted wool or technical nylon. Keep the chain fine to avoid disrupting the neckline. Maintain clean geometry by letting this exact shape carry the light. Evaluate the balance before heading out. Unclasp the metal and drop it on a hard surface. If the stark navy or icy grey outfit feels hollow without that point of focus, put the chain back on. If the garments hold their structure independently, leave the jewellery behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Filter your final additions through a strict functional lens.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin gold chain, high polish"
