      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Treat pattern as an adaptive tool. Shift your contrast based on the room. Choose low tonal variations for subtle environments and sharper lines when the context demands it. Tailored pieces take their pattern strictly from woven threads, such as {recommended_pattern_1}. Fluid garments take their motif from structured rhythm, like {recommended_pattern_2}. Enforce clean geometry across the silhouette. Pass over scattered florals, distressed motifs, and erratic splashes. Reject {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. Subject every print to the stride check. Put the garment on and walk quickly past a mirror. The graphic must blur and read as a smooth texture in motion. If the design seizes attention from the cut, leave the piece on the rack. Rely on mobile layers to create depth. Keep printed finishes matt and anchor the look with cool tones.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test every print against your structure, discarding anything that disrupts the cut.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the three-metre blur test. Stand three paces from the glass and step from side to side. A correct {recommended_pattern_1} will melt into a gentle, hazy surface as you move. If the motif remains rigid and highly visible from a distance, leave it on the rail. Let kinetic feedback dictate your final decision. Still images fabricate perfection, whereas motion reveals friction. High-contrast prints break strict silhouettes and disrupt clean geometry. When you introduce mobile layers over the top, the base fabric must act as a faint shadow rather than a competing focal point. Suppress the pattern to leave clear visual space for a solitary, cool metallic accent.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this distance test to ensure every pattern you handle actually serves your overarching logic.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aquarius__moon_cancer__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean geometry + hidden depth + one polished signal",
    "closing": "Let your hands navigate the weight, your eyes measure the temperature, and your instincts secure clean geometry + hidden depth + one polished signal.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Anchor your choices in structural precision. Pick up a garment and feel the weight of its construction. Your wardrobe relies on cool restraint and deliberate edges. Master your daily uniform by applying your core formula, clean geometry + hidden depth + one polished signal. Picture a sharp architectural coat layered over a densely woven knit, anchored by a single solid cuff. The silhouette is exact. The quality lives in the tactile density of the fabric, completely invisible from a distance. The solitary piece of hardware provides the only necessary focal point.\n\nBuild your collection slowly, but dress with immediate exactness. You do not need external validation to know a piece works. Instead, rely on your physical response. When you put on a new garment, pay attention to your breathing. If your breath becomes shallow or trapped in your upper chest, take the piece off immediately. If the precise cut allows your shoulders to drop and your exhale to settle into a low, steady rhythm, the garment belongs to you. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise your structural blueprint before you buy a single new garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe relies on materials that deliver clean geometry without stiffness. You must verify substance through the touch test. Pinch the material between your fingers and assess its dense, cool resistance. Avoid letting sight alone dictate your purchases. Source {texture_good_1} for your knitwear to ensure your layers compress and bounce back. Inspect {texture_good_2} for your bags and belts, requiring a surface that will patinate while moulding to your life. Build your tailored coats from {texture_good_3} to maintain sharp lines for years. Finally, add {texture_good_4} as your blouses or linings for fluid movement and hidden depth against the skin. Treat the ranked list below as your definitive inventory.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the materials that build your structural foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
        {
          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
