          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the float test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Source keepsake jewellery that balances mixed patina and polish. Look for aged brass with a polished gold accent, and layer it near cool silver to control the contrast. Choose belts cut from dense full-grain leather and fasten them with a brushed buckle. Finally, evaluate the visual mass of your additions against your clothing. If a metal component seems to hover delicately over the fabric rather than sinking into it, remove it. True clean geometry relies on deliberate weight.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your final hardware to ensure every piece pulls its weight.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged brass with a polished gold accent, mixed patina and polish"
        },
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed buckle"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the float test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored pieces derive pattern from physical structure. Trust your hands to identify {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2} woven directly into tweed. Fluid garments take their motifs from dye. Maintain clean geometry across your wardrobe by keeping all patterns strictly low-contrast and tonal. Look for cool shades that blur together. Pass over anything forcing the eye to decode a distinct graphic, and skip {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. Apply the underwater test to every printed silk. The design must register like faint light shifting on a dark seabed. If the motif reads like hard street signage or features sharp borders, leave it on the rack. Trust your immediate instinct for visual restraint. Require hidden depth. Choose items that reveal their complexity only upon close inspection.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate pattern as an extension of material structure rather than an applied decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the underwater test (read like light moving on the seabed, not signage)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Trust your immediate visual instinct over the garment label. Scrutinise the diffusion of every {recommended_pattern_1} you consider. Hang the piece against a bare wall and step five paces back. The motif must drop its hard edges and soften into shadow. It should mimic a cool haze settling over stone, not a stamped poster. If the shapes remain rigid across the room, leave the item on the hanger. Your wardrobe requires pieces that maintain clean geometry up close, but blur into fluid movement from afar. Seek out weaves that reveal hidden depth upon close inspection. If a print reads as stark lettering from a distance, it fails the test.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every patterned garment to this visual distance check before taking it to the till.",
      "tests": [
        "the underwater test (read like light moving on the seabed, not signage)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aquarius__moon_capricorn__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean geometry + softness + one polished signal",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on clean geometry + softness + one polished signal.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Measure every garment by its self-contained structure. Does it hold its own architecture, or does it collapse when you take it off the hanger? Trust the physical weight of a cool weave in your hands. Build your foundation on this exact equation: clean geometry + softness + one polished signal. Picture a structured wool overcoat cut in sharp right angles, worn over a fluid silk shirt, anchored by a single heavy metal cuff. This is your baseline.\n\nBuild slowly, assembling each piece with deliberate scrutiny over years, but dress fast. When you finish, apply the wrist test. Drop your arm straight down to your side. The sleeve must land with absolute intent, grazing the wristbone precisely to frame your chosen hardware without dragging. If you have to push the fabric back or adjust the fall, take the garment off. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your choices in a fixed physical reality before you evaluate any garment.",
