    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let clean geometry lead your office choices. Build your attire by anchoring it with sharp tailoring in stark navy worsted wool. Allow light movement and one polished signal to support this structure. Pick up your garments and assess their mass. Avoid judging by reflection alone. The heft of worsted wool dictates its authority. Never slip into shapelessness just because you leave the building. Even a midday coffee run calls for a razor-sharp profile in crisp cotton poplin. Keep your icy grey ribbed merino knits taut. Reject matt hardware, and maintain strict, cool edges until the day ends.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your professional environment by dictating the physical terms of your attire.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close quarters under low lighting, clean geometry must take the lead. Shadows swallow subtle details. Choose stark navy worsted wool or icy grey technical nylon that holds a sharp edge in the dark. Execute the low-light check. Stepping into a dim restaurant booth demands precise edges. If a garment collapses into shapelessness, fold it away. A single cool silver ring serves as one polished signal, catching whatever ambient illumination remains against fabrics that maintain light movement. Rely on the physical certainty of dense wool against your ribs. Visuals deceive in dim environments. Physical shape never does.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the close-range mechanics of low-light dressing.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A midnight petrol station run for paracetamol still requires a deliberate outline. Do not drop your standard for mundane tasks. Reach for a technical nylon jacket over a crisp cotton poplin shirt. Assess the drape. Trust your touch to verify the cloth. If a sleeve bunches at the elbow, take the item off. Your baseline dictates strict adherence to clean geometry + light movement + one polished signal. Construct the look with stark navy and icy grey layers. Fasten a cool silver cuff at the wrist. Look for precise cuts. Avoid anything that stretches out of shape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Maintain your exact baseline for mundane daily errands.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Keep your metal strategy strictly cool. Build your foundation entirely around {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Artificially aged pieces read as visual clutter against a modern wardrobe. Hammered copper and antiqued brass ruin your clean geometry. Restrict your zips and clasps to your three core metals instead. Lift a watch or a belt buckle from the counter to test its quality. Plating masks cheapness, but genuine density proves the item's worth. A solid {metal_1} clasp will rest heavy in your palm. If the item feels light or hollow, leave it behind. Reject any {excluded_finish} texture to keep your hardware stark, reflective, and functioning flawlessly as one polished signal that complements light movement.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware by its rigid reflection and its absolute physical heft.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select {stone_1} and {stone_2} for their sharp clarity and cool refractive qualities. When assessing a setting, lift the item to evaluate its gravity. An outward sparkle offers nothing without the substantial heft of high-grade minerals. Treat this tactile density as an instinctual measure of quality. Reject antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged finishes completely. These cloudy patinas register as mere clutter against your clean geometry. Enforce a strict boundary against this visual noise by anchoring your hardware exclusively in polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome to act as your one polished signal without disrupting light movement.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your metals and gems as structural tools, relying on pure physical density to filter out visual noise.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the item of jewellery off the table. Window displays lie. The true measure of any setting lies in its solid resistance against your palm. Assess the physical mass of a {metal_1} clasp or a {stone_1} cuff. If it feels hollow, leave it behind. Avoid tarnished brass, scratched bronze, and artificially aged alloys. These rough finishes register as visual debris against your clean geometry. Restrict your hardware to high-gloss silver, bright platinum, and reflective white gold. A highly polished surface supports your cool palette, standing out as one polished signal while permitting light movement.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply a strict physical standard to every metal piece before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Define the silhouette with clean geometry. Permit light movement in the fabric. Finish with exactly one polished signal. Confine your selections to the principle of one or two strong pieces per look. Turn first to silk scarves to provide this final touch. Look for a narrow silk band offering a soft glow against a stark navy collar. Always apply the take-off test before deciding an outfit is complete. Strip away the final addition. If the cool palette and worsted wool still function perfectly without it, put the extra item back in the drawer.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select and test your final additions using strict visual limits.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk band, soft glow"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Source fine jewellery finished to a high polish. Pick up a thin white gold chain and gauge its density. Feel the temperature. The links must feel heavy in the palm but fluid against the skin. You need a piece that provides subtle light movement without snagging, serving as your one polished signal. Perform the subtraction drill. Fasten the chain over a stark navy fine ribbed merino knit, step back, and remove the necklace. If the collar feels unresolved without that exact trace of cool metal, put it back on. If removing the chain restores the pure clean geometry of your neckline, leave the piece in the tray.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your metals through strict physical trials to ensure they serve the garment rather than distract from it.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin gold chain, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Source a small structured bag. Look for a smooth leather crossbody equipped with fine hardware in cool rhodium or silver. Feel the metal strap and clasp mechanisms. Squeeze the metal. Photographs flatter, but cheap alloys always rattle. The silhouette must hold strict, clean geometry to anchor the light movement of your garments. Conclude your dressing routine by removing one detail. Unfasten the very last element you added. If your icy grey wool retains its exact balance without that extra chain, return the piece to its box. The bag's components should act singularly as one polished signal.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your final utility pieces and ruthlessly edit the completed arrangement.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather crossbody, polished fine hardware"
