      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor your print strategy in adaptable contrast. Keep dark and light elements distinct enough to register clearly, but subdued enough to merge into a versatile block of cool colour. Your tailored garments require precise repeating structures like {recommended_pattern_1} to reinforce their edges. Allow fluid pieces to carry softer motifs like {recommended_pattern_2}. Test any printed garment by striding past a mirror. The print must visually soften as you move, registering as an agreeable, continuous texture. It must never blur or strobe under overhead lights. If the design fights against the light movement of a draped shirt or distorts a trouser leg, put it back. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. Maintain clean geometry and a polished surface without cluttering your one polished signal.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control the visual noise on your clothing.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Hang a {recommended_pattern_1} item across the room. Walk past it at a steady pace and watch how the print behaves. It must dissolve into a mild, shifting grain as you move. If the shapes stay hard or demand focus, leave the piece on the rail. You rely on light movement to keep your wardrobe functional. The pattern should soften into a quiet visual hum. Observe the visual rhythm. A successful print acts like a simple woven fabric from three paces away. It anchors clean geometry and a cool foundation, leaving room for one polished signal.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the motion test to check a pattern's true nature before you buy it.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aquarius__moon_gemini__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean geometry + light movement + one polished signal",
    "closing": "Trust your physical instincts, let the fabrics hang with intent, and anchor your silhouette in clean geometry + light movement + one polished signal.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your physical instincts seek a precise, cool equilibrium. Trust the sensation of weightless structure when you handle a garment. It must hold a sharp edge without dragging on your frame. Your core equation is clean geometry + light movement + one polished signal. Picture a sharply cut jacket with a strict shoulder, layered over a fluid, lightweight top, finished with a single high-shine piece of hardware at the wrist. Build your wardrobe slowly by acquiring highly adaptable pieces. Deploy them fast each morning.\n\nBefore you leave the house, apply the half-mirror test. Stand close enough to a mirror that you only see your chest and shoulders. Assess the visual balance. If the reflection shows stiff, unyielding lines, introduce a lighter, moving element. If the shape dissolves into a shapeless drape, swap the outer layer for something with rigid, precise edges. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. The balance of your frame does not. Look for a polished finish that adapts to any environment.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this foundational blueprint to build and test every outfit.",
      "tests": [
