  "venus_aquarius__moon_leo__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean geometry + athletic space + one polished signal",
    "closing": "Whenever visual noise threatens your focus, close your eyes, feel the weight of the cloth in your hands, and let your tactile instincts guide you straight back to clean geometry + athletic space + one polished signal.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "To navigate your wardrobe, rely on the sensation of kinetic balance. Lift a garment and gauge its structural memory against its capacity to yield. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not. Your foundation operates on a strict equation: clean geometry + athletic space + one polished signal. Picture a sharp-shouldered overcoat layered over a seamless technical underlayer, finished with a single high-shine hardware closure. The geometry provides the outer architecture. The athletic space gives you pure physical freedom. The single polished element acts as your anchor. If a piece restricts your reach or collapses under its own construction, discard it.\n\nBuild your collection slowly, deploy your outfits fast, and let the daily combinations drift by mood. Before acquiring any new item, subject it to the treaty test. Ask yourself if the garment dictates terms to your body or negotiates a fair alliance with your movement. If an armhole bites your shoulder or a waistline requires constant manual adjustment, the treaty is broken. Leave it on the hanger. Your clothes must operate as adaptable tools rather than rigid cages. Seek out fabrics that feel physically cool to the touch while retaining an unyielding shape. True adaptability requires pieces that work instantly, freeing you to focus entirely on your physical environment.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the foundational mechanics of your wardrobe before you bring in another piece.",
      "tests": [
        "the treaty test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your materials must hold clean geometry while allowing physical freedom. Apply the snap test before you buy. Pull the fabric between your fists. If it fights your grip or loses its shape, drop it immediately. Rely on this tactile feedback over any visual appeal. You need {texture_good_1} for shirting that maintains architectural boundaries and pure separation against cool metals. Layer this over {texture_good_2} for close-to-body base layers that deliver sharp lines and easy movement. Anchor the system with {texture_good_3}. Trousers cut from this must drape cleanly and resist creasing. Finish with {texture_good_4} for lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little, preserving your athletic space. Anchor the entire structure with one polished signal. Look for the fibres below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the materials that build your structure.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
