    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, clean geometry dictates your first move. A stark navy poplin shirt must cut a sharp line across the shoulder. Your supporting elements make that strictness wearable. Give your limbs room to breathe in an icy grey matt worsted wool trouser, ensuring the cloth never pulls taut when you bend. Let the cool glint of a steel watch provide a definitive finish, acting as your one polished signal. Treat your weekend hours with this exact discipline. Buying nails at a hardware shop demands the identical precise hem as a Monday morning boardroom pitch. Pick up an item and test the seams. Rely on your own movement to judge a fit. The glass deceives, but restricted motion tells the truth. If the shape distorts when you reach, leave it on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "The office demands absolute focus, so lock in your standards before you step out the door.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "Close-quarters settings require ruthless precision. In low light, your clean geometry must take the lead. Let navy worsted wool trace sharp lines across your shoulders. Keep the temperature cool with icy grey fine ribbed merino. Rely on the weight of the cloth. If a piece feels flimsy in your grip, drop it entirely. Apply your standards consistently across all proximity boundaries. A casual dinner requires the identical athletic space as a formal event. Let a polished steel watch dial catch the ambient room glow to serve as your singular anchor. Avoid excess details that clutter the eye. Rely entirely on a precise cut to perform the work in dim spaces.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the close-quarters environment by shifting your focal point rather than abandoning your core rules.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Routine errands require no compromise. Do not downgrade your clothing for a trip to the supermarket. Reach for a navy technical nylon jacket over crisp cotton poplin. The equation remains absolute. You must always execute clean geometry + athletic space + one polished signal. Assess the fabric with your fingertips. If a piece feels restrictive or limp, discard it. Your garments must allow you to sprint for a train without losing shape. Add a steel watch or a white gold ring to anchor the outfit. Rely on your tactile response. Let the cool fibres sit sharply against your skin.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your daily baseline as a rigid discipline, establishing your standard before you leave the house.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Commit to a cool metal strategy across all hardware and jewellery. Whether choosing a {metal_1} buckle or a {metal_2} clasp, preserve the athletic space around the detail. Avoid {excluded_finish} finishes entirely. Tarnished bronze, beaten copper, and forced patinas register as historic debris on a modern silhouette. Restrict your hardware to high-shine silver, gleaming platinum, bright white gold, and flawless chrome. Gauge every component physically before accepting it. A {metal_3} zip must carry enough actual heft to fall perfectly straight, reinforcing your single polished signal.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish strict boundaries for the metals you wear against your skin and the structural hardware on your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Hardware requires exactness to support clean geometry. Treat stones as structural elements rather than decoration. Demand absolute density and icy clarity. Seek out {stone_1} or {stone_2} cut into sharp facets that bounce light precisely. Lift the setting in your bare hand before buying. Visuals deceive, but mass never lies. If a ring lacks a reassuring, heavy pull against gravity, leave it on the counter. To preserve your athletic space, avoid murky minerals entirely. Artificially aged metals, hammered copper, and antiqued brass read as visual static against a present-tense wardrobe. Anchor every {stone_3} exclusively in polished silver, solid platinum, bright white gold, and mirror chrome. This strict discipline guarantees a cool, high-definition finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select stones and metals that function as precision structural hardware.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate every piece of jewellery by hand. Optical illusions fade, but physical heft remains constant. Rely on the immediate density in your palm as your primary metric. Distressed surfaces and irregular textures create visual friction, fighting your required clean geometry. Anchor your choices in high-gloss {metal_1} and highly reflective polishes to serve as your one polished signal. A sleek surface reflects a decisively cool aesthetic, while dull elements disrupt it. If an item lacks the substantial heaviness of solid construction, put it down.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate hardware through physical density and surface finish before bringing it into your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories serve a specific mechanical function. You have established your foundation with clean geometry and cleared out an athletic space. Now you must deploy your one polished signal. Limit yourself to one or two focused pieces per look. Anything more clutters the visual field. Apply the reduction test before you step outside. Stand at the mirror and strip away the final addition to ensure the silhouette stays strict. Begin this refinement with silk scarves. Treat them as a simple silk band that injects a subtle sheen against a matt wool collar. Keep the lines defined and the palette strictly cool. Trust your hands when knotting the fabric. The drape will confirm if the structure holds.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your accessories by treating them as precision tools.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk band, soft glow"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Fine jewellery operates under strict physical boundaries. Look for a thin white gold chain lying perfectly flat against the collarbone. Demand a high polish finish. The cool metal must catch the light sharply without creating visual noise, functioning purely as your one polished signal. Every addition must respect your clean geometry. Scrutinize the placement carefully. If the necklace interrupts the line of your collar or snags your attention, take it off immediately. The chain exists to provide a sharp metallic edge, never a distraction. Trust your fingers over your reflection. If the links twist or refuse to drape smoothly, drop the piece entirely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your fine jewellery with clinical precision, ensuring every metallic addition serves the entire silhouette.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin gold chain, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Require clean geometry in your leather goods. Select a small structured bag to wear as a smooth leather crossbody, preserving your athletic space. Check the surface tension. Press your thumb against the calfskin. It must resist. Look for polished fine hardware in a cool metal like rhodium. The sharp angles of the bag create necessary architecture against worsted wool. Evaluate the integration as your final step. Scan your overall shape objectively. If the strap breaks the visual line of your icy grey trousers, remove the bag. Trust your hands to strip away any excess weight.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your structural accessories and execute the final mirror edit.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather crossbody, polished fine hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored garments hold structure through their construction. Let them take {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} woven directly into cool worsted wool. Fluid garments require movement. Ensure athletic space in these pieces by selecting {recommended_pattern_3} to prevent visual clutter. Keep your contrast adaptive. Shift from tonal pairings for strict environments to sharper contrasts when the context changes. Apply the arm's-length test to every new acquisition. Hang the item and step back. It must read as a solid, calm plane of cloth from three feet away. Step in close. The weave should reveal exact, rewarding detail. Pass over anything merely printed on the surface. Leave {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} on the rack. Maintain clean geometry by letting the cut dictate the shape, rather than the print.",
      "sectionIntro": "Govern your patterns with the same strict physical filters you apply to your tailoring.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Assess scale by suspending the garment across the room. At a significant distance, any {recommended_pattern_1} must collapse into a smooth block of cool colour. Walk forward to inspect the cloth. The motif should only become legible when the fabric rests mere inches from your face. If the design registers loudly from afar, it severely disrupts clean geometry. Pick it up and test the weave. Trust your fingers to gauge the density and finish. A polished appearance requires absolute control of proportion. If visual noise dominates the surface, drop the item immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Execute the reach test to verify that a pattern serves your structure without causing visual clutter.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aquarius__moon_libra__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean geometry + cool composure + one polished signal",
    "closing": "Trust the strict drape of your garments and the heavy chill of your metals to secure clean geometry + cool composure + one polished signal.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Run your hand over the fabric before you check the label. You are looking for a cool surface and an unbroken line. If the material drags against your palm, put it back. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight and drape do not. Your wardrobe runs on a specific equation. Memorise it as clean geometry + cool composure + one polished signal. Picture a sharp tailored trouser cut with mathematical precision, a lightweight knitted shirt that drops without clinging, and a single light-catching lapel pin. That is your baseline.\n\nBuild your wardrobe systematically. Deploy the pieces fast depending on the day's demands. Apply the combination test before any purchase. Pick up the garment and ask yourself if it seamlessly bridges three completely different outfits already hanging in your closet. If it demands a total reset of your silhouette, leave it in the shop. A successful piece adapts without shouting. Check the finish. Everything you wear must resolve in a polished surface. Keep your geometry sharp. Keep your composure cool.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this foundational blueprint to anchor your dressing decisions.",
      "tests": [
        "the combination test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe requires materials that hold their structural boundaries. Rely on {texture_good_1} for shirting that creates pure separation. For base layers, choose {texture_good_2} to maintain crisp boundaries close to the body. Apply the snap test before you buy. Pull the fabric between your hands and release it. If it fails to spring back instantly into clean geometry, leave it on the rail. Anchor your lower half in {texture_good_3} for trousers that drape precisely and resist creasing. Finish with {texture_good_4} for mobile outerwear that blocks the wind while weighing almost nothing. This tactile foundation guarantees your cool composure. Scan the list below for your most reliable options.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to select the fibres that hold your structural boundaries.",
