      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your core pairing requires {sweet_spot_keyword_1} anchored by {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Pick up a {texture_good_1} shirt. Pull the cloth taut between your thumbs and let it release. You want a sharp recoil, a quick return to its resting state. That strict tension maintains the clean geometry of your silhouette. Combine this crisp structure with dense, matt trousers. If the material feels limp or pools in your grip, drop it. It lacks the cool structure you require.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your materials for structure and tension before you put them on.",
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Build your foundation from {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Anchor these pieces with {core_colour_4}. Use {core_colour_3} for a sharp neutral contrast. Your temperature is strictly cool. Pass over mustard, rust, and warm olive green. Leave them on the rack. Integrate your relief tone, a soft note used sparingly, to break up heavy blocks of colour. Treat your accents as precise tools. Deploy {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} to direct the eye. Watch out for a lifeless block of solid darks that makes you lose focus by noon. Fix it instantly. Add a sharp poplin cuff, a highly polished steel watch, or a vivid technical nylon trainer. This strict intervention restores clean geometry to the outfit.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat colour as a strict structural tool rather than a decoration, using this palette as your operational blueprint.",
