    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Lock down your clean geometry. Secure your cool composure. Then deliver one polished signal. Accessories require ruthless editing, so restrict yourself to a single strong piece per look. Start the process with silk scarves. Seek out a precise woven band that provides a steady, sleek glow. Always apply the rotation test before adding to your collection. If you cannot cycle the new addition through at least three stark navy or icy grey outfits this week, leave it on the shelf. Rub the hem between your fingers to verify the construction. If the edges feel frayed or the surface falters under direct light, reject it. Everything you add must remain strictly cool and highly polished.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use accessories as precision instruments to finalize your look.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk band, soft glow"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Choose clean geometry when evaluating fine jewellery. Look specifically for a thin white gold chain with a mirror finish. The surface must reflect light evenly without any matt texturing to deliver your one polished signal. This uninterrupted gleam ensures cool composure when worn against stark navy worsted wool. To verify the construction, apply the fluidity test. Hold the clasp firmly and spin the length of the chain between your thumb and index finger. If the links bind, snag, or resist the turning motion, leave the item on the velvet tray. The metal must roll in a smooth, flawless loop.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject fine jewellery to strict mechanical testing before allowing it into your wardrobe.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin gold chain, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your wardrobe with a small structured bag to maintain clean geometry. Seek out a smooth leather crossbody secured by pristine hardware in silver or white gold. Run your thumb over the metal clasps. They must feel heavy and precise. Let structural integrity dictate your choices. Subject every item to the fourteen-day audit. Force yourself to use the bag every day for two weeks. If a piece stays hanging on the hook because the leather feels too pliable against your icy grey layers or the dull finish breaks your cool composure, remove the item permanently. Ensure the bag provides exactly one polished signal.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your accessories by selecting bags that maintain your silhouette, then verify their utility in practice.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather crossbody, polished fine hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Divide your approach to prints. Tailored garments require precise woven structures. Fluid pieces demand tightly controlled, scaled repeats. Because your aesthetic must remain adaptable, adjust your contrast levels according to the garment's weight. A heavy coat can carry a stark, high-contrast grid. A lightweight shirt needs a low-contrast tonal weave. Hunt for {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Skip {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. Pass over any {avoid_pattern_2} that lacks rigid symmetry. Let clean geometry do the heavy lifting. Step ten feet back from the rack. If the motif looks muddy or confusing at a distance, drop the piece. It must read with absolute clarity to protect your cool composure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as an architectural tool to dictate proportion and scale.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the blink test to every printed silk scarf or tie. Hang the garment on a door frame. Close your eyes, then open them for a single split second. If {recommended_pattern_1} dissolves into an undefined blur, leave it behind. The lines must register sharply and instantly. Demand clean geometry from every motif. If the eye has to strain to decipher the shape, the design fails your one polished signal. Choose prints that maintain cool composure under a rapid glance.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the blink test to evaluate pattern legibility.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aquarius__moon_pisces__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean geometry + blurred edges + one polished signal",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on clean geometry + blurred edges + one polished signal.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe with deliberate slowness, but deploy your outfits instantly. Trust physical weight as your primary sensory compass. Run your hands over the garment and judge its density before you even try it on. You are looking for a cool, heavy detachment in the material. It must hang cleanly from your shoulders without clinging to your frame. If the fabric feels flimsy or demands constant physical adjustment, leave it on the hanger. Your clothing must remain entirely self-contained, requiring zero intervention once it touches your skin.\n\nYour core style formula is clean geometry + blurred edges + one polished signal. Picture a structured overcoat with sharp, defined shoulders, layered over a fine-gauge knit that softens at the collar, finished with a single piece of high-shine hardware. Trust the wrist test as your ultimate compass. Let your arms fall straight to your sides. Focus entirely on the cuff. If the fabric drags, shifts unpredictably, or feels clumsy across the back of your hand, take it off immediately. The cut must frame your joints with absolute independence.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation, the strict blueprint for evaluating every garment before it enters your life.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your core formula of clean geometry and blurred edges requires absolute material integrity. Rely on touch rather than reading the label. Pick up a garment and apply the breath test. Hold the cloth against your mouth and exhale slowly. If the air traps and bounces back hot, leave it on the rack. You are looking for fibres that keep your skin cool and dry. Rely on {texture_good_1} for knitwear that compresses and springs back. Invest in {texture_good_2} for bags and belts that mould to your grip. Anchor your coats in {texture_good_3} to lock in a sharp silhouette for decades. Layer {texture_good_4} underneath for fluid movement that acts as one polished signal. Build your foundation from the materials below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject poor construction and recognise the materials that build your foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
        {
          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "You are building a wardrobe of clean geometry. Poor fabrics destroy that structure. Pick up {texture_bad_1} and pinch the seam. If it yields a slick, greasy friction between your fingers, drop it. Next, test {texture_bad_2} against your skin. Exhale through the weave. Warm, trapped air indicates a failure to keep you cool. Finally, drag your palm across {texture_bad_3}. If it catches on your skin with a microscopic snag, leave it on the hanger. Your style relies on self-contained restraint. Clingy weaves sabotage that effect immediately. Trust your tactile instincts. Appearance deceives, but friction always tells the truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject structural failure before a piece ever touches your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Anchor your style in {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Pick up a piece of {texture_good_1} and test the mass in your hands. Close your eyes. Notice your lungs. If the item makes you drop your shoulders and draw a slow, deep draft of air into your chest, keep it. The scale provides better guidance than a mirror. Follow this bodily reaction to build clean geometry and structure the silhouette. Restrict your surfaces to cool tones and self-contained details. Blend matt and gloss finishes to keep the tension precise.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the exact physical friction required to anchor your style.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette remains strictly cool. Build the foundation with {core_colour_1}, {core_colour_2}, and {core_colour_3}. Use {core_colour_4} as a lighter neutral substitute. Keep your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly to break up dense blocks of matt cashmere or full-grain leather. Deploy {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} as deliberate focal points. Pass over hot saturated red, stark optic white, and harsh neon entirely. Watch for the cocooning trap, where heavy layers of formless grey consume your outline. Correct this by restoring one defined line. Pull out a neat silk cuff, stand up a structured collar, or let a metal pendant sit visibly on the collarbone. Rely on clean geometry to keep your shape intact.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your palette by treating colour as an architectural tool rather than a decoration.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Inky navy",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep teal",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
