  "venus_aquarius__moon_scorpio__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean geometry + quiet undercurrent + one polished signal",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on clean geometry + quiet undercurrent + one polished signal.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the physical sensation of structure against your skin. You are looking for garments that feel deliberate and contained. If a piece feels fussy or requires constant adjustment, leave it on the hanger. Picture a sharp tailored coat falling straight to the calf, a fine gauge rollneck layered beneath, and a single structural timepiece catching the light. This is your formula in action. It is clean geometry + quiet undercurrent + one polished signal. Build your wardrobe slowly, acquiring only items that meet this exact standard.\n\nCurate your pieces with extreme patience, but assemble your outfits with rapid precision. When evaluating a new acquisition, apply the breath test. Put the garment on, close your eyes, and inhale deeply. Notice how the material responds as your chest expands. A correct piece will feel like a cool, structured extension of your own frame, offering zero resistance to your lungs. If the item shifts awkwardly or feels chaotic against your ribs, take it off immediately. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight and construction do not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this framework and use it to vet every piece before it enters your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe relies on materials that hold clean geometry without stiffening into armour. Build your tailored coats and blazers from {texture_good_3} to maintain sharp, lasting lines. Layer them over {texture_good_1} for knitwear that compresses under pressure and springs back instantly. Add a quiet undercurrent of movement using {texture_good_4} for fluid blouses and internal linings. Anchor these garments with {texture_good_2} for shoes and bags that mould to your daily routines. Before you buy any textile, hold the fabric against your mouth and exhale sharply. If the air punches straight through, the weave is too loose to hold a structured shape. If it traps the air entirely, you will sweat. Look for the slow release of air.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the materials that build a self-contained wardrobe.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
        {
          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
