        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "dissolution: pale gauze on pale gauze with nothing beneath and the silhouette disappears",
          "fix": "restore one line: a bias-cut slip that traces the body, a fitted base layer, or the deep sea blue anchor worn closest to the skin"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At the desk, clean geometry leads your choices. Support this sharp structure with a muted foundation of cool tones. Reach for brushed wool trousers in dove grey or an inky navy silk shirt. Keep the surrounding finishes matt until you introduce a single metallic detail. A steel watch or a rhodium lapel pin provides your required solitary gleam. Evaluate your standards strictly before leaving the house. Pick up a blazer and look for slouching collars or lazy seams. The density of the cloth reveals the truth. If the cut relaxes in your grip, discard the piece.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the strict material requirements for your working hours.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "Let clean geometry lead in close, low-light settings. Dim rooms obscure inky navy and deep teal. Rely on your own grip to assess a garment. If the silk feels flimsy in your fingers, reject it. Sight deceives in shadow, but your touch tells the absolute truth. Reserve high shine for a singular white gold ring or a steel watch case. Choose matt brushed wool for trousers. If a collar pinches when you lean across a small table, leave the piece on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Here is how you handle your presentation when the lights drop and the space shrinks.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat your daily dressing as an unbroken practice. A quick errand demands the identical strict standard as a formal briefing. Enforce your baseline by executing clean geometry + quiet undercurrent + one polished signal. Build the foundation with a dove grey cashmere jumper layered over a pristine silk shirt. Step into brushed wool trousers in deep teal. Fasten a matt white gold cuff on your wrist. Keep the complete palette cool. Assess the true grade of your garments by how they fall on your frame. Let the stiff edge of full-grain leather boots direct your stride.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply absolute aesthetic discipline to every mundane task on your schedule.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your metal strategy is strictly cool. Build your foundation on {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. You have complete freedom to mix finishes across your accessories. Pick the hardware up and weigh it in your palm. Appearance deceives, but gravity never lies. Flimsy zips and hollow buckles betray the entire outfit. Demand clean geometry in every clasp and watch face. A highly reflective, glaring silver creates a distracting clash against your soft muted colours. Fix this by insisting on matt and brushed textures to keep the presentation cohesive. Treat your metals as a quiet undercurrent to the garments themselves, and steer clear of {excluded_finish}.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware with the exact same strict physical standards you apply to your tailoring.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Favour {stone_1} and {stone_2} cut with clean geometry. These materials absorb light rather than scattering it. Let their precise shapes provide that quiet undercurrent of density against your wardrobe. Press the stone against your inner wrist before you put it on. Genuine materials carry a distinct, lasting chill. The eye is easily tricked by clever plating, but temperature tells the truth. Watch out for high-gloss metallic settings. Gleaming chrome shatters the cohesion of your cool muted colours and creates an unwanted distraction. Anchor your jewellery exclusively in brushed or matt finishes to keep the visual integration flawless.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware as structural architecture, relying on physical density and visual precision to ground your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Hold the {metal_1} hardware in your open palm before committing to it. Examine the edges for absolute precision. Hollow buckles will rapidly undermine the clean geometry of your silhouette. Watch out for a specific visual failure. Highly reflective, glaringly bright metals clash severely against a cool {core_colour_1} garment. That sharp glare shatters the cohesion of your look. Avoid it. Anchor your accessories with matt or heavily brushed textures instead to provide one polished signal.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test the physical density and finish of every metal piece before it enters your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories deliver the one polished signal that finalizes your foundation. Your garments establish clean geometry. Your fabrics provide the quiet undercurrent. Hardware is your focal point. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start your selection with handbags. Seek out dense structures cut from full-grain leather. You want a strictly matt body secured by one polished clasp. Lift the bag by its handle. If the metal hardware clinks lightly or feels hollow, put the item back. Trust physical sensation over visual appeal. Keep the temperature cool across all your metal choices.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is where you finish the structure with hard materials.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, matt body with one polished clasp"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the float test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Treat scarves as structural elements. Select silk with a strictly matt finish in deep teal or dove grey. Gather the material and drop it from your collarbone. Proper matt silk drifts down in a slow, deliberate arc. This physical resistance provides the clean geometry required to frame a lapel. The fabric must hold a sharp fold rather than collapsing into a formless puddle. If it plummets heavily or clings to itself with static, leave it on the rack.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the physical requirements for your final layers to ensure they hold their shape.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the float test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Treat keepsake jewellery as a study in contrast. Seek out an aged metal carrying a polished accent. This mixed patina and polish provides necessary tension against your cool pieces. Fasten a solid full-grain leather belt with a brushed buckle to reinforce your clean geometry. Inspect your reflection. If a pendant or buckle hovers visually over your dove grey cashmere like a disconnected afterthought, take it off. Every accessory must anchor the garment, never floating away from it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your final additions and remove anything that refuses to integrate.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged brass with a polished gold accent, mixed patina and polish"
        },
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed buckle"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the float test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Root your tailored garments in structural integrity. Let them draw their visual interest directly from the weave. Fluid silk layers should take their pattern from movement and drape. Keep all pattern contrast strictly low and tonal to preserve the silhouette. Look for {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2}. Maintain clean geometry throughout every motif you select. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. Hold the printed fabric up to the light. The design must read like cool light refracting on a seabed. It must never read like sharp graphic signage. Trust your physical reaction to the cloth. If the print registers in your eye before the drape registers in your fingers, leave the item on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern strictly as an extension of texture, never as an independent announcement.",
      "tests": [
        "the underwater test (read like light moving on the seabed, not signage)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Step back from the mirror and blur your vision to evaluate your prints. A true {recommended_pattern_1} should dissolve into shifting tonal depths. It must resemble a quiet undercurrent rippling across a cool surface. It must never read like high-contrast signage or static branding. Avoid any motif that fights for attention or breaks your silhouette. You require patterns that support clean geometry, functioning as an elusive shadow rather than a standalone graphic. If the shapes remain sharp and instantly legible when you squint, leave the garment on the hanger. Trust visual fluidness over rigid borders.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every printed garment to this strict visual standard.",
      "tests": [
        "the underwater test (read like light moving on the seabed, not signage)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aquarius__moon_taurus__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean geometry + sensory comfort + one polished signal",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on clean geometry + sensory comfort + one polished signal.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your internal compass relies on physical calibration. If a garment restricts your stride or requires constant adjustment, discard it. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Build your outfits using a strict baseline formula. You need clean geometry + sensory comfort + one polished signal. Picture a sharp, structural tailored coat layered over a fluid, heavy knit sweater. Anchor this combination with a single cool, high-shine metallic watch against a matt leather belt. The silhouette provides the architecture. The knit provides the ease. The single polished element acts as the deliberate focal point.\n\nConstruct your wardrobe methodically over time. When getting dressed, deploy these components swiftly to meet shifting daily demands. Your clothing must serve as a closed system that requires nothing from the outside world. Before you keep any new piece, apply the treaty test. Ask yourself if this garment forces you into a negotiation. If you must adjust your posture, constantly pull down a hem, or compromise your mobility to make a piece work, leave it on the hanger. A successful item signs no treaties and accepts no compromises. It simply functions precisely as required.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this foundational logic to calibrate your physical choices.",
      "tests": [
        "the treaty test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your best fabrics deliver sensory comfort without sacrificing clean geometry. Filter every potential purchase through the crush check. Pick up the garment with both hands, squeeze the material tightly, and let it go. If it holds a wrinkle or feels rough, drop it. Allow the physical heft of the cloth to guide your choice over its hanger appeal. Seek out {texture_good_1} for shirting with strict architectural boundaries. Build your foundation with {texture_good_2} for close-to-body base layers that allow easy movement. Rely on {texture_good_3} for trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day. Top it off with {texture_good_4} for lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind. These polished materials work for you. Consult the hierarchy below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Let your hands evaluate the fabric before your eyes assess the cut.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Scrutinise every new piece by pulling the textile between your closed fists. Rely on your fingers to detect the deception of a cheap weave. If {texture_bad_1} sags or fails to snap back into its intended shape, it ruins your clean geometry and goes back on the rail. Reject {texture_bad_2} the second it catches rough on the collarbone or traps unnecessary heat. You need textiles that maintain cool regulation and adapt to your movement. If {texture_bad_3} feels limp in your grip or clings rather than draping with absolute precision, leave it behind. True materials cooperate entirely with your form. Rely on elements that hold a crisp structure and require zero adjustment.",
      "sectionIntro": "Reject any material that demands constant attention or betrays your core structure.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your signature tactile combination pairs {sweet_spot_keyword_1} against {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Secure your base with a substantial layer of {texture_good_1}. Pick up any potential new piece and gauge it with both palms. Squeeze the cloth. Pull it gently between your fingers. Trust your tactile read completely. A screen obscures cheap construction, but actual mass exposes the truth. If it feels flimsy or scratchy, leave it on the rack. You require a crisp drape that holds its shape. This structured foundation allows you to project exactly one polished signal per outfit. Anchor the look with a cool metal accent or a flat, matt finish. The resulting uniform stays totally self-contained and ready for anything.",
      "sectionIntro": "Combine your fabrics to anchor your proportions and establish a clear tactile baseline.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your temperature runs strictly cool. Construct your foundation using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Treat {core_colour_3} like your bright neutral. Depend on {core_colour_4} for dark definition. Introduce deliberate focus using {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Bring in a soft note used sparingly for relief. Leave mustard, rust, and warm olive green on the rack. Beware the pendulum trap. A phase of buying entirely floaty gauze gives way to a phase of entirely crisp utility. Stop swinging. Rely on your own tactile instincts to feel the imbalance. Force those extremes to cooperate. Retain a garment from the opposing end in every combination, permanently. This integration guarantees sensory comfort.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your wardrobe on a strict hierarchy of cool shades to remove daily friction.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Stark navy",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Icy grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
