        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At the desk, clean geometry must drive your decisions. Crisp cotton poplin shirting and sharp worsted wool trousers provide the strict visual boundaries this environment demands. Let tactile ease act as the silent partner. Select fine ribbed merino that moves with you rather than against you. Test your choices in a stationary setting. If you cannot stand waiting in line for twenty minutes without shifting a stiff collar or pulling at a restrictive seam, drop the item back on the hanger. Your focus belongs on the task, not a pinching waistband. Finish with a sleek steel watch or a simple silver cuff. This single bright detail anchors a cool palette of stark navy and icy grey.",
      "sectionIntro": "Here is how to direct your stylistic rules during the working day.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close quarters and low light, clean geometry takes the lead. Dim lighting obscures intricate weaves. Build your silhouette with a stark navy worsted wool trouser and a crisp cotton poplin shirt. Rely on a single silver ring or a steel watch. This cool metal catches ambient light to define your hands. Apply the late-night errand check. A quick trip to the local shop does not require suffering for a shape. If you must pull at a collar or shift a seam to tolerate the cloth, take it off. True adaptability means zero physical distraction. Trust your hands when selecting these items. Feel the fabric. Heavy cloth falls perfectly in shadow and needs zero adjustments.",
      "sectionIntro": "When the lights drop and the space tightens, exact structure matters more than complex texture.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat mundane errands exactly as you treat a structured appointment. A sudden trip to the supermarket does not excuse a lapse in your standard. Build your daily uniform around worsted wool trousers and a fine ribbed merino sweater in stark navy or icy grey. Keep every tone strictly cool. Test the flexibility of a technical nylon coat by reaching for a high shelf. If the fabric restricts your shoulders, leave it on the rack. Enforce your core logic in all contexts. Your rule is always clean geometry + sensory comfort + one polished signal. Anchor the silhouette with a white gold belt buckle or a polished silver watch. If a piece feels stiff when you move, discard it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Construct your daily baseline so it supports your physical habits without requiring constant adjustment.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Fake patinas, hammered copper, and antiqued alloys create visual clutter against a present-day aesthetic. Fix this by demanding brilliant, highly reflective cool-toned metals. Treat {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} as your only valid choices for structural elements and jewellery. Insist on clean geometry in every watch case and buckle to guarantee absolute sensory comfort. Completely reject any {excluded_finish} surface. When evaluating a new piece, lift it directly from the display. Polished surfaces trick the eye easily. Gravitational mass tells the absolute truth. If a clasp or zip feels hollow, leave it in the shop.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your hardware rigorously to maintain absolute structural boundaries across your entire wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select {stone_1} and {stone_2} for their stark clarity. Set them in pure, unornamented mounts to maintain clean geometry. Pick up every piece of jewellery before you commit. A camera flash obscures flaws, but sheer density confirms quality. Let the undeniable weight of the object direct your choices. Avoid matt or artificially aged finishes like oxidised silver and brushed brass. These distressed metals read as visual clutter against your precise clothing. Restrict your hardware strictly to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome. A brilliant, cool finish provides the exact contrast you need against dense worsted wool.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess the density and clarity of your hardware before you attach it to your frame.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the item off the counter and gauge its resistance in your palm. A gleaming surface manipulates perception, but true density remains constant. Before you accept a cool {metal_1} clasp or {stone_1} link, confirm it possesses enough undeniable mass to provide sensory comfort. Skip artificially tarnished finishes, pebbled textures, and brushed elements. Faux-aged hardware distracts from the garment. Keep your jewellery and hardware strictly to a highly polished, mirror-like gloss. This sharp reflection acts as your required finish lane, reinforcing the clean geometry of your shape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply a strict physical threshold to every piece of hardware before it touches your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories act as your one polished signal. They finalise the clean geometry of your garments and anchor your sensory comfort. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Rely on your physical intuition to evaluate an object. Exterior shine misleads the buyer, but the cold, heavy mass of a frame in your hand provides certainty. Execute the final mirror check before you leave the house. Face the glass, identify any item that disrupts your contained silhouette, and take it off. Begin your hardware selection with eyewear. Pick up a thin metal frame cast in a cool, polished silver finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Deploy hardware as a deliberate tool to finalise your silhouette.",
      "rankedItems": [
