    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored pieces require rigid, architectural repeats, while your fluid garments demand structural weaves that drape without distorting. Treat contrast as an adaptable tool. Dial it up with sharper definitions in {recommended_pattern_1} when visibility serves you, or lower it to a whisper for discretion. Apply this physical test to any patterned cloth. Step back across the room. The fabric must register as a calm, even block of cool colour from afar, saving its rewarding structural complexity for a close inspection. Look for {recommended_pattern_2} to build this foundation. Pass over confused prints, blurry graphics, and {avoid_pattern_1} outright. Your motifs must respect your pure clean geometry and never compromise your physical ease or sensory comfort.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your patterns with absolute precision so they serve your structure instead of fighting it.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Hang a patterned garment on a rail and view it from a distance. At this range, the item must read as a flat, cool block of colour. Walk closer. The true structure of a {recommended_pattern_1} should only reveal itself when you are near enough to touch the fabric. This is the proximity check. It ensures your clothing maintains strict, clean geometry instead of broadcasting noise to the rest of the street. Prioritise garments that feel substantial and smooth against the skin. Trusting this physical gauge guarantees both visual discipline and absolute sensory comfort.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this distance check to filter out loud prints before you buy them.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aquarius__moon_taurus__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean geometry + sensory comfort + one polished signal",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on clean geometry + sensory comfort + one polished signal.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Curate your wardrobe with agonising patience, then dress in three minutes flat. This is your rhythm. Your instinct compass is the physical drop and cooling touch of the fabric against your skin. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not. When you pick up a piece, check the internal temperature. It must feel cool to the touch and heavy enough to hold its own shape without relying on your frame. This creates an immediate boundary between you and the environment. You are building an isolation chamber, not a display case.\n\nYour core style formula is clean geometry + sensory comfort + one polished signal. Picture a razor-cut overcoat layered over an oversized dense knit, finished with a single solid architectural watch. This is architecture draped over pure physical relief. Before you acquire a new piece, apply the shelter test. Ask yourself if the garment acts as an impenetrable physical refuge against external demands. If the item clings, pulls, or requires constant adjustment, it fails the test. Leave it on the hanger. You require garments that construct a silent, structured barrier around your personal space.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise the exact structural requirements and sensory baselines that govern your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the shelter test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Sensory comfort begins the moment a garment touches your skin. Trust your hands to evaluate every piece before you try it on. Apply the melt test. Gather the fabric in your fist and release it. If it yields to your body heat and drops without holding a rigid crease, keep it. Look for {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Choose {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Rely on {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Finish your clean geometry with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. Build your foundation from the cool fabrics in this ranked list.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to identify the textiles that construct your wardrobe from the inside out.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed alpaca",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "enveloping winter coats and oversized cardigans"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fluid modal jersey",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers that follow the body without ever gripping it"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed cotton flannel",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "shirts and loungewear that feel like a remembered embrace"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Demand physical truth in everything you touch. Reject {texture_bad_1} immediately. It fails the melt test. If a loose thread met a lighter flame, it would shrivel into hard plastic instead of crumbling to cool natural ash. Rely on your fingers to detect that slick, lifeless surface instead of a deep matt finish. Leave {texture_bad_2} on the rack the moment it squeaks under your thumb. Your wardrobe relies on natural integrity to deliver one polished signal. Artificial threads suffocate and fight your frame. Pass over {texture_bad_3} when it feels brittle or stiff. You demand materials that respond to your movement. Drop any item that feels like a chemical imitation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to reject materials that lie to your hands.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2} in a single outfit. Let the friction between these surfaces do the work. {texture_good_1} sets the perfect baseline for this technique. Drop a sleeve against your bare arm and close your eyes. Notice whether the material dissolves against you or stands rigidly apart. If the weave fights your frame, leave it on the rail. Let the fabric's natural structure guide you. A stiff collar betrays the principle of clean geometry. A knit must collapse into your shoulder line immediately. Keep the tones strictly cool so the surface contrast remains the central focus.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test materials with your hands before putting anything on your body.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your temperature runs entirely cool. Anchor your foundation with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}, bringing in {core_colour_3} for depth and {core_colour_4} as a softer alternative to stark optic shades. Treat {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} as strict, deliberate highlights. Apply your relief tone sparingly, deploying it only as a soft note near the face to ease sharp edges. Pass completely over hard black, harsh neon, and heavy earth brown. Beware sinking into shapeless, unbroken dark layers. Pierce this visual weight with a sudden point of cool polish, such as a textured metal cuff or a tortoiseshell comb, securing your clean geometry.",
      "sectionIntro": "Take hold of your palette, treating these specific shades as the structural boundaries of your wardrobe.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Dove grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Inky navy",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep teal",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Oyster",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Pale aqua",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Smoked mauve",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Faded rose",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep berry",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft oatmeal",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "drowning in formless, head to toe black",
          "fix": "break it with a warm point of light, like a hammered gold cuff or a tortoiseshell comb"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At the desk or in a boardroom, clean geometry always leads. Build the daily uniform around a precise silhouette using structured boiled wool or heavy deep teal silk crepe. Let sensory comfort support this architecture. The materials must feel like a cloud on the inside while presenting strict, uncompromising boundaries to the room. Add a gleaming cool silver watch or platinum ring to act as your one polished signal. A demanding commute does not excuse sacrificing proportion. Choose tailoring that breathes and moves with the body rather than defaulting to shapeless layers. Verify the tangible reality of the items in your hands. If a shirt requires adjustment during a meeting, simply discard it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply these rules to maintain strict boundaries and absolute physical ease at the desk.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim spaces, sensory comfort dictates your baseline. Rely entirely on touch. Drape rich deep teal silk directly on bare skin and test the hems. Slip into cloud-soft lambswool. Fetching a morning espresso does not mean surrendering your precise shape. Maintain straight lines and keep the drape deliberate. Fasten a cool, matt silver cuff at the wrist to deliver one polished signal. Run your hands down the washed silk to evaluate how the fabric falls. Leave behind restrictive waistbands. Let an unstructured dove grey wool coat trace your frame.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your tactile priorities for intimate and low-light environments.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Evaluate the drop of the fabric. The weight of substantial silk trousers provides all the necessary information. A Saturday morning vegetable market run does not require you to abandon clean lines for a slouchy knit. Keep the silhouette crisp. A quick trip to the pharmacy is never an excuse to tolerate items that need constant pulling. Demand the exact same standard from your morning errands as you do for a scheduled appointment. Apply this rule strictly. Every day requires clean geometry + sensory comfort + one polished signal. Put on a relaxed blouse in dove grey and notice how the seams fall. Fasten a cool platinum chain at the collar, then stop.",
      "sectionIntro": "Maintain your dressing standards through every mundane hour of the day.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Anchor your wardrobe in cool metals. Build your foundation with {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. You have the freedom to mix finishes, contrasting a brushed surface against a {excluded_finish} detail. Always evaluate a piece of hardware by lifting it off the table. A heavy clasp feels correct against substantial garments, proving its worth through sheer mass. Watch out for blindingly bright trims. Highly reflective, gleaming chrome introduces a sharp distraction against soft, muted colours. Keep the look cohesive by ensuring your clean geometry relies on matt or brushed textures. This approach keeps your hardware grounded, never competing with your clothes.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish a strict physical standard for your hardware, ensuring every clasp and cuff supports your foundation.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Examine the physical weight of your jewellery. Select solid elements like {stone_1} and {stone_2} to ground your choices. Avoid glaring, over-polished silver casings that break the serene surface of your garments. An intensely glossy finish creates unwanted glare against a subdued, cool palette. Keep your settings brushed and strictly matt to unify the attire seamlessly. Integrate these muted accents with clean geometry to finish the silhouette, delivering one polished signal.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test the density of your hardware before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Check the literal weight of every hardware detail. A solid piece of cool {metal_1} must press firmly into your palm. Steer clear of high-gloss items that project a stark shine next to your quiet luxury foundation. A slick surface shatters the visual cohesion of an understated wardrobe. Select a subdued texture to integrate the element seamlessly into your sensory comfort. This deliberate physical restraint supports strict clean geometry. Verify the mass in your hand before you commit to wearing the piece.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every piece of hardware to a strict physical evaluation.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You established the shape of the garments using clean geometry, and secured physical ease through sensory comfort. Now, your accessories must deliver one polished signal. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start with handbags. Seek full-grain leather featuring a matt body with one polished clasp. Apply the anchor test to every addition. Pick up the item. If it grounds the outfit like a cool steel paperweight holding down crisp documents, keep it. If it pulls focus or feels flimsy, leave it. A true anchor secures the look without demanding attention.",
      "sectionIntro": "This section calibrates your finishing details, ensuring every addition serves the whole.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, matt body with one polished clasp"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Scarves demand strict material discipline. Look for pure silk with a definitively matt finish. A washed silk square in dove grey or deep teal provides the necessary physical weight. Maintain clean geometry in the drape. Test the settling power of the accessory before buying. Arrange the scarf around your neck and gauge its presence. The piece must ground your frame, drawing your posture down into a cool, self-contained state. If the fabric floats away from the collarbone or feels flimsy, drop it. True garments hold their ground and rest exactly where you place them.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your secondary accessories using strict physical standards.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select belts cut from thick deep teal full-grain leather, secured by a cool brushed silver buckle. For keepsake jewellery, seek out aged brass featuring a single polished gold accent. This careful blend of mixed patina and polish gives the piece depth without looking pristine. Press the metal against your skin to guarantee absolute sensory comfort. Before finishing dressing, perform a strict visual check for grounding gravity. Locate the heaviest element anchoring your clothes to your frame. If any lingering chain or thin strap distracts from this central weight or breaks strict clean geometry, remove it immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every final addition to ensure it physically supports your baseline rather than fighting it.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged brass with a polished gold accent, mixed patina and polish"
        },
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed buckle"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored garments take their pattern from structural weaves. Fluid pieces take theirs from the subtle shift of thread. Keep your contrast low and tonal to preserve a cool palette. Seek out {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. Maintain clean geometry. Trust the twilight test. Inspect the fabric in dim evening light. If the motif jumps out as a harsh graphic, leave it on the rack. The surface must merge into a rich, deep texture. This subtle approach ensures you always prioritise sensory comfort above visual noise.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control pattern by treating it as an extension of texture rather than a decorative addition.",
      "tests": [
        "the twilight test (merge into a rich, deep texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Subject your {recommended_pattern_1} to a low-light check. Hang the garment across a dim room and step ten paces back. The print must blur. It should lose its sharp edges and melt into a deep, rich shadow. If the shapes still fight for attention, leave the item on the rail. A successful print behaves like a texture. Pick it up and feel the weave to confirm its sensory comfort. Rely completely on this tactile evidence to verify your clean geometry, ensuring every piece delivers one polished signal without relying on graphic distraction.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this strict visual check to filter out prints that disrupt your baseline.",
      "tests": [
        "the twilight test (merge into a rich, deep texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
