    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Pick up the bag and check the hardware. Look for a smooth leather crossbody with highly polished zips in a cool metal like steel or platinum. Maintain clean geometry in the bag structure. It must sit flat against your ribs without bouncing. Squeeze the strap and assess the material's resistance. If the leather feels rigid or brittle under your fingers, leave it on the shelf. Perform a final evaluation before heading out. If the strap distorts the shoulder of your deep teal sweater or adds bulk to your frame, take it off. The bag must adapt to your clothing.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject your functional accessories to the exact same physical scrutiny as your core garments.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather crossbody, polished zips"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Ground your base with smooth leather footwear. Demand a clean gloss finish that catches the light. Pair this with a steel case watch. Select a high polish finish to establish a cool metallic point of focus against soft textures like cloud-soft lambswool. Maintain strict clean geometry across these final accessories. They must anchor every honest fabric in your wardrobe without competing. Finally, run the last-look test. Stand before the mirror and assess the silhouette. If a shoe buckle or a watch dial feels like a rogue element breaking your self-contained structure, take it off. Trust your hands. If your fingers instinctively hesitate over a clasp, the item is wrong. Remove it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your final accessories through weight and structure to ensure absolute visual cohesion.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather, clean gloss"
        },
        {
          "name": "Watch",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "steel case, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Maintain clean geometry by treating weave as your primary motif. Tailored pieces take their patterns strictly from the physical construction of the cloth. Fluid garments take theirs from the print. Keep your contrast adaptable, choosing low-contrast tonal variations for core items and sharper graphic definition for lighter layers. Apply the arm's-length test to every piece. It must project a calm, cool, even texture from across the room, only revealing a rewarding weave when you inspect it close up. Trust your tactile instincts over printed illusions. Build depth with {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Pass over loud novelties. Avoid {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. Rely on a matt finish to keep the lines sharp.",
      "sectionIntro": "Here is how to navigate scale and contrast without compromising your structure.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Hang the garment across the room and step back. At ten paces, a {recommended_pattern_1} should dissolve into a continuous, cool texture. Walk closer. At arm's length, the structure must resolve into sharp focus. This is the visual threshold you need to preserve clean geometry across your wardrobe. If the motif looks muddy from afar or chaotic up close, drop the piece. Rely on this strict distance rule to weed out fussy prints. Your goal is always clear lines layered over honest fabric. A pattern must never obscure the cut. It must only reveal its complexity when you pull the textile close to inspect the weave.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the strict logic of distance to evaluate every print.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aries__moon_aries__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean impact + sharp edges + one hot accent",
    "closing": "Always let your hands assess the literal weight of the material, trusting that physical resistance to guide you toward clean impact + sharp edges + one hot accent.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your hands to find structure. Pick up a garment and test its resistance. If the fabric collapses in your grip, drop it. Your baseline requires a warm, polished armour that holds its own shape. Memorise your formula: clean impact + sharp edges + one hot accent. Picture a heavily structured, sharp-shouldered jacket worn over a smooth, rigid column dress. Add a single, massive piece of high-shine hardware at the wrist. Keep everything strictly self-contained. The silhouette must never bleed into the background.\n\nBuild your wardrobe slowly, but assemble your looks with rapid precision. Before leaving your home, stand at the front door and apply the entrance test. Step across the threshold. If the outfit feels like a quiet apology or hesitates before you do, take it off. Your clothes must strike the eye the exact second you appear. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight and structural momentum do not. If a garment makes you feel obscure, discard it completely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master this core blueprint before you buy another garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the entrance test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Seek materials that hold a firm shape to ensure your wardrobe delivers clean impact and sharp edges. Apply the drape check before you buy. Hang the fabric over your bare arm under a direct overhead bulb. Rely entirely on your bodily response. Tags deceive. Cast shadows tell the truth. If the darkness thrown on your skin blurs at the borders, leave the garment on the rack. You require a textile that cuts a hard silhouette. Stock {texture_good_1} for sharp shirting that holds a crease and snaps visually. Anchor your structure with {texture_good_2} for knife-edge tailoring that never begs for a steamer. Deliver one hot accent in {texture_good_3} for statement footwear and accessories that reflect maximum warm light. Rely on {texture_good_4} for slip dresses and linings that gleam under low light. Prioritise these precise finishes.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands and eyes to identify the strict structural materials that build your foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "sharp shirting that holds a crease and snaps visually"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sharp wool twill",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "knife-edge tailoring that never begs for a steamer"
        },
        {
          "name": "Patent leather",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "statement footwear and accessories that reflect maximum light"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk satin",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "slip dresses and linings that gleam under low light"
        },
        {
          "name": "Techno gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "wrinkle-resistant trousers and jackets that keep a rigid shape"
        },
        {
          "name": "High-shine taffeta",
          "role": "rank 6",
