          "failure": "the beige-out: every piece at the same pale value looks unfinished rather than minimal",
          "fix": "rescue it with a graphite anchor piece or a bottle green accent, and let one texture change restore the depth"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, clean impact takes the absolute lead. You must build a sharp geometry using worsted wool trousers and a crisp cotton poplin shirt. This precise base requires zero adjustment during the day. Support this strict foundation by adding removable knits that slip on smoothly. A fine ribbed merino jumper in warm taupe handles dropping office temperatures without destroying the neat silhouette. Finish the uniform with a single point of heat. A dual-register watch or a piece of polished jewellery provides necessary friction. Maintain this exact standard beyond the desk. Test your discipline on a Sunday morning. Buying fresh produce from a local stall is still a true occasion. Pick up the tailored trousers for this errand, rather than reaching for loungewear.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish your working uniform by setting a strict geometry.",
      "tests": [
        "a farmers' market run is still a small occasion (Hearth)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim environments, one hot accent takes the lead. Discard stiff garments. Build a base of fine ribbed merino directly against the skin. Read the fall of worsted wool through simple touch. An evening out requires precise execution. Pair a soft camel knit with matt gold jewellery and a sharp steel watch to hit both metal registers. Grip the cloth tightly to ensure it drops cleanly against your body.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master low-light environments by bringing the fabric directly to your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "a farmers' market run is still a small occasion (Hearth)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat a Tuesday morning run to the post office as a genuine event. Do not abandon your baseline for mundane tasks. Demand garments that perform under active use. Select worsted wool trousers and a warm camel technical nylon shell for weather resistance. Maintain the exact same discipline you apply to a major meeting. Your daily equation remains clean impact + mobile layers + one hot accent, regardless of the destination. Fasten the silhouette with dual gold and silver hardware, ensuring the metal catches light while the fabrics stay flat and matt.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your baseline routine without lowering your standards.",
      "tests": [
        "a farmers' market run is still a small occasion (Hearth)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Divide your metals into two distinct categories. For jewellery resting directly on your body, choose {personal_metal_1} and {personal_metal_2}. For structural elements like belt buckles, zips, and bag hardware, rely on {structural_metal_1} or {structural_metal_2}. This split allows you to maintain a warm temperature without looking overly matched. Pick up every piece of hardware before buying. Substantial metal grounds mobile layers and gives them a definitive shape. Avoid hammered copper, antiqued brass, and artificially aged pieces. They generate visual clutter and fight a polished finish. Keep your hardware highly reflective. Rely entirely on brilliant {personal_metal_1} and mirror-like {structural_metal_1}. Leave {excluded_finish} behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the distinction between personal and structural hardware to construct a unified system.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Hold the settings in your palm. Heavy, solid components indicate reliable construction. Skip artificially weathered finishes, rough textures, and blackened patinas. They introduce unnecessary noise and disrupt smooth mobile layers. Keep your metals strictly to high-gloss, mirror-reflective finishes to maintain a polished dual-register system. Select stones based on absolute clarity and density. Look for {stone_1} to capture and hold warm light without scattering it. Introduce {stone_2} when a dense, unbroken surface is required. Keep all settings flush and structural to prevent the stones from catching on threads.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply strict physical standards to evaluate every piece of hardware.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "A photograph can deceive your eye. Density reveals the actual quality. Ensure every buckle, ring, and collar pin carries substantial heaviness. Reject tarnished treatments entirely. They create visual friction, ruining a clean impact. Opt for solid, polished {metal_1}. When applying one hot accent, anchor it with the heavy, smooth clarity of {stone_1}. This guarantees your hardware remains sharp and present, supporting a warm palette without introducing unnecessary friction.",
      "sectionIntro": "Measure the physical density of every accessory before incorporating it into your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You build the foundation for clean impact. You adapt to shifting environments with mobile layers. Use accessories to deliver exactly one hot accent. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Run every addition through the function test. Question its physical utility before you put it on. If an item catches on a doorframe or clinks heavily against a keyboard, reject it. Begin your collection with silk scarves. Choose a tightly woven silk band that holds a neat knot and casts a soft, polished glow. Look for warm dyes that reflect light upwards without slipping down your collar.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your accessories to direct visual focus and anchor the final layer of your outfit.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk band, soft glow"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Keep fine jewellery focused and highly polished. Select a thin gold chain to provide exactly one hot accent over camel knitwear or a technical nylon shell. Apply the snag check before you buy it. Fasten the clasp, drop the chain down your chest, and reach for a high shelf. If the metal catches on your collar or twists into knots during motion, leave it on the counter. The piece must offer a high polish surface to reflect light cleanly. A warm finish creates the necessary contrast, but only if the chain performs without requiring constant adjustments.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your jewellery for mechanical performance and precise visual contrast.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin gold chain, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Finish the system with a small structured bag. Select a smooth leather crossbody in camel with polished fine hardware. This piece delivers clean impact without interrupting your stride. Wear it across your mobile layers. Add one hot accent, perhaps a warm coral silk cord tied to the strap. Before heading out, run a strict one-handed operation check. Open the main clasp while walking. If the mechanism sticks or demands a flat surface to close, the design fails. Discard any bag that requires your full attention to operate.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your daily uniform with a final utility piece and pressure test its efficiency.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather crossbody, polished fine hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Your pattern strategy shifts to serve the occasion. Keep contrast low and tonal for standard days, then scale up the graphic intensity when you require clean impact. Tailored shapes take their geometry from the weave itself. Look for {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} woven directly into the cloth. Fluid garments accept printed motifs, provided they remain grounded in a warm temperature. Apply the desk test to any new design. Assess the garment from an arm's length and a half away. It must read as a sharp, deliberate texture. If the lines blur into mud, drop the hanger. Build your foundation, add lightweight mobile layers, then deploy pattern as your one hot accent. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Pattern serves as a structural tool, scaling in intensity to suit your environment.",
      "tests": [
        "the desk test (read as clean texture at arm's length and a half)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the seated reach gauge. Hang a {recommended_pattern_1} piece over a chair exactly an arm and a half away from where you sit. At this precise distance, the print must stop registering as a defined graphic and start reading as a rich, warm texture. If the pattern still demands attention, reject the piece. You require clean impact to anchor your garments. A loud motif breaks visual continuity. Trust your own sight on this blur effect. The design must dissolve into a polished surface, preparing the ground for one hot accent without dominating the frame.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this physical distance check to ensure your prints remain functional and cohesive.",
      "tests": [
        "the desk test (read as clean texture at arm's length and a half)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aries__moon_aries__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean impact + sharp edges + one hot accent",
    "closing": "Follow the heavy weight of the fabric and the cold density of the metal to build clean impact + sharp edges + one hot accent.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your physical reaction to visual weight. You need garments that feel substantial in your hands and look distinct on the body. Look for fabrics that hold a rigid line. Your personal formula is clean impact + sharp edges + one hot accent. Picture this. You pair a heavy wool architectural coat over a sharply cut silk shirt and a rigid gabardine trouser. The base remains totally graphic and polished. You finish it with a single, highly saturated, warm accessory. The look snaps into focus. This creates a solid block of impact. Avoid anything matt that drapes weakly or blends into the background.\n\nCurate your garments slowly and deploy them fast. A self-contained wardrobe requires rigorous editing. You must apply the hesitation test to every new acquisition. If you put on a jacket or pick up a structured bag and pause because the shape feels vague or the finish lacks a hard gleam, put it down. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. If you have to stand in front of a mirror and convince yourself the piece has enough visual volume, it fails the test. Rely entirely on sharp geometry and deliberate construction.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish this baseline to ensure every garment you acquire serves your exact structural requirements.",
      "tests": [
        "the hesitation test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Demand textiles that construct sharp edges and maintain a polished surface. Base your foundations on {texture_good_1} for shirting that holds a severe crease and snaps visually. Choose {texture_good_2} for knife-edge tailoring that never begs for a steamer. When applying one hot accent in a warm tone, rely on {texture_good_3} for statement footwear that reflects maximum light. Finish your internal layers with {texture_good_4} for slip dresses that gleam under low light. Rely on tactile feedback to guide your choices. Mirrors deceive, but touch reveals the truth. Execute the friction test on everything you consider. Stroke the sleeve swiftly and seek a glassy slip. If your palm catches or drags across the weave, put the hanger back.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every garment with your hands to secure the materials that build your visual fortress.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "sharp shirting that holds a crease and snaps visually"
        },
