    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Avoid materials that absorb light and blur your sharp edges. {texture_bad_1} is a trap. Pick it up and feel the weave. If it grips your skin, discard the garment. {texture_bad_2} fails immediately because it clings and softens your outline. Demand a frictionless glide from every surface. When a fabric pulls against your fingers, it ruins your clean impact. {texture_bad_3} might look warm on the rail but feels lifeless and matt on the body. Let your fingertips make the final decision. If the material drinks illumination rather than throwing it back, leave it behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify and reject the materials that blur your boundaries and dilute your presence.",
      "tests": [
        "the friction test (run your hand swiftly down the sleeve; seek the slip)"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your signature material pairing relies on extreme contrast to create sharp edges. Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to force a boundary between garments. Do not blend your layers. Keep the separation harsh. Test this physical boundary by rubbing the two fabrics together. You require zero friction between the pieces. If the textiles snag against each other, the combination fails. Bring in {texture_good_1} to add heat to the structure. This locks a warm, polished shell around a completely self-contained core, ensuring clean impact throughout.",
      "sectionIntro": "Combine contrasting materials to build a hard boundary between your layers.",
      "tests": [
        "the friction test (run your hand swiftly down the sleeve; seek the slip)"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette requires a strictly warm temperature. Build your base using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} in sharp wool twill for dense structure. When you require a stark slate, choose {core_colour_3}. Use {core_colour_4} to bridge tonal gaps without losing heat. Keep your relief tone, a precise note used sparingly, to separate heavy blocks of colour. Now execute your formula of clean impact + sharp edges + one hot accent. Deliver that heat exclusively through {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Reject muddy pastel, icy grey, and dusty sage entirely. Assess intensity closely under natural light. If a dye feels weak or apologetic, discard the garment. Beware the fade trap. Washed-out pieces dilute your visual weight. Rescue a dark foundation immediately with a saturated silk scarf at the neckline or a bright patent shoe.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your palette by anchoring your wardrobe in warm foundations before injecting a single jolt of power.",
