    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At the desk, clean impact leads. Build your base from sharp wool twill and crisp cotton poplin. Keep the silhouette direct and self-contained. Test your garments before you put them on. Pick up the wool and gauge its drop. A heavy drape never lies. Support this strictness with internal complexity, using heavy silk satin linings or warm gold hardware where only you notice them. Finish with a singular bright focus. A golden camel patent leather shoe cuts through the formality. Apply this rule universally. Stepping out for a quick espresso does not mean switching off your bold atmosphere. Refuse to drop your guard for a minor errand.",
      "sectionIntro": "Construct your working uniform as a deliberate extension of your own physical rules.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, let hidden depth lead. Dimmed rooms strip away bright colour, leaving only the drape and the hand of the cloth. Rely on heavy silk satin in deep bronze to catch the warm ambient glow. Keep your lines absolute. Ground the look in heavy metals. A solid gold cuff over crisp cotton poplin provides a sharp focal point. Apply your own bakery rule. A ten-minute walk for morning sourdough does not mean stripping off your heavy silk satin or diluting your bold expression. Maintain your firm edges, even at a quiet corner table.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the art of the evening, where close quarters require absolute physical conviction.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A mundane trip to the pharmacist is no excuse to dilute your aesthetic. Rely on your hands to judge a garment. Heft reveals quality. Anchor your look in a warm deep bronze or a sharp wool twill coat in golden camel. Your style demands clean impact + hidden depth + one hot accent every time you leave the house. Pair your structured base with sharp patent leather boots or a gleaming gold collar. Maintain strict boundaries around your personal presentation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat every ordinary morning as a deliberate aesthetic decision.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Establish a warm dominant hardware strategy using {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Reject {excluded_finish}, hammered, or oxidised surfaces outright. Antiqued edges look exhausted and lose their sharp definition. Stay strictly with polished warm metal that flashes from across the street. Pick up a solid {metal_1} chain before you commit to it. Judge the piece by its gravity in your bare hand. Appearances deceive. Grams tell the truth. Trust the sheer physical mass of a heavy watch case or a gleaming {metal_3} buckle to deliver clean impact.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every zip, clasp, and link as structural armour rather than mere decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Look for absolute density and fierce clarity in your jewellery. When you select a {stone_1} or a {stone_2}, grasp it in your bare hand. A stone must possess enough physical gravity to anchor your look and provide necessary hidden depth. Avoid battered, tarnished, or artificially aged pieces. These treatments read as exhausted and lose their sharp edge. Demand gleaming warm metal that reflects the sun from a block away. This brilliant, unyielding surface guarantees clean impact. Deploy a dense {stone_3} in a polished warm setting as your one hot accent. Let the heavy metal stand alone against your clothing.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones and metals using sheer density and brilliant reflection to construct your hardware.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the item in your palm before you buy it. Vision can trick you into accepting cheap hollow construction. Sheer weight never does. Rely on the heavy anchor of a solid piece resting in your hand. Avoid hammered, oxidised, or antiqued finishes entirely. They pull down your polished aesthetic, appearing weary and imprecise rather than bold. Demand strictly mirror-bright surfaces in warm {metal_1} that bounce the afternoon sun into the eye of a passerby. This highly reflective finish provides the exact gleam required to serve as your one hot accent. If a piece feels light or looks slightly dull, put it back.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this physical test to guarantee your hardware delivers the necessary gleam.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Anchor your garments in clean impact and hidden depth, then build in your one hot accent. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start with statement jewellery. Seek out a solid, high-polish warm yellow gold cuff. Trust your hands. Pick the item up and test its density. Flimsy metals warp. Run the auditorium test before buying. Place the cuff on a counter and walk away. If you cannot instantly read its high polish and bold geometry from the back row, reject it. Fine details vanish at a distance. You need dense, self-contained objects.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your silhouette by mastering the exact weight and placement of your hardware.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Statement jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "high-polish yellow gold cuff, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the stage test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Assess your footwear through the distance test. Put the shoe on the floor and retreat twenty paces. If the shine fades into a dull smudge, leave it on the shelf. You require high gloss and uncompromising patent leather to serve as your one hot accent. Pick up the boot and inspect the reflection. You must see a sharp, mirror-like gleam bouncing back at you. Trust your hands to verify the slick, impenetrable boundary. Choose a deep bronze or golden camel colour in these strict, lacquered finishes. A polished exterior builds a self-contained barrier. Reject suede and brush away any canvas. Your foundation demands rigid structure and brilliant, warm surfaces.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your footwear by demanding strict, high-gloss finishes that refuse to fade.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "patent leather, high gloss"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the stage test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Hunt for a structured bag with a rigid top-handle and highly polished hardware. Choose rigid patent leather to deliver your one hot accent. Verify that every clasp and lock aligns with your warm metal strategy. Before considering the outfit complete, check the total silhouette. Step away from the mirror and observe the proportions. If the bag blurs into your coat or loses its strict geometry, drop it. You require clean impact from afar. Only keep pieces that hold their boundaries firmly. Open the bag and inspect the lining to guarantee it holds the hidden depth you demand. Seek out thick suede or smooth calfskin interiors that completely refuse to slouch.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your geometry and apply a final check of visual distance.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Structured bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "patent leather top-handle, polished hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the stage test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor your warm tailored garments in rigid, geometric patterns. Reserve your fluid pieces for sweeping, large-scale motifs. Your aesthetic requires high visual voltage. Commit to designs that are high-contrast and graphic. Treat a striking print as your one hot accent against a solid, polished base. Seek out {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1}, {avoid_pattern_2}, and anything visually timid. Subject every piece to a twenty-foot distance check. Walk away from the glass. If the pattern blurs into a muddy wash rather than remaining bold and entirely legible, leave the garment on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every print as a deliberate structural choice rather than mere decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the twenty foot rule (bold and entirely legible from twenty feet)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Measure every {recommended_pattern_1} against the clarity threshold. Hang the garment on a door frame and reverse twenty steps. If the edges blur, leave it alone. You require patterns that maintain clean impact from across the room. A smeared motif signals hesitation. Look for sharp, polished lines that read perfectly from the opposite end of a train carriage. If a design forces a viewer to squint to decipher the shape, the piece fails. Anchor your warm palette with absolute precision. You need boundaries that stay entirely defined. This rigid structure gives you the perfect foundation to deploy one hot accent without the main pattern dissolving into an ambiguous mess.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this strict distance test to strip weak or indecisive prints out of your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the twenty foot rule (bold and entirely legible from twenty feet)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aries__moon_cancer__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean impact + hidden depth + one hot accent",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on clean impact + hidden depth + one hot accent.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe with slow, deliberate precision. Trust the physical weight of the weave in your hands as your sensory compass. Heavy, dense fibres anchor you. Flimsy knits betray you. Apply the shelter test to every new garment. Close your eyes and ask if the cut creates a silent boundary between your skin and the outside climate. If the garment feels like an exposed vulnerability rather than an insulated fortress, leave it on the rack. Your orientation is entirely self-contained. You do not dress to broadcast your presence to the street. You dress to secure your own perimeter.\n\nYour core style formula is clean impact + hidden depth + one hot accent. Picture a heavily structured wool overcoat layered over a fluid silk knit, anchored by a single piece of deeply heated hardware at the collar. The coat delivers the sharp exterior structure. The interior silk provides the private, tactile depth. The solitary pin introduces a concentrated strike of warm temperature to break the visual silence. This is how you assemble your uniform. Anchor your foundation in matt finishes and severe cuts, then conceal softer, fluid fabrics against your skin. Deploy your single accent with absolute restraint.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this foundational logic to evaluate every garment before you even attempt to wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "the shelter test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe on materials that feel complete in isolation. Look for fabrics that deliver clean impact without requiring complex styling. Apply the touch test before you buy. Assess the surface strictly by hand. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Accept only materials that feel warm and substantial in the palm. Choose {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Rely on {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without dragging you down. Look for {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Seek out {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. Prioritise the fabrics ranked below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your wardrobe in materials that pass the closest physical inspection.",
      "rankedItems": [
