  "venus_aries__moon_capricorn__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean impact + softness + one hot accent",
    "closing": "Trust the raw physical weight of your garments to dictate the boundaries of clean impact + softness + one hot accent.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your physical instincts are the only metrics that matter. Read the garment through your hands before you look in the mirror. Notice the exact drape of a heavy silk against your collarbone and the dense, warm weight of a woven wool on your shoulders. Build your wardrobe slowly. Curate pieces with ruthless precision over time, then pull them together fast on the morning you need them. Apply the visceral exit test to every new purchase. If your stomach tightens in doubt when you touch a hanger, leave the item on the rail and step out of the shop. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.\n\nYour guiding equation is clean impact + softness + one hot accent. Anchor your outfits with structural precision. Introduce a yielding fabric to sit near the skin, then finish with a single saturated focal point. Picture a razor-sharp tailored overcoat worn over a fluid knit roll-neck, paired with a heavy matt leather glove in a concentrated shade. The coat provides the boundary. The knit provides the ease. The glove holds the tension. Keep your focus entirely on your own physical experience of the clothes. You dress to secure your own boundaries, not to engage an audience.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise these structural rules before you buy another garment.",
      "tests": [
        "trust your gut and walk away"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe on materials that deliver clean impact and softness without asking for attention. Grip the fabric tightly when shopping. Crush a sleeve of {texture_good_1} in your fist. It must spring back immediately to prove its resilience. Seek {texture_good_2} for your bags and belts, allowing it to patinate and mould to your habits over time. For your tailored outerwear, require {texture_good_3} to hold a sharp edge and a solid shoulder. Introduce {texture_good_4} against your skin for fluid movement. Apply the candlelight test to every surface. If a material looks flat and lifeless in dim, warm evening light, leave it on the rail. Only invest in fibres that catch a low glow and reflect it back.",
      "sectionIntro": "Demand materials that do the physical work of structure and flow so you do not have to.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
        {
          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Rely entirely on touch to identify poor quality. Squeeze a handful of {texture_bad_1}. If it springs back with a synthetic crackle, drop it. Run your bare thumb over {texture_bad_2}. If it feels slick, hollow, or snags your skin, leave it on the hanger. Check the surface under low illumination. Under dim, warm lighting, cheap threads always give themselves away with a harsh, plastic sheen instead of a rich, matt glow. Your clothing forms a strict personal boundary that demands absolute material integrity. When you anchor a look with one hot accent, the underlying fabric must be physically flawless. Let your hands do the sorting.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to reject subpar materials before you even check the label.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to guarantee clean impact. This pairing builds the structured shell of your self-contained uniform. Introduce {texture_good_1} to provide crucial softness. Compress the yardage in your palm and feel the resistance. High quality yields and recovers, while cheap construction simply wrinkles. Move into a dim space and hold the item near a match flame. If the fibres swallow the illumination and go completely flat, leave the piece behind. If they catch the warm glow and reflect a rich sheen back onto your skin, buy it. Contrast this lustre with a strictly matt finish elsewhere.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your signature pairing by relying on your hands and eyes.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette runs exclusively warm. Anchor the foundation with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Bridge these base elements using {core_colour_3} and {core_colour_4}. Reserve your relief tone as a quiet note used sparingly to ease visual tension. Deliver clean impact against those stable grounds by finishing with {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Pass over icy electric blue, neon brights, and fleeting trend pastels. Wearing head-to-toe {core_colour_1} reads like you surrendered before leaving the house. Break up that flat block with a {core_colour_2} layer, a deep {accent_colour_1} scarf, or a heavy {core_colour_3} belt.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your choices in a deliberate, self-contained spectrum.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rich toffee",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Taupe",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Stone grey",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft cream",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Olive",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Moss green",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Oxblood",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Burgundy",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Plum",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Misty blue-green",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "head-to-toe black reads like you gave up on the way out the door",
          "fix": "break it up with a camel layer, a deep wine scarf, or a rich cognac belt"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, crisp tailoring delivers clean impact. Support this strict outer shell with absolute softness in the layers touching your skin. Pair a precise brushed wool blazer with a warm toffee silk blouse. A stiff collar pressing into your neck fails the pharmacy line test. If you cannot stand in a queue for ten minutes waiting for a prescription without adjusting a rigid seam, take the garment off. Construct a self-contained system that requires no fuss. Finish the look with a single hot detail, like a heavy gold ring or a thick chain. Ensure the metal is heavy and the finish mixed, leaving some surfaces matt. The tailoring provides the boundaries. The silk provides the ease.",
      "sectionIntro": "Demand absolute physical function from your workwear.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, softness leads your formula. Ground your evening choices in tactile fibres. Layer a matt camel cashmere jumper over a fluid silk shirt. Anchor the lower half with clean impact using rich toffee full-grain leather trousers. Include one hot accent with a warm, heavy gold pendant resting against the knit. Apply a strict comfort metric. Sitting quietly in a dimly lit corner wearing this exact combination must feel entirely natural. Never accept garments that require suffering for a silhouette. If a rigid seam restricts your movement, leave the piece behind. A truly self-contained aesthetic demands total physical ease.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your intimate evening settings by letting tactile fabrics and absolute physical comfort govern your choices.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A quick trip to the grocer for milk never justifies abandoning your standards. Treat every mundane errand as a strict practical trial for your garments. Pull a rich toffee cashmere jumper over a perfectly cut camel trouser. Check the mobility in your shoulders. If the fabric restricts your stride or pinches when you carry a heavy basket, donate the item immediately. Even on a completely unremarkable Tuesday, your baseline remains clean impact + softness + one hot accent. Anchor this warm palette by sliding a heavy brass cuff onto your wrist before you step out the door. Let the weight of the metal ground you while you navigate the street.",
      "sectionIntro": "Enforce your aesthetic boundaries across every routine task and transit.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Anchor your wardrobe with a warm dominant strategy. Select {metal_1} and {metal_2} as your primary hardware choices. You can incorporate {metal_3} in minor details if the overall temperature remains warm. Lift every chain and zip in your palm. A shiny surface will deceive you, but heavy mass reveals the actual quality. If the hardware feels hollow, drop the piece. Be ruthless with finishes. High-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to warm colours. It shatters the visual harmony. Stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive and protect the inherent softness of your garments. Avoid {excluded_finish} entirely. Use a single piece of substantial {metal_1} jewellery to serve as your one hot accent.",
      "sectionIntro": "Examine every zip, clasp, and ring as closely as the fabric it binds.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Test every stone and casing for physical density. Anchor your look with a heavy {stone_1} or a deep {stone_2}. This serves as your one hot accent. When reviewing clasps and watch cases, reject anything with a mirrored silver polish. That icy glare cuts harshly against your warm base colours. Always select matt or heavily brushed metals to keep the components cohesive.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every piece of hardware for density and light retention before it enters your collection.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Gauge {metal_1} by its physical heft before committing. Substantial weight indicates correct construction. When selecting your one hot accent, steer clear of high-polish chrome. Glossy, mirror-like silver reads as sharp and distracting against the softness of your warm palette. Select brushed or matt finishes instead. A matt surface ensures the hardware integrates seamlessly without breaking the visual line.",
      "sectionIntro": "Rely on physical weight and surface finish to dictate your hardware choices.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments supply the clean impact and the softness. Accessories exist solely to provide your one hot accent. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Apply a ruthless mirror rule before stepping outside. If a secondary item fights for attention, take it off immediately. One strong piece is always enough. Begin this process with handbags. Seek out full-grain leather bags featuring a completely matt body, interrupted by exactly one polished clasp. Let tactile feedback guide you. A solid clasp rests heavily in your hand, and thick, warm leather settles securely against your ribs.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use accessories as deliberate focal points to anchor your foundational garments.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, matt body with one polished clasp"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Look for silk scarves with a completely matt finish. Gloss creates visual friction. Rely on your fingers to find heavy, opaque silk. A warm camel textile folded tightly against the neck gives you necessary softness without disrupting a tailored shoulder. Put the scarf on and assess the visual balance. If the fabric knot competes with a thick collar chain or lapel pin, take the metal off. One single strong focal point is enough. A rich toffee silk serves perfectly as your one hot accent. Strip away any competing noise near your face and let the dense weight of the material dictate the rest of the styling.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your fabric accessories as precision tools for controlling texture and framing the face.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your warm wardrobe with keepsake jewellery that balances mixed patina and polish. Seek out aged brass featuring a polished gold accent. Fasten a full-grain leather belt finished with a brushed buckle. Let pure physical substance verify the craftsmanship. Assess the item without looking at it. If the metal feels flimsy, discard it. Before stepping out, execute a strict subtraction check to guarantee clean impact. Find the specific piece of hardware competing for attention and take it off. Pare the extras back until a solitary item remains to serve as your one hot accent.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your hardware by testing its physical density and stripping back the excess.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged brass with a polished gold accent, mixed patina and polish"
        },
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed buckle"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Your pattern strategy demands low-contrast tonal execution. Tailored structures take their visual rhythm from the physical weave. Look for {recommended_pattern_1} woven directly into the cloth. Fluid garments take their design from dye. Choose {recommended_pattern_2} or {recommended_pattern_3} to maximise drape and softness. Apply this physical test in the fitting room. Step three paces back from the mirror and unfocus your vision. A successful pattern will dissolve into a warm, unified texture. If the design stays sharp and fights the eye, leave it on the rail. Keep your core garments quiet. Pass over high-contrast {avoid_pattern_1} and stark {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. Channel any severe graphic energy solely into your one hot accent.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every pattern by how quietly it integrates into the physical garment.",
      "tests": [
        "step back and soften focus (blur into texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate prints from across the room. The details of {recommended_pattern_1} must blur together into a rich, warm wash of colour. If the shapes remain aggressively distinct from a distance, the textile fails. You require absolute softness in the overall impression to maintain clean impact up close. The design must read as an extension of the fabric itself. If the motif fights for visual dominance, it will drown out your one hot accent. Reject the item entirely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Run every printed garment through this visual distance test.",
      "tests": [
        "step back and soften focus (blur into texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aries__moon_gemini__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean impact + light movement + one hot accent",
    "closing": "Rely on your hands to evaluate the cloth, adapt to your changing environments, and always secure your foundation with clean impact + light movement + one hot accent.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your physical instinct for calibration. Your strongest pieces will always feel physically adaptable, wrapping you in a warm flexibility that breathes and shifts as your day changes. Build slowly, deploy fast, and let your daily combinations drift by mood. Gather these versatile anchors over months, and rely on them to pivot when required. Your formula is clean impact + light movement + one hot accent. Picture a sharply tailored jacket worn over a fluid, draping midi dress, finished with a single, highly polished ring. This creates immediate balance without locking you into a rigid aesthetic. If a garment feels too stiff or demands a perfectly curated environment to work, drop it immediately.\n\nAlways apply the treaty test before you buy. Ask yourself if the garment can negotiate a lasting peace agreement between two completely opposing environments. A great piece must broker an alliance between a morning sprint and an unexpected late dinner. Pick up the item and test its diplomatic range. If it forces you into a corner or requires an entire supporting cast of new clothes just to make sense, put it back on the rail. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight and adaptability do not. You need garments that travel across boundaries, carrying a polished finish that holds up under close scrutiny.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation, the core logic you must apply before any garment enters your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the treaty test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe around materials that deliver clean impact and light movement. Start with {texture_good_1} for shirting that holds an architectural boundary. Layer this over {texture_good_2} for close-to-body base layers with sharp lines. For trousers, require {texture_good_3} to ensure they drape cleanly and resist creasing. Finish with {texture_good_4} for mobile outerwear that blocks the wind. Validate every purchase with the two-hands test. Grasp the garment with both palms. If the fabric feels cumbersome or fights your grip, walk away. The right material feels fluid and responsive. Your hands will detect cheap construction before your eyes register it. These polished textures provide the flawless baseline you need before adding one hot accent in a warm metal.",
      "sectionIntro": "Filter every fabric through the lens of sharp boundaries and easy motion.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Investigate the fibre. Grab a section of the cloth in each fist, pull gently, and roll the threads between your fingers. If the material feels hollow or brittle, drop it. Avoid {texture_bad_1} entirely. It generates a cheap friction that ruins the clean impact you require. Steer clear of {texture_bad_2} for the same reason. It behaves like stiff paper and refuses to drape over warm skin. Watch out for {texture_bad_3}. It traps heat and snaps back with rigid hostility. Your skin recognises substandard weaving instantly. If the garment scratches, clings, or restricts your joints, leave it on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise failure before a piece ever reaches the fitting room.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your ideal combination relies on tension. Pair {sweet_spot_keyword_1} against {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to build a structured base. Add {texture_good_1} to ensure light movement. To verify the quality of this pairing, test the drape across your own frame. If the threads stiffen uncomfortably or hang without form, reject the piece. You require a clean glide. A polished surface must feel smooth to the touch, anchoring warm tones seamlessly. Rely on tactile feedback. Genuine density provides the final confirmation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Locate the precise combination of textiles that anchors your core silhouette.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette relies strictly on a warm temperature scale. Anchor your foundations with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} for heavy-duty garments like worsted wool trousers or a technical nylon jacket. Swap stark whites for {core_colour_3}. Keep {core_colour_4} close by to unite different layers. Deploy your relief tone solely as a soft note used sparingly. Bring the combination to life with one hot accent, pulling from {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} to inject deliberate heat. Pass over Icy pastel, Neon brights, and Cold blue-grey completely. They drain your baseline. Watch out for the seesaw trap. You might find yourself wearing all floaty gauze one month, and the next all crisp utility. Re-weave instead. Keep one item from the other hand in every outfit, always. This discipline guarantees clean impact and light movement.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your working colours as a strict set of tools rather than a random collection of choices.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Warm taupe",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
