      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your accessories deliver that crucial one hot accent. Worsted wool secures your needed clean impact. The cut of your garments maintains light movement. Control the visual heat by limiting yourself to one or two focused pieces per look. Begin with silk scarves. Knot a silk band at the throat to cast a soft glow against warm taupe layers. Subject your outfit to the last-look test. Stand before the glass and strip away any item that tips a balanced, polished register into clutter. Verify the fluidity of the accessory yourself. If the textile feels stiff, synthetic, or fails to flow naturally around your neck, leave it behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Curate your accessories with a ruthless editor's eye, demanding that every addition serves a distinct physical purpose.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk band, soft glow"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Treat fine jewellery as the baseline for your warm palette. Fasten a thin gold chain and run it across your collarbone. Rely on this tactile interaction as your definitive guide. If the links snag or drag on your skin, reject the item. You require a high polish finish that reflects light without catching on your technical nylon layers. This gleaming surface delivers exactly one hot accent against a warm taupe or camel foundation. Evaluate the geometry of the arrangement before departing. If the metal disrupts the symmetry of your neckline rather than settling smoothly against the cloth, remove it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your metals through strict physical criteria to build a cohesive accessory collection.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin gold chain, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your silhouette with a small structured bag. Compress the sides of a smooth leather crossbody. It must resist pressure. This rigid construction delivers absolute clean impact against a warm taupe coat. Inspect the hardware closely. Require polished fine metal clasps that shine cleanly without bulk. Secure a slender strap that permits gentle sway to supply necessary light movement at your hip. Execute a strict editing pass before stepping outside. If your bag clasp, earrings, and shoes all fight for dominance, eliminate the heaviest distraction immediately. Strip the visual noise down to leave exactly one hot accent.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your final anchoring accessory and enforce a strict visual filter before you leave.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather crossbody, polished fine hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored garments draw pattern from the weave. Fluid pieces take graphics from physical motion. Your adaptive approach means contrast scales with context. Keep warm foundational items tonal. Let your one hot accent carry sharper contrast. Apply the arm's length test. Hold the garment out. The surface must settle into an orderly solid from afar to project clean impact. Pull it close. A rich weave must reward the eye. If the graphic turns to static, discard the idea. The literal thread reveals the truth of the garment. Anchor structured pieces with {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Select {recommended_pattern_3} to enhance light movement in fluid layers. Ignore {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. Pass over {avoid_pattern_2}. Chaotic prints destroy a polished finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Approach pattern strictly as a tool to manipulate structure and physical motion.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the three-pace blur test to every printed piece. Hang the garment on a door frame and step back three paces. Assess the {recommended_pattern_1}. At this distance, the individual shapes must blur into a solid wash of warm colour. Step closer. The motif should only snap into focus when you are near enough to read a watch dial. If the print remains sharply legible from across the room, walk away. You need patterns that read as an unbroken surface from afar, functioning as one hot accent only when viewed up close.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this physical distance test to verify a pattern works for your proportions.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aries__moon_gemini__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean impact + light movement + one hot accent",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on clean impact + light movement + one hot accent.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your physical response to restriction. If a garment dictates your posture, leave it on the hanger. Build your wardrobe slowly, deploy it fast, and let your daily assembly drift by mood. Hold an item and check its weight. It should feel substantial enough to hold a shape but light enough to ignore. Your core formula is clean impact + light movement + one hot accent. Picture a crisp cotton shirt tucked into fluid wool trousers, finished with a single warm, polished metal pin. The structure provides the frame. The fabric provides the ease. The single point of heat provides the focus.\n\nRely on gravity to prove a garment's worth. Lift the piece and watch the drop. If the cloth clings, bunches, or requires constant pulling to maintain its line, put it back. You require cloth that respects the space between the material and your skin. Pick up garments that possess a matt finish for your base layers. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is the structural logic of your wardrobe, the foundation you use to build every outfit.",
      "tests": [
        "the fall test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your textures must deliver clean impact and light movement to provide a warm foundation for one hot accent. Seek out {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Find {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without dragging you down. Select {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Finish with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. When evaluating a new garment, rely on the edge test. Pinch the hem or collar and fold it back on itself. If the fold stays rigid or the boundary feels stiff against your thumb, put the item back. Master these materials by letting your fingertips make the final decision on quality.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the materials that serve your framework.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed alpaca",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "enveloping winter coats and oversized cardigans"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fluid modal jersey",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers that follow the body without ever gripping it"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed cotton flannel",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "shirts and loungewear that feel like a remembered embrace"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the edge test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Leave {texture_bad_1} on the hanger. It promises a crisp shape but feels like sandpaper against the collarbone. Test this immediately in the shop. Roll the cuff between your fingers. If the cloth holds a rigid crease instead of yielding, it will never deliver light movement. {texture_bad_2} is another trap. Drag your palm across the surface. If the fibres feel hollow, they will fight your body. You require clean impact and a warm touch from your textiles, not a stiff cage. Reject {texture_bad_3} entirely. Crush the sleeve in your fist. If the material stays crumpled, it ruins your polished baseline. Demand materials that cooperate.",
      "sectionIntro": "Your hands will tell you when a fabric is going to fail before you even put it on.",
      "tests": [
        "the edge test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Test the boundary of any new garment before you buy. Grip the collar of a {texture_good_1} jacket and press firmly. If the rim collapses or turns mushy under pressure, leave the item on the rail. You require a sharp outer boundary that constructs clean impact while permitting light movement through the main body of the fabric. Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to lock in a polished, self-contained silhouette. Rely on your hands to verify this structural integrity. Dense construction tells the truth. Complete the outfit by placing one hot accent in a warm metal tone near the neckline.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your signature texture combination by evaluating how fabrics behave in your hands.",
      "tests": [
        "the edge test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette relies on a fundamentally warm baseline. Build your foundation with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Ground these bases with the structural depth of {core_colour_3} or the earthy anchor of {core_colour_4}. Deploy the relief tone purely as a soft breath of air to separate heavy blocks of colour. Design a system that guarantees clean impact. Secure light movement through washed silk, then strike the baseline with one hot accent using either {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Pass over stark optic white, harsh neon, and icy pastel. Leave them on the rack. Beware the total freeze. Unbroken grey on grey presents as a void rather than true composure. Fix this immediately by introducing high shine. Add a heavy brass cuff, a patent leather boot, or a single line of electric dye.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your colours as physical materials for building structure, never as mere decoration.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bitter chocolate",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Dark mahogany",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Blackened indigo",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep forest green",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Burnt umber",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Washed black",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Burnt amber",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rich cognac",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Misty taupe",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "total ice: unbroken grey on grey can read as absence rather than composure",
          "fix": "add the polished signal, a mirror-finish cuff, a patent boot, or one line of electric colour"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Lead with clean impact for business hours. Let a dark mahogany blazer in heavy silk crepe do the structural heavy lifting. Anchor the shape with this precision, then introduce light movement below the waist. A wide trouser in washed silk softens the overall silhouette. Avoid stiff tailoring. A long schedule asks for yielding cloth that adapts to your stride, not rigid armour that fights your body. Gauge the drape by holding the hanger at arm's length. A full-length mirror might trick your eye, but the downward pull of heavy silk offers absolute certainty. Finally, deploy one hot accent at the collar. A dense gold chain stacked with a slim silver watch adds enough friction to keep the warm palette sharp.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your working days around clothes that perform under pressure.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "Close proximity in low light demands tactile precision. Reach for heavy silk crepe or cloud-soft lambswool in dark mahogany. Squeeze the piece in your fist. A demanding evening does not require rigid tailoring. It requires soft, pliable fibres that breathe with you through a long dinner. Base your choice on clean impact. Bring light movement to the cuff, and ground the look with one hot accent. Achieve this by pairing a polished warm metal ring with a matt chain. Check the material's give before committing. If the textile feels brittle or stiff under your thumb, leave it behind. You need pliable weight that yields to the touch without losing its structure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Close proximity and low light require a total shift in tactile priorities.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Build your daytime uniform for endurance. An overloaded itinerary does not require stiff canvas or hard collars. It requires a bitter chocolate washed silk shirt and polished boiled wool trousers that move flawlessly as you cross the city. Rely on your immediate physical response to the garment. If a seam restricts your stride, discard the piece. Apply this standard strictly, even at the supermarket checkout. Buying milk on a Sunday morning does not suspend your baseline. The requirement remains constant. Your daily equation is clean impact + light movement + one hot accent. Anchor a dark mahogany knit with a polished gold and silver pendant. Inspect the texture near a window. Ensure the warm colour retains its depth under flat daylight.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat an average Tuesday as the proving ground for your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Divide your hardware strategy into two separate lanes. For jewellery worn directly against the skin, select warm tones like {personal_metal_1} or {personal_metal_2}. For structural elements like buckles, zips, and bag clasps, switch to {structural_metal_1} or {structural_metal_2}. Keep every surface strictly polished. Avoid {excluded_finish} surfaces and artificially aged patinas. Hammered textures read as visual clutter when you demand clean impact from your wardrobe. Treat a high-shine metal piece as your one hot accent. Pick up the item and let it rest in your palm. Vision deceives you, but mass tells the absolute truth. A substantial zip or a dense clasp grounds your silhouette, keeping you completely self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Manage your metals in two distinct categories to keep your styling precise.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select stones that deliver one hot accent without overwhelming the frame. Lift the object off the tray before you buy. Judge the piece by how it sits in your hand. Trust that physical heft as your absolute guide. Choose dense, light-catching minerals like {stone_1} and {stone_2}. Set them against warm metals. Artificially aged hardware, hammered textures, and oxidised finishes register as visual clutter. They dilute your clean impact. Reject them entirely. Keep all your settings highly polished and mirrored. This high-shine finish provides the exact rigid structure needed to anchor your softer garments.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware by its physical density and its ability to reflect light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift a piece of jewellery or a belt buckle off the counter. Drop it into the palm of your hand. Feel the downward pull to verify its quality. Trust this tactile weight to guide your selections. A dense {stone_1} ring or a solid metal clasp provides the perfect anchor, functioning directly as your one hot accent. Avoid blackened brass, beaten copper, or any alloy subjected to artificial aging. These distressed elements read as distracting noise against a self-contained look. Demand a pristine reflection. Keep exclusively to highly polished, warm {metal_1} and brilliant, unblemished surfaces to secure a sharp, present-tense finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this immediate tactile test to ensure your hardware carries genuine physical authority.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Establish your foundation for clean impact. Build the shape for light movement. Then use your accessories to deliver exactly one hot accent against your warm palette. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start with eyewear. Choose a thin metal frame in polished silver. Before finalising the outfit, apply the one-signal test. Check the mirror for visual competition. If the silver frame fights with a belt buckle, remove the belt. Focus entirely on the tactile reality of the object. Pick up the frames and feel the smooth metal. If the surface feels dull rather than highly polished, put them down.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your final additions as precision instruments for sharpening the look.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin metal frame, polished silver"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Anchor your warm wardrobe with a smooth leather crossbody. Trust your fingers to check the surface tension. Run your thumb across the leather to confirm a completely smooth, unbroken expanse. Demand polished zips that glide freely without catching. Execute the one-signal test before leaving the house. Place the bag against a cloud-soft lambswool knit. If the piece introduces competing shapes rather than delivering exactly one hot accent, drop it. Every bag must function as a perfectly self-contained unit. Avoid excessive hardware, exterior pouches, or swinging tags. Let the strict shape and polished finish carry the weight.",
      "sectionIntro": "Interrogate every accessory for its structural integrity before bringing it into contact with your garments.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather crossbody, polished zips"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your foundation in smooth leather footwear with a clean gloss. This polished finish grounds warm bitter chocolate tones without fighting the rest of your garments. Keep your timepiece equally sharp. Select a watch featuring a steel case and a high polish to act as a precise focal point. Before finishing, scan your outfit from head to toe for conflicting messages. If your shoes, your steel watch, and your clothing are all demanding attention simultaneously, strip the excess away. Remove competing items until your look leaves exactly one hot accent standing alone. Rely on your skin to tell you what belongs. The cold weight of polished metal or the rigid resistance of fresh leather will confirm immediately if a piece fits your standard.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your accessories and strip away the excess to ensure absolute precision.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather, clean gloss"
        },
        {
          "name": "Watch",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "steel case, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Scale your pattern contrast to the garment, adapting from subtle weaves to sharp graphics as your environment shifts. Structured tailoring takes its pattern directly from the loom. Seek out {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} set in warm, densely woven threads. Subject these garments to the straight-edge test. Step back three metres from the mirror. The geometry must remain sharp and unyielding. If the boundaries blur, leave the item on the rack. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1}, {avoid_pattern_2}, and any weak prints. Fluid pieces draw their pattern from the dye. Let printed washed silk carry softer motifs to ensure light movement across your silhouette. Deliver clean impact by contrasting these fluid prints against solid boiled wool. Complete the arrangement with one hot accent pinned to the collar. Run your fingers over structured jackets to confirm the pattern is woven into the cloth. Trust this physical texture to guide your final choice.",
      "sectionIntro": "Pattern brings structure and rhythm to your wardrobe, demanding ruthless editing to maintain a polished finish.",
      "tests": [
        "the straight-edge test (lines stay crisp and true at three metres)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Stand three metres back from the garment and apply the straight-edge test. Look for absolute clarity in the boundaries. If the edges of a {recommended_pattern_1} begin to bleed, blur, or vibrate into the background colour at this distance, leave it on the rail. You require clean impact to anchor your styling. A muddy print disrupts your self-contained visual logic. Check the linework specifically. The shapes must hold their defined borders perfectly. A warm motif needs this strict geometry to succeed without looking messy. Trust your immediate read. If you have to squint to decipher the shape across a shop floor, the pattern lacks the polished execution you require.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this visual check to ensure any print serves your architecture rather than fighting it.",
      "tests": [
        "the straight-edge test (lines stay crisp and true at three metres)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aries__moon_leo__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean impact + athletic space + one hot accent",
    "closing": "Let the literal weight of your garments set your boundaries, anchoring your physical presence in clean impact + athletic space + one hot accent.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe with clinical patience, but dress with immediate velocity. Trust your body's response to friction and speed. When you pick a garment up, feel for structural resistance and smooth action. The fabric must hold its own shape before it touches your skin. Always apply the radius test to every piece you consider. Put the garment on and measure your physical perimeter. If the cut shrinks your wingspan, catches on your shoulders, or tangles your stride, leave it on the rail. You require unbroken, self-contained space to move. Look for warm, polished surfaces that reflect light sharply rather than swallowing it. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.\n\nMemorise your exact styling equation. Your formula is clean impact + athletic space + one hot accent. Picture a heavily constructed track trouser with a razor-sharp front crease, paired with a dense, boxy t-shirt that stands entirely away from the ribs. That provides the baseline structure and the breathing room. Finish the look with a single, highly polished pendant catching the light. That provides the concentrated heat. Never dilute this equation with fussy details or unnecessary layers. Keep the silhouette sharply defined and completely independent. Every item you wear must earn its place through pure visual force and unrestrictive geometry.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the fundamental mechanics of your personal style before you buy another piece of clothing.",
      "tests": [
        "the radius test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe around polished materials that hold their shape and deliver a warm, self-contained energy. You require clean impact from your garments. Rely on {texture_good_1} for sharp shirting that holds a crease and snaps visually, and choose {texture_good_2} for knife-edge tailoring that never begs for a steamer. These structural bases create the athletic space you need to showcase one hot accent. Amplify that accent with {texture_good_3} for statement footwear and accessories that reflect maximum light. Close to the skin, use {texture_good_4} for slip dresses and linings that gleam under low light. Before purchasing, execute the bounce test. Flick the hem with your fingers. The fabric must spring back to attention instantly to earn a place on this list.",
      "sectionIntro": "Your best fabrics deliver strict structure and high shine.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "sharp shirting that holds a crease and snaps visually"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sharp wool twill",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "knife-edge tailoring that never begs for a steamer"
        },
        {
          "name": "Patent leather",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "statement footwear and accessories that reflect maximum light"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk satin",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "slip dresses and linings that gleam under low light"
        },
        {
          "name": "Techno gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "wrinkle-resistant trousers and jackets that keep a rigid shape"
        },
        {
          "name": "High-shine taffeta",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "evening pieces that bounce light and cut a clear silhouette"
        },
        {
          "name": "Polished calfskin",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "footwear and accessories with a slick, radiant surface"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the bounce test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Reject anything that blurs your edges or clings without resistance. Apply a crush check to every new garment. Squeeze the material in your fist and release it. If it stays wrinkled or slumps lifelessly against your palm, drop it. You need textiles that dictate their own volume to deliver clean impact. Avoid {texture_bad_1} entirely. Its fuzzy surface absorbs light and muddies your warm colour palette. Step away from {texture_bad_2}. It hangs weakly and stretches out of proportion by midday. Pass over {texture_bad_3}. The flat finish drains the physical intensity you require. Let your fingers decide. If the material feels flimsy or overly porous, it fails.",
      "sectionIntro": "Eliminate materials that dilute your physical boundaries.",
      "tests": [
        "the bounce test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Contrast {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to guarantee your clean impact. Your chosen textiles must command their own volume. Fold a length of {texture_good_1} in half and press down hard on the crease. Let go and watch it smooth out instantly. If the fold line lingers, leave the item behind. You need this rapid recovery to maintain architectural tension around your frame. Anchor a stiff, matt weave against a slick surface. Picture a heavy cotton sleeve pushed up to reveal warm gold hardware. Rely on physical resistance. Your clothing must feel crisp, heavily structured, and ready to slice through the air.",
      "sectionIntro": "Nail your ideal combination of cloth to control your structure.",
      "tests": [
        "the bounce test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette is strictly warm. Anchor your base with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Substitute stark whites with {core_colour_3}, and bridge these tones using {core_colour_4}. Treat your relief tone strictly as a soft note used sparingly. Bring your exact style formula to life: clean impact + athletic space + one hot accent. Achieve this by injecting {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} to slice through the neutrals. Pass over muddy pastel, icy grey, and dusty sage completely. Beware the trap of a suffocating, ink-dark monochrome uniform that swallows your physical outline. Fracture that unbroken block immediately. Add oversized reflective metal at the wrist or vivid footwear in {accent_colour_2}.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your colours as a strict operating system.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Deep bronze",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Golden camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
