    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Pick up {texture_bad_1} and evaluate the perimeter directly. If the edge feels thick, rolls inward, or refuses to lie flat, drop the item. It will buckle against your frame. You require absolute precision to sustain your clean impact, and anything flimsy destroys that sharpness. Brush your fingers over {texture_bad_2}. If the surface catches on rough skin or carries an oily sheen, it fails. Your warm palette requires deep, matt textures to absorb light properly. Slick materials scatter light irregularly. {texture_bad_3} poses a similar threat. Pull gently at the cuff. If the knit stretches and fails to snap back instantly, leave it on the rack.",
      "sectionIntro": "Identify the materials that sabotage your form before you even try them on.",
