    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Give tailored garments pattern through the structural weave itself. Fluid pieces must take their pattern from the dye. Maintain clean impact by keeping your pattern contrast strictly low and tonal. Anchor your wardrobe with {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. Apply the underwater test to every printed garment. The motif must look like dappled warm light shifting on a sandy seabed. It must never read like high-contrast commercial signage. If the shapes hold strict borders, return the item to the rail. Your style requires blurred edges to function.",
      "sectionIntro": "Command pattern as an extension of texture to build quiet depth rather than visual noise.",
      "tests": [
        "the underwater test (read like light moving on the seabed, not signage)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate every print from a distance before you take it to the till. Hang a {recommended_pattern_1} garment across the room and step back ten paces. Narrow your eyes until the room goes soft. The motif must dissolve into a gradient of diffused warmth. If the graphic remains rigid and reads like sharp street signage, put the item back on the rail. You require patterns that instantly melt into blurred edges from afar. Let your own vision dictate the choice rather than the sales tag. This optical collapse ensures the textile serves your core structure, leaving exactly enough quiet space for one hot accent.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test every print against your own visual gauge before it earns a place in your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the underwater test (read like light moving on the seabed, not signage)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aries__moon_scorpio__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean impact + quiet undercurrent + one hot accent",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on clean impact + quiet undercurrent + one hot accent.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "When you pull a garment from the rail, gauge the weight and the breath of the fabric. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Your aesthetic demands a completely self-contained precision. Look for a dense, woven drape that offers a warm, protective envelope without restricting your movement. Construct your wardrobe at a slow, deliberate tempo, demanding absolute perfection in the cut, so you can deploy an outfit fast when dressing.\n\nYour dressing logic follows a strict equation: clean impact + quiet undercurrent + one hot accent. Picture a razor-sharp tailored coat layered over a fluid, matt underlayer, anchored by a single piece of heavy hardware at the collar. Before you commit to any purchase, apply the shelter test. Put the item on and determine if the shape builds a secure, private boundary against the noise of the street. If the construction feels flimsy or leaves your silhouette exposed, leave it on the rack.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the fundamental architecture of your personal style before you buy another piece.",
      "tests": [
        "the shelter test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "To build a wardrobe with clean impact, you must select materials that feel entirely self-contained. Rely on {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to warm candlelight. Pick {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Source {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Anchor these lighter layers with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. To verify a fabric belongs in your quiet undercurrent, apply the breath test. Hold the textile against your inner wrist and exhale slowly. If the material traps the air and feels instantly stifling, drop it. If it regulates your heat and breathes with you, keep it. Rely on this specific sensory feedback to curate your rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to evaluate a textile blindly to build your textural foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed alpaca",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "enveloping winter coats and oversized cardigans"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fluid modal jersey",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers that follow the body without ever gripping it"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed cotton flannel",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "shirts and loungewear that feel like a remembered embrace"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Avoid {texture_bad_1}. Crush a handful of the material in your fist. If it fights back with a rigid squeak and traps heat, leave the garment on the rack. Reject {texture_bad_2} immediately. Brush the surface over your inner wrist. The harsh bite disrupts the warm, quiet undercurrent you require. Drop {texture_bad_3}. It hangs stiffly and refuses to drape, undermining the fluid canvas needed to support your one hot accent. Trust your hands to detect these material failures.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to reject materials that fail your basic standards before you even try them on.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your central material balance relies on combining {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Pick up an item made of {texture_good_1}. Drape it heavily over your forearm and gauge how your muscles respond. If the piece allows you to drop tension completely, keep it. This bodily reaction establishes your quiet undercurrent. Pair this yielding base with a sharp shape to secure clean impact. Anchor the entire combination with one hot accent in a warm, matt finish. Avoid anything shiny or stiff that forces you to hold your ribs rigid. Trust your fingers to detect the difference between true ease and synthetic construction.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your material contrasts to anchor your daily choices.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Establish a self-contained foundation by pairing {core_colour_1} with {core_colour_2}. Ground these lighter base layers using {core_colour_3} or {core_colour_4} to build sharp, structural definition. Every colour you adopt must carry a distinct, warm temperature. Deploy the relief tone sparingly as a soft note to break severe lines. Leave stark optic white, harsh neon, and icy pastel on the rack. Deliver clean impact by introducing {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as a deliberate focal point. Avoid the trap of sinking into a shapeless, entirely dark silhouette. When you wear heavy layers, fracture that void with a glowing detail. Pick up a hammered gold cuff or slide a tortoiseshell comb into place. Let the physical weight of these distinct accents direct your daily dressing.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your palette by assigning strict jobs to each shade.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bitter chocolate",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Dark mahogany",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Blackened indigo",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep forest green",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Burnt umber",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Washed black",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Burnt amber",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rich cognac",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Misty taupe",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "drowning in formless, head to toe black",
          "fix": "break it with a warm point of light, like a hammered gold cuff or a tortoiseshell comb"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "When dressing for work, let clean impact take the lead. Build the foundation with heavy silk crepe tailored in dark mahogany. Support this crisp exterior by slipping a quiet undercurrent close to the skin. Reach for washed silk or cloud-soft lambswool to ensure internal comfort. A busy commute or a midday shop dash does not mean you must sacrifice this deep, tactile softness. Trust your hands to select fibres that feel reassuring and warm. Finish the look with one hot accent in polished gold to capture the office light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to calibrate your formula for the physical demands of the working day.",
      "tests": [
        "a school run or a corner shop dash does not require surrendering your softness (Cove)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In low-light settings, your quiet undercurrent must lead. Rely on tactile warmth to draw the eye closer. Reach for a dense cashmere knit or a fine merino slip in dark espresso. Dim lighting absorbs sharp details. It rewards the drape and weight of the fabric on the skin. Apply this strict rule for private evenings indoors. Moving from the dining table to the study does not require surrendering your yielding base layers for a rigid jacket. Maintain your clean impact. Finish the look with one hot accent in a warm metal. Let a thick brass collar or a single polished bronze cuff catch the candlelight.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the mechanics of low-light settings and close proximity.",
      "tests": [
        "a school run or a corner shop dash does not require surrendering your softness (Cove)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Build your morning routine around dense cotton drill and heavy linen. Stepping out to collect the post does not require surrendering your structural precision. Demand the same rigour for a mundane errand as you do for a formal appointment. Ground your daily layers in dark slate and warm metals. Do not dilute your uniform just because the calendar is empty. Your constant baseline must be clean impact + quiet undercurrent + one hot accent. Run your thumb over the seam. Your fingers will recognise quality before you even check the mirror. Reject anything flimsy. Keep your lines sharp and your colours deep. Never drop the standard.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your mundane routines as the strict testing ground for your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "a school run or a corner shop dash does not require surrendering your softness (Cove)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Establish a warm metal strategy to anchor your wardrobe. Let {metal_1} and {metal_2} dominate your structural zips and buckles. You can then deploy a distinct piece of {metal_3} as your one hot accent. Always lift a chain or cuff to test its value. Visuals trick the eye, but sheer density reveals true quality. Reject {excluded_finish} hardware outright. Highly reflective chrome silver glares sharply against soft, muted colours and shatters a quiet undercurrent. Fix this immediately by demanding matt and brushed textures to keep your entire look cohesive.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your hardware with the exact same rigour you apply to inspecting a winter coat.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Lift {stone_1} from the jeweller's tray and rest it in your palm. Ignore clever faceting. Let sheer physical gravity guide your selection. Choose dense materials that gather warm light internally rather than scattering it blindly. A heavy cut of {stone_2} serves perfectly as your one hot accent against heavy crepe or boiled wool. Beware the trap of intensely faceted, glittering gems. A brilliant cut pierces straight through soft woven fibres and creates harsh visual noise. Anchor your settings strictly in smooth, cabochon, or matt textures to build an unbroken, cohesive surface.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every stone by its physical density and its capacity to hold light without shouting.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "If you choose {stone_1} as your one hot accent, ensure the setting carries substantial weight. Pick up the piece of {metal_1} and test its balance in your palm. Let this tactile response direct your final selection. Avoid overly glossy coatings. A heavily lacquered surface creates a sharp, jarring distraction against warm fabrics. Rely on gently cast, matt metal to ensure your hardware maintains clean impact.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test the integrity of your hardware before it touches your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Establish clean impact. Maintain that crucial quiet undercurrent. Now, allow your accessories to deliver one hot accent. Hold yourself to a strict limit of one or two strong pieces per look. Start with handbags. Demand full-grain leather, choosing a completely matt body broken only by a single warm polished clasp. Pick the bag up by the strap to test its physical gravity. Apply the anchor test. An accessory must possess enough structural density to pull a self-contained silhouette firmly downwards. If the hardware feels hollow or the leather lacks substantial drag, leave the item on the shelf.",
      "sectionIntro": "Execute your accessory strategy by applying strict limits and demanding physical density.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, matt body with one polished clasp"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Limit your scarf selection to matt silk. Reject any surface sheen and focus entirely on the density of the weave. Pick the fabric up and fold it in half to test its physical grip. Wrap it around your neck and drop your hands. If the material slips or shifts when you move, put it back. It must act as an anchor that sits heavily and holds its shape against your collar. A dense length of heavy silk in a warm rust provides exactly one hot accent against dark foundations. Trust the friction of a dull finish. A slippery surface ruins your clean impact.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate the physical grip of your finishing pieces before you bring them near your face.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Build your keepsake jewellery around warm aged brass featuring a single polished gold detail. This friction between mixed patina and polish creates immediate clean impact. Anchor your garments with full-grain leather belts, checking that the hardware is a solid brushed buckle. Finally, apply the cohesion test. Stand still and gauge the combined weight of your components. Every accessory must pull the outfit inwards into a self-contained unit. If a chain or bracelet scatters your focus or fights against your one hot accent, take it off immediately. Depend entirely on your tactile response. If the object feels light, frail, or fails to ground your look, abandon it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your silhouette by strictly filtering the remaining elements that ground your frame.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged brass with a polished gold accent, mixed patina and polish"
        },
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed buckle"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Draw the pattern for your structured coats directly from the physical weave of boiled wool. Pull the pattern for your fluid garments from subtle dye shifts in washed silk. Enforce a strict low-contrast tonal rule. Every piece must read as a singular, warm, matt surface from across the room. Trust your hands to navigate this terrain. Sight deceives. Thread reveals the truth. When viewed from a distance, the motif must dissolve entirely into a heavy, tactile surface rather than fighting the eye. Seek out {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Skip {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. Pass over printed synthetics, stark geometrics, and flat painted stripes. Let your structured tailoring provide clean impact. Build your quiet undercurrent with subtle woven textures. Finish with one hot accent in a completely solid finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the use of pattern by evaluating its physical weave rather than its printed design.",
      "tests": [
        "the twilight test (merge into a rich, deep texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Take a garment featuring {recommended_pattern_1} and hang it across the room. Turn down the lamps, step away, and squint. This is the twilight test. If the shapes remain distinct and fight for attention, reject the piece. The design must dissolve into a wash of warm colour as the light drops. It should mimic a dense woven surface rather than acting as a flat graphic. This physical collapse guarantees your clean impact. When the print melts into a unified background in dim conditions, it provides a solid foundation. From there, you can introduce one hot accent without cluttering the silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the twilight test to assess the legibility of any pattern before it enters your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the twilight test (merge into a rich, deep texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aries__moon_taurus__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean impact + sensory comfort + one hot accent",
    "closing": "Trust your physical intuition to guide you toward clean impact + sensory comfort + one hot accent.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your physical instinct is a radar for friction. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. If a garment scratches, restricts your shoulders, or forces you to adjust it when you sit, leave it on the rail. Your dressing logic relies on a precise equation. Build every outfit around clean impact + sensory comfort + one hot accent. Picture a sharply tailored trouser cut from a soft woven cloth paired with a seamless knitted top. That provides the clean lines and the physical ease. Then add one heavy, highly polished piece of warm metal at the collar. The base handles the daily reality. The single bright addition cuts through the visual noise.\n\nConstruct this wardrobe methodically over time. Treat your garments as independent components, assembling them rapidly each morning to meet the specific climate and physical demands of your day. You are dressing for your own independent mobility. Apply the flight test to everything you buy. Pick up the garment and ask yourself if you could sprint across a departures terminal in it, sit in a cramped seat for six hours, and walk straight into a dinner reservation without changing. If the fabric restricts your stride or crumples instantly, it fails the test. Prioritise a polished finish that survives actual movement. Let that physical reliability dictate every purchase.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is the structural logic of your wardrobe and the physical standard every garment must meet.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your formula requires sensory comfort. Achieve this by selecting materials that hold their structure without fighting your joints. Run your hands over every piece. If a fabric cannot withstand an eight-hour train ride and emerge with a polished, warm finish, reject it entirely. Pick up {texture_good_1} for shirting that delivers clean architectural boundaries and pure separation. Build your close-to-body base layers with {texture_good_2} to maintain sharp lines and continuous breathability. Select {texture_good_3} for trousers that drape precisely and resist creasing through a demanding schedule. Seal the system using {texture_good_4} for lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs nothing. These fibres guarantee clean impact.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your materials strictly on how they function and feel against your body.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
