    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Inspect the jewellery by pulling on the chain or pressing the closure. Flimsy clasps and hollow links fail the basic requirement of sensory comfort. Drop them and move on. Scratched details and dull patinas introduce messy noise into a self-contained wardrobe. They register as distraction. Maintain an absolute strictness for polished {metal_1}. A slick, reflective finish delivers the exact precision required for one hot accent against a warm foundation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every piece of hardware to a strict physical test before it enters your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories provide your one hot accent. Anchor this final warm detail against the clean impact of your garments, ensuring the item never compromises your baseline sensory comfort. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start your selection with eyewear. Seek out thin frames in polished metal that shape the face without adding clutter. Subject every outfit to the subtraction rule. Before leaving the house, remove a single piece. If your silhouette remains fully self-contained rather than stripped bare, leave that extra item on the table. Rely on your physical intuition to determine when the geometry is complete.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat accessories as a strict discipline of selection, applying finishing elements that respect your physical boundaries.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin metal frame, polished silver"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Select your daily bag for sheer physical efficiency. Pick up a smooth leather crossbody. Check the hardware. You need polished gold zips that glide without catching. Put the bag on and load it with your actual belongings. Subject it to a movement trial. Walk briskly down a hallway. If you must adjust the strap or stop the pouch from swinging awkwardly within ten paces, put it down. A bag must grant sensory comfort and preserve your self-contained momentum. It serves as your mobile base. Keep the leather surface unblemished and let the warm metal hardware function as one hot accent against a camel exterior.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your bags as mechanical tools designed to secure your routine.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather crossbody, polished zips"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your foundation with smooth camel leather footwear holding a clean gloss. Fasten a polished watch case to cut through your warm dominant metals. These specific choices generate the clean impact required by your formula. Eliminate the excess. Review the final item of jewellery you put on. If the structure holds its authority without that bracelet or ring, leave the extra piece in its box. A self-contained silhouette requires zero clutter to guarantee absolute sensory comfort.",
      "sectionIntro": "Ground your formula with precise hardware and leather, then strip away the excess.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather, clean gloss"
        },
        {
          "name": "Watch",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "steel case, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Force your tailored garments to take their visual rhythm from classic menswear geometries. Fluid pieces must draw their shapes from organic repetition. Rely on {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} to build an adaptable foundation. Keep your pattern contrast adaptive, shifting between low-contrast tonal layers for subdued environments and sharper lines when the space demands it. Reject {avoid_pattern_1} entirely because it introduces visual clutter. Organise your wardrobe around solid foundations, then deploy a single patterned accessory as your one hot accent. Always evaluate a print up close. The design must register as an integrated element of the weave. If the motif looks stamped on the surface, leave the garment on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your patterns strictly before they overwhelm your frame.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Hang {recommended_pattern_1} on a door. Step back ten feet and walk quickly past it. Trust your peripheral vision as it catches the blur. A successful print dissolves into a soft, pleasant texture when you are in motion. If the motif remains stark or highly legible from a distance, it fails the test. You require garments that prioritise your baseline sensory comfort. A highly defined graphic disrupts that physical equilibrium. Build a quiet foundation using warm tones. Reserve your visual energy for one hot accent.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the Hallway Test to every patterned garment before purchasing.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_aries__moon_virgo__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "clean impact + honest fabric + one hot accent",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on clean impact + honest fabric + one hot accent.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your physical compass is adaptability. You need garments that shift contexts without dragging you down. Build your wardrobe slowly. When you dress, deploy fast and drift by mood. Your foundation is clean impact + honest fabric + one hot accent. Picture a sharp, structural jacket cut from dense, matt cloth, anchored by a single point of warm, polished hardware. The silhouette does the work. You do not need to fuss with it.\n\nTrust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. When you evaluate a new garment, apply the seam test. Run your fingers over the interior construction. If the stitching feels brittle or the hem hesitates against your skin, put the piece back. You require garments that maintain a self-contained finish under pressure. The interior architecture must support your movement without friction. A weak seam signals a garment that will warp when you adapt to a new environment. Trust your hands. If the structure feels weak, the garment is useless to you.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this core blueprint. It is the architectural foundation of your wardrobe and the physical standard you will use to evaluate every garment you touch.",
      "tests": [
        "the seam test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Anchor your warm palette in honest fabric to guarantee clean impact. Seek out {texture_good_1} for shirting that maintains strict architectural boundaries. Layer this over {texture_good_2} to keep your close-to-body shapes sharp. For trousers, choose {texture_good_3} to ensure a polished drape that refuses to crease. Finish with {texture_good_4} for lightweight outerwear that moves easily. When evaluating a new piece, always apply the recovery test. Crush a handful of the cloth tightly in your fist and release it. Watch how quickly the creases fall out. If the material stays crumpled, put it back on the rail. Rely on the raw material to guide you. Optics deceive. The literal weave tells the truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to identify materials that hold their shape and deliver structure without fuss.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the recovery test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Rely on your hands to judge a textile. Touch never lies. Run your fingers over {texture_bad_1}. If it feels artificially slick and traps warm air against your skin, it fails. Test every blend for resilience. Squeeze {texture_bad_2} hard in your palm for five seconds. When you open your hand, the fabric must rebound instantly. If deep wrinkles stay etched in the surface, walk away. You require materials that snap back to their original shape. Avoid {texture_bad_3} altogether. It produces static and actively disrupts the drape of your clothing. Your core strategy relies on one hot accent to draw the eye. Do not let poorly made materials distract from that execution.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject materials that fight against your body and sabotage your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the recovery test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Grab the hem tight in your fist. Squeeze hard for three seconds, open your palm, and watch the material. If it holds the wrinkles, discard it. You demand items like {texture_good_1} that spring back instantly to a polished state. This physical resilience guarantees clean impact. Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to build a self-contained structure. Keep the temperature warm and let the tension of the silhouette do the heavy lifting.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your materials by testing exactly how they respond to pressure.",
      "tests": [
        "the recovery test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your temperature is warm. Build your structural base using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Swap stark white for {core_colour_3} near your face, and ground the system with {core_colour_4}. Deploy your relief tone sparingly to give the eye a quiet place to rest. Construct your outfits to deliver clean impact. Rely on an honest fabric for structure, then introduce one hot accent using {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Pass over icy pastel, neon brights, and cold blue-grey. Watch out for the beige-out trap, where wearing identically pale items makes everything look unresolved rather than deliberate. Correct this immediately. Anchor the base with {core_colour_4} or inject {accent_colour_1}, and let one surface change restore the missing depth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your palette by observing how light interacts with your natural contrast.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Warm taupe",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
