    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Your tailored pieces take their architecture from woven geometry. Your fluid garments rely on precise printed rhythm. Because your strategy adapts to shifting environments, scale your contrast to the day. Choose low tonal variations for quiet focus or sharp definitions for a direct visual strike. Keep the underlying temperature distinctly warm. Check the resolution of every print. View the garment from an arm and a half away. If the pattern dissolves into a messy texture instead of holding a clean impact, reject it. Anchor your selections in {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Pass over anything that relies on {avoid_pattern_1} or {avoid_pattern_2}. These disrupt your polished finish. Ground your wardrobe in reliable, honest fabric. Introduce one hot accent through a single, tightly controlled motif.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate pattern as a strict structural tool, never as a mere surface decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the desk test (read as clean texture at arm's length and a half)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Hang a {recommended_pattern_1} garment on the rack and step back a pace and a half to evaluate its visual integrity. This mimics the typical distance across a workspace. Look at the cloth. The design must resolve into a sharp, legible texture from this exact range. If the motif turns into a muddy blur, drop the hanger and move on. You demand clean impact from your clothing. A successful print holds its distinct shape from a distance. It must remain orderly enough to ground your one hot accent without adding visual chaos. Trust your vision to catch the blur.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this specific visual distance check to filter out clutter before you buy any printed garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the desk test (read as clean texture at arm's length and a half)"
      ]
    }
