          "failure": "dissolution: pale gauze on pale gauze with nothing beneath and the silhouette disappears",
          "fix": "restore one line: a bias-cut slip that traces the body, a fitted base layer, or the deep sea blue anchor worn closest to the skin"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, soft shelter leads the strategy. Begin with a dove grey brushed wool blazer. Let your adaptable garments support this tailored exterior. A fine silk shirt provides temperature control without bulk. Choose cool, matt platinum for your jewellery. Fasten a silver pendant to ground the look. Your silhouette must survive beyond corporate environments. Pumping petrol at midnight demands just as much structural intention as a morning presentation. A deep teal coat must drape gracefully under harsh garage lights. Reject stiff synthetics. Evaluate the cloth with your fingertips. Your body knows the difference between restrictive polyester and fluid inky navy cashmere. Rely on that tactile intuition. Photographs deceive. Gravity pulling on heavy tweed tells the truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your working days in tactile reality rather than corporate expectation.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In low light, your soft shelter remains the foundation. Close settings strip away visual noise. Depend on the physical weight of brushed wool and the glide of silk against your skin. Let dove grey and deep teal operate under dim bulbs. Keep your metal strategy cool with a matt silver watch or a solid white gold ring. Let the fabric drape naturally over your bones. Walking to your car at 2 AM still requires a deliberate outline. Pick up your heavy inky navy cashmere coat before stepping into the night. Feel the dense weave in your grip. Shadows obscure the truth. Friction confirms it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the physical realities of dressing for close quarters and low-light environments.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A mundane morning errand demands the same structural integrity as a scheduled meeting. You still require a defined silhouette in dove grey brushed wool. The local pharmacy does not grant a pass to suspend your standards. Ground your choices in absolute consistency. Always anchor your morning with soft shelter + mobile layers + one sentimental keepsake, no matter the agenda. Let tactile feedback guide your dressing. Reflections distort reality. Dense cloth and cool, matt silk provide an honest assessment. If a sleeve restricts your arm when you reach for your keys, remove the garment. Keep a platinum ring or a silver chain constant.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the baseline of your daily dressing.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your hardware strategy demands strictly cool tones. Select {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} to construct your garments. Brilliant, reflective chrome clashes with muted colours, pulling focus away from your soft shelter. Rely on matt and brushed surfaces to maintain a seamless aesthetic instead. Eliminate {excluded_finish} completely. Assess the mass of the zips and buckles on your mobile layers by lifting them. Surface sheen distracts, but physical density proves the quality. Solid, dense metal anchors a piece properly. Flimsy, hollow alloys signify a weak foundation. A heavy {metal_1} clasp provides the precise physical gravity you need.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate the metal hardware that structurally anchors your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "When integrating {stone_1} and {stone_2} into your mobile layers, prioritise opacity over sparkle. Select stones with a cloudy surface that absorbs cool light rather than refracting it. High-shine hardware and highly polished components will look sharp and distracting next to your muted fabrics. Stick strictly to matt and brushed textures to keep the aesthetic cohesive. Gauge a piece by its density before you examine its setting. Lift the item from the display and close your fingers tightly around it. Ignore the shop lighting. The heavy pressure against your hand guarantees genuine quality. If the object feels hollow or insubstantial, put it down and walk away.",
      "sectionIntro": "Filter your stones for density and soft light absorption, ensuring they sit quietly without fracturing your cohesive surface.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Test any piece of {metal_1} by resting it in your empty palm. Assess its actual mass. Optical illusions fade, while gravity remains constant. Rely on this solid sensation to dictate your choices. High-gloss, reflective finishes clash harshly against the muted fabrics of a soft shelter. Mirror-polished surfaces pull the eye and disrupt a cool palette. Choose a matt finish or a lightly brushed texture instead. Subdued hardware integrates seamlessly with mobile layers, keeping the entire composition cohesive. Evaluate a {stone_1} ring using this exact same method, knowing the sheer weight provides the only reliable standard.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware using physical gravity rather than visual shine.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Establish the soft shelter. Arrange the mobile layers. Finally, ground the uniform with one sentimental keepsake. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look to maintain a clean foundation. Begin the selection with handbags. Demand thick full-grain leather and cool, brushed matt hardware. Perform the structural check on every new prospect. Lift the bag by its handle. If the structure hollows out in your grip or the metal feels light enough to drift on a breeze, leave it on the shelf. Depend on your grip. Authentic density refuses to bend, and solid fastenings close in silence.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess every accessory through its weight and physical construction.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the float test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Scarves act as the final link in your system of mobile layers. Source them exclusively in fine wool or pure silk. Insist on a completely matt finish. Avoid anything with a high sheen or a slippery grip. Apply the float test before you buy. Drop the textile from chest height. Watch the descent. If the material plummets in a heavy clump, leave it behind. If it catches the air and drifts down slowly, it passes. Inky navy and deep teal silk will absorb light and anchor the cool temperature of your clothing. Rely on this physical behaviour over printed patterns. Drag and air resistance reveal the true quality of a woven fibre.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject your secondary accessories to strict physical trials to guarantee their quality.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the float test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor garments using medium full-grain leather belts. Run your thumb over the hardware to verify every buckle has a flat matt finish. Next, add a sentimental keepsake cast in aged silver or oxidised metal. The dark patina of these pieces grounds the look without breaking the cool temperature of the fabrics. When you finish adjusting mobile layers, always apply the balance check. Ask yourself if the final piece of jewellery hovers seamlessly within the muted scheme. If the metal or leather visually sinks the outfit or drags the eye downward, take it off immediately. Surface appeal distracts, but actual heft confirms the quality. Trust somatic feedback to confirm the proportions are right.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor the silhouette with strict hardware rules and use physical weight to know when the outfit is complete.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the float test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Keep pattern contrast low and tonal. Tailored trousers and structured jackets take their cues from woven geometries like {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Fluid silk skirts take theirs from organic, descending lines. Pass over high-contrast graphics, {avoid_pattern_2}, and {avoid_pattern_1}. Subject every printed cloth to the underwater test. Pick it up and watch how the fabric distorts. The motif should resemble ambient light shifting across the seabed, never rigid street signage. Let structural behaviour dictate your choice. Cloth moves predictably, while printed illusions fail. Construct soft shelter from these subtle weaves. Throw on cool, matt mobile layers to complete the silhouette, ensuring the pattern remains a secondary detail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate print as a structural element, not a decorative afterthought.",
      "tests": [
        "the underwater test (read like light moving on the seabed, not signage)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Step back ten paces from the mirror and blur your vision. The ideal {recommended_pattern_1} should read like water rippling over stones, never like rigid geometry demanding attention. When selecting fabrics for mobile layers, look for motifs that diffuse into a muted, continuous wash of cool tones. Avoid anything that creates stark, distinct shapes from a distance. A successful print dissolves into the background texture, offering a subtle visual rhythm rather than a sharp focal point. Drop any piece that breaks this fluid illusion.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the underwater test to assess the legibility of any printed garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the underwater test (read like light moving on the seabed, not signage)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_cancer__moon_cancer__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "soft shelter + hidden depth + one sentimental keepsake",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on soft shelter + hidden depth + one sentimental keepsake.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Dress for the sensation of absolute privacy. Look for garments that absorb sound rather than reflecting it. Your physical instinct is a profound sensitivity to friction. If a piece snags or demands constant adjustment, discard it. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Build your outfits around a strict equation of soft shelter + hidden depth + one sentimental keepsake. Picture an oversized, fluid coat that acts as a physical boundary, worn over a densely woven base layer with structural details visible only up close. Finish this with a solitary inherited object kept near the collarbone.\n\nCurate your pieces with slow, deliberate precision over years. Deploy them instantly each morning. A functional collection requires garments that integrate smoothly. Assess every new piece by its initial tactile impact. Touch the cloth with your eyes closed. Pay attention to how the material drops and pools. If your stomach tightens or your immediate physical response is hesitation, drop the hanger and walk away. A garment must serve as an isolated, cool refuge. Refuse to compromise on that silent comfort. Keep your presentation entirely self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this core philosophy to govern every purchase and every outfit you assemble.",
      "tests": [
        "trust your gut and walk away"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Seek out {texture_good_1} for knitwear that compresses and bounces back. Build your soft shelter from {texture_good_3} in tailored coats that hold clean lines against the cool air. Rely on {texture_good_4} for fluid blouses that offer hidden depth beneath a heavy outer layer. Choose {texture_good_2} for bags and belts that mould to your grip and patinate over years of use. Test every new piece by sliding the material between your thumb and fingers. If the fabric catches against your skin or yields a squeaky friction, leave the garment on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the materials that build your foundation.",
