    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Stand across the room from any {recommended_pattern_1}. Close your eyes, open them for a single fraction of a second, and shut them again. If the design turns chaotic or confusing in that brief flash, drop the hanger. The motif must stay legible at a distance to align with your balanced proportions. You are looking for prints that grant light movement without overwhelming your frame. This clarity ensures the garment functions as true soft shelter. Trust your immediate visual reflex. When a print blurs into a mess, it compromises the quiet integrity of your cool tones.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the blink test to evaluate how a pattern performs at a distance.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_cancer__moon_gemini__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "soft shelter + light movement + one sentimental keepsake",
    "closing": "Trust your physical intuition above all else, allowing texture and drape to guide you toward soft shelter + light movement + one sentimental keepsake.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Run your hands over the weave before you check the label. Trust your fingers to find fabrics that drape with a cool, matt restraint. Your physical instinct demands a strict equilibrium between structure and ease. Pick up a piece and test its weight. If it feels rigid or heavy, drop it. You require garments that exhale when you put them on, offering fine woven integrity rather than synthetic stiffness. When you try something on, pay attention to your breathing. A correct garment allows your chest to lift without restriction. Trust this physical sensation as your absolute compass.\n\nYour core style formula is soft shelter + light movement + one sentimental keepsake. Picture an unlined sweeping overcoat worn over fluid wide trousers that pool at the shoe, anchored by a single inherited wristwatch. Build your collection slowly over the years. Deploy an outfit in five minutes. Before you purchase anything new, subject it to the host test. Ask your body if you could comfortably pour wine and serve a long dinner to guests in this garment without once tugging at a restrictive sleeve or rearranging a shifting neckline. If the piece requires your ongoing attention, it fails.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this foundational logic to evaluate every garment you consider bringing into your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the host test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Construct your soft shelter entirely by touch. Pick up a jumper in {texture_good_1} and crush it in your hand. It must bounce back instantly. For light movement against the skin, demand {texture_good_4} in your blouses and coat linings. Run the shadow test before purchasing. Hold the fabric in a dim room and watch the surface. It must absorb the ambient light with a cool, matt finish, never reflecting a harsh glare. Frame these layers with {texture_good_3}. Trust this material for tailored coats that hold a sharp shoulder line for decades. Ground the entire system with belts and shoes in {texture_good_2}. This will mould to your grip and slowly patinate, sitting quietly next to the metal of your one sentimental keepsake. Master these four textures first.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the specific materials that will construct your foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
        {
          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Assess {texture_bad_1} under low illumination. If it bounces back a hard glare instead of softening into a cool, muted shadow, reject it. Pick up {texture_bad_2}. If it feels brittle or sticky against your skin, it will never provide a soft shelter. Drop the garment immediately. Visuals deceive, but tactile response tells the truth. Avoid any fabric that disrupts your balanced proportions with stiff resistance.",
      "sectionIntro": "Trust your hands and eyes to reject the wrong materials before you even try them on.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Bring {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2} together to anchor your garments. Notice how shadows settle across {texture_good_1} when layered. A draped overcoat worn over a fine knit builds an immediate soft shelter. Gauge these pairings by their friction. If the fibres catch against each other or look slick under a bulb, leave the piece on the hanger. Demand a strictly matt finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Find the exact intersection of your best materials.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Build a soft shelter from your foundation of {core_colour_1}, {core_colour_2}, and {core_colour_3}. Keep {core_colour_4} ready as your neutral substitute. Your temperature is strictly cool. Direct the eye using {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as your single deliberate accent. Apply your relief tone only as a soft note used sparingly. Pass over hot saturated red, stark optic white, and harsh neon. Beware the heavy sink. Stacking dark, dense base tones without interruption can swallow the silhouette. Break the block. Layer {core_colour_4} at the collar, add one supple leather belt, or introduce your relief tone.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assign every tone a specific job to anchor your proportions and command focus.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Inky navy",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep teal",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Dove grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
