    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your hardware choices define the final phase of your dressing process. After constructing your soft shelter and securing an athletic space, introduce one sentimental keepsake. Apply the provenance test to every object. Hold the item and verify if it carries enough internal gravity to stand completely alone. A true companion holds a specific physical memory, perhaps a cool metal edge or a familiar worn grain. Enforce the rule of one or two strong pieces per look. Start by evaluating handbags. Insist on full-grain leather or thick suede. The metal elements must remain entirely muted. Select matt brushed hardware. Rely on your hands to assess the strap thickness and the density of the hide. Trust your grip.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your additions as functional tools and physical anchors rather than mere decoration.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Treat a scarf as your primary soft shelter. Seek out generous silk or fine wool with a resolutely matt surface. Pick the fabric up and crush it in your fist. It should drape heavily and hold zero sheen. Assess the item carefully before you buy. Ask yourself if this dove grey wrap feels like a private relic you would save from a house fire. Trust your fingers to find these cool, muted fibres. Avoid anything rigid, reflective, or stiff. The sheer density of good wool provides the only validation you need.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply these material rules to select scarves that serve as true investments.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your boiled wool or washed silk layers with a wide full-grain leather belt. Insist on a matt brushed buckle to maintain your muted profile. For your jewellery, choose a deep stone set in cool, aged silver or oxidised brass. Trust your physical instincts when balancing these heavy pieces against your soft shelter. Weight remains your truest guide. Always verify the piece's personal resonance before wearing it. Hold the item in your palm and determine if it acts as a private, inherited talisman. If the piece feels like a recent acquisition meant for an audience, remove it immediately. Keep only what feels entirely self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select finishing elements that introduce density and permanence to your silhouette.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Treat pattern as a structural element rather than a surface decoration. Restrict your designs to a low-contrast, tonal palette to maintain visual discipline. Tailored garments must draw their complexity directly from woven structures like {recommended_pattern_1}. Fluid pieces take their direction from muted, subtle variations like {recommended_pattern_2} or {recommended_pattern_3}. Pass over stark prints like {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. They disrupt the cool harmony of your wardrobe. Always subject a new print to the shadow test. Hold the material under a soft evening bulb. The motif must melt into the matt texture rather than floating above it. If the design stays sharp and rigid, drop the garment. The right pattern provides soft shelter, stepping back to preserve your athletic space.",
      "sectionIntro": "Filter every pattern through a strict lens of texture and structural depth.",
      "tests": [
        "the lamplight test (melt into a soft texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the shadow test to evaluate any {recommended_pattern_1}. Take the garment into a dimly lit room and step back. A successful print will melt completely into a muted, continuous texture under a single bulb. If the motif remains sharp or legible in the dark, skip the purchase. You require patterns that dissolve into a uniform surface to construct a true soft shelter. Harsh contrasts disrupt a self-contained mood. Look for cool, low-contrast weaves that blur together at a distance. Let the shadows strip away the details. A blurred surface proves the fabric's integrity.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every pattern to a strict visibility filter before wearing it.",
      "tests": [
        "the lamplight test (melt into a soft texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_cancer__moon_libra__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "soft shelter + cool composure + one sentimental keepsake",
    "closing": "Navigate by touch, assess the weight of the cloth, and permanently ground your wardrobe in soft shelter + cool composure + one sentimental keepsake.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your sensory compass is physical friction. Run your hands over every edge and seam before you try anything on. If a garment demands constant adjustment or catches against your movement, leave it on the hanger. Ground your wardrobe in the formula of soft shelter + cool composure + one sentimental keepsake. Picture a dense draped overcoat layered over a fluid shell, finished with a heavy pendant resting at the collarbone. This combination provides physical protection through heavy yardage while maintaining strict visual restraint through clean lines.\n\nConstruct this foundation slowly over seasons, but assemble your outfits in seconds. Your dressing routine must feel like a deliberate exhalation. When evaluating any new piece, apply the melt test. Put the garment on, close your eyes, and wait three seconds. The item must physically dissolve into your silhouette and remove all tension from your shoulders. If you remain aware of a stiff collar, a tight seam, or an awkward closure against your skin, the piece has failed. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your core operational blueprint, establishing the diagnostic rules you must use to evaluate every piece before it ever touches your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Seek out {texture_good_1} for knitwear that compresses and recovers in your grip. This forms your soft shelter against the elements. Build cool composure with {texture_good_3} in tailored coats that hold a precise edge. Anchor your accessories with {texture_good_2} for bags and belts that mould to your daily habits. Add {texture_good_4} in blouses for fluid movement. Assess every garment by hand. Squeeze the material in your fist for ten seconds. If it yields to your body heat and drops back into a smooth line instantly, buy it. Let the density of the cloth guide you. Visuals deceive, but gravity remains constant. Rely on the materials ranked below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your wardrobe from materials that feel as reliable as they look.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
