    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, allow soft shelter to lead your choices. Support this outer boundary with the remaining elements of your formula. A silk blouse worn against the skin provides internal calm, while a private silver locket rests unseen beneath your collar. Apply the corner-shop test. A quick walk outside for a tea never justifies abandoning your deep teal cashmere silhouette. Dress so a sudden dash for milk feels just as protected as sitting at your desk. Trust your hands over the mirror. Seek out weighty, cool, matt fabrics. If a dove grey blazer feels weak on the hanger, leave it behind. Visuals deceive, but gravity tells the truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply these directives to translate your style into the demands of the workplace.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "Let your soft shelter lead in dim settings. When the sun drops, visual details fade into shadows. Rely on touch. Choose an inky navy cashmere sweater or a heavy dove grey silk blouse. These matt fibres absorb the available light and prove substantial under the hand. Trust your fingertips to assess the thickness of the weave. Keep your cool metals close to the collarbone, letting a brushed silver pendant catch the minimal glow. An evening walk does not require abandoning your silhouette. Pull a thick brushed wool coat over your shoulders and step out. You know the drape is correct without looking in a mirror.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the shift into dim environments by adjusting your textures, not your silhouette.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Collecting a prescription from the chemist does not demand dropping your structure. When you stand at the counter, do so in brushed wool and full-grain leather. Layer a dove grey cashmere knit under an inky navy coat. Test the drape with your own hands. If a garment feels stiff against your joints, reject it. Your daily baseline always rests on soft shelter + sensory comfort + one sentimental keepsake. Zip your coat with a cool, matt silver fastening. Wrap a heavy silk scarf closely around your neck. Every mundane errand must meet this standard.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish a strict baseline for routine errands and daily motion.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your metal strategy relies on a cool foundation. Anchor your jewellery and structural hardware in {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Exclude {excluded_finish} entirely. Pick up a chain or a buckle and weigh it in your palm. Sight is easily fooled. Heft is undeniable. Rely on your grip to detect solid quality. High-gloss polish acts as a sharp, jarring distraction next to muted fabrics. Choose brushed and matt textures to keep the aesthetic cohesive. Heavy, substantial hardware grounds you and provides profound sensory comfort throughout the day.",
      "sectionIntro": "Curate your structural and decorative metals to anchor your clothing without demanding focus.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select dense, opaque stones to anchor your soft shelter. Look for {stone_1} or {stone_2} that absorb light rather than refract it. Always test a piece by holding it in your palm. Surface sparkle misleads the observer, but actual physical density proves the value. Heavy materials ground your posture and deliver steady sensory comfort throughout the day. Beware of highly polished settings. Glossy, mirror-like metals create a harsh, distracting contrast against muted fabrics. Counter this by pairing your stones strictly with matt or lightly brushed hardware. A solid cabochon of {stone_3} in a dulled cool setting provides a quiet, self-contained focal point.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate the density and finish of your hardware to ensure it grounds your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift every item of hardware from the tray. The pull of an object against your fingers provides the only necessary proof. Depend on your grip to judge the quality. A hollow chain or lightweight {metal_1} clasp immediately compromises your sensory comfort. Notice how high-shine polished finishes create a sharp distraction against your muted clothes. That glare shatters your soft shelter. Choose brushed and matt textures to anchor the outfit. A dense {stone_1} ring or a heavy, brushed pendant integrates seamlessly into thick cashmere and full-grain leather.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware by touch before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories provide your final anchor. Once you build a soft shelter from heavy tweed and establish true sensory comfort in your base layers, you must finish the look with one sentimental keepsake. Enforce a strict limit of one or two strong pieces per outfit. Apply this discipline first to handbags. Seek out thick suede or heavy full-grain leather. All zips and clasps must feature cool matt brushed hardware. To filter your choices, rely on the keepsake test. Pick the object up and close your fingers around it. Ask yourself if it feels like a private possession meant only for your own reassurance. Photographs exaggerate. Touch verifies. If the item demands external validation, leave it behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this section to anchor your wardrobe with tactile, deeply personal accessories.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Judge every scarf by its capacity for sensory comfort. Look for generous lengths of heavy silk or fine wool with a completely matt finish. Drape the fabric over your collarbone to assess its ability to provide soft shelter. Evaluate its private significance. If you do not feel an immediate physical instinct to hoard the item like a private treasure, put it back on the shelf. The material must create a physical barrier between you and the outside world. Keep the temperature strictly cool. Select muted charcoal or deep teal instead of printed patterns. Let the dense weight of the fibre do the work.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your scarves as essential tools for physical grounding and protection.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your waist with a wide belt cut from thick full-grain leather. Fasten it with a matt brushed buckle. Keep the metal aligned with your cool palette. For jewellery, seek out a deep sapphire or onyx set in oxidised silver. These heavy, darkened pieces provide vital sensory comfort when worn close to the body. Execute a final purge before you finish dressing. Strip away the excess until only the single piece holding genuine history remains. If the stone or metal does not feel like a private, grounding anchor, take it off.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your outfit by selecting your structural elements and heavy, personal hardware.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Build soft shelter through low-contrast, tonal variations. Anchor these motifs in cool, muted threads. Tailored garments take their pattern strictly from the structural weave, such as {recommended_pattern_1}. Fluid pieces carry broader, softer motifs like {recommended_pattern_2}. Pass over stark borders or harsh graphics entirely. Avoid {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. Evaluate every motif under a dim bulb. If the design glares rather than melting into the fabric, the piece fails the lamplight test. Drop the garment. Prioritise pure sensory comfort above visual noise. Images distort reality. The tension of the threads gives you the facts.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control visual noise by treating pattern strictly as a subtle extension of the fabric's physical weave.",
      "tests": [
        "the lamplight test (melt into a soft texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Hang a {recommended_pattern_1} shirt across the room and turn on a single low lamp. Step back and squint. A successful motif will melt into the fabric. It must blur into a wash of cool shadow rather than demanding attention. If the print stays sharp or projects across the dim space, put the item back on the rack. You require pure sensory comfort from your clothing. Seek out muted colours that recede entirely into a matt weave or heavy silk. The visual noise must remain low and self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the lamplight test to evaluate how a motif behaves under low illumination.",
      "tests": [
        "the lamplight test (melt into a soft texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_cancer__moon_virgo__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "soft shelter + honest fabric + one sentimental keepsake",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on soft shelter + honest fabric + one sentimental keepsake.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the weight of the cloth against your skin as your primary metric. Your wardrobe needs to move with you as your environment shifts. Build your foundation methodically over time, but adapt quickly on the day. Let your outfits drift by mood rather than strict uniform rules. Seek garments that provide a physical barrier between you and the noise outside without restricting your movement. If a piece demands constant adjustment or dictates a rigid posture, leave it on the hanger. You are dressing for your own autonomy. Rely on cool, muted finishes to anchor this flexibility.\n\nYour guiding equation is soft shelter + honest fabric + one sentimental keepsake. Picture a generously cut, unstructured overcoat layered over a dense, functional woven shirt, finished with a privately worn pendant resting against your collarbone. Run every potential purchase through the combination test. Ask yourself if the garment shifts seamlessly into three different silhouettes you already own. If it only works in one fixed configuration, it fails the test. Trust your hands to check the drape and construction. Looks lie. The way the cloth collapses and yields is your ultimate compass.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master these core principles before you evaluate another garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the combination test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your materials must act as a soft shelter, built from an honest fabric that protects your boundaries. Construct foundational layers with {texture_good_1} for shirting that creates pure separation. Anchor this with {texture_good_2} for close-to-body base layers ensuring easy movement. Rely on {texture_good_3} for trousers that hold a clean drape and resist creasing during long hours. Finish with {texture_good_4} for lightweight outerwear that blocks the wind. Always apply the snap test. Pull the cloth taut between your thumbs and release it. If it snaps back sharply, feels cool to the touch, and presents a flat matt finish, it possesses the resilience you require. Flimsy weaves will sag and fail. Discard them, and focus on the ranked fibres below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your materials by how effectively they perform under friction and resist daily wear.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
