      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Reject materials that undermine your need for sharp edges. Pick up {texture_bad_1}. It slips and slides between your fingers, lacking the grip required to hold a crisp fold. Leave it on the rack. Squeeze a handful of {texture_bad_2}. It crunches slightly and springs back with a hollow, synthetic pop. This betrays a cheap origin. Hold the fabric near a solitary flame. This low, warm illumination exposes inferior finishes immediately, revealing a harsh, oily shine rather than a deep, matt shadow. If it catches artificial light in the dark, drop it. Quality absorbs weak light. Cheap cloth reflects it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify materials that fail your standards before they touch your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Pair {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to establish a heavy base. Contrast them with {texture_good_1} to supply the sharp edges your silhouette demands. Take the item into a shadowed space and check it against a low, warm light source. If the yarn catches a hard reflection, leave it on the rack. You need a matt finish that drinks the light. Look for a heavy weave that holds its own shape when you drop it over a chair. This strict restraint keeps your aesthetic self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your fibre combinations by relying on strict contrasts of nap and weight.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Build everything on a strictly warm foundation. Rely on {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} to establish your base layers. Bridge any visual gaps using {core_colour_3} or {core_colour_4}. Treat your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly to break up solid blocks of shade. Drop {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} in as a single deliberate focal point. Cut sharp edges into these hues to keep the overall shape disciplined. Skip icy electric blue, neon brights, and fleeting trend pastels entirely. Draping yourself in an uninterrupted dark void suggests you simply stopped trying. Fracture that monotony by adding a {core_colour_1} wrap, a {accent_colour_1} scarf, or a {core_colour_2} belt. Trust your own visceral instinct to verify the heat of a hue. Tags lie. True warmth does not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your aesthetic by building exclusively upon a disciplined, intentional palette.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rich toffee",
          "role": "warm_base"
