          "failure": "head-to-toe black reads like you gave up on the way out the door",
          "fix": "break it up with a camel layer, a deep wine scarf, or a rich cognac belt"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let sharp edges lead your clothes for work. A precise collar or a crisp trouser crease directs focus. Support these lines with reliable structure and a warm, tactile surface like camel cashmere or rich toffee leather. Keep the overall palette muted. Avoid distracting prints. Test every outfit before you step outside. If you cannot wait comfortably in the queue at the chemist for twenty minutes, take the piece off. Workwear must function without restriction. Look for heavy silk to provide visual weight. You do not need to project authority outward. A tailored sleeve and a matt appearance keep your boundaries self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply these rules to calibrate your wardrobe for the working week.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, sharp edges lead. Crisp lapels on a camel blazer or the precise bias cut of a rich toffee silk slip dress define the silhouette. Combine matt gold and silver jewellery to ensure the dual register finish remains muted. Build from a warm palette. Test the combination against an evening errand. Standing under the stark lights of an all-night clinic requires zero physical restriction. If a stiff full-grain leather belt or a tight collar pinches, remove it immediately. Seek out items that yield. Fold a cashmere sweater and notice how the fibres compress without fighting your grip. Dress entirely for your own physical ease.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your evening garments by the immediate physical feedback they give your body.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A mundane rainy errand never demands discomfort. Grasp a heavy camel full-grain leather tote and slip on a rich toffee silk shirt cut for ease. Rely on the feedback of the garment against your shoulders. Photographs flatter, but mass is undeniable. You must demand enduring structure + sharp edges + one living texture in every daily combination. Hold the palette strictly warm. Pair a matt gold watch alongside a brushed steel ring to lock down your dual register discipline. Your dressing operates entirely self-contained, requiring zero applause to function.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your strict material baseline to the most mundane daily errands.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Split your hardware into two distinct categories. Against the skin, wear {personal_metal_1} or {personal_metal_2}. Let these warm pieces sit quietly. For the functional parts of your garments, like zips, buckles, and clasps, select {structural_metal_1} or {structural_metal_2}. These components provide the sharp edges your wardrobe requires. High-gloss reflective hardware looks distracting next to soft, muted colours. Avoid {excluded_finish} treatments completely. Stick to brushed or matt surfaces to keep the items cohesive. Always lift a buckle or clasp in your bare palm before buying. Visuals manipulate. Dense metal remains honest. Grip the item to confirm its true worth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Divide your hardware into specific zones to control how metal interacts with your clothes.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Weigh the piece in your palm. Surface polish tricks the eye, but sheer density confirms authenticity. Lean on this tactile test when assessing {stone_1} or a dense slab of {stone_2}. Demand sharp edges in your lapidary cuts to ground a warm colour palette. Watch out for highly polished hardware. Glossy chrome distracts the eye and breaks cohesion alongside muted garments. Reject high shine entirely. Rely on matt or brushed metals to bind your dual register selections together.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones through density and lapidary precision.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the {metal_1} clasp or {stone_1} pendant to gauge its mass. Images lie. A substantial gauge never does. Substantial hardware guarantees an enduring structure for your garments. Drop hollow rings and flimsy chains immediately. A highly reflective gloss on polished silver creates a jarring glare against warm, muted colours. Seek out a matt surface instead. A low-lustre patina defines sharp edges and grounds your self-contained accessories.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every piece of hardware by its physical mass before making a choice.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Clothing builds enduring structure. Seams and hems define sharp edges. Accessories complete the equation, offering one living texture. Restrict your selection to one or two strong pieces per look. Put your chosen items on, evaluate the physical weight, and deliberately remove the addition that breaks your clean silhouette. Rely on your internal gauge of balance. Self-contained discipline demands you drop the piece doing excess work. Ground your warm wardrobe using substantial handbags shaped from full-grain leather or thick suede. Seek out bags mounted with heavy, matt metal hardware. Let the sheer density of the hide carry the visual interest.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your accessories as a strict tactical exercise, applying ruthless physical restraint to every final detail.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Select generous silk or fine wool scarves in warm camel or deep toffee. Demand a strictly matt finish. Fold the fabric to form sharp edges against your collarbone rather than allowing it to pool loosely. Pick up the material and assess its heft. The downward pull provides your answer. Visuals distort, but physical bulk is absolute. Apply strict discipline before stepping out. Strip away any secondary item that competes for focus. One strong anchor provides the necessary tension.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your secondary accessories by applying the same rigid physical standards you use for your primary garments.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Demand sharp edges when evaluating a belt. Choose wide full-grain leather fastened by a matt brushed buckle. Select your keepsake jewellery with the same rigorous focus. Look for a deep warm stone set in oxidised aged silver or brass. Let these mixed metals remain muted. Before finishing, run a final audit. Pinpoint the heaviest metal element and unfasten the second-heaviest component. A single robust focal point is sufficient.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply strict physical limits to your final additions to ensure they never overwhelm the core silhouette.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchoring your wardrobe with enduring structure requires strict pattern restraint. Trust the heft and drag of the material to ground the design. Your tailored pieces draw their pattern solely from the weave of the cloth. Fluid garments take their patterns from dye. Maintain a low, tonal contrast across all prints. Step back from the mirror and let your vision drop out of focus. The right pattern will blur into a warm texture rather than an identifiable shape. Look for {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Pass over anything stamped with {avoid_pattern_1} or {avoid_pattern_2}. Grip the garment tightly. If the print distracts from the density and drape of the cloth, leave it on the rack.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the application of pattern by treating it as a subtle extension of the fabric itself.",
      "tests": [
        "step back and soften focus (blur into texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Stand five paces from the mirror and soften your gaze until the {recommended_pattern_1} blurs. A pattern should never demand attention from across the street. It must dissolve into a warm, mottled surface that rewards close inspection. Maintain sharp edges in the garment cut. Let the motif melt away into pure fabric weight. If the shapes stay harsh or legible when your eyes unfocus, put the item down. A self-contained pattern acts as a private enclosure. It protects your space rather than projecting outward.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every motif through the distance test.",
      "tests": [
        "step back and soften focus (blur into texture)"
      ]
    }
