      "tests": [
        "the heirloom test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Draw pattern in your tailored pieces directly from the structural weave. Reserve printed motifs for fluid garments. Ensure every design maintains a warm, low-contrast tonal shift. Every successful choice introduces hidden depth without compromising the enduring structure of the cloth. Test a print by stepping three paces back. The design must settle into the natural irregularity of ground viewed from a high ridge. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. Reach for {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as a subtle shift in grain rather than a flat surface graphic.",
      "tests": [
        "the field test (settle into a natural texture like ground seen from a hill)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Assess the scale by softening your focus. A successful {recommended_pattern_1} will stop registering as a harsh print and blend into a continuous, textured shadow. If the lines stay sharp and demand attention from a distance, leave the garment on the rail. You are building an enduring structure for your wardrobe. Strict contrasts fight this goal. Trust your eyes to seek out a warm haze rather than distinct boundaries. A pattern must collapse into a subtle, mottled surface to offer true hidden depth. Pick it up and inspect the weave. A good print feels firmly integrated into the cloth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this distance test to filter out harsh prints before they reach your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the field test (settle into a natural texture like ground seen from a hill)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_capricorn__moon_capricorn__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "enduring structure + softness + one living texture",
    "closing": "Navigate your wardrobe by touch, trusting the heavy drape of the cloth to guide you toward enduring structure + softness + one living texture.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the physical weight and the quiet surface of a garment. Your compass is the sensation of hush. Build your wardrobe slowly over the seasons. Wait for the precise cut and the matt finish. Deploy these garments fast on the morning you need them. Apply the shelter test before you buy anything new. Ask if the piece acts as a physical refuge. A heavy coat or a dense knit must offer a warm enclosure that protects your focus, rather than demanding your energy. Looks lie. Weight does not. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass.\n\nFilter every combination through your exact formula: enduring structure + softness + one living texture. Ground the look in a tailored wool coat that holds its shape on a hanger. Layer a fine cashmere knit beneath it to sit gently against the skin. Finish the combination with a brushed suede bag or a raw silk scarf. The structure provides the frame. The softness provides the comfort. The single living element keeps the combination breathing. Demand this precise balance every time you dress. Reject any piece that feels thin or flat.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation, the strict physical criteria you must demand from every garment before it enters your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the shelter test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Look for materials that deliver enduring structure and softness. Test the weave of every new piece to ensure breathability. Hold the material to your lips and exhale. If the air gets trapped, the fabric will suffocate you. Leave it on the rack. Squeeze {texture_good_1} in your fist and wait for it to spring back. Seek {texture_good_2} for belts and shoes that patinate and mould to your shape over time. When selecting tailored coats, rely on {texture_good_3} to hold clean lines for years. Layer {texture_good_4} underneath for fluid movement next to the skin, providing that one living texture your formula requires. Prioritise these warm, matt finishes in your wardrobe.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to evaluate a garment with your hands before you ever put it on your body.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
