          "failure": "drowning in formless, head to toe black",
          "fix": "break it with a warm point of light, like a hammered gold cuff or a tortoiseshell comb"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let enduring structure govern your professional hours. A tailored camel wool blazer or a sharp toffee gabardine trouser sets the baseline. These garments provide a strict boundary. Support this firm foundation with softness. A warm silk blouse introduces enough drape to break the rigidity. A morning commute never requires discarding your tailored silhouette. Keep your standards exact. Introduce one living texture carefully. A woven full-grain leather belt or a brushed cashmere scarf adds necessary friction against the silk. Rely on dual register metals. Mix polished gold earrings with muted bronze cuffs. Inspect the weave closely. Trust your fingers to verify the quality. Your own tactile response reveals the value. Visuals flatter, but sheer mass confirms the standard.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your professional attire in strict discipline.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In low light and close proximity, your enduring structure leads. Maintain your shape with full-grain leather or dense brushed wool. Dim rooms require tactile weight over visual noise. Mix a steel watch with a brushed gold ring. Rely on physical resistance. Grip the fabric tightly. Quality cloth releases without creasing. A casual evening out does not mean dropping your silhouette. Throw a heavy camel coat over a silk shirt. Reject shiny threads. Rely on a warm toffee palette and a matt finish that absorbs the ambient glow.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your silhouette when the lights go down.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Daily tasks demand practical garments. Do not drop your criteria for a mundane errand. A brief trip to the market does not permit substituting a tailored camel coat with cheap synthetic jersey. Your baseline remains constant. Build every outfit around enduring structure + softness + one living texture. Assess the items you select for basic chores by checking the drape. If a piece feels rigid or lifeless, leave it on the hanger. A warm toffee silk shirt layered under thick wool provides absolute comfort without sacrificing intention. Reach for full-grain leather boots instead of canvas trainers. Evaluate your daily clothing by its physical response. An item must perform functionally while maintaining a muted finish and rich construction.",
      "sectionIntro": "Dictate your standard for ordinary days rather than defaulting to utility alone.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Divide your metals into two distinct categories. For jewellery resting directly on your skin, select {personal_metal_1} or {personal_metal_2} to respect your warm palette. For the enduring structure of buckles, bag clasps, and zips, rely on {structural_metal_1} or {structural_metal_2}. Steer clear of a high-shine {excluded_finish}. A glaring, mirror-like reflection clashes harshly against the softness of cashmere and full-grain leather. Demand matt, antiqued, or brushed finishes to integrate the hardware properly. Evaluate every chain and fastening by lifting it in your palm. Polished surfaces distract, but heavy metal validates itself. Flimsy hollow alloys destroy the integrity of a garment, so insist on solid components that act as one living texture against the cloth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control the exact placement and finish of your hardware to anchor your garments properly.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select stones that absorb light rather than shatter it. When evaluating {stone_1} or {stone_2}, test the mineral directly. Lift the piece in your bare hand without looking. A proper stone feels cold and dense against your skin. This density delivers enduring structure to anchor the softness of your garments. Avoid glassy clarity. Highly polished facets create a sharp distraction next to muted colours. To keep the look cohesive, strictly select matt and brushed textures for the settings. A cloudy {stone_2} provides a warm anchor without breaking the visual quiet.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware by its density and its ability to absorb light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the buckle, link, or {metal_1} casting in your palm before making a decision. Sight is easily tricked by a thick plating, but physical drag confirms the density. Next, evaluate the surface reflection. High-gloss pieces glare against a muted, warm palette. A highly reflective polish shatters the inherent softness of your garments. Keep your visual composition integrated by selecting a brushed or matt finish. This discipline ensures your hardware provides enduring structure rather than a distracting visual spike.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use your hands to diagnose hardware before you trust it on your body.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories complete your foundation of enduring structure and softness. They supply the required one living texture to finish the equation. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Anything more dilutes the impact. Begin with your handbags. Seek out full-grain leather finished with brushed matt hardware. Execute the gravity check before buying. Lift the strap and gauge its resistance. You must feel a heavy drag in your grip before you even open the clasp. Substance cannot be faked. If the piece feels hollow or light, leave it on the shelf. Your warm wardrobe demands items that feel rooted and substantial. The dual metal hardware must possess that same undeniable density.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select accessories with undeniable physical gravity to ground your garments.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Assess your scarves in silk or fine wool. The finish must be completely matt. Reject anything that catches the light. Pick up the fabric and let it pool in your bare hand. Close your eyes and gauge the textile. Eyes misjudge fabric, but your palm registers the true yield. You require enduring structure, even in a draped garment. Suspend the piece by its hem. If it floats away without substance, drop it. The item must carry enough mass to root your collarbone and ground warm camel or rich toffee outerwear. Seek out genuine softness that serves as a weighted foundation rather than a fragile afterthought.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject your woven accessories to the same strict physical standards as your heavier garments.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor the waist with medium full-grain leather secured by a heavy matt buckle. Treat keepsake jewellery as deliberate grounding points rather than decorative additions. Select aged silver with an oxidised finish. This dark patina sits comfortably alongside the warm metals in your wardrobe. Trust your hands when selecting these items. Solid castings and stiff hides confirm their own worth. Before stepping out, verify the visual weight of your composition. Ask yourself if the accessories offer enough enduring structure against the woven softness of your garments. If an aged silver pendant feels hollow or a leather strap feels flimsy, remove the offending piece immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Complete the foundation with heavy leather and tarnished metal.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Seek out low-contrast, tonal arrangements. Tailored garments draw their visual rhythm from the loom. Look for {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2} woven directly into the cloth. Fluid garments take their character from muted dyeing techniques. Pass over sharp geometries, stark outlines, and {avoid_pattern_1}. Subject every print to the shadow check. View the garment away from direct sunlight. The shapes must lose their hard borders and dissolve into a deep, unified surface. Anchor your base in enduring structure. Build softness through blurred, warm tones.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate how a motif serves the fabric before you allow it into your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the twilight test (merge into a rich, deep texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Take your {recommended_pattern_1} into dim lighting to perform the twilight test. Stand back from the mirror and let your vision drop out of focus. The print must blur and sink into a dense, rich aggregate. It should dissolve into pure softness, rather than vibrating with sharp contrast. If the motif demands attention across the floor, leave the garment on the hanger. You need the design to melt into a warm, unified cloth. This approach depends on enduring structure to ground the aesthetic. The pattern must surrender to the weave. If the shapes remain starkly legible in the shadows, they break your balance.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use the twilight test to ruthlessly edit your printed garments.",
      "tests": [
        "the twilight test (merge into a rich, deep texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_capricorn__moon_gemini__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "enduring structure + light movement + one living texture",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on enduring structure + light movement + one living texture.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Learn to read a garment through your hands before you ever put it on. Test the weight balance. A heavy hem requires a lighter counterweight above it. Your baseline relies on warm, muted finishes that absorb light rather than reflect it. Look for matt surfaces. Apply your core formula to every outfit you construct. You need enduring structure + light movement + one living texture. Picture a heavy wool trench coat worn open over a fluid silk slip dress, anchored by a rough suede boot. The formula forces physical equilibrium.\n\nAccumulate your individual garments slowly over time. Assemble your daily outfits fast, letting your mood dictate the physical direction. Run every new acquisition through the flight test. Ask yourself if you could wear these exact pieces on a long-haul journey and disembark with everything still sitting perfectly in place. If a rigid armhole binds your shoulder or a tight waistband demands constant adjustment, leave the item on the rack. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.",
      "sectionIntro": "Understand these physical laws before you buy another piece of clothing.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Construct your wardrobe using warm materials that deliver enduring structure. Reach for {texture_good_1} when sourcing shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation. Layer {texture_good_2} next to your skin for base pieces that offer sharp lines and easy movement. Anchor your lower half in {texture_good_3}, allowing your trousers to drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day. Shield yourself using {texture_good_4} for lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks the wind and weighs little. Grip the hem tightly in your fist for ten seconds and release it. If the cloth retains a sharp fold, put it back. Trust your hands, prioritise light movement, and add one living texture from the hierarchy below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Secure your physical foundation by trusting only the materials that actively support your required structure and movement.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
