    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Divide your hardware into two clear lanes. For zips, shoe buckles, and bag clasps, rely on {structural_metal_1} or {structural_metal_2}. These elements provide the enduring structure your garments need. Reserve {personal_metal_1} and {personal_metal_2} for chains, rings, and cuffs worn directly on the body. Keep the temperature strictly warm and insist on a matt, muted finish. Reject any {excluded_finish}. Step away from artificially aged hardware, hammered copper, and faux-antiqued brass. Those surfaces add visual clutter. Stick to clean, untextured iterations of your core metals instead. Always lift a buckle or pendant in your palm before you buy it. Visuals deceive, but heavy mass tells the objective truth. Trust your hands to confirm the density.",
      "sectionIntro": "Lock your hardware strategy into two distinct lanes.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Look for opaque, matt stones like {stone_1} and {stone_2}. They bring dense, warm colour to your silhouette. Assess the setting carefully to ensure the mount remains robust. Heavy, solid material provides the ultimate proof of quality. These stones serve to anchor the enduring structure of your garments. Skip elaborate facets or mixed gemstone clusters. They act as a distraction against your clothing. Mount your stones in clean, brushed platinum or muted steel to honour your dual-register strategy. Rely on light movement in smooth chains to contrast the dense weight of the pendants.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your stones by their physical density and their capacity to anchor your silhouette.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Weigh the piece in your palm. The physical heft of {metal_1} grounds your outfit and provides an immediate tactile anchor. Reject overly ornate clasps or heavily branded toggles. Intricate logos register as visual noise against a warm palette. Rely instead on smooth, uniform casting. A dense buckle or a heavy {stone_1} pendant provides enduring structure, while flexible chain links allow for light movement. Let gravity verify the quality before you fasten the clasp.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess the quality of your hardware by testing its physical density.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You have anchored the look with enduring structure. You have added a layer of light movement. Now complete the equation with one living texture. Limit your finishing details to one or two strong pieces per look. Run the removal test before walking out. Stand by the door, strip away the final item you tied on, and assess the remaining shape. If the outfit falls flat without it, put the piece back on. Begin building this tactile layer with silk scarves. Select a crepe de chine square or a slim band. Ensure the fabric carries a matt finish to ground the warm temperature of your wardrobe. The silk must absorb light, never flash it back.",
      "sectionIntro": "Accessories are the mechanism for locking your foundational layers into place, deploying tactile details to finalise the silhouette.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square or slim band, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Treat fine jewellery as a tool to introduce light movement near the collarbone. Select a thin chain and small drops in brushed silver. The matt surface absorbs ambient light rather than flashing it back. Mix this muted silver with warm gold bands to satisfy your dual-register approach. Evaluate your additions stringently. Unclasp the necklace. If your clothes maintain their strong lines without it, the extra jewellery is merely visual noise. Drop it back into the velvet tray. Anchor these delicate pieces over a worsted wool lapel or a camel coat.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control the delicate elements that finish the upper half of the silhouette.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin chain and small drops, brushed silver"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your shape with a small structured bag that delivers enduring structure. Pick up a top-handle design in warm taupe kid suede. Examine the closures closely. Require fine matt hardware. The dense nap of the suede introduces one living texture to your silhouette. Swing the strap over your shoulder and walk a few paces. If the bag snags your garments or interrupts their light movement, set it down. Carry only what supports your physical frame.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your accessories by editing out the excess.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede top-handle, fine matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Divide pattern strictly by garment type. Your tailored pieces take their pattern from the weave. Look for {recommended_pattern_1} woven directly into the cloth to reinforce an enduring structure. Your fluid layers take their pattern from the dye. Seek out {recommended_pattern_2} on draped fabrics to encourage light movement. Because your wardrobe is adaptive, you must control your pattern contrast. Keep the visual jump between your warm base colour and the motif low and tonal for formal settings. You can push towards higher contrast when the environment relaxes. Always apply the passing test. Walk quickly past a mirror. The print must read as a soft, pleasant texture in motion. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1}. It creates flat visual noise. Choose {recommended_pattern_3} to preserve a muted, matt finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as a strict, controlled variable to build visual interest without breaking your silhouette.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Use the distance test to gauge any {recommended_pattern_1}. Hang the garment at the end of a corridor and step ten paces back. Squint at the fabric. A passing print in a warm palette blurs into a cohesive visual weave instead of separating into sharp shapes. Sway the hanger gently from side to side. The design must integrate seamlessly into the background rather than flashing violently. This guarantees the pattern brings light movement to the silhouette. If the graphic stays loud and highly legible from afar, leave it on the rail. It will only interrupt your enduring structure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the Hallway Test to check scale and contrast.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_capricorn__moon_leo__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "enduring structure + athletic space + one living texture",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on enduring structure + athletic space + one living texture.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the physical weight and drape of a garment against your shoulder. If a piece feels flimsy or restricts your reach, drop it immediately. Build your wardrobe slowly. Deploy garments with measured precision. Your core equation is enduring structure + athletic space + one living texture. Picture an architectural heavy coat layered over a flexible technical undergarment, finished with a neckpiece woven from rough, warm natural fibres. The combination must ground you. Look for pieces that possess a matt, understated finish rather than a reflective sheen. Trust this physical sensation. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.\n\nApply the host test before committing to any new silhouette. Put the garment on and observe your physical posture. A guest adjusts their collar and constantly checks their reflection. A host moves without restriction, serves others, and forgets their garments entirely. If a piece requires constant manual readjustment to maintain its shape, it fails the test. You require clothing that holds its architecture while you move through your environment. Evaluate the seams and the interior finish. Demand heavy, durable construction that absorbs light. Your foundation relies on garments that feel substantial in your hands and grant you absolute physical freedom.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this foundational logic before you evaluate another garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the host test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your formula requires enduring structure balanced by athletic space and finished with one living texture. Build your wardrobe foundation on {texture_good_3} for tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years. Layer {texture_good_1} for winter knitwear that compresses under pressure and springs back. Anchor these pieces with warm, muted {texture_good_2} for shoes and belts that mould to your grip and patinate through use. Slip {texture_good_4} underneath for blouses and linings that add fluid movement without clinging. Always trust your hands before you check the label. Press the fabric against the inside of your wrist. If it scratches or feels synthetic against that sensitive skin, drop it immediately. Let tactile feedback overrule the tag. Look for the ranked materials below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Focus your touch on materials that pass strict physical tests before they ever reach your wardrobe.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
