    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Reject {texture_bad_1}. Squeeze the cloth in your palm. If it feels slick and stiff, put it back. It traps heat and refuses to provide the athletic space your body needs. Apply the forearm test to {texture_bad_2}. Drag the cloth across your skin. If it catches or scratches, let go. Poor synthetics fail this check every time. You need warm, matt yarns that drape naturally. Rely exclusively on the immediate friction of the fibre against your body to expose cheap manufacturing.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to spot the cheap frauds that sabotage your comfort.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to establish your baseline. This exact friction drives your style. Grip the cuff and bunch it in your fist. If the yarn bites or pulls rigidly, reject the item. Your garments must move freely to preserve that vital athletic space. Look for warm, muted dyes that sink completely into matt fibres. A garment should feel heavy and substantial when you lift it. True density exposes the quality of a weave. Let your fingers confirm the weight. Introduce {texture_good_1} as a final layer to add quiet depth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the precise material friction that grounds your style.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor shapes with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Use {core_colour_3} and {core_colour_4} to bridge the gap. Your palette is entirely warm, built to absorb light. Apply {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as a single deliberate accent. Deploy your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly near the face. Pass over Icy electric blue, Neon brights, and Fleeting trend pastels. Guide your colour choices by their visual gravity. Avoid the matt sinkhole where heavy tones blend into a muddy mass. This deep wash will swallow you whole. Lift it. Add a pale collar layer, introduce one piece of polished leather, or use your relief tone to carve out athletic space within the silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Understand your palette as a strict tool for proportion and focus.",
      "rankedItems": [
