    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Keep all patterns strictly low-contrast and tonal. Your tailored coats and heavy jackets derive their geometry from the weave itself, such as {recommended_pattern_1} woven directly into brushed wool. For fluid garments like silk shirts or lightweight scarves, deploy {recommended_pattern_2}. Leave {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} on the hanger. Pass over anything that relies on sharp, high-contrast printing to make its mark. To verify a pattern belongs with your collection, expose the garment to dim lighting. If the motif deepens and feels warm, pulling the threads together into a single matt surface, keep it. If the design jumps out sharply, reject it. Your eye will recognise a proper motif because it supports an enduring structure rather than fighting against it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master pattern by demanding it serves your foundation rather than dominating it.",
