    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At the desk, enduring structure leads. Establish this foundation with a rigid dark mahogany blazer. Support the sharp tailoring with calm detachment. Achieve this quiet mood by introducing a warm, breathing surface against the skin, like washed silk in bitter chocolate. Anchor the wrists across dual registers. Pair a matt gold cuff with a polished silver watch. Scrutinise every cloth by crushing it in your fist. A glossy photograph can hide cheap thread, but a tightly bound worsted wool confirms its own quality. Carry this standard into the mundane. Stepping out for an afternoon espresso does not justify surrendering your lines. Pull on a boiled wool coat before opening the door. Keep your form intact.",
      "sectionIntro": "Take control of your working hours by establishing a rigorous physical standard.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, cool composure leads. Anchor your shape in dark mahogany heavy silk crepe. Transitioning to a private dinner does not mean relaxing your sartorial grip. Maintain your architecture even as the evening slows down. Let a layer of bitter chocolate washed silk sit close to the collarbone. The warm, matt surface absorbs ambient candlelight. Assess the drape by pulling the fabric through your fingers. Shadows hide poor tailoring in dim rooms. The physical drag of dense fibre against your skin provides an irrefutable measure of worth. Master this quiet gravity.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your physical presence and material choices for intimate, low-light environments.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A routine dash to the grocer is not an excuse to collapse into unshaped jersey. Maintain your standard. Demand that every daily outfit meets your strict metric of enduring structure + cool composure + one living texture, regardless of the destination. Lean on the immediate drape of the garment in your grip. Feel the dense give of cloud-soft lambswool or the precise fall of heavy silk crepe. Ground your choices in a warm palette of bitter chocolate and dark mahogany. Reject any item that feels hollow. When preparing for a standard weekday commute, check the heft of the cloth blindfolded. If the fabric feels substantial and moves with deliberate intention, wear it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hold your daily routine to the exact same standard you demand everywhere else.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Divide your hardware into two distinct registers. Keep {personal_metal_1} and {personal_metal_2} reserved for items resting directly against the skin. Use {structural_metal_1} and {structural_metal_2} solely as utility markers for zips, clasps, and buckles. This strict division provides enduring structure without clutter. All chosen metals must stay warm. Refuse {excluded_finish} hardware entirely. A high-shine surface shatters the quiet depth of muted garments and distracts from the textile. Require matt or heavily brushed finishes. Always test the mass. Lift a buckle or chain in your palm. A cheap alloy hides behind plating, but genuine metallic weight announces itself instantly. Rely on that solid physical heft to verify the component.",
      "sectionIntro": "Mastering hardware means treating metal as an architectural anchor rather than a decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Weigh the gemstone in your hand before fastening the clasp. Let the raw stone pull against your fingers. You need materials that ground your frame. Seek out the dense opacity of {stone_1} and the murky depths of {stone_2}. These opaque elements lend enduring structure to your hardware collection. Avoid highly polished brightwork. A gleaming cut fractures the muted warm tones of your garments. Select untreated and tumbled finishes to keep the visual field unified. Brilliant facets shatter your cool composure. Rely on rough dimensions and a subdued face to anchor your aesthetic.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every stone by its physical density and its resistance to light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate your {metal_1} pendant by letting it drop into your cupped hand. You require enduring structure to ground your warm wardrobe. High-shine, polished brass behaves like a mirror. It cuts harshly across your muted palette and ruins your cool composure. Reject glossy finishes entirely. Select brushed or matt hardware to maintain a cohesive surface tension. A tarnished metal finish integrates seamlessly with cloud-soft lambswool, allowing the quiet age of the object to speak instead of a superficial glare.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate the physical integrity of your hardware before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Anchor your silhouette in enduring structure and establish your cool composure. Accessories serve a singular purpose here. They deliver the required one living texture. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with handbags. Require full-grain leather paired with brushed matt hardware. Run your thumb across the strap to gauge the material. Apply the one-ember test. Search for that single spark of warm vitality radiating from the hide. If the grain feels cold or synthetic, leave it on the shelf. Rely on tactile friction to judge the truth. A painted topcoat looks pristine from afar, but natural scarring proves authenticity.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the strict rules for selecting the few vital accessories that complete your system.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Scarves demand strict material boundaries. Choose only silk or fine wool in a strictly matt finish. Reject any fabric that catches the light. Evaluate potential purchases by searching for isolated heat. Seek a sole injection of warm colour, perhaps a subtle dark mahogany, rather than a blazing clash of patterns. This solitary flash provides the vital contrast required for your look. Drape a piece of cloud-soft lambswool over your collarbone. It must maintain cool composure while softening the rigid lines of a jacket. Demand enduring structure from the weave itself. Squeeze the fabric. If the material collapses without pushing back, drop it immediately. A printed pattern mimics depth, but only the physical gauge of the yarn counts.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply strict material and finish requirements to your scarf selection.",
      "rankedItems": [
