          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Secure your waist with the enduring structure of a medium full-grain leather belt. Demand a strictly matt brass buckle. For keepsake jewellery, select aged silver. Pick up an oxidised ring and feel its heft. Trust your grip to measure reality. A solid metal piece should drop heavily into your palm without rattling. This satisfying density grounds a warm dark mahogany wool trouser. Cement true cool composure by editing your final additions. Inspect your finished outfit before crossing the threshold. If multiple metals or leathers compete for focus, remove the most demanding item until only a solitary textural accent remains.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your final layers and strip away the excess.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Ground your printed garments in enduring structure. Let tailored pieces take their pattern directly from the physical weave of the cloth. Seek out {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} woven in warm, muted yarns. Fluid garments accept low-contrast tonal prints. Choose {recommended_pattern_3} to introduce movement. Restrict all contrast to subtle shifts within a single colour family. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. High-contrast graphics shatter a unified silhouette. Apply the firelight test to every dyed piece. Hold the fabric under an evening lamp. The motif must deepen and warm in the shadows, settling into the material rather than lifting off it. If the design turns harsh in low light, leave it on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as a structural tool, never a decorative distraction.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Scrutinise every {recommended_pattern_1} under low, warm lamplight. Step back three paces and narrow your eyes. A successful motif never vanishes into a muddy puddle. It deepens into a rich shadow of {core_colour_1}. Demand enduring structure from your prints by ensuring the contrast holds a distinct shape even when the physical edges blur. If the design softens into a flat smear, put the piece away. A worthy print preserves strict cool composure, keeping its architecture intact as the ambient glare drops.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply a strict distance test under dim light to evaluate pattern depth.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_capricorn__moon_sagittarius__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "enduring structure + fast movement + one living texture",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on enduring structure + fast movement + one living texture.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the physical weight and drape of a garment in your hands. If the fabric feels flimsy or rigid, leave it on the rack. A successful wardrobe requires pieces that ground you immediately. Your exact aesthetic relies on enduring structure + fast movement + one living texture. Picture a heavy, tailored overcoat worn completely open over a fluid, bias-cut slip dress, finished with a brushed, matt tote bag. The coat provides the rigid architecture. The slip brings the necessary speed. The bag gives the eye a warm place to rest.\n\nConstruct your foundation slowly. Source your anchoring architectural pieces with absolute patience over time. Deploy the fast-moving elements daily to shift the mood. Apply the shelter test to every final look before you leave the house. Ask yourself if the garments feel like a quiet, warm sanctuary against the skin. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. If the final combination does not make you feel entirely shielded, anchored, and secure in your physical space, take a layer off and start again.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the mechanical rules of your wardrobe before you buy another piece.",
      "tests": [
        "the shelter test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe around enduring structure. Test every piece before buying. Drape it over your bare wrist in the shop. If the fabric feels dead against your skin, drop it. Let the actual mass of the cloth dictate your choices. Demand {texture_good_3} for tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years. Require {texture_good_4} for blouses and linings that add fast movement. Choose {texture_good_1} for knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back. Ground these outfits with one living texture. Look for {texture_good_2} for bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate. Seek a warm, matt finish across every weave. Stick to this strict hierarchy.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the materials that build your foundation.",
