          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Plum",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Misty blue-green",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the sofa drift: soften every piece far enough and one day you are simply in loungewear",
          "fix": "restore exactly one line: a rolled but real lapel, a trouser with a soft crease, or a firm leather bag against all that give"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, your quiet pieces take the lead. Anchor your shape in heavy, matt camel wool and rich toffee silk. A dawn commute to the office does not mean surrendering your shape. Maintain your tailored silhouette and let a living element, like brushed cashmere or full-grain leather, do the subtle work. Evaluate the cloth by bunching it tightly. Depend on your tactile sense. Discard any piece that feels brittle. Restrict your hardware to warm, muted jewellery in brass or bronze. Pin your collar flat and keep your lines crisp. You dress to secure your own physical boundaries, never to project outward.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your workwear as a closed perimeter, designed to protect your focus rather than broadcast your presence.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, your enduring structure must lead. Dim lighting swallows subtle colour shifts. Rely on the distinct shape of a brushed wool jacket or the heavy drape of a rich toffee silk shirt. Lift a piece of full-grain leather to assess its density. Heavy items hold their silhouette in the shadows. Count on the undeniable heft of the material rather than a mirror. A shadowed dinner table demands rigorous discipline. Keep the cuts sharp and the edges clean. Choose a warm, muted metal watch or a heavy gold ring that catches the sparse light. Avoid anything chaotic or loose that relies on bright lighting to stand up.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the exact pieces to choose when the lights drop and the space gets small.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A trip to the post office does not grant you a pardon from shape. Apply your core formula of enduring structure + quiet undercurrent + one living texture every single day. A Tuesday morning at the farmers market does not justify defaulting to oversized fleece. Reach instead for a tailored camel wool coat over a fine gauge cashmere crewneck. Let the heavy fabric drape cleanly over a muted cotton trouser. Keep the palette warm and grounded. Rely on heavy full-grain leather boots to anchor the silhouette. If the garment feels shapeless in your grip, put it back. Assess the drape before you put it on.",
      "sectionIntro": "Maintain your baseline logic across every mundane errand.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Hold every clasp, ring, and zip in your palm. Visuals can be faked, but density cannot. Solid {metal_1} or {metal_2} hardware gives your garments enduring structure. Your strategy is permanently anchored in these warm tones. You can introduce {metal_3} if the piece has serious heft. Steer clear of {excluded_finish} surfaces. A highly polished, reflective finish creates a sharp distraction against soft cashmere and brushed wool. Choose matt or antiqued metals instead. This subdues the hardware, allowing it to provide a quiet undercurrent across your wardrobe. Let the gravity of the metal confirm its true worth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your hardware as the solid foundation of your wardrobe, testing every piece for physical substance.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Your jewellery must provide enduring structure, acting as self-contained anchors. Pick up a piece of {stone_1} or {stone_2} and judge its heft in your palm. Sight is easily tricked, but physical mass remains constant. Trust your tactile senses over a visual inspection. A dense stone grounds your warm colours. Avoid highly polished, reflective settings that jar violently against a muted wardrobe. Brilliant shine distracts and breaks your cohesion. Demand a brushed, matt finish on all metal to maintain the necessary quiet undercurrent of stability. Choose opaque stones that absorb illumination instead of refracting it. This ensures your hardware serves your own physical comfort without broadcasting for outside approval.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your stones as physical anchors, testing their density before you consider their colour.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Pick the piece up. Gauge the item blindly. Trust your hands as your primary guide when evaluating {metal_1} or {stone_1}. Your wardrobe relies on an enduring structure. Flimsy hardware undermines that foundation immediately. Close your eyes and feel the density in your palm. A hollow chain or lightweight buckle feels weak. High-glare finishes disrupt the harmony of muted garments. A mirror surface looks harsh next to soft {core_colour_1} layers. Anchor your pieces with brushed, matt hardware to maintain a cohesive warm look.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your hardware with your hands before committing it to your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Establish the base with your enduring structure and your quiet undercurrent. Accessories deliver that crucial one living texture. Anchor your outfit by committing to exactly one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with handbags. Demand full-grain leather or thick suede finished with warm, matt brushed hardware. Apply the ripple test before purchasing. Press your thumb heavily into the hide and drag it an inch across the surface. The material must ripple and gather slightly ahead of your digit. If your thumb glides without resistance across a completely rigid plane, the hide is coated in synthetic sealant. Discard the item instantly.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your accessories to ground your wardrobe with physical substance and tactile reality.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "When selecting scarves, demand generous silk or fine wool. Look for a surface that absorbs light into a deep, warm finish. Avoid anything slick or glossy. Execute the cascade test. Drape the fabric over your forearm and snap your wrist slightly. The material must fall in fluid, heavy waves that settle instantly. If it flutters or stands away from the body, leave it behind. A camel cashmere wrap or a rich toffee silk scarf grounds the enduring structure of your heavier garments without adding unnecessary volume. Keep the shape substantial but the finish completely matt.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select soft accessories that support your frame through weight and weave.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Secure your garments with a wide full-grain leather belt fastened by a matt brushed buckle. Select keepsake jewellery that feels heavy in the palm. Trust the physical gravity of warm metals to anchor your clothing. Seek out a deep garnet or tiger eye stone set in oxidised brass or aged silver. These dense elements provide enduring structure against soft brushed wool. To finish, drop the final accessory into your outfit and watch the surface. If the item sends a visual ripple that disrupts that quiet undercurrent, remove the piece. A resonant addition sinks in without a splash.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your composition with hardware and stones that ground the body.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Examine the weave. Let tailored garments draw their pattern directly from the yarn. Fluid pieces must rely on subtle tonal shifts. Keep all pattern contrast exceptionally low. The variation should remain hidden until you inspect the cloth up close. Anchor your selections in enduring structure, letting a low-contrast {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2} serve as the quiet undercurrent. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and any motif that sits flat on the surface. Observe the piece in fading evening light. The design must settle into a warm, moving texture. If the lines hold a rigid shape in the shadows, leave the garment on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as an integral structural element of the cloth, never as a decorative afterthought.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Hang the garment across the room and lower the lights. Run the distance test. Step back ten paces. In dim lighting, a successful {recommended_pattern_1} must blur into a warm and shifting shadow rather than standing out as rigid geometry. If the motif stays sharp and demanding, reject the piece. The design must settle into the weave and alter as the cloth shifts. This optical softening establishes the quiet undercurrent your foundation requires. Select motifs that merge seamlessly into enduring structure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this visual test to ensure your patterns serve your foundation rather than fighting it.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_capricorn__moon_taurus__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "enduring structure + sensory comfort + one living texture",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on enduring structure + sensory comfort + one living texture.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your hands to judge the true weight of a garment. If the fabric feels flimsy or synthetic, put it down. Curate your wardrobe slowly over seasons. Build a foundation you can deploy instantly on early mornings without a second thought. Before you buy anything new, apply the decade test. Look at the seams and the silhouette. Ask yourself if the cut will make sense to your eye ten years from today. If it relies on a fleeting trend to justify its shape, leave it on the rail.\n\nMaster your core style formula. Build every look around enduring structure + sensory comfort + one living texture. Picture a heavy tailored wool overcoat providing the outer architecture. Layer it over a fine gauge cashmere crewneck sweater to keep the body warm. Finish the outfit with a woven leather belt or a suede loafer to give the eye a tactile focal point. Keep all fabric finishes matt. This anchors the look in reality and stops the silhouette from feeling contrived.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural blueprint for building a wardrobe that relies on physical instinct and longevity.",
