    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Treat a scarf as your primary source of sensory comfort. Reach for pure silk or fine wool in warm, muted shades like camel. Avoid anything with a high sheen. Specify a completely matt finish instead. Run the fabric through your fingers and assess the weave for long-term durability. Question whether the textile will maintain its integrity over seasons of daily wear. If the weave feels flimsy or artificial, set it aside immediately. A piece must drape with physical gravity. Look for a dense, unreflective surface that absorbs light. Let the natural fibres do the work.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select scarves that deliver physical insulation and structural weight.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the heirloom test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Secure your silhouette with a medium full-grain leather strap and a matt buckle to establish enduring structure at the waist. Limit keepsake jewellery to tarnished brass or antiqued bronze pieces that anchor your warm wardrobe. Before finalising your choices, examine their future. Pick up the metal object and gauge its true mass. Trust this instinct. If the piece lacks the heavy integrity required to survive a lifetime of wear, remove it. True tactile quality guarantees absolute sensory comfort for the long haul.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate the physical weight and generational permanence of your final details.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the heirloom test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Demand low-contrast tonal transitions to maintain a muted finish. Let tailored garments take their pattern directly from the weave, securing enduring structure. Allow fluid pieces to carry soft variations like {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2}. Test every print for the field effect. It must settle into a warm, natural rhythm, much like ground seen from a high hill. If the design jumps off the fabric, pass it by. Anchor your choices in sensory comfort. Pass over strict geometry. Reject {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every pattern as an extension of the fabric itself.",
      "tests": [
        "the field test (settle into a natural texture like ground seen from a hill)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Step ten paces away from the mirror to run the landscape test. A valid {recommended_pattern_1} must never remain sharp. It should soften into a warm, organic wash. It must resemble a dense forest canopy viewed from afar, where individual branches merge into a continuous block of tone. If the motif stays rigid and readable at this distance, it will disrupt your silhouette. Discard the garment. A pattern that dissolves properly delivers absolute sensory comfort through visual calmness. You rely on the heavy seams of a tailored piece to guarantee enduring structure, not on graphic lines. Keep the surface quiet.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this distance test to ensure your patterns remain grounded and subtle.",
      "tests": [
        "the field test (settle into a natural texture like ground seen from a hill)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_capricorn__moon_taurus__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "enduring structure + sensory comfort + one living texture",
    "closing": "Navigate every choice by the weight of the cloth in your hands, securing your perimeter with enduring structure + sensory comfort + one living texture.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe slowly. Trust the physical weight and density of a garment in your hands as your primary compass. Look for textiles that hold a warm internal temperature against your skin. When you put a piece on, check your physical stance. Apply the host test. Ask yourself if the garment makes you the architectural anchor of the space. If you feel like a guest trying not to ruin the upholstery, take it off. Looks lie. Weight does not. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Let the structure hold you in a secure, self-contained radius.\n\nConstruct your daily outfits using a deliberate baseline. Your core formula is enduring structure + sensory comfort + one living texture. Picture a heavy tailored overcoat draped over a fine-gauge knit sweater, finished with a brushed hide belt. The coat provides the rigid architecture. The knit provides the immediate tactile relief against your body. The brushed hide breaks the flat surface with natural variation. Stick to a matt finish across your core pieces to absorb light rather than reflect it. Assemble these elements without seeking external validation. Dress entirely for your own physical equilibrium.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your operating baseline, the structural foundation you must use to evaluate every garment before you buy it.",
      "tests": [
        "the host test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "To achieve true sensory comfort, you must filter every garment through your fingertips. Your wardrobe requires warm, matt fabrics that drink the light rather than reflecting it. Rely on {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Anchor these pieces over {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Build enduring structure using {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. Keep the warmth trapped close to your skin with {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Always run the patina test. Rub the hem between your thumb and forefinger. If you cannot feel the material wearing into one living texture after years of quiet friction, leave it on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the materials that will actively serve you.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed alpaca",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "enveloping winter coats and oversized cardigans"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fluid modal jersey",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers that follow the body without ever gripping it"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed cotton flannel",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "shirts and loungewear that feel like a remembered embrace"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the patina test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Reject {texture_bad_1} the moment it brushes your skin. It feels brittle and traps heat. Run your thumb across {texture_bad_2}. If the surface catches or feels slick, leave it on the hanger. Assess materials for their long-term behaviour. Will the item absorb your movement and soften to your exact shape over the years, or will it simply pill into exhausted threads? {texture_bad_3} fails this instantly, feeling limp and hollow in your grasp. Allow your tactile response to dictate the decision. A flat photograph hides a cheap weave, but your hands will always catch it. Look for warm, matt finishes that maintain their enduring structure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to instantly reject materials that undermine your baseline.",
      "tests": [
        "the patina test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Unite {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Let your hands dictate the rules. Rub the material between your fingers. Set your {texture_good_1} against a dense, warm, matt weave. Demand strict sensory comfort from the base layers outwards. Question how each surface will age under constant heat and friction. Reject any cloth that thins or degrades. Keep only the fibres that map your shape and gather character over years of wear.",
      "sectionIntro": "Lock down your exact material combinations using touch alone.",
      "tests": [
        "the patina test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette is strictly warm. Build your foundation using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} for large garments. Add weight with {core_colour_3} for tailored pieces that demand enduring structure. Rely on {core_colour_4} as a grounding base for heavy outerwear. Deploy {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} deliberately in concentrated areas to provide sensory comfort. Apply a soft relief tone sparingly when a dense outfit needs air. Leave stark optic white, harsh neon, and icy pastel on the rack. Watch for the heavy earth sink. A dark matt outfit layered entirely in deep shades will swallow your shape. Fix this by adding a lighter cream collar, incorporating a piece of polished leather, or introducing that soft relief note to break the visual mass.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your palette by treating hue as a building material.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bitter chocolate",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Dark mahogany",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Blackened indigo",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep forest green",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Burnt umber",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Washed black",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Burnt amber",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rich cognac",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Misty taupe",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the all-earth sink: brown on olive on bark, all matt and all heavy, can swallow you whole",
          "fix": "lift it: an oatmeal cream layer at the collar, one piece of polished leather, or the washed blue relief"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "For your working day, enduring structure takes the lead. Establish a firm perimeter with a sharp trouser crease or a rigid collar. Inside that tailored shell, support the outfit with sensory comfort and one living texture using washed silk or heavy silk crepe. A rapid dash for a taxi requires maintaining your cloud-soft lambswool against the cold. Keep every tone warm, focusing on bitter chocolate, dark mahogany, and warm brass. Select a fully matt finish. Trust your hands. Pick the garment up and evaluate the seam. The result must remain entirely self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Here is how you direct your formula for the demands of the working day.",
      "tests": [
        "a school run or a corner shop dash does not require surrendering your softness (Cove)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close quarters and low-lit rooms, visual details recede. Let sensory comfort take the lead. Reach for heavy silk crepe in dark mahogany. The matt cloth anchors the shape in dim spaces. Pair it with warm gold jewellery that rests quietly against the collarbone. Keep the styling self-contained. An evening spent near a hearth does not mean surrendering your architecture. Pull on a heavy lambswool knit in bitter chocolate before the room cools. Trust your skin to evaluate the drape. Sight is easily fooled, but the physical sensation of a garment against your neck never lies.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master close quarters and evening settings by letting touch dictate your choices.",
      "tests": [
        "a school run or a corner shop dash does not require surrendering your softness (Cove)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Running mundane errands still requires absolute discipline in your dress. Reach for a bitter chocolate wool coat over a washed silk shirt. Keep your foundation warm and strictly private. Apply your core rule to every outing. Anchor your day with enduring structure + sensory comfort + one living texture. Notice the weight of lambswool on your shoulders while standing in the checkout queue. Judge an item exclusively by how it holds you. If a jumper scratches your skin, discard it immediately. Choose dark mahogany layers and matt finishes that turn your focus inward.",
      "sectionIntro": "Enforce your strictest material standards during the most ordinary hours of your routine.",
      "tests": [
        "a school run or a corner shop dash does not require surrendering your softness (Cove)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your jewellery and hardware require a warm dominant approach. Select {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} for everything from watch cases to bag clasps. Avoid {excluded_finish} completely. Highly polished, reflective metal acts as a sharp, distracting interruption against your muted clothing. Anchor your look with brushed or matt surfaces instead to maintain a cohesive finish. Assess every buckle and ring physically. Pick it up and evaluate the heft in your palm. Appearance deceives, but sheer weight never lies. Heavy, solid metals ground the outfit, providing the enduring structure required for a self-contained aesthetic.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your garments with solid metals that share the muted warmth of your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Pick up {stone_1} and test its density in your fingers. The eye is easily tricked. The mass of the stone reveals its true quality. Demand dense materials that offer enduring structure to your jewellery collection. Avoid highly reflective, polished mounts. Mirrored shine fractures your warm palette and distracts from the muted garments against your skin. Keep the look integrated by seeking out brushed or matt metals to hold {stone_2} and {stone_3}. Solid, opaque stones anchor an outfit. Translucent, lightweight pieces dilute it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your jewellery exactly as you evaluate a dense winter coat.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate the physical load of your hardware before wearing it. Judge by gravity. Pick up every {metal_1} buckle and {stone_1} pendant to gauge its resistance in your hand. Solid, substantial components provide the enduring structure necessary to anchor your garments. If an item feels hollow or fragile, leave it behind. Demand real density to guarantee absolute sensory comfort. High-glare polish shatters warm, muted colours. Bright reflections create a harsh distraction. Ground your choices with a flat, matt finish instead to maintain complete visual cohesion.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test the mass and finish of your metals to secure a grounded outcome.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments establish an enduring structure and guarantee deep sensory comfort. Your accessories step in to supply the final requirement. They must act as your one living texture. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. A single item must anchor the outfit without demanding attention. Apply the one-ember test. If an accessory glares brighter than a single glowing coal in a dark hearth, leave it on the shelf. Handbags are your primary tool. Demand full-grain leather or thick suede. Inspect the hardware closely. The metal must be warm and completely muted. Accept only dull, matt clasps and heavily brushed rings that absorb the light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select accessories with absolute precision to finalise the architecture of your outfit.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Treat scarves as an anchor of sensory comfort rather than a decorative flourish. Demand generous silk or fine wool. Refuse anything with a reflective sheen. Your textiles must remain matt. Run the solitary coal check. Seek out a warm, smouldering undertone in a dark mahogany or bitter chocolate weave, resembling a dying ember in an ash grate. If the fabric flashes under the light, drop it. It will break your self-contained boundary. You need quiet materials that absorb glare. Require enduring structure even in woven accessories. A flimsy scarf is a liability. Wrap a heavy, muted length around your neck and verify its density.",
      "sectionIntro": "Scarves require precise material boundaries to function as an anchor rather than a distraction.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your waist with wide full-grain leather belts and a matt brushed buckle. Keep your keepsake jewellery heavy and grounded. Pick a deep stone set in oxidised brass or aged silver. Your hands know the difference between solid metal and hollow casting. Trust your grip to verify the load. These items supply enduring structure without overwhelming your quiet presentation. They hold their own alongside a warm palette of bitter chocolate and dark mahogany. Finish by scanning your outfit for isolated brightness. You need exactly one focal point. If your deep stone ring competes with your belt buckle, remove the piece doing too much.",
      "sectionIntro": "Secure your foundation and establish a final point of focus.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor your tailored jackets with patterns woven directly into the cloth to establish enduring structure. Let your fluid blouses take their motifs purely from the dye. Enforce a strict low-contrast tonal rule for every printed item. Look for {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} without a second thought. Subject every new piece to the firelight test. Drape the cloth under a warm evening lamp. Trust your immediate physical reaction to the visual shift. The dark tones must bleed into rich shadows, softening the motif. If the contrast sharpens or turns harsh under the glow, drop the garment.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your prints by demanding low contrast and testing them in low light.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Execute the firelight check to judge any print. Take {recommended_pattern_1} into a space lit only by a dim bulb. A muted pattern must deepen and turn rich in warm light. If the lines separate into harsh geometry in the shadows, leave the garment on the rack. Your wardrobe serves as a closed system. Any motif you choose must settle into the cloth to ensure sensory comfort. Watch how the print behaves as the room darkens. It should blur slightly into the background weave. Rely on your eyes as they adjust to the low illumination. If the design suddenly jumps forward or jars your focus under the lamp, it fails.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every print to the light of your actual environment.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_gemini__moon_aquarius__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "crisp separation + mobile layers + one clever contrast",
    "closing": "Trust the physical friction and weight of your garments to instinctively direct your crisp separation + mobile layers + one clever contrast.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Feel for pivot capacity in your hands. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not. If a garment locks you into a single rigid posture, leave it on the rack. Your foundational structure relies on crisp separation + mobile layers + one clever contrast. Picture a sharp collared shirt sitting cleanly against a fluid wide trouser, topped with an unlined overcoat you can sweep off in a second, finished with unexpected heavy hardware on an otherwise simple shoe. The garments must maintain distinct boundaries. Keep your base temperature cool.\n\nAssemble your wardrobe slowly to serve the community around you, but deploy your combinations fast depending on the morning's demands. Before you finalise any purchase, apply the flight test. Crouch down to the floor, reach high above your head, and imagine sprinting for a departing train. If the armholes pinch or the hem restricts your stride, the piece fails. You require clothing that permits immediate physical action without requiring constant pulling or tucking. When you trust your mobility, your attention stays entirely on the people you meet.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this operating system to test every garment before you buy it.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe on fabrics that deliver crisp separation. Start with {texture_good_1} for shirting that holds clean boundaries. Anchor this with close-to-body {texture_good_2} to maintain sharp lines under your mobile layers. Demand {texture_good_3} for trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing when you move between varied environments. Finish with {texture_good_4} for lightweight outerwear that blocks a cool wind without weighing you down. Put every new material through an endurance trial. Ask yourself if the textile can survive ten hours in a restricted seat and still look sharp enough for an immediate gathering with peers. If it crushes or binds, leave it on the rack. Combine these trusted textiles to build one clever contrast. Stick to the ranking below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Let your hands vet every fabric before you even consider the cut.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Leave {texture_bad_1} on the hanger. Test its resilience by crushing a sleeve in your bare fist for ten seconds. If it retains a net of deep wrinkles, drop it. It will let you down after a long day of continuous wear. Reject {texture_bad_2} just as quickly. Rub the hem between your thumb and index finger. A slick, synthetic squeak signals a weave that traps body heat and sticks to your limbs. You require crisp separation between your clothes to stay cool. Clinging materials destroy that structure. Let your tactile response dictate the choice. If a fabric feels heavy or suffocating on the rack, it will only feel worse against your skin.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify and reject the materials that actively sabotage your physical comfort.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to establish crisp separation. Assess every piece of {texture_good_1} by folding it tightly, sealing it inside a stuffed holdall, and extracting it six hours later. It must shake out smooth and drape sharply. Rely on the immediate physical sensation of the cloth. Visuals easily mislead. Density and drape offer undeniable facts. A cool palette relies on materials that fall perfectly into place during local community gatherings. Pick the item up and crush it in your palms. If it holds a harsh crease, drop it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to recognise your ideal material pairings by trusting how they behave in motion.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your temperature is strictly cool. Build a functional base using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} as grounding neutrals. Deploy {core_colour_3} as a bright substitute neutral, and anchor the look with {core_colour_4} as a structural deep neutral. Inject {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} for your single deliberate accent. Apply the relief tone purely as a soft note used sparingly to ease rigid blocks of shade. Pass over Mustard, Rust, and Warm olive green entirely. Watch for the hard shell trap. When life speeds up, you might reach for stiff technical jackets and rigid utility armour. Catch your hands in the act and pivot. Rely on your touch to guide you. The mirror deceives, but the flex of a garment tells the truth. Swap the unyielding shell for a brushed cotton piece that bends with your stride, ensuring your mobile layers move fast and hold you steady.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assign each shade a functional job to build an adaptable and reliable foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Stark navy",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Icy grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Optical white",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep slate",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp charcoal",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Chalk",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Steel blue",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Acidic yellow",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sharp cobalt",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Kelly green",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Chalky blue",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the hard shell: reaching for armour, technical jackets, and stiff utility layers when life speeds up",
          "fix": "swap the shell for a brushed cotton layer that moves just as fast and holds you besides"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, crisp separation dictates your baseline. Let stark navy worsted wool trousers sit distinctly apart from an icy grey cotton poplin shirt. Build fluid garments over this sharp divide using a fine ribbed merino cardigan that you can shed in seconds. Your solitary contrast then finishes the look, perhaps a cool metal watch worn with a conflicting matt ring. Sending a favourite jacket to the cleaner does not excuse a drop in your daily metrics. If an item is unavailable, pick up a different piece that maintains the exact same standard. Trust your physical responses. If a collar feels restrictive at a desk, discard the shirt immediately. You cannot support your team if your clothes distract you.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your working uniform by enforcing strict standards and trusting your physical responses to select the right garments.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip to the dry cleaner does not suspend your standards (Frost)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "Low light alters how garments behave. In dim settings, let crisp separation lead. Shadowy rooms swallow subtle details. Rely on sharp boundaries instead. Place an icy grey fine ribbed merino knit cleanly beneath a stark navy technical nylon jacket. Keep the overall temperature cool. Mix your metals freely. Wear a polished silver watch next to a matt steel ring. Grasp the worsted wool before putting it on. If the cloth feels limp, leave it on the hanger. Leaving your preferred cotton poplin out of commission does not mean you accept inferior cloth for dinner. Demand identical structural integrity from every item.",
      "sectionIntro": "Navigate intimate spaces and low-light environments by letting your hands dictate quality and sharp visual boundaries define your silhouette.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip to the dry cleaner does not suspend your standards (Frost)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Queueing at the local pharmacy to collect a prescription does not pause your baseline. Maintain strict discipline. Rely on the raw friction of the cloth to guide you. Your fingers know the truth before your eyes do. Pick up an icy grey poplin shirt and feel how it drops over a stark navy technical nylon vest. Mix silver rings with a matt bronze watch case. Require crisp separation + mobile layers + one clever contrast every time you dress. Evaluate the heavy drape of worsted wool trousers over your trainers. Do not settle for blurred edges just because you are stepping out for minor errands. Hold a cool, analytical view of how items interact.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your strict material logic to every minor task.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip to the dry cleaner does not suspend your standards (Frost)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "You possess total freedom to combine {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} across your wardrobe. Anchor this mixing in a strictly cool temperature. Artificially aged hardware, hammered copper, and antiqued brass disrupt your aesthetic. They create visual clutter. Avoid {excluded_finish} entirely. Instead, demand highly reflective, present-tense white metals for every zip, buckle, and watch case. Pick up any new piece of jewellery or bag chain before you buy it. The surface appearance will mislead you. Mass reveals the truth. Only wear hardware that feels dense in your palm. This solid physical foundation maintains crisp separation between your garments, even when you stack mixed metal rings or add heavy zips to your mobile layers.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware by its physical density and exact temperature.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Maintain crisp separation in your styling by selecting dense, cool stones. Lift the piece off the glass to judge its worth. A superficial visual appraisal fails, but pure gravity provides an honest metric. Test {stone_1} and {stone_2} in your palm for this required physical heft. Avoid textured copper and artificially darkened brass. This faux historical finishing reads as clutter against a present-tense aesthetic. Fix this visual noise by anchoring your jewellery in mirror chrome, platinum, white gold, and polished silver. This precise hardware approach allows you to build mobile layers without generating unnecessary friction.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware by weight, relying on dense stones and polished metals.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate the mass of every item in your palm. Prioritise tactile feedback over sight. Glossy plating easily masks cheap construction. Unyielding weight gives an honest answer. Let the sheer heft of a {metal_1} buckle or chain guide your final choice. Skip tarnished bronze, beaten copper, and any simulated weathered finishes. Those fake patinas read as messy interference against a cool palette. Stick exclusively to pristine {metal_1}, bright platinum, and mirror chrome. Dense hardware anchors mobile layers with absolute precision. When you build outfits around crisp separation, you need clean metal to hold the line.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the physical tests that separate genuine quality from cheap imitation.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Establish your crisp separation. Add functional mobile layers. Then deploy accessories to supply exactly one clever contrast. Restrict the build to one or two strong pieces per look. Start with eyewear. Look for a substantial acetate frame with a mixed finish, pairing a polished rim against matt temples. Read the sensory feedback of the materials. Your own body dictates the utility of a garment. Apply a strict removal protocol before stepping out into the cool air. Take off the final piece you put on. If the outfit loses its deliberate edge, put the item back. If you feel immediate physical relief, leave it behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is how you finish the build and test its weight.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "acetate frame, mixed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Carry a technical nylon crossbody bag. The matt fabric creates crisp separation against a thick worsted coat. Inspect the hardware for a mixed finish. Look for brushed metal zips paired with one polished ring. This keeps the overall temperature cool. Execute a practical load trial. Pack the bag with your daily items, sling it over your shoulder, and remove the bulkiest piece if it warps the outer profile. The strap must sit flat across your chest. Let the drag of the strap guide your choice. Reflections mislead. Friction is honest. Test the zips. If the teeth catch, leave it on the shelf. The design must accommodate multiple mobile layers without sliding down your arm.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess your accessories for structural integrity and functional hardware.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "technical nylon crossbody, brushed metal zips, one polished ring"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select a clean leather boot to anchor your base. Run your thumb along the welt. You require a clean profile without heavy rubber blocks. A polished or matt black calfskin provides crisp separation where the boot meets the trouser hem. Keep the leather dyes strictly cool. Before stepping out, audit your additions. Strip away the final piece of hardware you attached, be it a gold cuff or a steel collar. Judge the result by physical weight, not just the visual balance. If removing that metal makes the outfit feel unbalanced on your body, put the item back. If the foundation holds its ground without the extra mass, leave the piece on the table.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your silhouette with the right footwear and rigorously test your final edit before leaving.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "clean leather boot, clean"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored garments demand architectural lines. Fluid pieces take their visual rhythm from continuous repetition. Because your approach adapts to different environments, dial the pattern contrast up or down to suit the specific context. Keep the underlying colour temperature cool. Anchor your wardrobe with {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Completely reject {avoid_pattern_1}. Pass over any print that announces itself from ten paces away. Apply a rigorous kinetic test to every new acquisition. The printed fabric passes only if it reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion. Use these shifting motifs to establish crisp separation against your solid fabrics. Introduce a patterned shirt under your outerwear to build adaptable mobile layers.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test every printed garment by how it behaves when the fabric shifts.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Step back ten paces and walk briskly towards the glass. A successful {recommended_pattern_1} must blur into a gentle, tactile surface as you step forward. Drop the garment if the print flashes or demands rigid attention. You need this visual quietness to guarantee crisp separation under an open jacket or a heavy sweater. When the motif softens during an active stride, it acts as a subtle structural element. Look for a cool undertone in the ink to anchor the piece. If the design resolves into a pleasant, indistinct weave when you move, keep it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Run the ten-pace motion test on every patterned garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_gemini__moon_aquarius__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "crisp separation + mobile layers + one clever contrast",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on crisp separation + mobile layers + one clever contrast.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the physical instinct of kinetic equilibrium. Your clothes must move when you move and hold their ground when you stop. Build your wardrobe slowly and deliberately. Test each garment for structural independence before buying, then deploy your daily combinations fast. Your absolute baseline is crisp separation + mobile layers + one clever contrast. Picture a rigid cotton shirt tucked sharply into heavyweight wool trousers. Add an unlined, fluid trench coat that shifts with your stride. Finish the look with a heavy industrial buckle clamping down the soft waistband.\n\nWhen judging an outfit, apply the half-mirror test. Look at your reflection from collarbone to waist for precisely three seconds, then turn away. If you hesitate to fix a collar or force a hem to drape correctly, strip the layer off. Your body understands when the balance is compromised. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Keep the baseline temperature strictly cool, leaning into stark precision. Mix matt fabrics against high-shine finishes without hesitation. Looks lie. Weight does not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this blueprint to construct your foundation and calibrate your physical instincts.",
      "tests": [
        "the half-mirror test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Trust your hands to find the right materials. Look for {texture_good_1} to create crisp separation between your collar and your skin. Build your foundation with {texture_good_2} for base layers that hold a sharp edge but stretch across your shoulders. When choosing trousers, seek out {texture_good_3} to ensure a clean drape that survives hours of movement. Finish with {texture_good_4} to build mobile layers that block the cool air without adding heavy bulk. Put every potential purchase through the wrist-flick test. Hold the sleeve or hem and snap your wrist sharply. If the fabric ripples cleanly and settles back into a perfect line instantly, buy it. If it crumples or hesitates, leave it on the hanger. The ranked list below gives you your best targets.",
      "sectionIntro": "Let your hands verify the utility of your garments before you ever check a mirror.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
