          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede or smooth leather top-handle, fine mixed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Scale your print contrast to the garment's function. Anchor tailored jackets with structured geometrics like {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Let your fluid pieces carry looser arrangements. A fine knit easily takes {recommended_pattern_3}. Always demand crisp separation between the darkest ink and the base cloth. This precision establishes hidden depth inside the motif. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. Hang the item across the room to verify its impact. The graphics must maintain their borders from a distance. If the lines dissolve into an indistinct blur, walk away. Ensure the underlying temperature remains strictly cool.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply strict visual tests to your prints to ensure they serve your wardrobe rather than confusing it.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Step back ten paces and shut your eyes. Snap them open for a single split second. If {recommended_pattern_1} turns into a muddy smudge, drop the hanger. You require crisp separation to build your silhouette. A valid print remains instantly legible from across a crowded shop. If the borders bleed or the visual data becomes chaotic, the cloth fails. Rely on this rapid blink test to eliminate clutter. The motif must register sharply at a glance, preserving its geometry before you step closer to uncover the hidden depth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every print to a strict physical test of distance and clarity.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_gemini__moon_cancer__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "crisp separation + hidden depth + one clever contrast",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on crisp separation + hidden depth + one clever contrast.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your physical compass is structural precision. Run your hands over every piece before you try it on. Trust the drag of a heavy woven fabric and the slick resistance of a densely spun yarn. Build your wardrobe slowly. Scrutinise every seam before you commit. Deploy your outfits fast on the day. Your core style formula is crisp separation + hidden depth + one clever contrast. Picture a sharply tailored trench coat layered over a heavyweight crewneck, finished with a tactile scarf tucked cleanly at the collar. The edges remain entirely distinct. The depth sits in the fabric weight.\n\nApply the host test to every potential purchase. Ask yourself if the garment allows you to step back and direct the event without becoming the spectacle. Seek out pieces that maintain a cool, muted reserve. If a jacket demands constant adjustment or a collar forces you to match its energy, put it back on the rail. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not. Every item must serve your balanced structure, allowing you to move through your schedule without fighting your own clothes.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your foundational logic before you evaluate a single garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the host test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Seek out materials that build crisp separation into your attire. Trust your hands before your eyes. Squeeze {texture_good_1} in your fist. It must compress heavily and bounce back instantly to earn a place in your winter knitwear. For your belts and shoes, rely on {texture_good_2} to patinate slowly while holding a cool, muted finish. Build the architecture of your blazers from {texture_good_3} because it keeps a strict edge over time. When you need hidden depth, layer {texture_good_4} underneath as a fluid blouse. Before purchasing, execute the candlelight test. Hold the garment near a single low light source. If the surface throws back a harsh glare rather than absorbing the shadows evenly, put it down. Stick to the materials listed below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to evaluate fabrics with your hands before you ever check the composition label.",
      "rankedItems": [
