    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Avoid {texture_bad_1} that squeaks when you pinch it between two fingers. Grasp the fabric tightly. A stiff, rigid drape always betrays poor quality. Leave {texture_bad_2} on the rack if it catches on your knuckles or generates static electricity. Examine the piece in a dimly lit space. If the surface throws a harsh glare instead of absorbing the ambient glow, it fails. You require a cool, matt finish to ground your look. Cheap synthetic shine ruins the precise balance required to execute one clever contrast successfully. Pick the item up and test the weight. Drop anything that feels hollow.",
      "sectionIntro": "Identify the physical tells of poor construction before they ever touch your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Test new materials in a dark room beside a single small flame. The cloth must drink that glow to produce soft shadows. Pair {sweet_spot_keyword_1} directly against {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to force crisp separation between your layers. Run your bare hands across the threads to confirm a cool, matt profile. Sight is easily manipulated. Woven density provides the only reliable proof. Introduce {texture_good_1} sparingly beside a dense drape. This strict approach builds structural complexity without compromising your balanced orientation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Lock down your foundational material pairing.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Build your foundation with {core_colour_1}, {core_colour_2}, and {core_colour_3}. Use {core_colour_4} as your strict substitute for white. Your temperature is decisively cool. Create hidden depth by layering these foundational tones. Apply {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as a single deliberate accent point. Deploy the relief tone purely to break a heavy block of darkness. Leave hot saturated red, stark optic white, and harsh neon on the rack. They shatter your alignment. Watch out for the shadow sink. Piling dark foundational layers together flat and heavy will swallow your silhouette. Lift the visual weight. Put a {core_colour_4} layer at the collar, add one piece of structured leather, or inject the relief tone.",
