          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Establish your crisp separation. Secure your light movement. Hardware and additions provide your one clever contrast. Anchor this formula by restricting yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with eyewear. Pick up an acetate frame that shifts between gloss and matt textures. Put it on and gauge the physical balance. Subject your reflection to a load check before you finish dressing. Remove the final item you put on. If your neck feels physically lighter or your face regains its sharp edge, the extra piece was clutter. Let your body's stance inform your choices. Heavy additions will drag a cool palette down.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hardware and additions serve as the strict final variable in your daily uniform.",
      "rankedItems": [
