    "closing": "Follow the weight of the cloth in your hands, relying on physical gravity to secure your crisp separation + light movement + one clever contrast.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your physical instincts as your ultimate compass. When evaluating a new garment, gauge its kinetic potential. Pick it up and feel how it responds in your hands. If the structure restricts your shoulders or hangs entirely inert on your frame, put it back. You require garments that transition seamlessly between environments. Build your collection deliberately. Assess every piece for its capacity to shift contexts, and deploy it quickly when dressing for the day. You are looking for a precise balance between rigid control and total physical ease.\n\nYour baseline formula relies on crisp separation + light movement + one clever contrast. Picture a sharply tailored shirt tucked cleanly into a fluid, wide-leg trouser, instantly grounded by a heavy, architectural shoe. This requires an exact physical calibration. Run every prospective purchase through the fall test. Hold the item at waist height and drop it onto a flat chair. If it crumples in a lifeless heap instead of pooling with a distinct, cool structural integrity, leave it in the shop. Looks lie. Weight and drape do not.",
