      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored garments pull their pattern from the weave. Fluid pieces carry the ink. Rely on this division. Your adaptable approach requires mid-scale contrasts that shift easily between environments. Perform the straight-edge test. Step back three metres from the glass. The geometric boundaries must remain clear and true. If the shape blurs into visual noise, reject it. Choose {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2} for structured jackets. Allow {recommended_pattern_3} to inject light movement into thinner layers. Enforce crisp separation where a patterned fabric meets a solid block. Treat a subtle {recommended_pattern_4} as your clever contrast beside a cool {core_colour_1} background. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. They disrupt your baseline geometry. Trust your physical reflex. If the print fights the garment structure, leave it on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate pattern not by its beauty on the hanger, but by its behaviour on the body.",
      "tests": [
        "the straight-edge test (lines stay crisp and true at three metres)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Examine any {recommended_pattern_1} from a distance. Hang the garment on a door frame and cross the room. Squint hard. If the shapes bleed into a vague haze, drop the hanger and walk away. The geometry must hold true at a range. Trust your eyes on this point. Visual clarity guarantees crisp separation. A blurring motif creates visual mud. You need absolute boundaries in the ink. Pair this graphic discipline with separate garments that provide light movement. Keep the dye temperature strictly cool.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate prints strictly by testing their visual boundaries.",
      "tests": [
        "the straight-edge test (lines stay crisp and true at three metres)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_gemini__moon_libra__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "crisp separation + cool composure + one clever contrast",
    "closing": "Trust your physical instincts to map the exact boundaries of your silhouette, demanding nothing less than crisp separation + cool composure + one clever contrast.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Feel for a garment's pivot potential. Trust your hands to identify pieces that carry structural integrity without stiffening your posture. Your wardrobe operates on a definitive equation. Memorise it as crisp separation + cool composure + one clever contrast. Picture a sharply tailored blazer worn open over a fluid, lightweight base layer, finished with a heavy industrial boot. The layers do not bleed into each other. They hold their own distinct visual territory. You must maintain this exact physical equilibrium. Keep the overall temperature undeniably cool.\n\nCurate your collection with slow, analytical deliberation so you can deploy outfits rapidly and drift according to your immediate mood. When assessing a combination, apply the treaty test. Ask yourself if the conflicting items in your reflection have negotiated a successful peace. A dense knit must not crush a delicate hem. A rigid collar must not look absurd against a slouching trouser. Both ideas must maintain absolute dignity and hold equal ground. If one item completely dominates the rest, take it off immediately. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn this blueprint to build your operational baseline.",
      "tests": [
        "the treaty test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe entirely on materials that hold their shape. Crisp separation relies on textiles that refuse to collapse. Use {texture_good_1} for shirting to establish clean architectural boundaries. Pair this with {texture_good_2} for close-to-body base layers that maintain sharp lines. Anchor your lower half with {texture_good_3} trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing. Finish with {texture_good_4} for mobile outerwear that secures your cool composure while weighing almost nothing. Before you buy anything, perform the tension test. Grip a section of the garment between your palms and pull gently in opposite directions. Rely on this tactile feedback. If the weave feels responsive and the fabric snaps back precisely, it belongs in the priority list below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise the tactile sensations that guarantee your garments will hold their structural boundaries.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
