        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Put one hand inside the fabric and your other hand directly over it. Grind your palms together to check the friction. If the material feels hollow or the fibres catch on your skin, drop the piece. You rely on cool composure to build one clever contrast. Weak textiles ruin that structure. Materials like {texture_bad_1} feel slippery and squeak under tension. Garments cut from {texture_bad_2} stretch unevenly and refuse to return to their original geometry. Visuals deceive. Mass tells the truth. Let your touch govern the decision. If a textile feels dead or abrasive in your grip, it will fail on your body.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise structural failures before a garment touches your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Achieve crisp separation by setting {sweet_spot_keyword_1} against {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Run a friction check on every new piece. Grab the garment, close your eyes, and roll the weave between your thumbs. You are searching for the cool, definite finish of {texture_good_1}. If the yarn feels weak or blurred under pressure, discard it. Your wardrobe demands this specific resistance. Anchor a structured matt base with a smooth edge. Let the tactile difference between a rough knit and a polished thread define the outfit.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to find the exact friction your wardrobe requires.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your baseline temperature runs strictly cool. Construct your daily foundation from {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Add {core_colour_4} as a structural dark to guarantee crisp separation alongside lighter layers. Reach for {core_colour_3} when you require a stark light neutral. Leave Mustard, Rust, and Warm olive green on the rail entirely. They dilute your focus. Apply {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as a single deliberate hit of saturation. Keep your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly to break solid blocks. Beware the aesthetic pendulum, an error where you dress in airy linen one month and rigid canvas the next. Correct this habit immediately. Always keep one item from the opposing mood in play. Layer fine ribbed merino under rigid technical nylon to hold the line.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your working palette, an instrument built for exact tuning rather than random selection.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Stark navy",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Icy grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Optical white",
          "role": "white_substitute"
