    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, crisp separation dictates the outcome. Support this division with a cool palette, using stark navy and icy grey to build a disciplined base. Introduce a single unexpected material to break the uniformity. Grasp the fine ribbed merino and test the tension. Depend on your fingers to gauge the truth of a fabric. Appearance deceives, but structure provides facts. If your primary cotton poplin awaits collection from the dry cleaner, do not settle for a yielding substitute. A maintenance queue does not pause your rules. Demand rigid borders in every garment. Look for worsted wool that holds a sharp crease. Choose matt finishes for any metal hardware.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your working hours as a laboratory for precision, reserving zero tolerance for defaults.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip to the dry cleaner does not suspend your standards (Frost)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "For intimate evening settings, cool composure leads. Evaluate every piece by touch alone. Pinch a stark navy worsted wool sleeve. Does it hold firm? Mass reveals the truth where low light hides sloppy cuts. Avoid soft, collapsing shapes. Investigate the technical nylon. Depend on your bare hands to judge quality. Mix metals freely. Blend a sterling silver chain with a white gold watch. Combine a matt titanium ring alongside polished steel. Maintain this strictness constantly. Replacing a dropped button on your icy grey jacket requires the exact same rigour as ordering a cocktail in a dimly lit booth. Do not drop your standards for a minor repair.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat intimate settings as a strict test of physical construction, demanding sharp execution over loud distraction.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip to the dry cleaner does not suspend your standards (Frost)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat a Tuesday morning trip to the post office exactly as you treat a formal appointment. Queuing for a parcel does not grant permission to suspend your rules. Build your daily silhouette using stark navy worsted wool trousers paired with a technical nylon shell. Rely entirely on crisp separation + cool composure + one clever contrast. Inspect a crisp cotton poplin shirt and gauge the collar. If the points droop, discard the item. Combine an icy grey cashmere scarf with a polished silver watch and a matt gold ring. Gauge the density of the metal. Every mundane hour demands exact mechanics.",
      "sectionIntro": "Approach your ordinary routines as the primary proving ground for your styling mechanics.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip to the dry cleaner does not suspend your standards (Frost)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Treat hardware as a flexible toolkit. You have the freedom to mix your metals. A {metal_1} watch works perfectly alongside {metal_2} zips and a {metal_3} belt buckle. Keep the underlying temperature cool. Enforce crisp separation between different tones so they never blur into a muddy compromise. Avoid beaten copper, oxidised brass, and artificially aged items. These faux-vintage treatments introduce unwanted visual noise into a present-day aesthetic. Anchor your choices in polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome. Lift the buckle or chain before committing to it. Surface polish lies. Gravity tells the truth. Authentic hardware feels heavy in the palm. Embrace an {excluded_finish} surface to introduce variety without adding fuss.",
      "sectionIntro": "Metals provide your structural foundation, so evaluate your hardware with absolute physical conviction.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Combine {stone_1} and {stone_2} purely for their absolute density and flawless clarity. Lift the piece from the glass counter to evaluate its physical mass. Determine its quality by how it presses into your skin. A solid, light-capturing {stone_3} anchors the garment to guarantee crisp separation. Reject any antiqued settings or beaten surfaces. Tarnished alloys introduce unnecessary historical clutter into an immediate, sharp aesthetic. Demand highly polished, reflective metals to maintain a strict, cool temperature, freely mixing your hardware as long as the surface remains immaculate.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every stone and metal element by its physical gravity and optical precision.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Test every piece of jewellery before you wear it. Visuals deceive, but a heavy drop provides an honest metric. A thick {metal_1} ring should pull downward with unmistakable density. Maintain crisp separation by rejecting artificially tarnished brass or beaten copper. These simulated patinas introduce immediate visual clutter. Instead, select solidly cast pieces that anchor your cool composure. Place the item in your palm to verify its weight. If it feels hollow or light, put it back. Quality requires physical substance.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test the physical reality of your hardware before you accept its visual premise.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories supply the one clever contrast that completes your outfit. They reinforce the crisp separation of your layers and secure the cool composure of your final silhouette. Enforce a strict limit of one or two strong pieces per look. Apply the final-check test at the door. If an addition compromises the clean geometry of your poplin collar or clutters your profile, strip it away. Assess any new item blindly. Mirrors deceive. Physical density does not. Squeeze a silk scarf. Choose a matt crepe de chine square. Feel the dry friction of the weave. It must hold a sharp fold against your tailoring.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use accessories as precise structural tools to finalise your silhouette, rather than decorative afterthoughts.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Select fine jewellery to build subtle tension. Inspect thin chains and slim rings that combine gold and silver. Pair polished sterling silver against brushed white gold or a matt yellow gold band. Trust your physical response to the metal. If a piece catches on your cuff or restricts your movement, discard it. Perform a final audit before you step outside. Scan your reflection to ensure your metallic choices remain deliberately fragmented. If a thick bracelet dominates the outfit or disrupts your cool composure, take it off immediately. Let the icy grey tones of your clothing anchor these scattered metals. Keep the scale fine. Rely on the strict visual friction of mixed surface treatments to carry the detail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use fine jewellery to build complex metallic friction without adding physical weight.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin mixed gold and silver, mixed polished and brushed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor the composition with a small structured bag. Demand a rigid top-handle in kid suede or matt smooth leather. Gauge the density of its fine mixed hardware. Depend on this heavy resistance as your primary measure of quality. Images distort scale, but actual gravity tells the exact truth. Let the sharp geometry of the bag enforce crisp separation against your technical nylon garments. It must uphold the cool composure of your icy grey and stark navy palette. Before leaving, check the full silhouette. Step back and evaluate the entire outfit. If the bag's metallic hardware or suede texture blurs into the garments instead of standing apart, it fails. Remove the piece and swap it for one that holds its own distinct boundary.",
      "sectionIntro": "Secure your final structure and evaluate the entire composition before stepping out.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede or smooth leather top-handle, fine mixed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Ground your tailored garments in patterns built directly into the weave. Let your fluid pieces carry the surface prints. Adapt your contrast to the context. Anchor the foundation with tonal motifs, then deploy a graphic scale on a single piece to build crisp separation. Apply the arm's-length test to every patterned weave. Step back to confirm the surface resolves into a calm, solid block of cool colour. Move close to find a rewarding, intricate thread structure. Rely on {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} to add depth without breaking your strict geometry. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} completely. They scatter the eye and dilute the sharp cut of the garment.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control the visual noise of your garments by treating pattern as a structural tool.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the ten-pace blur test. Hang the garment across the room. Step back. At ten paces, the fabric must resolve into a single, uniform block. Move closer. The strict geometry of {recommended_pattern_1} should only emerge when you are within speaking distance. This mechanism maintains cool composure from afar while delivering structural detail up close. If the design fights for attention from across the shop floor, put it down. Inspect the boundaries of the motif. Demand crisp separation between the printed elements and the negative space. Blurry edges fail the test.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every print to a strict physical distance check.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_gemini__moon_pisces__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "crisp separation + blurred edges + one clever contrast",
    "closing": "Trust your physical instincts to align your wardrobe, reducing every choice to crisp separation + blurred edges + one clever contrast.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Curate your wardrobe slowly. Assemble your outfits with rigid precision. Trust your physical reaction to a garment's weight as your ultimate compass. Run your hands over the shoulder seams and hems. If the fabric feels substantial and cool against the skin, keep it. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Apply the decade test to every piece you consider. Inspect the garment's cut and ask yourself if it was drafted ten years ago or yesterday. If you cannot anchor the silhouette to a specific year, it passes.\n\nYour exact structural algorithm is crisp separation + blurred edges + one clever contrast. Picture a sharply tailored overcoat layered over a yielding knit, finished with a hard, structured shoe. The coat delivers strict, architectural lines. The knit dissolves the interior boundary against your body. The rigid shoe provides the sudden shift in surface tension to ground the entire look. Strip away excess detail. Rely entirely on a matt finish and a muted profile to let the silhouette do the heavy lifting.",
      "sectionIntro": "Internalise this blueprint before you evaluate another garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the decade test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe runs on a careful balance of weight and movement. You need {texture_good_3} to build tailored blazers that hold clean lines for years. That structure provides the crisp separation your look requires. Against that architecture, introduce the blurred edges of {texture_good_1} in your winter knitwear. It must compress under pressure and bounce back instantly. Add one clever contrast using the fluid movement of a {texture_good_4} blouse beneath a heavy lapel. Anchor it all with {texture_good_2} bags and belts that mould to your stride and patinate with wear. Let the textile's behaviour guide you, not the designer tag. Run your fingers over the cloth. If the surface resists your grip or produces a hollow scrape when pinched, put the garment down and walk away. Seek out the materials ranked below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the materials that do the physical work for your style.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
