    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Anchor your hardware in cool temperatures. Treat {metal_1} and {metal_2} as your primary metals. Introduce {metal_3} only sparingly. Avoid mirror-like shine. A highly polished belt buckle cuts a sharp, distracting line against subdued fibres. Stick to matt and brushed finishes. This muted approach guarantees crisp separation between pieces without overwhelming the eye. Lift every chain, zip, and watch casing before buying. Evaluate pieces purely by their heft. Solid hardware sits firmly against the body, proving its worth in grams. Eliminate {excluded_finish} completely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your finishing details by controlling their temperature, texture, and density.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Look for density and an opaque finish when selecting {stone_1} and {stone_2}. Highly reflective, mirrored hardware will flash aggressively against your muted garments. Select matt finishes to anchor the piece. Pair an opaque stone with a cool metal band to achieve crisp separation. This prevents the ring from reading as a solid block. Test the quality by lifting the object from the tray. Determine a gem's value by its sheer density in your palm. Let your fingers gauge the mass. Seek heavy stones that create blurred edges where they meet the setting. Avoid lightweight, glassy alternatives. They feel hollow and compromise the item.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate stones by their weight and how their finish interacts with your metals.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Assess the hardware in your palm. Optical illusions fade the moment a piece rests in your hand. Let density dictate your choices. If a {metal_1} buckle or {stone_1} detail feels hollow, leave it behind. You need solid components to anchor the outfit. Maintain crisp separation by choosing items with undeniable weight. Avoid highly polished surfaces. A mirror-like gloss flashes sharply against your cool, muted clothing and ruins the blurred edges of your look. Stick strictly to matt and brushed textures. A heavy, brushed finish absorbs light and integrates seamlessly.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply a strict physical test to every piece of hardware before adding it to your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your clothing establishes crisp separation. Your knitwear introduces blurred edges. Accessories exist to deliver one clever contrast. Hold to a strict maximum of one or two strong pieces per look. Overloading destroys the balance. Begin your selection with handbags. Demand full-grain leather and brushed matt hardware. Always apply a physical test before you commit. Pick the bag up by its strap and trust your hands over your eyes. Authentic quality sinks into your palm with a heavy, cool density. If the metal feels hollow, drop it. Ensure the construction feels capable of surviving decades of daily exposure. If you doubt its lifespan for even a second, reject it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the exact science of selecting and physically testing the pieces that finish your look.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the heirloom test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Pick up a scarf and evaluate the drape. Demand fine wool or silk with a strictly matt finish. Rely on physical gravity as your guide. The downward pull of the fabric matters more than its printed pattern. A substantial silk accessory in dove grey establishes crisp separation against a structured collar. Question whether the weave will withstand half a century of friction. If it lacks that enduring generational gravity, put it back. Seek out cool tones like deep teal that absorb light. A matt textile draped close to the neck supplies blurred edges without sacrificing geometric shape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess the textiles you place closest to your face.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the heirloom test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select a medium full-grain leather belt to build crisp separation at the waist. Insist on a matt buckle to control the muted finish. Introduce keepsake jewellery crafted from aged silver. Look for oxidised details that soften the metal, providing necessary blurred edges against a deep teal knit. Evaluate every piece with the heirloom test. Ensure the ring or chain feels like a private inheritance extracted from a locked mahogany box rather than a fresh retail purchase. If the surface gleams perfectly, return it to the shelf. Trust the cool, heavy reality of the material.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply these final physical standards to your leather and metals to ensure the finishing touches secure the look.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the heirloom test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Restrict patterns to a strict logic of woven geometry for tailored coats and subtle dye shifts for fluid pieces. Enforce a low-contrast tonal rule to protect your cool, muted baseline. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1}. Select {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2} instead. Execute the distance check. Step back and squint at the fabric. The motif must settle into a unified natural texture, resembling the ground seen from a distant hill. If individual shapes jump out, drop the item. Anchor your look with solid flat colour layers that build crisp separation. Soften the perimeter with blurred edges. Then provide a single structural contrast through subtle weaves that reveal their complexity only upon close inspection.",
      "sectionIntro": "Demand structural integrity from every print before you bring it near your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the field test (settle into a natural texture like ground seen from a hill)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Subject a {recommended_pattern_1} shirt to a harsh optical check. Hang the silk garment on a door, step ten paces back, and squint. The print must dissolve into a natural texture. It must read as an organic surface shift rather than a deliberate drawing. If the motif remains sharp or reads clearly from across the room, it fails. You require blurred edges to ground your cool palette. A harsh graphic destroys the intended visual weight. Take the piece down and return it to the rack.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this visual stress test to evaluate any pattern before you purchase it.",
      "tests": [
        "the field test (settle into a natural texture like ground seen from a hill)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_gemini__moon_scorpio__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "crisp separation + quiet undercurrent + one clever contrast",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on crisp separation + quiet undercurrent + one clever contrast.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Touch the garment first. You are looking for a cool, dry handfeel and a matt finish that absorbs light rather than reflecting it. Your guiding logic is crisp separation + quiet undercurrent + one clever contrast. Picture a rigid, sharply collared shirt layered over a seamless, fine-gauge knit, tucked into heavyweight pleated trousers, and grounded by a heavy, square-toed shoe. The garments must sit apart from each other, distinct and defined. Build your collection slowly. Wait for the exact piece that fits the structure. Do not buy temporary substitutes.\n\nApply the host test. Put the clothes on and move around. Ask yourself if the outfit makes you feel like the person who holds the keys to the building, reaching up to unlock a heavy door without hesitation, rather than a visitor terrified of creasing their cuffs. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Your wardrobe must serve you silently. If a collar shifts out of place or a waistband pinches when you sit, take it off. Leave it in the shop.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation, the absolute baseline for how your garments must interact.",
      "tests": [
        "the host test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe entirely on physical reliability. Seek out materials that create crisp separation between your layers. Select {texture_good_3} for tailored coats that hold a sharp, cool edge through years of wear. Balance this structure with a quiet undercurrent of {texture_good_4} for blouses that move cleanly against your skin. When inspecting knitwear, squeeze the sleeve. Demand {texture_good_1} that compresses and rebounds instantly. Ground the system with {texture_good_2} for bags and belts that mould to your grip. Apply one strict physical rule to everything you touch. If a material pushes back against your hand or produces a hollow squeak between your thumb and forefinger, leave it on the rail. Secure one clever contrast by mixing these dense and fluid materials. Let the physical response of the fabric guide your final decision.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the textures that serve your framework before you ever look at a label.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
