      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Subject your {recommended_pattern_1} to the hearth test. Take the garment into a room lit solely by a warm, low-wattage lamp and step back ten paces. Because your palette runs entirely cool, the yellow artificial light will instantly expose poor dyes and chaotic prints. The pattern must not turn muddy. Watch how it behaves as you move away. It should blur evenly and form one quiet undercurrent. If the design scrambles into a confused mess, put the piece back. You require crisp separation. The lines must hold their structural integrity in the shadows, adding visual depth without breaking the muted surface of the cloth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the hearth test to evaluate pattern legibility under difficult lighting conditions.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_gemini__moon_taurus__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "crisp separation + sensory comfort + one clever contrast",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on crisp separation + sensory comfort + one clever contrast.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your physical instinct here is the slide and snap of getting dressed. Pay attention to how garments pull over your shoulders and settle on your frame. If a piece requires constant adjustment, reject it. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Your governing logic is crisp separation + sensory comfort + one clever contrast. Picture a stiff cotton poplin shirt layered over a fluid silk camisole, worn with heavily washed denim and mixed silver and gold hardware. The structure holds the line. The silk provides the comfort. The mixed metals deliver the contrast. Keep your palette cool.\n\nBuild your wardrobe methodically, then deploy fast according to the day's demands. Apply the combination test before acquiring anything new. Hang the prospective garment against three radically different items you already own. If it fights the established geometry or demands entirely new underpinnings, put it back. You need pieces that adapt when your environment shifts. Seek balanced proportions that neither restrict movement nor drown your frame. Maintain a mixed finish across your accessories. Pair heavily polished leather with a matt suede jacket. This friction keeps the entire system functional and sharp.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation, the governing logic you will use to evaluate every piece of clothing you touch.",
      "tests": [
        "the combination test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your foundation on fabrics that guarantee crisp separation and sensory comfort. Start with {texture_good_1} for shirting that holds clean architectural boundaries. For base layers sitting close to the skin, {texture_good_2} gives you sharp lines and easy movement. Rely on {texture_good_3} for trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day. Top this with {texture_good_4} to create mobile outerwear that blocks the wind but weighs very little. Always apply the snap test before you buy. Pinch a section of the material, pull it taut across your thumbs, and let it go. If it snaps back instantly to its original shape, it will hold a reliable line. If it slumps or warps, leave it on the rack. Look for these specific materials.",
      "sectionIntro": "Trust your hands to find the materials that do the work for you.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Some materials betray you the moment they reach your hand. Pick up {texture_bad_1} and squeeze it tightly in your fist. If it crushes into dead wrinkles rather than holding its structure, drop it. Evaluate {texture_bad_2} by stretching the hem between your thumbs before letting go. If the fabric sags instead of springing sharply back into place, it fails. You require one clever contrast to anchor your outfits. You cannot build that tension with {texture_bad_3} that clings limply to your collarbone. Rely on the density in your grip. Visuals deceive, but a garment's heft tells the truth. When a material feels thin, sticky, or lifeless under your fingers, leave it on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to spot a failing fabric with your hands before you even take it to the fitting room.",
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your sweet spot hinges on crisp separation. Pair {sweet_spot_keyword_1} directly against {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to establish distinct boundaries. The friction between these surfaces dictates your choices. Assess a {texture_good_1} garment by checking its density. It must feel substantial across your shoulders. If the weave feels flimsy or hollow, leave it on the rail. You require rigid, matt threads placed next to smooth, cool fibres. Trust your hands. Photographs conceal poor construction, but true density reveals it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the exact intersection where opposing surfaces meet and hold their ground.",
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Keep your overall colour temperature entirely cool. Construct your daily foundation using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} in fine ribbed merino for absolute sensory comfort. Trust {core_colour_4} to provide structural dark lines in worsted wool trousers or a technical nylon jacket. Use {core_colour_3} as your essential light substitute. Treat the relief tone purely as a soft note used sparingly to interrupt solid blocks of dark clothing. Deploy {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as your single deliberate accent. Pass over Mustard, Rust, and Warm olive green without hesitation. Beware the flat monochrome trap that leaves an outfit feeling completely lifeless by midday. Fix this dullness immediately. Expose a stiff cotton poplin collar, slide on a polished architectural ring, or step into a vibrant geometric sneaker.",
