      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close evening settings, crisp separation takes the lead. Layer a technical nylon overshirt over icy grey worsted wool trousers. The slick synthetic surface defines a sharp boundary beside the dry wool. An unplanned dinner detour does not require surrendering your tailored dark silhouette. Rely on mixed metals to catch sparse light. Pair a polished silver pendant with a matt titanium ring. Weigh the cool hardware in your palm before dressing. Let your hands verify the density of the metal. Shadows conceal poor materials, but gravity exposes hollow pieces. Trust your grip to select heavy steel over frail zinc.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your intimate evening settings by relying on physical texture and metal weight when visibility drops.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Build your morning routine around crisp separation + sensory comfort + one clever contrast. A casual trip to the post office does not grant you permission to abandon your proportions. Treat a quick local errand exactly as you would a scheduled appointment. Keep your palette cool. Pull on stark navy trousers cut from heavy gabardine, then add an icy grey cashmere crewneck. Trust your own physical instincts when selecting these garments. Reflections lie, but a fabric's drape remains absolute. Mix your metals freely. Wear a high-shine silver ring alongside a matt brass watch. Anchor the base with thick leather loafers.",
      "sectionIntro": "Set your daily baseline and refuse to drop below it.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "You have the freedom to mix your metals across your wardrobe. Combine {metal_1} rings with a {metal_2} watch and {metal_3} zips. Your only rule is to maintain a cool temperature overall. Avoid antiqued, hammered, or artificially oxidised pieces. These aged details read as historical debris against a present-tense style. Rely instead on bright silver, polished platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome. This high-shine approach ensures crisp separation between your hardware and your garments. Pick up a chain or a buckle before you buy it. Feel the raw mass in your fingers to verify its true quality. Trust your hands to find the heavy, solid components that provide lasting sensory comfort. Skip any {excluded_finish} items that feel hollow or lightweight.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your hardware with your hands to anchor your clothing without adding visual clutter.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Apply the same uncompromising standards to your gems as you do to your metals. Gravity remains absolute. You require heavy, dense minerals that settle into place and provide immediate sensory comfort. Keep your stone selections highly polished and pristine to reflect a cool light. Avoid opaque surfaces that introduce messy visual clutter against your clean lines. Select {stone_1} or {stone_2} cut with geometric precision. You want sharp, distinct facets that establish crisp separation from their setting. A matt finish or a cloudy gem will drag the composition down. Select clear, light-refracting gems that sit firmly against the skin.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones by their density and how sharply they refract light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Assess every clasp, zip, and ring before integrating it into your wardrobe. Trust your hands to detect hollow casting or weak alloys, dropping anything that feels insubstantial. Poorly forged elements destroy your crisp separation. Keep to polished white gold, cool silver, mirror chrome, or {metal_1}. You can mix these distinct finishes freely across your fingers and wrists. These precise choices maintain a clean geometric edge and guarantee reliable sensory comfort.",
      "sectionIntro": "Lift the hardware and test its physical density before you evaluate the design.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories provide the vital one clever contrast. You have built a foundation of crisp separation. You have locked in the required sensory comfort. Now, select one or two strong pieces per look to finish the task. Begin with silk scarves, specifically a matt crepe de chine square in a cool tone like stark navy or icy grey. Apply the coil test before buying. Twist the fabric tightly from corner to corner. If the material binds into a rigid rope, drop it. A correct weave remains pliable under tension and recovers its fluid drape immediately. Rely on your tactile reaction to find the exact truth of the garment.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is how you finish the formula with absolute intention, using your hands to select the final layer.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Curate your fine jewellery to establish crisp separation between individual pieces. Mix thin gold chains with cool silver rings. Combine polished elements with brushed finishes so the metals never blur into a single heavy mass. Subject every piece to the rotation test. Spin a metal band around your finger or turn a bracelet on your wrist. If the item catches, drags, or dictates how you move, take it off immediately. You require pure sensory comfort. Rely entirely on how the metal behaves in motion.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware using strict physical boundaries.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin mixed gold and silver, mixed polished and brushed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Secure your essentials in a small structured bag. Pick up a matt kid suede or smooth leather top-handle piece. Check the clasps and zips. Fine mixed hardware easily bridges your cool icy grey and stark navy garments. Ensure the firm shape sits cleanly at your side to preserve crisp separation. Before purchasing, verify its balance in motion. Turn your body fully. If the bag swings wildly away from your hip and compromises your sensory comfort, put it down. Only carry items that respect your physical boundaries.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your accessories by selecting a functional container and subjecting the entire combination to a physical stress test.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede or smooth leather top-handle, fine mixed hardware"
        }
