    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Your tailored pieces take their patterns from structure. Look for a {recommended_pattern_1} woven directly into the cloth. Your fluid pieces take their patterns from movement, shifting towards a {recommended_pattern_2} that flows with the drape of the garment. Because your style adapts to the environment, you must adjust your contrast levels to match the piece. A structured jacket handles high-contrast geometry. A soft base layer requires subtle, tonal variations that preserve your sensory comfort. Always ensure the underlying ground remains cool. Avoid {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. Pass over anything that relies on busy novelty instead of crisp separation. Step back ten feet and blink. If the print turns muddy or confusing in that first split second, leave the piece on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as a dial you turn up or down to calibrate the specific function of a garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
