      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Scrutinise the friction of any new cloth. Rub the material tightly between both palms. If it squeaks, grips, or feels hollow, leave it on the rack. Avoid {texture_bad_1}. It generates static and clings awkwardly. Steer clear of {texture_bad_2}. This material catches the light cheaply and shatters your dark drama. Reject {texture_bad_3} entirely. It feels rigid across the shoulders and refuses to bend. Look for materials that adapt as you move through a crowd and keep you warm without trapping sweat.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to identify and reject the materials that fail you.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your baseline dark drama relies on a warm friction generated by {sweet_spot_keyword_1} paired with {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Evaluate every new item for resilience. Squeeze the cloth tight, pull it hard, and release. A polished finish demands memory. If the weave sags or stays crushed, leave it on the rail. You require a structured surface like {texture_good_1} that snaps back to a sharp line. This reliable physical tension adapts to any setting while grounding your steady presence within your group.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the precise physical tension required to hold your shape.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your colour palette operates on a strictly warm baseline. Build the heavy garments of your dark drama using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Deploy {core_colour_3} as your substitute for stark white. Use {core_colour_4} as your bridge neutral to link distinct items without losing heat. For deliberate accents, rely exclusively on {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2}. Treat your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly to break up dense blocks of shade. Pass over pale pastels, neon brights, and flat greys. Leave them on the rack. Watch out for the trap of the extreme pivot, wearing all floaty gauze one month and all crisp utility the next. Re-weave instead. Keep one item from the opposing end of the spectrum in every outfit, ensuring your mobile layers interlock.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your palette by treating colour as a structural tool, evaluating every garment strictly by its designated role.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Warm taupe",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
