          "failure": "the seesaw: one month all floaty gauze, the next all crisp utility",
          "fix": "re-weave instead: keep one item from the other hand in every outfit, always"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, dark drama sets the terms. Ground the outfit in warm taupe worsted wool trousers. The supporting components provide movement and light. Throw a camel fine ribbed merino knit over your shoulders and secure a bright gold cuff at the wrist. Treat every environment with identical rigour. The standard you set for a Monday board review applies directly to a brief outing for office supplies. Let the dense hang of your garments dictate your choices, relying on physical substance to maintain a polished finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Structure your clothing choices for the working week.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dimly lit rooms, dark drama leads. Close quarters amplify every choice you make. Trust your hands over your eyes. Dim lighting conceals poor construction, but touch reveals the true quality of a material. Run your fingers over fine ribbed merino. If the fabric feels stiff or thin, discard it. Maintain your high standards across all after-hours contexts, wearing the same crisp cotton poplin to a casual neighbourhood supper as you would to a formal evening gathering. Let deep camel and warm taupe absorb the ambient room light. Add a single brass pendant or a warm gold cuff to catch the shadows. Avoid shiny synthetics that reflect a harsh glare.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your fabric choices for close quarters and low lighting.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Routine errands require the same structured worsted wool trousers you would wear to a critical meeting. Do not drop your standard for a mundane task. Look at your reflection before crossing the threshold. You must always construct your outfit using dark drama + mobile layers + one molten flash. When you pull a warm taupe technical nylon shell over a heavy camel knit, finish it with a solid brass pendant. Check the fabric density in your palms. If the cloth feels weak, leave it on the hanger. Maintain strict structural integrity whether you are shaking hands with a client or navigating a crowded high street.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your highest standard of construction to your most ordinary routines.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your metal strategy operates on two distinct levels. For personal jewellery resting directly against the skin, build a warm foundation using {personal_metal_1} and {personal_metal_2}. Let these metals provide a sharp contrast against your dark drama. For structural elements like zips, belt buckles, and bag clasps, specify {structural_metal_1} and {structural_metal_2}. Always test hardware before purchasing by feeling the item in your palm. Heavy, solid cast components physically ground your mobile layers. Avoid hammered surfaces and artificially aged metals, as they register as visual clutter rather than architectural detail. Keep your hardware strictly polished, rejecting any {excluded_finish} coatings that dull the impact.",
      "sectionIntro": "Understand your hardware as a two-tier system, separating skin-level adornment from the functional architecture of your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Require dense, light-catching minerals to anchor the dark drama of your garments. Look for high-clarity {stone_1} and warm {stone_2}. Choose stones that sit smoothly against mobile layers. Avoid antiqued hardware, hammered surfaces, and artificially aged settings. They read as pure clutter against your precise garments. Frame your stones strictly in perfectly unmarred, highly reflective polished mountings. Judge the piece by holding it in your bare hand. Trust your tactile instincts to detect authentic density, relying on concentrated gravity to confirm its worth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select stones that ground your adaptive wardrobe through sheer density and uncompromising clarity.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Pick the item up and assess the drag against your palm. Let physical mass confirm true density. Rely on this solid weight to ground your wardrobe. Skip weathered brass and pitted copper. Distressed textures register as visual clutter against your adaptable garments. Keep strictly to sleek silver, pristine white gold, and mirror chrome. Let a highly reflective {metal_1} detail anchor the dark drama within a warm palette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Lift every piece of hardware before it touches your body.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "We establish outfits through dark drama and mobile layers. Accessories supply the final equation variable, providing the one molten flash. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. This restraint forces you to select items with actual density. Trust your physical instincts completely. Start building this habit with eyewear. Seek out a thick acetate frame with a highly polished surface. Hold the frames in your palms before wearing them. A solid acetate chassis feels heavy and warm against the skin. Scrutinise your silhouette right before crossing the threshold. Stand before a mirror and check the integration. If an accessory tangles in your fabric or competes with the garment, leave it behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Accessories calibrate your final visual output, dictating exactly where the eye lands.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "acetate frame, polished"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Select a smooth leather crossbody bag to ground the silhouette. Pick it up and feel its physical density. Look for clean shapes that sit flush against the body without snagging your fluid mobile layers. Check the hardware closely. Ensure the zips bear a highly reflective, polished surface in either gold or silver. Review your final outfit in the mirror before stepping outside. If the strap interrupts the drape of your worsted wool or fights the deep, warm tones creating dark drama, take the piece off immediately. The bag must integrate perfectly into the clothing, rather than carving it up.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the same rigorous standards to how you carry your physical cargo.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather crossbody, polished zips"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Ground the dark drama in a warm taupe or camel smooth leather flat. Look for an unbroken surface and a clean gloss. Avoid heavy lugs or thick suede. Pick up the shoe and check the hardware. Match any buckles to your dual register metals by mixing warm brass with bright steel. Evaluate the entire look before leaving the house. Check that your mobile layers fall freely over the instep. If a heavy buckle or extra element catches the eye before the overall silhouette does, take it off.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor the foundation of your outfit and verify the final balance before you leave.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather flat, clean gloss"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Your versatile approach demands an adaptive rule for pattern contrast. Keep contrast low and tonal for structured settings, then sharpen into distinct graphics when the context shifts. Draw tailored worsted wool from precise geometry. Fluid merino must take its visual cues from organic movement. Use {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} to construct mobile layers that retain dark drama. Always anchor these patterns in a warm base colour. Evaluate the contrast from three paces away before acquiring any piece. From this distance, the fabric must project a calm, uniform matt surface. Up close, the weave must reward the eye with complex detail. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1}, printed logos, and frayed edges.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as a structural tool rather than a surface decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Test the visual field of any {recommended_pattern_1}. Hang the garment across the room. At this distance, the design must dissolve into a solid, even block of warm colour. If the print disrupts the space, leave it on the rail. Walk closer and pick the fabric up. Now, the intricate geometry should reveal itself, offering a rewarding weave only to those standing right beside you. This optical shift allows the piece to support fluid mobile layers without overwhelming them. Patterns that read as quiet textures from afar preserve the sweeping dark drama of your silhouette. Depend on proximity to check the truth of the textile.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the physical distance required to evaluate a print.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_leo__moon_aries__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "dark drama + sharp edges + one molten flash",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on dark drama + sharp edges + one molten flash.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your hands to recognise structural resistance and high-polish surfaces. Pick up a garment and feel for a dense, unyielding weight that holds its own shape. Look for fabrics that carry a warm temperature without losing their rigid architecture. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Build your wardrobe with deliberate precision. Deploy your outfits fast. Ignore soft, yielding weaves. You need armour that reflects light.\n\nYour core style formula is dark drama + sharp edges + one molten flash. Picture a heavy, ankle-sweeping coat cut with absolute geometric precision worn over a severe, structured shirt, finished with a single, massive, polished cuff on your bare wrist. Apply the radius test. Put the garment on and measure the physical boundary it enforces. If the piece invites strangers to close the distance or softens your perimeter, leave it on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your architectural foundation, the strictly policed rules of engagement you must master before acquiring a single new garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the radius test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "To execute dark drama and sharp edges, you need materials that hold architectural tension. Seek out {texture_good_1} for sharp shirting that holds a crease and snaps visually against the collarbone. Anchor your silhouette with {texture_good_2} for knife-edge tailoring that never begs for a steamer. Introduce your one molten flash through {texture_good_3} for statement footwear and accessories that reflect maximum light. Underneath it all, deploy {texture_good_4} for slip dresses and linings that gleam with a warm polish under low light. Apply the bounce test before buying anything. Crush the garment in your fist and let go. The cloth must spring back instantly, refusing to collapse. Rely on this tactile confirmation. Verify the density before committing. Hunt for these core materials.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the specific textiles that construct your foundation.",
