    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Look for stones that radiate a warm depth rather than bouncing a hard glare. Anchor your aesthetic with {stone_1} and {stone_2} for their quiet grandeur. Keep them substantial. Weigh every piece in your palm before it touches your body. Highly polished, mirror-finish elements will cut harshly across your {core_colour_1} garments. Protect that carefully built softness by insisting on matt and brushed settings. Let {stone_3} sit deep in its mounting to maintain a cohesive surface.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones and settings by testing their physical density and observing their surface finish.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift every prospective piece to test its density. A solid {metal_1} buckle should drop heavily into your palm. Highly reflective, icy finishes clash against the warm {core_colour_1} garments in your wardrobe. Mirror finishes pull focus and destroy the quiet grandeur you are building. Correct this error by demanding dimmed matt or deeply brushed treatments for all your hardware. These clouded surfaces recede into the fabric and preserve the structural softness of the complete outfit.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every piece of hardware to a strict physical evaluation before you buy it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories provide the required one molten flash. They structure pure quiet grandeur and strike a heavy line against your surrounding softness. Limit your choices to one or two strong pieces per look. Apply the one-ember test to every metal addition. Search for a singular, warm point of heat buried in the ash, rather than a scattering of bright sparks. Handbags act as your primary vehicle here. Demand thick full-grain leather construction. The skin must carry a dense, matt body with one polished flash from a solid brass lock or buckle. Trust your grip when handling these items. True mass gives an absolute, undeniable answer.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every accessory by its physical weight and undeniable heat.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, matt body with one polished flash"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Assess your scarves carefully. Seek out silk with a strictly matt finish. Reject any textile that bounces sharp light back at the mirror. Evaluate the drape entirely by touch. Hold the textile against a neutral backdrop and inspect the weave closely. Look for a single, glowing thread of warm camel or toasted copper buried within the material. If the fabric lacks that solitary spark of heat, drop it immediately. Cultivating this hidden temperature establishes quiet grandeur.",
      "sectionIntro": "Curate your neckwear to anchor your warmth.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select keepsake jewellery that anchors your silhouette. Seek out aged brass pieces carrying a molten gold accent. Mix these warm finishes freely. Rub the metal between your thumb and index finger. It must feel substantial and warm against the skin. This tactile grounding builds quiet grandeur. Before stepping outside, scan your outfit for competing focal points. You need exactly one glowing ember against the softness of your camel layers. If a second high-shine ring or bright pendant fights the primary glow, take it off. Leave just a single focal point burning.",
      "sectionIntro": "Mastering your final accessories requires strict editing and a total reliance on touch.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged brass with a molten gold accent, mixed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Build your pattern strategy on a strict division between structure and drape. Tailored garments draw their markings entirely from the yarn. Look for woven {recommended_pattern_1} to provide quiet grandeur without visual noise. Fluid pieces carry subtle dyed motifs like {recommended_pattern_2}. Keep all pattern contrast strictly low and tonal to maintain the essential softness of your silhouette. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1}, {avoid_pattern_2}, and any stark backgrounds. Always subject a print to the firelight test. Hold the cloth near a glowing bulb. If the lines jump or sharpen under the warm illumination, leave the item on the rail. The right motif must deepen and blur by lamplight.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your eye to reject loud graphics and seek subtle structural complexity.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate every {recommended_pattern_1} in an unlit room. Drape the silk or cashmere across a chair and switch on a single warm lamp. Step back and look. The print must deepen into the shadows. If the motif melts into absolute softness, keep it. If the lines turn sharp or chalky under dim lighting, return the piece to the rack. Your aesthetic requires quiet grandeur. A pattern only succeeds if it smoulders like hot coals when the room darkens. Bright shop lighting bleaches dye. Shadows reveal the true depth of the fabric.",
      "sectionIntro": "Run every pattern through this strict lighting filter before you commit.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_leo__moon_gemini__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "dark drama + light movement + one molten flash",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on dark drama + light movement + one molten flash.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. When evaluating a heavy overcoat, pick it up and feel the drape. Seek versatile pieces that feel warm to the touch and adapt easily to your frame. Build your wardrobe slowly over seasons. Collect garments that shift across contexts. When you dress, deploy fast based on the crowd you are meeting today. Your clothes must foster connection. Check the physical transitions between your garments.\n\nKeep the overall finish polished. Your core formula is dark drama + light movement + one molten flash. Picture a heavy wool trench coat worn open over a bias-cut silk slip, finished with a single liquid chain at the collarbone. The elements must serve the collective whole. Apply the combination test before you leave the house. Put every piece on together and pay attention to friction. A dense sleeve must glide over a fluid cuff without catching. If the outfit feels disjointed or stiff, change the underlying layer. Trust your hands to locate the problem.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this blueprint as your foundational operating system.",
      "tests": [
        "the combination test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe from fabrics that support light movement and maintain a polished surface. Start with {texture_good_1} for shirting with clean architectural boundaries. Layer this over {texture_good_2} for close-to-body base layers that hold a sharp line. For trousers, demand {texture_good_3} to ensure a clean drape that resists creasing through long days. Finish with {texture_good_4} for mobile outerwear that blocks wind and anchors the dark drama of your silhouette. Apply the snap test before you purchase anything. Pull the fabric taut and let it go. If it snaps back into shape instantly, it will hold the warm hues of your palette. If it crumples or slumps, leave it on the hanger. Seek out these specific materials.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the materials that build your foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "You require fabrics that support dark drama and anchor one molten flash. Flimsy textiles undermine your system. Pick up {texture_bad_1} and pinch the hem. If the fibres compress into a spongy mass between your fingers, drop it. Test {texture_bad_2} by crushing a handful of the material. If it collapses silently rather than springing back to life, it lacks the required tension. Avoid {texture_bad_3} completely. It might look warm on the hanger, but it sits flat and lifeless against the skin. Reject textiles that fail to offer structural resistance.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject weak materials instantly before you ever try them on.",
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your exact equilibrium relies on tension. Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to anchor your silhouette. Layer {texture_good_1} over this foundation to ground the dark drama of your core formula. Assess every new piece before you commit. Stretch the cuff firmly between your thumbs. The weave must spring closed immediately upon release. If the yarn stretches out and loses its shape, leave it on the rail. This strict recoil creates the structure you need. Balance that firm memory with lighter garments that generate light movement as you step. A warm metallic button adds a polished anchor. Rely on physical sensation as your definitive guide. Mirrors deceive you. Density reveals the truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your materials manually to ensure they hold their tension.",
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette runs strictly warm. Ground your uniform in {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} to secure dark drama in your foundation. Rely on {core_colour_3} as a sharp white substitute, and use {core_colour_4} to bridge your high and low contrast garments. Apply {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} strictly as deliberate, singular interruptions. Treat your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly, perhaps hidden inside a jacket lining or flashed on a technical nylon strap. Bypass icy pastel, neon brights, and cold blue-grey entirely. They wash out your edges. Watch out for the visual fatigue of dressing entirely in one flat block of colour. A static hue will drain your focus before lunch. Interrupt a lifeless outfit immediately. Wedge a rigid cotton poplin collar against your neck, slide a heavy structural silver ring onto your hand, or lace up a vivid geometric sneaker. Trust your tactile reaction. If a tonal combination feels thin against your skin, swap the base layer.",
      "sectionIntro": "Deploy your colours as precision tools with strict jobs, refusing any shade that blurs your boundaries.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Warm taupe",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft cream",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
