          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Pale clay",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "a flat monochrome look that bores you by midday",
          "fix": "add a crisp white poplin collar, a silver architectural ring, or a bright geometric sneaker"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Ground your work attire in dark drama. A worsted wool blazer establishes a firm, reliable boundary. Let light movement support this structured anchor. A crisp cotton poplin shirt or a fine ribbed merino knit in warm taupe introduces an approachable, warm layer. Finish the composition with one molten flash. A polished silver watch worn alongside a gold collar bar delivers a deliberate finish. Assess every item before dressing. An early morning commute deserves the exact same tactile standard you require at your desk. Trust your hands to check the drape. Avoid rigid seams that bite into your shoulders. Look for a smooth camel knit or pliant textiles that yield to your routine. If a collar pinches, leave it behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assemble your working layers by trusting the weight and drape of your materials.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "Let dark drama lead when the lights drop. In close quarters, shift your focus from rigid construction to yielding surface texture. Choose soft brushed cashmere or pliant silk blends to adapt to ambient heat. Avoid stiff layers that box in your chest. A late dinner requires the same physical comfort as lounging at home. Mix a thin gold chain with a heavier silver cuff to catch dim light near your face. Give your garments a strict physical check. Run your thumb inside the collar. If the seam digs into your neck when you lean forward, discard the piece immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat low lighting and intimate proximity as a specific technical environment.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A wet Sunday walk for the papers demands a highly polished baseline. Treat a quick trip to the pharmacy as a live test of your discipline. Do not degrade your choices just because the errand is brief. Trust the physical certainty of the garments. If a warm technical nylon jacket feels flimsy in your grip, drop it. Reach instead for trousers in worsted wool and pair them with a crisp cotton shirt. Your standard remains constant across every mundane environment. You must anchor every outfit with dark drama + light movement + one molten flash. Finish the casual look with a heavy camel coat and a polished bronze ring.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat mundane routines as the strict proving ground for your discipline.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Separate the metal you wear against your skin from the hardware holding a garment together. Your personal metals are {personal_metal_1} and {personal_metal_2}. Use these for rings, watches, and chains. For structural elements like zips, shoe buckles, and bag clasps, choose {structural_metal_1} or {structural_metal_2}. This dual approach builds a warm palette without forcing every rivet to match. Avoid hammered textures and artificially aged pieces entirely. Such antiqued finishes create visual clutter. Stick strictly to polished surfaces and steer clear of {excluded_finish}. To test any piece of jewellery or a heavy zip, hold it flat in your palm and gauge the heft. Appearance deceives the eye. Pure mass reveals the truth. A dense, high-shine clasp anchors the dark drama in a heavy coat and accentuates the light movement at your cuff.",
      "sectionIntro": "Divide your hardware into two functional categories to establish control.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Use {stone_1} as your foundation for structural clarity. It catches ambient light with an open, accessible edge. Introduce {stone_2} or {stone_3} when you require deep density. This solid core creates dark drama, anchoring the piece without closing off your silhouette. Avoid raw crystals and unpolished geodes. These add unnecessary organic noise. Confine your gemstone choices to a high-shine, expertly faceted finish across both your metallic registers, always maintaining a warm baseline. Lift the setting with your open palm. Surface reflections deceive the eye, but dense minerals are honest. Trust your hands to verify the stone's true weight.",
      "sectionIntro": "Your stones and metals must function as structural anchors, grounded in physical reality rather than visual tricks.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Judge your accessories blindly. Close your eyes and let the metal rest in your hand. Gravity tells the truth. Keep your selections strictly polished to avoid diluting your impact. A heavy, mirror-finish {metal_1} cuff or a solid ring set with {stone_1} reflects a warm gleam that slices cleanly through dense textiles. This high-shine hardware provides the precise contrast needed to balance dark drama. Reject hollow chains immediately. Demand undeniable physical density from every item of jewellery you own.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess every piece of hardware by its sheer physical mass.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments establish dark drama. They incorporate light movement. Accessories deliver your one molten flash. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with eyewear. Seek a polished acetate frame. Let tactile instinct guide your selection. Pick up the frames and apply the rotation test. Spin them slowly between your thumb and forefinger. If the weight drops unevenly or the hinges rattle mid-turn, discard them. You need solid density that assumes a warm temperature against your temples.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your final additions with ruthless physical precision.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "acetate frame, polished"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Select bags for strict utility. Pick up a smooth leather crossbody in a warm camel. Run your thumb over the polished zips. They must glide without catching. Put the strap over your shoulder and execute a swift motion check. Slide the bag from your hip to your chest. Focus on resistance rather than appearance. If the leather grips your garments and restricts your stride, drop the piece. You need uninterrupted light movement across your torso. Let the mixed metal hardware supply a molten flash against your coat. Ground the shape with dark drama, choosing rigid silhouettes that refuse to slouch. The surface finish must remain gleaming and slick, never matt.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject your functional accessories to strict physical trials.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather crossbody, polished zips"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Ground dark drama with a smooth leather flat. Seek a clean gloss finish that catches the overhead lighting and pairs exactly with a warm camel trouser. Pick the shoe up and check the structure. The leather must remain rigid under your grip. Allow light movement above the ankle, but keep the foot precise. A simple dual-metal buckle across the vamp delivers a molten flash without overwhelming the silhouette. Before leaving, perform a walking evaluation. Flex your foot and inspect the toe block from above. If the profile warps under your weight or the gloss yields to a matt crease, take the pair off.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your footwear by testing its structural integrity and surface finish.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather flat, clean gloss"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Keep your pattern contrast adaptive. Tailored garments take their pattern from subtle, woven structures like {recommended_pattern_1}. Fluid pieces demand the sharp lines of {recommended_pattern_2} to project light movement. Evaluate the contrast from a distance. The design must register sharply without requiring careful study. Trust this immediate visual reflex. If the shapes bleed together into a muddy wash, drop the hanger. Pass over chaotic prints, faded borders, and {avoid_pattern_1}. Inject dark drama through absolute precision. A warm palette relies on this strict exactness to maintain a polished finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your motifs by testing their visual limits.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Prop the garment against a wall and step back ten paces. Close your eyes, then open them for a single split second. A successful {recommended_pattern_1} retains its exact geometry. It does not blur into a hazy gradient. You require clean separation between the graphic elements. If the boundaries dissolve in that first glance, leave the piece on the rail. Your style relies on light movement to function. A murky print weighs down that aesthetic and destroys the intended effect. Demand crisp, deliberate contrast. Trust your immediate visual instinct. If you have to squint at the fabric to decipher the shapes, the pattern fails.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use the ten-foot blink test to evaluate every printed fabric before you commit.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_leo__moon_leo__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "dark drama + athletic space + one molten flash",
    "closing": "Trust your physical instincts to secure the ultimate alignment of dark drama + athletic space + one molten flash.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your physical instinct is heat and friction. Trust the sensation of heavy, high-gloss surfaces warming against your skin and dense technical fabrics holding their shape. Your absolute blueprint is dark drama + athletic space + one molten flash. Picture this. You pull on a heavyweight technical mesh base layer that grants absolute mobility. You layer a structured, sweeping, severe overcoat on top. You finish the look with a single, highly reflective, heavy cuff at the wrist. The contrast between severe structure and high-performance mobility is your baseline.\n\nBuild your wardrobe slowly. Take months to hunt down the exact weight and cut of a garment. Once you own the right pieces, deploy fast. Throw them together in seconds on the day. Before leaving the house, run the entrance test. Stop and check your physical readiness at the threshold. If the silhouette prevents you from breaking into an immediate sprint, or if the metallic element lacks a blinding, polished glare, take the piece off. Your clothing must provide sharp architectural boundaries and absolute physical freedom simultaneously. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight and mobility do not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat this core blueprint as your foundational law for building a wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the entrance test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe requires materials that construct athletic space around the body while delivering a polished finish. Trust your hands to seek out density and shine. Run the shadow test. Hold a fabric under a direct overhead bulb and check the depth of the folds. If the shadows look flat or dusty, drop the garment. You need deep, saturated contrast to anchor your dark drama. Reach for {texture_good_1} to build sharp shirting that holds a crisp crease. Select {texture_good_2} for knife-edge tailoring that stays rigid and never begs for a steamer. To introduce that vital one molten flash, rely on {texture_good_3} for statement footwear that bounces maximum warm light. Finally, lay {texture_good_4} against the skin for slip dresses and linings that gleam aggressively under low ambient light. Work strictly from this roster.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to identify fabrics that hold a hard edge and bounce light back.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "sharp shirting that holds a crease and snaps visually"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sharp wool twill",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "knife-edge tailoring that never begs for a steamer"
