    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let dark drama dictate your work choices. Construct the bulk of the silhouette using sharp wool twill dyed in deep bronze. A chaotic dash for the morning train gives you no excuse to abandon proportion. Support this heavy anchor with slick fabrics that slide cleanly against the body. Crisp cotton poplin provides a fast layer under wool tailoring. Deliver one molten flash through a single strike of polished warm metal at the wrist. Avoid matt surfaces entirely. Let tactile response dictate your purchases. If a textile feels sluggish against your fingers, reject it. Your garments must actively accelerate your pace.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your work attire around strict visual regulation and physical speed.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In low lighting, dark drama takes the lead. Test a heavy silk satin shirt under a dim bulb. Rub the fabric between your thumb and forefinger. If it crumples into soft folds, drop it. A quiet midnight drink does not mean abandoning proportion. Keep your silhouette balanced. Grasp the collar of a crisp cotton poplin shirt. It must stand rigid against your neck. Bring deep bronze up to your face and let warm gold jewellery rest against your collarbone. Rely on the fast cut of a sharp wool twill trouser to carve a stark profile through the shadows.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the rules for close quarters and low lighting.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat a trip to the petrol station with strict discipline. A Saturday market morning gives no reason to soften your lines. Demand garments that hold their shape. Experience the slick drape of heavy silk satin on bare skin. The cloth must feel substantial. Do not dilute the visual impact. Your baseline remains dark drama + fast movement + one molten flash. Keep every cut balanced. Pair a golden camel coat with rigid black denim. Add a warm brass collar. Assess a new material by twisting a hem between your hands. If it retains sharp creases, leave it behind. Finish with patent leather boots. Store mirrors flatter, but the physical drape of a garment never deceives.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish your standard for ordinary days, enforcing the same strictness for a mundane errand as you would for an evening event.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Commit to a warm hardware strategy. Limit your selections to {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Weigh the piece in your palm. Heavy, dense hardware acts as the necessary anchor for dark drama. Flimsy chains fail instantly. Reject items that look exhausted. Oxidised, hammered, or antiqued textures drain vitality. Stay strictly in polished {metal_1} that catches light from the opposite pavement to deliver one molten flash. A {excluded_finish} surface belongs elsewhere. Keep your structural elements bright and severe.",
      "sectionIntro": "Implement a strict hardware protocol to anchor your silhouette.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "To sustain dark drama, you require gems that project light fiercely rather than absorbing it. Look for the blinding clarity of {stone_1} or the saturated heat of {stone_2}. Before putting any piece on, gauge its density. A proper piece of jewellery feels like a solid lead weight in your hand. Avoid cloudy inclusions or rough-cut stones completely. These irregular finishes absorb ambient glow and stall your visual momentum. Instead, insist on high-gloss, faceted stones mounted in warm settings that shoot brilliant reflections straight back at the observer.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware by testing its raw physical density and its capacity to project light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Pick up every piece of {metal_1} before bringing it to the till. A heavy chain or solid cuff anchors the fast movement in your silhouette. Discard any item that feels hollow or insubstantial. Stay entirely away from brushed or matt finishes. These dull treatments drag the aesthetic down and blunt your edge. Insist on a strictly polished, high-shine surface instead. Your warm metal must reflect light like a hard mirror, delivering exactly one molten flash to cut sharply through the surrounding dark drama.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test the gravity of your hardware before you commit.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Anchor dark drama and fast movement by deploying exactly one molten flash. Enforce strict limits. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start with statement jewellery, specifically a polished metal collar. Demand a warm, high polish. Apply the spotlight test to evaluate the finish. Hold the metal under a bare bulb. Trust your physical flinch when the light hits. If the surface scatters the beam or looks matt, drop it. You require a blinding reflection that shoots the glare straight back into your eye. This hard, reflective boundary cuts through deep bronze and golden camel fabrics, delivering strict precision without adding mass.",
      "sectionIntro": "Accessories establish the final boundary of your silhouette. Treat them as hard, functional hardware rather than decoration.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Statement jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "polished metal collar, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the spotlight test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Base your footwear exclusively on patent leather. You need an aggressive gloss to anchor your dark drama at street level. Examine a structured shoe under direct overhead lighting. If the leather swallows the beam, leave the pair in the box. The finish must fire a sharp, piercing glare straight back at the ceiling. This hard, mirrored casing builds fast movement into your foundation. Pair these high-shine boots with your warm deep bronze trousers. Reject any surface that reads soft or dull.",
      "sectionIntro": "Ground your look at the floor with shoes built for sharp, aggressive reflection.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "patent leather, patent gloss"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the spotlight test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select eyewear featuring a heavy acetate frame. Demand a high-shine finish. Deep tortoiseshell constructs dark drama. Ensure the shape sweeps sharply at the temples to force fast movement across your profile. Check that any exposed hinge hardware stays warm, ideally deep bronze. Stand in front of a mirror and scan your entire outfit for the brightest reflection. If two polished pieces fight for dominance, remove the weaker item. Rely on your immediate physical reaction to balance. A static pose deceives. Clutter does not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your hardware and execute a strict edit before you finish dressing.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "acetate frame, high shine"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the spotlight test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor your tailored garments in strict, high-contrast geometry like {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2}. Fluid layers demand sweeping scale to generate fast movement. Pick up {recommended_pattern_3} or {recommended_pattern_4} for bias cuts and heavy drapery. High-contrast graphic impact is mandatory. Avoid anything that dissolves into a warm tonal wash. Pass immediately over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. Apply the ten foot rule to every printed piece. Stand across the room and test the visual strike. If the shapes do not slice through the distance with loud, crisp precision, leave the garment on the rail. Scale and sharp boundaries project pure dark drama.",
      "sectionIntro": "Pattern is a structural tool used to force attention, never a background texture.",
      "tests": [
        "the ten foot rule (stay crisp, loud, and legible from across the room)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate prints from across the shop floor. A successful {recommended_pattern_1} retains its aggressive graphic impact at a distance. If the lines blur together, walk away. You require strict boundaries to build dark drama. Warm tones need precise edges to stay completely polished. Test the visual clarity before you even take the item to the fitting room. Demand fast movement from the design. A crisp scale forces the eye to track the silhouette rather than settling on a soft haze.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply a strict distance test to evaluate every print before buying.",
      "tests": [
        "the ten foot rule (stay crisp, loud, and legible from across the room)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_leo__moon_scorpio__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "quiet grandeur + quiet undercurrent + one molten flash",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on quiet grandeur + quiet undercurrent + one molten flash.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe at a slow, deliberate tempo. Seek out heavy, dense fabrics that hold their shape independent of your body. Trust your hands when you evaluate construction. Run your fingers over internal seams and hems to check their structural integrity. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. When selecting a garment, assess its architecture. If it collapses or stretches out of proportion on the hanger, leave it on the rail. You require pieces that create a defined, self-contained silhouette without relying on constant adjustment.\n\nMemorise your core style formula: quiet grandeur + quiet undercurrent + one molten flash. Picture a heavy, structured overcoat layered over a fluid, fine-gauge knit, anchored by a single dense cuff resting against your skin. Apply the wrist test to every final detail. Fasten the cuff or button the sleeve, then drop your arm to your side. If the piece rattles, shifts unexpectedly, or requires nudging back into position, remove it. Your components must settle instantly, anchored by their own mass and projecting a steady, warm gravity.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation, the absolute baseline for every garment you assess.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Seek materials that build quiet grandeur. Your fabrics must create a self-contained environment. Rely on {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to a warm, muted glow. Trust {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without bulk. Look to {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Anchor these foundations with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. Run every piece through the melt test before buying. Crush a sleeve in your fist. If the material fights back or holds a stiff crease, leave it on the hanger. It must collapse entirely into a heavy puddle in your palm. Rely on this tactile feedback above all else. The correct cloth drapes closely, acting as a silent canvas for one molten flash of metal.",
      "sectionIntro": "Let your hands filter the world before you put anything on your body.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
