    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let quiet grandeur dictate your choices at work. A full calendar does not demand rigid tailoring. It demands boiled wool that yields to your shoulders and washed silk that can race through a busy day. Support this primary focus with a hushed colour base of bitter chocolate or dark mahogany. Finish the look with a single piece of warm matt gold jewellery at the wrist. Avoid stiff blazers and sharp collars. Squeeze the fabric hard. If it stays wrinkled, put it back. Rely on cloud-soft lambswool and heavy silk crepe to maintain a strictly self-contained silhouette from morning until night.",
      "sectionIntro": "Take control of your daily uniform by establishing clear physical boundaries for your working hours.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "Low light asks you to shift focus. In close settings, quiet grandeur takes the lead. A demanding night does not require hard construction. It requires heavy silk crepe that keeps pace. Reach for dark mahogany. The warm fabric sits against your body. You feel the drape before anyone notices the cut. Base your decisions on sheer touch. Glass tells only half the story. The feeling of washed silk slipping over your skin reveals the truth. Pair this with a matt bronze cuff. The metal catches candlelight without glaring. Check the seam finish. It must lie perfectly flat. Close spaces expose poor stitching. Keep the garments close. Your evening wardrobe serves you, not an audience.",
      "sectionIntro": "Determine exactly how to dress when the lights drop and the space shrinks.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Mundane routines do not excuse stiff uniforms. They call for pliable garments capable of moving fast. Construct your morning base using yielding lambswool or heavy silk dyed in bitter chocolate. Picking up a prescription at the local chemist does not excuse a lapse in discipline. Your daily baseline remains quiet grandeur + quiet undercurrent + one molten flash. Assess every piece by breaking into a run. If a trouser restricts your stride to catch a train, leave it on the rack. Seek out dense knits paired with warm gold rings that sit flush on the skin. The daytime hours demand pieces that yield to your joints rather than dictate their posture.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat a crowded Tuesday exactly like a formal appointment.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your hardware strategy leans warm. Build your foundation by mixing {metal_1} and {metal_2}, introducing {metal_3} when a piece requires quiet grandeur. Lift every buckle, ring, and piece of jewellery to evaluate its physical density. Optics manipulate, but sheer mass always tells the truth. Leave hollow hardware behind. Avoid {excluded_finish} treatments entirely. Because your palette relies on a warm temperature, a highly reflective mirrored finish will immediately read as stark and visually disruptive against soft muted layers like {core_colour_1}. Fix this clash by strictly choosing matt and brushed textures. This muted finish strategy ensures your metals stay completely cohesive alongside your self-contained wardrobe.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select metals that anchor your warm palette and carry undeniable physical substance.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select dense, opaque minerals like {stone_1} and {stone_2} to anchor your warm palette. Always lift a piece from the velvet tray before purchasing. Sight is easily fooled. Heft offers absolute certainty. If the setting feels hollow in your palm, leave it behind. You need substantial mass to establish a quiet undercurrent beneath your garments. Avoid highly polished chrome and brilliant-cut gems. A mirror-like, high-shine finish creates a sharp distraction against muted cloth. Stick to brushed metals and matt cabochons to keep the look cohesive. Even {stone_3} works perfectly when its surface absorbs light instead of fracturing it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your aesthetic with heavy, opaque stones and muted metals.",
      "tests": [
