    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored coats demand {recommended_pattern_1} for their architecture. Fluid layers require {recommended_pattern_2} to maintain their motion. Rely strictly on low-contrast tonal patterns. High-contrast graphics fracture your self-contained edges. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} completely. Pick the piece up and execute the lamplight test. Hold the garment next to a warm bulb. The design must melt entirely into a soft texture, behaving like a shadow trapped inside the weave. Trust your hands to evaluate this depth. Reflections trick the eye. The tangible thickness of the fabric never does. When a motif fades beautifully into the material, it secures your quiet undercurrent and establishes true quiet grandeur.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as a subtle extension of your texture, never a visual interruption.",
      "tests": [
        "the lamplight test (melt into a soft texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the shadow test to evaluate any {recommended_pattern_1}. Step back from the mirror and squint under a warm bulb. A successful print loses its hard boundaries immediately. It must dissolve into a rich surface grain or a shadowed depth. If the shapes stay sharp and fight for attention, drop the garment. The motif should act as a textural hum rather than a focal point. Keep the scale contained and the colour contrast low. Watch how the lines blur into an ambiguous field. This subtle dissolution guarantees your quiet grandeur.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this specific visual check to separate functional prints from distracting geometry.",
      "tests": [
        "the lamplight test (melt into a soft texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_leo__moon_virgo__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "dark drama + honest fabric + one molten flash",
    "closing": "Let your tactile instincts map the path through dark drama + honest fabric + one molten flash.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the physical weight of a garment against your skin. This is your sensory compass. Acquire pieces slowly, testing them for structural integrity. Assemble your outfits fast when the environment shifts. Look for garments that hold a warm, heavy drape over the shoulder. If a weave feels thin or requires constant adjustment, reject it. Your wardrobe must function as a reactive system. Pick the garment up and test its heft. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.\n\nYour core style formula is dark drama + honest fabric + one molten flash. Picture a heavy, dark overcoat layered over a dense, unblended knit, finished with a single polished structural clip catching the light at the lapel. Before you purchase any anchor piece, apply the treaty test. Ask yourself if the garment possesses the gravity and finish required to sit at a diplomatic negotiating table. If it feels like a compromise, drop it. You need clothes that perform their function with absolute precision.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this blueprint to build a wardrobe that functions as a precise, adaptable toolkit.",
      "tests": [
        "the treaty test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "To build dark drama, you need honest fabric that holds its shape. Look for {texture_good_1} when selecting shirting that requires clean architectural boundaries. Choose {texture_good_2} for close-to-body base layers that demand sharp lines. Ground your lower half in {texture_good_3}. It allows trousers to drape cleanly and resist creasing. Rely on {texture_good_4} for lightweight outerwear that blocks the wind. Apply the two-hands test to every piece. Pick up the garment and pull the fabric gently between both hands. If it yields and snaps back with polished resistance, it belongs in your wardrobe. Rely on your grip to assess the weave. Finish the look with one molten flash of warm metal.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to read a garment with your hands before you put it on your body.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Grip the unknown cloth by the hem and collar, then snap it taut. If it resists with a stiff squeak or yields with a weak stretch, drop it. Reject {texture_bad_1} completely. It catches on dry skin and traps warm air close to the body, destroying any chance of a clean shape. Leave {texture_bad_2} on the hanger. It develops an artificial sheen and loses its structure immediately. Your baseline is dark drama. That specific depth crumbles on poor synthetics. Fingers register the truth. Drop any imposter.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to identify the materials that will betray your structure.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Find the friction between {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. This tactile collision anchors your dark drama. Evaluate any new piece by gripping the collar in your left hand and the sleeve in your right. Pull the material taut to measure its resistance. Visuals offer suggestions, but heavy threads provide facts. A lightweight {texture_good_1} must still carry a dense, polished weave that drops squarely to the floor. If the textile feels hollow or floats away from your frame, drop it immediately. Seek a warm surface that holds a strict shape. Your selections must rely on real tension between these opposing tactile weights.",
      "sectionIntro": "Isolate the exact material contrast where your best silhouettes click into place.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your baseline temperature is strictly warm. Build heavy structural garments in {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Treat {core_colour_3} as your clean light base, and keep {core_colour_4} on hand to bridge disparate layers. Anchor the look with dark drama. Strike with {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} when you require a sharp edge. Drop a soft note used sparingly into the mix when you want a quiet shift. Leave icy pastel, neon brights, and cold blue-grey on the rack. Avoid the oscillation trap. Do not wear head-to-toe fine ribbed merino one week and pivot entirely to stiff crisp cotton poplin the next. Counter this swing by locking one opposing material into every outfit you wear. Focus on how the dye sits in the weave's density to evaluate quality.",
      "sectionIntro": "Take strict control of your wardrobe by anchoring your hues in defined boundaries and rejecting anything outside them.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Warm taupe",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft cream",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sand beige",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Warm stone",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Olive drab",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Espresso brown",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rust orange",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Ochre gold",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Pale clay",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the seesaw: one month all floaty gauze, the next all crisp utility",
          "fix": "re-weave instead: keep one item from the other hand in every outfit, always"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Anchor your work uniform in honest fabric. Let crisp cotton poplin and worsted wool form the foundation. Support this base with dark drama in the tailoring. Construct a silhouette that holds its shape through a long afternoon. Even a long shift behind a desk requires strict structure. Contrast a warm taupe ribbed merino knit against a camel trouser. Finish the combination with a singular metallic gleam at the collar or cuff. Select a single brass ring or a gold pendant. This approach builds a strict boundary between you and the environment. Keep the metals controlled but visible.",
      "sectionIntro": "Govern your working hours by letting your structural components take the lead.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close quarters, tactile materials take the lead. When lighting drops, a warm taupe worsted wool or a fine ribbed merino will catch the ambient glow. Reach for garments with dense weaves. Grip the textile and test its recovery. If the piece sags in your hands, leave it on the hanger. Your tactile judgement overrides the mirror. Even a private dinner at home demands a sharp, deliberate silhouette. Throwing on a technical nylon jacket over camel knitwear must still present a structured shoulder. Introduce dark drama through strict cuts rather than relying on black dye alone. Contrast a matt surface against a solitary, highly polished gold chain. Let that single point of reflection sit near the collarbone to catch the candlelight.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the shift from daylight utility to low-light proximity.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat a Tuesday morning at the post office with exactly the same severity you apply to an evening engagement. A late-night drive to buy milk demands a deliberate outline. Do not suspend your baseline for minor tasks. Maintain your daily requirement of dark drama + honest fabric + one molten flash. Build this uniform with worsted wool trousers in camel and a heavy technical nylon jacket in warm taupe. Trust your grip when pulling items from the wardrobe. Glass reflects an illusion. Gravity is absolute. Secure a polished brass chain over the collar to finish the structure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Construct a reliable daily uniform that serves your immediate routine without compromising your structural baseline.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "You operate on a split-level metal strategy. For items worn directly against your skin, restrict your choices to warm, polished {personal_metal_1} and {personal_metal_2}. For structural elements like zips, belt buckles, and bag clasps, rely entirely on {structural_metal_1} and {structural_metal_2}. Your wardrobe depends on an honest fabric providing dark drama. Hardware supplies the necessary strict contrast. Avoid artificially aged details. Hammered copper, antiqued brass, and tarnished surfaces read as historical clutter against your present-tense garments. Restrict your hardware to pristine, high-shine surfaces to maintain a strictly polished lane. Reject {excluded_finish} entirely. Before buying any piece of hardware, lift it. Ignore the shine until you confirm the density. A lightweight buckle betrays cheap construction, regardless of the surface gleam.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat hardware as a structural tool, enforcing a strict division between personal adornment and functional closures.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select gems that fracture light cleanly. A dense {stone_1} or a clear {stone_2} provides the required focal point. Rely on your fingers when evaluating any setting. Lift the setting off the velvet. A genuine gem carries an undeniable gravity. Reject hammered finishes and artificially aged elements. Antiqued textures register as disorganised clutter against your warm foundation. Maintain your dark drama by restricting your hardware to smooth, high-gloss surfaces and perfectly polished reflections.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your look with stones and settings chosen for their precise density and clarity.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Let your fingers measure the quality of a piece. Evaluate the heft before you check the mirror. Hold the item flat in your palm. If a {metal_1} bracelet feels hollow, leave it on the tray. You require solid density to anchor your dark drama. Reject artificially distressed pieces. Hammered surfaces and oxidised details introduce messy interference next to an honest fabric. Restrict your selections to a flawless, mirror-like shine. A heavy, warm, polished finish ensures your hardware functions as a sharp focal point.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your hardware by touch before you commit to the purchase.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Establish the base with dark drama. Layer heavy honest fabric over your shoulders, like worsted wool or technical nylon. Complete the sequence with exactly one molten flash. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look, letting a warm, polished finish act as your focal point. Begin your textile additions with silk scarves. Fold a silk band tightly to cast a soft glow at the collar. Always run the last-look test before leaving the house. Take off the final detail you put on. If the outfit deflates into basic shapes, return the item to your frame. If the overall silhouette suddenly gains sharp clarity, leave the piece on the table.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is how you anchor your clothing with finishing touches.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk band, soft glow"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Reach for fine jewellery crafted with a high polish. Select a thin gold chain to anchor the neck. Avoid any dull or matt finishes here. Lift the chain and let the metal drop through your fingers. The immediate drop of real metal confirms its value. The piece must cast a warm glow above the collarbone to contrast and deliver dark drama. Run the mirror check before heading out. Stand in the light and confirm the chain acts as a single sharp detail rather than visual noise. Keep the focus entirely on the polished gold.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise the look by trusting your hands to select the right metal details.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin gold chain, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select a small structured bag. Demand a smooth leather crossbody profile. Inspect the metal components. Polished fine hardware must carry a warm finish. Press the clasp. Structural weight reveals the truth. Give the leather a hard push. It must resist the pressure. This strict geometry builds dark drama against worsted wool. Execute a final reduction before stepping outside. Stand completely still. Strip away the single element that crosses the boundary between your camel coat and the crossbody strap. If the bag hardware fights your rings, remove the bag. Every object left on the body must pull its own weight.",
      "sectionIntro": "Secure your final functional piece and run the ultimate visual audit.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather crossbody, polished fine hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Treat pattern as a structural tool rather than surface decoration. Tailored garments must take their geometry directly from the weave itself. Fluid pieces accept printed motifs like {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2}. Because you require an adaptable wardrobe, scale your contrast levels. Use tonal blending for formal settings and introduce sharper distinctions when the environment shifts. Apply the distance check. Hang the piece at arm's length. It must present a calm, solid field of warm colour from afar. Step closer. The geometry must reveal a rewarding texture, confirming you chose honest fabric. Build dark drama through this woven depth. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} completely. Leave {avoid_pattern_2} on the hanger. Scan the surface to find structural integrity, skipping flat synthetic prints entirely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your pattern choices by treating geometry as an extension of the cloth.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the three-step rule to any {recommended_pattern_1}. Hang the garment against a flat wall and step back exactly three paces. From this distance, the print must melt into a steady block of dark drama. It should read as a single, polished shadow. Now step close. The motif must sharpen immediately. If it looks muddy up close or loud from afar, leave it on the rail. Every honest fabric rewards proximity. The tight weave and the warm dye should only reveal their complexity when someone enters your immediate orbit.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this strict visual test to control how your pattern reads across a room.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_leo__moon_taurus__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "quiet grandeur + sensory comfort + one molten flash",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on quiet grandeur + sensory comfort + one molten flash.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Run your hands over every piece before you take it into the fitting room. Notice the warm weight of the fabric against your skin, testing how it moves when you grip it. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Build your collection with steady deliberation, adding items only when they meet your strictest criteria for comfort. Evaluate each garment for absolute ease and structural integrity. Apply the physical recoil test. If a piece requires constant adjustment, pinches your movements, or feels rigid across your shoulders, trust that immediate bodily rejection and step away. Leave the item exactly where you found it.\n\nYour defining equation is quiet grandeur + sensory comfort + one molten flash. Picture a heavy, matt overcoat falling cleanly to the calf, offering complete coverage without unnecessary bulk. Layer it over fine, yielding knitwear that sits gently against the ribs, expanding as you breathe without ever restricting your motion. Anchor this understated shape with a single dense piece of light-catching jewellery resting low at the wrist. The overall silhouette remains structured to the eye but completely adaptable to the body. Every single layer must feel physically reassuring to wear, working seamlessly to present a unified, deliberate front.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise the core logic of your wardrobe and let physical instinct drive every single styling decision.",
      "tests": [
        "trust your gut and walk away"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Trust your hands to find sensory comfort. Squeeze a {texture_good_1} sweater. It must compress and bounce back, refusing to pill. Inspect the {texture_good_2} of a new belt and apply the patina test. Ask yourself if the surface will soften and deepen with your body heat rather than flake away. Seek {texture_good_3} for tailored coats that hold an unwavering edge. Line those pieces with {texture_good_4} to ensure fluid movement against your skin. These materials build an architecture of quiet grandeur. Look for warm dyes that sink deep into the fibres. Anchor this matt foundation with one molten flash of heavy hardware. Study the hierarchy of your best textures below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Your materials must pass a strict physical threshold before they touch your skin.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
        {
          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the patina test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Pick up {texture_bad_1} and crush it in your fist. If it springs back with a hollow, rigid resistance, drop it immediately. True quiet grandeur requires materials that yield to your physical form. Apply a simple friction check to {texture_bad_2}. Rub the fabric between your thumb and forefinger. If it generates static or feels slick with an artificial coating, it will suffocate rather than breathe. Reject any garment that merely decays rather than softening into character. Picture how the surface will respond to three years of daily friction. If the fibres will pill into cheap fuzz or a falsely matt finish will permanently crack, leave it on the hanger. Let your tactile senses dictate the purchase. Visuals can be faked, but the true density of a weave cannot hide.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to interrogate every fabric, discarding anything that feels hollow or synthetic.",
      "tests": [
        "the patina test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your ideal pairing merges {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. This combination builds the quiet grandeur at the core of your style. Layer {texture_good_1} over these base elements to create tactile depth. Keep the underlying temperature warm. Apply the patina test before committing to new items. Dig your thumbs into the material and ask how it will handle ten years of friction. True luxury deepens with age rather than degrading. Look for materials that absorb life and grow richer over time. Trust your hands over the mirror.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your texture combinations by demanding a rigorous physical response from raw materials.",
      "tests": [
        "the patina test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your overall temperature is warm. Build a foundation with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. These tones provide sensory comfort and establish the base. Introduce {core_colour_3} and {core_colour_4} to shift the weight of an outfit without breaking harmony. Reserve {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} as deliberate strikes of contrast. Deploy your relief tone sparingly to lift a dense ensemble. Pass over icy electric blue, neon brights, and fleeting trend pastels entirely. The recurring trap is relying on head-to-toe black. A solid block of uniform darkness reads as lazy and unresolved. Fix this immediately by fracturing the dark column with a {core_colour_2} layer, a {accent_colour_1} scarf, or a {core_colour_3} belt.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your wardrobe by mastering a disciplined selection of targeted tones.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rich toffee",
          "role": "warm_base"
