          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged brass with a molten gold accent, mixed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Restrict your tailored pieces to patterns born directly from the loom. Let woven structure carry the visual weight. Reserve printed motifs strictly for fluid garments. Your guiding rule is low-contrast tonal shading. Authentic quiet grandeur relies on this restraint. Step back three paces and let your vision blur. The print must melt into a cohesive, warm texture. If the design stays sharp and jars the eye, leave it on the hanger. Seek out {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. Such stark graphics disrupt your baseline. Anchor your daily choices in pure sensory comfort. A successful motif never competes with the drape of your clothing.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as a structural element that requires strict physical discipline.",
      "tests": [
        "step back and soften focus (blur into texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Assess any printed textile from across the room. A successful {recommended_pattern_1} will stop registering as a defined graphic and merge into a warm, unbroken surface. If the shapes stay distinct and demand attention from a distance, leave the piece behind. You require clothing that delivers quiet grandeur. Harsh contrasting lines disrupt that goal. Trust your immediate perception. If the motif refuses to blend evenly, it fails the test.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every print to a strict distance test.",
      "tests": [
        "step back and soften focus (blur into texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_libra__moon_aries__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "balanced proportions + sharp edges + one refined touch",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on balanced proportions + sharp edges + one refined touch.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the physical weight of a garment in your hands before you put it on. If it feels poorly balanced on the hanger, it will fight you on the body. Your formula is balanced proportions + sharp edges + one refined touch. Build a look around this. Take a structured jacket cut strictly at the hip. Pair it with straight trousers that drop cleanly to the shoe. Finish with a single smooth scarf tied tightly at the collar. This is your baseline. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.\n\nBuild your wardrobe methodically. Deploy it rapidly by reading your environment. When you try a new piece, rely on the fall test. Stand perfectly still in front of a mirror and watch how the fabric drops from your shoulders to your waist. A successful garment drops straight down without clinging, twisting, or collapsing inwards. If you have to pull at the hem to correct the shape, leave the item in the shop. Mix matt and polished finishes freely to create depth. Rely on an overall cool temperature to ground the silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation and the physical standard you will use to evaluate every garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the fall test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Anchor your cool palette in materials that hold strict lines. You need garments that establish balanced proportions without restricting your physical movement. Start with {texture_good_1} for shirting. It provides clean architectural boundaries and pure separation against your skin. Layer {texture_good_2} beneath it for close-to-body foundations that maintain crisp seams while you move. Choose {texture_good_3} for trousers that drape cleanly and refuse to crease through a long day. Add one refined touch with {texture_good_4} for lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks the wind and weighs little. Assess the material directly before buying. Perform the edge test by pinching a cuff or hem between your thumb and forefinger. If the fabric holds a rigid boundary, buy it. If it collapses into a soft curve, leave it on the rail. Rely on the following hierarchy to select your core textiles.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every fabric against its ability to hold structure and endure friction.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
