      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "total ice: unbroken grey on grey can read as absence rather than composure",
          "fix": "add the polished signal, a mirror-finish cuff, a patent boot, or one line of electric colour"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, sharp edges take the lead. Build the foundation with strict worsted wool trousers and crisp cotton poplin shirts. Let these firm lines dictate the silhouette. Bring in an even scale across your items to support those cuts, then add your final polished detail through a matt watch strap. Navigating the outdoor market on a freezing morning does not excuse a loss of proportion. Pick up a structured technical nylon coat over your fine ribbed merino to keep your shape strict. Keep your palette firmly cool with stark navy and icy grey. Demand rigid finishes. Grasp the hem and check for tension. A coat that droops over your arm has no place in your wardrobe.",
      "sectionIntro": "Construct your work garments with strict geometry and rigid shapes.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim light and close quarters, geometry must lead. Sharing a late drink does not require abandoning proportion. Maintain your strict silhouette even when the room relaxes. Heavy fabrics perform better than thin weaves in shadows. Select a worsted wool blazer or a crisp cotton poplin overshirt in cool stark navy. Grasp the cloth. It must feel substantial. Mix metals freely at the wrist. A matt silver watch beside a bright gold ring provides enough contrast under candlelight. Examine the outfit by its overall shape. Drooping sleeves require an immediate change of garment.",
      "sectionIntro": "Mastering close-quarters dressing requires scaling down your silhouette without losing structure.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Buying paracetamol at the local chemist at seven in the morning demands the exact same geometry as an afternoon appointment. A Sunday trip to the greengrocer does not mean you surrender your shape to oversized jersey. Pick up an icy grey worsted wool jacket and layer it over a fine ribbed merino knit. Add rigid stark navy denim to build a firm foundation. Look for stiff hems and precise seams. You must always deploy balanced proportions + sharp edges + one refined touch. Mix your metals freely. Fasten a steel belt buckle and wear a gold watch. Shapeless fabric falling over your boots signals a structural failure. Discard the item. Keep your cool palette strictly enforced.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your baseline routine as a discipline, not a default.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "You hold complete freedom to blend {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} across your jewellery and structural zips. Your cool tones provide an ideal backdrop for this mixture. Pick up any new piece to gauge its density. A quality buckle or solid ring drops heavily into your palm. Avoid artificial aging. Pre-tarnished surfaces and hammered textures introduce historical fiction that fights your crisp geometry. Fix this clutter by demanding gleaming {metal_1} and bright {metal_2}. Mix a mirror polish with {excluded_finish} detailing to guarantee your sharp edges remain unbroken.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select and test the metals that anchor your jewellery and structural hardware.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Demand density and absolute clarity from your stones. Choose {stone_1} and {stone_2} as strict geometric anchors. Assess the heft of the piece in your bare palm. True quality reveals itself through sheer mass. Reject artificially aged, beaten, or tarnished jewellery entirely. Faux-vintage materials read as pure clutter against a precise aesthetic. Limit your selections to high-shine chrome, strict platinum, and polished white gold. This cool brightness ensures your geometry remains perfectly intact. Every cut must serve a deliberate structural purpose.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every piece of hardware through strict physical testing to guarantee it serves your structural requirements.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Heft every {metal_1} clasp and watch bracelet to confirm the weight matches the shine. Tarnished bronze, beaten copper, and artificially weathered alloys scan as visual noise. They drag a sharply modern aesthetic into the past. Leave that vintage clutter on the tray. Insist on solid platinum, brilliant white gold, and high-shine chrome. These clear, cool metals establish absolute precision across your accessories.",
      "sectionIntro": "Let gravity determine the quality of your hardware.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments build a structure of balanced proportions and distinct sharp edges. Accessories provide the one refined touch. Commit to wearing one or two strong pieces per look. Assess the overall geometry and verify that only a solitary item breaks the rigid lines. If a steel watch and a printed neckpiece both fight for visual priority, remove one. Start your selection with silk scarves. Seek out a crepe de chine square in a cool shade. Verify the textile has a strictly matt finish. Tie the fabric closely at the collarbone to keep the silhouette strict.",
      "sectionIntro": "Accessories establish the final layer of your visual uniform, demanding precise curation over careless accumulation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Treat fine jewellery as structural reinforcement. Look for thin chains and slender rings that blend cool silver with gold. Combine polished surfaces with brushed, matt textures to keep the visual impact light against worsted wool or technical nylon. Enforce the solitary focus rule before wearing anything new. If a mixed-metal ring introduces high shine, thick volume, and heavy texture all at once, leave it in the box. A piece must broadcast exactly one distinct detail to anchor a stark navy outfit and preserve your sharp edges. A slim silver band set with an icy grey stone passes this standard. Measure the cold temperature and sheer drag of the metal against your skin.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select and evaluate fine metals with the precision of an architect selecting structural steel.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin mixed gold and silver, mixed polished and brushed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Let the weight of the leather guide you. If the handle feels flimsy, drop it. Select a small structured bag to finish the look. Choose a top-handle shape in kid suede or smooth leather. Look for fine mixed hardware to keep cool tones adaptable. Run your fingers over the seams to verify they hold firm. Maintain strict proportions across the silhouette. Evaluate the focal points before you leave. Read the outfit as a whole and ensure only a single item pulls focus. If the suede top-handle competes with heavy silver rings, strip the jewellery away.",
      "sectionIntro": "Edit your final additions by checking their physical structure and isolating their visual impact.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede or smooth leather top-handle, fine mixed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Your pattern strategy relies on adaptive contrast, shifting intensity based on the garment's construction. Tailored coats and trousers must take their pattern from the literal weave of the cloth. Fluid shirts and loose layers carry the actual printed ink. Look for {recommended_pattern_1} woven directly into worsted fabrics. Pick up technical synthetics bearing {recommended_pattern_2}. Reject {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. Subject every printed piece to the straight-edge test. Step back three metres from the glass. The printed lines must stay perfectly crisp and true at that exact distance. If a boundary blurs or wavers, drop the garment. Pass over {avoid_pattern_2} without a second thought. These busy motifs disrupt the garment's visual weight and ruin your balanced proportions. They dilute the strict geometry required by cool colours.",
      "sectionIntro": "Pattern introduces strict visual rhythm, demanding rigorous selection to serve your structural rules.",
      "tests": [
        "the straight-edge test (lines stay crisp and true at three metres)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Examine {recommended_pattern_1} from a distance. The internal geometry must hold its structure without distortion from across the room. If the shapes bleed into the surrounding fabric, leave the garment on the rail. You require prints that retain their distinct borders. Look for crisp boundaries cutting with absolute clarity against a cool background. Avoid designs that rely on gradient fades or soft colourway transitions. Trust your naked eyesight over the designer label. If the motif looks fuzzy from afar, it will compromise your structure up close.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every pattern to a strict physical distance check before it enters your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the straight-edge test (lines stay crisp and true at three metres)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_libra__moon_cancer__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "balanced proportions + hidden depth + one refined touch",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on balanced proportions + hidden depth + one refined touch.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Treat your wardrobe as a responsive toolkit. Your primary physical instinct is adaptability. When you pick up a garment, test its structural tolerance in your hands. If the fabric feels brittle or the cut locks you into a single rigid silhouette, drop it. Trust the pieces that breathe and shift with your body. Your core style formula is balanced proportions + hidden depth + one refined touch. Picture a draped medium-weight trouser cut straight, paired with a dense knit sweater that reveals its complex construction only up close, finished with a single matt hardware closure. This combination establishes a steady, cool baseline that anchors you without restriction.\n\nBuild your collection deliberately and let your daily execution drift by mood. You require a system that absorbs changing environments. Apply the flight test to every item you consider. Put the garment on and sit down. Ask yourself if you could sleep through a long-haul flight in these layers and proceed directly to your next commitment upon landing without feeling compromised. If the seams dig into your shoulders or the fabric loses its shape immediately, leave it on the rack. Your garments must sustain your momentum. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish your physical baseline and strict mechanical criteria before you add another piece to your collection.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Construct balanced proportions starting with {texture_good_1} for shirting that establishes clean boundaries. Underneath, deploy {texture_good_2} as a base layer for sharp lines and easy movement. Ground the silhouette in {texture_good_3} trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing. Introduce hidden depth through {texture_good_4} for lightweight outerwear that blocks wind without adding bulk, leaving room for one refined touch in your mixed metals. To vet any new material, apply the crush test. Squeeze the sleeve tightly in your fist, then release it and check the recovery. If it demands a steamer before wear, drop it. Let the sheer gravity of the cloth dictate your purchase. Keep the overall palette cool. Focus your hands on these primary fibres.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the tactile signatures that dictate how a garment actually performs.",
      "rankedItems": [
