    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, hidden depth must direct your decisions. A charcoal twill trouser paired with dense cashmere reveals its complexity only when someone sits directly beside you. Keep your palette cool with icy grey accents. Mix your metals freely across your hands. A matt silver cuff next to a gold ring catches dim lighting without competing. Rely on your tactile instincts rather than visual confirmation to approve construction. Even an evening walk to the local market does not mean surrendering your silhouette to shapeless loungewear. Maintain a sharp cut. A thick cotton collar layered under a technical nylon jacket provides necessary structure. Test the friction between these textiles with your fingers to ensure the combination holds tension.",
      "sectionIntro": "Calibrate your choices for low light and close quarters.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat a routine commute to the post office exactly like a formal appointment. A brief errand does not demand the collapse of your silhouette. Build the morning around an icy grey technical nylon shell. Let your fingers gauge the collar stiffness. Mix a matt silver zipper with a polished gold watch case. Keep the temperature cool across every layer. Always anchor the day in balanced proportions + hidden depth + one refined touch. Do not downgrade your construction just because the destination is trivial.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your everyday habits in garments that require zero adjustment between tasks.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "You possess total freedom to mix your hardware. Combine {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} across your zips, watch cases, and rings. This fluid approach anchors the cool tones in your clothing while layering hidden depth. Artificially aged surfaces and hammered copper create visual noise that disrupts your balanced proportions. Keep strictly to clean surfaces and leave {excluded_finish} metal entirely alone. Always pick the piece up in your hands. A photograph lies. Gravity tells the truth. A solid {metal_1} buckle feels utterly different from a hollow replica. Trust the mass in your hand to dictate the final purchase.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your hardware as the structural rigging of your wardrobe, demanding the exact same scrutiny you apply to cloth.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Avoid artificially aged finishes and hammered metals. These distressed textures create visual clutter against a sharp, present-tense silhouette. Keep your hardware firmly anchored in the current moment with polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome. Choose stones that offer hidden depth rather than loud sparkle. Seek out the dense, cool mass of a {stone_1} or the stark clarity of a {stone_2}. Hold the piece in your palm before putting it on. Refraction creates illusions. The physical pull on your fingers is real. If it feels hollow, leave it in the tray. You require balanced proportions in every single element, starting with the sheer physical density resting against your skin.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones and metals through physical mass and flawless finishes.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the item from the counter and weigh it in your palm. The sheer density of an object is its only honest metric. Rely on this tactile instinct to evaluate quality. Avoid artificially aged alloys, hammered surfaces, and faux patinas. These finishes read as nostalgic clutter and actively disrupt your balanced proportions. Maintain a sharp, present-tense aesthetic by selecting highly polished, cool metals like {metal_1}. Whether you mix hardware or stick to a uniform high-shine finish, the piece must possess a substantial, grounding weight. A dense, mirror-smooth buckle or a heavy {stone_1} ring introduces hidden depth without compromising your sleek foundation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply a strict physical test to ensure your hardware grounds rather than distracts.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You have secured your balanced proportions. You have built your hidden depth. Now, accessories provide your one refined touch. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Anchor this practice with the take-off test. Remove the very last item you put on before leaving. If the silhouette crumbles without it, your garments failed. If the item feels redundant, leave it on the table. Begin your selection with silk scarves. Demand a crepe de chine square with a strictly matt surface. Trust the cool, dry friction of the textile against your neck. Vision is easily manipulated. Let the material itself serve as your final judge.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate and edit your finishing details using strict physical instinct.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Build your fine jewellery collection on thin bands and delicate chains, combining cool silver and gold without hesitation. Pair a highly polished silver ring beside a brushed gold cuff. This contrasting surface treatment creates hidden depth against worsted wool. Mix metals freely across your fingers and neck, but always verify the composition. Apply the threshold check before leaving. Unfasten the final chain before you turn the handle. If your foundation holds without it, leave the piece behind. Let tactile reality be the only judge. Disregard your reflection. Rely on the cold drop of metal against your collarbone.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the integration of fine jewellery and mixed metals.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin mixed gold and silver, mixed polished and brushed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your carrying choices in strict architecture. Look for a small structured top-handle bag in kid suede or smooth leather. Run your fingers over the seams. Trust your grip to judge the construction. Surface appearances are meaningless against the strict measure of physical mass. Seek out fine mixed hardware. Blending gold with a cool silver clasp builds hidden depth. Prioritise balanced proportions over carrying capacity to prevent an oversized shape from ruining the silhouette. Perform one last subtraction. Drop the most prominent item. If the look survives, it was unnecessary.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your final structural additions through touch and strict editing.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede or smooth leather top-handle, fine mixed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Assign scale based on structure. Tailored garments demand architectural rigour, taking their structural cue from {recommended_pattern_1}. Fluid layers handle organic rhythm, leaning on {recommended_pattern_2} to establish hidden depth without overpowering the silhouette. Because your lane is adaptive, scale your contrast to the garment's function. A structured outer layer carries high-contrast lines perfectly. A lightweight shirt needs muted contrast to maintain a cool visual temperature. Memorise your pass-over list and instantly bypass {avoid_pattern_1}. It fractures your outline. Apply the passing test to every printed piece before buying. Put the item on and walk swiftly towards a mirror. A successful motif stops shouting and reads as a soft, pleasant texture in motion. If the lines fight your physical movement, reject the piece entirely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat print as a structural material, testing its visual weight through pure movement.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Test the motif from a distance. Suspend the {recommended_pattern_1} across the room and approach it quickly. Squint as you move. The design must dissolve into an agreeable, gentle grain rather than holding a rigid shape. If the graphic remains legible from the opposite wall, leave the garment on the rack. Look for motifs where the cool colour melts into a quiet, continuous hum. This optical shift provides essential hidden depth. Trust your physical reaction to the blur. Static inspection lies. Motion reveals the truth. A passing print builds balanced proportions without pulling the eye out of alignment.",
      "sectionIntro": "Run every print through a simple visual filter to ensure it serves your structure.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_libra__moon_capricorn__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "balanced proportions + softness + one refined touch",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on balanced proportions + softness + one refined touch.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe slowly over seasons, then dress fast in the morning. Your strategy relies on a strict filter for cut and drape. Run your thumb over every seam and hem. You are feeling for a heavy, cool fluidity. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not. Your foundation rests entirely on a strict equation. Memorise it as balanced proportions + softness + one refined touch.\n\nPicture a fine-gauge knit tucked precisely into tailored trousers, anchored by a single piece of matt metal at the collarbone. The outfit never speaks before you do. When you try on a new piece, check the mirror and ask yourself who is pouring the tea. If the garment feels like the host and you feel like the guest, leave it in the shop. You must remain the undisputed subject. Every item you own must serve your absolute self-containment.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master this underlying architecture before you buy another piece of clothing.",
      "tests": [
        "the host test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Ground your wardrobe in softness and balanced proportions. To achieve this, you need matt surfaces that absorb cool light. Reach for {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Choose {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Look for {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Finish with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. To verify any piece, apply the breath test. Press the cloth against your mouth and inhale slowly. If the weave fights your intake, leave it on the rack. Rely on your senses. Appearance deceives. Stiff fabrics betray their rigidity. Your materials must offer absolute physical autonomy, serving as one refined touch against the skin.",
      "sectionIntro": "Let your hands filter out the rigid and the reflective before the garment ever touches your skin.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
