      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Avoid {texture_bad_1}. Stretch the fabric across your palm and breathe sharply onto it. If the fibres trap the heat and force the air back, drop the piece immediately. This material suffocates the skin and destroys any attempt at balanced proportions. Run your thumb across {texture_bad_2}. Notice the artificial, lifeless scrape. It cannot yield to your joints. Harsh textiles disrupt your core necessity of softness. They build rigid structures instead of draping in quiet, cool harmony. Reject {texture_bad_3} for the same reason. An unyielding, matt surface blocks the subtlety of your styling. It fights against your frame and dilutes the impact of one refined touch.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify and reject hostile materials before they ever touch your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Your ideal surface is a matt finish that absorbs light. Pull {texture_good_1} from the rack and test the weave. Gather the cloth in your fist and release it. If the creases lock or the fibres feel stifling, drop the garment immediately. You need yielding materials to support your balanced proportions. Cool colours demand a flat surface. Any synthetic sheen will compromise the drape. Keep your garments close and self-contained. Let your hands judge. Labels deceive. The tactile response tells the truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify the exact fabric finishes that anchor your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette relies on a temperature that is strictly cool. Test every tone to ensure it aligns. Build your foundation using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_3}, anchoring them with the structural depth of {core_colour_2}. When you need light, reach for {core_colour_4}. Deploy {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as your single deliberate accent. Treat the relief tone as a soft note used sparingly. Pass over hard black, harsh neon, and heavy brown. Beware the murky sink trap, where dense, matt, dark layers pile up and swallow your form. Lift this trap immediately. Place a {core_colour_4} layer at the collar, add one piece of smooth leather, or introduce the relief tone. Maintaining strict control over these elements guarantees balanced proportions in every look.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your palette by strictly controlling the tones that sit closest to your face.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Dove grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
