          "fix": "rescue it with a graphite anchor piece or a bottle green accent, and let one texture change restore the depth"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let light movement lead your choices in the office. Choose a stark navy worsted wool trouser that yields to an active stride. Support this mobility with equalised scale. Pair the trouser with a cleanly cut icy grey cotton poplin shirt. Stepping out to the corner for a flat white does not mean dropping your structure. Keep the collar crisp. Finish the outfit with a single polished detail. Fasten a cool silver watch or a matt platinum cuff. You need pieces that respond as you work alongside your team. Build a reliable shape that adapts without stiffening.",
      "sectionIntro": "Navigate your working hours with practical materials and clear intent.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, light movement takes the lead. Test how fine ribbed merino shifts when you lean across a table to speak with a friend. Keep the temperature cool with stark navy or icy grey. Mix your metals freely. Wear a silver chain next to a gold watch. Even off-duty hours do not require losing your shape. Keep your lines sharp with worsted wool trousers. Rely on your hands to gauge the cloth. If the fabric feels stiff, put it back.",
      "sectionIntro": "Adapt your approach when the light drops and the setting becomes intimate.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Running local errands does not justify wearing shapeless fleece. Keep your standard intact. Your daily equation remains balanced proportions + light movement + one refined touch. Build early mornings around crisp cotton poplin and fine ribbed merino in cool shades of stark navy or icy grey. Layer worsted wool over technical nylon when stepping out into the neighbourhood. Mix a thin silver chain with a heavy gold ring. Place a matt surface directly against a high polish. Grip the material and feel the tight weave bounce back in your hands. Dress to engage actively with your community. Give yourself reliable tools for the day.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your simplest errands as proof of your baseline standard.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your cool palette requires clean, sharp hardware. You have the total freedom to mix {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} across a single outfit. Alternate these elements to introduce light movement into a rigid silhouette. Always test the pieces directly in your palm. Optics tell lies. Absolute mass tells the truth. Reject artificially aged components like hammered copper or tarnished brass entirely. These faux-vintage pieces register as immediate visual clutter on a present-tense aesthetic. Limit your selections strictly to sleek, reflective elements like polished silver, white gold, and mirror chrome. Vary your surfaces to keep the hardware dynamic. Blend {excluded_finish} textures with high-polish gloss to build complexity without breaking the modern lines of your garments.",
      "sectionIntro": "Approach your hardware selection as a strict functional toolkit.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Treat your gems as tools for catching cool light. Trust your hands to detect the true density of a piece. Select {stone_1} and {stone_2} for their piercing clarity and substantial weight. Avoid pre-tarnished alloys, beaten copper, and artificially distressed materials. These create visual static that clutters your open, adaptable style. Rely instead on gleaming silver, solid platinum, white gold, and mirror-like chrome to frame your {stone_3}. The right hardware supports your balanced proportions without tipping into excess.",
      "sectionIntro": "Mastering your hardware starts with understanding how metals and stones respond to light and gravity.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the piece off the counter to verify its weight. Rely on the sheer heaviness in your palm to judge an item. Forced patina creates visual noise against an adaptable, present-tense wardrobe. Anchor your outfit with balanced proportions by selecting high-shine {metal_1}, gleaming platinum, brilliant chrome, and {stone_1}. These choices keep the aesthetic sharp and the temperature cool.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess the tactile reality of your hardware.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments build balanced proportions and allow light movement. Accessories deliver the required completion, bringing one refined touch. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start with eyewear. Select a heavy acetate frame with a mixed finish, contrasting a high polish against a matt interior. Ensure the resin sits in a cool shade. Subject every pair to the function test. Put the frames on and tilt your head sharply towards the floor. If they slide down the bridge of your nose, leave them behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the physical tests required to select functional objects that complete your silhouette.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "acetate frame, mixed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Require your bags to work for you. Test the function directly. Sling a technical nylon crossbody over your shoulder and pull the brushed metal zips with a single hand while pacing. If the track sticks or forces you to look down, drop the piece. You need construction that allows uninterrupted light movement. Verify the shape against your body. The strap must sit flush against a cool icy grey coat to maintain balanced proportions, avoiding awkward bulk. Let the hardware clash across your frame. Anchor those matt brushed fastenings with one polished ring on the strap base. Trust your bare hands to judge the hardware tension. Friction proves the utility.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess your functional accessories with uncompromising physical standards.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "technical nylon crossbody, brushed metal zips, one polished ring"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your feet with a clean leather boot. Scrutinise the hardware. Mix your metals here, pairing steel eyelets with a brass side zip to integrate the rest of your pieces. Ensure the leather holds a cool, matt undertone. Pick the boot up and bend the toe box backward. You need pliable hides that guarantee light movement through the ankle. Stiff shafts disrupt your natural stride. Always perform the function test before heading out. Put both boots on, lace them firmly, and walk quickly across a hard floor. If the heel slips, the sole drags, or the instep pinches, abandon them. Trust your bones over the mirror. Your shoes must serve your anatomy.",
      "sectionIntro": "Lock down your footwear and verify your choices before walking out the door.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "clean leather boot, clean"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored worsted wool takes its geometry directly from the weave. Fluid layers carry printed motifs that trace light movement when you walk. Scale your contrast to adapt to your environment. Rely on subtle tonal differences for close quarters. Switch to sharper distinctions when the setting demands visibility. Pick up {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. If the design reads as clean texture from a distance, it passes. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. Keep your silhouette grounded in balanced proportions. Anchor these pieces in a cool palette. True quality registers in the physical weight of the cloth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Handle pattern as a strict tool for scale and distance, not a decorative afterthought.",
      "tests": [
        "the desk test (read as clean texture at arm's length and a half)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the desk test to verify your instinct. Drape any {recommended_pattern_1} over a chair, step back an arm's length and a half, and squint. Trust your eyes when they lose focus. The print must resolve into a clean, cool texture. If the lines stay sharp or fight for your attention, drop the piece. You want patterns that dissolve into solid cloth from a short distance away. This visual discipline ensures every printed garment will support balanced proportions. Let the motif sink into the background.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this precise distance check to evaluate any printed garment before you buy it.",
      "tests": [
        "the desk test (read as clean texture at arm's length and a half)"
      ]
    }
  },
