  "venus_libra__moon_leo__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "balanced proportions + athletic space + one refined touch",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on balanced proportions + athletic space + one refined touch.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Anchor your choices in the physical sensation of unrestricted movement. Test the garment by shifting your weight and reaching upwards. If a seam pulls or a hem restricts your stride, leave the piece on the rail. Your structural blueprint relies on balanced proportions + athletic space + one refined touch. Picture a heavy cotton drop-shoulder sweatshirt paired with straight-leg wool trousers cut generously at the thigh, finished with a precise leather loafer. The shapes provide mechanical freedom. The single sharp detail grounds the execution. Maintain a cool temperature across your garments to ensure these modular parts connect seamlessly.\n\nBuild your wardrobe methodically over time, selecting pieces that adapt to your environment and community responsibilities. Deploy them swiftly by mood each morning. Before you step outside, apply the flight test. Sit on a low chair, cross your ankles, and ask yourself if you could endure an eight-hour flight exactly as you are dressed. If a waistband digs or a shoulder seam binds, change your clothes. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Mix your metals and layer matt and glossy finishes freely to keep the final result practical.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this framework to anchor your physical instincts and guide your daily choices.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "To guarantee balanced proportions and secure your required athletic space, buy fabrics that work with your momentum. Seek out textiles that hold a cool dye flat and true. Subject every garment to the motion test. Try the piece on, reach high, sit down, and bend to tie your shoe. If the weave resists your body, drop it. Build your shirting with {texture_good_1} to define clean boundaries. Rely on {texture_good_2} for base layers that ensure easy movement. Invest in {texture_good_3} for trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing. Finish with {texture_good_4} as your lightweight outerwear to block wind. These materials deliver one refined touch without compromising daily utility. Work from this ranked list.",
      "sectionIntro": "Prioritise materials that guarantee mobility while maintaining a sharp physical boundary.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Put the item on and stride aggressively across the shop floor. If the material binds at the knee or bites into your shoulder, leave it on the hanger. You require athletic space to function. Your physical comfort dictates the fit. Pick up {texture_bad_1}. If it sits stiffly in the hand, it will trap heat and limit your reach. Rub {texture_bad_2} between your fingers. A brittle scrape against your thumb signals a poor weave that will fight your body for hours. Avoid these rigid traps. Keep your fabrics cool and adaptable. A bad texture feels like a cage.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify the materials that will actively fight your body.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Anchor your style in the raw friction between {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Pick up a piece of {texture_good_1} and evaluate the weight in your bare hands. Notice the cool finish against your skin. You need pure mechanical freedom to pivot and stretch. Check every new item by dropping into a deep crouch and swinging your arms across your chest. If the material limits your extension or pins your joints, reject it immediately. Rely on this strict physical feedback to enforce balanced proportions.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your material pairings by grounding them in strict physical function.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Keep your temperature entirely cool. Build your foundation with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Rely on {core_colour_3} as your strict white substitute, and ground these choices with {core_colour_4} to define your edges. This discipline creates the athletic space you need. Bring in {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as your single deliberate accent. Add your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly. Pass over Mustard, Rust, and Warm olive green. Watch for the hard shell trap. Notice when you start reaching for armour, technical jackets, and stiff utility layers when life speeds up. Fix this error immediately. Swap the shell for a brushed cotton layer that moves just as fast and holds your structure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your wardrobe's palette by treating dye as a strict tool, not a random choice.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Stark navy",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Icy grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Optical white",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep slate",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp charcoal",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Chalk",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Steel blue",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Acidic yellow",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sharp cobalt",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Kelly green",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Chalky blue",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the hard shell: reaching for armour, technical jackets, and stiff utility layers when life speeds up",
          "fix": "swap the shell for a brushed cotton layer that moves just as fast and holds you besides"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let your need for athletic space lead your choices at work. Support this ease with strict fibres. Anchor your day in stark navy worsted wool trousers and a fine ribbed merino knit. You must be able to stretch for a high shelf or pivot without seams binding. Add a singular polished detail. A mixed metal watch or a matt silver collar provides focus. Test the garments in motion. Grabbing a coffee down the street should not mean leaving your cool climate behind. Keep your icy grey technical nylon jacket zipped when you step outside. Look for construction that holds its shape from desk to pavement without pinching your joints. Trust your hands to check the drape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Your working environment requires strict structure, but never at the expense of your mobility.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close settings and dim lighting, visual details fade. Your athletic space must dictate the mood. Keep the garment construction generous. Reach for a charcoal cashmere polo and let the cool fabric pool slightly at the cuff. Mix a dull silver ring with a matt steel watch case. Walking the dog at midnight does not mean dropping your established geometry. Evaluate the give of the material. Drop into a low crouch to check the tension across your back. The textile must move with your frame. Do not let intimate environments trick you into wearing constricting layers.",
      "sectionIntro": "Take control of low-light settings by letting your garment construction guide the room.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A quick trip to the pharmacy is no excuse to drop your standards. A morning walk to the bakery does not mean you abandon your structure. Keep your foundation constant. Always anchor your choices in balanced proportions + athletic space + one refined touch. Maintain a cool palette by pairing straight-leg washed black denim with a crisp cotton poplin shirt. Trust your own physical senses when evaluating a fit. Reach forward and test the tension across your shoulders. If the fabric catches, take the garment off immediately. Mix your metals freely across these daytime tasks. Pair a matt silver watch with a polished gold chain.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess your daily uniform as a strict test of both mobility and structure.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "You have complete freedom to mix {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} across your wardrobe. Your only constraint is clarity. Avoid hammered copper, antiqued brass, or artificially aged materials. These read as visual clutter against your cool palette. Rely instead on slick platinum, bright chrome, or highly polished white metals. Keep your buckles and clasps substantial to maintain balanced proportions. Your hardware must support an athletic space. Test every single piece. Pick up the belt or zip and drop it into your palm. The true measure of quality is absolute gravity. Trust your hands to judge the density. Combine both matt and high-shine finishes to add structural friction to your garments.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your hardware as the structural framework of your wardrobe, not an afterthought.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select {stone_1} and {stone_2} for their absolute clarity and dense light-holding structure. Assess the piece by weighing it in your hand before examining the cut. Heavy mass provides the only reliable measure of integrity. This structural density guarantees your hardware maintains balanced proportions against your layers. Avoid manufactured wear. Artificial oxidation and distressed settings introduce visual clutter to a forward-moving silhouette. Choose clean, present-tense metal bases. Freely mix polished silver, platinum, and mirror chrome to frame {stone_3}, keeping the overall temperature strictly cool. This sharp finish preserves your athletic space.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones by their density and how sharply they refract cold light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Pick up a {metal_1} watch or belt buckle and judge the piece by its physical drag. A solid, heavy item grounds an outfit built for athletic space. Lightweight, hollow pieces actively compromise your balanced proportions. Avoid artificially tarnished surfaces, hammered textures, and simulated aging. These distressed finishes register as visual clutter against a sharp, contemporary wardrobe. Demand clean, highly polished {metal_1} or brilliant {stone_1} to enforce a strict cool temperature. Rely on your hands to verify the density of the jewellery before you wear it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the physical weight test to every piece of hardware before you commit.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories deliver the one refined touch that completes your system. Once you establish balanced proportions and secure your necessary athletic space, restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start your selection with eyewear. Source an acetate frame carrying a mixed finish. Pick the frames up and apply the surface test. Pull the glasses away from your face and drop them onto a wooden table. Listen for a dense, solid impact. A hollow clatter reveals fragile construction. Rely on this physical feedback to confirm the integrity of your objects.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use these directives to evaluate and select the final objects that complete your daily uniform.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "acetate frame, mixed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Check your bag against your daily movement. Pick a technical nylon crossbody with brushed metal zips and a single polished ring. This hardware combination serves your freedom to mix metals, letting brass sit right next to cool steel. Keep balanced proportions in focus when evaluating the profile. The piece should rest flat against your ribs. Run the strap test before you buy. Lift the handle swiftly over your head. If the material catches your collar or traps your arm, abandon the item. You require immediate athletic space everywhere you move. Trust your skeletal feedback above all visual impressions. The actual weight against your body tells the truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your daily carriers purely on how they handle real friction.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "technical nylon crossbody, brushed metal zips, one polished ring"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Ground your foundation with a clean leather boot. Keep the silhouette stark with a smooth black or slate grey calfskin upper lacking excessive stitching. This profile guarantees balanced proportions against worsted wool trousers. Allow any zips or hardware to mix freely between steel and brass, preserving a distinctly cool tone throughout. Before leaving, apply the subtraction test. Remove the most prominent piece of hardware. If the outfit collapses into formlessness, put it back. If stripping that item away reveals sharper lines and grants you immediate athletic space, leave the piece on the table.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your accessories from the ground up and subject the complete assembly to a strict physical audit.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "clean leather boot, clean"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Ground your tailored pieces in structural weaves like {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_3}. Your fluid garments require adaptable motifs like {recommended_pattern_2}. Adjust your contrast levels to suit your environment. Keep the lines crisp for formal settings and blur the transitions when adapting to your community. Scale the print to maintain balanced proportions across your frame. Ensure the cut always gives you athletic space. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. They disrupt your cool palette and fight your mobility. Apply the approach test to any new print. Walk toward a mirror. A successful design reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion. If the graphic leaps off the fabric, leave the item on the rack.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate pattern purely on how it behaves while you move.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Step back three paces from the mirror to run the blur test. A cool {recommended_pattern_1} must dissolve into a pleasant texture as you shift your weight. If the motif stays rigid or demands focus, drop it. Seek balanced proportions by letting the print recede into the background of your {core_colour_1} layers. Build enough athletic space into the cut so the fabric glides with your movement. When the pattern reads simply as a soft, continuous surface rather than a distinct graphic, it passes the test.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the blur test to ensure your patterns serve the silhouette rather than dominating the eye.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_libra__moon_pisces__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "balanced proportions + blurred edges + one refined touch",
    "closing": "Rely entirely on your physical instincts to secure balanced proportions + blurred edges + one refined touch.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Train your hands to recognise friction and weight. Run your fingers over a fabric. If it catches or drags, leave it on the rack. You require materials that slip smoothly over the skin and fall into quiet, deliberate lines. Your visual baseline relies on balanced proportions + blurred edges + one refined touch. Picture a soft-shouldered wool coat layered over a fine-gauge cashmere sweater and straight trousers, finished with a single, heavy timepiece. Everything in this combination feels intentional and keeps the overarching temperature cool. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not.\n\nBuild slowly and methodically. Every piece must earn its place through exceptional construction and precise fit. Subject every garment to the host test. Picture yourself serving drinks in your own home. Reach across the table to pour a glass of water. If the shoulder pulls, if the fabric pinches, or if you feel compelled to adjust the collar, leave the piece behind. You must never feel restricted. The clothes must support your movements without requiring your attention. Keep the silhouette perfectly balanced. Reject anything that demands constant fussing. You are buying structural integrity, not just an image.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation, the set of physical operating principles you will use to evaluate every garment before it touches your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the host test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Quiet luxury requires physical substance. Your muted, cool palette demands deep textures to avoid looking flat. Apply the forearm test before buying. Drag the fabric across the inside of your arm. If the material scratches or resists, drop it. Build your foundation with {texture_good_1} for winter layers that compress and bounce back. Construct strict symmetry using {texture_good_3} for tailored coats that hold clean lines for years. Rely on {texture_good_2} for belts and shoes that mould to your shape and patinate. Finish with {texture_good_4} for fluid blouses that soften transitions and provide a solitary elegant detail. Maintain a matt surface across every garment. Seek out these specific materials to construct your baseline.",
      "sectionIntro": "The fabrics and hides that form the physical architecture of your wardrobe.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
        {
          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Trust your skin to detect failure. Slide {texture_bad_1} against the back of your neck. If it catches or feels hollow, put it down immediately. You require soft transitions to maintain your cool, muted register. {texture_bad_2} behaves in the exact opposite manner. It throws a harsh glare and refuses to drape gently. Reject any weave that feels brittle between your fingers. The finish must remain strictly matt. Harsh {texture_bad_3} builds an unyielding cage around your frame. Press every piece against your bare skin. If the thread bites, it fails completely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Certain textiles will fight your frame and disrupt your polish. Learn to identify and eliminate them on contact.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Drape the material over your knuckles to evaluate its substance. You require a cool, dense weight resting directly on the skin. If the textile feels insubstantial or immediately traps heat, leave it on the rail. Build your foundation by combining {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. This specific pairing guarantees a matt surface and muted depth. Introduce {texture_good_1} to ground the look without sharp contrast. Keep transitions soft to maintain a gentle gradient between each piece. Trust your hands. Gravity reveals the truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your exact material pairings to construct a reliable tactile foundation.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette remains strictly cool. Anchor the wardrobe in {core_colour_1}, {core_colour_2}, and {core_colour_3} to ground your symmetry. Place {core_colour_4} near the face to illuminate the complexion. Pass over hot saturated red, stark optic white, and harsh neon entirely. Trust your raw instinct when evaluating a hue. Shop lighting deceives. Overcast daylight exposes the reality. Watch for the flat sink. Layering dark matt tones upon one another can swallow you whole. Lift the outfit. Introduce {core_colour_4} at the collar, add one piece of supple leather, or step in with your relief tone as a soft note. Finish the look by pulling in {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} for your single deliberate detail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your palette with strict discipline, and you control your entire presentation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Inky navy",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep teal",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Dove grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Moonlit ivory",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Faded denim blue",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Smoked mauve",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sage grey",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Faded rose",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep berry",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Muted plum",
