        },
        {
          "name": "Soft oatmeal",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the all-earth sink: brown on olive on bark, all matt and all heavy, can swallow you whole",
          "fix": "lift it: an oatmeal cream layer at the collar, one piece of polished leather, or the washed blue relief"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, blurred edges lead your strategy. Let soft brushed wool or a dove grey cashmere layer soften the boundary between you and the room. Support this softness with absolute symmetry in your garments. Anchor the outfit with a single focal point, like a cool silver watch against an inky navy cuff. Reviewing contracts never justifies surrendering your shape to a shapeless fleece. Keep the tailoring even. Let the muted fabrics absorb the harsh overhead lighting. Pick the garment up and feel the weave. Rely on your hands. If the fabric feels rigid, leave it on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Execute your style formula in a daily professional environment.",
      "tests": [
        "paying a utility bill does not require collapsing your silhouette (Blaze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim settings, your transitions take the lead. Choose deep teal silk or brushed wool to absorb the shadows. Reach for cool silver jewellery that catches the ambient light without flashing. Pick up a thick cashmere sweater in inky navy and test the drape over your arm. The weight must pull downwards immediately. Lounging at home requires the same structural discipline as a formal dinner. Keep the look grounded in muted colours and matt weaves. Trust your grip when selecting these evening pieces. If the material feels stiff, drop it. Let a solitary element, like a white gold watch, anchor the wrist.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the precise rules of dressing for close proximity and low light.",
      "tests": [
        "paying a utility bill does not require collapsing your silhouette (Blaze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Posting a parcel at the local depot does not require abandoning your shape. Maintain your structure for mundane tasks. Your baseline mandates balanced proportions + blurred edges + one refined touch. Keep your textiles muted and your tones strictly cool. Pull on a brushed wool overcoat in deep teal. Step into full-grain leather boots. Check the collar of a dove grey silk shirt to ensure it aligns perfectly at your neck. Silver hardware provides the finish. Never suspend the standard.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your mundane routine as the primary proving ground for your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "paying a utility bill does not require collapsing your silhouette (Blaze)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your metal strategy requires a strictly cool temperature. Confine your hardware to {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Gleaming, reflective silver slices too sharply against muted textiles, creating a distracting glare. Fix this error by rejecting {excluded_finish} entirely. Demand matt or brushed textures to unify the clothing. Ensure your hardware supports garments with steady symmetry. Pick the piece up in your hand. Assess the sheer gravity of a solid metal buckle to confirm its quality. A dense steel zip dictates exactly how the fabric falls.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select metals that anchor your garments rather than competing with them.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select {stone_1} and {stone_2} that absorb light. Lift the piece in your palm to evaluate its mass. A genuine stone feels cold and heavy. Reject high-gloss surfaces and intensely faceted gems. High-shine pieces look sharp and distracting against cool cashmere, breaking your visual cohesion. Correct this error by seeking out entirely matt or heavily brushed settings. Look for an opaque {stone_3} to keep the styling grounded. This physical density anchors your symmetry. The solid opacity protects your soft boundaries. Placed deliberately, the stone acts as your one refined touch.",
      "sectionIntro": "Ground your hardware with dense, opaque stones that absorb light rather than reflect it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift every piece of jewellery or hardware off the counter. Rely on your grip to assess quality. A solid clasp proves its worth through undeniable heft. Brightly polished pieces introduce an abrasive glare against cool fabrics. A mirror surface shatters the quiet cohesion of your garments. Instead, seek out brushed or matt treatments exclusively. A dense, unpolished {metal_1} fastening or a solitary {stone_1} detail provides one refined touch without competing for attention.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply a strict physical test to every piece of hardware before it enters your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories provide the one refined touch needed to anchor balanced proportions and ground blurred edges. Hold strictly to the rule of one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with handbags. Demand full-grain leather and brushed matt hardware. Put every item through the one-ember test. Seek out a cool, steady heat, like a lone ember holding its temperature in a dark grate. If the finish glares, abandon it. Lift the bag by its strap and let the metal sink towards the floor. Rely on this density to guide you. Visuals deceive, but mass never lies.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply strict physical discipline to your final additions, demanding weight and purpose from every item.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Treat scarves as structural tools to maintain steady geometry. Pick up a length of fine wool or dense silk and check the finish. It must absorb light entirely. Demand a strictly matt texture. Wrap the fabric around your neck and run it through the shadow test. A deep teal scarf should sit against your coat as a quiet block of colour, offering a steady, cool presence rather than a sudden flash. If the material shines or reflects the room, drop it. The cloth must remain flat, heavy, and resolutely muted.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your textile additions for strict light absorption and physical weight.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select medium belts cut from heavy full-grain leather. Secure them with a simple matt buckle to maintain balanced waistlines. Reserve cool tones for your keepsake jewellery. Seek out dense links cast in aged silver or oxidised metals. These unpolished finishes offer a refined focus without disrupting your muted palette. Soften harsh visual breaks to keep your transitions intact between metal and fabric. Rely on your grip to judge a piece. The inherent heft confirms the authenticity of the cast. Before leaving, apply the glare test. Scan your reflection and strip away any piece of hardware that catches too much shine against your deep teal garments.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your final hardware with the same rigorous scrutiny you apply to your heaviest garments.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Let tailored jackets pull pattern from heavy weaves like {recommended_pattern_1}. Let your fluid pieces carry {recommended_pattern_2}. Keep the contrast tonal and low. You want to establish soft boundaries, where the motif melts into the base cloth rather than leaping off it. Run the lamplight test. Hold the fabric near a low bulb. A genuinely cool, muted print will deepen steadily in the warm glow without turning brassy. Pass over anything sharp or highly graphic. Leave {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control the scale and contrast of your prints to maintain a steady visual field.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the twilight test to any {recommended_pattern_1}. Hang the garment in a dimly lit room and step back ten paces. In fading light, the motif must dissolve entirely. If the shapes remain sharp or the contrast reads clearly across the floor, leave it on the rack. You need blurred edges. The design must sink quietly into the cool, matt background fabric. Touch the material in the dark. A dense weave grounds a subtle arrangement. Thin materials often use harsh contrast to distract the eye. Run your fingers over the cloth and feel for heavy substance.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every patterned garment to a strict visual threshold before allowing it onto your hangers.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_libra__moon_sagittarius__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "balanced proportions + fast movement + one refined touch",
    "closing": "Always let your bare hands steer you away from daily friction and directly toward balanced proportions + fast movement + one refined touch.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your physical instinct relies on zero friction. If a garment restricts your stride or requires constant adjustment, reject it outright. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Base every outfit on a strict equation of balanced proportions + fast movement + one refined touch. Picture a voluminous lower garment paired with a close-cut top layer. Add a flexible shoe built for agility. Finish the outfit with a single piece of delicate neckwear. This combination grounds your silhouette, allows you to navigate crowded spaces without hesitation, and provides a singular point of focus.\n\nCurate your wardrobe with an adaptable tempo. Gather garments slowly over time, but assemble your outfits quickly to match the day's encounters. Keep your baseline temperature cool. Rely on your hands to blend matt fabrics with high-shine surfaces instinctively. Mix your metal hardware freely. To verify your choices, apply the half-mirror test. Stand before a glass that reflects only your top half. Check if the collar sits right, the fabric falls cleanly, and your chosen detail anchors the frame. If this upper portrait feels resolved, the lower half will succeed. If it feels scattered, take it off.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this foundational logic to anchor your physical instincts before you build a single outfit.",
      "tests": [
        "the half-mirror test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your foundation on {texture_good_1} for shirting that maintains clean architectural boundaries and balanced proportions. Pair this with {texture_good_2} for close-to-body base layers offering fast movement and sharp lines. Maintain a cool temperature across these pieces to anchor your wardrobe. For the lower half, rely on {texture_good_3} for trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing. Finish with {texture_good_4} for lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind, perhaps using the garment hardware as your one refined touch. Before you buy, apply the wrist-flick test. Pick up the cuff and snap your wrist. The fabric must resettle instantly without clinging. Let the raw drape guide your final decision. Source your fabrics from the list below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Your materials must perform under active conditions while maintaining strict structural integrity.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the wrist-flick test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Run your hand over {texture_bad_1}. If it snags on your skin or creates drag, drop it immediately. You need textiles that feel cool against the skin and permit fast movement. Test the sleeve tension. Bend your elbow sharply and watch the material. If the fabric binds or feels stiff in the air, leave the piece on the hanger. Test {texture_bad_2} next. Notice how it falls. If it sticks to itself instead of slipping smoothly, it restricts your stride. Avoid any weave that feels stifling. Rely on tactile friction to guide your choices.",
      "sectionIntro": "Reject materials that fight your body.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist-flick test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Build your foundation by contrasting {sweet_spot_keyword_1} against {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. This specific friction guarantees balanced proportions and accommodates fast movement. Verify the cloth by crushing the hem in your fist. If the fabric fails to spring back instantly, drop it. Use {texture_good_1} to pull the outfit into a cool, matt finish. Introduce one refined touch to seal the look. Trust your bare hands over the mirror.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the tension between your core fabrics to build a reliable uniform.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist-flick test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your colour temperature is strictly cool. Build a practical core from {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Rely on {core_colour_3} as your crisp alternative, reserving {core_colour_4} to carve out structure at the shoulders or hem. Treat {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} as deliberate focal points. Deploy your relief tone sparingly, using it only as a soft note to break up stark blocks. Pass over Mustard, Rust, and Warm olive green entirely. Avoid the trap of untethered lightness. An entirely pale outfit appears initially pleasant but quickly fades into the background by lunch. Fix this by dropping in a sharp anchor. Add a strictly tailored jacket, a structured leather flat, or a dense {core_colour_4} layer exactly where the eye lands first. Trust your tactile response to confirm the density of these anchors. Your own physical sense of gravity is a better guide than the mirror, ensuring fast movement without your outfit feeling unmoored.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your palette by anchoring your contrasts and rejecting tones that blur your focus.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Stark navy",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Icy grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Optical white",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
