          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Kelly green",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Chalky blue",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "prettiness without anchor: all-pale, all-soft reads charming then forgettable by lunch",
          "fix": "give it one anchor: a sharply tailored blazer, a structured flat, or the gentle navy piece worn where the eye lands first"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, fast movement takes the lead. You must be able to pivot and walk without hesitation. Support this pacing with balanced proportions. Pick up a stark navy poplin shirt and pair it with icy grey worsted wool trousers to provide visual structure while keeping the silhouette close to the body. Ground the combination with solid hardware, like a cool, matt steel watch. Test every garment at the end of a long shift. If waiting in the local pharmacy queue makes you wish you chose different shoes or a looser collar, discard the piece. Professional utility never demands physical suffering. Trust your own joints and arches to dictate what stays. Mirrors deceive, but aching feet do not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your work garments as a strict system of utility and scale.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, fast movement leads. A stiff collar or rigid jacket fails. Rely on icy grey fine ribbed merino to sit close to the skin. Keep the overall temperature strictly cool. Pair dark worsted wool trousers with a fluid silk blouse. Trust your hands to check the fabric tension. If you cannot sit low on a crowded banquette in these garments without adjusting the waistband, take them off immediately. Mix your metals and finishes. Fasten a glossy platinum watch next to a flat matt bronze cuff.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the garments you rely on when the lights go down and the setting draws close.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat a morning dash to the local grocer as a strict test of your baseline. If buying fresh produce requires stiff waistbands or pinching shoes, change your clothes. Reach for technical nylon trousers and a crisp shirt in icy grey. Assess the textile by pulling the seam. Focus entirely on the density. The cut must allow a sudden sprint to catch the train. Add a mixed silver and gold watch or a single polished steel ring against the cool cotton. Whether you are running local errands or stepping out to help a neighbour, your standard remains constant. Your daily operation always demands balanced proportions + fast movement + one refined touch.",
      "sectionIntro": "Drill your everyday baseline until it operates entirely on raw instinct.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "You have the freedom to mix {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} across your jewellery and hardware. Treat these elements as structural supports for fast movement rather than simple decoration. When selecting a new buckle or clasp, pick it up and test the weight in your palm. Judge entirely by the downward pull. Substantial hardware grounds your clothing, whereas hollow alloys betray a flimsy make. Artificially aged pieces read as clutter against a present-tense style. Keep to the cool, clear strike of your primary metals and reject {excluded_finish} components entirely. Maintain balanced proportions by ensuring no single piece overwhelms the rest of the body.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your metals strictly by their weight and structural integrity.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Look for firm density and clear structure. Select a cool, solid {stone_1} or {stone_2} to bring necessary gravity to your jewellery. Pick up any item before you buy it. Your literal grip is the final judge. Volume alone means nothing. A proper stone feels heavy in the palm. If it feels hollow, leave it on the tray. Maintain your focus on balanced proportions. Dense stones allow for fast movement without flipping over or rattling against your collarbone. Pre-weathered alloys and hammered finishes register as visual noise when you need sharp efficiency. Anchor your choices in mirror-polished, untarnished hardware instead, mixing your metals freely. When you set a precise {stone_3} against a crisp collar, you create a deliberate, functional anchor.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your jewellery by its density and structural integrity to build a highly functional foundation.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Assess the mass of every item in your bare hand. True quality reveals itself through immediate physical resistance. Rely on the heavy drop of a solid piece to guide your selections. Hammered copper, antiqued brass, and artificially aged alloys generate visual clutter when you require balanced proportions. Keep your hardware firmly in the present tense. Ground your cool palette in polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome. A dense link of {metal_1} or a cold {stone_1} provides exactly the anchor you need.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate hardware by its sheer physical density before it ever touches your body.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments establish balanced proportions, while your technical nylon allows fast movement. Finish the structure by adding exactly one refined touch. Commit to the principle of one or two strong pieces per look. Before you leave, apply the too-much test. If your hardware clatters against a collaborative work table or distracts your colleagues during a meeting, strip a layer away immediately. Begin this category with eyewear. Source a cool acetate frame featuring a mixed finish. Open the arms and test the hinges. The resistance must feel solid.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate and deploy your accessories as precise functional tools to anchor your structure.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "acetate frame, mixed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the too-much test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Select a technical nylon crossbody to guarantee fast movement. Keep the hardware cool and mixed. Pair brushed metal zips with one polished ring to anchor the strap. Rely on your hands to judge the gear. A heavy strap tricks the eye, but your shoulders know the reality. Run the clearance check. Load the pockets and swing the bag across your worsted wool coat. If the buckles clank loudly or the fabric catches against your side, the design is too much. Leave it on the shelf. The bag must maintain balanced proportions against your frame. Pick pieces that support your stride.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your carrying gear strictly by how it handles the physical demands of your day.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "technical nylon crossbody, brushed metal zips, one polished ring"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the too-much test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your feet in a clean leather boot. Pick up the shoe and check the sole. Trust your hands to gauge the weight. You need a base that guarantees fast movement across city pavements. Pair a cool leather finish with your trousers to establish balanced proportions from the ground up. Now stand in front of the mirror for your exit audit. Strip away the extra layer that complicates the silhouette. If a mixed metal ring or watch feels heavy against your skin or disrupts the clean lines of your shirt, take it off.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finish your outfit with proper footwear and apply a ruthless final audit before stepping out the door.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "clean leather boot, clean"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the too-much test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored pieces pull their pattern directly from the structural weave. Fluid garments take theirs from surface print. Choose adaptable patterns that shift easily with your environment. Scale your contrast to the context, stepping from subtle tonal shifts to clearer graphics as the situation dictates. Anchor this strategy in {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Pass over anything stamped with {avoid_pattern_1} or {avoid_pattern_2}. Keep your balanced proportions intact by ensuring no single print overtakes the cut. Apply the glance test. A split-second look should register an integrated cool surface, not an isolated graphic. If a design yells its identity before the fabric registers, leave the item on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your visual noise by treating pattern as a structural element rather than applied decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the glance test (a pleasant impression rather than a specific shouting motif)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Stand ten paces back from the mirror and narrow your eyes. A proper {recommended_pattern_1} must dissolve into a unified texture. If a distinct motif jumps out, leave the hanger on the rail. You require clothing that supports fast movement through a crowd, not a static signpost. A successful design reads as a steady wash of cool colour at a passing glance. If the print snags your attention or distorts your balanced proportions by dragging the eye to a single spot, it fails the test. Pick the fabric up and drape it over your arm. Watch how the shapes behave when the cloth bends. Rely on your immediate physical reaction. If the visual noise makes you hesitate, put the piece back.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the distance test to ensure any print serves your silhouette rather than shouting over it.",
      "tests": [
        "the glance test (a pleasant impression rather than a specific shouting motif)"
      ]
    }
  },
