    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat the rainy Sunday morning walk to buy the newspaper as a strict test. If you grab a misshapen jumper, discard it. A stark navy worsted wool track trouser and a heavy icy grey jersey sweatshirt demand the identical level of scrutiny as your tailored pieces. Keep the colour palette strictly cool. Picking up a prescription at the chemist does not suspend your rules. Anchor every mundane outing in your core requirement. Your standard mandates balanced proportions + sensory comfort + one refined touch. Select garments that feel structurally sound to the fingers. A mixed stack of polished silver and matt gold rings provides that final point of focus.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your daily habits by demanding structure from your most ordinary garments.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your palette rests on a cool foundation, but your approach to hardware remains entirely unrestricted. Mix {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} freely across your jewellery and garment closures. Establishing balanced proportions between contrasting tones stops the combination from appearing chaotic. Vary your finishes, but avoid {excluded_finish} treatments entirely. Artificially aged pieces like hammered copper or stained brass introduce visual clutter to a present-tense wardrobe. Fix this by anchoring your choices in polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome. Test every clasp, buckle, and zip by lifting it before purchase. Digital images conceal poor construction. The physical density of a metal mechanism confirms its quality. Substantial hardware secures your garments properly and guarantees lasting sensory comfort. Add one refined touch with a clean, unblemished buckle.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your hardware to anchor your garments with absolute precision.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select {stone_1} and {stone_2} for their sheer clarity and strict internal geometry. These gems establish balanced proportions. Lift the jewellery from the display tray. Do not trust the shop lighting. Gauge the carat by its physical pull on your fingers. A dense cut guarantees sensory comfort against the skin and serves as one refined touch. Bypass distressed settings and cloudy inclusions outright. They register as visual noise against a crisp wardrobe. Demand pristine, highly reflective facets that keep your aesthetic climate cool. Introduce a smooth matt band to create structural contrast.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate the density and geometric clarity of your hardware before adding it to your body.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate every piece of jewellery or hardware before wearing it. A screen cannot transmit cheapness, but your hand will detect it instantly. Lift a {metal_1} buckle or a setting for {stone_1} to verify its gravity. A solid piece guarantees sensory comfort through its undeniable, cool density. Skip intentionally oxidized alloys and rough textures. Fake heritage details interrupt your clean lines. Rely instead on pristine finishes in either a high polish or a flat matt face to maintain balanced proportions and secure one refined touch.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate hardware through immediate physical mass and clear finishes.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Establish your foundation with balanced proportions and uncompromising sensory comfort. Complete the structure with one refined touch. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin your collection with silk scarves. Source a matt crepe de chine square in a cool tone to pair with stark navy layers. Since you mix metals freely elsewhere, keep this fabric finish entirely flat. Subject every combination to the subtraction principle. Dress fully, then remove the last item you added. If the silhouette collapses, restore the piece. If the collar feels cleaner without the extra weight, leave the scarf in the drawer. Let physical drag make the final decision. Heavy fabric bunched at the throat will irritate you by midday.",
      "sectionIntro": "This section outlines your finishing strategy, giving you strict rules for selecting and testing your accessories.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Select fine jewellery to secure balanced proportions across your silhouette. Pick up thin chains and narrow rings in mixed silver and gold. Pair contrasting surfaces without hesitation. Layer a polished silver pendant alongside a brushed gold band. This strict focus on thin metals keeps the overall aesthetic temperature cool and precise. Always prioritise sensory comfort. Assess your layers before you lock the front door. Unclasp any piece that catches on a technical nylon seam or pulls when you turn your head. If you hesitate, abandon the item entirely. A successful metal accessory, serving as one refined touch, must move seamlessly with your physical movements.",
      "sectionIntro": "Filter your accessory selection through strict physical mechanics.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin mixed gold and silver, mixed polished and brushed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your layout with a small structured bag to deliver one refined touch. Pick up a top-handle shape in kid suede or smooth leather. Verify the handle yields to your grip for absolute sensory comfort. Specify fine mixed hardware on the clasp or hinges. Blending silver with gold establishes a cool baseline that adapts to the rest of your components. Edit your carry before stepping out. Drop the extra pouch or heavy keychain. If the bag feels lighter and more intentional without the added clutter, leave the excess behind. Trust your own muscles to tell you when the structure achieves balanced proportions.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your assembly with strict accessory requirements and edit the result before leaving.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede or smooth leather top-handle, fine mixed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Divide your approach between structured and draped garments. Tailored items demand precision. Anchor them strictly in {recommended_pattern_1}. Fluid pieces require movement, making them the correct vehicle for {recommended_pattern_2} and {recommended_pattern_3}. Adapt your contrast levels to the specific environment. Keep the scale moderate to transition smoothly through varying settings. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. Pick up the garment and swing the fabric lightly. Evaluate the print dynamically. The motif must read as a soft, pleasant texture in motion rather than a flat graphic. If the lines stagger when the cloth shifts, the visual disruption ruins your sensory comfort. Ground approved prints against a solid, cool {core_colour_1} backdrop to establish balanced proportions and provide one refined touch.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as an architectural tool rather than mere surface decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the Pacing Test to evaluate any {recommended_pattern_1}. Step ten feet back from a mirror and walk swiftly from left to right. Watch the reflection. The design must melt into an agreeable, continuous surface in motion to serve as one refined touch. If harsh lines snag your attention or jump from the fabric, leave the garment on the rail. A passing print dissolves into soft shadow and light when you move. This optical softening secures sensory comfort for the eye. Anchor the pattern with a cool colour. Trust your bodily reaction when handling the garment. If the structure feels rigid, put it back. You achieve balanced proportions when the motif fades into the background rather than dominating the frame.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use the Pacing Test to filter out chaotic prints and measure visual volume.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_libra__moon_taurus__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "balanced proportions + sensory comfort + one refined touch",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on balanced proportions + sensory comfort + one refined touch.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Run your palm over the fabric before you check the label. Seek out the silent resistance of heavy, dense yardage and the dry finish of brushed fibres. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Your dressing strategy rests on a strict foundation of balanced proportions + sensory comfort + one refined touch. Picture a tailored trouser cut straight from the hip, paired with a fluid knit sweater, finished with a crisp, structured leather bag. This is your baseline.\n\nBuild your wardrobe slowly. Curate garments over seasons, but deploy them quickly in the morning without hesitation. When evaluating a new piece, close your eyes and feel the interior seams. If a collar bites, a sleeve pulls, or the silhouette distorts your natural frame, drop the garment immediately. Listen to that tightening in your stomach and step out the door without looking back. Do not negotiate with uncomfortable construction. A quiet, cool aesthetic demands absolute physical ease. If the structure fails your touch test, leave it on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your core operating manual, a strict set of physical laws to build your wardrobe from the ground up.",
      "tests": [
        "trust your gut and walk away"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your fabrics must pass the candlelight test. Hold a potential purchase near a soft light. If the surface throws back a sharp glare, leave it on the rail. You require a cool, matt diffusion. Look for {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Choose {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without bulk. Rely on {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Anchor your silhouette with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. These materials guarantee sensory comfort and maintain balanced proportions. Add one refined touch to finish the look. Let the weave itself dictate your choices. True quality never relies on an artificial finish. Build your foundation from the list below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your fabrics by trusting your hands and studying how a surface absorbs light.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
