    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Drop {texture_bad_1} the moment you touch it. If the weave catches against your skin or feels rough, leave it on the rack. It violates your strict demand for sensory comfort. Test {texture_bad_2} by crushing the sleeve in your fist. If the textile squeaks or fights your grip, it will sit stiffly against your frame and ruin your balanced proportions. Check the finish under harsh store lighting. You need a matt surface that completely absorbs illumination. If the fabric throws back a cheap glare, it breaks your cool aesthetic. Step away from {texture_bad_3} entirely. It creates rigid bulk where you require a soft drape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject the fabrics that compromise your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "The sweet spot requires a strict pairing. Anchor {sweet_spot_keyword_1} against {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Pick up a piece of {texture_good_1} and gauge its drape. Your fingers must confirm the contrast against a denser weave. Construct an outfit that ensures sensory comfort without sacrificing structure. Examine the garments away from direct sun. A superior textile reveals a quiet, cool depth in the shadows. A sharp shine betrays a cheap yarn. Insist on a matt surface that drinks in the ambient light. This rigorous tension secures balanced proportions.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the tension between textiles to anchor your daily choices.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Keep your overarching temperature decisively cool. Trust your immediate physical response to a dye. Mirrors deceive, but your flinch is honest. Anchor your foundation in {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_3} as your primary base neutrals. Rely on {core_colour_2} for your structural dark tailoring. Reach for {core_colour_4} whenever you require a white substitute. Deploy your relief tone sparingly as a soft note to ease the boundaries between heavy garments. Restrict your focal point to a single deliberate accent using {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Leave hard black, harsh neon, and heavy earth brown on the rack. Defaulting to a solid wall of dark clothing looks as though you surrendered to fatigue before leaving the house. Break up a flat column by fastening an {accent_colour_1} belt or draping an {accent_colour_2} wrap to guarantee balanced proportions.",
      "sectionIntro": "Filter every garment through a deliberate set of tones to build a reliable foundation.",
