    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Find your sweet spot where {sweet_spot_keyword_1} meets {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Pick up a piece of {texture_good_1}. Drape it over your forearm and observe the fall. If the material hangs lifelessly rather than rippling slightly as you move, put it back. You want textiles that acknowledge your kinetic energy. Pair that yielding softness against a cool, matt wool to construct the sharp edges your silhouette demands. This contrast builds a closed circuit of tactile feedback. Let your skin dictate the difference between responsive cloth and stiff armour.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the exact point where two contrasting textiles collide to build your signature tension.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette runs strictly cool. Rely on {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_3} as your base foundations. Establish structure with {core_colour_2} as your dark neutral, and reach for {core_colour_4} when you require a white substitute. Keep your relief tone soft, reserving it solely to break up solid blocks. Place a single deliberate accent using either {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Pass over hard black, harsh neon, and heavy earth brown. Watch out for dissolution. Piling pale gauze over pale gauze causes your silhouette to vanish entirely. Fix this error by restoring a single defining line. Add a bias-cut slip that traces the body or a tight base layer worn next to the skin. When combining weightless layers, you must maintain sharp edges to keep your form clear.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your palette as a strict boundary line, selecting shades by their precise function.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Dove grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Inky navy",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
