      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "dissolution: pale gauze on pale gauze with nothing beneath and the silhouette disappears",
          "fix": "restore one line: a bias-cut slip that traces the body, a fitted base layer, or the deep sea blue anchor worn closest to the skin"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let sharp edges lead your working hours. Start with a tailored blazer in deep teal boiled wool. The crisp shoulder line establishes a firm boundary. Support this structure with one pearl of light. A single white gold pendant resting on washed silk provides focus. Avoid any garment that demands attention during a difficult meeting. Run the pharmacy queue test before leaving the house. Visualise standing in line for a prescription at eight in the evening. If your heavy silk crepe trousers dig in or the blazer restricts your arms, take them off. The garments must hold their own shape so you do not have to. Depend on a muted, cool palette of dove grey to eliminate daily decision fatigue.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your working hours as an arena for precise calibration.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim light, sharp edges lead. Pick garments that slice cleanly through shadows rather than fading into them. Reach for a deep teal slip in heavy silk crepe and let the stark hemline define your shape. Keep jewellery muted and close to the body. A matt platinum cuff or brushed silver collar provides enough cool illumination without overwhelming the room. Subject your evening choices to a strict physical toll assessment. If you cannot sit gracefully in that dove grey gown without wincing at a stiff seam or pulling at a neckline, take it off. Suffering serves nothing. Trust your hands when deciding what to keep on. Looks lie. Weight does not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Curate your evening choices by testing how garments perform in close quarters and dim light.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A routine trip to the post office must not require suffering for an aesthetic. Construct a cool, muted palette of dove grey and deep teal to navigate mundane errands. Reach for washed silk and cloud-soft lambswool before you step outside. A boiled wool coat thrown over a fine knit gives you an insulated, practical shell. The logic holds fast regardless of the occasion. Keep your baseline grounded in weightless layers + sharp edges + one pearl of light. Inspect the drape of your trousers and the cut of your collar. Pluck a matt silver ring from your dish before leaving the house. Everyday movement demands absolute consistency.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build a functional baseline for ordinary days.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Anchor your weightless layers with dense, cool metals. Build your foundation on {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Stay entirely away from high-gloss reflections. A mirror-bright {excluded_finish} fractures your muted aesthetic, glaring harshly against your soft textiles. Demand brushed, oxidised, or frosted surfaces that absorb rather than reflect. The metal must remain matt. Before you buy any piece of jewellery, pick it up. Visuals deceive, but sheer mass never lies. Trust your palms to judge whether a belt buckle or necklace clasp possesses the heavy density required to ground your wardrobe.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hardware grounds your clothing and defines your physical boundaries.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Lift every piece of jewellery before buying. Gauge its true weight against your palm. Anchor your hardware with {stone_1} for its dense opacity. Use {stone_2} when you require deep structural grounding. Your stones must sit firm beneath your weightless layers. Highly reflective, polished settings disrupt the eye and shatter the cohesion of your cool palette. Choose exclusively brushed and matt finishes. This treatment locks your stones into your wardrobe, letting the hardware reinforce your sharp edges without fighting for attention.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your hardware as precision tools, measuring every stone for density and structural intent.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Highly polished silver creates a glaring distraction against soft, muted colours. Stick to brushed and matt textures to keep the aesthetic cohesive. Test your {metal_1} hardware by lifting it off the glass counter. Let the physical drop into your hand reveal its quality. A solid, substantial heft proves the integrity of the object. This density grounds your weightless layers. Use the unyielding metal to introduce sharp edges to the silhouette. If the item feels hollow or flimsy in your fingers, put it back down.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware through physical touch.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Construct your garment base using weightless layers. Frame the silhouette with sharp edges. Accessories provide the finishing element, serving as that crucial one pearl of light. Commit to one or two strong pieces per look to maintain a cool, deliberate focus. Begin with handbags. Demand full-grain leather or thick suede. Inspect the closures for muted, matt brushed hardware. Subject every bag to a strict density check. Lift the empty item from the shelf. If the leather feels thin enough to fold like paper, reject it entirely. Base your decisions on physical substance over visual appeal. A truly self-contained wardrobe demands tangible gravity.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control the final layer of your outfit with strict, tactile evaluations.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the float test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Constructing weightless layers demands generous silk or fine wool with a completely matt finish. Perform the float test before acquiring any scarf. Lift the textile by one corner and let go. Observe the way the fabric moves through the air. The descent speed provides a true measure of quality. If it drops heavily to the floor, leave it. If it catches the air and drifts down slowly, it works. This resistance guarantees the fabric will drape correctly, allowing you to fold it into sharp edges around the collar. Keep the temperature cool with deep teal. Reject any weave that introduces a glossy sheen.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate soft accessories by how they interact with gravity and air.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the float test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor the waist using a wide full-grain leather belt fastened with a matt brushed buckle. Avoid highly reflective finishes entirely. For keepsake jewellery, seek out a deep stone set in aged silver or oxidised brass to keep the metal temperature strictly cool. These dense materials provide necessary physical gravity beneath weightless layers. Before stepping outside, conduct a final integration check. Stand still in front of a mirror and evaluate the composition. If a heavy leather belt appears to hover apart from your frame instead of merging firmly into your sharp edges, remove it immediately. The pieces must lock together perfectly.",
      "sectionIntro": "Ground the silhouette with heavy hardware and run one final diagnostic on the composition.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the float test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored garments take their pattern directly from the loom. Look for woven structure rather than printed surface. Fluid garments take their pattern from subtle tonal shifts. Enforce a strict low-contrast tonal rule for any visible motif to maintain a cool reserve. Apply the underwater test to every print you consider. The design must read like light shifting across the seabed, never like rigid signage. Reach for {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} when selecting weightless layers. Maintain sharp edges with {recommended_pattern_3}. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. If a motif demands immediate attention or breaks the self-contained boundary of the garment, put the piece back on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as a structural element rather than a surface decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the underwater test (read like light moving on the seabed, not signage)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate {recommended_pattern_1} by stepping back and narrowing your eyes. Trust your immediate sensory reaction. The print must blur into a cool, matt shadow without clear borders. It must never broadcast legible information like a printed poster. If a motif leaps out to grab your attention, drop the garment instantly. You need patterns that dissolve into pure, receding texture. Combine these obscure shifts of tone into weightless layers. Anchor the blur by demanding sharp edges at a collar or cuff. This discipline keeps the silhouette firmly grounded.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every patterned garment to this strict visual blur test before you buy.",
      "tests": [
        "the underwater test (read like light moving on the seabed, not signage)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_pisces__moon_aquarius__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "weightless layers + mobile layers + one pearl of light",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on weightless layers + mobile layers + one pearl of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe meticulously. Deploy it without a second thought. Your compass relies entirely on weight and drape. Look for fabrics that skim the skin rather than clinging to it. Demand a cool, muted finish on every surface. Your fundamental algorithm is weightless layers + mobile layers + one pearl of light. Picture a fine-gauge knit slipping easily over a fluid undershirt. Add trousers that shift cleanly with your stride. Finish the construction with a single piece of reflective hardware at the collar or cuff. This provides the solitary point of illumination against matt textiles.\n\nTrust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not. Test every potential purchase by passing it across your inner arm. The wrist test will tell you everything you need to know about the yarn and the weave. If the fabric catches or drags on the delicate skin there, leave the garment on the hanger. A correct piece feels entirely absent once it settles on your frame. Grip the sleeve of a jacket and crush it in your fist. Watch how it recovers when you let go. It must return to a smooth state immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation, the physical baseline you must secure before adding a single accessory.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your foundation with materials that understand structure without noise. Apply the breath test to every new garment. Hold the fabric to your mouth and exhale. If the air hits a solid wall, put the hanger back. You need absolute breathability to construct weightless layers. Seek out {texture_good_1} for winter knits that compress under your grip and immediately spring back. Ground these softer elements with {texture_good_2} in your bags and belts, letting the surface wear into a cool, matt patina over years of use. For tailoring, rely on {texture_good_3} to hold a clean shoulder line. Slip {texture_good_4} underneath to create mobile layers that shift fluidly against your skin. Finish this foundation with one pearl of light at your collar, and follow this exact material hierarchy.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to filter out the impostors before a garment ever touches your skin.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
