      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Grip the hem of any piece containing {texture_bad_1} and crush it in your fist. Watch how it recovers when you let go. A brittle crunch reveals stiff threads that will ruin your cool, muted shape. Avoid {texture_bad_2} if it catches on your skin. You need textiles that shift seamlessly. Anything rigid blocks the quiet fluidity your style demands. Leave {texture_bad_3} behind if it feels dense or unyielding. Trapped heat signals poorly spun fibres. You require absolute breathability to construct weightless layers.",
      "sectionIntro": "Identify the materials that betray your physical instincts before you put them on.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to build your mobile layers. You need textiles that yield. Gather the fabric in your hands and drop it over a flat surface. It must collapse into liquid folds rather than holding its own rigid shape. This gravity check guarantees the garment will drape rather than restrict. Rely on these matt finishes to anchor your muted selections. Keep the tones strictly cool, using textural friction to generate visual interest.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your materials strictly before they touch your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Maintain a strictly cool temperature throughout. Anchor the foundation with {core_colour_1}, {core_colour_2}, and {core_colour_3}. Treat {core_colour_4} as your white substitute. Build a matt base using these shades before introducing a focal point. Use {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as that single deliberate accent. Deploy the relief tone sparingly to soften a strict combination. Pass straight over hot saturated red, stark optic white, and harsh neon. Watch for the swaddling trap. Piling shapeless pieces together causes the silhouette to dissolve entirely. Cure this by reinstating a sharp collar, a folded cuff, or letting one pearl of light rest visibly at the neckline.",
