  "venus_pisces__moon_cancer__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "weightless layers + hidden depth + one pearl of light",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on weightless layers + hidden depth + one pearl of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Anchor your wardrobe in touch. Run your fingers over the fabric before you check the construction. You are looking for a cool, dry hand and a fluid drape that moves silently over the skin. Your operating logic is weightless layers + hidden depth + one pearl of light. Picture a sheer, tissue-fine inner layer slipped under a dense, soft overshirt, finished with a single, softly glowing pendant resting just above the collarbone. Keep the silhouette close but entirely unrestrictive. The garments must serve your need for absolute self-containment.\n\nBuild this foundation with absolute patience, then dress rapidly from instinct. Apply the melt test to every potential purchase. Drape the piece over your forearm and close your eyes. The item must dissolve into your personal architecture instantly. It should feel like a quiet extension of your body rather than a rigid external cage. If the cloth catches, creates friction, or demands constant adjustment, leave it on the hanger. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural logic, the sensory baseline that dictates how your garments must feel and function.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe from materials that create weightless layers and keep your silhouette self-contained. Seek out {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen fades to a matt candlelight. Add {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without mass. Look for {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Anchor the system with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. When assessing a new piece, perform the breath test. Hold the fabric against your mouth and exhale sharply. If the air bounces back, the garment will trap heat and disrupt your cool equilibrium. If the breath passes directly through, trust the material. Evaluate your options using the ranked list below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every new garment by the physical reality of how the fabric behaves in your hands.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed alpaca",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "enveloping winter coats and oversized cardigans"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fluid modal jersey",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers that follow the body without ever gripping it"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed cotton flannel",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "shirts and loungewear that feel like a remembered embrace"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Test every garment against your skin. Reject any piece that fails the breath test. If the fabric traps your heat instead of letting the air pass through, leave it on the rail. This stifling sensation is the physical tell of {texture_bad_1}. Trust your hands when they encounter {texture_bad_2}. If the surface feels slick or rigid, it will never yield. Reject {texture_bad_3} entirely. When you touch it, the coarse threads push back against your fingers. You require materials that drape cleanly and offer cool comfort. Look for a matt surface that supports one pearl of light. Do not compromise on this.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands and skin to instantly identify and reject hostile materials.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to establish quiet tension. This pairing gives you control without raising your voice. Trust your hands over your eyes. Pick up a piece of {texture_good_1} and assess the density. Test the cloth against your lips. A weave that lets air pass too freely lacks the necessary structure. You require solid, matt textiles to achieve a self-contained finish. Keep surfaces muted and tones cool. Build your outfits with hidden depth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your weave combinations to dictate how a piece performs.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your temperature is cool. Establish a matt base with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_3}. Define the perimeter using {core_colour_2}, and let {core_colour_4} act as your primary focal point. Introduce your deliberate accent strictly through {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Apply your relief tone purely as a soft note used sparingly to separate dense blocks of colour. Combine these precise shades to form weightless layers. Pass over hard black, harsh neon, and heavy earth brown. Watch for the comfort trap. Yielding to total softness strips away all form, reducing your clothing to pyjamas. Counteract this by reinstating a single strict boundary. Select a structured leather bag, a true rolled lapel, or a trouser bearing a distinct crease to provide hidden depth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Keep your colour foundation strict and your tones precisely calibrated.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Dove grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Inky navy",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep teal",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Oyster",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Pale aqua",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Smoked mauve",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Faded rose",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep berry",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft oatmeal",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the sofa drift: soften every piece far enough and one day you are simply in loungewear",
          "fix": "restore exactly one line: a rolled but real lapel, a trouser with a soft crease, or a firm leather bag against all that give"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At the desk, hidden depth leads your strategy. Build an opaque, self-contained base in cool dove grey or deep teal. Support this central core with featherweight, stacked pieces of washed silk. These airy additions construct an external shell. Finish the approach with a single point of brightness. A muted platinum lapel pin provides this final illumination quietly. Consider your weekend trip for artisan bread a deliberate event. If an item lacks the discipline required to select winter squash on a Sunday morning, do not put it on to negotiate a contract on a Tuesday. Maintain this exact standard everywhere. Keep your shapes absolute and your surfaces strictly matt.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your style logic to the rigorous demands of the working day.",
      "tests": [
        "a farmers' market run is still a small occasion (Hearth)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In low-light settings, let hidden depth take the lead. A quiet morning walk to the florist is still a small occasion. Dress for it. Choose garments that reward close scrutiny rather than projecting across a space. Select heavy silk crepe in deep teal to absorb ambient illumination. Notice how a cool, matt finish draws the eye inward. Avoid high-shine materials that reflect glare. Pick up a piece of washed silk in dove grey and observe its soft shadow. Keep the details reserved solely for the person standing next to you.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat intimate settings as an invitation to pull the eye inward with muted surfaces.",
      "tests": [
        "a farmers' market run is still a small occasion (Hearth)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A Saturday trip for fresh vegetables remains a deliberate visual choice. A morning run to the pharmacy does not grant you permission to abandon your aesthetic baseline. Look for garments that do the work for you on quiet mornings. Put on a cloud-soft lambswool jumper in a cool deep teal and an unstructured dove grey coat. Rely on these pieces to uphold your standard when you step out for milk. Avoid grabbing random cotton jersey just because it is early. Your daily movement demands exact adherence to your equation. Maintain weightless layers + hidden depth + one pearl of light as your constant rule.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat every mundane errand as a strict drill in your daily mechanics.",
      "tests": [
        "a farmers' market run is still a small occasion (Hearth)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your hardware runs exclusively cool. Rely on {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} across the board. Gauge every chain or buckle by its heft in your hand. The object must feel substantial. Highly polished {metal_1} cuts harshly against muted tones like {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}, becoming a sharp distraction. Restrict your jewellery and hardware to {excluded_finish} or strictly matt textures. A brushed surface absorbs ambient glare. This choice grounds the palette and builds the hidden depth your aesthetic demands.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your metals with the same physical scrutiny you apply to your heaviest textiles.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Choose your stones for their sheer physical density. An opaque cut of {stone_1} or a cabochon of {stone_2} must sit remarkably heavy in your palm. This raw mass anchors your soft textiles. Avoid brilliant facets that pierce your cool, muted baseline. Select matt or brushed settings to maintain a seamless continuity. Let a single, dense stone act as your one pearl of light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your subdued palette with stones selected strictly for their physical density and muted opacity.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Let gravity make your final decisions. A heavy {metal_1} cuff or solid {stone_1} pendant grounds your outfit, while flimsy materials betray themselves instantly. High-gloss hardware fractures the quiet continuity of your wardrobe. A mirror polish cuts too sharply into muted, cool fibres, pulling focus from the whole. Rely on matt and brushed {metal_1} to maintain cohesive harmony. A softened surface absorbs light rather than bouncing it. It builds hidden depth without resorting to a distracting flash.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware by its physical mass before you put it on.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You have arranged your weightless layers. You have secured your hidden depth. Now, finish the look with one pearl of light. Hold to the rule of one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with handbags. Seek out full-grain leather or thick suede, accented only by cool, matt brushed hardware. Subject every piece to the ripple test. Set the empty bag on a table and watch how it settles. If the material breaks into rigid angles, leave it behind. It must collapse into heavy, rolling waves. Rely entirely on your tactile instincts to gauge quality.",
      "sectionIntro": "Accessories demand ruthless discipline. They must punctuate your silhouette without disturbing its quiet foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Assess your scarves strictly by material and finish. Demand generous silk or fine wool with a completely matt surface. Perform a drape check. Drop the fabric onto a flat table and watch it pool like poured liquid. If the textile catches the light or holds a rigid fold, leave it on the shelf. You need these exact textiles to stack weightless layers without adding bulk. Select cool tones like deep teal or dove grey to build hidden depth close to the collar. Secure the cloth with a small platinum pin.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply strict material standards to the elements that sit closest to your face.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Source a wide full-grain leather belt finished with a matt brushed buckle. Fasten it to ground your weightless layers. For keepsake jewellery, seek out a deep stone set in oxidised silver or aged brass. These dense, cool metals create an anchor of hidden depth against your skin. Before stepping out, stand before the mirror and check your silhouette. If a metal edge interrupts the fluid line of your garments or sends a harsh shadow through the visual calm, take it off. Every piece must sit like a smooth stone in a still pool, completely undisturbed.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finish the look by testing your final structural additions for perfect visual silence.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "When introducing print, enforce a strict low-contrast tonal rule. Tailored pieces pull their pattern directly from the woven thread. Fluid garments carry the printed motif. Apply the dusk test. Observe the piece as the light drops in a dim room. The pattern must settle into a cool, moving shadow. If it sharpens into a jarring distraction, leave it on the rail. Rely on {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} to anchor your selections. These motifs support weightless layers and offer hidden depth without shouting. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} completely. Look for muted, self-contained repetition.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control the visual noise of your garments by choosing motifs that whisper rather than shout.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Examine any printed garment in fading daylight before buying. Hang a piece featuring {recommended_pattern_1} in a dim space, step back, and squint. Look for a motif that dissolves entirely. The design must lose its rigid borders and melt into a soft, cool texture in the shadows. If the shapes remain distinct in low light, the contrast is too harsh. Leave the item on the rail. You require prints that retreat into the background. Build your weightless layers from patterns that blur into quiet obscurity when evening sets in.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every potential print to a strict test of low-light legibility.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_pisces__moon_capricorn__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "weightless layers + softness + one pearl of light",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on weightless layers + softness + one pearl of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your tactile instinct to judge every garment. Pick it up and weigh it in your hands. If it feels heavy, rigid, or restrictive, leave it on the rail. You require pieces that float rather than bind. Your visual anchor is your core formula of weightless layers + softness + one pearl of light. Build this with a sheer, fine-gauge base under a fluid knit, anchoring the arrangement with a single point of subtle, cool luminescence at your collarbone. Let the layers drift around your frame without clinging.\n\nApply the host test to every new acquisition. Ask yourself who is hosting whom. If a piece requires constant adjustment, dictates your posture, or projects outward for an audience, it has become the host. You are the host. The garments must serve your absolute physical autonomy and allow you to remain entirely self-contained. Curate your collection slowly over seasons, but assemble your outfit swiftly each morning. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your architectural foundation, the strict physical laws that dictate how every garment you own must behave.",
