    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Select generous silk or fine wool scarves with a strictly matt finish. Hold the fabric and trust your hands to verify the pure softness of the material. A stiff edge betrays cheap production. Disregard the showroom mirror and focus purely on how the cloth falls. Subject every piece to the focal-point test. Look for a solitary, contained point of intensity, perhaps a single thread of cool silver through dove grey, that serves you alone. Avoid blazing patterns that signal to the entire room. Seek out textiles that gather quietly at the neck to anchor your silhouette in self-contained luxury.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply strict rules of texture and physical restraint to select your final accent pieces.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your weightless layers with a wide full-grain leather belt. Scrutinise the hardware. You require a matt brushed silver buckle. Treat keepsake jewellery with the same strict restraint. Pick out a deep lapis lazuli stone set in oxidised silver or aged brass. These heavy pieces ground the physical softness of your garments. Stand before your wardrobe and execute a final check. Strip away extra items until only one pearl of light remains against your cool clothing.",
      "sectionIntro": "Secure your garments with dense hardware and perform a strict final edit.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor tailored garments with structural woven motifs. Fluid pieces require subtle repetition to maintain your weightless layers. Enforce a strict low-contrast tonal rule for every print you consider. A faint {recommended_pattern_1} or a muted {recommended_pattern_2} serves you better than a disruptive {avoid_pattern_1}. Pass over any design that announces itself from across a street. Judge the textile by how it behaves in reality. Subject the piece to the shadow test. Bring the patterned silk or brushed wool close to a heavy lamp. Watch how its cool tones deepen and warm by lamplight without losing their self-contained subtlety. If the motif flattens into a harsh grid, drop the hanger. Superior construction weaves the design directly into the fibre.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control the visual noise of your garments by selecting prints that function as woven texture.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the firelight test to {recommended_pattern_1}. Carry the garment into a dim space lit only by a warm bulb. A successful print absorbs that golden glow while retaining a distinctly cool temperature. It must hold its matt finish and subdued contrast even when the light tries to heat it up. If the edges of the design suddenly jump forward, drop the piece. Trust your immediate discomfort when a pattern breaks its boundaries. Seek out absolute softness in every line. Stack weightless layers over a pattern that stays perfectly self-contained in the shadows.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject your patterns to an environmental stress test before you buy.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_pisces__moon_gemini__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "weightless layers + light movement + one pearl of light",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on weightless layers + light movement + one pearl of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your hands. Pick up a garment and test its drift. If the material feels stiff or dense, put it back. You require garments that slip across the skin like cool water. Your baseline requires physical restraint and a balanced silhouette. Your formula is weightless layers + light movement + one pearl of light. Picture a finely spun base layer worn beneath an unlined, fluid coat, finished with a single point of luminosity at the collarbone.\n\nBuild your collection deliberately and assemble your outfits fast. Apply the decade test before you acquire any piece. Look at the proportions in the mirror and ask if the cut would have made sense ten years ago and if it will still work ten years from now. If the shape is anchored to a passing season, take it off. Demand matt surfaces that absorb the ambient light. Find the precise midpoint between structure and drape. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is the structural logic of your wardrobe, the absolute baseline you must return to when an outfit feels unresolved.",
      "tests": [
        "the decade test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe on fabrics that deliver weightless layers and light movement. Seek out {texture_good_1} for knitwear that compresses under pressure and springs back. Anchor these soft pieces with {texture_good_2} accessories that mould to your habits and develop a matt patina. For structured garments, choose {texture_good_3}. It holds sharp lines across tailored coats while maintaining a cool, muted finish. Slip {texture_good_4} underneath for blouses that provide a fluid drape, treating this final layer as your one pearl of light. Always verify the friction before you buy. Slide the material between your thumb and forefinger. Reject the piece if the surface catches against your skin. Choose your foundation from the hierarchy below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Trust your hands to evaluate the integrity of every garment before you look at the price tag.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
        {
          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "if a fabric resists your touch or feels squeaky between your fingers, leave it behind"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Rely entirely on tactile feedback. If {texture_bad_1} fights your grip or squeaks under your thumb, drop it immediately. Rigid {texture_bad_2} fails this test because it refuses to yield. It sits artificially against the skin and completely restricts the light movement your frame requires. Insist on a cool, matt finish for your foundations. Avoid {texture_bad_3} that traps heat or snaps back unnaturally when stretched. Heavy, inflexible fibres build stiff cages rather than fluid silhouettes.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test every cloth in your hands before it touches your body.",
      "tests": [
        "if a fabric resists your touch or feels squeaky between your fingers, leave it behind"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Pinch the cloth before you try it on. If the warp pushes back or whistles under pressure, walk away. You need elements that drape silently over the body. Your sweet spot marries {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Combine these smooth weaves to construct weightless layers, letting them slide together without catching. Introduce {texture_good_1} for a cool contrast that anchors the shape. Let your fingertips judge the difference.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your core pairings to build a silhouette that flows without friction.",
      "tests": [
        "if a fabric resists your touch or feels squeaky between your fingers, leave it behind"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your temperature is strictly cool. Build the foundation from {core_colour_1}, {core_colour_2}, and {core_colour_3}. Replace glaring brights entirely with {core_colour_4}. Inject {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} only as intentional focal points. Deploy your relief tone in small doses to soften strict edges. These muted shades anchor your weightless layers and provide a canvas for light movement, culminating in exactly one pearl of light. Pass over Hot saturated red, Stark optic white, and Harsh neon. Identify the trap of metallic excess. Inspect every zip and clasp. Restrict shine to a single molten detail, forcing every other hardware piece to remain tiny, matt, and purely structural.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your palette by assigning strict functional roles to every shade.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Inky navy",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep teal",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Dove grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Moonlit ivory",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Faded denim blue",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Smoked mauve",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sage grey",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Faded rose",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep berry",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Muted plum",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft oatmeal",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "gilt overload: grandeur tips into gaudiness",
          "fix": "hold the line at one molten flash and keep every other metal moment small, matt, and supporting"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, light movement takes the lead. Direct focus by securing a single cool silver pin to an inky navy brushed wool jacket. Support this ease with weightless layers. A dove grey silk blouse provides necessary fluidity beneath the dense tailoring. Defeat a freezing morning commute in cashmere by relying on the drop of the fabric rather than bulk. Squeeze the cuff of a deep teal shirt. If the material feels stiff, discard it. Choose matt platinum rings to keep the metals muted, allowing one pearl of light to centre the silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Construct your working wardrobe by relying entirely on strict tactile feedback and structural precision.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, dim rooms flatten your shape. Counter this with weightless layers of silk that shift naturally as you breathe. Wear a deep teal silk blouse or an inky navy cashmere wrap to encourage light movement. Let the drape dictate the silhouette. A cool silver cuff reflects candlelight, serving as your one pearl of light. Keep the finish matt and muted so the gleam comes from within the weave, not a polished surface. Preserve your structural balance on casual evening walks by pairing a full-grain leather jacket over a dove grey cashmere jumper.",
      "sectionIntro": "Mastering intimate evenings requires adjusting your fabric choices for low light.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Routine errands demand the same careful proportion. Anchor your weekend routines on weightless layers + light movement + one pearl of light. Drape a brushed wool jacket over a silk shirt to buy groceries. Brush your fingers across the cashmere to check its drape before dressing. Leave resistant fabrics on the hanger. A cool charcoal jumper paired with a soft silver chain establishes a comfortable baseline. Maintain this strict discipline daily.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat every ordinary errand as a strict test of your baseline rules.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Build your jewellery collection around cool tones. Adopt {metal_1} as your primary anchor. Introduce {metal_2} and {metal_3} when you require subtle variation. Avoid highly polished hardware. Mirrored surfaces clash abruptly against your soft palette. Select matt and brushed finishes to preserve cohesion. Exclude {excluded_finish} entirely to prevent unwanted glare. Weigh each piece in your palm to measure its solid density. Ensure your chains are delicate enough to sit perfectly beneath weightless layers without dragging the textile out of shape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware with the same strict criteria you apply to textiles.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Seek gems with low clarity that trap illumination inside. Target {stone_1} and {stone_2} for their cool density. Assess their mass before making a purchase. Empty, hollow settings have no place in your collection. A dense stone introduces light movement against a muted {core_colour_1} textile. Avoid high-shine chrome mountings that cut harshly against your soft wardrobe. Glossy, polished silver splinters the cohesive look of your garments. Demand a matt or brushed metal surface to maintain unity. Wear {stone_3} to anchor the outfit.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your gems by their physical mass and how they hold light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Scrutinise every clasp, chain, and buckle before you commit. A substantial {metal_1} fastening grounds the garment without stiffening your silhouette. It serves as a necessary anchor for your weightless layers. Watch out for high-shine hardware. Highly polished metals act like small mirrors. They fracture the visual calm of a muted, cool palette and distract from the overall shape. Stick strictly to a matt finish or brushed textures. A brushed {metal_1} closure integrates seamlessly into the fabric.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware physically to ensure it serves the garment rather than fighting it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories provide the one pearl of light. They ground the drape of your weightless layers, offering a fixed point against the continuous light movement of your garments. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with handbags crafted from dense full-grain leather. Look for brushed matt hardware that remains cool to the touch and absorbs the ambient light of the room. Evaluate the generational value before acquiring any new item. Run your fingers over the strap and the metal clasp to measure the raw density. If the object feels like it could have waited silently in a dark dressing table for a century and still emerge perfectly formed today, keep it. Otherwise, leave it behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Accessories demand ruthless editing and strict physical criteria to anchor your silhouette.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the heirloom test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Focus on scarves woven from pure silk or fine wool. Inspect the surface to ensure the finish remains entirely matt. Pick the item up, close your eyes, and test the drape. It must provide unhindered light movement. Let these exact fibres build weightless layers across your shoulders. Gauge the historical endurance of the material. Ask yourself if a descendant could pull this cool textile from a cedar chest fifty years from now and instantly recognise its superior quality by touch alone. If the fabric catches on your skin or resists forming a fluid knot, put it back.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your woven accessories using strict physical standards.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the heirloom test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your belts in medium full-grain leather finished with a cool, matt buckle. Secure any keepsake jewellery in aged, oxidised silver. Let these dense metals sink into the cloth rather than sit on top. Rely on this solid weight to ground the light movement of your garments. Conduct a final check before you finish dressing. Ask yourself if the piece carries the profound heft of an antique. If it feels like a hollow trend stamped out yesterday, take it off immediately. Trust the sheer gravity of the metal to confirm its worth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Secure your layers with grounding hardware and run a strict final check.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the heirloom test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Treat pattern as an extension of the weave. Tailored garments draw their pattern from the internal geometry of the yarn itself. Fluid garments carry prints that shift and pool. To anchor weightless layers, insist on low tonal contrast. Ensure every motif sits in a cool, muted register. Demand {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Reject {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. Perform a visual distance test on any new print. Step back and squint at the fabric. A correct design settles into a natural terrain, blurring like the surface of a distant hillside. Pass over stark borders and rigid grids because high contrast destroys subtlety. A proper pattern introduces light movement, letting the eye travel across the garment without snagging on a harsh graphic. Strong geometric blocks always read as flat.",
      "sectionIntro": "Read the surface of the cloth, seeking subtle structure rather than immediate distraction.",
      "tests": [
        "the field test (settle into a natural texture like ground seen from a hill)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Stand three paces back from the garment and narrow your eyes. A successful {recommended_pattern_1} will soften into a unified, muted surface. The print must blur into a natural grain, settling into a texture that resembles the earth seen from a high ridge rather than a sharp geometric grid. Hard borders disrupt the eye. Look for motifs that dissolve gracefully at their edges. Support weightless layers by choosing prints that share this atmospheric quality. If the contrast remains stark or highly legible from ten feet away, leave the piece on the rail. Seek out this gentle dissolution to guarantee the pattern integrates with your cool garments instead of competing for focus.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every printed fabric to the landscape distance test before you commit to a purchase.",
      "tests": [
        "the field test (settle into a natural texture like ground seen from a hill)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_pisces__moon_leo__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "weightless layers + athletic space + one pearl of light",
    "closing": "Let your physical instincts dictate every garment you acquire, securing a wardrobe built entirely on weightless layers + athletic space + one pearl of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your physical compass is the sensation of absolute zero resistance. Pick up a garment and test its drape. If it drags, feels restrictive, or carries heavy visual noise, put it back. You require cool, matt surfaces that glide over the skin without trapping heat or catching light. Your binding formula is weightless layers + athletic space + one pearl of light. Picture a translucent, tissue-weight top slipped over a clean, technical trouser. The fabric stands away from your body to provide total freedom of movement. You finish this structure with a single point of luminosity at the collarbone.\n\nBuild this wardrobe slowly. Vet every piece for strict geometric balance and zero friction. Once assembled, deploy your outfits fast and drift by mood. Do not overthink the combination on the day. Trust your gut and walk away if a piece requires adjustment or constant tending in the fitting room. If you feel compelled to tug at a hem or fix a seam, the garment has failed you. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this foundational logic to calibrate your physical instincts before you acquire another garment.",
      "tests": [
        "trust your gut and walk away"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Construct your wardrobe using materials that preserve your athletic space. Run every new piece through the melt test. Pick up the garment and crush it in your fist. If the material fights your grip with stiff resistance, drop it. It must yield into your palm completely. Build your foundation with {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to a matt candlelight. Add {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter you, forming true weightless layers. Seek {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Finish with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge, keeping your silhouette cool and grounded.",
      "sectionIntro": "Stock your wardrobe with materials that pass your physical tests and build your core structure.",
      "rankedItems": [
