    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Anchor your cool wardrobe exclusively with {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. High-shine {excluded_finish} slices too sharply across soft, muted fabrics. It creates a glaring, distracting focal point. Stick strictly to brushed, antiqued, or matt surfaces to keep the entire system unified. Weigh every chain, zip, and buckle in your palm before acquiring it. A flimsy, hollow clasp completely undermines the integrity of your weightless layers. You require dense, cast metal that drops heavily into your hand.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your hardware as structural architecture, selecting metals that support rather than distract.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "When selecting stones and metal, focus on elements that ground the weightless layers of your garments. Choose dense, opaque materials like {stone_1} or {stone_2} in cool settings. Avoid high-shine silver. A mirror polish will cut sharply against muted fibres and shatter the visual cohesion. Stick strictly to brushed or matt finishes to absorb light rather than reflect it. Evaluate every {stone_3} by its physical presence. Pick the item up and test it in your palm. Rely on your internal physical gauge to verify quality. If a piece feels hollow or fails to register heavily in your grip, leave it in the display case.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply strict criteria for density and finish to all hardware.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Hold every {metal_1} cuff or {stone_1} ring in your palm before you put it on. A solid piece sinks against your skin and anchors your weightless layers. Leave hollow items on the counter. Watch out for a highly polished surface. Mirror finishes create a sharp distraction against a {core_colour_1} washed silk shirt and break the quiet harmony of your clothing. Require a cool, matt or sandblasted finish to absorb the glare and maintain your muted lane.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply a strict physical filter to every piece of hardware.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your foundation relies on weightless layers and athletic space. Accessories deliver the final element. They provide that one pearl of light. Apply a strict quota to these additions. A single strong piece anchors an outfit. Before you walk out the door, drop the extra item pulling focus. A solitary, deliberate choice does the work. Begin with handbags. Demand thick full-grain leather. Scrutinise the metal details. They must feature cool, brushed matt hardware. Judge every bag by its physical heft. A well-constructed handle drops with undeniable gravity.",
      "sectionIntro": "Approach your accessories as structural anchors, selecting only the essential elements to finish your look.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Limit scarves to pure silk or ultra-fine wool in a completely matt finish. Run the fabric through your fingers. It must pool like water without catching the glare. A dove grey or deep teal length of fabric adds vital insulation while protecting your weightless layers. Always pause at the mirror before finishing your routine. Remove the accessory that tips the balance. A solitary anchor secures the entire composition. Any additional detail competing for attention is simply noise.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your neckwear using the precise material logic you apply to your garments.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor garments with medium full-grain leather belts finishing in a completely matt buckle. Treat keepsake jewellery with similar strictness. Select rings and pendants cast in aged silver or deeply oxidised metals. Pick up these items and feel their cool density. Let this physical pressure serve as your definitive guide. Perform a strict subtraction test before moving on. Unfasten the clasp that demands too much attention. If an oxidised cuff disrupts your weightless layers, take it off immediately. One quiet anchor is enough.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your final finishing logic to functional accessories and strip away the excess.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored garments draw their pattern entirely from the woven fibre. Fluid pieces accept print, provided the execution remains strictly low-contrast and tonal. Test a graphic by stepping away from the glass and letting your vision blur. If the motif does not dissolve into a continuous cool texture, reject it. Look for {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Pass over anything sharply defined. Leave {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} on the rack entirely. Intricate illustrations disrupt the athletic space you establish with your silhouettes. Inspect {recommended_pattern_3} blindly. The weave must feel integrated and flat, never stiff.",
      "sectionIntro": "Approach pattern as a structural element rather than decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "step back and soften focus (blur into texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the ten-pace test to protect your athletic space. Hang a garment featuring {recommended_pattern_1} on a door. Step back across the room and let your eyes drop out of focus. A successful print must collapse into a cool, continuous texture. It should read like the natural variation in boiled wool, never as an isolated drawing. If the shapes stay sharp and legible from a distance, leave the item on the rack. The right design melts into a muted background. Rely on this optical shift. It prevents dense graphics from compromising your outline.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every print to a strict visual test to guarantee it serves as texture rather than distraction.",
      "tests": [
        "step back and soften focus (blur into texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_pisces__moon_pisces__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "weightless layers + blurred edges + one pearl of light",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on weightless layers + blurred edges + one pearl of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the sensation of cool air against your skin as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not. Rely on the physical experience of dressing rather than the image in the mirror. Your blueprint is weightless layers + blurred edges + one pearl of light. Picture a fine-gauge knit draped over a fluid slip dress, finishing with a single small stud catching the light near your face. Ensure the hemline diffuses rather than cutting sharply across your frame. The transition between garments must remain imperceptible. Every piece must sit softly without restricting your breath or binding your shoulders.\n\nBuild your collection slowly, but deploy your outfits fast. This requires a ruthless curation of proportion and drape. Apply the host test to every new acquisition before you purchase it. Ask yourself if you can pour a glass of water, lean across a dining table, and serve a meal without adjusting a single seam. If you have to tug at a collar, adjust a sleeve, or smooth a pleat, leave the garment on the hanger. Your clothes must operate flawlessly in the background. If a piece requires constant management or styling tricks to maintain its shape, it fails the test.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your structural blueprint and set your physical limits for every garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the host test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe demands materials that support weightless layers and blurred edges. Trust your hands to find them. Apply the puddle test. Pick up the fabric and let it pool in your palm. If it feels rigid, drop it. It must dissolve into a soft puddle. Seek out {texture_good_1} for knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back. Look for {texture_good_3} for tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years. For bags, shoes, and belts, select {texture_good_2} that will mould to your life and patinate. Rely on {texture_good_4} for blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement. A matt, cool finish across these materials builds the foundation for your one pearl of light. Memorise this priority list.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the materials that build your wardrobe before you even check a label.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
        {
          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Drape the garment over your forearm. True luxury materials dissolve into your cool palette and soften against the skin. If {texture_bad_1} feels rigid or creates a sharp, unyielding boundary, it fails the puddle test. It will sit as an inflexible shell, disrupting your weightless layers. Avoid {texture_bad_2} entirely. Rub the fabric between your thumb and index finger. If it feels slick, synthetic, or reflects a hard glare, drop it. Your finish must remain matt. Trust your fingers to detect tension immediately. A textile must yield entirely. Cameras trick the eye, but gravity reveals the flaw.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify and reject the materials that fight your natural balance before they even touch your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Seek out the intersection of {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Combine them to construct continuous, blurred edges from collar to hem. Assess this physical union. Drop your palm down your sleeve to your trouser leg. The two surfaces must yield and soften into one another. If your hand catches on a stiff boundary or a harsh seam, take the piece off. Pair {texture_good_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to test this principle. The resulting surface feels cool and cohesive. Rely on this tactile feedback to guide your choices. Sensation tells the truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Combine your surfaces to enforce absolute physical cohesion.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor everything with your foundation colours. Construct your base using {core_colour_1}, {core_colour_2}, and {core_colour_3}. Treat {core_colour_4} as your true illuminating neutral. Inject focus with {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2}. Introduce your soft relief tone strictly to break up uniformity. Your defining temperature is absolutely cool. Pass over piercing saturated red, stark optic white, and harsh neon. Beware the heavy earth trap. Stacking dense, matt shades without light will drag you down. Lift the arrangement immediately. Place {core_colour_4} at the neckline, incorporate one piece of polished leather, or apply your soft relief tone to create space. Always build towards one pearl of light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your assigned palette as a strict set of parameters to eliminate guesswork.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Inky navy",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep teal",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
