      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Reject {texture_bad_1}. Pick it up and notice how the stiff weave scratches against your skin. It builds a rigid shell instead of yielding to your movement. Discard {texture_bad_2} the moment you touch it. The synthetic finish traps heat and feels entirely dead in the hand. Examine any questionable textile under a single weak lamp. If the thread throws back a harsh shine instead of absorbing the shadows, it fails. That glare shatters your silhouette. You require matt absorption. Leave {texture_bad_3} on the rack if it holds rigid structure. You need pieces that drape in absolute silence.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise and reject the textiles that disrupt your quiet presentation.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Seek the exact tension between {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Build your outfit with weightless layers that feel cool to the touch. Before you buy a piece of {texture_good_1}, hold the material against the window at dusk. The surface must absorb the fading light and return only a subtle, matt glow. If it flashes back a harsh shine, drop it. Pair these quiet surfaces to construct a completely self-contained shape. Your fingers easily recognise the difference between cheap gloss and true structural depth. Rely on that tactile truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your signature tactile combination.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette sits firmly on the cool side of the spectrum. Anchor your garments in {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_3}. Ground the silhouette with {core_colour_2}, and use {core_colour_4} for illumination. Reserve {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} as your singular deliberate accents. Deploy your soft relief tone strictly to interrupt a dense monochromatic block. Pass over hard black, harsh neon, and heavy earth brown. Beware the muddy woodland trap. Stacking flat, matt moss and bark tones creates a dense mass that swallows your frame. Break this visual sink instantly. Place a pale cream knit at the collar, integrate a brushed leather belt, or drop in your relief tone. Sight deceives, but physical drape does not. Assemble these elements into weightless layers with blurred edges, finishing with one pearl of light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your palette as a strict architectural code, assigning every tone a distinct job.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Dove grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
