          "fix": "lift it: an oatmeal cream layer at the collar, one piece of polished leather, or the washed blue relief"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let blurred edges lead your work uniform. Avoid rigid tailoring. A stiff worsted blazer drains your physical energy. Choose a heavy silk crepe jacket with soft, unconstructed shoulders. Support this silhouette with cloud-soft dove grey lambswool underneath. Finish the look with a single, clear focal point. A cool matt silver cuff or a deep teal enamel ring directs the eye. Apply the desk test before leaving the house. Sitting stationary for a three-hour meeting requires the exact same ease as resting on a sofa. If a stiff collar interrupts your focus, leave the garment on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Construct a work uniform that protects your physical focus rather than performing for an audience.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, soft transitions take the lead. Dim lighting flattens stiff construction. Rely on heavy silk crepe and washed silk in deep teal to absorb the shadows. Keep your metals cool and matt. A white gold ring with an unpolished sapphire provides enough quiet reflection for a restaurant table. Do not dial up the contrast for the evening. Pouring a glass of water in your kitchen at midnight demands the same uncompromising softness as a formal dinner. Assess the truth of a weave by rolling it between your thumb and forefinger. Rigid construction reveals itself immediately to the touch. If a seam scratches your neck, leave it behind. You need fine knits that shape around your collarbone without a sound.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control the tactile mechanics of intimate dressing.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Apply your strict standards to the quietest moments of your week. A rainy Sunday walk for the papers demands the exact same gentle construction as a formal appointment. Never suspend your rules just because an errand is brief. If you are stepping out to collect a prescription, reach for a cool dove grey boiled wool jacket instead of unconsidered athletic gear. Trust your hands to seek out cloud-soft lambswool for ordinary morning routines. Your requirement for weightless layers + blurred edges + one pearl of light remains entirely constant. Fasten a matt silver clip to your lapel before leaving to buy milk.",
      "sectionIntro": "Maintain your strictest physical standards even during the most mundane routines.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your hardware strategy runs strictly cool. Root your choices in {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Mirror-polished {metal_1} catches excessive glare, cutting harshly against muted tones like {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Ground the styling with matt and brushed finishes to maintain a seamless aesthetic, entirely avoiding {excluded_finish}. Evaluate every clasp and zip before you buy. Assess the solid mass. A photograph obscures flimsy construction, but gravity reveals it immediately. The metal must hold enough physical density to anchor your weightless layers.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your hardware by testing the weight and finish of every metal detail.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Choose {stone_1} and {stone_2} with a dense, cloudy interior. These minerals must hold a soft internal glow rather than throwing off sharp outward reflections. Cup the mineral in your palm before you commit. The eye is easily tricked by clever faceting, but actual heaviness never lies. A heavy stone grounds your soft clothing perfectly. Avoid high-gloss, mirrored settings. A highly polished prong cuts aggressively against your muted fabrics. Demand matt or deeply brushed hardware to keep the transition from fabric to mineral seamless.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess the density and clarity of every stone before wearing it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the piece off the display velvet. Close your fingers around it. A solid cast of {metal_1} must carry distinct heft when resting against your skin. Next, examine the surface. Highly polished metals create a jarring glare against your layers of cool, muted fabric. That intense mirror finish breaks your quiet profile. Fix this by insisting on brushed or matt textures. A flat finish absorbs the ambient light and sits smoothly against your wrist.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your jewellery in person before you buy it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Anchor weightless layers and blurred edges using one pearl of light. Accessories provide this precise focal point. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Establish this baseline with handbags. Demand full-grain leather or thick suede. Check the fastenings to confirm they feature matt brushed hardware. Rely on tactile feedback when assessing construction. Appearance deceives. Density dictates quality. Execute the one-ember test on every metal component. Rest a silver clasp against your deep teal boiled wool. The hardware must behave like a solitary ember glowing softly in a cool, muted landscape. If the finish flashes sharply, drop the item entirely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Introduce hardware and structure with strict discipline, ensuring every addition serves only to ground your silhouette.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Wrap your neck in generous silk or fine wool. Always demand a flat, matt finish. Drop the fabric against your skin. It must drape seamlessly into your silhouette. Check the surface under natural daylight. If the material throws off a hard reflection, leave it on the rack. Isolate your contrast carefully. Construct a cool foundation in dove grey or deep teal, then add exactly one quiet point of illumination to anchor the shape. Keep the boundaries soft to maintain those blurred edges.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate scarves strictly by their drape and surface finish.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Cinch your clothing with a wide full-grain leather belt. Look for a matt brushed buckle, avoiding any high-gloss finishes. For keepsake jewellery, choose a deep stone set in aged silver or brass, heavily oxidised. These cool, muted metals sink into the look rather than fighting it. Always apply the subtraction rule before concluding the outfit. Put on every accessory you plan to wear, then strip away the noise. Remove pieces until only a single point of quiet heat remains. If the belt buckle catches the eye, the deep stone must recede. Maintain soft transitions everywhere else. You need exactly one smouldering focal point.",
      "sectionIntro": "Curate your final metallic and leather additions by stripping away the noise until only the essential remains.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Demand strict low-contrast tonal variations. Your tailored pieces take their pattern from the weave itself. Look for {recommended_pattern_1} to provide understated structure. Your fluid garments take their pattern from the dye. Choose {recommended_pattern_2} to create movement. Pass over stark colours, sharp optical illusions, and any {avoid_pattern_1}. Seek blurred edges in every print. Run the low-light check on unfamiliar patterns. Take the fabric away from the store window. A successful cool design will turn rich and dense in dim conditions, melting its shapes together instead of jumping off the cloth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every pattern to a strict contrast rule to maintain your understated wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the dusk test. Take a {recommended_pattern_1} into a room lit by a single dim lamp. Step back ten paces and look at the fabric. A correct motif will lose its strict boundaries and sink into a cool shadow. The shapes must retreat into the cloth rather than fighting for focus. If the print stays rigid and highly legible across the room, leave the item on the rack. The design must dissolve into the background when the light drops. Trust this visual shift as a reliable measure. A sharp graphic print will stay distinct in the dark. A matt design with proper blending will step back and grant you complete visual silence.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply a strict visual test to ensure your patterns remain quiet.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_pisces__moon_scorpio__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "weightless layers + quiet undercurrent + one pearl of light",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on weightless layers + quiet undercurrent + one pearl of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the sensation of cool, matt precision against the skin. Your internal compass relies on structure that feels like empty space. Build your wardrobe slowly. Scrutinise every hem and weave before it crosses your threshold. Once assembled, deploy these pieces fast. Your binding logic is weightless layers + quiet undercurrent + one pearl of light. Picture a sheer, structured over-shirt falling cleanly over a smooth, second-skin base, anchored by a single point of cold polish catching the light at the collar.\n\nSubject every potential acquisition to the melt test. Put the garment on and close your eyes. The fabric must dissolve entirely into your physical boundaries. If the material feels noticeable, restrictive, or demands constant readjustment, leave it on the rack. A correct garment melts into your self-contained framework, providing a muted, protective shell without adding mass. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this blueprint as your foundational filter for every garment you assess.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "To construct your weightless layers, you must rely entirely on touch. Look for {texture_good_1} when selecting knitwear that needs to compress and spring back without losing its shape. Choose {texture_good_3} for tailored blazers that hold clean, self-contained lines over years of wear. Assess the density of the cloth in the shop. Pick up the fabric, close your eyes, and feel whether it integrates with your hand or fights against it. Let your hands verify the weave before looking in the mirror. Pure tactile response dictates what enters your wardrobe. Build a quiet undercurrent of fluid movement with {texture_good_4} in your blouses and linings. Anchor the wardrobe with {texture_good_2} for shoes and belts that take a subtle, matt patina over time. Keep the temperature cool and seek out the materials ranked below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to isolate the fibres that will build your foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
