      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Reject materials that build a rigid shell. Pick up a piece of {texture_bad_1}. Squeeze it in your fist. If it springs back with a harsh, synthetic resistance, leave it on the rail. Your style requires a quiet undercurrent, a foundation that yields to your shape. When you test {texture_bad_2}, observe how it drapes over your collarbone. It must integrate completely with your natural silhouette, falling seamlessly over your skin. If it holds its own artificial structure, it fails the test. You are building a cool, matt wardrobe where every piece rests lightly. A stiff textile will never offer a fluid drape, and it will only distract from your one pearl of light. Drop anything that feels scratchy or rigid in your hand.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject materials that fight your body.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Anchor your styling in the tension between {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Measure quality through pressure. The mirror offers false promises, but the drape across your arm reports the facts. Test every piece by pressing it onto your bare forearm. It must yield to your body heat and soften into your skin without stiff resistance. Use this yielding quality to build your weightless layers. Introduce a cool, matt {texture_good_1} element to ground the heavier surfaces. Keep your silhouette strictly self-contained. Drop any item that stands away from your frame.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the precise friction between your chosen tactile surfaces.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Keep your temperature strictly cool. Anchor your foundation with {core_colour_1}, {core_colour_2}, and {core_colour_3}. Use {core_colour_4} as your white substitute to secure a muted, matt finish. Judge the dye through the weave. Focus on how the cool pigment absorbs into the fibre. For a deliberate accent, choose {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Apply your soft note sparingly when the eye requires a break. Always reject hot saturated red, stark optic white, and harsh neon. Watch for the couch slide. Relax every piece too far and suddenly you are wearing pyjamas. Correct this by reinstating a single sharp edge. Bring back a tailored lapel, a pressed trouser crease, or a rigid leather bag to anchor the give. Complete the system with one pearl of light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Construct your palette using precise tones that dictate the shape of the body rather than demanding the attention of the room.",
