          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the hard shell: reaching for armour, technical jackets, and stiff utility layers when life speeds up",
          "fix": "swap the shell for a brushed cotton layer that moves just as fast and holds you besides"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At the desk, honest fabric leads. Crisp cotton poplin and worsted wool provide necessary structure. Support these foundational pieces with weightless layers. Use fine ribbed merino or technical nylon to regulate your temperature without restricting your arms. Punctuate the collar with one pearl of light. Mix cool metals or add a single bright stone to cut through the stark navy and icy grey. Apply this logic relentlessly. Your Sunday morning dash for the paper in the pouring rain demands the exact same standard of physical ease. Do not accept stiff garments simply because you are earning a wage. Grip the seam and pull. If the garment fights your movement, drop it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your office uniform by trusting your hands.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim restaurants or private rooms, visual noise vanishes. Let one pearl of light take the lead against a dark, cool backdrop. Anchor stark navy worsted wool with fine ribbed merino. The deep tones recede into the shadows. Bring illumination to the collarbone with a mixed-metal chain or a sliver of icy grey, matt platinum. Keep the construction entirely self-contained. Do not rely on complicated styling tricks. Run your choices through the ripple test. A late evening walk through the city demands the very same gentle standard as sitting across a candlelit table. Drop any stiff collars. Trust the quiet drape of crisp cotton poplin against your skin. Avoid any construction that dictates your posture.",
      "sectionIntro": "Calibrate your intimate evening choices for close physical proximity and low ambient light.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Apply your baseline standard without exception. A bleak Tuesday run to the post office requires the exact same systemic rigour as a scheduled meeting. Gauge the mass of your garments by hand. Depend on technical nylon or worsted wool that falls cleanly in stark navy. Keep the palette strictly cool. A quick walk to the local market must uphold this precise baseline. Build your morning around weightless layers + honest fabric + one pearl of light. Do not suspend this logic for convenience. Anchor an icy grey silhouette with mixed metals, contrasting a matt surface with a polished silver ring. Evaluate the assembly entirely by its unhindered mobility.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat every mundane errand as a strict test of your physical systems.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Exercise your freedom to blend {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} across a single outfit. This mixed approach requires strictly cool undertones to remain coherent. Build your foundation with weightless layers. When you attach hardware to an honest fabric, test the density. Lift the chain or buckle in your palm. Appearances deceive, but gravity tells the truth. Reject false history. Fake aging, antiqued brass, and hammered copper read as visual clutter against a self-contained silhouette. Keep your hardware strictly to mirror chrome, polished silver, platinum, and white gold. Let a brilliant {metal_1} clasp serve as your one pearl of light. Do not force finishes to match. Wear a matt surface alongside an {excluded_finish} detail without hesitation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware using density, temperature, and absolute freedom.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select stones that channel light rather than scatter it. A clear {stone_1} or a dense {stone_2} acts as a vital anchor. Pick the object up in your palm. Look past the surface finish, because pure mass provides the real answer. If it feels hollow, put it back. This true heaviness creates essential tension over weightless layers. Hold your fasteners to equal standards. Pre-tarnished surfaces and forced oxidisation read as messy clutter against a modern line. Fix this failure by keeping strictly to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome. Rely on clean, cool clarity.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones for absolute density and keep your hardware sharply defined.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Gauge the physical density of any ring or cuff before you buy it. Visuals mislead, but heft is absolute. Lift the piece in your palm to judge its solidity. If it lacks weight, leave it on the shelf. Skip distressed finishes and artificial scratching. These details create visual static that interrupts a present-tense wardrobe. Maintain a cool temperature with pristine {metal_1} or a clear {stone_1}. You build with weightless layers, so your hardware must provide a solid, undeniable anchor. Let gravity guide your choice.",
      "sectionIntro": "Let your hands verify the density of your hardware before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Start by selecting weightless layers. Anchor them using honest fabric. Finish the composition by adding one pearl of light to illuminate the face. Accessories follow a strict boundary. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with eyewear. Select a cool acetate frame featuring a mixed finish, perhaps pairing brushed steel temples with a highly polished bridge. Judge the physical resistance of the frame in your hands. Do not rely on your reflection to gauge quality. Apply the take-off test before you commit to wearing them. Put the frames on, check your reflection, and strip them away. If your stark navy worsted wool feels incomplete without the glasses, the accessory is a crutch. Your garments must stand alone.",
      "sectionIntro": "This section defines the strict limits of your accessory strategy, teaching you to select objects that amplify your foundation rather than distract from it.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "acetate frame, mixed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Assess your bags by their structural efficiency. Pick up a crossbody constructed from technical nylon and smooth leather. Prioritise tactile sensation over visual appeal. Run your fingers over the hardware. Seek out a mixture of brushed and polished zips. Keep the metallic tones entirely cool to suit your icy grey staples. Apply the removal test before you purchase any piece. Sling the strap across your chest and strip it away in one swift motion. If the strap tangles or the shape drags, leave it on the shelf. The design must integrate smoothly over your weightless layers. It must function as a self-contained unit. Demand an honest fabric that supports your uninterrupted mobility.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject your functional carriers to the exact same rigorous physical testing as the garments on your back.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "nylon and leather crossbody, brushed and polished zips"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your weightless layers with footwear shaped from smooth leather. Keep the silhouette entirely clean. Reject unnecessary buckles or heavy welts. Next, secure a watch featuring a steel case. Run your thumb over the bracelet to verify a mix of brushed and polished links. Trust this cool metal to provide sharp contrast to your softer garments. Finally, execute the subtraction method. Strip away the last accessory you fastened. If your outfit retains its precise structure without it, leave the extra item on the table.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your accessories by relying on strict lines and physical weight.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather, clean"
        },
        {
          "name": "Watch",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "steel case, mixed brushed and polished"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Your weightless layers demand honest fabric to carry any visual design. In structured garments, draw your pattern strictly from the physical weave. In fluid pieces, let the dye sink completely through the material. Shift your contrast to adapt to your changing environment. Fade a subtle {recommended_pattern_1} into your cool palette on quiet days, or sharpen the boundaries of {recommended_pattern_2} when you require definition. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and any rigid surface printing. Put the piece on and step in front of a mirror. The print must dissolve into a gentle, flowing grain the second you move. Rely on the drape of the cloth. If the shapes trap your eye while the material sways, leave the item behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern not as decoration, but as a physical texture made visible.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the ten-pace walk test. Hang a garment featuring {recommended_pattern_1} on a rail at the end of a corridor. Step back and examine the colour and the lines. At ten paces, the print must blur into an agreeable moving grain. Stack weightless layers over the piece and walk towards a mirror. If the motif flashes sharp borders or rigid angles in motion, drop it. The correct design simply registers as a soft weave when you move. Keep the temperature cool. Avoid anything that projects a stark outline from a distance.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every pattern to a strict visual test before it enters your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_pisces__moon_taurus__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "weightless layers + sensory comfort + one pearl of light",
    "closing": "Calibrate your eye to the shadows, let your fingers judge the weave, and always build outward from weightless layers + sensory comfort + one pearl of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the sensation of absolute physical ease against your skin. Your wardrobe must feel entirely private. It is engineered for your own sensory relief before any mirror is involved. Your blueprint relies on a strict equation. Memorise it. Your core formula is weightless layers + sensory comfort + one pearl of light. Picture a fine knit draped over a frictionless base layer, anchored by a single, small point of illumination at the collarbone. It is a closed circuit of refinement. If a piece requires adjustment, leave it on the hanger.\n\nConstruct this archive with forensic slowness, but deploy it rapidly each morning. When selecting a new garment, run your hands over the seams and gauge the drape. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. If your body tenses or you feel even a fraction of rigid resistance, trust that immediate physical rejection. Drop the hanger and leave the shop. Do not rationalise a bad fit. The garment must serve your need for cool, muted insulation from the very first touch.",
