    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Construct your outfit in deliberate stages. Establish your weightless layers to guarantee strict sensory comfort, then provide one pearl of light to anchor the silhouette. Bags and leather goods demand intense curation. Restrict yourself to minimal additions. Put them on, assess the overall shape, and immediately strip away any item that clutters the clean lines. If a piece clamours for attention, leave it in the closet. Start building this disciplined habit with your holdalls. Select rigid forms crafted in full-grain leather or thick suede. Inspect the zippers and clasps, insisting on matt brushed hardware. Run your thumb over the hide before you commit. Rely on the heavy, cool density of the material to verify its endurance, discarding any bag that lacks structural substance.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to edit your finishing details down to the absolute essential, using every addition to anchor the silhouette rather than distract from it.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Wrap your neck in generous silk or fine wool. Look for a strictly matt weave that absorbs the surrounding light. These textiles must contribute to your weightless layers without adding bulky heat. Choose deep teal or dove grey to keep the colour palette strictly cool. Let your hands judge the fabric. A proper drape feels substantial in the palm even when the cloth itself is sheer. Apply a strict reduction test before walking out the door. If a scarf competes with your brushed silver watch, remove the fabric. A single focal point is mandatory. Keep your adornments completely self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every addition by its tactile weight and visual silence.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your waist with a thick full-grain leather belt. Ensure the hardware features a strictly matt, brushed buckle. For keepsake jewellery, select a deep cool stone set in oxidised silver or forged titanium. Rely entirely on your physical grip to evaluate the quality of these pieces. Trust the dead weight of the object over its polish. Before you finish dressing, check the physical tension of your garments. Remove any item that compromises your essential sensory comfort. One heavy, grounding element provides all the necessary structure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Complete the silhouette with structural hardware and apply a rigorous final edit.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Your tailored pieces draw structure from {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Fluid garments rely on {recommended_pattern_3} woven directly into the silk or tweed. Keep the contrast strictly low and tonal to protect a self-contained finish. Maintain pure sensory comfort by passing over stiff, rubbery surface prints. Ignore {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} completely. Put the textile to a visual test. The motif must dissolve into a continuous matt grain from across the room. If the graphic vanishes into the weave, the item will successfully anchor your weightless layers. If the design jumps out or breaks the cool harmony, return it to the shelf.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate pattern by how it integrates into the fabric rather than how it catches the eye.",
      "tests": [
        "step back and soften focus (blur into texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Execute a distance check for every print you consider. Hang the garment against a plain wall and take three long strides backwards. Half-close your eyes until your vision softens. If the {recommended_pattern_1} maintains sharp edges or stark contrast, reject the piece. The design must melt into a continuous, cool wash of colour. This ensures the print behaves like a woven texture rather than a distinct, jarring graphic. When you integrate weightless layers, every visible pattern must recede into a quiet field. Rely on this blurred-vision technique to guide your selections. A truly self-contained aesthetic requires motifs that never interrupt the eye.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this physical test to ensure your patterns behave as texture rather than distraction.",
      "tests": [
        "step back and soften focus (blur into texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_sagittarius__moon_aquarius__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "expansive colour + mobile layers + one theatrical finish",
    "closing": "Trust your somatic instincts to bridge any environment, relying on pure physical weight to construct expansive colour + mobile layers + one theatrical finish.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your sensory compass is kinetic freedom. Pick up a garment and test its weight in your hands. Squeeze the fabric and pull it across your shoulders. It must yield to your movement and breathe with your body. Collect your clothing through organic drift. Build your wardrobe slowly as your routines shift, acquiring pieces that serve multiple environments. Run the combination test on every new item. Ask yourself if the piece plays a team game. If it cannot bridge three entirely different contexts in your existing closet, leave it on the rack. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not.\n\nYour core formula is expansive colour + mobile layers + one theatrical finish. Picture a generous, warm overshirt worn open over a lightweight mock neck and relaxed trousers, anchored by a heavy boot and completed with a large, highly reflective lapel pin. The silhouette remains entirely adaptable. The layers give you temperature control and physical ease. The final theatrical element provides sharp visual focus. Let the layers remain fluid and keep the finishes mixed. If a garment demands rigid posture or restricts your reach, reject it immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this logic to evaluate every garment before it enters your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the combination test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Building mobile layers requires fabrics that move exactly when you do. Choose {texture_good_1} for shirting that delivers clean architectural boundaries and pure separation. Layer it over {texture_good_2} for close-to-body base layers that maintain sharp lines. For trousers, pick {texture_good_3}. It drapes cleanly and resists creasing. Top this with {texture_good_4} to create lightweight outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little. Always perform the snap test before taking a garment home. Pull the fabric taut between your fingers and let it go. If it springs back into shape immediately, it passes. This structural memory provides a reliable base for warm expansive colour and grounds your one theatrical finish. Trust your hands. Prioritise the materials ranked below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to identify the materials that build your foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Reject {texture_bad_1} the second it feels clammy against your skin. It traps heat and binds your movement, ruining the fluidity you need for mobile layers. Trust your fingertips to spot {texture_bad_2} by its cheap, brittle surface tension. Pinch the fabric and give it a sharp tug. If the material stretches out and sags instead of violently returning to its original shape, it fails the tension test. This lifeless drooping undermines any attempt to anchor warm expansive colour. Rely entirely on material drag to evaluate clothing. A photograph hides structural failure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Leave these materials on the rack when they fail your physical checks.",
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your target sits where {sweet_spot_keyword_1} meets {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. You are building with mobile layers, so the material must stack cleanly without clinging. Anchor this system using {texture_good_1}. Listen for the sharp crack of the threads snapping back into position after you stretch them. That sudden noise confirms the weave holds enough tension for active use. Leave behind any garment that stretches silently or droops. Introduce a warm palette, contrasting matt textiles against mixed metals in bright silver and heavy gold. You are dressing to engage with your community, so the result must remain tactile, approachable, and ready for continuous motion.",
      "sectionIntro": "Combine your key materials to anchor your wardrobe in physical reality.",
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette demands a warm temperature. Build your foundation with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Rely on {core_colour_3} as your primary white substitute, and use {core_colour_4} to bridge combinations. Treat your relief tone strictly as a soft note used sparingly. Deploy {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} to inject expansive colour into your selections. Pass over icy pastel, neon brights, and sterile grey. Reflections flatter weak garments. The actual drape of worsted wool provides accurate data. Let physical drag guide your decisions rather than a flat image. Beware the trap of a lifeless single-tone block that feels uninspired by noon. Remedy this monotony instantly by exposing a stiff white poplin collar, sliding on a structural silver ring, or anchoring the outfit with a geometric sneaker as your one theatrical finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Audit your wardrobe to ensure your baseline tones serve your physical reality.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Warm taupe",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft cream",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sand beige",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Warm stone",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Olive drab",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Espresso brown",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rust orange",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Ochre gold",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Pale clay",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "a flat monochrome look that bores you by midday",
          "fix": "add a crisp white poplin collar, a silver architectural ring, or a bright geometric sneaker"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, mobile layers dictate the pace. Establish a structured, warm foundation using worsted wool or fine ribbed merino. Support this architecture with expansive colour. A crisp cotton poplin shirt in camel sets the stage. Fasten a mixed metal watch or a heavy brass pendant to complete the construction. Keep the components active and ready to adapt to a shifting environment. Avoid static, restrictive tailoring. Treat a morning strategy meeting and a quick lunch run with equal intent. Build the shoulders first and leave the soft fleece on the rack.",
      "sectionIntro": "Approach your working hours as an active practice, not a static uniform.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "A late supper with close friends still requires a deliberate outline. Test your dark wash denim and a heavy cotton overshirt under dim lighting. If the shape collapses into a blur, change the silhouette. In close quarters, mobile layers take the lead. Stack a crisp cotton poplin shirt over fine ribbed merino. Keep the palette warm with camel and taupe. Mix your metals without hesitation. Sit a matt brass pendant next to a polished silver ring to catch the low light of a table lamp. Shadows obscure weak construction. The raw friction of the fabric against your skin provides the real measure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the mechanics of dressing for low light and close proximity.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Rely on your bodily intuition as your primary guide. Trust your somatic response to evaluate clothing. Pick up a garment and gauge its movement. If a piece restricts your stride, discard it. Do not suspend your standards for a Tuesday trip to the post office. An evening run to the petrol station still requires an intentional shape, built from worsted wool and a technical nylon shell. Ground the base in a warm camel or taupe. Demand consistency from your garments across every environment. You must strictly apply expansive colour + mobile layers + one theatrical finish to a morning commute just as you would a community gathering. Anchor the look with a mixed metal chain or a heavy matt brass ring.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your routine errands as the primary testing ground for your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your strategy is absolute freedom. Blend {metal_1} with {metal_2} and {metal_3} across your rings and buckles. When assessing hardware, pick it up. Photography flatters cheap casting. Physical grams provide the facts. A hollow link betrays itself instantly. Let the sheer mass of the object verify its quality. Avoid tarnished brass, hammered copper, and artificially induced patinas. These pieces register as costume debris rather than functional modern elements. Instead, counteract your warm textiles by anchoring expansive colour with polished silver, bright platinum, white gold, or mirror chrome. Leave any {excluded_finish} on the shelf.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your structural hardware and jewellery using sheer mass and finish, discarding any traditional rules.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "You need dense, light-capturing minerals like {stone_1} and {stone_2} to ground your mobile layers. Lift the setting in your palm. Evaluate the gem by its sheer density. If a piece feels hollow, leave it on the tray. A heavy stone acts as a fixed anchor amidst expansive colour. Pair these dense minerals exclusively with gleaming hardware. Avoid artificially darkened settings and dull, scratched surfaces. These treatments create visual noise that disrupts your one theatrical finish. Ground your warm garments with pure white gold or flawless platinum to establish a strict, present-tense boundary.",
      "sectionIntro": "Demand literal mass from your stones and insist on highly reflective metals to anchor your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Test the integrity of a clasp by weighing it in your hand. If the links feel fragile, walk away. Reject blackened engraving or distressed edges. These elements register as historical clutter against your mobile layers. Keep your hardware firmly in the present tense by selecting polished {metal_1} and bright {stone_1}. A warm aesthetic requires distinct details to contrast with the fabric. Your jewellery must anchor the outfit with literal gravity.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your hardware physically before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Build your foundation using expansive colour. Add fluid mobile layers. Ground these garments with one theatrical finish. Restrict your hardware to one or two heavy pieces per look. Begin with your eyewear. Seek out a substantial acetate frame featuring a mixed finish, combining gloss and matt textures alongside mixed metal hinges to catch warm light. Pick up the frames and put them on. Apply the skull-tracking test. Turn your head quickly to address a colleague beside you. The frame must lock entirely to your face without slipping down your nose. If the glasses shift or bounce when you move, put them down.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your accessories as functional tools to physically ground your garments.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "acetate frame, mixed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Pick a technical nylon crossbody in warm camel or taupe. Test the strap dynamics before committing. Swing the bag fully around your torso. If the fabric drags or catches on your mobile layers, drop the piece and walk away. Look for hardware that completely ignores rigid matching rules. Inspect the bag for brushed metal zips sitting right next to one polished ring. This sharp contrast provides visual interest without demanding heavy structure. Rely on expansive colour to unify these elements, allowing the carrier to shift cleanly across your back.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your bags by how they respond to your physical stride.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "technical nylon crossbody, brushed metal zips, one polished ring"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your expansive colour with a clean leather boot. Seek unadorned surfaces in warm shades of chestnut or deep mahogany. Combine finishes without hesitation. Pair a matt suede boot with polished silver side zippers, and wear gold jewellery on your wrists. Prioritise the suppleness of the hide over its visual appeal. Before stepping out, subject your outfit to the pivot trial. Spin fully on your heel and watch the glass. Your mobile layers must swing and drape fluidly alongside your body. If a rigid ankle shaft interrupts your natural stride or a heavy pendant swings awkwardly as you turn, remove the offending item immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your final components before leaving the house.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "clean leather boot, clean"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Assign your patterns based on garment construction. Tailored pieces pull their structure from woven motifs like {recommended_pattern_1}. Fluid pieces take their impact from dyed designs like {recommended_pattern_2}. Because you adapt to varying environments, shift your contrast levels deliberately. A low-contrast {recommended_pattern_3} anchors a quiet setting. A sharp, graphic layout acts as a tool to project expansive colour outward. Test every print by stepping back ten feet. Shut your eyes, snap them open, and evaluate what hits you. If the motif turns muddy or confusing in that first split second, drop the hanger. You require clear, legible shapes on warm grounds. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. They compromise your visual clarity. Mix your approved prints across varying finishes, letting matt and gloss interact.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess every print by its scale and construction, treating pattern as a structural tool rather than mere decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Walk across the room and glance at the garment on the rack. A strong {recommended_pattern_1} reads perfectly from afar. If the print collapses into visual static from a distance, leave it behind. You need warm expansive colour that holds firm boundaries. Whether you wear the piece as a base layer or drape it over a chair, the design must remain distinct. The motif either proves its clarity instantly or it fails.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this distance reflex to audit every print before you buy.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_sagittarius__moon_aries__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "expansive colour + sharp edges + one theatrical finish",
    "closing": "Trust the heavy drag of dense cloth and the cold bite of polished metal to guide your instincts toward expansive colour + sharp edges + one theatrical finish.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the physical tension of polished fabrics against your skin. If a garment feels flimsy or hesitant, discard it. Build your wardrobe slowly, but assemble outfits rapidly by mood. Your governing equation is expansive colour + sharp edges + one theatrical finish. Picture a heavy woven shirt in a warm tone, tucked into a heavily structured tailored trouser, anchored by a high-shine boot. The garments must hold their shape while supporting absolute visual volume.\n\nApply the entrance test before leaving the house. Ask yourself if the outfit forces you to shrink to fit the environment. If you feel an urge to soften the silhouette or strip away an accessory, take the clothes off. Your pieces must claim physical space through heavy construction. Mix your hardware freely across thick buckles and heavy jewellery. Keep the proportions balanced between the upper and lower body. Your drive for high-contrast combinations is your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Structure does not. Trust your hands to find dense, polished materials that refuse to collapse.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is the structural foundation of your wardrobe, a set of rigid physical rules you must apply to every garment you select.",
      "tests": [
        "the entrance test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your garments demand materials that support sharp edges and carry warm, expansive colour without swallowing the light. Seek out {texture_good_1} for collars that snap to attention. Build your foundation on {texture_good_2} to ensure your tailoring remains rigid. Before purchasing, apply the shadow test. Drape the fabric over your hand against a bare bulb. If the silhouette blurs, leave it on the rack. You require materials with enough density to block the beam entirely. Physical gravity provides a better guide than a shop mirror. Ground your footprint in {texture_good_3} to deliver one theatrical finish, and rely on {texture_good_4} when you need a lining to gleam against bare skin.",
      "sectionIntro": "Stock your closet with textiles that hold sharp tension and reflect maximum light.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "sharp shirting that holds a crease and snaps visually"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sharp wool twill",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "knife-edge tailoring that never begs for a steamer"
