    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let sharp edges lead your strategy at the office. Structured wool twill provides necessary geometry. Support these clean borders with expansive colour and one theatrical finish. A demanding agenda calls for pliable, polished weaves that can sprint. Grab the textile and pull it. It must yield to movement while maintaining crisp boundaries. Pair deep bronze tailoring with freely mixed metals at the wrist. Let a heavy silk satin blouse provide a single gleaming punctuation point beneath. Appearances distract, so let the physical responsiveness of a garment dictate its use.",
      "sectionIntro": "Deploy your formula in the workplace.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close quarters and low light, expansive colour sets the mood. When sitting shoulder to shoulder in a dimly lit space, deep bronze silk satin catches every glint of candlelight while crisp poplin holds a strict boundary. Test the mobility of a garment before leaving the house. A late evening requires yielding threads that move fluidly past midnight. Mix gold and silver chains freely high on the neck to provide one theatrical finish. Check the bend of your elbows. If the material restricts your arms, discard it immediately. Reach for warm golden camel wool twill tailored with sharp edges to define the shoulders.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master these directives to navigate close settings and evening hours.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat an ordinary morning exactly like a major event. Even when buying paracetamol at the chemist, your baseline remains expansive colour + sharp edges + one theatrical finish. A chaotic agenda requires textiles that match your pace. Reach for heavy silk satin or crisp cotton poplin that flows rapidly with your stride. Heavy restriction slows you down. Rely on a warm golden camel coat paired with a gleaming patent leather boot. Combine gold and silver chains at the collar to catch the daylight. Rely on the drape of the cloth in your fingers. If a piece fights your movement, drop it instantly.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your standard to ordinary days and mundane tasks without compromise.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Wear a {metal_1} cuff alongside a {metal_2} belt clasp and a {metal_3} lapel pin. You hold total freedom to combine these hardware choices within one outfit. This strategy functions under two strict rules. Every component must project a warm temperature, and the geometry must support your sharp edges. Reject {excluded_finish} components entirely. Weathered or beaten surfaces ruin crispness. Demand strictly polished warm hardware that throws a hard glare from a block away. Before committing to a piece, lift it off the counter. A gleaming surface fools the eye, but sheer physical mass delivers the facts. Choose heavy density over any visual promise.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your garments with structural pieces that deliver immediate impact.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Reject deliberately aged, beaten, or darkened settings. These cloudy finishes look exhausted and dilute your impact. Anchor {stone_1}, {stone_2}, and {stone_3} in intensely polished warm metal that flashes from the opposite pavement. Demand settings cut with sharp edges. Lift the item off the jeweller's tray. A stone's sparkle distracts, but its dense physical gravity reveals the absolute truth. Pick pieces that provide one theatrical finish to your hand.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones using physical density and brilliant light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Test every {metal_1} cuff and {stone_1} ring before purchase. Weigh the item in your palm to gauge its gravity. If it feels hollow, return it to the case. Your wardrobe requires profound physical density to ground expansive colour and anchor sharp edges. Inspect the surface finish closely. Reject hammered, antiqued, or oxidised textures immediately. These clouded treatments fail to hold a strict geometric line. Demand a strictly polished, warm metal surface that beams a brilliant reflection. This high-gloss clarity delivers the necessary architectural weight for one theatrical finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every piece of jewellery through direct physical contact to ensure it meets your structural standards.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You have laid the groundwork with expansive colour. You have structured the garment with sharp edges. Now, complete the look with one theatrical finish. Keep your discipline strict and restrict yourself to a single strong piece. Begin your selection with statement jewellery, specifically a solid metal collar. The surface must carry a high polish. You are mixing metals freely in warm tones, so the reflection must remain pristine. Apply the sensory test. With your eyes closed, you must be able to identify the piece purely by the heavy, rigid bite of the metal resting against your collarbone. Physical contact provides your true compass.",
      "sectionIntro": "Accessories dictate the final impact of your garments, so select them with strict physical criteria.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Statement jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "polished metal collar, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the blackout test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Move directly to your footwear. Look for shoes crafted entirely in patent leather with a high gloss. Your boots must carry the sharp edges that define your overall geometry. Examine the construction blindly. Run your fingers over the toe box without looking. You must feel a slick exterior and a rigid internal structure. If the leather yields under pressure, put it back. Your footwear must reflect light aggressively to provide one theatrical finish. Ground your expansive colour choices with these highly polished anchors. Opt for warm leather tones like deep bronze or golden camel. When examining hardware on a boot, mix your metals freely. A bright brass buckle and a gleaming steel zip belong together.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your footwear to enforce your structure.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "patent leather, patent gloss"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the blackout test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Pick up thick acetate frames. Look for a polished finish in warm tortoiseshell or deep bronze. Trust your hands to check the gloss on the plastic. It must feel dense and substantial. A flash of freely mixed copper and bright steel at the temple adds necessary tension. Your eyewear must hold its own against expansive colour elsewhere in your outfit. Finally, test the shape in poor light. Stand in a dim room and squint into a mirror. If your face loses its sharp edges in the gloom, the accessory is failing you. Swap the frames for a stronger geometric cut to ensure one theatrical finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Lock down your final accessories and test the overall silhouette.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "acetate frame, high shine"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the blackout test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Channel expansive colour into high-contrast, graphic geometry. Tailored jackets must take their structure from {recommended_pattern_1}. Fluid layers require {recommended_pattern_2} to anchor the eye. Apply the distance metric. Stand ten paces away in a shadowed corridor. If the motif dissolves into a hazy wash, drop the garment immediately. The design must project absolute intent from across the room. Grip the cloth. A print must carry physical conviction. If the scale feels delicate under your fingers, reject it. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1}, {avoid_pattern_2}, and any motif too small to read. They dilute the impact. Instead, seek out {recommended_pattern_3} rendered in a warm palette. Demand sharp edges.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the geometry of your wardrobe by filtering every print through high-contrast scale.",
      "tests": [
        "the low-light rule (must still read as intent from ten feet in dim light)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Subject {recommended_pattern_1} to the focus test. Hang the garment up and strip off your glasses, or squint heavily. If the design loses its structure and smears into a continuous blob, leave it on the rack. You require patterns that hold their internal geometry regardless of visibility. Your visual strategy depends on sharp edges to contain expansive colour. A weak print compromises that rigid structure. Look for crisp boundaries between warm dye and negative space. Combine these distinct shapes with freely mixed gold and platinum hardware to maintain a polished, theatrical finish across your entire frame.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your prints against the failing light to verify their structural integrity.",
      "tests": [
        "the low-light rule (must still read as intent from ten feet in dim light)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_sagittarius__moon_cancer__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "expansive colour + hidden depth + one theatrical finish",
    "closing": "Let the undeniable heft of the garment and the unbroken slip of the fabric lead you straight to expansive colour + hidden depth + one theatrical finish.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Anchor your choices in pure, warm saturation. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight and finish do not. Run your hand over the surface of any prospective garment. It must feel entirely resolved and deliberately slick, never raw. Your fundamental equation is expansive colour + hidden depth + one theatrical finish. Picture a heavy, tailored outer layer saturated in broad dye. It opens to reveal a complex, densely woven interior structure. You complete this architecture with a single massive, highly polished rigid cuff.\n\nBuild your foundational layers methodically, but deploy your final theatrical elements on sudden impulse. When you stand before the mirror and question whether a singular, heavy accessory tips the balance too far, apply the hesitation test. If your hand hovers over the piece because the scale feels overwhelming, that very pause is your mandate to wear it. The integrity of your wardrobe requires that sudden strike of extreme proportion. Reject anything that feels half-measured, and lean heavily into the absolute scale.",
