    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Softness leads at the desk. Let a cashmere sweater or silk blouse dictate your baseline comfort. Broad washes of warm camel support this ease, while an oversized matt silver lapel pin provides visual focus. Mix your metals indiscriminately, combining that pin with heavy gold rings. Pick up a blazer and evaluate its mass. The physical weight must confirm the visual structure. Maintain this discipline relentlessly. A morning coffee run does not justify abandoning your silhouette. Demand the exact same standards for every minor outing. Prioritise how the cloth feels against your shoulder over the reflection in the glass.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat this tactile strategy as your non-negotiable uniform for the office.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close and dimly lit settings, rely entirely on drape. Ground your warm palette in rich toffee silk and camel cashmere. Trust your bare hands to evaluate the weave. Heavy natural fibres always fall perfectly. A sudden trip to the wine merchant requires the same balanced proportions as a formal dinner. Mix your metals without hesitation. Stack a dense silver ring alongside a slender gold chain. Ensure every surface remains matt to absorb the dim light. Avoid shiny synthetics entirely. Select a single untreated tiger eye pendant as your focal point.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your evening approach by leading with tactile materials before adding a focal point.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Errands require discipline. When fetching a prescription from the chemist, apply your exact equation. Even on a Tuesday morning, demand expansive colour + softness + one theatrical finish. Build this warm base with a camel brushed wool coat over a rich toffee cashmere sweater. Mix a matt silver ring with a heavy brass cuff. Do not downgrade into shapeless fleece. Reach for full-grain leather loafers instead of canvas trainers. Judge these pieces by how they drape and move with your body. You know your proportions. Trust your grip.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat everyday errands as the strict test of your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "You have complete freedom to mix your hardware. Combine {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} across your zips and buckles. Ground the mixture. Let at least one piece bring a warm tone to the skin. Steer clear of {excluded_finish}. Avoid mirrored chrome. A high-gloss polish reflects too sharply against subdued weaves and disrupts the impact of an expansive colour. Choose matt or brushed textures to lock the elements together. Pick the item up and test its gravity. Solid hardware anchors light fabrics and proves the quality of the cast.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your hardware to physically anchor your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Evaluate a {stone_1} or a {stone_2} by lifting it. The stone must carry genuine weight. High-shine settings slice through a subdued coat like a harsh glare. Anchor your jewellery by selecting strictly matt or brushed surfaces to maintain visual cohesion. Opaque stones absorb light rather than refracting it. Require this warm, heavy opacity to anchor expansive colour across your wardrobe. Rely on your grip to confirm a piece possesses the necessary heft.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your hardware by testing its physical density and light absorption.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the {metal_1} piece off the table. Close your eyes and gauge the heft. A polished exterior often hides a hollow core. Density provides the true measure of quality. The item must press heavily into your palm. Reject highly reflective surfaces that interrupt muted textiles and pull focus from your warm garments. Select sandblasted or strictly matt finishes to integrate the hardware seamlessly. A dense and unpolished metal provides one theatrical finish without breaking your cohesive foundation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your hardware with your hands before checking the mirror.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your accessories deliver the one theatrical finish. When a foundation relies on expansive colour and deep softness, you require absolute grounding. Commit to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with handbags. Require thick full-grain leather and brushed matt hardware. Lift the bag by the handles. Ask yourself if it possesses enough sheer density to moor your warm layers. If the item feels hollow or lightweight in your grip, drop it. A proper carryall serves as a heavy physical ballast.",
      "sectionIntro": "Ground your wardrobe with heavy, disciplined accessories.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Limit your textile additions to scarves in pure silk or fine wool. Demand a strictly matt finish. Apply a practical gravity check before acquiring a new piece. Ask whether the item grounds your garments with actual substance or merely decorates the surface. A warm camel wool scarf must hold its own against heavier outerwear. Drape the fabric to assess its softness against your collarbone. Rely on these pieces to introduce rich toffee colour without employing high shine. Mix your metals freely in your rings or watch, but ensure your woven elements absorb light rather than reflect it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your woven pieces as functional anchors.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select belts in medium full-grain leather with a completely matt buckle. Use rich toffee leather to bring a warm element to the waistline. Add keepsake jewellery carved from aged silver and oxidised metals. Combine these tarnished pieces freely with your clean metals. Your accessories exist to puncture the softness of your clothing. Pick up the heaviest item before you finish dressing. Drop it into your hand and feel the gravity. The metal must provide genuine ballast to tie the garments to the earth. If a piece floats rather than sinks, leave it in the drawer.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finish your accessory selection by sourcing heavier details and applying a final physical check.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Look to the loom for tailored garments. The weave supplies the design. Fluid pieces take their prints from subtle dyes, but your standard remains strictly low-contrast and tonal. Seek out {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. The pattern must sit quietly within your palette of warm tones. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. It creates harsh visual breaks. Test every printed piece in a dark room. The motif must lose its sharp edges and merge into a single rich, deep texture. This fading effect protects the inherent softness of the cloth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern strictly as a subtle extension of the fabric itself.",
      "tests": [
        "the twilight test (merge into a rich, deep texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate {recommended_pattern_1} at dusk. Hang the garment in low lighting and step away. Watch the contrast as the room darkens. A successful print surrenders its sharp borders and dissolves into a dense, unified surface. If the individual motifs still separate starkly in the shadows, leave the item on the hanger. You require complete visual softness to make the pattern viable. Trust the blur. The material must consolidate into a warm, atmospheric depth rather than fighting to stay heavily defined.",
      "sectionIntro": "Run this visual drill before committing to any print.",
      "tests": [
        "the twilight test (merge into a rich, deep texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_sagittarius__moon_gemini__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "expansive colour + light movement + one theatrical finish",
    "closing": "Rely on your hands to guide you through the physical world, building your wardrobe through expansive colour + light movement + one theatrical finish.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Look for garments that yield to your environment. Your sensory compass is breath and give. When you pick up a piece, check how it moves through the air. Your foundational equation is expansive colour + light movement + one theatrical finish. Picture a fluid wide-leg trouser that ripples when you step, paired with a soft dropped-shoulder tunic washed in a warm dye. Anchor this pairing with a dramatically oversized architectural belt. This combination allows you to adapt to the people around you while maintaining your own physical centre.\n\nBuild your collection organically by drifting across moods. Collect versatile layers that invite play rather than rigid uniforms. When testing a new addition, apply the seam test. Run your thumb along the interior stitching. If the thread feels stiff or the join bites into your skin, leave the piece on the rail. Reject anything that fights your natural rhythm. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Friction doesn't. Your clothes must move with your community and your body simultaneously.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this framework to filter out visual distractions and lock in your physical instinct.",
      "tests": [
        "the seam test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your foundational materials must facilitate light movement while holding structure across a long day working alongside others. Build warm shirting with clean architectural boundaries using {texture_good_1}. Anchor these with close to body base layers in {texture_good_2} for sharp lines and easy mobility. Trousers require {texture_good_3} to drape cleanly and resist creasing. Top the outfit with {texture_good_4} for lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind. Verify the quality yourself. Perform the recovery test. Crush a handful of the fabric in your fist for ten seconds and release the tension. If it remains deeply wrinkled, discard the garment. You need materials that spring back immediately. Choose these fibres to carry your expansive colour and prepare the canvas for one theatrical finish. Here are your most reliable textures.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to find the materials that support your movement before you even check the label.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
