      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Scrutinise every new textile. Squeeze a sleeve of {texture_bad_1} in your fist and watch how the fibres behave when you open your hand. If the fabric holds a harsh crease instead of relaxing back into light movement, put it back. Drag your thumb down a section of {texture_bad_2}. If you detect a dry synthetic resistance, that material will trap heat and stifle your warm tones. Rely entirely on tactile feedback. Decline stiff materials that isolate your body or dictate your shape. You require fabrics that adapt to the room and breathe with you.",
      "sectionIntro": "Eliminate any cloth that fights your physical instincts.",
      "tests": [
        "the recovery test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your signature friction relies on pairing {sweet_spot_keyword_1} against {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. You require pieces that maintain their structural integrity to generate light movement around the body. Pair a smooth surface with something visibly coarse. Construct an outfit from warm tones, relying entirely on surface contrast rather than added bulk. Always gauge the heft of the cloth before you put the item on.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the precise friction point where two contrasting surfaces activate each other.",
      "tests": [
        "the recovery test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette stays strictly warm. Build the foundation with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}, substitute stark white with {core_colour_3}, and bridge the scheme using {core_colour_4}. Inject expansive colour through {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Deploy your relief tone purely as a soft note applied sparingly. Pass over icy pastel, neon brights, and cold blue grey. Watch out for a pale monotone. When every piece sits at the same pale value, the outfit appears unfinished rather than minimal. Rescue this error by introducing a {core_colour_4} grounding element or a {accent_colour_1} focal point. Let one tactile shift restore the depth. Verify the proportions with your own hands, relying on physical feedback to guide the silhouette.",
