      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim lighting and close quarters, light movement takes the lead. Prioritise fine ribbed merino and crisp cotton poplin right against the skin. Keep your entire palette warm. Rely on warm taupe and camel to catch the ambient glow of low lamps. Mix your metals freely. Layer matt steel jewellery with bright gold rings to create a complex surface in the shadows. Maintain a strong foundation at all times. A relaxed evening is no reason to tolerate a weak base layer beneath your jacket. Your personal requirements apply regardless of the audience. Sight fails in the dark. Rely on tactile weight and fibre density to judge the quality of every piece.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master intimate settings by shifting your attention to proximity and touch.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip to the dry cleaner does not suspend your standards (Frost)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A Tuesday morning trip to the local garden centre for potting soil does not grant you a pass to abandon your core principles. Anchor your morning garments in warm taupe worsted wool. Layer them over camel technical nylon. Treat your formula as an active practice. You must execute expansive colour + light movement + one theatrical finish even on mundane errands. Stack a bright brass cuff next to a dull silver watch. Combine a matt canvas bag with a high gloss boot. Select garments that let you comfortably lift a heavy box or help a neighbour.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your core principles directly to your routine errands.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip to the dry cleaner does not suspend your standards (Frost)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Because your palette runs warm, you hold total freedom to mix and layer your metals. Combine {metal_1} with {metal_2}, or introduce {metal_3} to build visual depth. Blend both matt and mirror finishes to amplify the light movement across your hardware. Lift any piece in your palm before committing to it. The eye is easily tricked by a surface coating. Weight provides the facts. Avoid artificially aged alloys and pitted copper. Those fake patinas register as visual clutter that drags down an adaptable and progressive presentation. Anchor your hardware instead in smooth, reflective surfaces. Keep to solid {metal_1}, reflective {metal_2}, and high shine {metal_3}.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hardware demands the same rigorous physical scrutiny as your fabrics; treat every zip, clasp, and ring as a deliberate architectural choice rather than an afterthought.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
