      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Ground your expansive colour and your layers of light movement by committing to one theatrical finish. Hold strictly to the rule of one or two strong pieces per look. Always enforce the movement test before buying. Put the item on, bend forward, and reach your arms up. If the piece slides down or requires adjustment, walk away. Begin with eyewear. Pick up an acetate frame with a mixed finish, blending matt and polished surfaces. Gauge the sturdiness of the material by flexing the arms slightly. Integrate these frames with your warm palette, letting the mixed textures sit against camel worsted wool or warm taupe nylon.",
      "sectionIntro": "Accessories provide the defining hardware for your uniform, requiring strict physical validation to ensure they work in motion.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "acetate frame, mixed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Evaluate your daily bag for absolute practicality. Sling it over your shoulder and reach inside blind. If you hesitate or fumble, leave it on the shelf. Choose a technical nylon crossbody that guarantees unhindered access. Seek out matt brushed metal zips paired with one polished ring to blend your hardware freely. Ground the piece in a warm taupe or let an expansive colour saturate the fabric. Ensure the strap slides easily to provide light movement across your torso. Heft the piece by the handles. If the zips catch or the rings feel hollow, drop the bag immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every bag by how it handles the physical demands of your day.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "technical nylon crossbody, brushed metal zips, one polished ring"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor the outfit with your footwear. Choose a clean leather boot with a smooth, matt surface. Keep the profile uncluttered to balance the light movement happening in your upper layers. Avoid thick soles. Rely on warm leather tones like chestnut to support your foundation. Inspect the construction manually. Bend the toe box to check the resistance. Apply a strict trial before you buy. If you cannot crouch, climb stairs, or pivot without noticing your feet, put the pair back on the shelf. Aesthetics deceive. Blisters do not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Lock down your foundation with footwear that serves your daily terrain.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "clean leather boot, clean"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Draw a firm boundary between your silhouettes. Tailored garments must take their pattern entirely from the structural weave itself. Fluid pieces take theirs from applied surface prints. Since your approach requires adaptive contrast, choose motifs that shift in intensity depending on how you layer them. Lean on {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} to introduce a warm baseline. The fabric must resolve into a clean texture from a distance. If it turns into a muddy blur, drop it. Keep your focus on an expansive colour. You need fabrics that maintain light movement without stiffening under heavy ink. Avoid {avoid_pattern_1} completely. Pass over stiff printed suiting, digital floristry, and rigid geometric blocks.",
      "sectionIntro": "Pattern serves as a structural tool to bridge different environments, so you must select motifs that adapt to your layered combinations.",
      "tests": [
        "the desk test (read as clean texture at arm's length and a half)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Put the {recommended_pattern_1} garment over the back of a chair and step away an arm length and a half. This is the desk test. Turn around and look at the fabric. The print must blur into a clean texture from this distance. If the motifs still demand attention, leave the piece on the rack. You require patterns that provide light movement instead of rigid distraction. Trust the blur. Ensure the warm palette reads as a continuous surface before you wear the item.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the desk test to gauge how your patterns resolve from a short distance.",
      "tests": [
        "the desk test (read as clean texture at arm's length and a half)"
