    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Let expansive colour set your foundation. Once that baseline is established, bring in pattern as a structural tool. Let tailored pieces take their pattern from rigid geometry like {recommended_pattern_1}. Let fluid pieces take movement-driven prints like {recommended_pattern_2}. Modulate your contrast according to the garment. Keep structured layers low-contrast and tonal, then push a high-contrast graphic on a single technical nylon shell. Apply the glance test. If a quick look yields a cohesive warm blur rather than a solitary shouting motif, the scale is correct. Inspect the dye penetration on the reverse side. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} entirely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Pattern is an architectural tool, so deploy it to construct shape rather than decorate a surface.",
      "tests": [
        "the glance test (a pleasant impression rather than a specific shouting motif)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Hang the garment across the room. Step back ten paces. Blink rapidly. If {recommended_pattern_1} blurs into a pleasant, warm field, it passes. If it broadcasts a single demanding motif, leave it on the rail. You need prints that serve expansive colour without shouting over the cut of the cloth. The goal is to maintain cool composure. A demanding graphic shatters that focus. Retreat across the floor to verify the motif. Up-close examination flatters weak designs. The blurred impression reveals the true weight of the pattern.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the rapid blink test to filter out demanding graphics.",
      "tests": [
        "the glance test (a pleasant impression rather than a specific shouting motif)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_sagittarius__moon_sagittarius__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "expansive colour + fast movement + one theatrical finish",
    "closing": "Trust your physical reactions, rely on dense polished metals to anchor your frame, and dress strictly for expansive colour + fast movement + one theatrical finish.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your compass is momentum. When you pick up a garment, test how quickly it responds to your hands. Drop it on a table to see if the fabric ripples or collapses. You are dressing to the formula of expansive colour + fast movement + one theatrical finish. Picture a warm, sweeping coat thrown over a sharply cut silk trouser, grounded by a massive, polished structural boot. The silhouette must feel ready to sprint across a crowded street. If a piece restricts your stride or feels stiff and static, leave it on the rail. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Movement does not.\n\nBuild your wardrobe impulsively and drift by mood. Let your orientation toward community dictate the scale of your silhouettes. You dress to connect. Apply the radius test to every new acquisition. Stand in front of a mirror and stretch your arms wide to measure the literal space the outfit occupies. If the garments cling strictly to your frame without extending your physical presence toward others, the piece is too timid. It must reach out. Pair warm, polished finishes with loose cuts to ensure you claim your space. Mix polished metals freely to amplify the effect. Never settle for anything that demands you shrink.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation, the physical laws that dictate how you build and test your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the radius test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe around materials that take a high polish and carry warm pigment without diluting it. Look for {texture_good_1} to construct sharp shirting that holds a crease and snaps visually. Demand {texture_good_2} for knife-edge tailoring that never begs for a steamer. Fast movement requires textiles that recover instantly. Apply the spring test. Crush a fistful of the garment and drop it. If the material does not spring open immediately, leave it on the hanger. Rely on your grip to measure a fabric's energy. Contrast these structured weights using {texture_good_4} for slip dresses and linings that gleam under low light. Finally, deploy {texture_good_3} for statement footwear and accessories that reflect maximum light, guaranteeing your look always has one theatrical finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "These are the core structural materials that support your aesthetic. Prioritise them heavily.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "sharp shirting that holds a crease and snaps visually"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sharp wool twill",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "knife-edge tailoring that never begs for a steamer"
        },
        {
          "name": "Patent leather",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "statement footwear and accessories that reflect maximum light"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk satin",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "slip dresses and linings that gleam under low light"
        },
        {
          "name": "Techno gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "wrinkle-resistant trousers and jackets that keep a rigid shape"
        },
        {
          "name": "High-shine taffeta",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "evening pieces that bounce light and cut a clear silhouette"
        },
        {
          "name": "Polished calfskin",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "footwear and accessories with a slick, radiant surface"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the bounce test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Trust your hands to spot dead weight. Test everything with a quick snap check. Pull the hem and let it go. If it flops limply instead of recoiling with tension, drop it. It will fail to project expansive colour to the people around you. Leave {texture_bad_1} on the rail when it feels sluggish against your fingers. {texture_bad_2} traps stale heat against your body and stifles a warm palette. Reject materials that cling weakly to your skin. Grab a handful of {texture_bad_3} and squeeze it hard. If the fabric stays crushed when you open your fist, it lacks the sharp structure you need.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject failing fabrics before you ever reach the fitting room.",
      "tests": [
        "the bounce test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Find your tension exactly between {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Grab {texture_good_1} in your fists. Squeeze tightly. Open your hands and watch the reaction. If the piece springs back instantly, keep it. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. That rapid recoil builds the fast movement your silhouette requires. Combine this reactive base with heavy, warm pigment, then anchor the ensemble with thick mixed metals. A polished surface reflects the light directly, drawing your community in.",
      "sectionIntro": "Pairing your core surfaces requires a calibrated grip.",
      "tests": [
        "the bounce test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor your foundation in {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} to set a base for expansive colour. Treat {core_colour_3} as your substitute for stark white. Deploy {core_colour_4} to bridge gaps between contrasting pieces. Push {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} forward as your single deliberate accent. Your palette temperature is exclusively warm. Avoid muddy pastel, icy grey, and dusty sage entirely. Keep a soft relief tone on standby to lower the visual volume when necessary. Beware the trap of retreating into a severe, blackened monochrome outfit. It crushes your presence and halts fast movement. Fracture that rigid shape by strapping on a heavy polished mixed metal wristband or stepping into a sharp {accent_colour_1} patent leather pump. Rely on this choice to deliver your one theatrical finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Lock down your foundation before you deploy your accents.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Deep bronze",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Golden camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Warm ivory",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rich terracotta",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Warm sand",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Toasted chestnut",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Jet black",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fire engine red",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Hot tangerine",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brilliant marigold",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Washed peach",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "a restrictive dark monochrome look that stifles your presence",
          "fix": "break the silhouette with a massive polished gold cuff or a bright poppy red shoe"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At the desk, let fast movement take the lead. Crisp cotton poplin shirting gives you instant physical speed. Support this pacing with wide blocks of warm golden camel near the face to push energy outward toward your team. Cap the outfit with a single dramatic end point, like a heavy silk satin lapel or a patent leather shoe. A morning coffee run demands the exact same strict intention as a board meeting. Do not leave your sharp wool twill behind or reach for dull jersey. Test office attire by gripping the collar. Demand material that fights back against your fingers. Drop any garment that hangs limp. Rely on rigid mixed metals to catch the overhead light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Command your working hours with deliberate physical intent, dropping any default corporate basics.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In a crowded living room or a low-lit booth, fast movement takes the lead. Dim lighting swallows subtle choices, so cut through the shadows with sharp wool twill trousers that sweep aggressively over your shoes. Rely on deep bronze heavy silk satin to catch the ambient light. Mix thick gold and silver chains freely around your neck. Trust the actual density of these pieces to anchor your proportions when visibility drops. Shadows obscure visual choices, making mass your only reliable anchor. Routine evening errands require the identical level of commitment. Carry your warm atmosphere into every mundane interaction.",
      "sectionIntro": "Calibrate your high-contrast signature for close quarters without sacrificing your momentum.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat a Tuesday morning trip to the greengrocer exactly as you treat an opening night. Buying groceries does not require packing away your boldest pieces. Apply your baseline equation without exception. Your daily routine requires expansive colour + fast movement + one theatrical finish. Pull on a warm golden camel jumper over a crisp cotton poplin shirt. Add polished bronze boots and a stacked assortment of silver and brass rings. Do not dilute your palette or drop into matt basics just because the task is mundane. The pieces must propel you forward into your local streets. Step in front of the mirror. If the silhouette feels stagnant, swap the shoe for glossy patent leather.",
      "sectionIntro": "Dictate the terms of your ordinary days with absolute visual consistency.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Mix {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} with total freedom. Stack them across your rings, buckles, and zips. The secret to this collision is a relentless commitment to high shine. Reject the {excluded_finish} trap. Aged, beaten, or oxidised surfaces read as sluggish and dull. Demand completely glossy warm metal that glints clearly from the opposite pavement. When evaluating a new chain, lift the item directly. Evaluate it by its sheer gravity in your palm. If a piece lacks the heavy, undeniable mass needed to ground your fast movement, drop it back on the counter.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your stride with hardware that feels undeniably solid.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Demand {stone_1} and {stone_2} for your largest rings and pendants. Lift the piece to test its density. Judge large gems by how heavily they sit against your skin. You require substantial rocks to anchor your expansive colour. Seek out stones with absolute clarity that handle the light like a prism. Avoid tarnished, beaten, or artificially aged settings. They look fatigued and surrender their sharp edges. Rely strictly on high-gloss, warm metals that flash across the street. This blinding foundation provides the only correct stage for {stone_3}.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess your stones by their sheer density and how they bend the light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Test every piece of hardware by holding it in your palm. Close your fingers around a {metal_1} cuff or a ring set with {stone_1}. Gauge the object blindfolded. A lightweight hollow casting will rattle and dilute your impact. You require serious mass to anchor your aesthetic. Reject oxidised, hammered, or antiqued treatments. These artificially aged textures look entirely tired and rob your attire of its required crispness. Stay strictly in a polished warm metal that catches the light from afar. Whether you mix different alloys or commit to a single solid piece, this heavy gleam delivers one theatrical finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware by holding it blind and letting gravity dictate the outcome.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments establish the expansive colour and fast movement. Your accessories supply the one theatrical finish. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Put every addition through the audience check. Set the object on a table, retreat to the opposite wall, and check if its silhouette reads clearly. If it disappears into the background, leave it behind. Begin with statement eyewear. Seek out oversized acetate in a glossy warm tone. Grip the sides and check the resistance. The material must feel dense and hold a hard shine.",
      "sectionIntro": "Deploy your accessories as the final, deliberate punctuation of your outfit.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Statement eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "oversized acetate, glossy warm tone"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the stage test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Anchor your garments with a substantial belt. Reach for wide leather straps equipped with a massive polished brass buckle. The warm metal provides a hard focal point against an outfit of expansive colour. Apply the auditorium rule before you leave the house. Step back from the mirror and imagine projecting your presence to the back row of a busy community hall. If the brass does not catch the light and read clearly from that distance, it lacks the necessary scale. A highly polished reflection gives structure to your frame. Wear the wide belt to corral excess fabric so you maintain total physical freedom during fast movement.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select a bold belt to serve as a structural anchor rather than a simple utility.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Substantial belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide leather, massive polished brass buckle"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the stage test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your expansive colour using high-shine calfskin platforms. Look for rigid, polished surfaces. Avoid matt suede or porous leathers. Pick up the shoe and test the weight. It must feel substantial enough to ground deep bronze or golden camel garments. Mix gold and silver hardware freely over your warm layers. Before leaving, run the thirty-foot metric. Step back across the room from a full-length mirror. If the high shine on your footwear does not read instantly from afar, change the shoes.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your foundation pieces to ensure they anchor the silhouette and project your intent clearly.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "high-shine calfskin platform, high shine"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the stage test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Split your strategy between rigid and draped garments. Your tailored pieces demand stark woven geometry. Your fluid pieces require oversized, high-contrast prints to force fast movement through the silhouette. Demand uncompromising graphic execution. Deploy expansive colour within warm, sharply defined boundaries. Stand at the far end of a room and evaluate the garment. The motif must remain aggressively bold and entirely legible. If the shapes blur into an indistinct wash, drop the piece immediately. Trust your own physical instincts. Ignore the close-up mirror. Distance proves the scale. Memorise your pass-over list. Skip tiny dots and timid shapes. Leave {avoid_pattern_1} on the rack entirely. Instead, grab {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as a high-contrast structural tool to amplify your physical presence.",
      "tests": [
        "the twenty foot rule (bold and entirely legible from twenty feet)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Hang your {recommended_pattern_1} at the end of a long hallway. Pace back twenty feet and turn around. If the pattern degrades, leave the garment on the rail. You require absolute visual clarity from a distance. The print must remain bold and entirely legible to a friend spotting you from the opposite end of a train carriage. Test every printed piece against this strict metric. If the motif holds its polished edges and the palette stays distinctly warm, the garment passes. Trust the physical act of stepping back. A tight focus distorts reality. Proper perspective requires actual space. A successful piece delivers expansive colour without ever losing its sharp definition.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject your prints to a strict distance test before committing to them.",
      "tests": [
        "the twenty foot rule (bold and entirely legible from twenty feet)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_sagittarius__moon_scorpio__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "expansive colour + quiet undercurrent + one theatrical finish",
    "closing": "Trust the heavy drag of warm cloth to map your daily instincts, anchoring your geometry in expansive colour + quiet undercurrent + one theatrical finish.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the physical weight of a garment as your sensory compass. Pick it up and gauge the density of the weave. If the fabric feels hollow or floats away from your hand, put it back. Build slowly, deploy fast. Every successful combination relies on a strict ratio. You must combine expansive colour + quiet undercurrent + one theatrical finish. Picture a heavy, unlined coat resting over a dense, knitted tunic, finished with a single, oversized, architectural cuff at the wrist. The base pieces absorb light through a matt surface, allowing the warm fabric to anchor the final element.\n\nEvaluate every piece against the melt test before you commit. Put the garment on, close your eyes, and stand naturally. The cloth must melt completely into your frame. If a shoulder seam forces you upright or the hem demands constant manual adjustment, it fails. The garment must surrender its own structure to yours. Mix your metals freely to break up solid blocks of heavy textile. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assemble this core architecture in your mind before you acquire another garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your quiet undercurrent with materials that absorb light into a warm, matt surface. Hunt for {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Anchor your layers in {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Reach for {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth, and pick up {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. Always apply the melt test. Crush the fabric in your fist. It must pool back into your palm like heavy water rather than springing away in stiff creases. Rely on the heavy drag of the cloth to guide your choices. Visuals deceive, but mass tells the truth. With this yielding foundation, you can successfully balance expansive colour and support exactly one theatrical finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to locate the tactile foundation of your wardrobe.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
