    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift that {metal_1} cuff and let it rest in your palm. A lightweight casting feels hollow and instantly breaks the illusion. Examine the surface finish carefully. Brilliant, mirror-like polish glares harshly against warm, muted textiles. This sharp reflection disrupts the quiet undercurrent you need to anchor your wardrobe. Fix this clash by demanding brushed, hammered, or strictly matt hardware. A matt {stone_1} ring or a heavily brushed {metal_1} pendant absorbs light rather than fighting it. This softer exterior grounds the piece, letting its raw, physical mass do the work.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every piece of hardware by its physical mass and surface friction.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your accessories deliver the required one theatrical finish. Since your warm foundation relies on expansive colour and a quiet undercurrent, strict discipline is necessary. Limit your selection to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with handbags. Choose full-grain leather bags finished with brushed matt hardware. Run your thumb firmly across the surface of the hide to perform the tension test. The material must gather and wave slightly ahead of your pressure. Reject anything that stays flat or feels coated like rigid plastic. Genuine skin responds physically to tension. Let tactile resistance guide your final purchase.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish your accessory strategy by applying strict limits and testing every material by hand.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Anchor an expansive colour using a matt silk or fine wool scarf. Evaluate the surface before you commit to the accessory. Apply the wave test by gripping both ends and snapping a single wave down the length. Watch the material drop. The fabric must swallow the light in warm, heavy folds rather than bouncing a harsh glare back at you. If a dark mahogany weave shines when it moves, leave it on the rack. Require absolute fluidity from every woven piece you own.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hold your accessories to a strict tactile standard.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor the quiet undercurrent with a medium full-grain leather belt. Look for a matt buckle that absorbs light. For keepsake jewellery, seek out oxidised pieces in aged silver. Mix them directly with your warm metals. Toss the leather or the silver ring onto a dark mahogany washed silk shirt laid flat. Watch the surface tension. If the piece disrupts the fabric's natural flow or drags the eye too sharply, remove it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Lock down your finishing pieces and test their physical impact.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Maintain your quiet undercurrent through a strict low-contrast tonal code. Tailored jackets draw their structure from woven motifs like {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Fluid silk pieces take their scale from organic, liquid forms like {recommended_pattern_3}. When evaluating a printed cloth, observe the yardage in dim lighting. A successful motif will melt into the fibres, forming a warm, shifting shadow across the drape rather than glaring back as a flat graphic. Pass over sharp borders, high-contrast novelties, and anything stamped firmly onto a matt surface. Reject {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. Discard {avoid_pattern_2} the moment you detect harsh lines. Trust your fingertips over your eyes. Patterns integrated into the wool feel inseparable from the thread. Build visual density with {recommended_pattern_4}.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as an architectural tool to define your silhouette, never as a mere surface decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Run the dusk test on every print. Place any printed garment across the room in fading evening light to verify its depth. If {recommended_pattern_1} holds its shape as a sharp graphic, leave it on the rail. You want the lines to collapse into a warm, shifting haze. True quality in textile design relies on this deliberate dissolution. The motifs must melt into the base cloth. Establish a quiet undercurrent by selecting prints that surrender their hard edges to the shadows. Rigid borders betray cheap dye. Watch how the ink behaves as the illumination drops. When a pattern stays rigid in the dark, it fails.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your prints by observing how they behave as the light fades.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_sagittarius__moon_taurus__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "expansive colour + sensory comfort + one theatrical finish",
    "closing": "Dress purely by physical weight and warmth, measuring every garment against your ultimate standard: expansive colour + sensory comfort + one theatrical finish.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Let physical weight guide your choices. Run your palm across a garment to test its density. A piece must feel substantial before you even check the seams. Your fundamental equation is expansive colour + sensory comfort + one theatrical finish. Picture a heavy fluid knit tucked into a warm soft tailored trouser, anchored by a single oversized sculptural cuff. The garments provide absolute physical ease while the single focal point carries the visual weight.\n\nBuild this collection slowly. Wait for the precise matt finish and the exact warm undertone before acquiring a new piece. When evaluating a garment, apply the host test. Mimic reaching across a wide dining table to pour wine. If a sleeve restricts your movement or a waistband pinches, leave the item on the rack. The clothing must support total freedom of movement. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight and ease do not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise these foundational rules to filter out garments that look appealing on the hanger but fail in practice.",
      "tests": [
        "the host test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Prioritise sensory comfort above all else. Trust your hands when shopping. Squeeze {texture_good_1} in your prospective winter knits. It must compress and bounce back instantly. Hunt down {texture_good_3} for your tailored coats. These dense materials hold clean lines for decades. Reduce internal friction by wearing {texture_good_4} blouses and choosing jackets fully lined in the same fluid cloth. Perform the patina test on your accessories. Drag your thumbnail lightly across {texture_good_2} bags and belts. The surface should yield to pressure and absorb the oils from your skin. This proves it will mould to your shape with a warm, muted character instead of cracking under stress. Anchor your wardrobe in these selections.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test every fabric with your own hands before committing to a purchase.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
        {
          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the patina test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Avoid {texture_bad_1}. Pick it up and evaluate the friction. If it feels brittle or slides too quickly through your fingers, leave it on the rail. Reject {texture_bad_2} outright. It traps heat and reflects light in an artificial glare that disrupts any attempt at expansive colour. Run a structural check. Ask yourself if the material will soften and map to your shape over years of wear, or if it will simply peel and degrade. Even a piece built for one theatrical finish must possess enduring integrity. Rely on your grip to assess quality. Sight deceives the buyer. If the surface feels like a thin film waiting to crack, put it down.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify and reject materials that fail in the hand.",
      "tests": [
        "the patina test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to build your foundation. Pick up a {texture_good_1} garment and crumple it in your fist. Demand complete sensory comfort before you put it on your body. Scrutinise how the material will break in over time. A stiff fabric that peels or frays fails the evaluation. You require textiles that yield to your body heat and develop a richer, matt surface after months of heavy wear. Pair a thick, warm weave against a supple hide. This opposing weight provides structure without rigidity.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your outfits by balancing opposing weights.",
      "tests": [
        "the patina test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette runs permanently warm. Build your daily foundation around {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Bridge these deep bases with {core_colour_3} and {core_colour_4}. When you want expansive colour, deploy {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as your single deliberate accent. Keep your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly to break up dense cashmere or wool. Pass completely over icy electric blue, neon brights, and fleeting trend pastels. Watch for the heavy sink. Layering {core_colour_1} over {core_colour_2} in entirely matt fabrics can swallow your frame. Lift this visual density immediately. Add a lighter neutral layer at the collar, introduce a single piece of heavy full-grain leather, or deploy your relief tone.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your wardrobe in the exact tones that support your physical frame.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rich toffee",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
