          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the all-earth sink: brown on olive on bark, all matt and all heavy, can swallow you whole",
          "fix": "lift it: an oatmeal cream layer at the collar, one piece of polished leather, or the washed blue relief"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let sensory comfort dictate your foundation at work. Build your base in cashmere and brushed wool to establish physical ease. Support this foundation with broad applications of your warmest tones, like camel and rich toffee, to flood the eye without overwhelming it. Reserve your single theatrical detail for a silk blouse or a heavy full-grain leather belt. Treat every morning with the exact same tailoring standard. Buying milk at the local shop demands the identical clean fit you require for a Monday meeting. Maintain a matt presentation on all your garments. Choose mixed metals for your rings to anchor the styling. Avoid anything high-shine or stiff. Rely on your hands to evaluate the drape before putting anything on your body.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the mechanics of dressing for your working hours.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, sensory comfort takes the lead. Dim lighting obscures fine tailoring. Rely on your fingertips to judge a garment. Appearance alters in the shadows, but the heavy drape of full-grain leather reveals the truth. Look for warm layers in camel or rich toffee. Avoid shiny materials. Pick up a piece of matt silk and let it absorb the ambient glow. Stepping out to collect the post requires the exact same draped cashmere as a private supper. Combine your metals without hesitation. Pair a heavy gold chain with a brass cuff.",
      "sectionIntro": "Calibrate your wardrobe for low light and close proximity.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Never suspend your baseline for a simple errand. Waiting on a train platform warrants a heavy brushed wool coat in rich toffee. Walking the dog demands the tailored drape of a heavy canvas trouser. Trust items that feel soft against the skin and hold their structure under pressure. Knot a warm camel silk scarf at the collar. Your baseline remains expansive colour + sensory comfort + one theatrical finish. Mix a matt gold pendant with a hammered copper ring. Apply this routine every day.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your daily routine as the primary proving ground for your aesthetic rules.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "You have complete freedom to mix your metals. Layer {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} across your hands and wrists. This warm blend grounds your garments and provides one theatrical finish without disturbing the overall balance. Keep your textures controlled. High-glare, mirrored hardware slices harshly through soft {core_colour_1} fabrics. Stick entirely to matt and brushed surfaces to maintain cohesion, avoiding {excluded_finish} altogether. When evaluating a thick chain or a dense belt buckle, pick the item up in your palm. Ignore the high-glare lighting of a boutique. A solid brass casting pulls firmly against your muscles. A flimsy, hollow piece ruins the structure of a coat. Rely on the heavy, dragging pull of solid metal to verify its quality.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hardware dictates the final read of your garments through texture, heft, and temperature.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Lift the hardware in your bare palm. Base your gemstone decisions entirely on mass. True density grounds a heavy cashmere sweater. You require heavy pieces like {stone_1}, {stone_2}, and {stone_3}. They anchor your foundation and provide a solid base for expansive colour. A gleaming mirror polish cuts harshly against your brushed wool. A highly reflective setting breaks the visual flow. Demand matt or softly brushed metals to maintain absolute harmony. Only accept stones that absorb warm light rather than throwing blinding reflections.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones by their density and light absorption to ensure they ground your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the {metal_1} cuff from the velvet display tray. Judge the piece by its heft. A substantial object sinks directly into the palm of your hand. If the item feels hollow or lightweight, leave it on the glass. Highly reflective, mirrored surfaces clash severely against the {core_colour_1} brushed wool of your outerwear. Glossy metals disrupt the sensory comfort of your garments. Always require a matt or brushed finish. This subdued texture anchors your look and allows you to mix {metal_1} alongside warm brass or copper without friction.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate the weight and texture of your hardware with your hands before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You have built your wardrobe on expansive colour and secured your physical ease through sensory comfort. Now, anchor these elements with one theatrical finish. Accessories execute this final step. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with handbags. Demand thick, full-grain leather bodies finished with brushed matt hardware. When combining these items, rely on the one-ember test. Stand before a mirror and locate the single point of visual heat. Against a muted foundation of camel wool and rich toffee silk, your mixed metal jewellery or heavy brass buckle should provide a solitary, glowing focal point. If a second accessory competes for that warm spark, remove it immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your accessories by selecting solitary points of heat that ground your wardrobe without overwhelming it.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Evaluate scarves strictly by touch before looking at the tag. Trust your fingers to identify pure silk or fine wool. Drop the fabric immediately if it catches the light. You require a completely matt surface. Apply the daylight dye check to verify the saturation. Pin the textile against a bright pane of glass and search for a persistent heat buried inside the threads. A genuine warm piece holds a hidden spark in its depths, much like the final glowing coal in an open hearth. A camera alters hues, but your hands do not. If you cannot locate that fire, leave the item on the rail. This layer exists strictly to deliver absolute sensory comfort.",
      "sectionIntro": "Handle your scarves with unforgiving physical scrutiny.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your clothing with medium full-grain leather belts, insisting on a strictly matt buckle. They must sit quietly against your camel cashmere and brushed wool. For keepsake jewellery, seek out aged silver and oxidised metals. Mix these finishes freely. Prioritise sensory comfort when judging the weight of a thick ring or a heavy pendant. Pick it up and feel the density in your palm. Before finishing, run the solitary spark rule. You want exactly one point of warm light against your clothing. If an oxidised silver pendant draws the eye, ensure your belt buckle remains entirely flat and dull. One spark is enough.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select deliberate hardware to ground your fabrics, and run a final diagnostic check before stepping out.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored pieces take their pattern from the loom itself. Look for a {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2} woven directly into heavy cloth. Fluid garments carry their pattern on the surface. Pick up a silk blouse and search for a {recommended_pattern_3} printed in a soft, matt finish. Keep your pattern contrast low and tonal. High-contrast graphics break your register. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1}, {avoid_pattern_2}, and any stiff printed cottons. Subdued motifs secure your sensory comfort. They also provide a quiet backdrop when you apply one theatrical finish. Always use the firelight test. Take the textile into a dim corner away from overhead glare. A worthy pattern will deepen and turn warm under lamplight. A failing print simply flattens into a harsh silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every printed or woven textile by its contrast level and structural form.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Subject every {recommended_pattern_1} to the shadow check. Move away from overhead fixtures and examine the fabric under a desk lamp. The print must deepen into the shadows and grow warm, losing its sharp edges. If the shapes stay stark or turn flat in low lighting, reject the garment entirely. A matt surface requires an underlying richness to survive dim environments without looking completely lifeless. Trust your hands to confirm the weave provides strict sensory comfort while your eyes evaluate the visual depth. When the motif blurs into a cohesive, quiet shadow, you know the piece is correct.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject your prints to a strict environmental test to ensure they behave properly in low lighting.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_scorpio__moon_aries__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "close drape + sharp edges + one warm point of light",
    "closing": "Trust your hands to find the heaviest cloth, rely on your eye to verify the geometry, and anchor your entire silhouette in close drape + sharp edges + one warm point of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Assess every garment by its immediate structural feedback. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Pick it up and feel the density of the cloth against the sharpness of its cut. Apply the radius test to every piece before you commit to it. Step away from the mirror and close your eyes. If the garment requires an audience to justify its striking shape, take it off. It must hold its power within a three-foot radius of your own body, completely independent of external validation. Build your collection slowly and strictly for yourself. Deploy it rapidly without seeking a second opinion.\n\nYour foundation relies on high-contrast tension. Your core style formula is close drape + sharp edges + one warm point of light. Picture a heavyweight fluid shirt wrapping tightly around the ribs, anchored by stiff trousers tailored with a severe, razor-sharp crease. Finish the geometry with a solitary, highly polished warm metal accessory catching the ambient glare at the collar. Rely on this exact combination when your instincts waver. A bold finish demands absolute commitment. Mix matt cloth against high-shine hardware to maintain the necessary visual heat without tipping into costume.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation, the absolute baseline you must return to whenever a garment leaves you doubting your own eye.",
      "tests": [
        "the radius test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your foundation on textiles that engineer sharp edges without constant pressing. Seek out {texture_good_1} for shirts that snap visually alongside {texture_good_2} for tailoring that holds a rigid line. Rely on the recoil test in the fitting room. Crush a sleeve in your fist and release it. If the fabric springs back smooth, it will serve you. If it stays crumpled, leave it. Let your hands verify the truth. Appearance deceives, but sheer density never lies. Contrast these structural bases with {texture_good_4} cut for a close drape that gleams under low light. Anchor the combination with {texture_good_3} in your footwear to provide exactly one warm point of light. Pull exclusively from the hierarchy of materials below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your physical presence in textiles that hold their own shape and demand zero coddling.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "sharp shirting that holds a crease and snaps visually"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sharp wool twill",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "knife-edge tailoring that never begs for a steamer"
        },
        {
          "name": "Patent leather",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "statement footwear and accessories that reflect maximum light"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk satin",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "slip dresses and linings that gleam under low light"
        },
        {
          "name": "Techno gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "wrinkle-resistant trousers and jackets that keep a rigid shape"
        },
        {
          "name": "High-shine taffeta",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "evening pieces that bounce light and cut a clear silhouette"
        },
        {
          "name": "Polished calfskin",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "footwear and accessories with a slick, radiant surface"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the bounce test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Pick up {texture_bad_1} and flick the material. If the cloth swallows the impact rather than pushing back, it will never hold your sharp edges. Reject it entirely. Run your bare palm down {texture_bad_2}. If the surface drags against your skin instead of gliding flat, it will snag on itself and ruin a close drape. Leave {texture_bad_3} on the rack if it yields under mild pulling like damp paper. These weak materials lack the tension required for bold expression. They cannot ground your warm details. Demand fibres that resist your grip.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify the fabrics that sabotage your shape before you even try them on.",
      "tests": [
        "the bounce test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "You need fabrics that refuse to surrender their shape. Twist the hem of a garment tightly. If the wrinkles remain embedded, drop the piece immediately. You want a vigorous recovery that resets to its original form. Match {sweet_spot_keyword_1} directly with {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. This establishes the sharp edges you require. Bring in {texture_good_1} to enforce close drape over your frame. Keep the physical footprint strictly contained to your own proportions. Finish with a heavy solid metal element to cast exactly one warm point of light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test every fabric for a strict physical recoil before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "the bounce test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe must operate on a warm frequency. Construct the primary architecture using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} for structural blocks. Ground these deep shades with {core_colour_3} and {core_colour_4}. Once the base is set, inject {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as a single deliberate jolt. Hold your relief tone in reserve, deploying it solely to grant the eye a brief rest. Bypass muddy pastel, icy grey, and dusty sage entirely. Avoid the trap of an oppressive, shadow-heavy block that swallows your frame. Break open that dark monotony by maintaining sharp edges and slicing the silhouette with a heavy polished metal cuff for one warm point of light, or a stark shoe in {accent_colour_2}. Demand close drape from the cloth, and let the sudden colour take control.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your palette by controlling heat and absolute contrast.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Deep bronze",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Golden camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
