    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let sharp edges lead your working hours. Build your foundation from crisp cotton poplin collars and severe wool twill trousers. Support these strict lines using the close drape of heavy silk satin underlayers. Keep the finishes mixed. Pair a high-shine patent leather shoe with a matt bronze buckle to establish one warm point of light. A rushed commute over wet pavements does not mean giving up your exact proportions. Avoid throwing on an oversized knit just because the morning is cold. Trust your hands to select dense woven materials that hold their own shape. Pick up a tailored jacket and feel the shoulder line. If the sleeve collapses, leave it on the rack. Rely on deep bronze and warm golden camel to ground the outfit. Let the strict cuts do the work.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your working wardrobe around the pieces that demand strict focus.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim light and close settings, dictate the mood through precise boundaries. Choose heavy silk satin cut with strict, defined shoulders to maintain sharp edges. Avoid anything loose or blurred. Run your thumb under the lapel. If the structure yields under minimal pressure, leave the piece behind. You need a rigid border even in an unlit space. Mix high-shine leather with deep bronze wool twill, finishing with solid gold jewellery for exactly one warm point of light. Sharing a late evening drink does not require dropping your exact proportions. Keep the silhouette uncompromising and tight. Throw out faded lounge trousers. Replace them with heavy golden camel cotton poplin. Never settle for entirely matt surfaces. You must preserve a self-contained, close drape whether you sit at a formal dining table or recline on a sofa.",
      "sectionIntro": "Command your proportions and finishes across intimate distances and low lighting.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Standing in the queue at the post office requires the exact same discipline as an evening out. A Saturday morning at the local market does not give you permission to abandon proportion for shapeless jersey. Enforce your boundaries daily with crisp cotton poplin that holds its structure against the skin. Pick garments that maintain a strict internal geometry rather than bleeding into the space around you. Anchor the morning routine with the absolute baseline of close drape + sharp edges + one warm point of light. A solid block of golden camel or a deep bronze ring serves as that required beacon. Keep your silhouette strict and self-contained. Every ordinary Tuesday errand is a mandate to keep your physical framework completely intact.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat everyday errands as rigorous tests of your chosen shapes.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your strategy is strictly warm. Anchor your garments in solid {metal_1}, {metal_2}, or {metal_3}. Test every clasp, chain, or zip under a stark, direct lamp. If the surface fails to throw a blinding, razor-sharp glare back at your eye, reject it. Avoid {excluded_finish} styles entirely. Hammered, tarnished, or intentionally aged surfaces look exhausted and destroy the clarity of your sharp edges. Instead, demand a highly polished finish that commands attention from the opposite pavement. Let this intense, concentrated hardware act as exactly one warm point of light against your close drape. Rely on your hands when inspecting pieces. Solid metal carries absolute density, while cheap alloys feel hollow.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your hardware as a deliberate structural weapon.",
      "tests": [
        "the reflection rule: hold the hardware under a direct light source; if it does not produce a sharp, blinding reflection, it is too dull"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Let sheer gravity be the true judge of quality. A lightweight stone indicates a fragile construction. Demand bold, unyielding settings for {stone_1} and {stone_2}. Execute the prism test before any purchase. Hold the gem up to a natural window. It must capture the incoming rays and project a singular, focused beam of colour. If the light scatters into dullness, the facet is useless. Bypass clouded or deliberately opaque treatments. They drag the aesthetic into fatigue and kill the crispness of your sharp edges. Insist on a strictly smooth, polished warm metal that flashes fiercely across a crowded room. Let these dense stones act as exactly one warm point of light to anchor the close drape of your garments.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate the exact density and light return of your stones to guarantee maximum impact.",
      "tests": [
        "the reflection rule: hold the hardware under a direct light source; if it does not produce a sharp, blinding reflection, it is too dull"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Gauge the heft of a piece before trying it on. Genuine materials verify their own quality through sheer mass. Next, expose the {metal_1} to direct daylight. If the surface absorbs the glow rather than rebounding a fierce, white-hot flash, put it down. Antiqued or artificially distressed finishes read as weak against your close drape. Insist on high-gloss, warm hardware that cuts through the visual noise from fifty yards away. This guarantees the sharp edges of your silhouette remain anchored by exactly one warm point of light, rather than fading into hollow decoration.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this physical test to strip away weak hardware before it compromises your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "the reflection rule: hold the hardware under a direct light source; if it does not produce a sharp, blinding reflection, it is too dull"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories deliver the one warm point of light that completes your close drape and sharp edges. Restrict yourself to a single definitive piece per look. Apply the gallery test before stepping outside. Put the item on and back away from the mirror. If the shape fails to project its geometry across a vast empty hall, take it off. Start your collection with structural jewellery. Look for a thick gold cuff forged over a blackened base with a mixed finish. Balance the item on your wrist to verify its substantial mass. The striking contrast between matt darkness and bright polished warm metal provides the exact definition your self-contained silhouette requires.",
      "sectionIntro": "Here is how you punctuate your outfits using metal and weight.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Statement jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "gold cuff over blackened base, mixed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the stage test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Ground the sharp edges of a heavy wool trouser with a stiff leather boot. Look for blackened hardware paired with a single gloss detail, perhaps a polished bronze buckle or a thick resin heel to serve as one warm point of light. Your physical response is the only metric that matters, so check the rigidity of the sole by trying to bend it with both hands. It should resist completely. Next, evaluate the finish under a targeted spotlight. If the gloss detail throws a bright, warm reflection while the surrounding leather sinks into a deep matt texture, keep the boot. If the shoe washes out into a flat, indistinct mass, leave it on the shelf. Build your close drape on this deliberate contrast.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your footwear choices in physical density and exact material contrasts.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "leather boot, blackened hardware with one gloss detail"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the stage test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select structured bags constructed from rigid leather in a warm golden camel. Look for blackened brass fittings and one highly polished pull to serve as exactly one warm point of light. Clean, sharp edges demand absolute precision. Ensure the surrounding garments maintain their close drape without bunching around the strap. Before leaving the room, test the boundary lines. Retreat to the opposite wall and examine the entire silhouette. The bag must remain entirely separate from the coat's outline at twenty paces. If the leather merges into your jacket and loses its distinct geometry, the accessory fails. Swap it for a piece that enforces its own borders.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finish the foundation by interrogating your carrying pieces before you leave the house.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Structured bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "rigid leather, gunmetal fittings, one polished pull"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the stage test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored garments derive their power from precise geometry. Look for a bold {recommended_pattern_1} that reinforces sharp edges rather than softening them. Fluid pieces demand sweeping scale. Choose an oversized {recommended_pattern_2} that settles into a continuous close drape without fracturing the line. You require high-contrast graphic tension to anchor your warm palette. Test every motif across the shop floor. If the design bleeds into an indistinct wash at fifteen paces, leave it on the rail. A successful print must remain utterly definitive from a distance. Pass over any blurred {avoid_pattern_1} or delicate {avoid_pattern_2}. They lack the necessary physical force. A weak print telegraphs its flimsiness the second you look at it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as a structural element, choosing scale and contrast to reinforce your geometry.",
      "tests": [
        "the twenty foot rule (bold and entirely legible from twenty feet)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Examine {recommended_pattern_1} through a camera lens. Photograph the garment from across the room and check the screen. The motif must remain utterly sharp and legible when reduced to a two-inch image. If the lines dissolve into a chaotic blur, leave the item on the rack. Your aesthetic requires absolute visual clarity. Demand stark internal contrast within the print itself. Anchor this uncompromising graphic weight with close drape. Enforce sharp edges across the collar, and finish the look with exactly one warm point of light at the throat. You require definitive borders, never vague suggestions.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every motif to a strict distance evaluation.",
      "tests": [
        "the twenty foot rule (bold and entirely legible from twenty feet)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_sagittarius__moon_virgo__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "expansive colour + honest fabric + one theatrical finish",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on expansive colour + honest fabric + one theatrical finish.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the physical sensation of adaptability as your compass. If a garment feels rigid or locks you into a single silhouette, drop it. Ground your choices in a warm palette. Build every look on expansive colour + honest fabric + one theatrical finish. Picture a dense woven jacket over a fluid knit foundation, anchored by heavy boots and capped with a single highly reflective accessory. The foundations ground the outfit. The final touch disrupts it.\n\nDrift by mood and build your wardrobe to shift gears daily. Apply the combination test before acquiring anything new. Pick the garment up and ask your hands if it can pivot from a structured daytime layer to an unstructured evening drape. If it demands an exact supporting cast to function, leave it on the hanger. Trust your physical instincts over any mirror. Looks lie. Weight and adaptability do not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat these directives as your absolute baseline for assessing any garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the combination test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your foundation relies on an honest fabric to anchor your warm palette. Pull a cuff away from your skin and release it. If it snaps back instantly with zero memory of the stretch, it passes the snap test. Let the sheer heft of the garment guide your choices. Look for {texture_good_1} to give your shirting pure separation and clean architectural boundaries. For base layers that sit close to the body, demand {texture_good_2} to maintain sharp lines through a long day. Anchor your lower half in {texture_good_3} so your trousers drop cleanly from the waist. Finish with {texture_good_4} for mobile outerwear that blocks the wind without dragging you down. An honest fabric holds expansive colour without fighting it. Build your foundation from the materials below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Let the fibre do the physical work before you even consider the cut.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Avoid {texture_bad_1} that catches on your cuticles. Subject any stretchy {texture_bad_2} to the recoil test. Stretch the textile across your knuckles and let it go. It must recover its original shape instantly. If it slumps or ripples against your warm skin, drop the garment. Your wardrobe requires reliable materials to anchor one theatrical finish. {texture_bad_3} routinely fails here, promising structure in the shop but melting over your shoulders within an hour. Trust your fingertips to detect a cheap weave. If it feels lifeless in your grip, it will hang dead on your back.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject what your eyes might forgive.",
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your sweet spot requires the exact tension between {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Examine a piece of {texture_good_1}. Tug the bias firmly between your thumbs. The material must crack back into shape at once. That immediate recovery proves you have found an honest fabric. Pair this crisp structural integrity against heavier, matt knits. Warm tones need this tactile friction to avoid looking flat. Bypass weaves that slump lazily under tension. Rely on your fingers. If the cloth feels limp or hesitant, discard it. Your best pieces will always push back against your grip.",
      "sectionIntro": "Combine surfaces that demand interaction from your hands.",
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your temperature runs warm. Build your base using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} as primary grounding elements. Treat {core_colour_3} as your strict white substitute. Deploy {core_colour_4} as a bridge when shifting into cooler pairings. Test these tones in natural light. Introduce your deliberate accent through {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Rely on a soft note used sparingly to provide visual relief. Pass over icy pastel, neon brights, and cold blue-grey. They strip depth from your look. Beware assembling a dull single-tone uniform that drains your focus before lunch. Break that monotony. Pull a crisp cotton poplin cuff past your sleeve, slide on a dense mixed-metal ring, or step into a vivid technical nylon trainer. Execute your strategy with expansive colour. Rely on physical texture to make flat shades sing.",
      "sectionIntro": "Identify the tones that serve your structure, trusting the dye to do the heavy lifting while you assemble the layers.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Warm taupe",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
