    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, sharp edges take the lead. Let the precise lines of a boiled wool jacket or heavy silk crepe trousers set the perimeter. The remaining elements sit beneath to keep you contained. Anchor these structural pieces with close drape in washed silk. Remember that a tense quarterly review or a delayed train does not require surrendering your thickest knits to stiff corporate uniforms. Add just a single warm gleam of dual-register metal at the wrist or collar. Keep all surfaces matt to absorb the office lights.",
      "sectionIntro": "Let us establish the rules of engagement for your working hours.",
      "tests": [
        "a school run or a corner shop dash does not require surrendering your softness (Cove)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "Let close drape lead when the lights go down. Sharp edges disappear in shadow. Rely on the feel of washed silk or dense cashmere against your collarbone. Choose deep, rich tones that fall seamlessly against the body. A late evening indoors does not mean you must forfeit your soft boundaries. If a piece feels stiff or restrictive, take it off immediately. Fasten a muted bronze clasp to catch whatever warm ambient glow remains. Prioritise the heavy fall of cardigans and how they move with your limbs in tight spaces.",
      "sectionIntro": "Navigate intimate quarters by letting touch replace projection.",
      "tests": [
        "a school run or a corner shop dash does not require surrendering your softness (Cove)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A hurried trip to the chemist does not require compromising for convenience. Anchor your daily choices in bitter chocolate and dark mahogany. Choose fluid tops that fit neatly. Pair them with tailored trousers to establish strict borders. Your daily rule never changes. You must build every outfit using close drape + sharp edges + one warm point of light. If a jumper feels sloppy on the shoulder, remove it. Finish the look with a small brass hoop or a rose gold stud. Treat a Tuesday morning with the exact same discipline as an evening out. Maintain your self-contained presentation at all times.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish strict rules for ordinary mornings and never lower your standards for convenience.",
      "tests": [
        "a school run or a corner shop dash does not require surrendering your softness (Cove)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your hardware strategy splits strictly into two functional lanes. For the structural architecture of your clothing, including buckles, zips, and heavy bag clasps, rely entirely on {structural_metal_1} and {structural_metal_2}. Keep personal jewellery worn against the skin confined to {personal_metal_1} or {personal_metal_2}. Anchor this system with careful texture choices. A brilliant, mirror-polished surface creates a jarring distraction next to soft colours. Reject {excluded_finish} and high-shine pieces outright. Demand brushed or matt textures to keep the visual cohesion intact. When evaluating a new piece, lift it off the glass counter. If a clasp or ring feels hollow, abandon it. Dense hardware provides the sharp edges required to ground your warm wardrobe.",
      "sectionIntro": "Mastering your hardware requires dividing your metals into two distinct jobs.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Assess the gravity of a stone in your palm. Select dense, opaque gems like {stone_1} and {stone_2} that draw focus inward rather than relying on a transparent sparkle. High-gloss hardware will pierce your muted garments with a distracting glare. Ground your selections entirely in brushed metals to lock the composition together. Demand sharp edges in the setting to contain the stone. This creates a self-contained, warm anchor built specifically for you.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones through their physical density and their inward capacity to hold light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Test the physical heft of a {metal_1} piece before wearing it. Camera flashes cast a harsh glare over warm palettes. Drop bright mirror polishing entirely. Anchor your hardware in flat, matt textures to ensure the jewellery aligns seamlessly with your garments. A heavy {stone_1} ring or a solid cuff grounds your silhouette. Combine this density with the close drape of your clothing. Use solid forms to build sharp edges at your wrists and collar.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware through physical mass and surface finish rather than sight alone.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories execute the final phase. Build your close drape, define the sharp edges, and then place one warm point of light. Commit to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with handbags. Demand full-grain leather or thick suede. Seek out matt brushed hardware. Apply the anchor test before buying. Trust your physical instincts. Pick the bag up in your hands. Does it pull your centre of gravity down into the floorboards? If the density firmly settles your stance, keep it. If the item feels hollow or rests lightly on top of your garments, leave it on the shelf. Visuals deceive, but pure mass tells the truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hardware and leather require strict physical testing before they join your wardrobe.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "When selecting scarves, insist on generous washed silk or fine boiled wool. Demand a strictly matt finish. Apply the anchor test before leaving the shop. Wrap the textile and evaluate its drape over your shoulders. The material must pull your awareness inward with a satisfying, warm heft. Fold the fabric to construct sharp edges framing the jaw. Avoid anything that floats away from the collarbone. Render this piece in your darkest core tones to secure a strictly self-contained silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your final layers through strict physical criteria to ground your silhouette.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select wide full-grain leather belts fastened with a matt brushed buckle to introduce sharp edges to your trousers. Keep your keepsake jewellery heavy. Pick up a deep warm stone set in oxidised brass or aged silver. Run the anchor test as your final step. Identify the heaviest item you are wearing. If this piece feels like a distraction rather than a grounding weight, take it off entirely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finish your silhouette with definitive hardware and a strict elimination test.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored pieces pull their visual structure from {recommended_pattern_1}. Fluid garments rely on {recommended_pattern_2} to ground the fabric. Keep your choices strictly low-contrast and tonal. You need sharp edges to define your silhouette, and a high-contrast surface instantly destroys those lines. Pass over distinct geometric borders and large graphic prints. Walk directly past {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. Test any pattern in dim lighting. A successful print does not fight for attention in the shadows. Instead, the individual motifs will blur, merging into a warm, deep texture. If the shapes remain starkly visible as the light fades, the contrast is too high. Leave the garment behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control the eye by building texture, not by adding noise.",
      "tests": [
        "the twilight test (merge into a rich, deep texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate {recommended_pattern_1} by hanging the garment across the room as evening falls. Turn down the lamps and step back. The individual lines of the print must completely dissolve. In low light, the contrast should recede into the background, leaving only the appearance of a heavy, interwoven surface. A highly visible graphic disrupts the continuous geometry of your clothing. You need a design that collapses into a warm, dimensional shadow. Grasp the fabric in the dark. Let tactile reality guide your choices. When the visual boundaries melt away entirely, the garment will preserve your close drape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the twilight check to separate true texture from distracting graphics.",
      "tests": [
        "the twilight test (merge into a rich, deep texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_scorpio__moon_cancer__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "close drape + hidden depth + one warm point of light",
    "closing": "Trust your hands to guide every garment choice, building your wardrobe strictly upon close drape + hidden depth + one warm point of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Assess the weight of the fabric before you look at the garment. Your sensory compass relies on dense, matt textiles that absorb light rather than reflect it. Pick up a piece and feel for a heavy, grounding drop. Look for cuts that stay close to the frame without clinging. Your exact blueprint is close drape + hidden depth + one warm point of light. Picture a heavyweight gauge knit sweater sitting perfectly flush under a structured, thick weave overcoat, anchored by a single piece of glowing hardware at the wrist. The garments do all the structural work. Avoid anything that balloons away from your body.\n\nBuild your collection at a slow, deliberate tempo, but deploy your chosen garments immediately. Spend months finding the exact cut that satisfies your strict physical criteria. When you try something on, close your eyes and evaluate the friction against your skin. If the weave feels hollow or the structure compromises your posture, heed that immediate physical rejection and leave the piece on the rack. Your visual language is entirely self-contained. You dress only to satisfy your own rigorous parameters. Trust this tactile response as your absolute guide. A mirror can deceive your eyes. The sheer weight of an object never lies.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master this core physical logic before you evaluate another garment.",
      "tests": [
        "trust your gut and walk away"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your textiles must build a self-contained climate. Seek out {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight, creating one warm point of light against a matt foundation. Choose {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Pick up {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Anchor your close drape with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. Apply a strict oxygen check to new garments. Press the material directly against your mouth and inhale deeply. If the fibres stifle your lungs, drop the piece. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Let the density of the cloth overrule the sales tag.",
