          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the sofa drift: soften every piece far enough and one day you are simply in loungewear",
          "fix": "restore exactly one line: a rolled but real lapel, a trouser with a soft crease, or a firm leather bag against all that give"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Enforce a close drape at the office. A crowded train carriage never justifies abandoning fitted proportions for shapeless volume. Select garments that map directly to the body. Rely on the heavy drop of brushed wool and the matt finish of rich toffee leather to establish your physical boundaries. Grasp the textile to verify its density. Heavy silk and thick camel cashmere deliver the self-contained structure you require. A solitary muted gold ring or a discrete bronze cuff provides one warm point of light. This combination guarantees softness without sacrificing professional architecture.",
      "sectionIntro": "Here is your framework for navigating the working day.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "Dim lighting demands strict adherence to close drape. Build an evening silhouette around warm, muted camel cashmere that maps your frame precisely. Avoid bulky coats that construct a wall between you and the table. Enforce exact boundaries at dinner. Introduce dual-register metals to the collarbone. Mix matt gold and polished silver to capture ambient illumination, securing one warm point of light against the skin. Lift the fabric by the hem to test its plunge. Heavy silk drops vertically, providing undeniable softness and keeping your self-contained outline strictly defined.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use these directives to navigate evening settings and hold your shape in dim light.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Errands demand the same structural discipline as an evening out. Never surrender your silhouette to oversized fleece while standing in a chemist queue. Construct a daily uniform with deliberate intent. Pull on matt cashmere in a warm camel and add brushed wool trousers in rich toffee. Step into full-grain leather footwear. Contrast a silver watch dial with a yellow gold ring to maintain dual-register interest. Reject any compromise to this baseline. Build every outfit around close drape + softness + one warm point of light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your daily routine as an exact discipline.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your hardware runs on two separate tracks. Treat your jewellery as personal metal worn directly against the skin. Restrict these intimate pieces to {personal_metal_1} or {personal_metal_2}. For structural necessities like zips, belt buckles, and bag clasps, shift to {structural_metal_1} or {structural_metal_2}. This deliberate division prevents visual noise. Never accept {excluded_finish}. Glossy hardware flashes harshly and breaks the harmony of your muted, warm palette. Demand a matt or brushed surface instead to anchor your close drape. Weigh every buckle and clasp before purchasing. Assess the gravity in your palm. Dense, unpolished hardware secures the garment and grounds your self-contained aesthetic.",
      "sectionIntro": "Mastering your hardware requires a strict physical hierarchy.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Hold {stone_1}, {stone_2}, and {stone_3} in your palm to confirm their opaque, warm density. A genuine mineral carries undeniable gravity. If the piece feels hollow or light, reject it entirely. Bypass highly reflective chrome or polished silver settings. Glaring surfaces slice aggressively through the muted softness of your knits. Require matt metals and heavy stones to secure one warm point of light without breaking your self-contained boundaries.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones by their pure physical density to ensure they ground your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Let gravity deliver the final verdict on {metal_1}. A heavy fastener anchors the entire outfit. Watch out for high-shine finishes that flash aggressively against the tactile softness of your garments. Mirrored glare shatters the self-contained mood of a close drape. Prevent this by demanding a muted, matt surface or a brushed texture. If you incorporate a piece of {stone_1}, ensure the surrounding bezel shares this subdued treatment. You are constructing a uniform, not hanging a mirror.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the weight test to all hardware to ensure your choices anchor the garment rather than distract from it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories secure your final variable. Your garments establish close drape and softness. Your leather and hardware must deliver one warm point of light. Adhere to the principle of one or two strong pieces per look. A sturdy belt or a heavy strap holds enough gravity to ground an entire outfit. Begin with handbags. Select full-grain leather or thick suede finished with matt brushed hardware. Ignore the shop display and test the structure directly. Prove the material by executing the hide check. Press your thumbs deep into the leather. A rich skin gathers into a slow, heavy wave, while a cheap surface folds sharply.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the final variable of your formula by selecting hardware and leather that test heavy in the hand.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Require generous silk or fine wool scarves in completely matt finishes. Choose deep camel or rich toffee dyes that remain strictly warm. You are looking for absolute softness against the neck. Always execute the drop test. Gather the textile in your fist and release it over a wooden counter. A suitable fabric pools smoothly into a fluid puddle. If the item forms sharp ridges or resists gravity, leave it behind. Your wardrobe demands accessories that achieve close drape without friction. The fibres must yield instantly to the shape of your collarbone. Reject any surface sheen.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your scarves based purely on how the material yields under tension.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select wide belts in full-grain leather secured with a matt brushed buckle. Choose keepsake jewellery featuring a warm, deep stone set in oxidised brass or aged silver. These pieces must anchor the softness of your garments without fighting them. Evaluate the tension with your own hands. Fasten the belt over a cashmere layer and shift your weight. If the thick hide or heavy metal distorts the knit and breaks your close drape, the accessory acts as a cage. Remove it immediately. The garment must fall flush against your body, allowing the hardware to act solely as one warm point of light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finish your foundations with functional pieces that honour your need for unbroken lines.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor your decisions in softness. Maintain a strict low-contrast, tonal approach to pattern to keep your silhouette self-contained. Tailored items take their structure from woven scales like {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Fluid pieces draw their movement from continuous, muted motifs like {recommended_pattern_3}. Pass over high-contrast graphics, sharp borders, and erratic geometries. Leave the {avoid_pattern_1} on the rail. Run the dusk test. Observe the fabric in fading daylight. If the motif settles into a warm, moving texture as the room dims, keep the item. If the lines remain stark, drop it. Your pattern choices must always serve close drape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master pattern by treating it as an extension of texture, never a disruption.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Test {recommended_pattern_1} under failing light. Hang the garment in shadows, step back, and squint. The design must blur into a warm, shifting texture. If the shapes maintain sharp edges, walk away. Your aesthetic relies entirely on softness. Rigid geometry fights the body and destroys your self-contained boundaries. Demand a close drape that pulls the motif directly into the fabric structure. A matt weave diffuses harsh contrast. If the scale looks stiff in the dark, it will feel stiff on your shoulders.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every print to a strict environmental threshold before it touches your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_scorpio__moon_gemini__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "close drape + light movement + one warm point of light",
    "closing": "Let your hands measure the weight, let the shadows test the dye, and always anchor your silhouette in close drape + light movement + one warm point of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Evaluate every new garment through your hands first. Look for fabrics that settle quietly over your frame rather than gripping it. Pick up a piece and test its drape. If the material feels stiff or synthetic, put it back. Build this wardrobe slowly over time, choosing each piece with deliberate care, so you can deploy it fast every morning. Apply the host test before you commit to a purchase. Ask yourself if the garment feels like you are pouring wine for guests at an intimate dinner. If the item demands attention or requires constant physical adjustment, it fails. You need clothes that support a warm, grounded presence.\n\nYour styling relies on a precise balance of elements. Memorise your formula, which is close drape + light movement + one warm point of light. Picture a fine gauge wool knit resting exactly at the shoulder, worn over a softly tailored fluid trouser that shifts slightly when you walk. Finish this with a single piece of matt heritage jewellery near the collarbone. This combination gives you structure and ease in equal measure. Avoid rigid tailoring entirely. Seek out fabrics that possess a muted finish and a heavy, liquid fall. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this fundamental logic to anchor your wardrobe and evaluate every garment before it touches your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the host test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Let your fingertips lead your sourcing. Seek out {texture_good_1} for winter layers that compress and bounce back. Buy {texture_good_3} for tailored coats that hold clean lines and establish a close drape. Introduce {texture_good_4} for blouses that provide light movement beneath those heavier garments. Ground everything with {texture_good_2} for bags and shoes that mould to your life. Run a simple friction check before buying. Rub the material between your thumb and index finger. If the fabric resists your touch or feels squeaky, leave it behind. Choose materials that absorb light into a warm, matt finish. This builds a stable, quiet foundation that prepares the eye for exactly one warm point of light from your jewellery.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to identify the materials that serve your style.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
