      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored pieces must take their motif from the weave itself. Ground your structured garments in {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Allow softer, fluid pieces to carry {recommended_pattern_3}, provided the dye matches the low-contrast tonal register of the base layer. Pass over stark graphics that interrupt close drape. Ignore {avoid_pattern_1} entirely, along with {avoid_pattern_2}. The wrong design shatters the visual line. The right one supports continuous light movement across the fabric. Subject every item to the firelight test. Take the garment into a dim room lit by a solitary tungsten bulb. The motif must deepen and turn warm under the lamplight. If the shapes flatten out or lose their depth in the shadows, drop the hanger. You need patterns that melt into the texture, creating depth without fighting the silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Force every pattern to serve the garment's structure, treating motifs as a strict extension of texture rather than a standalone feature.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Take your {recommended_pattern_1} away from the fluorescent overheads to verify its integrity. Hold the textile under a dim reading lamp. Watch how the motif behaves as the shadows drop. A correct print will deepen into the background, blurring softly into the yarn. If the edges remain sharp or stare back at you, drop the item. The design must surrender to the dimness. It should allow light movement across the surface rather than throwing a rigid graphic shape. Your prints must sink into their quiet, warm environment. They must never demand focus when the room darkens.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject your motifs to the firelight test to expose how they truly behave.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_scorpio__moon_leo__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "close drape + athletic space + one warm point of light",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on close drape + athletic space + one warm point of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Anchor your wardrobe in weight and silence. Pick up a garment and feel its density. If it feels frantic or demanding, put it back. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Your system runs on a strict equation of close drape + athletic space + one warm point of light. Picture a dense knit cut close against the ribs, tailored trousers with enough room in the thigh to sprint, and a single warm reflective element resting against the skin.\n\nBuild your collection slowly. Invest in structural precision over time so you can get dressed in two minutes flat. Before you leave the house, apply the wrist test. Assess the space where your sleeve meets your hand. If the fabric catches on your joints or the finish feels chaotic, take the garment off immediately. You require pieces that contain your movement without broadcasting it. Keep the finishes matt. Rely on quiet structures that let you operate in total autonomy.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise the exact physical parameters and instinct tests that dictate your entire wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your foundation on materials that pass the melt test. Pick up the garment and crush it in your fist. If it fights your grip, drop it. The material must collapse into your palm like warm water. Seek out {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Look for {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight to maintain your athletic space. Choose {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Rely on {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. These fabrics guarantee a close drape that serves your physical instincts, anchoring your silhouette before you add one warm point of light. Master these options first.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject stiff fabrics before you even look in the mirror.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed alpaca",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "enveloping winter coats and oversized cardigans"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fluid modal jersey",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers that follow the body without ever gripping it"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed cotton flannel",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "shirts and loungewear that feel like a remembered embrace"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Drop any fabric that feels brittle against the skin. Test every drape manually. If a piece of {texture_bad_1} stands away from your neck instead of collapsing into a warm pool over your collarbone, leave it on the hanger. Stiff fibres disrupt your close drape. Evaluate {texture_bad_2} by touch. If it feels slick and hollow like plastic, it fails. You need materials that fold inwards and stay quiet. High-shine synthetics trap heat and sit entirely outside your boundaries. Reject any textile that squeaks between your thumb and forefinger. Look for a matt surface always.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to recognise the materials that fight your silhouette and reject them on sight.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Build your self-contained foundation by pairing {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Prioritise a close drape. Drop {texture_good_1} into your open palm. Watch how the fibres behave. If the piece yields instantly, puddling into the exact contours of your hand, keep it. Let physical surrender dictate your choices. Keep your finishes matt and your selections warm and muted. Reject any piece that fights back or holds its own rigid shape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your core fibre combinations to anchor your wardrobe in reality.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette temperature is warm. Construct your base using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Anchor these shades with {core_colour_3}. Treat {core_colour_4} as a strict grounding element. Introduce a soft note used sparingly when the eye requires a pause. Rely on dense pigments that offer visual weight. Pass over stark optic white, harsh neon, and icy pastel completely. Deploy {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} for your single deliberate accent. Beware the burying effect. Stacking formless layers will erase your physical edges. Correct this instantly by introducing a sharp boundary. Pop a stiff collar, roll back a tailored sleeve, or wear exactly one warm point of light resting heavy at the collarbone. Define your shape through the close drape of your core pieces.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your palette with the exact physical intuition you use to judge weight and balance.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bitter chocolate",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Dark mahogany",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Blackened indigo",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
