      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "swaddling: layer upon layer of shapeless grey and the silhouette dissolves entirely",
          "fix": "restore one defined line, a structured collar, a neat cuff, or let the keepsake pendant sit visibly at the neckline"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At the desk, let close drape take the lead. Build your foundation with a dark mahogany blouse that sits near the ribs. Support this primary component with athletic space in the shoulders and a single warm gleam of bronze at the wrist. Professional environments do not require stiff worsted tailoring. They demand heavy silk crepe and lambswool that can run for a train. Test a blazer by gripping the sleeve. If the fibres feel brittle, walk away. You need pliable, matt fabrics that fold silently during long meetings. Keep the silhouette completely self-contained, filtering out all noise.",
      "sectionIntro": "Your working hours demand function over formality, built strictly from the inside out.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim environments, close drape leads your choices. Evening venues demand ease, not stiff construction. You need pliant layers that let you move fast. Reach for heavy silk crepe in bitter chocolate. Seek out a dark mahogany top that grants you athletic space without losing its form. Feel the weave. If the material feels rigid, put it back. Low light obscures cheap construction, but the fabric dragging against your skin reveals the truth. Add a matt gold cuff to provide exactly one warm point of light. The warm metal creates quiet contrast in the shadows. Keep the finish muted. Your approach must remain entirely self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the art of evening dressing by prioritizing touch over visual impact.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Standing in the queue for a prescription at the chemist is a true test of your wardrobe. Your standard remains exactly the same here. You apply close drape + athletic space + one warm point of light to every waking hour. A rigorous schedule asks for garments that can move at speed. Leave rigid tailoring on the hanger and select washed silk or boiled wool. Pair a bitter chocolate sweater with matt trousers that offer physical freedom. Add a muted gold ring to ensure the palette remains warm. Let heavy fibres guide your selection. Visuals deceive. Fabric density provides the truth. If a piece restricts your stride, discard it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your ordinary routine as the primary proving ground for your decisions.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Limit your jewellery and hardware to a warm dominant strategy. Rely on {metal_1} and {metal_2} as your primary choices, bringing in {metal_3} only for subtle accents. Hardware must never disrupt your close drape or clutter your athletic space. Weigh every piece in your palm. Mass dictates quality. Rely on this physical heft as your guide. Reject {excluded_finish} entirely. High-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours. Stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select hardware that anchors your garments without shouting over them.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Choose stones that anchor your self-contained world. Avoid high-shine, heavily faceted cuts. They cast a sharp, frantic glare that clashes terribly with your warm, muted colours. Insist on matt or softly brushed surface textures to keep your jewellery cohesive. A raw {stone_1} or a dense {stone_2} will properly ground your close drape and protect your athletic space. Examine the cut. Require absolute physical heft from your gems. Seek out opaque stones that absorb ambient glow rather than reflecting it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select stones to serve as dense, silent anchors for your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Gauge the object's gravity before wearing it. Pick up each {metal_1} cuff or {stone_1} pendant to test its mass. High-gloss metal flashes abruptly next to muted clothing. This sharp reflection severs the close drape and cuts into the athletic space you need. Ground your hardware by demanding strictly brushed or matt textures. A dense, unpolished finish sits correctly in the hand and rests cleanly over your garments. It delivers one warm point of light while keeping your presentation completely self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware through physical mass and a strict control of shine.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You have built the silhouette using the close drape. You have secured the necessary athletic space. Now finish the composition with exactly one warm point of light. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start with handbags. Demand full-grain leather or thick suede equipped with matt brushed hardware. Assess the hide manually. Apply the keepsake test by asking if the item possesses the sheer physical density to survive decades of daily use and pass to an heir. Ignore the label and rely on the scale of the fixtures. Seek dense straps and heavy buckles that anchor the washed silk or cloud-soft lambswool garments you wear.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select accessories as functional equipment, treating them as structural anchors rather than decorative additions.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Treat scarves as an extension of your physical perimeter. Demand generous proportions in washed silk or fine wool. Keep the finish entirely matt. A glossy surface fractures your visual boundaries. Wrap these lengths securely to ensure close drape. Leave enough room at the shoulder to preserve athletic space. Subject each textile to the keepsake standard. Ask if you would seal this specific item in a cedar box to keep for yourself for decades. If the fabric lacks the gravity of a permanent possession, leave it on the shelf. Select warm bitter chocolate tones to frame the jawline.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select scarves that respect your physical boundaries and tactile standards.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor trousers with wide full-grain leather belts, choosing a matt brushed buckle. Confine keepsake jewellery to a deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised to strip away the shine. These warm pieces must sit heavy and quiet to defend athletic space. Finish your dressing sequence by weighing the metal in your palm. If the object feels like fleeting decoration rather than a permanent talisman, take it off. Only keep the item if you would turn back home to retrieve it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your functional hardware and final relics to complete the system.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor your wardrobe in low-contrast, tonal weaves. Tailored coats and heavy trousers take their structure from {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Fluid shirts and woven scarves take their movement from {recommended_pattern_3} and {recommended_pattern_4}. Maintain close drape in these softer garments. Keep your structured pieces cut generously to ensure athletic space. Step away from stark graphics. Reject {avoid_pattern_1} and skip {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. Pass over anything that registers clearly from across a street. Apply the lamplight test before buying. If the motif does not melt into a soft, muted shadow under dim evening illumination, leave the garment on the rack. The pattern must recede into the fabric.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as a subtle shift in texture rather than a visual disruption.",
      "tests": [
        "the lamplight test (melt into a soft texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Hang the garment near a single warm lamp. Step back three paces. Squint. Watch how {recommended_pattern_1} behaves in the shadows. If the motif remains a sharp graphic, leave it on the rail. It will fracture the silhouette. Look for the print to dissolve into a soft, matt blur. The visual noise must melt away completely. You require pieces that hold a strict boundary. If a pattern shouts across the room, it destroys crucial athletic space. Demand a print that stays entirely self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this visual stress test to ensure any pattern respects your strict boundaries.",
      "tests": [
