    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Rely on the immediate sensation of the garment when pulling items from the wardrobe. Sight distracts. Density and heft reveal the actual form. Walking to the bakery does not require abandoning your warm atmosphere. Treat a morning trip to the pharmacy with the exact same visual discipline you apply anywhere else. Your baseline is absolute. You must always build close drape + blurred edges + one warm point of light. Pick up a dense brushed wool jumper in rich toffee. Avoid stiff shoulders and rigid seams. Step into soft full-grain leather loafers. Add a single matt gold ring. Maintain a self-contained finish. Never dilute your visual standard for a mundane errand.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your aesthetic discipline to the most ordinary moments of your day.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Anchor your hardware strategy in warm tones. Build your foundation with {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. A highly polished finish will carve a sharp, distracting line against the blurred edges of your garments. Reject {excluded_finish} surfaces entirely. Stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the overall look resolved and cohesive. Before you buy a belt or a heavy zip, lift the piece. Judge a buckle by the immediate gravity it presses into your palm. If the metal feels hollow or lightweight, drop it. Choose dense, silent hardware that anchors your close drape without begging for attention.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your hardware by evaluating its physical gravity and eliminating bright reflections.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Weigh the gem in your hand. Substantial mass reveals a stone's true quality. Choose dense, clouded stones like {stone_1} or {stone_2} that absorb illumination rather than scattering it. A highly polished, icy setting will shatter the cohesion of your soft textiles. Anchor your jewellery in brushed or matt finishes to protect the harmony of your {core_colour_1} garments. When you master close drape and blurred edges, these opaque gems provide exactly one warm point of light. They sit quietly against cashmere or silk. Let the sheer density of the mineral guide your choice.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select heavy, clouded stones to ground your garments and reflect your muted palette.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Test a {metal_1} cuff or buckle with your eyes closed. Focus solely on the downward pull in your hand. Heavy hardware grounds your silhouette. Next, inspect the surface finish. High-shine, mirror-polished metals create severe, distracting reflections that fight against your muted fabrics. Avoid these glaring finishes. Your hardware must respect your blurred edges. Choose brushed, hammered, or strictly matt surfaces instead. A substantial, warm {metal_1} detail provides an anchor without breaking the seamless continuity of your layers.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the tactile weight test to every piece of hardware before you commit.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments establish the close drape and the blurred edges. Now, you need accessories to deliver that one warm point of light. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start with handbags. Demand full-grain leather or thick suede construction, finished with matt brushed hardware on the straps and closures. Subject every bag to the ripple test. Press your thumb firmly into the outer panel. The hide should gather into heavy folds. If the surface crinkles or feels hollow beneath your fingers, put it down. Rely entirely on your hands to assess quality. Solid construction cannot be faked.",
      "sectionIntro": "Deploy your accessories as structural anchors rather than afterthoughts.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Focus purely on scarves in generous silk or fine wool. Seek out perfectly matt finishes in a warm camel or rich toffee. Apply the drop test before you commit. Gather the material in your hands and release it onto a solid surface. Watch how it settles. The fabric must collapse into liquid pools immediately. Stiff woven squares fail this test completely. You require textiles that guarantee close drape around your neck. Avoid harsh borders entirely. Hand-rolled hems provide necessary blurred edges. Trust the settling weight of the fabric when evaluating these pieces.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your textiles rigorously before allowing them near your face.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your waist with wide full-grain leather belts finishing in a matt brushed buckle. When selecting keepsake jewellery, look for a deep stone set in oxidised brass or aged silver. Gauge the solid construction of these pieces in your palm over any visual promise. Apply the disturbance test to finish. Place the item against your warm camel garments. If the hardware creates a sharp glare that interrupts your close drape, take it off immediately. Each accessory must sink quietly into your foundation, maintaining your blurred edges rather than demanding focus.",
      "sectionIntro": "Follow these rules to select your final details and test the completed outfit before stepping outside.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored garments take their pattern strictly from the weave itself, such as a {recommended_pattern_1}. Fluid pieces rely on low-contrast tonal shifts like a {recommended_pattern_2}. Enforce a strict low-contrast rule across every piece to protect the blurred edges of your silhouette. High-contrast prints break this line. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. Apply the dusk test before purchasing. Hang the garment in dim light and step back. The surface must settle into a warm, moving texture rather than a static graphic. If a sharp shape jumps out at you in the shadows, leave it on the rack.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as a subtle extension of texture, restricting visual noise to keep your silhouette grounded.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Execute the shadow check on any {recommended_pattern_1}. Drape the silk shirt or cashmere scarf over a chair across the room and dim the lamps. A proper motif drops its rigid geometry in low light. It melts into a warm, shifting grain rather than projecting a harsh graphic. Step back and soften your focus. If the shapes stay sharp against the base colour, abandon the piece. You need pattern to behave like a physical shadow. This strict standard guarantees close drape against the collarbone. It secures blurred edges without introducing visual noise.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every print to a strict physical evaluation before bringing it near your face.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_scorpio__moon_sagittarius__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "close drape + fast movement + one warm point of light",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on close drape + fast movement + one warm point of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your physical need for unbroken momentum as your ultimate compass. When you evaluate a new garment, test its speed and silence. Look for the melt test. The piece must dissolve into your own physical architecture, leaving no excess fabric to manage. If a collar dictates your posture or a sleeve drags, take it off immediately. The exact formula for this boundary is close drape + fast movement + one warm point of light. Picture a narrow tailored coat falling seamlessly over a fine-gauge knit, finished with cropped trousers that clear the ankle for immediate action, and anchored by a single piece of dull, heated metal resting against the collarbone. It is a closed circuit.\n\nBuild this foundation slowly, but deploy it fast. Test every hem and seam against your daily velocity. You are constructing a shell that allows you to remain entirely self-contained. Rely on touch over sight. Run your hand down the fabric. If the finish is harsh or the lining catches on your knuckles, reject the piece. Trust this physical instinct as your absolute law. Looks lie. Weight and friction do not. Keep your selections entirely muted and matt. You do not need to project your presence to the outside world. Keep the heat close to the skin and let the construction do the silent work.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this master blueprint and use it to calibrate every garment you test.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your best materials must yield to the body and facilitate fast movement. Apply the melt test. Crush the garment in your hands. If it fights back or holds a stiff crease, drop it. It must collapse into a matt, fluid puddle. Ignore the hanger appeal and focus on how the textile behaves under pressure. Look for {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight, offering one warm point of light near the collarbone. Select {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without bulk. Rely on {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth, ensuring a close drape that never binds. Finish with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select materials that protect your physical space and respond instantly to your movement.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
