      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Reject anything that stands away from the body. Evaluate a new item by dropping it over your bare forearm. If the fabric stays rigid and refuses to soften against your skin heat, put it back. You require a close drape. {texture_bad_1} fails this immediately. It traps air and creates a stiff shell around you. Pay attention to how the material sounds when rubbed together. {texture_bad_2} creates a distinct scratching noise and resists yielding. Avoid {texture_bad_3} entirely. It carries a chilly, synthetic sheen that disrupts a warm, matt palette and clings in sharp folds instead of sliding. Rely on your sensory feedback. If the cloth feels like scaffolding rather than liquid, it contradicts your need for fast movement.",
      "sectionIntro": "Leave behind any fabric that refuses to soften against your bare skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Gauge the quality of your garments blindly. Drape a piece of {texture_good_1} across your collarbone. If it holds a stiff edge, reject it. You demand materials that dissolve against your frame and settle into a close drape. This tactile assessment provides absolute certainty. Build your foundation here, finding the exact tension between {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Keep the silhouette self-contained. Combine these muted, matt layers with one warm metallic anchor.",
      "sectionIntro": "Nail your tactile foundation to anchor your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette is strictly warm. Build your daily foundation using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Anchor them with the structural dark of {core_colour_3} and the earthy green of {core_colour_4}. Enable fast movement through your wardrobe by choosing a single deliberate accent in either {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Treat your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly to rest the eye. Bypass stark optic white, harsh neon, and icy pastel. Beware the armchair slump. If you soften every single item, you essentially step out in pyjamas. Correct this by returning one structured line to your body. Introduce a shaped lapel, a trouser bearing a subtle crease, or a firm leather holdall to ground the softer elements, setting a quiet backdrop for one warm point of light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your palette as a strict system so you never have to hesitate when getting dressed.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bitter chocolate",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
