          "failure": "the sofa drift: soften every piece far enough and one day you are simply in loungewear",
          "fix": "restore exactly one line: a rolled but real lapel, a trouser with a soft crease, or a firm leather bag against all that give"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Base your professional attire on your core formula: close drape + fast movement + one warm point of light. A hurried morning commute does not mean trading precision for careless volume. Construct your outfit with garments that track your frame exactly. Rely on bitter chocolate heavy silk crepe or dark mahogany boiled wool to provide this unbroken line. Support the shape with vertical details that draw the eye straight up. Finish the look with a solitary warm, matt metallic piece at the ear. If a fabric feels cumbersome or chaotic to the touch, leave it on the hanger. Keep the silhouette self-contained and entirely practical.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use these rules to structure your physical presentation for a working environment.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In low light, close drape remains essential. Dim restaurant corners swallow visual details. Counter this by wearing dark mahogany heavy silk crepe that sits smoothly against the ribs and shifts instantly as you turn. A casual evening drink does not require abandoning the tight proportions that facilitate fast movement. Let the architecture of the garment do the heavy lifting, then introduce one warm point of light. Anchor the collar with a muted gold pendant. The matt surface of boiled wool worn over bare skin provides ample tactile contrast without demanding attention. Let your immediate physical reaction to the materials guide you. Reflections deceive, but the sheer gravity of a garment speaks the truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the geometry of close-quarters dressing.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A breezy morning fetching vegetables at the outdoor market does not demand you surrender your precise proportions to a shapeless shell jacket. Waiting in line at the dry cleaner is no excuse to suspend your rules. Rely on your joints to evaluate seams and weights. If a sweater restricts your shoulders, leave it on the rack. Seek out warm, cloud-soft dark mahogany lambswool that shifts easily. Build your routine strictly around close drape + fast movement + one warm point of light. Add a matt bronze ring alongside a bitter chocolate washed silk shirt. You maintain a self-contained boundary through these precise daily choices.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your mundane routines as the primary proving ground for your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Base your hardware entirely in a warm temperature. Build the foundation of your collection with {metal_1} and {metal_2}. You may introduce {metal_3} sparingly for deliberate contrast, but never let it overtake your baseline. Demand a close drape from your chains and bracelets so they sit perfectly flat against your skin. Highly reflective {excluded_finish} creates a jarring distraction against your muted garments. Restrict your pieces to matt and brushed textures to keep the visual field cohesive, ensuring you maintain one warm point of light. When assessing a new clasp or buckle, lift it directly off the jeweller's tray. The heavy reality of the metal in your palm provides the only metric that matters for fast movement.",
      "sectionIntro": "Mastering the weight, finish, and temperature of your metals ensures every zip and buckle serves your structure rather than breaking it.",
      "tests": [
