  "venus_scorpio__moon_taurus__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "close drape + sensory comfort + one warm point of light",
    "closing": "Let physical sensation guide your hands, ensuring every garment you own delivers close drape + sensory comfort + one warm point of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Cultivate a wardrobe built entirely on physical sensation. Build slowly and edit ruthlessly. Your baseline is absolute physical ease, a completely self-contained ecosystem where every seam serves your peace of mind. Trust your hands before your eyes. Pick up a fine-gauge knit or a silk tunic and run your fingers over the grain. You are looking for garments that pass the melt test. When you slip a sweater over your head, wait for the drop. The fabric must immediately yield and melt into your shoulders without requiring a single adjustment. If a collar stays stiff or a sleeve pulls, take it off. Looks lie. Weight does not. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass.\n\nYour operating blueprint is close drape + sensory comfort + one warm point of light. Picture a heavy silk slip skirt paired with a lightweight cashmere crewneck, finished with a single brushed pendant resting against the collarbone. The garments sit close to the body, providing insulation and a protective boundary, while the matt finish absorbs rather than reflects. You are dressing for your own tactile experience, not for an audience. Do not compromise on the friction of a lining or the gauge of a thread. Require every piece you own to wrap you softly and hold its shape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this physical logic as the absolute foundation of your daily uniform.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your garments from materials that deliver sensory comfort and close drape. When you evaluate {texture_good_1} for winter knits, grip the sleeve tightly. It must bounce back instantly. Seek {texture_good_2} for your footwear and belts, allowing the material to mould to your shape over time. For structured outerwear, rely on {texture_good_3} to hold a clean line. Underneath it all, use {texture_good_4} for blouses and linings to create fluid movement. Always apply the collapse test before purchasing. Drop the garment onto a flat surface. If the fabric pools into a heavy, liquid puddle rather than holding stiff folds, it will serve your needs. Anchor these foundational, muted materials with one warm point of light in your jewellery.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every material with your hands before you allow it against your skin.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
        {
          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the collapse test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Reject anything that stands away from the body with artificial stiffness. Run your thumb across {texture_bad_1}. If it catches, feels hollow, or lacks a warm undertone in the hand, leave it on the rail. A proper close drape requires weight and compliance. Assess {texture_bad_2} by letting it fall onto a table. If it retains a rigid, empty outline instead of sinking instantly into a dense pool, it will never yield to your shape. Let the sheer mass of the item guide you. Stay self-contained by avoiding rigid synthetics that build a stiff shell around your frame. You need materials that respond quietly to gravity.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify the textiles that actively fight your physical form.",
      "tests": [
        "the collapse test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Pair {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. This combination guarantees the close drape you require. To check a new piece, release it from a height. Observe the resulting shape. If the structure remains hollow and stiff, leave it behind. It must surrender and gather fluidly. Do not trust your eyes alone. Rely on the pure density of the weave in your hands. Adding {texture_good_1} anchors the pairing. Keep your choices self-contained, warm, and matt.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your signature pairing to ensure every piece handles correctly.",
      "tests": [
        "the collapse test"
