    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, close drape dictates the rules. A camel brushed wool blazer creates a tailored shoulder, holding its form without restricting your movement. Sensory comfort operates quietly underneath. Trust your hands to check the inside seams of a rich toffee silk blouse. The fabric must feel immediately soothing on your skin. Finish the combination with a single warm gold watch to complete the equation. Maintain absolute strictness during your desk hours. Banish shapeless cardigans and oversized jumpers. If a garment demands constant pulling or tucking to remain professional, do not buy it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your working uniform around reliable structure and silent materials.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dimly lit intimate settings, let close drape lead the way. Low lighting diminishes contrast, so rely entirely on texture over visual trickery. Reach for a heavy silk shirt in rich toffee or a camel cashmere knit worn directly against the skin. An evening spent indoors still demands a deliberate silhouette. Never default to formless loungewear. Choose items that sit near your body and fall naturally across your frame. Keep your metals warm and matt. A solitary brushed gold ring catches the shadows perfectly. Evaluate the physical sensation across your shoulders. If a piece requires constant adjusting, retire it immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your evening dressing by leading with touch rather than sight.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat an ordinary morning with exactly the same discipline you apply to significant events. A walk to the pharmacy to buy paracetamol still demands deliberate shape. Reach for garments that follow your frame closely without gripping it. Slide into camel cashmere trousers or a supple toffee leather jacket. Never suspend your standard for mere convenience. Ground your daily choices in your fundamental rule. Every single outfit must deliver close drape + sensory comfort + one warm point of light. Lift a piece of clothing and gauge its density in your fingers. Rely entirely on your bodily response to make your final choice. Physical heft reveals the truth behind a loose weave. If it feels rigid or insubstantial, put it back. Complete the look with a single matt gold ring.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the art of ordinary days by enforcing strict sensory boundaries.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your metal strategy requires a warm foundation. Anchor your jewellery and structural elements with {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Assess every zip and buckle by weighing it in your hand. An item's true quality is revealed by its pull toward the floor. Substantial, solid hardware provides sensory comfort and anchors the close drape of your garments. Guard against highly reflective components. A glossy {excluded_finish} fastening creates a jarring distraction against soft muted colours. Demand brushed or matt textures to keep the visual field cohesive.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate the finish and mass of every metal component.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select your stones by testing their solid density. Hold the piece carefully. Your jewellery must carry enough pure mass to ground your outfit. Seek out {stone_1} and {stone_2} for their opaque depths. Highly polished reflections clash harshly against your soft, warm palette. Restrict your settings to unpolished or sandblasted finishes to unify the elements. A heavy {stone_3} ring provides a visual anchor while maintaining sensory comfort. Let your fingers evaluate the piece. A dense stone requires close drape from your clothing to properly support its sheer gravity.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your stones for physical density and visual warmth.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Weigh every piece of jewellery before inspecting the design. Feel the {metal_1} against your skin. A mirror shine shatters your warm, muted palette, cutting harshly against soft fibres. Choose a dulled, matt surface instead. Your hardware must act as a steady ballast, not a distracting flash. Pair a close drape with solid materials that sit quietly against the body.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this physical test to select metals that ground your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories complete your foundational equation. After securing the close drape and ensuring absolute sensory comfort, your leather goods deliver exactly one warm point of light. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with handbags. Look for substantial full-grain leather or thick suede constructed with matt brushed hardware. To verify the hide, perform the ripple test. Press firmly into the side of the bag with your thumb and push forward. The material must gather into soft, organic waves ahead of your hand. If the leather buckles into sharp angles or feels unyielding, leave the item on the shelf. Let the raw density of the material guide your selection.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this section to select and evaluate the structural finishing pieces that ground your wardrobe.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Choose generous silk or fine wool scarves to secure absolute sensory comfort at the neck. Gather the textile in both fists, hold it up, and release it over a table. Watch the cloth descend. If it cascades immediately into soft, liquid waves, keep it. If the material stalls or creates a stiff peak, walk away. Passing this fluidity check guarantees pure close drape against the collarbone. Seek out a warm palette of muted camel or rich toffee fibres that absorb light. The finish must remain strictly matt. Pair these fabrics with a brass or gold element, anchoring the muted cloth with your dominant metal.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply rigorous physical standards to the textiles you place nearest your face.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your waist with a wide full-grain leather belt fastened by a matt brushed buckle. Ground your keepsake jewellery in physical density. Choose a deep garnet stone set in oxidised brass or aged silver. Each piece must offer true sensory comfort against your body. Run a final visual check before leaving. Place your chosen item against your rich toffee or camel layers. If the accessory introduces a sharp, disruptive glare across your clothing, remove it. The piece must sink seamlessly into the warm ensemble like a heavy stone vanishing into dark water.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your outfit by anchoring it with weight and testing it for visual disruption.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored pieces take their visual depth from woven structure. Fluid pieces draw their movement from faint, tonal shifts. Keep your contrast strictly low and tonal to maintain a quiet aesthetic. Prioritise sensory comfort by ensuring any motif is spun directly into the threads rather than printed stiffly on top. Seek out {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} for their subtle complexity. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} entirely, along with any graphic that interrupts the fabric's close drape. Subject every patterned garment to the dusk test. As the evening light drops, the design must settle into a warm, moving texture rather than snapping into sharp focus. If the shapes refuse to blur into the weave, put the item back on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as a subtle variation in weave rather than a surface decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Test patterns in the shadows. Drape the {recommended_pattern_1} across a chair and step back into low light. At five paces, the print must melt into a continuous wash of muted warmth. If the individual motifs remain distinctly legible or the contrast demands attention, abandon the piece. The design should read as a moving physical texture rather than a graphic stamp, communicating sensory comfort from across the room. Require this softening effect. It guarantees the material will wrap quietly around your frame without projecting outward.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this distance check to filter out aggressive prints.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_scorpio__moon_taurus__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "close drape + sensory comfort + one warm point of light",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on close drape + sensory comfort + one warm point of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Anchor your wardrobe in the physical weight of cloth against skin. Pick up a garment and test its density in your hands. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Your entire approach rests on a strict foundation. Look for close drape + sensory comfort + one warm point of light. Picture a dense cashmere roll-neck sitting flush against your collarbone, paired with heavy wool trousers that fall perfectly straight to the shoe, finished with a single piece of matt jewellery catching a warm reflection. This is your baseline.\n\nBuild your wardrobe slowly through careful procurement. Deploy it fast on the day. You are constructing a private uniform of physical ease. Before you commit to keeping a piece, apply the wrist test. Put the garment on and lift your arm as if checking a watch. If the fabric pulls at the shoulder or the cuff drags against your skin, reject it. The cut must grant you complete physical autonomy. If it demands constant adjustment, take it off.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this physical baseline before you evaluate another garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your foundation on sensory comfort. Look for {texture_good_1} in knitwear that compresses and springs back, holding its shape close to the body. Seek out {texture_good_2} for belts and shoes that will mould to your shape and soften over years of daily friction. Choose {texture_good_3} for coats that enforce a clean, structured boundary between you and the weather. Layer {texture_good_4} against your skin for a close drape that moves fluidly. Apply the candlelight test before buying anything new. Ask yourself if the fabric surface absorbs a warm glow or reflects a harsh glare. You want a matt, muted finish that drinks in one warm point of light. Let the materials listed below form your baseline.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the weight and warmth of materials that actually serve you.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
        {
          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Examine every piece under low illumination. Take the item into a dim space and check how it handles the environment. If it bounces back a harsh glare rather than absorbing light into a warm, matt surface, leave it on the hanger. A material like {texture_bad_1} feels stiff in your hands and refuses to yield to a close drape. Reject it. Pick up {texture_bad_2} and crush it in your palm. If it snags on your knuckles or emits a hollow, synthetic rustle, it fails. Avoid {texture_bad_3} entirely. It traps heat and acts as a rigid barrier rather than moving with your body. Trust your fingers. Visuals deceive, but tension and density reveal poor construction.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject incorrect materials instantly.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Hold your textiles near a single low flame. Watch how the surface handles the glow. It must absorb that warm illumination rather than reflecting it. A true matt finish drinks the light entirely. Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to achieve this exact effect. Demand close drape even from your heaviest materials. Lift the garment and gauge its sheer density. Assess the physical mass directly. Heavy grams tell the truth. Layer in {texture_good_1} to introduce subtle depth while keeping your visual presence strictly self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Combine your materials deliberately to build a tightly controlled visual signature.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your fundamental temperature is warm. Anchor your wardrobe in {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. These shades absorb light and ground your appearance. When you require a neutral bridge to connect garments, pull {core_colour_3} and {core_colour_4}. Leave Icy electric blue, Neon brights, and Fleeting trend pastels on the rack. Deploy {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} as your single deliberate accent. Treat your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly to break up heavy blocks of dark cloth. Beware the trap of over-wrapping. Piling on formless, matt grey knitwear will erase your frame entirely. Correct this error by reinstating a single crisp edge. Turn up a sharp collar, press a precise cuff, or position a metal pendant at your throat to draw the eye. Rely on close drape to trace your shape in silk or leather.",
      "sectionIntro": "Filter out the noise and build your palette strictly on the shades that support your natural temperature.",
      "rankedItems": [
