  "venus_taurus__moon_aquarius__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "soft structure + mobile layers + a touch of quiet depth",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on soft structure + mobile layers + a touch of quiet depth.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe slowly, but dress fast. Your compass here is physical weight and tactile density. Pick up a garment and close your eyes. Feel the density of the weave between your fingers. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. You are hunting for items that offer a warm, insulating wrap around the body. Demand a completely matt, muted finish on the surface. If the material catches the light or shines, put it back on the hanger. The fabric must absorb light entirely.\n\nAnchor your dressing routine to your core style formula: soft structure + mobile layers + a touch of quiet depth. Picture a generously cut overcoat draped loosely over a fine knit, grounded by a heavy shoe. Apply the shelter test to every prospective purchase. Put the piece on and ask yourself if it provides a secure, physical retreat from the outside world without restricting your movement. A garment either offers structural safety or it fails. If it feels flimsy or pinches at the shoulder, leave it in the shop.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every new addition to your wardrobe against these strict physical rules.",
      "tests": [
        "the shelter test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe from materials that naturally form soft structure and mobile layers. Apply the melt test to every potential purchase. Pick the fabric up and squeeze it. If it holds stiff peaks, put it back. It must melt seamlessly into your palm. This warm fluidity ensures your garments carry a touch of quiet depth rather than rigid bulk. Rely on {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Choose {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without pulling at the seams. Look for {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden gravity. Seek {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay completely soft at every edge.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the fibres that build your foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed alpaca",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "enveloping winter coats and oversized cardigans"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fluid modal jersey",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers that follow the body without ever gripping it"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed cotton flannel",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "shirts and loungewear that feel like a remembered embrace"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Avoid {texture_bad_1}. It catches on dry hands and generates a harsh static charge against the body. Pass over {texture_bad_2}. It holds an artificial rigidity that actively fights the soft structure you require. When in doubt about a textile's origin, perform the burn test. Snip a loose thread from an inside seam and bring a flame close. If it shrinks into a hard plastic bead instead of crumbling into ash, leave the item on the rack. {texture_bad_3} fails this assessment immediately, trapping warm air and suffocating your skin.",
      "sectionIntro": "Eliminate poor textiles by recognising their immediate failures under your hands.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Find your baseline by bridging {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Gather a length of material in your hand and let it drop. It must collapse into a warm pool against the counter rather than retaining its previous shape. This physical surrender is non-negotiable. It gives a textile like {texture_good_1} its true value. When you demand soft structure, the cloth must drape heavily and quietly. Avoid any stiff synthetics that stand away from the limbs. Your mobile layers must shift exactly when you do.",
      "sectionIntro": "Nail down the exact tactile balance that anchors your daily styling.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor your foundation exclusively in warm tones. Let {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} serve as your base. Deploy {core_colour_3} when a garment requires firm edges and rely on {core_colour_4} for an earthy grounding element. When you add your single deliberate accent, select {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Apply your relief tone sparingly to lift a dense outfit. Pass over stark optic white, harsh neon, and icy pastel entirely. These tones disrupt your muted finish. A common trap is vanishing into an unbroken, formless block of deep black. Correct this mistake immediately by breaking the dark expanse with a warm point of light. Reach for a hammered gold cuff or a tortoiseshell comb. Let these precise choices ground your mobile layers.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your palette as a strict utility.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bitter chocolate",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Dark mahogany",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Blackened indigo",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep forest green",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Burnt umber",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Washed black",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Burnt amber",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rich cognac",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Misty taupe",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "drowning in formless, head to toe black",
          "fix": "break it with a warm point of light, like a hammered gold cuff or a tortoiseshell comb"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At the desk, soft structure takes the lead. Define your outline with boiled wool jackets and heavy silk crepe trousers. Support this foundation with mobile layers that shift easily as you reach across a table. Add a touch of quiet depth through warm, muted metals at your wrist. Commuting with heavy portfolios is no excuse to abandon tailoring. Keep the drape deliberate. Evaluate a piece by sitting and bending. The sleeve of a washed silk blouse must follow your arm without pulling. Reject stiff collars and rigid waistbands. Require your garments to hold their lines without restricting your breath.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess your working attire through the lens of drape and form.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, a touch of quiet depth takes precedence. Reach for heavy silk crepe or cloud-soft lambswool in warm dark mahogany. A relaxed evening indoors still demands precise volume. Maintain soft structure even in private spaces. Pinch the cloth tightly to evaluate the drape. If a bitter chocolate slip feels thin in your fingers, discard it entirely. Let tactile judgment guide you. Seek a muted, matt finish that absorbs the ambient glow.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your evening and private environments by demanding the exact same standards you require during the day.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Running standard errands requires the exact same discipline. Treat a Tuesday morning walk to the post office as a reason to engage your system. Your core equation remains constant. You must insist on soft structure + mobile layers + a touch of quiet depth. Shrug on an unstructured coat in dark mahogany. Let the thick gauge of a bitter chocolate sweater settle over your shoulders. Mix warm metals by fastening a matt silver and gold pin to your lapel. Assess the yarn density before buying any casual knit. The weave must feel substantial against your knuckles. Ensure the silhouette balances an unrestrictive armhole with a neat hem.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat ordinary errands as a proving ground for your styling rules.",
      "tests": [
        "a market morning does not require abandoning proportion (Breeze)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your metal strategy splits into two distinct registers. Wear {personal_metal_1} and {personal_metal_2} directly against the skin. For the buckles, zips, and clasps that anchor your soft structure, demand {structural_metal_1} and {structural_metal_2}. A highly reflective glaze cuts too sharply against warm fabrics and disrupts visual cohesion. Stick exclusively to brushed or matt textures. Reject any {excluded_finish} surfaces immediately. Trust your hands to assess quality. Lift every chain and fastener. Surfaces deceive, but sheer physical density always tells the truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hardware provides the rigorous mechanical anchor for your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "When evaluating jewellery, demand physical gravity. Select opaque, light-absorbing stones like {stone_1} and {stone_2} rather than highly faceted, transparent gems. Weigh the pendant in your bare palm. Use these solid elements to introduce a touch of quiet depth to your mobile layers. Avoid any high-gloss, heavily polished silver settings. A mirror finish looks harsh and completely distracting against your warm, muted garments. Restrict your rings and bracelets to matt or gently brushed states to protect the baseline aesthetic.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones precisely as you evaluate your fabrics.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the {metal_1} piece from the counter and feel its downward pull. Trust your fingertips to detect hollow links or flimsy clasps. Steer clear of high-shine plating. A gleaming, polished surface creates a harsh glare against a muted {core_colour_1} knit, fracturing your carefully built silhouette. Correct this by demanding brushed or matt treatments. A dulled, warm patina respects your soft structure rather than competing with it. Let the cold heaviness of a solid {stone_1} inset confirm the final quality of the ring.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every piece of hardware to a strict tactile evaluation before bringing it home.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your accessories deliver a touch of quiet depth to your foundation of soft structure and mobile layers. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start with handbags. Seek out full-grain leather bags fitted with brushed matt hardware. Apply the anchor test before committing. Swing the strap over your shoulder and feel its dense, warm gravity settle against your hip. It must act as a ballast for your fine knits. If the leather feels hollow or the buckle clinks thinly, walk away. Weight grounds the outfit.",
      "sectionIntro": "Here is your framework for selecting the final elements that anchor your wardrobe.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Complement your core by selecting scarves in washed silk or fine boiled wool. Seek a strictly matt finish in warm tones like dark mahogany or bitter chocolate. Trust your hands over the mirror. Grab the textile. If it feels like it will scatter on a passing breeze, leave it on the shelf. You need enough physical weight to drag the piece down into a deliberate, heavy drape. Avoid anything with a high sheen or a flimsy, transparent weave. This physical substantiality reinforces your mobile layers.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your final layers using weight and texture as your primary filters.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Choose medium full-grain leather belts secured by a matt buckle to uphold your soft structure. Restrict your keepsake jewellery to aged silver and oxidised metals. These materials carry a naturally warm shadow, resting solidly against dark cloth. Evaluate your final arrangement in the mirror. Scrutinise your metallic pieces and leather goods together. Remove any item that feels thin or visually floats away from the body. Retain only those dense additions that drag your centre of gravity straight down to the floor, providing a touch of quiet depth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your additions by filtering out the noise and checking their physical weight.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Your tailored garments draw pattern entirely from weave and yarn tension. Your fluid pieces take their pattern from low-contrast, tonal dyes. Keep all visual contrast strictly low. Look for {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Pass over anything sharp. Leave {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} on the rail. Subject every printed piece to the twilight test. Step into a dimly lit space. If the motif remains distinctly visible, put the garment down. The pattern must dissolve entirely into a warm, rich surface, leaving only the pure geometry of the drape. Pattern must serve soft structure. It must never fight the silhouette. Incorporate printed cloth into your mobile layers to introduce visual texture without breaking the muted palette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control pattern rigidly to maintain focus on cut, drape, and texture.",
      "tests": [
        "the twilight test (merge into a rich, deep texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "When inspecting {recommended_pattern_1}, hang the piece across the room in dim evening light. Observe how the shapes behave. They must lose their sharp edges and melt into a wash of warm shadow. A successful print reads merely as dense texture from ten paces away. If the individual motifs remain distinct and demand focus in the gloom, they will disrupt the soft structure of your outline. Step back and squint. The item should look like a continuous plane of rich material, blending seamlessly into your mobile layers.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your patterns in low light to verify they serve the garment rather than fighting it.",
      "tests": [
        "the twilight test (merge into a rich, deep texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_taurus__moon_aries__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "structure + sharp edges + a touch of quiet depth",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on structure + sharp edges + a touch of quiet depth.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Feel the weight of the fabric before you look at the cut. Your wardrobe relies on dense, substantial materials that hold their own shape without your intervention. Seek out warm undertones and matt finishes that absorb light rather than reflecting it. Build your wardrobe slowly, focusing on exact tailoring and architectural lines, then deploy these pieces fast. When you test a garment, apply the breath test. Put it on, stand still, and take a deep breath in. If the seams pull or the silhouette collapses when your ribcage expands, put it back. The clothing must remain impassive and solid.\n\nYour baseline equation is structure + sharp edges + a touch of quiet depth. Picture a heavy winter overcoat with severe, precision-cut lapels worn over a dense, fine-gauge knit. The outer layer provides the rigid geometry. The inner layer offers the subtle tactile weight. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. You are constructing a self-contained uniform. The items you select must stand independently, requiring no adjustment throughout the day. Drop anything that feels flimsy or requires constant fixing.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this blueprint to calibrate your physical instincts before you evaluate another garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe demands physical substance to hold its structure and sharp edges. Rely on materials that absorb light into a warm, matt finish to give your silhouettes a touch of quiet depth. Look for {texture_good_3} in your tailored coats and blazers to maintain clean architectural lines year after year. Layer with {texture_good_1} for winter knitwear that compresses under a heavy coat and springs right back. Ground these foundations with {texture_good_2} in your bags and shoes, allowing the material to mould to your specific grip and develop a rich patina. Introduce {texture_good_4} for blouses or internal linings to provide fluid movement against rigid tailoring. Squeeze the cloth in your fist. If it crushes flat and fails to recover, discard the garment immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise quality before your eyes make a decision.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
