    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Choose generous silk or fine wool for your scarves. Enforce a strictly matt finish. These textiles must anchor your core formula of structure and sharp edges. Apply the float test when evaluating a new accessory. Drop the fabric gently over a wooden chair. Genuine fine wool or heavy silk will trap air and drift downwards slowly. If the item plummets heavily or hangs with rigid folds, discard it. Rely entirely on your physical instincts here. Your hands understand the difference between substantial drape and artificial stiffness. Select warm tones like camel or rich toffee to keep the look completely self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Handle soft accessories with the exact same rigour you apply to your tailoring.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the float test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor the waistline with structure. Choose wide full-grain leather belts in camel or rich toffee, fastened by a matt brushed buckle displaying sharp edges. Trust your hands to measure the gravity of a piece when selecting keepsake jewellery. Do not trust a shop mirror. Assess the piece by its solid heft. Look for a warm, deep garnet stone set in aged silver or oxidised brass. Before stepping out, apply the flush test. If a ring or metal fitting feels like it hovers awkwardly away from your skin or requires constant manual adjustment, remove it completely. Every item must sit flush and contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your final hardware and apply a strict physical check to finish.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the float test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored garments must draw their pattern directly from the physical weave. Fluid pieces accept printed motifs, provided the application remains subtle. Enforce a strict low-contrast tonal rule across every item. Look for {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} to build internal structure. Apply the underwater test to any printed fabric. The visual must behave like light shifting across a warm sandy seabed. It must never read like static roadside signage. Reject heavy graphics. Leave {avoid_pattern_1} on the rail. Demand sharp edges in your woven grids, letting the thread itself dictate the geometry.",
      "sectionIntro": "Filter out distraction by relying on the physical weave to generate your motifs.",
      "tests": [
        "the underwater test (read like light moving on the seabed, not signage)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Subject every {recommended_pattern_1} to this visual check. Hold the garment across the room and squint until your vision blurs. A successful pattern mimics light refracting through shallow water. It shifts. It creates structure without demanding attention. If the print reads like a stamped barcode, put the item down. High contrast ruins the muted effect. Look for motifs that sink into the base weave. Ensure the pattern maintains self-contained boundaries up close but dissolves into a soft wash from three paces away.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this strict visual test to evaluate any pattern before you bring it into your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the underwater test (read like light moving on the seabed, not signage)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_taurus__moon_cancer__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "structure + hidden depth + a touch of quiet depth",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on structure + hidden depth + a touch of quiet depth.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the weight of the cloth in your hands. Look for garments that hold their own shape on the hanger before you even put them on. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Your foundation relies on heavy, dense weaves that absorb light into a warm, matt surface. Picture a heavy overcoat cut with sharp shoulders, worn over a thick crewneck jumper and stiff trousers. That exact combination creates structure + hidden depth + a touch of quiet depth.\n\nBuild your wardrobe slowly. Examine every single piece in total isolation before it enters your closet. Deploy it fast when you dress. Apply the wrist test to guarantee the architecture of the piece holds up. Put the jacket on and pull the sleeve back to expose your forearm. If the cuff collapses into messy folds, or if the edge feels flimsy against your bare skin, take the garment off immediately. The item must frame your arm with unwavering precision. If you have to constantly adjust the collar or pull at the hem to maintain the silhouette, the piece fails. You require clothes that stand entirely independent of your own physical movement.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your core operating system, the strict set of physical rules and sensory tests you must use to assemble your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Texture is how you build structure and a touch of quiet depth. Let your fingers do the auditing. Pick up a garment and apply the breath test. Hold the fabric to your mouth and exhale. If the heat traps and the material stifles, drop it. You require warm, matt materials that breathe with your body and maintain a self-contained silhouette. Look for {texture_good_1} in knitwear that compresses and bounces back. Seek out {texture_good_2} for bags and belts that patinate quietly over time. Rely on {texture_good_3} for tailored coats that hold clean lines for years. Finally, use {texture_good_4} for blouses that add fluid movement beneath heavier pieces. Build your foundation from the materials below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Trust your hands to verify the integrity of every garment before you check the label.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
        {
          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Rely on your tactile senses to reject inferior goods. Sight is easily manipulated, but true heft reveals reality. Bury your face in a piece of {texture_bad_1} and exhale firmly. If the fabric throws the air straight back at you, discard it immediately. True luxury relies on hidden depth, and suffocating textiles cannot deliver it. Next, run your thumb over {texture_bad_2}. If it feels slick and leaves a harsh, high-gloss slide rather than a warm, matt drag against your skin, put it down. Finally, crush {texture_bad_3} in your fist. If it collapses into rigid, paper-like creases and refuses to spring back, it will never hold the self-contained shape you need.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject poor textiles before they ever touch your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your signature textural pairing combines {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Assess the tension of {texture_good_1} by pulling it gently. The material must hold a defined shape while yielding to your grip. Shrug the item on and inhale deeply. True hidden depth reveals itself when the fabric settles over your frame without grabbing your skin. Discard any item that restricts your ribs or forces a stiff posture. The cloth must support your natural motion. Pair this dense weave with a muted, warm surface to complete the equation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your tactile pairing by testing how the fabric responds to your frame.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette operates on a strictly warm frequency. Build your base with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} for dense, heavy garments. Layer {core_colour_3} and {core_colour_4} to bridge the space between cashmere outerwear and silk shirts. Deploy {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} purely as intentional focal points. Keep your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly to separate solid blocks. Reject icy electric blue, neon brights, and fleeting trend pastels entirely. Watch for the swathing trap. If you stack endless undefined layers of muted cloth, your physical outline disappears completely. Correct this instantly by restoring a defined edge. Reinstate a sharp collar, fold back a crisp cuff, or drop a heavy pendant right at the collarbone. This secures the hidden depth you require without sacrificing your physical shape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your palette by treating every tone as a deliberate, functional tool.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rich toffee",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
