          "name": "Misty blue-green",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "swaddling: layer upon layer of shapeless grey and the silhouette dissolves entirely",
          "fix": "restore one defined line, a structured collar, a neat cuff, or let the keepsake pendant sit visibly at the neckline"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, structure leads. It provides a strict perimeter. The remaining elements, hidden depth and a touch of quiet depth, soften the interior. Build your outfit around a heavy camel wool blazer. Underneath, layer a rich toffee silk shirt. Let the warm, muted fibres rest close to your skin. Apply the Tide test. Stepping out to buy milk is no excuse to drop your silhouette. Keep your lines sharp and your collar fastened. Let tactile feedback guide your accessories. Your hands tell the truth about quality. Feel the full-grain leather of your belt. A solid brass buckle provides weight. Avoid loose garments that swallow your frame.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your aesthetic rules to a working environment by grounding your choices in firm boundaries and tangible weight.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "Hidden depth takes the lead in low light. Pick up a rich toffee silk shirt or a warm camel cashmere jumper. Test the density with your bare hands. Close environments demand materials that reward proximity. Avoid anything stiff or abrasive. Ease the tension but hold the line. Even behind closed doors, refuse to surrender your silhouette. Maintain precise boundaries during private hours. Let warm, matt metals rest directly against the skin. Prioritise touch above all else.",
      "sectionIntro": "Navigate evening and intimate settings by shifting your focus to tactile weight.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Running mundane errands provides no exemption from sharp borders. Maintain your edges. Build your daily foundation on heavy brushed wool trousers and a camel cashmere knit. Step out in full-grain leather boots. Every ordinary day demands structure + hidden depth + a touch of quiet depth. Look for warm fibres that absorb light. A muted finish keeps your presentation entirely self-contained. Measure a garment by its physical resistance. Grab the material and test its density. Solid weaves tell the truth. Leave flimsy knitwear on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your daily routines with the same physical rigour you apply to major appointments.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your hardware strategy builds on a warm foundation. Anchor your wardrobe with {metal_1} and {metal_2}. These tones integrate seamlessly into a muted wardrobe. Always scrutinise the finish. A high-gloss {excluded_finish} creates a harsh glare against soft fabrics. Demand a brushed or matt surface instead. This keeps the aesthetic cohesive and reinforces the underlying structure of your garments. Before buying a belt or a bag, lift the buckle in your palm. Online images lie. Absolute gravity proves value. Your fingers will instantly recognise solid cast hardware over hollow alloys. Keep {metal_3} in reserve for small details like watch cases or spectacle frames.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your metals as functional anchors, choosing hardware that grounds your warm palette.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Anchor your jewellery with dense, warm opacity. When evaluating {stone_1} or {stone_2}, lift the object in your hands. Do not judge by gleam. Only the raw mass matters. Rely on the solid gravity of the piece to confirm its quality. These heavy, opaque elements provide essential structure to your wardrobe. Never pair them with high-shine, gleaming silver. A polished, mirror-like finish cuts too sharply against soft, muted colours, instantly breaking your visual cohesion. Stick strictly to brushed or matt textures to keep the outfit unified.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select heavy, dense stones that ground your wardrobe without reflecting the light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the {metal_1} off the tray and weigh it in your palm. Assess the physical heft independently. A substantial item establishes necessary structure. Reject glaring reflections. A mirror-gloss finish creates a sharp, distracting glare against soft, warm colours and muted fabrics. It shatters your visual cohesion. Instead, seek out burnished, sandblasted, or matt textures. A dull {stone_1} or textured metal surface provides hidden depth. They anchor your outfit without demanding attention.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to evaluate your jewellery with your hands before you put it on.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "While your primary garments provide structure and cultivate hidden depth, your final details deliver a touch of quiet depth. Restrict your choices to one or two strong pieces per look. Evaluate every addition through the keepsake test. Ask yourself if the object possesses the undeniable physical permanence to sit alone on your dressing table for the next fifty years. If the construction feels hollow, leave it on the shelf. Begin your selection with handbags. Demand full-grain leather or thick suede. Inspect the closures closely. You require warm metals, specifically matt brushed hardware that refuses to catch the light. Pick the bag up by its handles. Authentic leather validates itself through unyielding heaviness.",
      "sectionIntro": "Accessories act as the definitive anchor for your wardrobe, requiring rigorous selection and an uncompromising demand for physical weight.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Subject every scarf to the same long-term scrutiny. Squeeze the folded material and ask if it possesses the enduring gravity to outlive you in a cedar chest. Select generous silk or fine wool with a strictly matt finish. Grasp the textile between your fingers to locate its underlying architecture. A flimsy drape fails you immediately. Seek out warm tones like camel that provide hidden depth without drawing focus. If the fabric feels temporary, leave it on the shelf.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your scarves by demanding absolute material integrity.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Build structure at the waist with a wide full-grain leather belt. Demand a matt, brushed buckle in warm brass to maintain your muted palette. Move to keepsake jewellery next. Select a deep stone set in oxidised brass or aged silver. This provides hidden depth without breaking your self-contained perimeter. Finish by checking the physical grounding. Close your hand over the metal and stone. If the item projects outward to an audience instead of anchoring you inwardly, take it off immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your final layer with weight and deliberate intent.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Keep pattern contrast strictly tonal and low. In tailored garments, draw your pattern from the weave itself to build structure. In fluid pieces, rely on subtle dye variations that blend seamlessly into the fabric. Seek out {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} for their understated complexity. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. Apply the lamplight test to every new garment. Hold the fabric under a soft evening bulb. The pattern must melt smoothly into the warm material rather than jumping off the surface. If the design demands attention instead of revealing hidden depth, leave it on the rail. Good pattern is woven into the yarn itself. Sight proves unreliable. The tactile density of the textile conveys the final verdict.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as a subtle structural element rather than a decorative addition.",
      "tests": [
        "the lamplight test (melt into a soft texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Take {recommended_pattern_1} as your baseline. Assess its restraint under low illumination. View the garment under a dim lamp or squint your eyes at three paces. The distinct shapes must soften into a continuous, warm field of colour rather than shouting their individual geometry. This optical shift provides hidden depth. The woven thread maintains its literal structure, but the contrasting dye melts together in the shadows. If the motif remains stark and highly legible, leave the piece on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the lamplight test to evaluate the visual volume of any patterned garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the lamplight test (melt into a soft texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_taurus__moon_capricorn__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "structure + softness + a touch of quiet depth",
    "closing": "Trust the pure physical weight of the cloth against your skin to find your precise balance of structure + softness + a touch of quiet depth.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Curate your wardrobe with methodical patience. Build slowly over years and dress quickly in the morning. When selecting a garment, test the weight of the fabric against your skin. You want warm fibres that drape with deliberate gravity rather than clinging or floating. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Your foundation relies on a strict equation of structure + softness + a touch of quiet depth. Picture a heavy wool overcoat cut with razor precision, layered over a fine-gauge cashmere crewneck, finished with a dark matt horn button.\n\nBefore you buy anything new, apply the host test. Ask yourself if the garment serves your physical comfort or if you are merely hosting it for a designer. If a piece requires constant adjustment or draws the eye to an external motif, put it back. You require garments that keep your boundaries intact and self-contained. Seek out matt finishes in both cloth and hardware that absorb light rather than reflecting it. Every piece must feel completely integrated into your own space. If you feel like a display hanger for the clothes, the piece fails.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your operational baseline for evaluating every garment before it touches your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the host test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your textiles must deliver both rigid structure and yielding softness. Rely on {texture_good_3} for coats that hold a firm shoulder. Contrast this density with {texture_good_1} in knitwear that compresses and recovers in your grip. Against the skin, {texture_good_4} adds a touch of quiet depth without drawing focus. Anchor the foundation with {texture_good_2} for shoes and bags that patinate quietly over years of use. Apply the candlelight test before buying. Carry the garment into dim lighting and observe how it handles a low, warm beam. The material must absorb the glow into a muted, matt surface instead of bouncing it back. Rely on your hands to gauge true mass. Visuals deceive, but a heavy textile always reveals its quality. Seek out the materials ranked below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Let your hands verify what your eyes suspect when evaluating a garment.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
