    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Picking up a prescription at the local chemist deserves identical tailoring to a scheduled board meeting. Never suspend your standard for convenience. Anchor your morning choices in structure + softness + a touch of quiet depth. Combine a rich toffee matt silk shirt with sharp trousers. Fasten a camel full-grain leather belt with a muted silver buckle, worn alongside a warm gold ring. Rely purely on tactile feedback rather than mirrors. Close your eyes and feel the density of the cashmere weave. If the fabric feels thin or pulls out of shape during a simple commute, discard it immediately. Test every garment by its performance in the mundane world.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your daily errands as the ultimate testing ground for your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Divide your hardware into two specific zones. Reserve {personal_metal_1} and {personal_metal_2} for the rings and chains worn closely on the body. For the mechanical elements of your garments, rely on {structural_metal_1} and {structural_metal_2} for your zips, clasps, and buckles. Steer clear of {excluded_finish} treatments. A glaring polish creates a sharp distraction that ruins the cohesion of your warm palette. Insist on brushed or matt finishes. Lift every piece of hardware and judge its mass. The eye is easily tricked by a clever surface plating. True density reveals itself in grams and ounces. If a clasp or chain feels hollow, it lacks the heavy structure you require.",
      "sectionIntro": "Approach your metals as deliberate architectural choices, not mere decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Your stones must possess an opaque quality that absorbs light rather than refracting it. Pair an unpolished {stone_1} with the softness of your garments to build intentional contrast. Lift the jewellery before you wear it. Visuals present an illusion. Mass provides reality. A proper {stone_2} will rest heavily in your palm. Avoid highly reflective, polished settings. A brilliant cut introduces an erratic distraction against your warm, muted fabrics. Rely strictly on matt and brushed finishes to keep the visual field perfectly cohesive.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the selection of dense, grounding stones to anchor your daily pieces.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift a {metal_1} buckle or {stone_1} ring and weigh its heft in your fingers. Glossy, mirror-like polishing shatters the harmony of a warm outfit. A gleaming surface fights your muted fabrics and catches unwanted glare. Insist on brushed or matt finishes instead. A subdued surface absorbs light, allowing the piece to provide steady structure without overpowering the softness of your garments.",
      "sectionIntro": "Weigh every detail before it enters your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments build a foundation of structure and softness. Accessories deliver the final necessity, bringing a touch of quiet depth. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Handbags anchor this approach. Seek out full-grain leather or thick suede finished with matt brushed hardware. Put every potential addition through the one-ember test. A successful item must hold a steady, warm heat rather than flashing violently for attention. Evaluate the object entirely by touch. Solid metals and dense hides prove their worth through mass. If a strap feels flimsy or a clasp rattles lightly, reject the piece entirely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your strict material standards to the final details, ensuring your additions anchor your garments rather than distracting from them.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Scarves require generous proportions in silk or fine wool. Always demand a completely matt surface. High shine creates unnecessary noise. Grip the material to locate absolute softness. Heavy fabric drops gracefully, while cheap cloth puffs up around your collar. Assess the colour intensity before acquiring any new piece. A rich toffee wrap should glow like a single hidden coal. If the warm hue starts a blazing fire, leave the item on the shelf. Anchor your outfit with strict structure below, then let the scarf supply quiet depth near your face.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your secondary layers by treating every textile addition as a strict physical calculation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your garments using a wide belt cut from warm camel full-grain leather. Select a brushed buckle with a strictly matt finish. This pairing provides the vital structure needed to ground the softness of your woven layers. For keepsake jewellery, choose items cast in oxidised aged silver or brass. Find a deep stone set securely into the metal to exploit this dual register. Before leaving, examine your finished outfit. Look closely and identify any detail that flashes rather than smoulders. Keep only the pieces that generate a steady, low heat. Strip off the rest.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finish your foundations with metals and stones that absorb light rather than reflect it.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Ground your tailored garments in {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} to reinforce their structure. For fluid layers that provide softness, choose {recommended_pattern_3}. You must insist on low-contrast tonal variations across all your prints. High-contrast designs disrupt a self-contained wardrobe. Always test a new piece near a low incandescent bulb. The hues must deepen and turn warm by lamplight. If the motif turns stark or separated under a dim glow, walk away. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} completely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use pattern as a subtle building block to anchor your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Take your garments to a low, warm lamp to perform the firelight test. A successful {recommended_pattern_1} will sink into the shadows and appear to deepen. You need patterns that retain their internal structure even when the lighting dims. If the motif looks stark or brittle under a warm bulb, put it back on the rack. The print must melt into the softness of the fibre under dim lighting. Keep only those patterns that shift into complex, obscure tones when the sun goes down.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every pattern to this environmental lighting check before making a purchase.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_taurus__moon_gemini__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "structure + light movement + a touch of quiet depth",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on structure + light movement + a touch of quiet depth.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Pick up a garment and test its flexibility. Your physical instinct for equilibrium is your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not. Build your foundation around structure + light movement + a touch of quiet depth. Picture a tailored wool blazer worn open over a fluid silk shirt, anchored by a densely woven scarf. The crisp lines construct a defined frame. The silk introduces gentle kinetic energy as you move. The scarf provides subtle complexity without overwhelming the eye. Trust this physical weight in your hands before you put the garments on your body.\n\nCurate your pieces slowly, but assemble your outfits fast. Your wardrobe must adapt to shifting environments without hesitation. Apply the combination test before you purchase a new garment. Pick the item up and physically hold it next to three existing pieces in your closet. Ask yourself if this single garment can anchor a sharp morning silhouette and a relaxed evening drape by simply changing the trousers. If it requires an entirely new supporting cast to function, leave it on the rack. Look for a warm, matt finish in your fabrics to guarantee they blend seamlessly.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is the structural blueprint for your wardrobe, a framework designed to train your eye and refine your physical instincts.",
      "tests": [
        "the combination test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe demands fibres that provide structure without rigidity. When sourcing shirting with clean boundaries, seek out {texture_good_1} in warm tones. For base layers, choose {texture_good_2} to maintain sharp lines and light movement. Trousers require a constant drape. Rely on {texture_good_3} to resist creasing through heavy wear. Finish with {texture_good_4} for mobile outerwear that blocks the wind but weighs nothing in the hand. Always apply the snap test. Pull a section of the cloth taut and release it abruptly. If the material springs immediately back to a crisp edge, it will hold its shape and provide a touch of quiet depth. If it collapses into a shapeless pile, drop it. Rely on your grip to judge the cloth. Prioritise the materials ranked below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the tactile signals that prove a fabric will hold its shape.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Apply tension to the fabric. Pull the cloth taut between your fingers and let it snap back. If {texture_bad_1} rebounds with a harsh, rigid crack, drop it. You require light movement to navigate the day. Stiff synthetics lock you into an inflexible shell and fight your joints. Pick up {texture_bad_2} and crush it tight in your fist. If it retains a sharp, brittle crease in your palm, leave it on the rail. A warm, matt textile should release tension rather than memorialising it. Heavy stiffness betrays your need for balance. Read the surface with your fingertips to detect cheap friction. If the material feels slick or scratchy against the skin, reject it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify and discard materials that betray your design.",
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your sweet spot lives between {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. You are looking for light movement against a warm, muted base. Stretch a panel of {texture_good_1} across your palms, then release it. It must fall fast and clean back into shape without clinging. This crisp rebound provides the right contrast against softer fibres. Keep tones muted and let varying weights do the work. Listen to your touch. If the garment hangs limp, leave it on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the exact point where different cloth weights meet.",
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your whole colour spectrum rests on a warm foundation. Build your base using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} as heavy anchoring layers. Bring in {core_colour_3} as your strict white alternative. Bridge varying tones with {core_colour_4}. Deploy {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} exclusively as deliberate strikes of focused interest. When an outfit requires a soft note used sparingly to break up visual mass, rely on your relief tone. Maintain rigid structure across all shades. Avoid the trap of a monochromatic outfit that loses its shape halfway through your day. Wake up a lifeless column by introducing a crisp poplin shirt collar, an architectural silver band, or a structured suede training shoe. Leave stark pastels, neon brights, and harsh blue-grey on the rack. They clash with your muted finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your palette as a strict boundary line.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Warm taupe",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft cream",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
