      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "a flat monochrome look that bores you by midday",
          "fix": "add a crisp white poplin collar, a silver architectural ring, or a bright geometric sneaker"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, structure leads. Anchor your daily uniform in camel worsted wool trousers that retain their shape on a hanger. Support this firm base with a crisp cotton poplin shirt to introduce light movement. Build a touch of quiet depth using a warm taupe fine ribbed merino knit. Combine silver and gold in your jewellery to maintain a dual register. Keep the visual output muted and balanced. Look for garments that dictate their own lines. Test the drape by feeling the heft of the fabric. Remember the rule: a midday dash for coffee never justifies trading worsted wool for shapeless jersey. Avoid items lacking clear intent.",
      "sectionIntro": "Work demands a specific application of your rules, keeping your instincts sharp under professional constraints.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, let light movement lead. Dim lighting flattens heavy cloth. Shift to fine ribbed merino knits that glide alongside the body. Pair them with warm taupe silk skirts that catch the ambient glow. Evaluate the drape before you dress by feeling the density of the weave. Mix muted bronze hardware with brushed gold rings to capture the sparse light. Close quarters demand breathable fibres. Do not surrender your defined boundaries just because the setting is relaxed. Keep your shape sharp with a touch of quiet depth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Prepare your garments for dim rooms and close company.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A routine trip to the local market provides no reason to abandon your silhouette. Demand the exact same standard for basic errands as you do for a formal appointment. Anchor every ordinary morning in structure + light movement + a touch of quiet depth. Examine your garments on the hanger and assess how they fall. Pair a worsted wool trouser in camel with a simple technical nylon jacket. Check the shoulders to ensure they sit precisely where they belong. Avoid grabbing a shapeless fleece just because the task is mundane. Ground your everyday choices in a warm palette, favouring matt finishes in rich taupe and soft browns. Rely on the natural gravity of the cloth to guide your decisions.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your mundane routines as the true physical baseline for your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Execute a dual-register approach for your metals. Keep your garment hardware, the zips, buckles, and clasps, grounded in {structural_metal_1} and {structural_metal_2}. Reserve {personal_metal_1} and {personal_metal_2} strictly for jewellery worn directly against the skin. This separation brings a touch of quiet depth to your tailored foundation while maintaining a consistently warm undertone. Assess the object by its physical mass in your palm. Demand heavy alloys. Reject artificially aged elements like hammered copper or antiqued brass. They register as chaotic clutter that distracts from your balanced proportions. Instead, insist on clean, solid alloys with a muted finish. Banish {excluded_finish} entirely. Select matt or brushed surfaces that absorb light rather than reflecting it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Implement strict boundaries between the metals you wear against your skin and the ones that secure your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Evaluate your jewellery by its literal density. Use {stone_1} and {stone_2} to provide structure to a warm colour profile. Always test a piece by gauging its gravity in your hand. A hollow casting fails you. Steer clear of oxidized treatments and faux-vintage patinas, as these distressed textures disrupt your balanced proportions. Restrict your hardware strictly to brushed silver, matt white gold, and dense platinum with a muted finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your stones and metals by measuring their actual physical mass.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the piece to gauge its structural integrity. Heavy density proves the true quality of your jewellery. You require hardware that anchors your outfit and introduces a touch of quiet depth. Reject any metalwork that mimics wear and tear. Distressed textures read as visual noise against your warm palette. Keep to clean, unaged forms with a completely matt surface instead. A smooth {metal_1} clasp or a solid {stone_1} pendant provides the correct focal point. Let the sheer gravity of the item dictate your choice.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware by holding it in your palm before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories deliver a touch of quiet depth. Your garments already provide structure. They already offer light movement. Do not overwhelm the frame. Limit yourself to one or two defining pieces per look. Start with a matt silk scarf. Fold a crepe de chine square or knot a slim band at the neck to introduce a warm finish. Always run the mobility test. Turn your neck sharply and shift your shoulders. If the knot slips or the fabric requires constant fixing, take it off.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your final details with ruthless precision.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square or slim band, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Build your fine jewellery around structure. Select thin chains and small drops cast in brushed silver. The metal must remain entirely matt to ground the warm camel and taupe threads in your garments. Put the piece through the balance check before buying. Fasten the necklace and pace the floor for five minutes. If the clasp slides forward to rest on your collarbone, the weighting is wrong. Leave it on the counter. The hardware must hold its physical position.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate the physical balance of your smallest metal additions.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin chain and small drops, brushed silver"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your carry in pure structure. Select a small top-handle bag crafted from kid suede. Check that the hardware remains fine and matt, incorporating mixed warm metals to keep your dual register consistent. This rigid form grounds the light movement of your clothing, offering a touch of quiet depth without excess bulk. Before you head out, inspect your reflection from every angle. Check your profile in the mirror to test your overall equilibrium. If the bag swings awkwardly or breaks your tailored line, leave it on the table.",
      "sectionIntro": "Secure your belongings with deliberate geometry and test your physical balance before walking out the door.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede top-handle, fine matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Assign pattern strictly according to the garment. Your tailored coats and trousers require {recommended_pattern_1} to reinforce their structure. Conversely, softer garments must carry {recommended_pattern_2} to support their light movement. Because your wardrobe adapts across different environments, keep your pattern contrast moderate rather than stark or heavily saturated. Evaluate the print from a distance to ensure it maintains clear boundaries. If the design loses its definition from a few paces away, drop it. Memorise a strict pass-over list to protect your muted finish lane. Walk straight past {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. Instead, ground your warm palette with {recommended_pattern_3} or introduce {recommended_pattern_4} for subtle variation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Govern your patterns with strict rules to keep your visual volume entirely within your control.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Put {recommended_pattern_1} on a hanger at the far end of the room. Close your eyes, count to three, and open them for a single split second. Apply this blink test to every printed garment. If the shapes bleed into a muddy blur, walk away. If the motif fights the garment's inherent structure, leave it behind. You require immediate legibility. The design must hold its boundaries clearly while complementing any light movement. Keep the tones strictly warm and the overall finish muted. Visual confusion is a trap. Demand absolute clarity before you commit.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every print to a strict distance evaluation to separate intention from confusion.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_taurus__moon_gemini__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "soft structure + light movement + a touch of quiet depth",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on soft structure + light movement + a touch of quiet depth.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "To find your footing, rely on the sensory weight of a garment. Trust your hands to seek out dense, warm fabrics that yield to pressure rather than holding a rigid shape. Your baseline equation is soft structure + light movement + a touch of quiet depth. Picture a heavy cashmere wrap coat layered over a fluid silk skirt and a fine gauge knit sweater. The coat provides the boundary. The skirt brings the motion. The knit anchors the visual weight.\n\nApply the melt test before you commit to a piece. Put the garment on and close your eyes. The fabric must feel as though it is dissolving into your frame, sinking into your posture rather than perching stiffly on your shoulders. If a collar bites into your neck or a rigid hem bounces away from your calf, leave the item on the rack. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Build your foundations methodically, ensuring every new item passes this check. Once the pieces are in place, deploy your outfits quickly by feel.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation, the set of physical laws that dictate how clothes must behave on your frame.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your materials must deliver soft structure and light movement. Build your warm foundation around {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Rely on {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Ground your wardrobe using {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Finish with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. This combination ensures a touch of quiet depth in every outfit. Subject every garment to the patina test. Rub the fabric between your fingers and ask how the surface will age. If it will grow richer and more matt over years of wear, buy it. If it will pill or peel, drop it. Let the fabric's long-term endurance guide your hand. Immediate appeal is an illusion, but durability is a fact.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the materials that serve your precise needs.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed alpaca",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "enveloping winter coats and oversized cardigans"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fluid modal jersey",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers that follow the body without ever gripping it"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed cotton flannel",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "shirts and loungewear that feel like a remembered embrace"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the patina test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Avoid anything that feels stiff, synthetic, or brittle. Pick up a piece of {texture_bad_1} and crush it in your fist. If it fights back and refuses to yield, it will ruin your soft structure. Leave it on the rail. Step away from {texture_bad_2}. Run your thumb over the surface to check for a coarse drag. A harsh finish destroys light movement. Apply the same aging assessment you use for your best textiles. Ask yourself how the item will age after ten years of hard wear. If it will crack, pill, or turn to rags instead of settling into a warm, matt lustre, reject it entirely. Rely on your fingers to guide you away from rigid traps.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to recognise and reject the elements that actively fight your styling goals.",
      "tests": [
        "the patina test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to build soft structure. Gather a handful of {texture_good_1} and release it to observe the recovery. Watch how the weave drops back into shape. Question how the material will behave after ten years of heavy use. Superior weaves grow richer and softer in your hands over time. Cheap textiles simply thin out. Warm tones require a matt surface to absorb light and ground the entire outfit.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the exact tension between your best materials.",
      "tests": [
        "the patina test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor your choices in a definitively warm palette. Rely heavily on {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} to build your foundation. Ground these pieces with {core_colour_3} for a dark neutral baseline, and use {core_colour_4} as your earthy green neutral. Deploy {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} strictly as your single deliberate accent. Keep a soft note used sparingly to provide visual relief. Pass over stark optic white, harsh neon, and icy pastel without a second thought. Guard against the sofa drift. If you allow every item to drape and slouch, you are effectively wearing pyjamas. Fix this immediately by restoring one clean boundary. Pick up a proper turned lapel, a trouser pressed to a defined edge, or a rigid calfskin satchel to push back against the ease and defend your soft structure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish your baseline tones and rigid boundaries before you ever reach for an accent.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bitter chocolate",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
