      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "When dressing for the office, soft structure takes the lead. Build an outline with garments that hold shape through precise tailoring rather than stiff fibres. Support this primary element with light movement. A warm, matt bitter chocolate blazer in boiled wool requires the gentle drape of a washed silk blouse to avoid rigidity. Mix steel and gold at the wrist to keep the hardware practical. Subject these pieces to the chemist test. If you cannot wait comfortably in the prescription queue without pulling at a hem or adjusting a collar, leave the garment on the hanger. Workwear must not demand physical endurance. Heavy silk crepe trousers should feel entirely forgiving.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your formula to the office by establishing reliable silhouettes and eliminating physical friction.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "Test your evening choices against physical fatigue. Pick up a bitter chocolate heavy silk crepe dress and imagine sitting through a drawn-out dinner service. If the fabric binds your arms or demands constant adjustment, drop it. Zero suffering is the rule. In close, low-light settings, soft structure leads. Run your fingers over dark mahogany boiled wool or cloud-soft lambswool. Combine these textiles with warm, dual-metal accents. Stack a matt gold cuff against an oxidised silver ring. The body must relax entirely into the cloth. Trust your hands. Mirrors can mislead you, but tactile friction reveals the truth. If a collar feels rigid against your neck, it will read as stiff under dim lights.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your intimate evening wear by prioritising tactile reality over visual performance.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat mundane errands as a test of your foundations. Avoid the trap of lowering your standards for utility. Walking to the corner shop for milk does not mean retreating into shapeless jersey. Anchor your casual pieces in a warm palette. Reach for a boiled wool cardigan over washed silk trousers. Maintain your core equation of soft structure + light movement + a touch of quiet depth regardless of the agenda. Pick up a bitter chocolate knit and test the yarn. Choose garments that feel substantial but yield to your frame. A dark mahogany lambswool sweater paired with matt silk provides absolute comfort without compromising your aesthetic baseline.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build an everyday wardrobe that requires no conscious thought to execute.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "You operate a split metal strategy. Treat {personal_metal_1} and {personal_metal_2} as intimate anchors worn strictly against the skin. Reserve {structural_metal_1} and {structural_metal_2} for functional hardware on bags, belts, and zips. Your palette is warm, meaning you must ruthlessly avoid {excluded_finish} surfaces. A highly reflective polish creates a glaring distraction against washed silk or boiled wool. Keep the aesthetic intact by demanding matt and brushed textures. This maintains soft structure across your wardrobe. When evaluating a new buckle or cuff, lift it in the palm of your hand. Visuals can trick the eye, but heavy mass provides absolute certainty. If the item lacks a heavy, satisfying drop, put it back.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control the hardware on your body by dividing your metals into distinct functional categories.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "When evaluating jewellery, pick the piece up to test its density. Surface shine is a distraction, whereas sheer heaviness confirms quality. Select heavy, opaque stones like {stone_1} and {stone_2} that draw warm light inward rather than flashing it back. These denser materials provide the perfect grounding for soft structure. Avoid high-gloss metals entirely. A highly polished finish cuts sharply against muted fabrics and distracts the eye. Always demand brushed or matt hardware to maintain a cohesive surface.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your wardrobe with hardware that absorbs light and adds physical gravity.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the piece in your palm. A photograph lies about scale, but the physical weight of an object proves its worth. Before you buy any {metal_1} or {stone_1}, feel its heft. Heavy hardware grounds the light movement of your garments. Avoid high-shine, highly polished finishes. Reflective surfaces pull focus and look harsh against a muted, warm palette. Stick to brushed or matt textures to maintain a cohesive finish. Let the density of the hardware anchor the soft structure of your clothes.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your hardware through touch to ensure it supports the drape of your clothes.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You have established soft structure. You have engineered light movement. Now, ground the silhouette with a touch of quiet depth. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start with handbags. Demand full-grain leather finished with brushed matt hardware. Before purchasing, put every item through the ripple test. Bend the material gently between your fingers. The surface must undulate and absorb light like a warm pool of dark mahogany. If the finish flashes or reflects a sharp glare, drop it. Gauge the hide purely by its substantial yield.",
      "sectionIntro": "We now anchor your garments with precise, intentional hardware and leather.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Evaluate your scarves for fluidity. Hold a square of washed silk or fine wool by a single corner and give it a sharp flick. Watch how the fabric falls. You are looking for light movement. The textile must settle into fluid, heavy waves rather than crisp, stiff folds. Keep the finish completely matt to absorb ambient room light rather than reflect it. A warm dark mahogany silk scarf should look dense and saturated. Reject any accessory with a high sheen or a slippery surface. Depend on your own tactile instincts over visual appeal. Sheen is artificial, but the downward pull of a heavy textile is absolute. If the fine wool feels airy but holds a yielding soft structure, keep it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Force your neckwear to prove its quality through pure physical performance.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your trousers with a medium full-grain leather belt. Look for a dark mahogany hide finished with a matt buckle. Select keepsake jewellery in aged silver or oxidised metals, and trust your hands to assess the weight of the pieces. Ensure the overall finish remains warm to match your palette. Before completing the outfit, examine the collision point between materials. Drop the clothing onto your frame and observe how the accessories interact with the fabric. If a stiff buckle or rigid ring abruptly halts the natural drape of your washed silk shirt, remove the item. Every piece of hardware must support the soft structure of your silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your hardware choices by checking the physical interaction between your accessories and your garments.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Treat pattern as an extension of the textile itself. Your tailored garments require soft structure. Let them draw their visual interest entirely from the weave, using {recommended_pattern_1} to create subtle dimension. Your fluid pieces should rely on low-contrast tonal variations like {recommended_pattern_2}. Keep all contrast strictly minimal so the motif barely emerges from the background. Subject every print to the dusk test. View the garment as the room darkens. The motif must soften and merge into a warm, shifting topography across the cloth. If the lines stay rigid, reject the piece. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. They break the visual calm. Depend instead on {recommended_pattern_3} to provide a reliable, muted foundation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every pattern as a structural component rather than a surface decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Examine {recommended_pattern_1} under failing light. Hang the garment across the room and drop the lighting. A successful design loses its hard edges and becomes a warm shifting surface. If the motif remains rigid in the dimness, leave it on the rail. Trust your immediate visual instinct over the label. You require soft structure. The print must blur into the base cloth rather than sitting on top as a sharp graphic. Step back from the mirror and squint. If the shapes jump forward, the contrast is too severe. Select patterns that melt into the material.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your prints using a simple test of light and distance.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_taurus__moon_libra__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "soft structure + cool composure + a touch of quiet depth",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on soft structure + cool composure + a touch of quiet depth.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Curate your wardrobe with methodical slowness. Run your hand over a garment before you check the label. If the fabric catches on your skin or the cut feels restrictive, trust your physical recoil and walk away. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not. Your physical response is immediate. You are building a collection rooted in quiet luxury, and this requires acquiring pieces only when they pass a strict tactile test. Every piece must feel inherently warm and expertly woven.\n\nYour foundational equation is soft structure + cool composure + a touch of quiet depth. Picture a lightweight wool coat with an unstructured shoulder layered over a fine knit, finished with a tailored trouser that breaks cleanly over a leather loafer. The coat provides the soft structure. The precise drape of the trouser delivers cool composure. The matt finish of the leather anchors the look with a touch of quiet depth. Avoid anything that demands attention or distorts your natural balance. Let the pure cut and drape of the garments do the heavy lifting.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise these principles to build a wardrobe governed by instinct and strict physical discipline.",
      "tests": [
        "trust your gut and walk away"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe on fabrics that absorb light and provide soft structure. Pick up a garment and apply the candlelight test. Hold the material up to a lamp. If the surface throws back a harsh glare, drop it. You require a warm, matt finish that holds a touch of quiet depth. Seek out {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to a dull glow. Rely on {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Choose {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Finally, invest in {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. Consult the ranked list below to source your materials.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the warm, muted fibres that build your foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
