  "venus_taurus__moon_scorpio__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "structure + quiet undercurrent + a touch of quiet depth",
    "closing": "Trust the gravity of your materials and the absolute truth of your own hands, demanding nothing less than your foundational equation: structure + quiet undercurrent + a touch of quiet depth.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Build slowly. Assemble your wardrobe piece by piece, relying on deliberate precision over rapid acquisition. Feel the weight and the drape of the fabric before you wear it. Trust a dense, heavy weave against your skin. It must feel warm and substantial, grounding you firmly in your own space. Let this density be your baseline. Your clothing follows a strict equation: structure + quiet undercurrent + a touch of quiet depth. Picture a heavy, tailored coat cut with sharp shoulders, layered over a fine knit that sits close to the ribs, finished with a dense timepiece that catches the light only when you turn your hand.\n\nKeep your focus strictly inward. Your clothes serve you, not an audience. Apply the wrist test before keeping any new garment. Run the cuff between your thumb and forefinger to check how the exact edge rests against your joint. If the sleeve collapses, feels hollow, or fails to hold a rigid shape, leave it on the rack. You require pieces that maintain a distinct, secure perimeter around your body. They must sit heavy and resolute. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your baseline blueprint, the structural foundation for everything you will build and wear.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe demands physical substance to maintain its structure. Look for materials that possess a quiet undercurrent of uncompromising quality. Pick up a garment and apply the candlelight test. If the fabric absorbs a low, warm glow rather than reflecting a harsh glare, it serves your wardrobe. Let the gravity of the textile guide you. Your eyes can be fooled, but true mass is absolute. Choose {texture_good_1} for knitwear that compresses under your hands and springs back. Select {texture_good_2} for bags and belts that mould to your grip. Rely on {texture_good_3} for tailored coats that hold clean lines for years. Layer {texture_good_4} against your skin for a touch of quiet depth in blouses and linings. Keep these four materials as your baseline.",
      "sectionIntro": "Your hands will tell you exactly what belongs in your wardrobe before you even look at the garment.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
        {
          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Reject {texture_bad_1} immediately. Pick it up and feel the synthetic slip between your fingers. It lacks the heavy density required to hold strict structure. Avoid {texture_bad_2} for identical reasons. Squeeze a handful of the material. If it crushes into sharp creases and refuses to spring back, leave it on the hanger. A quiet undercurrent demands components with inherent integrity. Recreate the low-light check with everything you consider taking home. Hold the cloth near a soft, amber bulb. If the surface bounces back a sharp reflection rather than drinking in the dimness to form a flat, matt finish, it fails. You require textiles that ground you in self-contained silence. Rely on weight and drape. If an item lacks profound density in your grip, drop it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify and discard the materials that actively undermine your silhouette.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Pick up a length of {texture_good_1} and crush it in your fist. The fibres must feel dense and resilient, delivering a touch of quiet depth without demanding external attention. Bring the material near a low, flickering match. The surface must drink the warm illumination, remaining softly matt and muted instead of throwing a hard reflection. Vision deceives, but your bare hands tell the strict truth about a garment's quality. Squeeze the cloth to confirm its mass. Avoid any glossy finish that distracts the eye. Keep the combination strictly self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Isolate the precise texture combination that anchors your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor your wardrobe in a warm climate. Build your foundation using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} to create a self-contained base. Introduce {core_colour_3} and {core_colour_4} to shift the mood without disrupting the harmony. When you require a focal point, deploy {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as your single deliberate accent. Treat your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly. Pass over icy electric blue, neon brights, and fleeting trend pastels. These tones shatter your muted finish. Rely on the tension of the fabric in your hands. Grasp the garment and feel its density. A superior weave proves its worth through drape and resistance before you ever put it on. Watch for the trap of swaddling. Layering shapeless garments can easily dissolve your silhouette entirely. When your shape begins to blur, you must restore a defined line. Add a crisp collar, a neat cuff, or let a keepsake pendant sit visibly at the neckline. This precise adjustment introduces a touch of quiet depth to break the monotony. Keep your edges distinct, allowing your palette to frame your proportions rather than hide them.",
      "sectionIntro": "Manage your foundation tones with precision, allowing them to frame your silhouette rather than swallow it.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rich toffee",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Taupe",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Stone grey",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft cream",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Olive",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Moss green",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Oxblood",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Burgundy",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Plum",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Misty blue-green",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "swaddling: layer upon layer of shapeless grey and the silhouette dissolves entirely",
          "fix": "restore one defined line, a structured collar, a neat cuff, or let the keepsake pendant sit visibly at the neckline"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, structure must take the lead. Let it dictate the sharp shoulder of a brushed wool blazer or the clean edge of a full-grain leather briefcase. Support this architecture with a quiet undercurrent of soft, warm materials. A camel cashmere polo neck provides vital grounding. Introduce a touch of quiet depth through heavy metals, like a matt brass buckle or a thick gold chain. Apply absolute rigour to your entire day. Walking your dog merits the identical standard as sitting in a board meeting. Trust the heft in your hands to guide your choices. Pick up a piece of tailoring and test the weight. Mirrors play tricks. The sheer heaviness of a garment never will. Flimsy materials betray you, so leave them on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Mastering your working hours means establishing a rigorous daily standard and relying on strict material cues.",
      "tests": [
        "walking the dog deserves the same standard as a meeting (Moss)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim settings, the quiet undercurrent must lead. Discard stiff lapels. Reach for a camel cashmere sweater or a rich toffee silk shirt. Assess the garment by how it falls. Trust your hands to guide you. Your eyes will deceive you in shadows, but the physical pull of heavy yarn will not. Warm, matt bronze jewellery provides the correct finish without catching unwanted reflections. Keep the silhouette self-contained. Stepping out into the dark requires precisely the same dedication to your aesthetic as any public appearance.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply these strict rules when the lights drop and the physical proximity closes.",
      "tests": [
        "walking the dog deserves the same standard as a meeting (Moss)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Dress deliberately for mundane tasks. Running an errand calls for the very same uncompromising baseline as your highest-stakes appointments. Do not keep a separate pile of degraded clothes for chores. Throwing on a rich toffee brushed wool coat over warm silk is your daily baseline. Require every outfit to execute structure + quiet undercurrent + a touch of quiet depth at all times. Look for garments that hold their shape while you wait in the pharmacy queue. Choose heavy full-grain leather boots that anchor your step on an ordinary Tuesday. Avoid anything flimsy. If a garment is not fit for a serious appointment, do not wear it to fetch the morning paper. Trust the heavy drape of proper tailoring to support your daily movement.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your everyday routines as the primary arena for your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "walking the dog deserves the same standard as a meeting (Moss)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Anchor your wardrobe in warm tones. Seek out {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} for all hardware. Build firm structure from dense metal. Avoid {excluded_finish} finishes completely. Mirror-bright surfaces will catch the light sharply and fight against your muted styling. Rely exclusively on matt and brushed textures to maintain cohesion. Pick the item up before buying it. Your vision can be swayed by shine. The downward pull of a piece is your only reliable metric. If a zip or watch case lacks gravitational pull, put it back. You need heavy materials to anchor soft wool and thick leather. Let the physical density of the hardware dictate your choice.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware like a structural engineer.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Evaluate every gem by how it absorbs light. Reach for opaque pieces like {stone_1} and {stone_2}. They bring structure to your warm fabrics. Avoid highly reflective hardware. High-shine finishes look sharply distracting next to muted garments. Stick entirely to brushed and matt textures to keep your composition cohesive. Lift every item in your palm to test its quality. Trust your tactile senses. Do not be swayed by surface appearance. Solid density is your true measure. If a stone feels insubstantial, leave it behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess your stones by their density and the precise way they control light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Pick up every buckle, clasp, and ring. Rely on your tactile sense to assess the true quality of a piece. Surface finishes play tricks on the eye. Real heft confirms the value. If {metal_1} lacks severe weight, leave it on the shelf. You need substantial weight to support your structure. Watch out for highly polished finishes. Glossy, reflective metals clash sharply against warm, muted garments and distract the eye. Fix this error by demanding matt or brushed textures. A heavily brushed {metal_1} cuff or a dense {stone_1} ring absorbs ambient light instead of throwing it back. This discipline keeps your components perfectly cohesive.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware by touch to ensure it supports your visual intent.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You have built your structure. You have secured the quiet undercurrent. Now your accessories must provide a touch of quiet depth. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look to maintain a self-contained finish. Begin with handbags. Look for full-grain leather or thick suede, checking that all metal hardware carries a warm, matt brushed finish. Trust your hands when evaluating these items. If a piece does not possess the dense gravity of a future heirloom, put it back. A shiny coating can hide cheap construction. A profound heaviness proves its worth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Curate your accessories as tools of final calibration.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Build structure around your collar with fine wool or generous silk. Always insist on a completely matt finish. Select warm tones that absorb light rather than reflect it. Subject every potential addition to the keepsake test. Ask yourself if the textile warrants careful preservation in a private cedar box thirty years from now. Let your bare hands act as the final judge. Do not judge a scarf by its colour alone. The strict bulk of the fibres must convince you. If the yarn feels fragile or the drape lacks substance, reject it immediately. The fabric must hold a deliberate fold.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply strict tactile standards to your soft accessories.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Fasten wide full-grain leather belts to provide necessary structure. Demand a matt brushed buckle in brass that keeps the palette warm. For keepsake jewellery, pick a deep garnet or dark amber stone set in oxidised brass or aged silver. Question the longevity of your final hardware before deciding your outfit is complete. Grasp the heaviest piece you plan to wear. If the metal feels like a temporary decoration rather than a dense heirloom you will eventually secure in a wooden box, take it off. True weight dictates what stays.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your final hardware and personal stones to ensure every piece justifies its place on your body.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Define your structure through woven motifs rather than printed graphics. Tailored garments take their pattern from the weave itself. Your fluid pieces require the quiet undercurrent of subtle, low-contrast dye. Maintain a strictly low-contrast tonal rule for all designs. Pass over harsh {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. Look instead for {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} rendered in warm, closely matched threads. Execute the lamplight test to verify the effect. Bring the garment into a room lit only by a warm bulb. The pattern must melt into a continuous, soft texture. If the lines stay rigidly defined, the contrast is too severe. Shut your eyes and run your fingers over the cloth. The tactile surface must always agree with the visual motif.",
      "sectionIntro": "Approach pattern as a subtle structural tool rather than a surface decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the lamplight test (melt into a soft texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Test every print with the distance check. Drape {recommended_pattern_1} across a chair and switch on a single warm bulb. Walk ten paces away. The shapes should blur into a unified, matt surface. If the lines remain distinctly legible in the dim room, the contrast is too aggressive. A correct pattern respects the underlying structure of the garment rather than fighting it. Trust this physical response as your primary guide. Ignore the initial visual impact. Density and drape remain constant. Pick it up and feel the weave in your hands.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use the lamplight method to test whether a pattern truly belongs in your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the lamplight test (melt into a soft texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_taurus__moon_sagittarius__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "structure + fast movement + a touch of quiet depth",
    "closing": "Let your hands and physical instincts map the path to structure + fast movement + a touch of quiet depth.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your physical instincts as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not. Test the internal seams of a garment and feel the drape against your forearm before you check a label. Construct your wardrobe slowly, but dress with fast momentum. Apply the host test to every new acquisition. Ask yourself if the piece allows you to pour a drink for a guest or reach across a table without adjusting a collar or smoothing a hem. If a garment requires constant physical management, drop it immediately.\n\nYour aesthetic relies on a strict calibration. Your core style formula is structure + fast movement + a touch of quiet depth. Picture a sharply tailored blazer with absolute shoulder precision, worn over a fluid trouser that catches the air when you stride, finished with a heavy, matt scarf tucked deep inside the collar. The outer edges dictate your shape. The drape provides the speed. The hidden layers ground the outfit. Stick to warm tones and muted finishes to force the eye onto the cut rather than the surface.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the architectural rules of your wardrobe before you buy another piece.",
      "tests": [
        "the host test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Trust your hands to find materials that deliver structure, fast movement, and a touch of quiet depth. Look for {texture_good_3} in tailored blazers that hold clean lines over years of wear. Inject fast movement with {texture_good_4} for linings and blouses that slip over the skin without catching. Build a touch of quiet depth using {texture_good_1} for heavy winter layers. Grab a handful of the sleeve and squeeze. It must compress heavily and bounce back instantly. Finish with {texture_good_2} for shoes and bags, and always apply the patina test before you purchase. Rub the surface with your thumb and ask if the material will develop a warm, muted richness from daily friction, or if it will merely scratch and peel. Build your wardrobe from this foundation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to read a garment before you ever check the composition label.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
