        "the patina test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Pair a matt, {sweet_spot_keyword_1} finish with a {sweet_spot_keyword_2} weave. Look for {texture_good_1} that feels warm to the skin. Bunch the sleeve in your hand to test it. You need fast movement as the cloth falls back into place. Require materials that mature over the next decade. Premium yarns and quality hides soften into their shape instead of breaking down. Rely on your tactile sense to detect this enduring character. Avoid any textile that catches or feels brittle.",
      "sectionIntro": "Lock down your signature fabric pairing to anchor your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the patina test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette relies on a fundamentally warm temperature. Anchor your garments in {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Use {core_colour_3} and {core_colour_4} to bridge combinations. Deploy {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as your single deliberate accent to create sharp visual structure. Treat your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly near the face. Pass over icy electric blue, neon brights, and fleeting trend pastels entirely. Watch for the trap of the heavy earth sink. Piling dense, matt, dark woodland tones together will swallow your frame whole. Fix this by introducing light. Place a pale cream knit at the collar, add one piece of full-grain leather, or deploy your relief tone to lift the combination.",
