    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your clothing establishes the structure and generates the fast movement. Your accessories exist solely to provide a touch of quiet depth. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with handbags. Demand full-grain leather and inspect the metal closures to ensure you are holding genuine matt hardware. Before stepping out, apply the one-ember test. Examine the piece in your hand and ask if it holds enough heat to warm the entire silhouette on its own. A solitary, glowing coal anchors a dark hearth perfectly. If the item requires a second accessory to justify its inclusion, drop it.",
      "sectionIntro": "This section defines how to select and test the few grounding additions your wardrobe requires.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Choose scarves exclusively in silk or fine wool. Insist on a completely matt finish. Glossy surfaces slip and lose their deliberate drape. You need textiles that grip your coat collar to secure your silhouette. This deliberate friction delivers fast movement. Assess the colour depth of every camel or toffee piece you consider. Roll the material in your hands and bring it into the sunlight. Search for a hidden spark of warm pigment trapped deep inside the yarn. If the dye turns to cold ash or casts a clinical shadow against your jaw, abandon it on the rack. The fabric must hold its own internal heat to earn its keep.",
      "sectionIntro": "Your neckwear requires strict material discipline to function correctly.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Build structure with a medium full-grain leather belt. Inspect the hardware. Demand a matt buckle. Anchor your warm metals with oxidised keepsake jewellery. Feel the dense heat of the cast metal. If the piece feels hollow, drop it. Real density guarantees quality. Finally, review your reflection to locate the primary focal point in your outfit. Strip away any competing details. Fast movement requires absolute focus. Keep only one source of visual heat.",
      "sectionIntro": "Secure your proportions and run a final physical check before stepping out.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Limit contrast. Keep your patterns tonal and low-contrast to preserve a continuous line. In tailored jackets, let {recommended_pattern_1} add structure through the physical weave of the cloth. In fluid silk, allow {recommended_pattern_2} to create fast movement across the drape. Pass over stark graphics entirely. Trust your physical response to a print. Pick up a piece with {avoid_pattern_1} or {avoid_pattern_2} and scrutinise the visual noise. If the sharp lines jar your focus, drop the item immediately. Take your chosen garments into a dim room with a single lamp to conduct the firelight test. A suitable motif will sink into the matt fabric and reveal a deep, warm tone under the bulb, rather than sitting flat and harsh on the surface.",
      "sectionIntro": "Let pattern serve the construction of your garments rather than fighting it.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Examine {recommended_pattern_1} under appropriate lighting. Pull the garment away from the harsh shop overheads and find a low, warm lamp. Watch the ink. The tones must deepen into the cloth, gathering richness in the dim setting. If the design turns muddy or loses its boundaries, leave it on the rail. You require clear structure in your prints. Look for shapes that deliver fast movement across the weave without blurring at the edges. Trust this visual instinct. The shop mirror deceives the eye. The shadows reveal the reality. A successful print holds its quiet depth under a soft bulb, never turning matt or grey.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your prints using a targeted environmental shift.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_taurus__moon_pisces__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "structure + blurred edges + a touch of quiet depth",
    "closing": "Trust the drag of dense cloth and the warmth of subdued metals to guide your hands toward structure + blurred edges + a touch of quiet depth.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Run your thumb over the seam of a garment before you check the label. You are looking for a heavy, silent drape. Trust this physical instinct as your compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Your formula is structure + blurred edges + a touch of quiet depth. Picture a sharply tailored wool overcoat worn over a heavily felted knit, finished with a pair of thick, matt leather boots. The silhouette holds firm. The textures absorb light rather than reflecting it. Add a dense, warm scarf. Nothing shouts. The luxury lives entirely in the weight of the cloth and the precision of the cut.\n\nBuild slowly. Acquire single, flawless pieces over months. Wear them fast in the morning. When a piece works, it becomes an unthinking reflex. Rely on your body to gauge a garment. Put on a jacket. If you immediately feel a restless friction, take it off. If the cloth feels flimsy or demands attention, heed your own physical rejection. Listen to that sudden drop in your stomach and step out of the changing room. Leave the shop. You require garments that ground you inward. If a piece requires you to perform or adjust, drop it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this logic before you touch another garment.",
      "tests": [
        "trust your gut and walk away"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your best fabrics combine physical structure with blurred edges. Rely on {texture_good_3} for tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years. Layer {texture_good_1} for knitwear that compresses in your grip and bounces back. Close to the skin, use {texture_good_4} for blouses and linings that add fluid movement. Ground these choices with {texture_good_2} for bags and belts that mould to your daily habits. Subject every potential purchase to the candlelight test. Hold the material under a warm, dim light. If the surface reflects a sharp glare, drop it. Look for a heavy, matt finish that drinks in the light to reveal a touch of quiet depth. Trust your hands. Master the list below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise materials that anchor your wardrobe in absolute privacy and focus.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
        {
          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Leave {texture_bad_1} on the rail. Touch the cloth, and your fingers will immediately register the mistake. It reflects light in stark, flat sheets. Take any prospective garment into a shadowed corner. Observe how the threads handle a dim environment. If the piece bounces glare back at you instead of drinking in the glow, drop it. Rely on physical resistance over visual appeal. Trust your bare hands as your ultimate compass. Avoid {texture_bad_2} entirely. It builds a rigid, unyielding shell that ruins your requirement for blurred edges. When you encounter {texture_bad_3}, notice the slick, cold finish. It lacks the muted, matt surface your orientation requires. You need textiles that absorb scrutiny, not textiles that reflect it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject the materials that compromise your foundation.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Trust your touch to master the tension between {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Bring your {texture_good_1} into a room lit by a single warm flame. Study the threads. If the cloth turns dead and flat in the shadows, leave it on the rack. The right material holds a soft inner glow when the room dims. Contrast these elements to build blurred edges across your silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the tension between your core textures to build a deliberate foundation.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your temperature is warm. Build your colour foundation using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} as your heaviest layers. Add {core_colour_3} and {core_colour_4} to provide structure to your softer knits. Treat {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} as deliberate punctuation marks. Deploy your relief tone sparingly to give the eye a resting place. Leave icy electric blue, neon brights, and fleeting trend pastels on the rail. Defaulting to head-to-toe black suggests a sudden loss of styling stamina. Intervene at once. Split up a solid dark column by introducing a {core_colour_1} tailored coat, wrapping a {accent_colour_2} scarf at the collar, or fastening a {accent_colour_1} leather belt at the waist.",
      "sectionIntro": "Identify your colour roles and deploy them with strict discipline.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rich toffee",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
