        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "head-to-toe black reads like you gave up on the way out the door",
          "fix": "break it up with a camel layer, a deep wine scarf, or a rich cognac belt"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Structure dictates your approach to demanding tasks. Let blurred edges and quiet depth provide the necessary support. A sharp shoulder line requires warm, heavy silk or thick brushed wool to temper the severity. Demand absolute precision from your clothing across all contexts. A quiet morning drafting proposals requires the exact same rigorous cut as a high-stakes Monday briefing. Keep your silhouette strict but choose deep toffee and camel fibres that mute the surrounding noise. Let the shape do the heavy lifting while soft, matt surfaces keep your energy self-contained. Reject anything rigid or distracting. Your clothing must frame you precisely without ever turning into armour.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your physical instincts to the office.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In low light, blurred edges take the lead over rigid structure. Let dim lighting fall on warm, matt surfaces. Choose a rich toffee silk shirt over a stiff collar. Treat a quiet coffee at the local roaster with the exact same baseline as an evening out. Avoid highly polished gold. Pick out aged brass jewellery or brushed bronze buckles, allowing the metal to glow dimly. Trust your tactile instincts as your absolute guide. Focus on how the cloth settles against your frame. Assess the fall of a camel cashmere sweater by observing how it rests heavily against the body. Notice how full-grain leather boots firmly anchor the overall shape. Keep your layers minimal and completely self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the art of dressing for close proximity and low light.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A Tuesday morning hardware shop run for brass screws demands the exact same clean drape as a board meeting. Do not lower your standards for mundane tasks. Build your outfit using your constant equation. The rule is always structure + blurred edges + a touch of quiet depth. Pair dense camel wool trousers with a fluid silk top. Add matt yellow gold rings. Layer a rich toffee cashmere wrap tightly around your neck. Notice how the warm tones anchor your body. Grab the fabric and test its heft. Heavy cloth falls correctly. Avoid flimsy jersey joggers entirely. Let dense weaves dictate your daily baseline.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your simplest errands as a strict testing ground for your daily baseline.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your hardware strategy runs warm. Anchor your collection in {metal_1} and {metal_2}, reserving {metal_3} for subtle accents. Avoid highly polished surfaces. A gleaming, highly reflective watch strap will clash against the subdued yarns of your {core_colour_1} cashmere. Reject {excluded_finish} metals that scatter harsh light. Seek out matt and brushed finishes to keep the visual cohesive. Muted textures maintain the blurred edges of your look while adding a touch of quiet depth. When evaluating a buckle or chain, lift it. Let the physical mass in your palm guide your final decision. The satisfying weight acts as your true guide for quality. Structure starts with this undeniable reality.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hardware acts as the definitive anchor for your wardrobe. Select every piece with uncompromising intent.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Look for stones that absorb light rather than refract it. {stone_1} and {stone_2} serve you best when they present a muted face. Lift the piece to verify its mass. Ignore the showcase lighting. Test the weight. Trust your grasp. A heavy, warm density confirms the quality of {stone_2} in your palm. Frame these pieces in burnished hardware. Avoid gleaming reflective metal, as it shatters the harmony of your muted colours. Require a matt finish to maintain cohesion. Dense opaque stones paired with sanded metal will build a touch of quiet depth into your silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess your stones by their physical density and their refusal to reflect light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift every {metal_1} chain or belt buckle off the table. Judge the piece with your eyes closed. Only heavy, solid materials pass the test. Let heavy sensation guide you. A mirror-like clasp flashes harshly against a warm {core_colour_1} coat, severing the visual calm. Instead, select matt or gently brushed surfaces to keep the pieces cohesive. You require structure, softened by blurred edges, and anchored by a touch of quiet depth. Solid, subdued metals support this perfectly.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate the physical substance of every clasp, chain, and buckle before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments establish the necessary structure alongside the softness of blurred edges. Accessories deliver the final component. They supply a touch of quiet depth. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Put on your chosen accents, check the mirror, and strip away the most demanding detail. A single heavy focal point grounds an outfit better than competing elements. Apply this severe edit to your handbags. Demand full-grain leather or thick suede. Pick up the bag and gauge its physical density. Inspect every strap and closure. Choose warm metals with a matt brushed finish. Skip any high-gloss hardware that catches sharp reflections. Dense materials do the work without demanding attention.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your finishing details by their tactile weight and visual silence.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Look for generous silk or fine wool scarves. Always insist on a matt finish. Test a warm camel length against your collar. Trust your physical reaction to the fabric. Edit the final arrangement ruthlessly. If a heavy scarf dictates the neckline, take off the large gold cuff. One strong anchor brings a touch of quiet depth. Force every other piece into a supporting role. Never let an extra accessory fight for attention.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hold your accessories to a strict limit before you step out the door.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your garments with wide full-grain leather belts fastened by matt, brushed buckles. Grasp the leather to verify the heft. Let the resistance of the hide guide your choice. A thick layer of leather provides immediate grounding. For keepsake jewellery, select a deep stone set in warm oxidised brass or aged silver. The darkened metal creates blurred edges around the gem. Enforce a strict limit on your accents before stepping outside. Remove the one accessory doing too much. A single substantial ring provides enough structure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply strict limits to your finishing details.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Keep your patterns rooted in structure. Tailored pieces pull their motifs directly from the physical weave, relying on the built-in geometry of {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Fluid garments require low-contrast tonal shifts that respect your warm palette. Assess every motif from a distance. The shapes must merge into a rich, unified surface. If you see stark graphics instead of blurred edges, put the hanger back. Maintain a strictly low contrast rule across all fabrics. Pass over stark colour blocking, distinct outlines, and {avoid_pattern_1}. Rely on {recommended_pattern_3} when you need slight variation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control visual noise by treating every printed motif as an extension of physical texture.",
      "tests": [
        "step back and soften focus (blur into texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Hang the item against a wall. Walk backward ten paces and let your eyes drop out of focus. A successful {recommended_pattern_1} will surrender its crisp borders and dissolve into a warm, continuous texture. If the graphic shapes remain distinct from this distance, leave the piece on the rail. You require firm structure in the tailoring, never in the print. The motif must melt into soft, blurred edges that read as a solid hue from afar. This fading effect keeps the visual detail strictly contained to your immediate physical space.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the Ten-Pace Texture Test to evaluate any patterned garment.",
      "tests": [
        "step back and soften focus (blur into texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_virgo__moon_aquarius__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "precise fit + mobile layers + one meticulous detail",
    "closing": "Trust your hands to measure the cloth, rely on gravity to test the metals, and always anchor your wardrobe in precise fit + mobile layers + one meticulous detail.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your physical instinct for equilibrium is your most reliable guide. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. When you pick up a garment, test its responsiveness. It must yield to your movement rather than restricting it. Build your wardrobe methodically but deploy it fluidly. Your neutral temperature requires careful calibration, avoiding extreme contrasts. Apply the treaty test to every new acquisition. If a piece of clothing requires you to adjust your natural stride or posture to accommodate its structure, reject it. You demand an equal pact between fabric and form.\n\nKeep your finishes matt and your lines clean. Your guiding equation is precise fit + mobile layers + one meticulous detail. Picture a tailored base layer sitting flush against the skin, topped with a fluid, unstructured overcoat that shifts as you turn, anchored by a single, carefully machined metal fastening at the lapel. The precise fit establishes the architecture. The mobile layers provide the physical adaptability. The one meticulous detail serves as the deliberate focal point. Rely on this specific balance to ensure the garments remain functional tools.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish your physical baseline before you build.",
      "tests": [
        "the treaty test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "To build mobile layers that work across any neutral palette, you must judge every fabric by how it yields to your grip. Apply the two-hands test. Crush the material between both palms and release it to see if it immediately flows back into a soft, matt shape. Let the tactile feedback in your fingers dictate your choices. Look for {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Seek {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Rely on {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Finally, hunt down {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. These materials guarantee a precise fit because they move the moment you do. Start with this hierarchy.",
      "sectionIntro": "Let your hands filter out the rigid and the synthetic before a garment even touches your shoulders.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed alpaca",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "enveloping winter coats and oversized cardigans"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fluid modal jersey",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers that follow the body without ever gripping it"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed cotton flannel",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "shirts and loungewear that feel like a remembered embrace"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Execute the tension check. Grip a sleeve with both fists and pull in opposite directions. If the material fights your movement with a rigid, hollow stiffness, it fails. Avoid {texture_bad_1}. It lacks the fluid drape required to anchor one meticulous detail. Leave {texture_bad_2} on the rack. Run your thumb across the weave. If it catches dry skin or feels like spun plastic, it will trap heat and ruin your balance. Reject {texture_bad_3} immediately. Squeeze it tightly in your palm and let go. A surface that instantly traps a grid of hard creases will dictate your day, demanding constant maintenance instead of adapting to your shape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Identify and reject materials that fight your movement or disrupt your silhouette.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to anchor your wardrobe. This tactile pairing guarantees a precise fit that adapts to your movement. Test the structural memory before you buy. Stretch the fabric gently to feel the tension and notice how the fibres return to their original shape. A piece of {texture_good_1} must hold enough density to drape properly. If the yarn feels hollow or the weave lacks resistance, put the item down. Your garments must operate efficiently in motion. Rely on your touch to locate the correct neutral, matt surfaces.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your core tactile combinations to ensure your clothing performs perfectly in motion.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your temperature is purely neutral. Build the foundation with {core_colour_1} alongside {core_colour_2}. Swap stark white for {core_colour_3}. Ground lighter components using {core_colour_4}. Deploy {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as a single deliberate focal point. Apply your relief tone only as a soft note used sparingly. Pass over neon brights, hard jet black, and glitter finishes entirely. Watch for the pendulum trap. You will wear only heavy silk crepe and cloud-soft lambswool for weeks, then suddenly pivot to severe utility garments. Stop this cycle. Fix it by integrating both hands. Keep one item from the opposing discipline in every rig. Rely on mobile layers to fuse soft drape with rigid structure in a single outfit.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your exact shades by assigning strict functional jobs to every dye in your wardrobe.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Pewter grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Misty greige",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Oyster",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Shadow taupe",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Driftwood grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep slate",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Muted plum",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sea-glass teal",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Pale oat",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the seesaw: one month all floaty gauze, the next all crisp utility",
          "fix": "re-weave instead: keep one item from the other hand in every outfit, always"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, precise fit leads. A sharply cut sleeve or a closely mapped shoulder in boiled wool sets your baseline. Let mobile layers support this foundation. Add a cardigan in cloud-soft lambswool to manage shifting office temperatures. Ground the ensemble with one meticulous detail, perhaps a matt silver collar pin resting against pewter grey. Test every combination with the queue metric. If you cannot stand comfortably for twenty minutes waiting for a train, change your clothes immediately. A working wardrobe never requires suffering for the aesthetic. Keep the overall palette neutral and the finishes muted. Trust the cut of the cloth to hold the line.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your working week by establishing a strict baseline of cut and comfort.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In intimate settings, your mobile layers take the lead. Reach for washed silk and heavy silk crepe that move with your body. Dim light softens visual contrast. Rely on a neutral palette anchored in pewter grey to establish structure. Anchor the look with one meticulous detail to provide focus. Evaluate your clothing against the late-night errand test. If you are standing under harsh fluorescent lights to buy paracetamol, your heavy silk should still feel entirely functional. You do not need to suffer physical restriction for an evening aesthetic. Demand a precise fit that supports without binding. Keep all surfaces matt to absorb ambient illumination. Select cool-dominant metals like brushed titanium or oxidised silver. Let the physical weight of the textiles do the work.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control the low-light environments where physical proximity dictates your choices.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Fetching a prescription from the local chemist does not require you to endure stiff tailoring, nor does it excuse shapeless jersey. Demand garments that support constant motion. Build an adaptable foundation from washed silk shirts and cloud-soft lambswool knits. Keep the overall temperature strictly neutral. Let a pewter grey trouser take the strain. Grab the fabric. Trust your hands. Ensure the weave holds its shape without restricting your stride. Your baseline is always precise fit + mobile layers + one meticulous detail. Require every piece to transition from morning transit to evening tasks without a mirror check.",
      "sectionIntro": "Construct your daily uniform to endure constant movement without sacrificing form.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Anchor your jewellery and structural hardware in a cool-dominant strategy. Choose {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} to maintain a neutral temperature. Restrict your hardware finish to muted or matt surfaces, and reject {excluded_finish} pieces entirely. Lift every chain, clasp, and buckle in your bare hands to evaluate its integrity. Rely on your tactile instincts over your vision. The eye lies, but sheer density tells the truth. Heavy metal hardware grounds your mobile layers, pulling the fabric smoothly downward. Avoid beaten rustic textures and artificially aged alloys. They act as visual noise. Rely instead on the sharp execution of clean, unblemished {metal_1} or {metal_3} to secure a precise fit.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your hardware not as a decorative afterthought, but as the structural anchor of your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Choose stones that hold light with a muted glow rather than a sharp glare. Look for {stone_1} or {stone_2} set cleanly against neutral hardware. Weigh the piece in your palm to evaluate its mass. Appearance tricks the mind, but gravity never does. A dense piece guarantees the item will anchor those mobile layers rather than floating above them. Reject overly ornate bezels or heavily faceted gems. They introduce visual clutter that disrupts a precise fit. Rely instead on smooth, untextured cool hardware with a matt finish. Ensure the setting feels substantial enough to perform its structural job.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware using strict density rules to anchor your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Pick up every ring, clasp, or buckle before you buy it. Assess the heft directly. If it feels hollow or flimsy in your palm, leave it in the shop. Artificially aged metals, hammered copper, and antiqued brass read as visual clutter against your precise fit. Avoid them entirely. Anchor your neutral palette with solid, weighty materials. Keep to clean {metal_1}, brushed platinum, brushed steel, or muted white gold. When you fasten a heavy {stone_1} pendant over a washed silk shell, you should feel its absolute mass settling against your collarbone to serve as your one meticulous detail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate hardware with your hands before you trust your eyes.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments demand a precise fit. You build flexibility using mobile layers. Now you must finish the process with one meticulous detail. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start with silk scarves. Select a neutral crepe de chine square or a slim band, ensuring the fabric is strictly matt. Trust your fingertips to evaluate the material. Images lie. Friction provides your true bearing. Apply the subtraction method before you leave the house. Pause at the door and remove the final accessory you put on. If the visual tension of the outfit collapses, put the piece back on. If the balance remains exactly the same, abandon the item.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the tactical application of your finishing touches.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square or slim band, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Anchor your mobile layers with fine jewellery in cool dominant finishes. Look for thin chains and small drops in brushed silver. The surface must read entirely matt, never catching the light sharply. Avoid any high-shine metals that disrupt your neutral palette. Let your touch confirm the construction. Draw the chain through your fingers to guarantee the links are smooth and substantial. Execute the boundary check at the door. Verify in the glass that these brushed silver pieces sit cleanly against your washed silk garments. They should support a precise fit and act as your one meticulous detail without screaming for attention.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your secondary pieces strictly by their surface finish and structural integrity.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin chain and small drops, brushed silver"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Pick up a small structured bag in kid suede. Evaluate the top-handle for rigid construction and inspect the fine matt hardware. The metal must read as cool brushed steel or platinum to anchor your neutral palette. Carry the bag against your side. If its bulk disrupts the precise fit of your trousers, put it down. Perform the final structural edit before opening the front door. Stand before the mirror and strip away any item that interrupts the fluid drape of your mobile layers. If an accessory catches the eye before the architecture of your clothing does, leave it in the tray.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your final items and rigorously audit the complete silhouette.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede top-handle, fine matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored garments draw their pattern directly from the structural weave of the cloth. Fluid pieces take theirs from dyed motifs. Modulate your visual contrast to suit the day. Choose tonal combinations for quiet environments, and increase graphic separation when the context shifts. Rely on {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} to build depth. Pass over stiffened surface prints, glued appliqués, and {avoid_pattern_1}. Execute the visual sweep. Hold the garment away from your body. It must resolve into a solid, matt field of {core_colour_1} or another neutral shade. Bring it close to your eyes to confirm a rewarding, intricate texture. Any pattern you select must integrate seamlessly into the fabric without disrupting a precise fit or interfering with your mobile layers.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your eye to evaluate pattern as a physical property of the cloth.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the arm's-length protocol to every patterned garment you consider. Hold the piece out by the shoulders. From this vantage point, the fabric must resolve into a calm, solid block of neutral tone. Bring it back toward your chest. The material should only reveal the fine geometry of {recommended_pattern_1} when viewed strictly within personal space. If the motif remains loud from across the shop floor, drop the hanger. This controlled legibility ensures the visual texture supports your mobile layers instead of fighting the structural lines. Trust your physical senses to evaluate this shift. You need a matt surface that keeps its complexity hidden, serving as one meticulous detail until someone stands close enough to read the weave.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the arm's-length check to keep your patterns under strict visual control.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_taurus__moon_virgo__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "structure + honest fabric + a touch of quiet depth",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on structure + honest fabric + a touch of quiet depth.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your hands to find equilibrium. When assessing a garment, test its physical response. Grip the cloth. If it feels entirely rigid, put it back. If it collapses completely, put it back. You need balanced physical resistance. This is your sensory compass. Dress by the formula of structure + honest fabric + a touch of quiet depth. Picture a tailored jacket with an unpadded shoulder layered over a dense knit, anchored by heavy matt trousers. It is a working uniform that bridges formality and ease. Build your wardrobe slowly, but deploy it adaptively each morning.\n\nDemand internal integrity from everything you buy. Apply the seam test before making a purchase. Turn the garment inside out and trace the hidden stitching with your bare thumb. If the thread feels brittle or the binding feels rough and hurried, the piece will fail you. A well-made garment must offer a warm, substantial weight in the hands. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Cheap construction will always betray itself through flimsy internal tension. Leave weak garments on the rack.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this foundational logic to build a wardrobe that functions exactly as it should.",
      "tests": [
        "the seam test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe on structure, honest fabric, and a touch of quiet depth. Trust your hands to find materials that serve a warm, matt palette. Look for {texture_good_1} when buying shirting that requires clean architectural boundaries. Rely on {texture_good_2} for base layers sitting close to the body that maintain sharp lines. Choose {texture_good_3} for trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day. Finish with {texture_good_4} for lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little. Before buying anything, apply the recovery test. Crush the hem in your fist, release it, and watch if it snaps back to a crisp line. Rely on the immediate feedback of gravity. Appearance is easily faked, but absolute density reveals true quality.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to verify the materials that build your wardrobe foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
