      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Execute the crush check on a sleeve of {texture_bad_1}. Watch the release. If the material traps the crease and looks instantly exhausted, it fails. It lacks the firm structure required to anchor your silhouette. Steer clear of {texture_bad_2} if it presents a harsh, artificial sheen instead of a warm, matt finish. Test the fabric against your bare arm. If the surface feels slick, clings without intention, or carries a hollow weight between your fingers, drop it. Materials must hold their own shape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify the materials that undermine your baseline by reading their tactile failures.",
      "tests": [
        "the recovery test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} directly against {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. This friction guarantees an honest fabric sits securely against your frame. Grasp a section of {texture_good_1} tightly in your palm for a slow count of three. Release your grip entirely. If the material stays crushed and limp, abandon the piece. The cloth must snap back into shape instantly. That resilience ensures a warm surface remains matt throughout a day of constant movement. Rely on this tangible feedback over any printed tag.",
      "sectionIntro": "Define your primary surface tension to anchor every outfit.",
      "tests": [
        "the recovery test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette runs exclusively warm and muted. Ground your base in {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} for heavy trousers or worsted coats. Treat {core_colour_3} as a white substitute in crisp poplin shirting, and use {core_colour_4} to bridge light and dark pieces. Restrict deliberate accents to {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Deploy the relief tone as a soft note used sparingly near the face. Leave pale pastels, neon brights, and sterile blue-grey on the rail. Watch for the pale wash-out trap. Piling identical light values together looks flimsy and unfinished. Rescue the outfit by dropping in a dark {core_colour_4} anchor piece or a distinct {accent_colour_1} element. Let one sudden shift in weave supply the structure required to finish the look.",
      "sectionIntro": "Lock down your rules of tone and contrast before you evaluate another garment.",
      "rankedItems": [
