    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, let structure lead your choices. Build the foundation with the sharp shoulder of a blazer or the crisp collar of a cotton poplin shirt. Support this framework with an honest fabric. A demanding schedule requires worsted wool and fine ribbed merino that yield slightly to your joints. Grab the sleeve and pull. If the material fights your grip, abandon the garment. Your clothes must follow your movements without collapsing. Ensure the outfit delivers a touch of quiet depth. Rely on a warm, dual-register watch, mixing muted gold with matt silver to keep the details balanced.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your working wardrobe as a toolkit, built to endure a long shift without restricting your movement.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, honest fabric leads. Dim lighting flattens visual detail. Rely on the physical reality of fine ribbed merino against the skin to ground the look. A long dinner calls for supple layers that move seamlessly with your body, not restrictive shells. Build a base of warm taupe or camel. Mix silver and gold chains at the collar, ensuring both carry a muted, matt finish to catch the ambient glow without glaring. Gauge the garment by how it behaves in motion. Discard anything that binds your shoulders across a small table. Check the tension in the seams. If a piece restricts your reach, leave it behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Adjust your approach for intimate settings, prioritising tactile reality over visual volume.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A relentless routine demands forgiving textiles that adapt to movement, not stiff cages that trap you. Pick up a crisp cotton poplin shirt and gauge its resistance. If the garment dictates how you sit, put it back. Dropping prescriptions at the local chemist offers no excuse to lower your standards. Anchor your mornings in camel worsted wool and warm taupe technical nylon. Ensure every combination delivers structure + honest fabric + a touch of quiet depth. Secure the look with a brushed steel and gold watch. Let the textile do the heavy lifting while you navigate the day.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your baseline requirements for daily movement and mundane errands.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Separate your hardware into two distinct lanes. For jewellery resting against the skin, choose warm {personal_metal_1} or {personal_metal_2}. For the components securing your garments, such as zips and buckles, rely entirely on {structural_metal_1} or {structural_metal_2}. This dual approach provides reliable structure without competing with an honest fabric. Reject pre-aged brass and hammered copper. They act as nostalgic debris that drags down a current, active silhouette. Resolve this by demanding smooth, unblemished metals for every fastening. Always avoid {excluded_finish}. Evaluate a new chain or clasp by assessing its heft in your palm. A bright finish masks cheap casting, so rely entirely on absolute physical mass to confirm its grade.",
      "sectionIntro": "Mastering your hardware ensures your metals anchor your garments rather than distracting from them.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
