    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, precise fit leads. Anchor your wardrobe in tailored brushed wool trousers, ensuring the cut sets clear boundaries for your day. Support this exactness with hidden depth, choosing a silk lining that only you can feel, and finish with one meticulous detail. An early morning commute or a long desk session does not require surrendering your softness. Keep a neutral soft stone cashmere sweater folded in your full-grain leather briefcase for these moments. Let a matt platinum watch serve as that final grounding element. Scrutinise the fabric of a shirt before you buy it. Avoid stiff synthetics. Rub the material between your thumb and index finger to verify the fibres yourself.",
      "sectionIntro": "Here is how to calibrate your uniform for the office.",
      "tests": [
        "a school run or a corner shop dash does not require surrendering your softness (Cove)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, let your hidden depth lead. A dim room obscures colour, meaning the physical sensation of the cloth becomes your primary anchor. Build these intimate outfits from a neutral palette of oatmeal and soft stone. Close your eyes and run your fingers over the seams to gauge a garment's integrity. Keep a heavy cashmere jumper by the door to pull over your silk trousers for evening engagements. Pair it with a matt platinum ring or a thick silver cuff. Assess the tactile response of every piece you select. The surface must feel substantial against your skin and entirely soundless when you move.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is how you calibrate your wardrobe for intimate spaces and low lighting.",
      "tests": [
        "a school run or a corner shop dash does not require surrendering your softness (Cove)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Dress for an ordinary Tuesday with absolute intent. A corner shop dash does not require surrendering your self-contained rigour. Do not downgrade your clothing for the post office queue. Treat every errand as a continuation of your baseline by maintaining the standard of precise fit + hidden depth + one meticulous detail. Construct this routine from an oatmeal cashmere jumper and soft stone brushed wool trousers. Select unlined full-grain leather loafers over synthetic trainers. Fasten a solitary matt palladium watch to your wrist. Keep the overall temperature perfectly neutral. Never assume an early morning run justifies inferior construction.",
      "sectionIntro": "Execute your mundane routines with the same strict adherence you apply to significant appointments.",
      "tests": [
        "a school run or a corner shop dash does not require surrendering your softness (Cove)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Anchor your selections in cool-dominant metals. Build your hardware profile around {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Keep the temperature strictly neutral to integrate with your core garments. Weigh a heavy clasp or a solid watch bezel in your palm before committing. Dense hardware confirms a solid casting. Highly polished chrome pulls focus and clashes awkwardly against muted fabrics. {excluded_finish} finishes disrupt visual cohesion. Instead, seek out brushed, oxidised, or strictly matt surfaces. This tactile restraint provides hidden depth without shouting. A solid {metal_1} zip on full-grain leather or a brushed {metal_2} buckle secures the structural integrity of the piece.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hardware dictates the structural integrity of a garment. Treat every zip, clasp, and buckle as a deliberate physical choice.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Avoid brilliant metallic finishes entirely. A high-shine reflective surface glares sharply against cashmere and disrupts your neutral, muted aesthetic. Restrict your hardware strictly to matt or softly brushed textures to unify the garments. Select dense, opaque materials like {stone_1} and {stone_2}. Press the mineral against your wrist to verify its temperature. A glossy surface fakes quality, but the sudden chill of a real stone proves its authenticity. Your stones must sit quietly in their settings. A precise fit structures your tailoring, while dense, light-absorbing minerals provide hidden depth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones by their physical density and light-absorbing restraint.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate every piece of {metal_1} or {stone_1} by its sheer density before you ever look at it. Calibrate your senses to physical gravity as your primary filter. A substantial clasp or a heavy watch case anchors an outfit. Avoid heavily polished objects. Gleaming surfaces introduce a sharp glare that distracts from your neutral, muted wardrobe. Stick strictly to matt or brushed textures to maintain a cohesive appearance. This tames the exterior and guarantees the hardware provides hidden depth instead of a shallow reflection. When the finish is right, the metal becomes an organic extension of your clothing's precise fit.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every piece of hardware to a strict physical evaluation before purchasing.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You established a precise fit. You engineered the fabrics for hidden depth. Now resolve the silhouette with one meticulous detail. Anchor your outfit using the principle of one or two strong pieces per look. Dress completely, then evaluate the focal points. Take off the extra cuff or the secondary belt that disrupts your neutral baseline. A single grounded anchor does the heavy lifting. Begin with handbags. Seek out thick suede or dense full-grain leather. Inspect the buckles and closures. Accept only matt brushed hardware. Rely on raw tactile feedback to evaluate the density of the materials. Heavy hides and friction never deceive you. Squeeze the handles to test their construction. If the metal reflects the room or the leather feels hollow, put it down.",
      "sectionIntro": "Approach your accessories as structural components rather than decoration, letting tactile feedback dictate your final selections.",
      "rankedItems": [
