    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Verify the graphic clarity of {recommended_pattern_1} from a distance. Drape the shirt over a chair and walk away. When you look back, the motif must maintain crisp borders. If the edges bleed together into an ambiguous wash, leave the item on the rack. You require clothing that supports a self-contained focus. A pattern that takes too long to decipher distracts the eye and undermines the garment structure. Insist on immediate legibility. A clear read from a distance guarantees the precise fit of your clothing remains the primary anchor point.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the distance blink test to verify the legibility of any printed textile.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_virgo__moon_gemini__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "precise fit + light movement + one meticulous detail",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on precise fit + light movement + one meticulous detail.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Build a highly adaptable system. You are looking for equilibrium. Your instinct compass is physical calibration. Trust your hands to find fabrics that shift with your environment rather than fighting it. Seek out a neutral temperature and a distinctly matt finish in your core garments. If a piece demands rigid posture, drop it. You need components that pivot quickly when your routine shifts. Build this foundation deliberately over time, but deploy it fast when getting dressed. Choose items that layer and recombine without friction.\n\nYour exact equation is precise fit + light movement + one meticulous detail. Picture a sharply tailored trouser anchored by a fluid shirt that shifts when you walk, finished with a single crisp cuff. Test every new purchase with the half-mirror test. Stand in front of a looking glass that only captures your waist upwards. If that isolated reflection reads as a complete, deliberate composition, the piece works. If the garment relies on the rest of the outfit to make sense, leave it in the shop. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation and the primary filter for every garment you pick up.",
      "tests": [
        "the half-mirror test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe from textiles that guarantee a precise fit and light movement. Trust your grip to evaluate the cloth. Pick up a garment and apply the wrist-flick test. Snap the hem upward and watch how the fabric settles. If it drops straight back down with zero resistance, the material works. Rely on {texture_good_1} for shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation. Choose {texture_good_2} for close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy mobility. Seek {texture_good_3} for trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day. Use {texture_good_4} for lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little. Keep the surface finish matt and neutral in temperature. Anchor the construction with one meticulous detail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every textile with your hands before you put the garment on your body.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the wrist-flick test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Reject {texture_bad_1} the moment it touches your skin. Rub the weave between your thumb and index finger. If it feels slick or traps heat, it will fail you. Test the sleeve by pulling it sharply across your forearm. If the fabric hangs lifelessly instead of settling back into a precise fit, put the item back on the rail. Avoid {texture_bad_2} entirely. Crush the material in your fist. If it collapses into rigid creases rather than springing back to a smooth surface, it ruins your underlying structure. Your clothes must support your frame rather than fight it. Rely on this tactile feedback as your primary guide. A stiff, suffocating cloth always betrays your lines.",
      "sectionIntro": "Identify and eliminate the materials that actively undermine your architecture.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist-flick test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Anchor your wardrobe exactly between {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. To locate this tension, run the cuff-drop test. Pull your sleeve downward as if you are checking a heavy silver watch. Watch how the cloth behaves. It must settle instantly into a precise fit. Avoid anything that flutters limply or clings to the skin. You want {texture_good_1} that drops clean and straight. The fibres need enough inherent memory to support light movement without losing their structural integrity. Gravity reveals the true quality of a garment. A proper textile grounds your silhouette the second you let go.",
      "sectionIntro": "Find your structural anchor by testing how textiles respond to gravity and force.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist-flick test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your overall temperature is neutral. Construct your foundation with {core_colour_1} for structural garments. Rely on {core_colour_2} and {core_colour_3} for your base layers. Let {core_colour_4} bridge these tones. Introduce {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as your single deliberate accent. Apply the relief tone purely as a soft note used sparingly. Keep your finishes muted and matt. Pass over neon brights, glitter finishes, and sugary pastels entirely. Watch out for prettiness without a grounding weight. All-pale or all-soft garments lose their structural authority by noon. Fix this immediately. Add a sharply tailored worsted wool blazer, a structured flat, or a gentle {core_colour_1} piece worn exactly where the eye lands first. Demand a precise fit, light movement, and one meticulous detail to make these shades work.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your palette as a strict, functional toolkit.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Graphite",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft stone",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Oatmeal",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Greige",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Chalk white",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Dry sage",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Bottle green",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Dark chocolate",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Pale butter",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "prettiness without anchor: all-pale, all-soft reads charming then forgettable by lunch",
          "fix": "give it one anchor: a sharply tailored blazer, a structured flat, or the gentle navy piece worn where the eye lands first"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, precise fit leads your selection. Lock your worsted wool trousers to the exact drop of your waist. Let light movement act as the supporting framework. A soft stone fine ribbed merino knit prevents the silhouette from becoming rigid. Rely on the immediate sensation of the cloth against your skin to judge the standard. Reflection deceives, but the physical drape of the fabric tells the truth. Cap the look with a brushed silver watch. Keep the palette entirely neutral to maintain a muted finish. Remember that a morning trip to buy fresh produce remains a small occasion demanding this exact discipline. You do not abandon your standards when you step away from the desk. Button your crisp cotton poplin shirt and feel the structure before heading outside.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish your baseline at the desk by allowing architecture to dictate every garment.",
      "tests": [
        "a farmers' market run is still a small occasion (Hearth)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In low lighting, a precise fit takes the absolute lead. Pick up a fine ribbed merino sweater in oatmeal. Check the weight. If it feels flimsy in your grip, drop it. It must sit close to the ribs without clinging. Keep your palette strictly neutral. Choose matt sterling silver rings over high-shine platinum. Picking up Sunday morning pastries in a soft stone knit remains a deliberate event. Treat it as one. Apply the same rigorous standard to technical nylon trousers. They must deliver light movement without generating static. Grasp the cloth. If a piece refuses to settle smoothly in your hand, reject it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the art of dressing for close proximity and low lighting.",
      "tests": [
        "a farmers' market run is still a small occasion (Hearth)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat Tuesday morning with the same rigour you apply to a formal event. A walk to the pharmacy or the greengrocer is still an occasion demanding deliberate structure. Do not suspend your standards for mundane errands. Select garments in a neutral temperature and anchor them with matt steel hardware. Trust your physical grip to evaluate quality. The heaviness of worsted wool determines how a trouser falls. Ensure every outfit answers strictly to precise fit + light movement + one meticulous detail. Choose crisp cotton poplin shirting over formless knitwear. Let the built-in tension of technical nylon manage the strain of your daily transit.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the same exacting standards to your daily routine as you do to major events.",
      "tests": [
        "a farmers' market run is still a small occasion (Hearth)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Avoid artificially weathered metals. Hammered copper and oxidised brass read as visual clutter. Keep your hardware clean and current with {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Ensure the surface remains matt, rejecting any {excluded_finish} finish that disrupts the neutral palette of your garments. Hardware must anchor a precise fit while allowing light movement. Lift every buckle, chain, and clasp before buying. Let your hand assess the density. A hollow buckle fails immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your hardware strictly by its density, finish, and structural purpose.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Evaluate your minerals by their density and refraction. Seek out {stone_1} and {stone_2} that maintain a strictly neutral cast and a clouded, matt finish. Before you commit to a piece, weigh the setting in your palm. A heavy, solid bezel ensures a precise fit against the skin. Avoid distressed copper, oxidised brass, and faux-vintage patinas. These finishes read as clutter. Keep your hardware strictly to brushed silver, satin platinum, matt white gold, and brushed steel. Combine these strictly neutral, muted metals with {stone_3} to create light movement at the wrist or collar. The contrast between matt metal and dense stone delivers necessary discipline.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your minerals by measuring their density and clarity against your physical baseline.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the {metal_1} piece from the counter and gauge its heft. Sheer mass remains an absolute measure of quality. Intricate carvings and hammered textures act as visual friction against a precise fit. Maintain a strictly neutral temperature across your metals. Restrict your selections to unblemished {metal_1} and smooth, neutral-toned alloys. A heavy cuff or a dense {stone_1} signet ring provides the exact gravity you require.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this strict physical assessment to every piece of hardware before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Once you secure a precise fit and establish light movement, your look requires exactly one meticulous detail. Limit yourself to one or two focused pieces per outfit. Start with silk scarves. Select a matt crepe de chine square or a slim band to introduce a muted finish. Keep the accessory temperature entirely neutral. Depend on the pure tactile feedback of the fabric against your neck. Run a strict excess test before you leave. Fasten the silk band and step back. If the knot fights the clean architecture of your collar, remove it immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the final layer by selecting additions that serve a distinct textural purpose.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square or slim band, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the too-much test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Select fine jewellery in brushed silver. Look for a thin chain resting flat against an oatmeal collar or small drops that provide light movement beside the face. A matt finish prevents the metal from catching harsh glare. Demand a precise fit from your rings and clasps so they sit flush against the skin without twisting. Run the physical balance test by evaluating the weight. Put the piece on and pause. If the metal feels heavy or interrupts the visual line of your clothing, remove it immediately. Avoid thick cuffs and oversized pendants. The silver must act as a quiet anchor, blending with a neutral palette rather than dominating it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your metals using physical weight and balance.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin chain and small drops, brushed silver"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the too-much test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Pick up a small structured bag to anchor the silhouette. Choose a kid suede top-handle to introduce light movement against worsted wool. Inspect the metalwork. All closures must feature fine matt hardware in brushed steel, keeping the overall temperature neutral. Before committing, run a final subtraction test. Strip away any object that pulls focus or breaks a precise fit. Every remaining element must earn its place as your one meticulous detail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Edit your final additions to secure the geometry of the silhouette.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede top-handle, fine matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the too-much test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor your {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} in structured garments where a precise fit defines the geometry. Assign {recommended_pattern_3} to draped pieces that yield light movement. Adapt your contrast level to the environment. Shift between a low-contrast weave and a defined graphic as the situation dictates. Build this around a neutral palette and a muted, matt finish. Submit every garment to the blur test. A split-second look must leave a cohesive overall impression, never a singular loud shape that hijacks the eye. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1}, {avoid_pattern_2}, and any print that reads as a novelty rather than a meticulous detail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the geometry of your garments by controlling the scale and placement of every print.",
      "tests": [
        "the glance test (a pleasant impression rather than a specific shouting motif)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the ten-foot test to any {recommended_pattern_1} garment. Step back from the mirror and soften your focus. The print must dissolve into a cohesive texture, leaving a pleasant impression rather than an isolated block of colour. Close your eyes and stretch the cloth. Trust this physical response. The tension of the weave indicates true durability. The fabric must hold a precise fit, anchoring the look entirely. Avoid high-contrast shapes that demand constant attention. A neutral ground ensures the design integrates quietly. Inspect the details for neutral, matt buttons instead of reflective metals. If the print leaps out to announce itself before you register the seamwork, put the item back.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject your patterns to a strict distance test before you buy them.",
      "tests": [
        "the glance test (a pleasant impression rather than a specific shouting motif)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_virgo__moon_gemini__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "precise fit + light movement + one meticulous detail",
    "closing": "Trust the physical tension of the cloth to anchor your daily decisions, ensuring a foundation built strictly on precise fit + light movement + one meticulous detail.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Feel for structural balance in every piece you pick up. Trust your hands to find fabrics that hold their shape while accommodating yours. Looks lie. Weight does not. Your exact formula is precise fit + light movement + one meticulous detail. Picture a tailored trouser sitting exactly at the natural waist, paired with a fine gauge knit that shifts freely around the ribs, finished with a single piece of matt hardware. Ensure the temperature always reads neutral. The surface finish must absorb light rather than reflect it.\n\nAdapt your tempo to your environment. Build your foundation methodically over years. Deploy your garments swiftly each morning. Run the combination test before acquiring any new item. Ask yourself if the piece integrates smoothly with three distinct silhouettes already hanging in your closet. If it demands a complete structural overhaul to work, put it back. You require adaptable garments that pivot across different situations. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass.",
