    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments establish a precise fit and provide light movement. Accessories supply the final stage, delivering one meticulous detail. Restrict yourself to one or two focused elements per look. Begin with silk scarves. Choose a crepe de chine square or a slim band. The surface must remain entirely matt. Keep the overarching temperature neutral. Before you acquire a new item, apply the integration rule. Weigh the fabric in your palms. If the piece requires you to buy new clothing to accommodate it, drop it. It must slot into your current lineup instantly. Trust your fingers over a shop mirror. Glass flatters. The physical drag of heavy crepe offers a true guarantee.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate and select your finishing elements with absolute physical scrutiny.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square or slim band, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Select fine jewellery that acts as one meticulous detail against the collarbone. Pick up a thin chain featuring small drops and inspect the surface. Avoid high shine. Look for brushed silver. This matt finish keeps your temperature completely neutral. Let your fingers test the links. The piece must provide light movement over your skin rather than sitting stiffly. Subject the item to a versatility check before purchasing. Ask yourself if this exact necklace transitions smoothly from a heavy silk crepe blouse to a boiled wool jumper. If it demands a specific garment shape to function, leave it behind. You need a precise fit that works constantly without requiring adjustments.",
      "sectionIntro": "Audit your secondary accessories with the exact same physical rigour you apply to your garments.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin chain and small drops, brushed silver"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your carrying needs with a small structured bag in a neutral shade. Look for a kid suede top-handle design finished with fine matt hardware in brushed platinum or muted silver. The clean geometry of the shape ensures a precise fit against the body. Trust your hands when examining the suede. It must feel dense rather than flimsy. Evaluate the piece with the combination check. Hang the bag beside three different coats from your closet. If you have to change your shoes or rethink your layers to make the new piece work across all three, leave it in the shop. Silhouettes trick the eye. Sturdy construction provides certainty. Ensure the handle acts as one meticulous detail that perfectly complements your light movement.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your daily carrying piece and subject every new accessory to a strict integration check.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede top-handle, fine matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored coats demand {recommended_pattern_1} to ground their structure. Fluid trousers take {recommended_pattern_2} to maintain light movement. Because your strategy requires versatile pieces, adjust your pattern contrast to match the daily environment. Soften a sharp motif with a neutral ground, or ground a stark shape with a muted finish. Pass over chaotic scales, novelty prints, and {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. Apply the blink evaluation before purchasing. Step ten feet back from the mirror and open your eyes. If the design looks muddy or confusing in that first split second, drop the garment. Seek a precise fit where the print serves as one meticulous detail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Pattern introduces necessary rhythm to your wardrobe without breaking the strict physical parameters you established.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Subject every {recommended_pattern_1} to a sudden distance appraisal. Hang the piece three metres away. Turn your back, pivot sharply, and look. If the design bleeds into a murky blur during that initial fraction of a second, drop it. The geometry must hold its shape without hesitation. Because your palette requires a neutral foundation, you cannot rely on heavy saturation to force clarity. Crisp boundaries must do the work. Secure a precise fit across the shoulders. Allow the sharp edges of the print to act as one meticulous detail. Incorporate light movement through the drape of the fabric rather than the scatter of the ink. Trust your optic reflex entirely. If you have to stare to decode the motif, the garment belongs back on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this distance test to ensure your prints remain clear and intentional.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_virgo__moon_libra__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "precise fit + cool composure + one meticulous detail",
    "closing": "Let your hands navigate the rail until you recognise the exact balance of a precise fit + cool composure + one meticulous detail.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Build systematically and deploy fast. Your sensory compass relies on alignment and physical ease. Trust the weight and drape of the fabric against your skin. A garment must settle immediately into place without tugging or shifting. Apply the flight test to everything you buy. Put the piece on, bend your arms, and take a long stride. If you cannot sprint across a terminal or sit for three hours without adjusting a collar or pulling at a seam, leave the garment on the rack. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not. Your foundation requires a neutral temperature balance, allowing you to adapt to changing contexts without losing your baseline structure.\n\nYour defining framework is precise fit + cool composure + one meticulous detail. Ground this logic in a concrete uniform. Visualise a strictly tailored wool trouser, a fluid silk shell, and a structured blazer cut with exact geometry. Keep the entire base matt and subdued. You then pierce that quiet foundation with exactly one sharp piece of cool-dominant hardware at the cuff or the lapel. Avoid items that compete for attention. Every piece must earn its place through immaculate construction. Look for balanced proportions. Pick up a garment and inspect the seams. If the stitching drifts, drop it.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation, the set of operating principles that governs how you test, select, and combine garments.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your fabrics must deliver cool composure through their physical weight. Build your foundation on {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Layer {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without bulk. Look for {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Finish with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. These materials succeed because they hold a neutral, matt and muted finish. To verify their drape, perform the gravity test. Lift the fabric and drop it from waist height. If it lands with a heavy thud or refuses to yield, leave it on the rail. It must catch the air and settle slowly into a precise fit. Rely on this tactile feedback above all else.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to filter your textiles before you ever look at a label.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed alpaca",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "enveloping winter coats and oversized cardigans"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fluid modal jersey",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers that follow the body without ever gripping it"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed cotton flannel",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "shirts and loungewear that feel like a remembered embrace"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Toss {texture_bad_1} into the air. Watch the descent. If it parachutes outwards and drifts aimlessly before hitting the bed, leave it in the shop. Good materials drop straight downwards. Avoid {texture_bad_2} if it catches on your cuticles or carries a high, reflective shine. Look for a matt, muted finish instead. Run your palm across {texture_bad_3}. If the surface feels slick like wet plastic, reject it entirely. A wardrobe built on one meticulous detail cannot tolerate materials that cling, drag, or spark static against the skin.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject what fails against the skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your ideal tension lives between {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Pick up a piece of {texture_good_1}. Squeeze it tightly in your fist. Apply the long-haul journey test. Ask yourself if it will hold a precise fit after sleeping in a cramped window seat. If the surface crushes or sags, leave it on the hanger. Merge these approved layers to establish a neutral base. Look for a dense, matt weight. Let your grip decide. Fibres conceal their flaws, but density reveals them.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your pairings by how they behave under pressure.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette temperature is strictly neutral. Construct your foundation using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Bridge the gaps with {core_colour_3} and {core_colour_4}. Demand a precise fit in every base garment. Restrict all hardware to cool metals with a matt finish. Inject {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as your single deliberate accent. Introduce the relief tone purely as a soft note used sparingly. Leave neon brights, hard jet black, and glitter finishes on the rack. Recognise the armour trap. When your day accelerates, you will instinctively grab stiff nylon, heavy technical coats, and inflexible utility gear to shield yourself. Stop your hands. Replace these rigid items with a thick brushed cotton overshirt. It responds to your pace while maintaining solid form.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat these colours as architectural materials rather than paint, applying them with strict discipline.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Pewter grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Misty greige",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Oyster",
          "role": "white_substitute"
