        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the hard shell: reaching for armour, technical jackets, and stiff utility layers when life speeds up",
          "fix": "swap the shell for a brushed cotton layer that moves just as fast and holds you besides"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let a precise fit lead your workwear. It establishes the clear baseline shape of your tailoring. Keep the rest of your approach relaxed to support that clean structure. Soften rigid collars into washed silk, and trade stiff blazers for boiled wool. Introduce a single calculated element, like a brushed steel lapel pin, to close the look. Read the cloth with your fingertips when evaluating any garment. If the material feels restrictive, put it down. Even a damp morning dash for the train demands the exact same forgiving drape as a major meeting. Anchor every choice in a neutral palette built around pewter grey.",
      "sectionIntro": "Dress for the working day with strict intention.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim settings, cool composure leads. Keep the palette strictly neutral. Assess washed silk by touch alone in low light. Close your eyes and crush the material in your fist to ensure it springs back without a sharp crease. Choose pewter grey heavy silk crepe for evening, allowing the matt surface to absorb shadows rather than reflect them. Apply the Ripple test to all intimate clothing. A thickly spun lambswool jumper grabbed for a wet weekend errand must envelop you with the identical soft security as your best dinner wear. Anchor the look with a single silver cuff. Reject anything stiff. If a piece requires constant adjustment, leave it on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Dress for low light and close proximity by letting physical ease dictate every single choice.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat a rainy Sunday morning paper run with the exact discipline you apply to formal obligations. Do not drop your standards for a mundane trip to the late-night pharmacy. Reach for a pewter grey heavy wool coat instead of an unconsidered anorak. Demand matt fabrics and silver-toned hardware regardless of the destination. Your baseline always requires precise fit + cool composure + one meticulous detail. Layer fluid silk beneath heavy lambswool for ordinary errands. Keep your selections neutral even when you are just stepping out to buy milk.",
      "sectionIntro": "Mastering daily dressing requires refusing to lower your standards for mundane tasks.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Base your hardware choices on a cool foundation. Select {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} to anchor your neutral wardrobe. A precise fit requires accessories that integrate without friction. Pick the jewellery up before securing the clasp. A shiny plating masks cheap materials, but gravity exposes them. Keep only the heavy pieces. Hammered copper, artificially aged components, and distressed brass register as clutter against a present-day look. Limit your selections strictly to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome. Avoid {excluded_finish} items entirely. Your metals must act as sharp architecture rather than antique decoration.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your metals with the same physical scrutiny you apply to your tailoring.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Drop the piece into your bare palm before putting it on. Visual scale tricks the eye. Pure density anchors the piece. Look for the dense clarity of {stone_1} or the solid structure of {stone_2}. Their impact relies on actual physical weight. Keep the colour temperature of these stones completely neutral. Reject tarnished settings or beaten metals. Such simulated wear degrades the stone. Confine your metal choices to polished silver, gleaming platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome. A heavy stone set in an immaculate band guarantees a precise fit and sharp execution.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones strictly by their structural density and reflective clarity.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift every piece of jewellery or belt buckle before you wear it. A photograph lies about quality. The drop against your palm confirms it. Pass over anything etched, oxidised, or intentionally scratched. These distressed textures register as pure visual clutter against your wardrobe. Ground your style instead in highly polished, starkly reflective surfaces like {metal_1} or the cold clarity of a {stone_1}. Demand the same precise fit from your watch and rings as you do from your tailoring. Rigidly maintaining this standard ensures your hardware supports your cool composure rather than fighting against it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess the physical heft of every piece of hardware before you commit to it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Base your foundation on a precise fit and maintain a steady cool composure, leaving your accessories to supply exactly one meticulous detail. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Always apply the take-off test before you step out the door. Strip away the last item you added. If your remaining outfit suddenly looks hollow, your core layers are failing to hold their own. If that removed piece was carrying the entire visual load, it is too loud for a muted finish. Begin your collection with silk scarves. Choose a crepe de chine square or a slim band. Verify that the fabric has a completely matt surface. This flat finish absorbs light, pairing seamlessly with heavy silk crepe or structured wool to keep the overall temperature strictly neutral.",
      "sectionIntro": "This section outlines how to select and test the finishing touches that ground your wardrobe.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square or slim band, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Anchor your fine jewellery in brushed silver. Select thin chains and small drops to maintain a muted, matt finish. This approach preserves a strictly neutral temperature against your skin. Subject every new acquisition to the metal tension check. Fasten the clasp and wait for a bodily response. If the metal disrupts your balance or feels wrong against a fluid silk collar, your fingers will instinctively rise to remove it. Heed that urge and drop the rejected item back into its box. A successful piece demands a precise fit at the collarbone or earlobe. Keep only the pieces that guarantee your cool composure from the moment they are secured.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate fine jewellery through strict physical parameters.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin chain and small drops, brushed silver"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select a small structured bag in kid suede. Pick up a top-handle design and scrutinise the fastenings. Require fine matt hardware in brushed steel or brushed palladium. These subdued metals maintain your neutral temperature. Rely on your tactile senses to assess the construction. Surface friction never deceives. When you grasp the suede, it should feel dense and pliant. Ensure the overall scale supports a precise fit alongside your tailored garments. Before opening the door, apply the subtraction rule. Assess your outfit and strip away the single piece that feels forced. If a competing clasp disrupts your cool composure alongside a pewter grey coat, take the accessory off.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your silhouette by securing the right bag and editing your finished look.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede top-handle, fine matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor your wardrobe in patterns that support a precise fit. Tailored pieces take their geometry directly from the loom, demanding woven-in structures like {recommended_pattern_1} in neutral tones. Fluid fabrics rely on surface continuity. They require designs that drape without distortion, such as {recommended_pattern_2} or {recommended_pattern_3}. Your contrast levels must remain adaptive, scaling up for visual interest but remaining strictly muted in execution. Apply the passing test before purchasing. Agitate the fabric with your hands. It must read as soft, pleasant texture in motion. Reject the piece if the motif separates aggressively from the background. This visual restraint guarantees cool composure across varying environments. Bypass {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. Leave {avoid_pattern_2} on the rack when its scale threatens to overwhelm the garment silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Pattern introduces scale and rhythm to your garments, dictating how a silhouette reads from a distance.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Run the Ten-Stride Test. Hang a {recommended_pattern_1} washed silk shirt on a door frame. Walk ten paces away, turn sharply, and evaluate the fabric. The motif must instantly blur into a quiet, continuous shadow when observed in motion. It should merge perfectly with your neutral garments rather than flashing as a rigid block of ink. If the shapes remain stark and legible from across the room, abandon the item. A successful print always surrenders to a precise fit, adding depth while preserving cool composure. Trust your immediate visual reflex. If the contrast jars your vision even slightly, reject the garment without hesitation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the art of reading pattern from a distance to guarantee it serves your underlying structure.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_virgo__moon_scorpio__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "precise fit + quiet undercurrent + one meticulous detail",
    "closing": "Let your tactile compass guide every acquisition, filtering out visual noise until you are left with nothing but precise fit + quiet undercurrent + one meticulous detail.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Look for physical equilibrium. Your sensory compass is friction. If a collar pulls or a seam dictates your posture, leave it on the hanger. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Your foundation demands a neutral temperature base that shifts seamlessly across different environments. Frame your wardrobe around a strict equation of precise fit + quiet undercurrent + one meticulous detail. Picture a sharply tailored overcoat layered over a fine-gauge knit, anchored by a single matt hardware buckle at the waist. The garments provide structure without demanding constant management.\n\nBuild your archive slowly, but adapt your daily layers fast. When evaluating any new acquisition, apply the flight test. Put the garment on and ask if you could pack it blindly for an unexpected departure or cross a city on foot without adjusting a hem. If the fabric restricts your stride or requires special handling, it fails. Your aesthetic relies on absolute physical autonomy. Trust your hands. If a piece requires careful posturing to look correct, return it. Everything you own must work with you, not against you.",
      "sectionIntro": "Define the absolute physical parameters and foundational logic that govern your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Run every new material through the compression check. Roll the fabric tightly in your fists or stuff it into the corner of a canvas holdall. If it shakes out ready to wear, it serves your baseline. Your wardrobe demands a precise fit and a quiet undercurrent without requiring constant maintenance. Source {texture_good_1} for shirting that holds clean architectural boundaries. Rely on {texture_good_2} for base layers that give you sharp lines and easy movement. Look for {texture_good_3} when cutting trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing. Finish with {texture_good_4} for mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs nothing. Add one meticulous detail in a matt finish to complete the structure. Hunt for these exact specifications.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your materials strictly by their performance and structural integrity.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Rely on tactile feedback to find a precise fit. Pick up {texture_bad_1}. Rub it between your fingers. If it feels brittle or stiff, drop it. Your clothes must move easily. Try on {texture_bad_2} and sit in a low chair. Reach your arms up as though lifting heavy luggage into an overhead bin. If the seams dig into your shoulders or the torso bunches awkwardly, take it off immediately. You need garments that adapt to long journeys, not ones that require endless adjustment. Avoid {texture_bad_3} altogether. It clings uncomfortably to the skin and carries a harsh glare that overpowers your neutral palette. A quiet undercurrent demands softness, allowing the cut and one meticulous detail to ground the look.",
      "sectionIntro": "Eliminate any material that fights your body or ignores your physical instincts.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to establish your foundation. Grab a length of {texture_good_1} and test its resilience. Squeeze the cloth firmly. If it creases sharply and refuses to recover, discard it. Run your personal transit check before making a decision. Put the article on and reach across your chest. It must follow your motion instantly. A precise fit requires materials that act as an extension of your own mechanics. Seek out surfaces that absorb light rather than reflecting it, establishing a quiet undercurrent. The finish must remain matt. Let your chosen hardware sit against these subdued weaves to provide one meticulous detail. Give your fingers the final vote on every piece you keep.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your materials rigorously to ensure they support your physical mechanics.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your tones sit at a true neutral, avoiding extremes of heat or ice. Build your base with {core_colour_1} as a structural anchor, flanked by the cool reliability of {core_colour_2} and the warmth of {core_colour_3}. Use {core_colour_4} to bridge these temperatures. Deploy {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} to create a quiet undercurrent of intention. Call upon your relief tone sparingly, applying it only to break up heavy visual blocks. Always bypass neon brights, glitter finishes, and sugary pastels. Watch out for the hard shell trap. When the week accelerates, you might instinctively reach for stiff utility pieces and technical outerwear to act as armour. Catch this impulse. Swap the rigid shell for a brushed cotton piece that moves just as fast and holds you securely, ensuring a precise fit. Use an unpolished steel button as one meticulous detail to finish the garment.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your palette as a disciplined toolkit, selecting tones that serve your structure rather than broadcasting a mood.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Graphite",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft stone",
          "role": "cool_base"
