    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "In the office, your guiding formula anchors you. An unrelenting schedule requires precise fit + sensory comfort + one meticulous detail to function properly. Prioritise pliable worsted wool and crisp cotton poplin over rigid shells. Let tactile ease support the silhouette. A fine ribbed cashmere layer provides elasticity when lifting a file. Complete the outfit with a singular, obsessive element. A matt silver watch bezel against an oatmeal cuff grounds the look. Feel the weight of the cloth. If the item restricts your stride, leave it on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your working garments by demanding both exactness and agility.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In low-light settings, cut becomes your primary tool. Dim lighting obscures fine patterns, demanding precise fit + sensory comfort + one meticulous detail to carry the look. Look for garments that sit cleanly against the skin without restriction. A long evening out does not call for stiff armour. It asks for adaptable fabrics that stretch and recover naturally. Choose heavy silk crepe in a neutral tone. The material must respond instantly as you gesture. Finish the look with a brushed platinum ring or a matt white gold cuff. These cool metals catch ambient candlelight softly. Assess how the outfit behaves when seated, ensuring the silhouette remains sharp.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the close-quarters environment by leaning on cut and material rather than visual noise.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Your garments must handle a twelve-hour shift, spanning the morning commute to running practical errands. A varied day demands highly mobile textiles. Reach for soft worsted wool trousers that allow a full stride. Layer a neutral technical nylon jacket over the top. Never suspend your standard for a mundane task. The daily equation remains constant through precise fit + sensory comfort + one meticulous detail. Fasten a brushed chrome clasp or a matt steel pin. These metallic elements anchor the structure. Rely on physical instinct when evaluating a piece. If the shoulder seam binds when you reach upward, leave the item on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat an ordinary Tuesday morning as a practical challenge.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Anchor your hardware on a cool dominance that suits a neutral temperature. Build your collection around {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Keep finishes consistently matt and step entirely away from {excluded_finish}. Apply the drop test to every clasp and ring. Bounce the item lightly in your palm to gauge its density. A heavy {metal_1} watch provides physical grounding, satisfying your baseline requirement for sensory comfort. Reject deliberately weathered components. Beaten copper, artificially darkened brass, and distressed alloys act as visual static against a balanced aesthetic. Eradicate this clutter by strictly wearing unblemished silver, solid platinum, matt chrome, and pure white gold. The right metal functions as a structural anchor.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your metals through physical mass, cool tones, and unblemished finishes.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Anchor your pieces with {stone_1} and {stone_2}. Select these minerals for their structural density and precise cut. Lift the item from the display to check its physical gravity. Every piece must offer absolute sensory comfort. Ensure the settings sit flat against your skin without snagging on worsted wool. A neutral temperature dictates the supporting cool metals. Reject weathered brass, beaten copper, and artificially darkened materials. These aged finishes register as visual clutter. Rely instead on brushed sterling, unblemished platinum, and matt chrome.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones and metals using physical mass and structural clarity as your strictest filters.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Weigh the {metal_1} piece in your hand. Substantial density offers genuine sensory comfort against the collarbone. Hollow alloys fail this physical check. Leave lightweight pieces behind. Faux-aged brass and hammered copper create unnecessary visual noise. Avoid them. Keep to smooth, unworked cool metals. Unembellished platinum, pure white gold, and matt {metal_1} bring exactness to a neutral palette, supplying the one meticulous detail your outfit requires.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test the physical density of every metal component before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You build an outfit on precise fit and anchor it in absolute sensory comfort. Accessories supply the one meticulous detail required to finish the work. Restrict yourself to a single structural piece per look. Trust your hands to evaluate an item's mechanical reality. If it slides out of place or demands constant readjustment, it fails the function test. Leave it behind. Start your collection with silk scarves in a neutral temperature and a strictly matt finish. Pick up a heavy crepe de chine square or a slim band that ties without adding bulk.",
      "sectionIntro": "Curate your finishing elements with strict physical criteria.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square or slim band, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Approach fine jewellery with a ruthless eye for practicality. You require a precise fit in every piece. Choose a thin chain and small drops cast in brushed silver. Put the metal through a strict mobility check. Fasten the clasp, turn your head sharply, and reach across your desk. If the chain snags your collar or the drops swing heavily enough to pull at your earlobe, abandon the item immediately. Your adornments must deliver genuine sensory comfort without sacrificing their matt, cool aesthetic. Keep the overall palette entirely neutral. Pick the piece up and gauge its flexibility. It must rest silently against your skin.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select accessories that integrate flawlessly with your physical movements.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin chain and small drops, brushed silver"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select a small structured bag in kid suede. Check the hardware. It must feature a fine matt finish in your dominant cool metals. Verify the dye. Ensure the suede holds a strictly neutral temperature to ground the piece. Feel the top-handle. It must deliver sensory comfort in your bare grip. Ensure the overall construction maintains a precise fit under your arm or beside your hip. Trust physical mechanics over visual appeal. Before you step out, apply the closure check. Open the main clasp with one hand, retrieve an item, and shut it completely. If the mechanism requires a flat surface and both hands to operate, leave the bag behind. Your pieces must function instantly, supplying one meticulous detail to the final look.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject your final additions to rigorous mechanical standards, guaranteeing they serve your structure rather than restrict it.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede top-handle, fine matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored garments pull their pattern from the loom. A structured blazer expresses {recommended_pattern_1} through the weave itself, demanding a precise fit to frame the visual noise. Fluid pieces take their pattern from the dye vat. Seek out {recommended_pattern_2} printed on flexible silk. Trust physical feedback. Your fingers understand density better than your eyes, so evaluate the thread before the motif. Because your contrast is adaptive, scale graphic intensity to the garment's function. Keep underlying tones neutral and broad structural layers muted and matt. Subject everything to the distance check. By the time someone stands an arm and a half away, the print must visually dissolve into a flat, clean texture. Pass over {avoid_pattern_2}. Reject {avoid_pattern_1} entirely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as an architectural variable, not a decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the desk test (read as clean texture at arm's length and a half)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Drape the garment over a chair. Take two full steps back to simulate the distance across a standard work surface. Apply this desk test to every printed piece. Watch how {recommended_pattern_1} behaves from this exact boundary. If the lines bleed into a disorganised smudge, reject the item. The motif must consolidate into a coherent, muted surface. Your clothing depends on a precise fit. Erratic graphics distort that structural geometry. A neutral scheme requires absolute visual clarity. Rely entirely on your own grip. Squeeze the material to ensure the physical mass matches the printed scale. Sensory comfort demands a textile that feels as substantial as it looks.",
      "sectionIntro": "Filter out visual noise by testing how a printed design resolves from a fixed boundary.",
      "tests": [
        "the desk test (read as clean texture at arm's length and a half)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_virgo__moon_virgo__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "precise fit + honest fabric + one meticulous detail",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on precise fit + honest fabric + one meticulous detail.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Look for a self-contained structure in everything you consider. Trust the physical weight and the drape of the cloth as your sensory compass. The temperature of your wardrobe remains strictly neutral. Do not rely on excess to do the work. Your baseline rule is precise fit + honest fabric + one meticulous detail. Picture a dense heavy-loom trouser tailored flush to your waist, worn with a muted knit, and finished with a single piece of heavy, matt hardware. This works because the components stand alone without demanding attention.\n\nBuild your foundation slowly by testing every garment, but deploy your outfits fast. Always apply the fall test. Drop the item onto a hard floor. Listen to the sound it makes on impact. If it flutters and collapses into a formless puddle, leave it on the rack. If it lands with a heavy, definite thud and holds its structural shape, keep it. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish your structural baseline and operational rules.",
      "tests": [
        "the fall test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe entirely on an honest fabric. Pick up the garment and perform the edge test. Fold the hem tightly between your fingers and release it. If the line snaps back sharp and clean, trust it. Look for matt, neutral finishes that hold a precise fit without failing under physical stress. Use {texture_good_1} for shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation. Rely on {texture_good_2} for close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement. For trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day, choose {texture_good_3}. Finish with {texture_good_4} for lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to read a material's physical limits before you even check the care label.",
