        "the edge test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to build a matt baseline. Bring in {texture_good_1} to break up the surface. Crush the hemline to see if it holds a sharp fold. If the material collapses under your thumb, leave it on the rail. It must snap back crisp. A precise fit demands materials that dictate their own boundaries. Keep the dye lots neutral to let these surface contrasts do the work. Judge the cloth blindly. If it feels weak, it is.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the specific surface combinations that form your baseline.",
      "tests": [
        "the edge test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette temperature is neutral. Anchor your wardrobe with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Layer them alongside {core_colour_3} and {core_colour_4} for a self-contained foundation. Apply your relief tone, a soft note used sparingly, to lift heavy blocks of shade. Reject neon brights, glitter finishes, and sugary pastels entirely. They warp your strict aesthetic. Deploy {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as an intentional strike. Beware the total ice trap. A solid wash of grey on grey projects an empty void instead of calculated restraint. Break the monotony with a polished signal. Clasp a mirror-finish silver cuff, pull on a patent leather boot, or slice the look with one sharp streak of electric colour. Secure this approach with a precise fit to lock in your visual impact.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your palette as a strict system, relying on function over preference.",
