    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Pattern must serve the garment structure. In tailored pieces, draw motifs from the literal weave of the textile, acting as your honest fabric. In fluid pieces, rely on subtle scaling. Your versatile approach requires adaptable contrast. Keep tonal variations muted for quiet settings and sharpen the edges when the environment shifts. Always run the straight-edge test. Step back three metres and verify the lines. They must stay crisp and true to guarantee a precise fit. Build your options around {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Pass over superficial prints. Leave {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} on the hanger entirely. Pick up {recommended_pattern_3} or {recommended_pattern_4} and inspect the dye saturation. True geometric structure integrates seamlessly into a neutral palette rather than fighting it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate pattern as an architectural tool rather than a decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the straight-edge test (lines stay crisp and true at three metres)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Check the distance integrity of {recommended_pattern_1}. Stand three metres back and examine the geometry. The shapes must hold perfectly. The boundary between the muted motif and the neutral ground should remain true and unbroken. Pick the garment up and inspect the surface. A genuine honest fabric holds dye with rigid discipline. A lesser blend allows the edges to bleed. Choose textiles that maintain crisp lines even in a quiet palette. This structural clarity is essential to maintain a precise fit. If the design blurs or vibrates across the room, leave the piece on the rack.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the straight-edge test to evaluate the discipline of any printed motif.",
      "tests": [
        "the straight-edge test (lines stay crisp and true at three metres)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_virgo__moon_virgo__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "precise fit + honest fabric + one meticulous detail",
    "closing": "Rely on the physical tension under your fingers to navigate the noise, trusting only in a precise fit + honest fabric + one meticulous detail.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your hands to check the construction before you buy. A garment must feel engineered. Your blueprint is precise fit + honest fabric + one meticulous detail. Picture a tailored trouser sitting exactly on the waist, paired with a dense woven shirt and finished with a single row of heavy topstitching at the collar. If the textile feels slippery or the cut pulls across the shoulder, put it back. Keep the temperature neutral. You are looking for a muted finish and a balanced silhouette that respects your frame.\n\nBuild systematically and curate for adaptability, so you can dress fast. Every item must function across multiple settings. Test every new piece with the fall test. Drop the garment onto a solid table. Watch how it lands. If it collapses into a shapeless puddle, it lacks the internal architecture you require. If it retains its lines and settles with a heavy, decisive impact, you can rely on it. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation, the strict physical laws you will use to evaluate every piece of clothing before it touches your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the fall test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Building a neutral wardrobe around a precise fit requires materials that hold structure. Seek an honest fabric that cooperates with your daily movement. Use {texture_good_1} for shirting that maintains a clean architectural boundary against the collarbone. Layer it over {texture_good_2} to keep close-to-body base layers sharp. For the lower half, rely on {texture_good_3} to build trousers that drape cleanly and refuse to crease. When stepping outside, pull on {texture_good_4} for lightweight outerwear that blocks wind without adding bulk. Before you buy, apply the edge test. Run your thumb along the hem and collar. If the boundary feels crisp and refuses to roll under pressure, the garment will serve you. Consult this hierarchy of reliable materials.",
      "sectionIntro": "Your foundational textiles must support your movement and hold a sharp line throughout the day.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the edge test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Pick up {texture_bad_1} and squeeze the edge of the hem. If the boundary feels thick, stiff, or glued rather than woven, leave it on the rack. Inferior weaves mask their flaws with bulky perimeters. Avoid {texture_bad_2} entirely. The moment it touches your skin, it generates a harsh static charge and clings to the body. You rely on a flawless cut and one meticulous detail to anchor a look. When {texture_bad_3} loses its intended matt finish and catches the light with an artificial shine, it corrupts the entire structure. Rely on the physical resistance of the material. True quality fights back slightly when pinched.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject inferior materials before they even reach the fitting room.",
      "tests": [
        "the edge test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your ideal material tension sits exactly where {sweet_spot_keyword_1} meets {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Start your core layer with {texture_good_1}. Before committing to any purchase, run the seam roll check. Pick the piece up and pinch the hem. Fold the seam back on itself to see if the structure holds firm. If the material collapses limply in your grip, drop it. Demand a precise fit. Seek out neutral, muted threads that hold a clean shape without rigid stiffness. Ground these materials with heavy steel metals. Weigh every piece in your palm. Let your bare hands verify the absolute truth about the manufacturing.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your materials by isolating the exact tension between opposing weaves.",
      "tests": [
        "the edge test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your temperature is strictly neutral. Build your dark anchor using {core_colour_1} for heavy outerwear and {core_colour_2} for balanced base trousers. Place {core_colour_3} directly against the skin in an honest fabric. Bridge the gap with {core_colour_4} in thick worsted wool. Treat {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as your single deliberate accent. Apply the relief tone as a soft note used sparingly. Pass over neon brights, glitter finishes, and sugary pastels. Watch for the total flat trap. Wearing unbroken monolithic shades from neck to ankle creates a hollow void instead of deliberate calm. Break the absence with a hard reflective signal. Fasten a mirror finish cuff, step into a patent leather boot, or expose a single strike of electric thread at the wrist.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assign every shade a strict job and never let them blur.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Graphite",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft stone",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Oatmeal",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Greige",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Chalk white",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Dry sage",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Bottle green",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Dark chocolate",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Pale butter",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "total ice: unbroken grey on grey can read as absence rather than composure",
          "fix": "add the polished signal, a mirror-finish cuff, a patent boot, or one line of electric colour"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "A precise fit dictates your working day. Let the shoulder of a worsted wool jacket sit exactly where it should. From that baseline, the other elements fall into place. The woven material grounds your silhouette, while a single sharp finish completes the sleeve. Rely on your own hands to judge an item. Let the friction of the textile inform your choice. Focus on a matt silver watch casing worn with a crisp cotton poplin shirt in a neutral soft stone. Pick it up and assess the drape. Reaching across a desk must never disrupt the garment's balance. Stepping out for a midday meal does not mean dropping your working climate. Keep the jacket on, step out into the street, and hold your baseline.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish your working standard by testing how your garments respond to movement.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In low light and close quarters, a precise fit leads your wardrobe. Shadows swallow flat colour. Shape remains. Pick up a fine ribbed merino jumper in a neutral soft stone. Run your hands over the seams. Trust your grip to tell you the truth. Assess the density of the knit under your fingers. Pair this piece with worsted wool trousers that drape cleanly over a matt silver buckle. Anchor the outfit with solid steel hardware. Even in private, hold your ground. Apply the proximity check. Sit down in the garment. It must move seamlessly with your joints without pulling. Dress for the eye sitting two feet away.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your strategy for holding your standards steady when the lights go down and the distance closes.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Dress for a morning commute exactly as you would for an afternoon review. A quick walk to the station requires no abandonment of your baseline atmosphere. Trust your hands to verify the structural integrity of technical nylon or crisp cotton poplin. Evaluate the weave entirely through touch. Keep the temperature strictly neutral. Build around oatmeal tones and heavy dominant hardware. Ensure your metal surfaces stay flat and matt. Maintain your baseline by checking that every outfit contains precise fit + honest fabric + one meticulous detail. Hold your daily garments to this rigid measure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Construct your daily routine with rigorous physical standards.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your strategy runs clean. Anchor your jewellery and hardware with {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Just as you demand a precise fit from your garments, require absolute physical density from your metals. Pick up the piece in your bare hands. Gauge the resistance in your palm. Avoid faux-antique brass, beaten copper, and artificially tarnished alloys. These register as visual noise against a modern foundation. Clean up the silhouette by relying on unweathered silver, solid platinum, white gold, and sleek chrome. Maintain a neutral visual temperature across every clasp and zip. Finally, inspect the surface. Reject any {excluded_finish} coatings. Demand a quiet matt texture.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your metals with the exact same ruthless scrutiny you apply to your tailoring.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Lift the piece in your bare hand before you commit. Evaluate every gem by its gravity. A heavy setting grounds the accessory. Seek out dense, opaque pieces like {stone_1}, {stone_2}, and {stone_3} that absorb light into a muted finish. Maintain a neutral temperature in your settings to support a balanced orientation. Avoid porous rocks and synthetic composites that introduce unnecessary noise against a present tense wardrobe. Set these stones in thick, unyielding bezels instead. This discipline ensures your accessories complement the precise fit of your garments without adding visual clutter.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate stones and metals by their mass and clarity, treating them as structural components rather than mere decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Hold every piece of {metal_1} and {stone_1} in your bare hand. Let gravity confirm the construction. Dense hardware anchors your clothing. Lightweight items feel flimsy and break your structure. Test the hinges and clasps. A mechanism must lock with an audible snap. Stick to perfectly smooth {metal_1} with a matt finish. A clean, smooth surface provides necessary clarity against a neutral background. This solid hardware anchors your wardrobe, allowing you to focus on an honest fabric and a precise fit.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test the physical density of your hardware before it makes it onto your body.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Once you establish a precise fit, and after you anchor the look in an honest fabric, you must place exactly one meticulous detail. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin this process with silk scarves. Seek out a crepe de chine square or a slim band, ensuring the dye settles into a strictly matt surface. Trust your hands to evaluate the drape. Watch how the fabric cascades over your knuckles. Apply the one signal test to every addition. If the silk introduces a dominant texture, keep the surrounding worsted wool or technical nylon completely neutral. If the accessory brings a complex weave, pull the rest of the silhouette back to flat stone or oatmeal.",
      "sectionIntro": "Accessories test your discipline and focus.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square or slim band, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Examine the linkage of every necklace. Ensure the links lay flat against the collarbone without twisting. Anchor your fine jewellery entirely in brushed silver. Look for thin chains and small drops that rest naturally against the skin. Seek out a matt surface that absorbs light. Apply the solitary mark rule before wearing any piece. Check if the metal adds exactly one deliberate mark to your silhouette without fighting the worsted wool underneath. Check the tension in the metal chain. If it shines too brightly, leave it behind. A simple piece must complement a precise fit, sinking quietly into a neutral scheme of oatmeal or soft stone.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware using the exact same physical metrics you apply to your tailoring.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin chain and small drops, brushed silver"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Carry a small structured bag. Seek out kid suede for the body and ensure the top handle provides a precise fit in your grip. Specify fine matt hardware in brushed steel or silver to anchor the neutral metals. Opt for neutral tones. Avoid glossy finishes. Execute the isolation check before stepping out. Scan your complete silhouette and locate the primary visual draw. If the textured suede fights a heavy silver watch or a complex shoe, remove the rival piece. The entire composition must broadcast exactly one clear message.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your final layer of accessories and strip away the excess.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede top-handle, fine matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored garments draw their visual rhythm strictly from the structural weave. Fluid pieces take theirs from printed motifs. Adapt your pattern contrast to the garment's purpose. Anchor larger items with low contrast tonal weaves, reserving defined muted contrasts for smaller accessories. Secure a precise fit before evaluating the print. A poor cut distorts good geometry. Build your foundation on {recommended_pattern_1}, {recommended_pattern_2}, and {recommended_pattern_3}. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. Apply the straight edge test to any linear motif. Step back three metres and study the fabric. The lines must stay crisp and true. If they warp or soften at the boundaries, reject the garment. Ensure every pattern respects your neutral temperature and provides a matt, steady background for your metals.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as an architectural element rather than a surface decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the straight-edge test (lines stay crisp and true at three metres)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the distance check to any {recommended_pattern_1} you consider. Hang the garment and examine the motif from across the room. The edges must stay sharp and true. If the lines blur into an ambiguous wash at this distance, leave the piece on the rail. Your style relies on a strictly neutral palette. Fuzzy borders distort that careful balance. Combine a sharply defined print with a solid worsted wool trouser. Require a precise fit through the collar and shoulder. A soft edge often disguises cheap printing methods. True boundaries reveal proper weaving techniques. Let the clarity of the motif be your primary filter.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every printed piece to a rigorous physical distance test before it joins your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the straight-edge test (lines stay crisp and true at three metres)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_cancer__moon_aries__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "soft shelter + sharp edges + one sentimental keepsake",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on soft shelter + sharp edges + one sentimental keepsake.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe slowly. Scrutinise every seam before it crosses your threshold. Your sensory compass is a drop in volume, the physical relief of stepping inside and pulling a heavy door shut. When evaluating a new garment, apply the shelter test. Put the item on and assess your breathing. If the fabric feels exposed, thin, or requires constant adjustment, leave it on the rack. Seek out cool, matt textures that absorb light and offer immediate physical insulation from outside noise. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.\n\nYour fundamental dressing equation is soft shelter + sharp edges + one sentimental keepsake. Ground every look in this strict structure. Picture a dense cashmere wrap coat draped over a rigidly pressed poplin shirt with a severe collar. Finish the combination with a heavy silver pocket watch resting against your ribs. The coat provides the containment, the shirt delivers the precision, and the metal adds the private history. If a silhouette feels vague, check the balance. You must anchor the protective layers with rigorous tailoring and keep the single personal artefact secure against your chest.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this framework to anchor every future clothing decision.",
      "tests": [
        "the shelter test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "You are constructing a soft shelter from the outside world. To build it, rely strictly on the tactile test. Close your eyes and rub the material between your thumb and forefinger. If the fibre fights back or feels rigid, leave it on the rail. Rely on your hands to evaluate quality, ignoring visual illusions. Choose {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Turn to {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that insulate without restricting movement. Select {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Finish with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay pliant at every edge. These muted materials absorb light, keeping your palette cool, matt, and strictly self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Audit every garment against its physical sensation on your skin to build your foundation of textures.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
