    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Do not rely on sight alone. Lift every piece of {metal_1} before you put it on. Feel the absolute weight in your hand. True quality carries unmistakable gravity. If the item feels hollow, put it down. Beware of blinding, highly polished hardware. A glossy surface creates a distracting glare that shatters the quiet mood of your garments. Instead, seek out brushed or matt finishes. These subdued choices deliver necessary sharp edges while remaining perfectly integrated with your cool, self-contained wardrobe. Rely on this tangible heft to ground your decisions.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your hardware physically before letting it near your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You have constructed the soft shelter. You have defined the sharp edges. Now, finalise the structure with one sentimental keepsake. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start with handbags. Demand full-grain leather or thick suede fitted with matt, brushed hardware. Enforce a cool metal finish to align with your muted palette. Pick up the bag and apply the anchor test. Weigh the base in your hands. Ask yourself if this object firmly tethers you to the earth. Trust this tactile response as your primary guide, letting the downward pull dictate your choice.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the physical weight and structure of your accessories to ground your daily uniform.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "When selecting a scarf, seek generous lengths of fine wool or washed silk with a completely matt finish. Test the fabric in your hands before you wear it. Lift the material and let it fall. A true anchor piece pulls firmly towards the floor. It drops straight down and never flutters. Trust this satisfying weight in your grip. This drape provides a soft shelter around your neck while remaining entirely self-contained. Stick to your established cool palette to keep the textile quiet. Use this muted fabric to balance the sharp edges in your tailoring.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply these rules to your scarves, using weight and drape to ground your silhouette.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Fasten a wide full-grain leather belt at your waist. Choose a matt brushed buckle in a strict, cool tone. Next, select your keepsake jewellery. Look for a deep stone set in heavily oxidised aged silver. This dense metal cuts through soft shelter, bringing sharp edges to your frame. Before you finish dressing, check the physical grounding of your finishing touches. Strip away any accessory that floats or rattles. Keep only the solid objects that physically drag your centre of gravity downward into the floor.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your final hardware and apply a strict physical test to ensure every item carries its own weight.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the anchor test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Provide soft shelter with fluid pieces that draw their pattern from structural weaves rather than surface printing. Tailored garments take their pattern from precise construction and subtle thread variations. Enforce a strict low-contrast tonal rule for every patterned piece. When evaluating {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2}, step back into a dimly lit space to conduct your twilight test. If the design demands attention in the shadows, leave it on the rack. The motif must dissolve into a rich, deep texture as the light fades. Pass over anything that interrupts this quiet discipline. Reject {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. Maintain sharp edges without relying on high-visibility graphics. Let cool, muted complexities do the structural work instead.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate pattern strictly by its architectural value rather than its decorative appeal.",
      "tests": [
        "the twilight test (merge into a rich, deep texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Hang the {recommended_pattern_1} garment across the room and turn the lights down. A successful print will stop behaving like a graphic and dissolve into a rich, deep texture. If the design stays stark or legible in the shadows, leave it on the rack. Your wardrobe requires patterns that retreat into the fabric. Stand back and let your vision drop out of focus. The motif must blur into a continuous cool surface. This approach creates soft shelter without compromising structure. Keep your silhouettes defined and build sharp edges through strict tailoring rather than high-contrast prints. Trust your own eyes to spot when a textile settles into muted subtlety.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the twilight test to control how your patterns behave in low light.",
      "tests": [
        "the twilight test (merge into a rich, deep texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_cancer__moon_capricorn__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "soft shelter + softness + one sentimental keepsake",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on soft shelter + softness + one sentimental keepsake.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your hands to find the quietest weight on the rail. Your physical instinct is looking for garments that act as a private sanctuary rather than a public broadcast. Look for a cool, matt finish that absorbs light rather than reflecting it. Build your outfit using your formula, soft shelter + softness + one sentimental keepsake. Picture a dense, enveloping overcoat worn over a fine, fluid knit top, finished with a small inherited locket resting against the collarbone. This combination creates a strictly self-contained environment. The fabrics must glide silently over your skin. If a garment crackles or catches, leave it behind.\n\nBuild your wardrobe slowly and edit ruthlessly. Do not rush to fill gaps with temporary solutions. Every piece must pass the melt test. Put the garment on and stand perfectly still. Observe how the fabric interacts with your shoulders and joints. It must melt into your frame, yielding completely to your posture rather than forcing you into a rigid silhouette. If a structured collar sits awkwardly or a seam fights your movement, take the piece off immediately. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the physical instincts and styling formula that form the foundation of your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your soft shelter from {texture_good_1} that compresses under your grip and springs back. Seek {texture_good_3} for coats that maintain absolute structure. Rely on {texture_good_4} for interior softness against the skin. Ground these layers with {texture_good_2} accessories that yield and patinate over time. Run the grip test before bringing anything new into your wardrobe. Close your eyes and squeeze the material. If it feels flimsy or traps heat, drop it. You need dense, cool weight with a matt finish. Let your hands verify the integrity of every thread. Focus your sourcing strictly on these exact materials.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the dense, matt materials that build your quiet wardrobe.",
