    "style_core": {
      "text": "Feel the weight of the fabric in your hands before you put it on. Your wardrobe is an architecture of retreat. Build it using a strict equation: soft shelter + blurred edges + one sentimental keepsake. Picture a dense, enveloping knit layer that drops past the knee, worn over a fluid, bias-cut base that obscures the exact line of the body. Finish it with a private, inherited object resting cool against the collarbone. Seek out matt finishes that absorb light. The garments must feel substantial but yield entirely to your frame.\n\nCurate your pieces at a glacial pace, but get dressed fast. When assessing a new garment, apply the melt test. Drop the fabric onto a table and watch how the seams behave. The item should collapse into a soft pool of cloth. It must not hold a rigid shape. A stiff collar or a sharp shoulder will feel like an intrusion on your personal space. If the piece stands up on its own, leave it on the rack. You require garments that drape, fold, and wrap without restriction. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.",
