    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Trust your hands to identify imposters. {texture_bad_1} fails immediately. It traps heat against the skin instead of letting it circulate freely. You know the threshold for breathability, so enforce it ruthlessly. {texture_bad_2} presents a similar problem. It clings and restricts rather than maintaining a cool, private boundary. {texture_bad_3} looks matt but feels distinctly abrasive against the neck. You require materials that soothe the senses. A stiff, suffocating fabric disrupts your composure and distracts from that one sentimental keepsake resting against your collarbone.",
      "sectionIntro": "Reject materials that actively fight your physical comfort.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe on a foundation of {sweet_spot_keyword_1} layered under {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. This pairing creates a quiet undercurrent of physical ease. Pick up a prospective item and crush it in your fist. It should pool back into shape without rigid creases. Next, check the weave for absolute ventilation. A true {texture_good_1} lets air pass freely without resistance. Look for surfaces with a cool, matt finish. Avoid anything shiny or stiff. Your clothes must move with you, wrapping you in physical comfort while remaining entirely self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Combine your textures with deliberate intent to anchor your physical comfort.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your temperature is strictly cool. Assess how a tone reflects on your skin and let your physical response guide you. Treat {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_3} as the foundation for your soft shelter. Rely on {core_colour_2} for structural anchors. Pick up {core_colour_4} as a reliable white substitute. Restrict saturation to a single deliberate accent, deploying {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} selectively. Introduce the relief tone as a soft note used sparingly to break a severe edge. Pass over hard black, harsh neon, and heavy earth brown. Avoid the specific trap of head-to-toe black. It reads like you gave up on the way out the door. Fix this failure by splitting the dark block with a {core_colour_4} layer, a deep {accent_colour_1} scarf, or a matt {core_colour_3} belt.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your palette to exert total control over your visual impact.",
