    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the distance test to any {recommended_pattern_1}. Hang the garment on a hook, step back three paces, and let your eyes lose focus. A successful print dissolves into a continuous, warm surface. It must resemble cracked earth viewed from a high ridge. If the motif remains sharp, isolated, or visually separate from the cloth at this range, leave it on the rail. You require patterns that settle quietly into the weave. Always confirm that the design respects enduring structure rather than fighting the cut. Lift the item to verify the visual blur matches the actual weight of the cloth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every printed garment to a strict visual distance check.",
      "tests": [
        "the field test (settle into a natural texture like ground seen from a hill)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_capricorn__moon_taurus__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "enduring structure + sensory comfort + one living texture",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on enduring structure + sensory comfort + one living texture.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your physical response to a garment before you check the mirror. Feel the dense weave and the silent friction of the cloth against your skin. If a piece pulls or restricts, drop it. Build your wardrobe methodically over time. Deploy it by daily instinct. When you put a piece on, apply the host test. Ask yourself if the cut makes you feel like an anxious guest in borrowed tailoring, or the host who owns the house. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not.\n\nYour baseline mechanism is enduring structure + sensory comfort + one living texture. Picture a heavy wool overcoat with a rigid shoulder line. Underneath it, place a fine gauge cashmere sweater that sits close to the skin. Finish the combination with a matt suede boot. The overcoat provides the external architecture. The knit delivers the necessary warmth and physical ease. The suede adds a rough surface to break up the flat planes. Look for this exact balance every time you dress. If an outfit feels rigid, you need the soft layer. If it feels fragile, you lack the heavy architecture.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your wardrobe to the physical reality of how clothes actually feel and function.",
      "tests": [
        "the host test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe on a foundation of enduring structure and sensory comfort. Rely on {texture_good_1} for knitwear that compresses under a heavy coat and springs back into shape. Choose {texture_good_2} for bags and belts that mould to your life. Ground your outerwear in {texture_good_3}, as it holds a clean line year after year. Layer {texture_good_4} for blouses that provide fluid movement. Always apply the candlelight test to your fabrics. Hold the material up to a warm, dim light. If the surface drinks the illumination and reveals a matt, muted depth, you have found your one living texture. If it glares or reflects sharply back at you, put the garment down. Let your hands and eyes confirm the density of the thread.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise your core materials before you even check the label.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
