      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Examine every piece closely under low light. If the material throws off a harsh, brittle glare instead of maintaining a warm, matt finish in the glow, leave it on the hanger. Avoid {texture_bad_1}. Pinch it between your fingers. Its tell is a distinct squeak under your thumb, betraying a complete lack of breathability against the skin. Drop any item made of {texture_bad_2}. It fails immediately in the hand. You will feel a hollow, limp drape rather than the enduring structure you require. A cheap weave snags on dry cuticles and holds a rigid, artificial shape. Trust your tactile response to catch these failures. Your clothes must soften with wear, never trapping heat.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands and eyes to ruthlessly reject materials that fail your baseline standards.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your sweet spot balances {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Make sensory comfort the baseline for every choice. When combining layers, place {texture_good_1} close to heavier weaves. Take the item into a shadow and test its surface. The textile must absorb the ambient warmth. It must never bounce the light back. If it shines abruptly, leave it on the rail. Combine matt threads with soft woven layers to ground the shape. Depend on the heaviness in your palm to verify the quality. Visuals deceive, but gravity remains honest.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the exact intersection of weaves to ground your daily choices.",
      "tests": [
        "the candlelight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette relies on a warm temperature. Anchor your collection with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Link these items using {core_colour_3} and {core_colour_4}. Keep a single deliberate focal point using {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Deploy your soft relief tone sparingly to separate heavy visual blocks. Leave icy electric blue, neon brights, and fleeting trend pastels on the rail. Watch out for the heavy sink. When every item is matt and heavy, stacking dark shades creates a muddy void that can swallow you whole. Lift this combination by placing a light neutral near the collar, adding one item of polished leather, or applying your soft relief tone. Apply these tones to garments that deliver enduring structure and sensory comfort.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your colours as tools with specific jobs, grouping your tones systematically rather than throwing them together at random.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rich toffee",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
