          "fix": "lift it: an oatmeal cream layer at the collar, one piece of polished leather, or the washed blue relief"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, enduring structure leads the uniform. Establish the perimeter with a heavy brushed camel wool blazer. Support this firm architecture with immediate physical ease, allowing the rigid shell to yield. A fluid silk blouse provides quiet insulation without adding bulk. Anchor the look with a warm, matt rich toffee full-grain leather briefcase to supply necessary friction. Pick up the bag and test the weight. Notice how the raw hide grounds the polished tailoring. Call on the Flint test before you leave the house. A mid-morning walk to the corner shop demands the exact same precise drape as a quarterly boardroom presentation. Never downgrade your tailoring for minor tasks.",
      "sectionIntro": "Translate your core style parameters into a strict working uniform.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close quarters and dim light, visual details fade. Let sensory comfort take the lead. Reach for camel cashmere that invites a second touch. Maintain your structural standards even behind closed doors. Heavy silk provides a grounding weight against the skin. Avoid harsh synthetic fibres that rustle loudly in quiet spaces. Choose rich toffee full-grain leather that softens with wear. Select muted, warm gold jewellery that absorbs low light rather than flashing. Depend on the heavy drop of brushed wool to hold its line in the shadows.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the transition into low-light environments by letting touch supersede sight.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Apply the same strict filtering to your weekend garments as you do your formal wear. Standing in the queue at the post office requires your core baseline of enduring structure + sensory comfort + one living texture. Anchor your daily movements in camel brushed wool trousers that hold a firm line. Layer over a muted silk shirt. Finish the silhouette with warm toffee leather shoes. Let your physical intuition guide your choices when pulling garments from the rail. Trust the mass of the fabric over its hanger appeal. Assess the heavy drape of a cashmere jumper before you put it on.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your aesthetic rules to every waking hour, because true discipline does not take a day off.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Let warm metals define your strategy. Select {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} for your buckles, zips, and jewellery. Trust your hands when evaluating hardware. Pick the item up. Evaluate the actual weight in your palm to guarantee quality. You need dense, substantial hardware to anchor your textiles in enduring structure. Avoid mirror-polished silver. A harsh, highly reflective zip or clasp fractures the visual calm of a muted palette and pulls focus from your cashmere. Instead, reject the {excluded_finish} finish entirely. Demand brushed, antiqued, or matt surfaces to keep the aesthetic cohesive. This deliberate muting ensures your metals provide quiet density rather than sharp distraction, preserving your baseline of sensory comfort.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your hardware as the final test of structural density and warmth.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Seek stones that absorb light rather than refract it. Look for the warm opacity of {stone_1} or the dense weight of {stone_2}. Feel the heft of the piece to gauge its value. A substantial stone anchors a garment, providing enduring structure. Skip heavily faceted gems that throw off blinding reflections. A glaring finish creates a jarring distraction next to your softly muted fabrics. Stick to opaque settings to maintain total visual cohesion. Ensure the underside sits flat, delivering uninterrupted sensory comfort.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware strictly by its weight and its capacity to absorb light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Pick up a {metal_1} cuff or belt buckle. Close your eyes. Assess the heaviness in your palm. Rely on physical resistance over visual appeal. Bright, gleaming hardware cuts harshly across warm fabrics. It interrupts the cohesive surface you require. Select matt or brushed finishes instead. A subdued exterior integrates seamlessly with garments built for sensory comfort. Use substantial {stone_1} pieces to provide enduring structure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every piece of hardware before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments establish enduring structure. Your knitwear secures sensory comfort. Accessories must carry the final element. Use them to introduce one living texture to the outfit. Always limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start with handbags. Require full-grain leather finished with brushed matt hardware. Evaluate every choice with the one-ember test. A successful addition glows with a subtle, warm heat beside your muted textiles. It never flashes. Grip the item. If the metal catches the light sharply, drop it. You need quiet, steady materials to anchor your foundation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Your accessories provide the final tactile element, requiring a strict limit and a demanding eye.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Treat scarves as tools to secure sensory comfort. Select fine wool or heavy silk, but always demand a matt finish. Avoid anything that shines like glass or reflects hard light. Scrutinise the textile before buying. Ask if this camel or rich toffee fabric holds a steady, warm core amidst your other layers, rather than sparking a bright fire. Look for a dense weave that folds heavily. If the silk slips loosely or throws off a sharp sheen, put it back. You need a grounded, muted fabric that holds its colour deep in the thread.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate the textiles you wrap and knot to complete your baseline layers.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your waist with a medium full-grain leather belt. Run your thumb over the hardware to ensure a dull, matt buckle, discarding any metal that gleams. For keepsake jewellery, seek out heavily oxidised pieces or aged silver. This deliberately tarnished finish brings enduring structure to a soft camel knit. Finally, conduct a final mirror check before moving on. Scan your reflection and remove the single accessory that flashes too brightly. You need a steady, warm smoulder throughout your look, never a glaring spotlight.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your accessories by grounding your look in muted metals and applying a strict visual edit.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor your tailored garments with {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2} to define their shape. Let fluid pieces carry softer woven variations like {recommended_pattern_3} or {recommended_pattern_4}. Patterns should support your baseline enduring structure without breaking the muted boundary. Keep all pattern contrasts strictly tonal. You are aiming for visual depth that reveals itself only upon close inspection. When evaluating a cloth, confirm its sensory comfort before accepting the design. Apply the firelight test to every patterned weave. Hold the fabric under a dim, warm bulb. The motif must deepen and glow naturally in lamplight. It should soften into the base cloth rather than jumping off the surface. Avoid high-contrast {avoid_pattern_1} and sharp {avoid_pattern_2}. Pass over flat prints, high-definition graphics, and anything that creates a stark visual interruption.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate pattern as a precise tool to reinforce the architecture of your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Subject every {recommended_pattern_1} to a shadow check. Take the garment into a space lit only by a low table lamp or a glowing hearth. Watch how the motif behaves. A successful print will sink into the weave, becoming a richer, warm wash in the dim glow. If the lines sharpen or spring forward to demand attention, leave the item on the rack. Your chosen prints must uphold a quiet, enduring structure. True patterns in your wardrobe provide visual sensory comfort, blurring softly at a distance rather than competing for focus. Rely on this physical verification. Assess the depth of the motif under subdued lighting to guarantee it remains firmly grounded.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this environmental lighting check to separate harmonious prints from disruptive graphics.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_capricorn__moon_virgo__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "enduring structure + honest fabric + one living texture",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on enduring structure + honest fabric + one living texture.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Anchor your choices in physical adaptability. Trust the weight and drape of a garment against your shoulder as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not. Your foundation relies on pieces that shift easily between contexts without losing their shape. Dress using this exact formula: enduring structure + honest fabric + one living texture. Picture a heavy cotton canvas trench coat worn open over a fine merino crewneck, finished with a rough suede belt. The canvas holds the line, the merino breathes with your body, and the suede provides a warm, matt anchor that grounds the combination.\n\nBuild your wardrobe slowly over time, but deploy your outfits fast. You need components that lock together in seconds without a prolonged morning debate. Apply the half-mirror test before you leave. Stand before a waist-high glass and evaluate only your top layers. The upper half of your outfit must look entirely resolved on its own. If the jacket and knit require the trousers or boots to make sense, take a layer off and start again. You want a balanced, muted finish that supports your frame. Trust your hands when checking these layers. If a fabric feels synthetic or fragile, drop it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your core styling formula and the physical tests that keep your wardrobe grounded.",
      "tests": [
        "the half-mirror test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your foundation demands enduring structure and honest fabric. To find it, rely on the wrist-flick test. Pick up a garment by the hem and snap your wrist sharply. If the material floats or collapses, put it back. You need weight and predictability. Choose {texture_good_1} for shirting that holds clean architectural boundaries. Build your base layers from {texture_good_2} to maintain sharp lines close to the body. Seek out {texture_good_3} for trousers that drape properly and resist creasing throughout the day. Finish with {texture_good_4} for mobile outerwear that blocks the wind. These textiles anchor warm, muted tones perfectly and create the ideal matt background for the one living texture you add to complete the look. Treat the following list as your baseline.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify materials that do the physical work for your wardrobe.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the wrist-flick test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Leave {texture_bad_1} on the rack. It traps heat against the skin and feels slick between your fingers. Apply the snap check to any woven item. Grasp the cuff and jerk it downward. If the material flops lifelessly or hangs rigidly, walk away. You need enduring structure to hold a shape, not a cheap imitation. Avoid {texture_bad_2} entirely. It catches the light with a harsh sheen instead of absorbing it with a warm, matt depth. Let the raw friction of a bad weave warn you away. Vision deceives, but the hand recognises cheap construction instantly.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise and reject inferior materials before you ever put them on.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist-flick test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Pair {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Demand warm tones that remain strictly matt. Slide the garment onto your arm and pull your hand straight down. Watch the cuff. An honest fabric drops into position immediately. It does not cling. It does not hesitate. Rely on gravity to reveal the quality. You need fibres that obey physics. Test {texture_good_1} using this exact motion. If the sleeve catches on your forearm or floats softly in the air, leave the piece on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the physical tests that separate true quality from cheap imitations.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist-flick test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette rests on a decidedly warm temperature. Build the base with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Treat {core_colour_3} as your alternative to severe white. Use {core_colour_4} to connect opposing tones in a single outfit. Deploy {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} as your deliberate accents. Rely on a soft note used sparingly as a relief tone to interrupt heavy blocks of colour. Leave icy pastel, neon brights, and cold blue-grey on the rack. They clash with your underlying warmth. Beware the trap of unanchored prettiness. An entirely pale or soft outfit registers as pleasant but fades from memory by midday. Fix this by grounding the look. Introduce enduring structure through a sharply cut worsted wool blazer or a rigid leather shoe where the eye lands first.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your palette by assigning each shade a distinct physical job, treating your tones as architectural tools rather than mere decoration.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Warm taupe",
          "role": "warm_base"
