    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, an honest fabric leads. You need material that breathes under prolonged stress. Let your tailoring frame the body to provide the architectural support, while a single tactile surface detail completes the look. Build the base around worsted wool trousers and a crisp cotton poplin shirt. Warm taupe and camel pieces manage the visual heavy lifting. Establish this shape first, then introduce your muted metals. Measure every item against your weekend baseline. Trudging out in the rain to fetch the Sunday papers requires a forgiving, yielding comfort. Hold your boardroom attire to that exact requirement. If a garment feels restrictive when you reach across a desk, drop it. Assess the weave critically. If the material feels stiff, it will fail you by noon.",
      "sectionIntro": "This protocol calibrates your baseline physical standards for the workplace, anchoring your focus on what functions under pressure.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim settings, enduring structure takes the lead. Trust your physical reactions in the dark. Vision deceives you. Touch reveals the absolute reality of a garment. If worsted wool feels abrasive against bare skin, drop it immediately. The absolute ease you demand when running out for coffee on a freezing morning must translate directly to the fine ribbed merino you wear to a dinner reservation. Establish your evening palette with deep camel tones. Mix your metals deliberately. Place a heavy silver ring next to a muted gold chain. This dual pairing catches ambient light without glare. Ensure every surface remains rigorously matt.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your evening garments by isolating their tactile properties in low light.",
      "tests": [
