      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Treat metals on two distinct tracks. For items worn directly against the skin, select the warm tones of {personal_metal_1} and {personal_metal_2}. For the functional architecture of your garments, limit zips, clasps, and belt buckles to {structural_metal_1} and {structural_metal_2}. This strict division establishes enduring structure. Avoid hammered, antiqued, or artificially tarnished surfaces. They read as costume clutter against present-tense clothing. Anchor your hardware exclusively in the sharp clarity of polished silver, white gold, platinum, and mirror chrome. Eliminate {excluded_finish} components completely. When evaluating a buckle or heavy chain, lift the item in your palm. Evaluate the heft before looking at the shine. A dense clasp guarantees the garment will hold its shape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hardware dictates the functional integrity of your garments.",
