    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Visual bulk means nothing without physical heft. Let your palm act as the final judge to measure quality. Artificially weathered hardware, distressed materials, and heavily oxidised details read as pure visual noise. They actively fight the honest fabric of your garments. Correct this distraction by choosing flawlessly polished {metal_1}. This sleek, unblemished surface provides the precise warm anchor that your enduring structure demands, cutting cleanly through your muted foundation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware through touch to ensure it grounds your garments correctly.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories deliver the final variable. You have defined the enduring structure. You have anchored the look in honest fabric. Now you must supply one living texture. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Run the too-much test before you finish. Assess the physical and visual weight. If the detail overwhelms the garment, the balance collapses. Take the last item off. Begin your selection with silk scarves. Pick up a crepe de chine square or a slim band. Feel the resistance in the weave. The silk requires a muted, matt finish that holds a warm dye. Reject any surface that catches the light.",
      "sectionIntro": "This section establishes the strict parameters for completing your look with precision and restraint.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square or slim band, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the too-much test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Treat fine jewellery as you would any honest fabric. Look for thin chains and small drops cast in brushed silver. The finish must remain matt to sit quietly against warm camel layers. Evaluate the visual load to check your balance. Put the items on and stand back. If your eye lands on the silver before recognising the enduring structure of your worsted wool coat, remove the piece. Trust your own hands to gauge the material. Photographs deceive. High density proves the quality.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select supplementary elements with the same stringent criteria you apply to woven garments.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin chain and small drops, brushed silver"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the too-much test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select a small kid suede top-handle bag to secure your items. Your carrying options require enduring structure to hold their shape empty or full. Scrutinise the fine matt hardware. Mix your metals deliberately in these small fittings. Choosing a lock mechanism that combines dull brass and brushed steel activates your warm tones without adding unwanted shine. Test the resistance of the metal with your fingers. Heavy, solid components confirm lasting utility. Before leaving, remove the heaviest element. Stand before the mirror and locate the single accessory demanding the most visual attention. If a bulky watch or a dominant pendant fights your honest fabric garments, leave it in the tray. Every remaining piece must work in complete balance.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor the outfit with practical weight, then apply a final filter to eliminate excess.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede top-handle, fine matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the too-much test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Trust the weight of the weave over the lure of a print. Let tailored pieces draw their pattern directly from the threads. Look for {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_3} embedded in an enduring structure. Fluid garments dictate softer surface designs like {recommended_pattern_2}. Adapt your contrast to the environment. Keep the difference between motif and ground subtle for daytime contexts, reserving sharper visual separations for the evening. Pass over prints that interrupt a warm, matt finish. Leave {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} on the rail. Apply the glance test. A successful design registers as a soft, continuous rhythm across the cloth, never an isolated graphic demanding attention.",
      "sectionIntro": "Pattern introduces visual momentum, but it must always obey the geometry of the garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the glance test (a pleasant impression rather than a specific shouting motif)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Employ the distance check on any printed piece. Hang the garment across the room, drop your gaze, and look up for a split second. You need a pleasant, unified wash of warm, muted tones. You do not want a specific shouting motif. When inspecting {recommended_pattern_1}, deliberately blur your vision. If the print reads as a gentle shift in shade rather than sharp recognisable shapes, it passes. Measure the density of the thread before you look at the dye. Heavier cloths hold their shape regardless of the surface print. Choose garments with enduring structure, ensure you are holding honest fabric, and let the pattern serve merely as a quiet visual hum.",
      "sectionIntro": "Run every pattern through a strict visual filter before you commit.",
      "tests": [
        "the glance test (a pleasant impression rather than a specific shouting motif)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_gemini__moon_capricorn__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "crisp separation + softness + one clever contrast",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on crisp separation + softness + one clever contrast.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the sheer weight and drape of the cloth. Your compass relies on precise tailoring and yielding movement. Execute your looks using crisp separation + softness + one clever contrast. Picture a sharply tailored top coat layered over a fluid, unstructured blouse and heavy trousers, grounded by a severe architectural shoe. This provides the rigid boundary you require to remain entirely self-contained. Always check the finish. It must remain matt, inherently cool to the touch, and absorb light rather than reflect it.\n\nCurate your garments slowly, but deploy them with immediate certainty. Run the decade test on every single purchase. Hold the item in your hands and determine if its proportions would have looked deliberate ten years in the past, and if they will remain resolute ten years from today. If a piece relies on a temporary silhouette, leave it on the rail. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your wardrobe here before making any further decisions.",
      "tests": [
        "the decade test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe relies on materials that hold a cool temperature and a matt surface. Let tactile feedback guide your selections. Before buying, perform the friction check. Drag the fabric across your inner arm to ensure it delivers total softness. Build your foundation with {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Choose {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Rely on {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Finish with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. These fabrics allow you to execute crisp separation between layers. Introduce one clever contrast in your hardware, and the composition is complete.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the materials that work for you before you even look in the mirror.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed alpaca",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "enveloping winter coats and oversized cardigans"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fluid modal jersey",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers that follow the body without ever gripping it"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed cotton flannel",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "shirts and loungewear that feel like a remembered embrace"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Avoid {texture_bad_1} entirely. It ruins the crisp separation your garments require by clinging stubbornly to the body. Verify the integrity of every yard of cloth. Rub the textile against your bare neck. If {texture_bad_2} leaves a hot, prickling trail, drop it immediately. It disrupts the cool, self-contained drape you need. Steer clear of {texture_bad_3} as well. This stiff, unyielding weave catches the light in harsh patches rather than absorbing it into a matt surface.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify the textiles that actively undermine your aesthetic.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe requires strict tailoring anchoring deep softness. Build this tactile tension by pairing {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Pick up an item made of {texture_good_1} and evaluate its heft. Press the textile directly to your inner pulse point. If it scratches the tender skin of your wrist, put the piece back. Garments deceive on the hanger, but your skin reveals the truth. Seek out cool, muted wools and heavy washed silks that absorb light. Avoid stiff polyester blends. These strict textile choices build a self-contained uniform.",
      "sectionIntro": "Find the exact tension between fibres to build your foundations.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette runs strictly cool. Build the foundation using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_3} as your primary bases. Anchor them with {core_colour_2} for dense structural depth. Deploy {core_colour_4} as your blank substitute. Achieve crisp separation by blocking these shades clearly against one another. Bring in {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} for your single deliberate accent. Treat your relief tone purely as a hushed note used sparingly. Bypass hard black, harsh neon, and heavy earth brown. Watch for the trap of excessive shine, where grandeur slips into gaudiness. Fix this by permitting exactly one molten flash per look. Keep every other hardware detail small, matt, and strictly supporting.",
      "sectionIntro": "Govern your palette by assigning strict roles to every hue.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Dove grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Inky navy",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep teal",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Oyster",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Pale aqua",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Smoked mauve",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Faded rose",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep berry",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft oatmeal",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "gilt overload: grandeur tips into gaudiness",
          "fix": "hold the line at one molten flash and keep every other metal moment small, matt, and supporting"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, let crisp separation lead your choices. Build your foundation with deep teal heavy silk crepe trousers and a dove grey washed silk blouse. A demanding day does not require stiff tailoring. It requires responsive textiles that move with your frame without restriction. Rely on cloud-soft lambswool or boiled wool jackets to provide flexible structure. Support this base with a single unexpected element, like an angular cool platinum cuff. Check the garments manually. Pick up the knitwear and squeeze the sleeve. If the material fights your grip, leave it on the rack.",
      "sectionIntro": "Approach your boardroom garments with strict physical standards.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim, close quarters, crisp separation leads. Low light obscures complex details. Rely on sharp boundaries to define your silhouette in heavy silk crepe or boiled wool. Keep your palette cool with deep teal and dove grey, anchored by brushed platinum. Subject your evening wear to the endurance check. A long dinner requires pliant garments that accommodate continuous posture changes. Assess the mass of the fabric before you put it on. True density cannot be faked. Heavy silk must pool like liquid metal. Matt finishes catch ambient light and draw focus inwards.",
      "sectionIntro": "Calibrate your approach for close quarters and low-light environments.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Run the Wren test. A dense Tuesday itinerary does not demand stiff woven armour. It asks for yielding fibres capable of a sudden sprint. Waiting for a prescription at the chemist does not suspend the rules. Pair cloud-soft lambswool trousers with a sharply cut dove grey washed silk blouse. Add a matt platinum pendant. You must execute crisp separation + softness + one clever contrast across every ordinary hour. Keep your palette cool and strictly muted. Pick up the blouse and stretch the seam. If the thread bites into your shoulder blade, leave it on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your everyday errands with the exact same physical rigour you apply to closed-door meetings.",
      "tests": [
        "a packed day does not require hard clothes; it requires soft ones that can sprint (Wren)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your hardware strategy demands a cool, understated approach. Anchor your collection with {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}, ensuring every buckle, zip, and ring shares this identical cool temperature. Reject {excluded_finish} treatments entirely. A highly reflective clasp creates a harsh glare that disrupts the muted colours in your garments. Rely on dense structural elements to establish crisp separation at a closure or waistline, while sticking strictly to brushed and matt textures to protect your required softness. When considering a new piece of jewellery, lift it in your palm to assess its mass. A photograph cannot convey true gravity. Only heavy, solid metal grounds a self-contained outfit properly.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat metal as a structural tool to ground your garments, selecting each piece with the same uncompromising rigour as your textiles.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select your stones to reinforce the muted, cool landscape of your wardrobe. Lift a {stone_1} ring or a {stone_2} pendant off the velvet. Evaluate the gem by its uncompromising weight. Rely on this heavy physical density as your primary filter. Gleaming, highly polished hardware acts as a sharp distraction against your subdued pieces. It ruins the necessary softness of your layers. Limit your settings to matt or brushed finishes to keep the visual field cohesive. Mount a dense {stone_1} in brushed metal to achieve crisp separation against your knits without breaking your self-contained aesthetic.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones and metals by their physical gravity and visual restraint.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift every ring, buckle, and chain off the table. Do not trust a superficial shine. Rely on raw, unyielding weight to anchor your details. A dense piece of {metal_1} grounds an outfit properly. Next, evaluate the surface finish. Mirror-polished metal acts like a visual flare, reflecting light too sharply and destroying the essential softness of your cool wardrobe. Insist on brushed, frosted, or oxidised textures instead. A genuinely matt {metal_1} finish absorbs ambient light rather than fighting it. This exact choice allows the metal to establish crisp separation against your garments without ever becoming a jarring distraction.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test the physical reality of your hardware before you commit to wearing it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories deliver your one clever contrast. They anchor the crisp separation and physical softness you constructed in your garments. Limit your styling to one or two strong pieces per look. Overloading creates noise. Start with handbags. Demand full-grain leather or thick suede. Inspect the closures for cool, matt brushed hardware that absorbs ambient light. Apply the heirloom test to every item. Ask yourself if a discerning descendant would fight to keep this piece decades from now. Rely on durable substance rather than fleeting trends. Pick the bag up and verify the true density of the hide.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your look with heavy, undeniable accessories that pass the test of time.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the heirloom test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Treat scarves as structural tools to inject necessary softness into your geometry. Seek generous dimensions in fine wool or opaque silk. The finish must remain completely matt. Avoid high-gloss synthetics that catch unwanted reflections. When evaluating a new piece, confirm the drape manually. Quality requires actual substance. Evaluate the textile for permanence. Question whether this specific deep teal wrap will maintain its quiet integrity after decades of continuous use. If the fabric feels thin, leave it on the shelf. Use a large dove grey scarf to anchor your cool palette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate scarves purely as structural additions to your physical foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the heirloom test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your waist with wide full-grain leather and a brushed matt buckle. This rigid band forces crisp separation below the softness of boiled wool. Layer in keepsake jewellery, choosing a deep stone set in aged silver or oxidised brass. Always prioritise cool metal tones to maintain absolute discipline. Test the hardware for generational endurance. Drop the object into your bare palm and measure its physical density. If the metal lacks the robust construction and self-contained gravity to outlast its wearer, leave it in the shop.",
      "sectionIntro": "Secure the finishing elements to anchor the frame and ground the silhouette.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the heirloom test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Maintain crisp separation between your patterned pieces and your solid garments. For a self-contained aesthetic, demand low-contrast tonal designs. Tailored pieces take their visual rhythm from the physical weave of the cloth, such as a subtle {recommended_pattern_1}. Fluid layers carry printed motifs, like a {recommended_pattern_2} or a {recommended_pattern_3}. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. Apply the field test to any print. Step back and assess the cloth. The design must settle into a unified, muted texture that reads as a single shadow. If the shapes jump forward as distinct graphics, leave the item on the rack. Deliver softness through the physical drape of the fabric, ensuring the overall visual impression remains perfectly ordered.",
      "sectionIntro": "Filter out visual noise and evaluate your patterns with strict physical discipline.",
      "tests": [
        "the field test (settle into a natural texture like ground seen from a hill)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Execute the Landscape Test. Drape the garment over a chair, step back ten paces, and blur your vision. A successful {recommended_pattern_1} will stop demanding attention. It must dissolve into a cohesive, matt terrain, resembling a cool hillside seen from a high ridge rather than a sharp graphic. This visual shift guarantees the print provides the necessary softness to ground your silhouette. If the motif remains rigid or projects outwards across the room, drop the fabric immediately. The pattern must settle quietly into itself.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this visual field test to verify that a pattern respects your boundaries.",
      "tests": [
        "the field test (settle into a natural texture like ground seen from a hill)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_gemini__moon_taurus__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "crisp separation + sensory comfort + one clever contrast",
    "closing": "Let the weight of the cloth guide your hands toward crisp separation + sensory comfort + one clever contrast.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Judge a garment by its immediate physical weight and temperature. The material must drape with a heavy, cool certainty against your skin. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not. Your blueprint relies on a strict equation. Build every outfit around crisp separation + sensory comfort + one clever contrast. Picture a tailored trouser cut with a razor-sharp crease, paired with a fine-gauge knit that sits softly against the collarbone, anchored by a sharply structured flat shoe.\n\nConstruct your wardrobe with slow precision. Acquire items over time, then deploy them fast on a dark morning without a second thought. Run every new acquisition through the melt test. When you pull a garment on, it must vanish instantly into your physical awareness. If you have to adjust a collar, shift a shoulder seam, or tug at a hem, leave it on the hanger. The piece must dissolve seamlessly into your posture. If you feel the architecture of the garment fighting your natural movement, it fails.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat this section as the structural logic of your wardrobe, the blueprint that turns instinct into daily practice.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Anchor your sensory comfort in fabrics that absorb light. Seek out {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Look for {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Rely on {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Finish with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. Before purchasing, verify how the material ages. Run the cloth through your fingers and gauge if time and friction will improve its character. Visuals deceive. Density holds the truth. If the fabric will degrade rather than break in, leave it on the rail. The four primary textures below guarantee crisp separation against the rest of your cool, muted wardrobe.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the textiles that build your physical foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
