          "failure": "the sofa drift: soften every piece far enough and one day you are simply in loungewear",
          "fix": "restore exactly one line: a rolled but real lapel, a trouser with a soft crease, or a firm leather bag against all that give"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Crisp separation leads your work strategy. Build distinct layers to define your silhouette, starting with a dove grey washed silk shirt tucked firmly into tailored trousers. Let tactile ease act as your primary supporting metric. Test the endurance of the fit. If you cannot stand still for twenty minutes without a heavy silk crepe seam digging into your ribs, leave the garment on the rack. Your clothes must aid your posture, never demanding physical tolerance. Finally, introduce a single shift in styling to disrupt the uniformity. Pair a deep teal boiled wool jacket with a sharply pressed collar, finishing the look with a cool, matt silver watch. You know what functions. Trust your hands.",
      "sectionIntro": "Approach the professional environment by anchoring your styling decisions in strict physical boundaries and tactile ease.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light quarters, crisp separation dictates the outcome. Build outfits around distinct borders between garments. Pair a dove grey washed silk blouse directly over deep teal tailored trousers. Avoid blended edges. Anchor the look with a single brushed platinum cuff. Test every evening piece by asking if you could wear it to sit comfortably on a low sofa for hours. If the waistband digs in or the sleeves restrict your reach, discard the item immediately. You do not need to suffer physical pinching for an evening aesthetic. Keep the overall palette cool and the finish strictly matt.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master low-light intimate settings by letting clear structural boundaries lead your decisions.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "An early, damp commute is not an excuse to abandon your baseline. Anchor your daily movement in boiled wool trousers and a cloud-soft lambswool jumper in deep teal. Test the weight of every piece in your hands. If an item feels stiff or restrictive, leave it on the hanger. Your approach always demands crisp separation + sensory comfort + one clever contrast. Pair a sharply tailored cool grey overcoat with a yielding knit layer. Rely on muted, matt textures to maintain visual calm.",
      "sectionIntro": "Structure your routine around items that work with your body, never against it.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your metal strategy leans decisively cool. Anchor your hardware choices in {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. A brilliant, highly reflective {excluded_finish} clasp will ruin your crisp separation. It creates a harsh glare against soft, muted fabrics. Fix this by demanding matt and heavily brushed textures across all your structural buckles and zips. Before you commit to a piece of jewellery, lift it. Sight misleads, but gravity remains constant. A solid {metal_1} cuff should pull downward in your palm. If it feels hollow, leave it on the shelf. Let the substantial heft of genuine metal provide sensory comfort against the skin.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish strict boundaries for the hardware you wear against your skin and the metals that hold your garments together.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select solid, cool stones like {stone_1} and {stone_2} to ground your wardrobe. Pick the piece up from the velvet display to feel its true burden in your palm. Cameras and mirrors lie, but physical mass is undeniable. Let your hands verify the heft before you purchase. Seat these dense stones exclusively in brushed metal settings. High-shine polished silver cuts too sharply against muted fabric and breaks the finish. Skip the mirrored chrome and insist on matt textures to build consistency. This deliberate pairing delivers crisp separation between your clothing and your hardware without relying on jarring light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your wardrobe with dense stones and brushed metals.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Pick up that {metal_1} cuff or {stone_1} pendant. Close your eyes and gauge its mass in your palm. Allow this tactile feedback to serve as your absolute guide. Next, examine the finish. Highly reflective metal acts like a mirror, catching sharp fragments of light that disrupt your clothing. It ruins the sensory comfort you built with your fabrics. Instead, select brushed, frosted, or matt surfaces. A low-sheen, cool {metal_1} creates crisp separation against your textiles without fighting them.",
      "sectionIntro": "Weigh every piece of hardware in your hand before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Secure a clean line of crisp separation. Sink into absolute sensory comfort. Only then do you introduce one clever contrast through an accessory. Restrict your strategy to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with handbags. Demand thick full-grain leather finished with cool, brushed matt hardware. Assess the material yourself using the thumb test. Press firmly into the surface of the hide. The leather must yield into deep, rolling waves. It must never crack into tiny, brittle lines. Trust your fingers over a mirror. A superficial glaze easily fools the eye. Genuine density proves its worth in your grip.",
      "sectionIntro": "Deploy accessories as functional tools to calibrate your outfit, never as mere decoration.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Focus entirely on scarves in fine wool or silk. Demand a strictly matt finish. Avoid any slippery sheen. When evaluating a piece, put it through the drop test. Gather the fabric in your fist and release it onto a hard surface. Watch how it settles. You want a heavy, liquid collapse rather than a hollow, stiff crumple. Trust this weight to deliver true sensory comfort. Layer a deep teal scarf over a pale, cool base to build crisp separation. Keep your knots minimal and tight to the neck.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your scarves by how they fall, not just how they look.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select belts cut from medium full-grain leather and finish them with a matt buckle. This grounds the waist securely. Layer in keepsake jewellery strictly cast in aged silver or oxidised metals. These cool tones sit quietly against your skin. Ensure absolute sensory comfort when choosing rings or cuffs. Pick up the metal and trust your hands. If the piece feels sharp or hollow, put it back. Finish with the sweep test. Run your palm down your front. If a heavy silver pendant or an overly thick belt loop catches your fingers and creates a ridge in the fabric, take the piece off. Every item must lie flat and move smoothly with your frame.",
      "sectionIntro": "Your final check determines if your accessories support your physical frame or fight against it.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored coats take their pattern from tight, structural weaves. Fluid silk trousers pull theirs from the physical shadow of the drape. Keep all patterns low-contrast and tonal. Look for {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Skip {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. Test any patterned cloth with your hands. Close your eyes and run your fingers over the fabric. If it feels like touching a cool, moving shadow, trust it. This physical instinct guarantees sensory comfort. When combining patterns, demand crisp separation in scale. Let the cloth do the work.",
      "sectionIntro": "Pattern serves structure and texture, never distraction.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Look at {recommended_pattern_1} in low evening light. Dim surroundings reveal the truth of a print. In shadows, harsh lines fail. You want the design to settle into a cool, shifting blur. Pick the shirt up and evaluate the weave. The pattern must never shout. Instead, it should dissolve into a matt, muted wash that prioritises sensory comfort above visual noise. Keep the hem and cuffs contained to ensure crisp separation from your solid trousers. Trust your hands when examining the cloth. If the print feels stiff or looks sharp without bright light, leave it on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the dusk test to measure how a pattern behaves when the light fades.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_gemini__moon_leo__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "crisp separation + athletic space + one clever contrast",
    "closing": "Rely on your hands to evaluate the tension of every garment to secure a daily uniform defined by crisp separation + athletic space + one clever contrast.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your physical instinct for breath and momentum. Build your wardrobe modularly and shift pieces fast as your daily environment demands. Apply the combination test before you commit to any new garment. Pick up the piece and gauge its mechanical reach. Ask yourself if it can transition from an active morning commute directly into a local group project, pairing instantly with the trousers and jackets you already rely on. If it locks you into a single rigid look, leave it on the rail. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight and adaptability do not.\n\nAnchor your daily decisions in your core formula: crisp separation + athletic space + one clever contrast. Picture a lightweight technical windbreaker layered over a structured cotton shirt, finished with tailored track trousers cut wide enough for a full stride. The separation is clean. The space allows complete physical freedom. The contrast arrives by mixing a perfectly matt outer shell with a smooth, cool base layer underneath. Mix your finishes freely and combine different hardware across your watch and zips without restriction. Let the garments do the work.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise these functional rules as your baseline operating system before you acquire another garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the combination test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your materials must establish crisp separation between layers while maintaining athletic space around your joints. Build clean boundaries using {texture_good_1} for shirting. Add {texture_good_2} for base layers that hold sharp lines against the body. Anchor the lower half with {texture_good_3} for trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing. Finish with {texture_good_4} for mobile outerwear that blocks wind. When assessing a new garment, perform the snap test. Pull the fabric across your knuckles and release it. It must flick back with a rigid tension that guarantees structural integrity. Rely on this tactile response over a mirror image. Tension reveals reality. Ground your selections in a cool palette, using one clever contrast in a matt or gloss finish to break the surface. Source from the inventory below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the exact textiles that build your silhouette and support your daily movement.",
      "rankedItems": [
