    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Execute the pinch evaluation to verify a fabric can hold a strict boundary. Grip the sleeve, pull it away from your arm, and let go. You demand materials that rebound sharply. If the weave oozes back into place or hangs lifelessly, leave it. Avoid {texture_bad_1}. It clings to the body and traps heat rather than maintaining a cool environment. Grab a fistful of {texture_bad_2}. If the fibres feel limp or crush into a flat, matt mess, drop the hanger. {texture_bad_3} presents the exact same flaw, pooling heavily around the ankles instead of holding structural distance. Rely on your bare hands to detect anything spongy, stifling, or weak. Your touch tells the absolute truth when a photograph deceives you.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject weak materials on contact.",
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Build your base with {texture_good_1} to establish crisp edges. You require textiles that hold their shape while providing physical room. Check the structural integrity by tugging the hem away from your body and releasing it. The cloth must spring back instantly. Sluggish weaves fail this physical check. Trust your fingers to identify resilient, matt materials. Keep the temperature cool. Pair a rigid outer shell with a flexible inner layer to secure your core formula.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to pair your textiles by feeling their resistance.",
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Keep your temperature strictly cool. Build your daily foundation using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Employ {core_colour_4} when you need a structural dark base. Rely on {core_colour_3} as your strict white alternative. Treat your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly to break up heavy blocks. This creates the crisp separation required by your approach. Leave Mustard, Rust, and Warm olive green on the rack. They clash with your undertone. Once the base is locked, inject {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} to guarantee athletic space. Trust your own senses when combining these tones. The trap is falling into a lifeless monochrome uniform that feels stagnant by noon. Fix this immediately by introducing a stark white poplin collar, a heavy silver structural ring, or a vivid geometric trainer for that one clever contrast.",
