    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Sharp edges lead your workday. Build the foundation from heavy wool twill trousers. Let dark drama support the cut. Pair the wool with a warm deep bronze silk blouse. Demand the same uncompromising standard for a Tuesday desk shift as you do for a board presentation. Rely on the physical resistance of the cloth to gauge its density. Flimsy fabrics betray a tailored cut, so reject lightweight synthetics instantly. Pick up a structured leather briefcase and check the rigid handle. Introduce dual-metal accents through stacked silver and gold rings. Step into highly polished patent leather brogues.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your weekday appointments as a testing ground for heavy cloth and strict cuts.",
      "tests": [
        "walking the dog deserves the same standard as a meeting (Moss)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close quarters, let dark drama lead. Low light requires heavy silk satin in deep bronze to capture and reflect illumination. Pick garments that test rigid in your hands. Rely purely on the textile's pushback against your grip. If a fabric yields effortlessly, leave it in the drawer. Uphold your exact structural standards during a private evening at home just as you would for a formal dinner. Maintain sharp edges behind closed doors. A warm golden camel poplin shirt must retain its architecture under candlelight. Finish with polished dual-metal jewellery, placing gold and rhodium chains flat on the sternum.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the strict technical demands of low-light dressing.",
      "tests": [
        "walking the dog deserves the same standard as a meeting (Moss)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Buying stamps at the post office demands uncompromising crisp cotton poplin. Never drop your standards for mundane errands. Evaluate a garment by squeezing the shoulder seam. Heavy silk satin provides an undeniable heft that store mirrors often fail to communicate. Your baseline is always dark drama + sharp edges + one molten flash. Apply this strict rule to a morning coffee run. Choose precise wool twill trousers in deep bronze. Step into a black patent leather boot. Fasten a polished solid gold collar. Let an early December frost be met with an aggressively structured silhouette. Keep the entire palette warm. A golden camel coat delivers the required bold expression without compromise.",
      "sectionIntro": "Enforce your aesthetic rules just as strictly on a Tuesday morning as you do on a Friday night.",
      "tests": [
        "walking the dog deserves the same standard as a meeting (Moss)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Divide your hardware into two separate categories. Build your personal jewellery collection in warm {personal_metal_1} and {personal_metal_2}. For the structural components built into your clothes, look for heavy zips and precise buckles in {structural_metal_1} or {structural_metal_2}. Always test a piece before committing. Pick the item up and assess the heft in your palm. A photograph can be manipulated, but true gravitational pull proves a metal's worth. You require serious mass to anchor your dark drama. Every metallic surface must be brilliantly polished. Reject anything hammered, aged, or oxidised. These {excluded_finish} textures look exhausted against your sharp edges. You must stay strictly in high-shine, warm metal that acts as a beacon in sunlight.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the physical rules for the hardware that anchors your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Assess your hardware by its sheer density. Look for {stone_1} and {stone_2} with a hard, brilliant clarity. Pick the piece up in your hands. The optical illusion of a well-cut glass imitation shatters once you hold a genuine mineral. A heavy stone grounds the arrangement. House these stones in strictly polished warm metal. Tarnished or intentionally distressed finishes dilute your exactness and fail to hold their precision. Avoid them entirely. You require a high-gloss finish that catches the light from across the street. The pure reflection of gleaming settings against dense {stone_1} delivers the dark drama and sharp edges you require.",
      "sectionIntro": "Demand hard clarity and absolute density from every stone before you commit to wearing it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the {metal_1} off the tray. Judge a chain purely by its downward drag. Trust your hands to detect hollow links. If the item feels airy, put it back. You need dense materials to ground your dark drama. Steer clear of matt or brushed treatments. They read as dirty and blunt your sharp edges. Require a high-gloss finish in a warm tone that throws glare down the block.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use your hands to test every piece of hardware before it touches your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You have constructed the dark drama. You have carved the sharp edges. Now, complete the structure with one molten flash. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Subject every item to the reflector check. Ask yourself if the object glares back like a studio mirror under a theatrical beam. Begin with statement jewellery. Look for a polished metal collar featuring a severe, brilliant gleam. Trust your bare hands to judge its true worth. Dismiss the showroom presentation and evaluate the solid mass. Pick the piece up and feel the heavy, warm drag of dense metal against your palm.",
      "sectionIntro": "Deploy your accessories as the uncompromising final variable that anchors your entire silhouette.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Statement jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "polished metal collar, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the spotlight test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Pick up your footwear and inspect the surface. Maintain sharp edges down to the floor with rigid patent leather. Rely on the material's stiffness as your physical guide. Do not trust a flawless photograph. Feel for an unyielding construction that holds its shape entirely when empty. Apply the spotlight test to every pair. Hold the shoe under a single bare bulb. If the exterior absorbs the beam or scatters the reflection, put it down. You require a patent gloss so slick it throws back a hard, solid circle of illumination. This mirrored armour cuts through visual clutter. Deploy dark drama at the base of your outfit, anchoring a warm palette with a heavy, structured boot or an architectural heel.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your foundational pieces by their structural integrity and reflective finish.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "patent leather, patent gloss"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the spotlight test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Treat eyewear as strict architecture. Seek out thick acetate frames in warm amber or deep tortoiseshell. Ensure the surface holds an intensely polished finish. Run your thumb over the corners and look for sharp edges. Check the rigidity with your grip. Flimsy plastic bends under pressure, but dense acetate confirms structural integrity. Before walking out the door, execute a focal check. Stand before a mirror and identify the singular striking element. If a heavy frame and a chunky necklace are fighting for control, remove the piece doing too much. True dark drama requires absolute focus.",
      "sectionIntro": "This final check separates precision from excess.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "acetate frame, high shine"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the spotlight test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Build dark drama through high-contrast graphic prints. Divide your approach between structure and drape. Look for tailored coats carrying {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. Let fluid shirts take {recommended_pattern_3}. Always apply the distance rule. Step backward across the room to verify the geometry. If the motif blurs into a muddy wash instead of retaining sharp edges, drop the hanger. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. They drag a warm presentation into indistinct noise. Demand absolute clarity.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject your patterns to the same strict scrutiny as your tailoring.",
      "tests": [
        "the ten foot rule (stay crisp, loud, and legible from across the room)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Subject every {recommended_pattern_1} to the ten-pace test. Hang the piece against a plain wall, step back ten paces, and evaluate the graphic impact. A polished motif must maintain strict separation between its warm hues at this range. If the print collapses into a hazy gradient, leave it behind. Authentic dark drama requires uncompromising legibility from across a large space. Trust this hard boundary to filter out weak design. When a garment proves it can retain clean, sharp edges from a distance, buy it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this strict distance check to ensure your prints never dissolve into visual noise.",
      "tests": [
        "the ten foot rule (stay crisp, loud, and legible from across the room)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_leo__moon_gemini__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "dark drama + light movement + one molten flash",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on dark drama + light movement + one molten flash.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your sensory compass here is physical adaptability. Build your wardrobe through slow accumulation. Deploy those pieces rapidly according to the shifting rhythm of your schedule. Trust your hands when assessing a garment. If the material feels stiff and unyielding, leave it on the rail. Seek out a polished, warm finish in everything you touch. The surface must carry a faint gleam rather than a flat matt absorption. Look for construction that responds immediately to a change in posture. A balanced cut allows you to pivot from rigid constraints to total physical freedom in a single motion.\n\nYour exact mechanical formula is dark drama + light movement + one molten flash. Picture a heavy, floor-length coat layered over a fluid, weightless dress, anchored at the collarbone by a single piece of reflective jewellery. Apply the flight test to every outfit before you step outside. Ask yourself if you could sprint through an airport terminal in these garments without losing your shape. If the hem tangles around your ankles or the sleeves restrict your reach, take it off immediately. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is the mechanical foundation of your wardrobe, the strict physical criteria you must demand from every garment before it touches your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Seek out polished fabrics that anchor your dark drama and enable light movement. When you handle a garment in a shop, apply the drop check. Lift the hem, release it, and watch how it falls to the floor. If it drops like a dead weight, walk away. If it drifts and settles in warm, undulating folds, buy it. Rely on the fabric's behaviour in mid-air to guide you. Choose {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Rely on {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Select {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Finish with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. Memorise the hierarchy below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject your fabrics to strict physical tests before letting them touch your skin.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed alpaca",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "enveloping winter coats and oversized cardigans"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fluid modal jersey",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers that follow the body without ever gripping it"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed cotton flannel",
          "role": "rank 7",
