        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Throw a piece of {texture_bad_3} onto a flat surface. Watch the drop. A heavy cloth sinks straight down. A weak weave catches the air and hovers. Reject {texture_bad_1} on sight. Squeeze the sleeve in your fist. It crunches into sharp ridges and refuses to fall flat. This stiffness destroys the dark drama you require. Rub a fold of {texture_bad_2} between your fingers. If it drags or sparks with static, drop it. You build your look around one molten flash from warm metal, not an accidental electric charge. Trust your touch. A bad fabric reveals its cheapness instantly.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject failure before a piece ever reaches your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Your signature pairing lives where {sweet_spot_keyword_1} meets {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Contrast them to anchor your dark drama. Evaluate the material by its physical gravity alone. Toss a piece of {texture_good_1} slightly upward. Watch how it catches the air. It must drift down with a slow, deliberate grace. If it drops heavily to the floor, leave it on the rack. Layer these opposing weights to build a warm, polished surface.",
      "sectionIntro": "Find your structural anchors by testing how different weaves interact in your hands.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Keep your palette strictly warm. Build the foundation of your wardrobe from {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Rely on {core_colour_3} to provide the dark drama that gives an outfit its definition. Add {core_colour_4} to ground the mix. Introduce {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} as deliberate strikes of colour. Deploy your relief tone sparingly, using it only to give the eye a resting place between heavier shades. Leave stark optic white, harsh neon, and icy pastel on the rack. They do not serve you. Recognise the hard shell trap. When life speeds up, you might find yourself reaching for armour, technical jackets, and stiff utility layers. Catch this reflex early. Swap the shell for a brushed cotton layer that moves just as fast and holds your shape besides. Rely on your hands to gauge the garment before you put it on. If the material feels rigid, reject it. Prioritise pliable textiles like washed silk to ensure the light movement necessary for a balanced cut. Complete the combination with a solid silver or bronze cuff to break up an entirely matt finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your colours by learning exactly which role each shade plays in your wardrobe.",
      "rankedItems": [
