          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select stones that hold a deep, warm lustre to sustain dark drama. Reach for {stone_1} and {stone_2}. Lift the piece to test its density. A faceted cut tricks the eye, but pure density confirms its value. Examine the mass directly in your palm. These dense stones require a flawless setting to capture true light movement. Steer clear of beaten copper, tarnished brass, and purposely aged alloys. Such distressed finishes create chaotic static against your focused, modern baseline. Demand absolute reflection instead. Restrict your hardware entirely to high-gloss platinum, white gold, polished silver, and mirror chrome.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every stone and metal setting by its sheer physical weight and uncompromising surface clarity.",
      "tests": [
