    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Divide your pattern strategy by garment structure. Tailored coats and trousers take their visual interest from the weave itself. Fluid pieces take their markings from the dye. Scale your contrast to adapt to the room. Keep the shades tonal for routine days, or push the contrast higher when the context requires strict focus. Rely on {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} to build your structured layers. Inject light movement through {recommended_pattern_3} in your softer silks. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. They disrupt your polished finish. Test every print by walking past a mirror. This is the passing test. The motif must blur into a soft, pleasant, warm texture in motion. If the shapes remain rigid, leave the piece behind. Trust your physical reaction to the fabric in stride.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your eye to read pattern as a function of structure and motion.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the Ten-Pace Test before you buy any {recommended_pattern_1}. Hang the garment across the room. Step back ten paces and squint slightly to blur your vision. Ask a friend to swing the fabric or catch the edge yourself to generate light movement. Watch how the print behaves in the air. A successful design dissolves entirely. It must read as a soft, pleasant texture melting into a warm, polished surface. If the motif remains rigid and fights for focus from across the floor, leave it on the hanger. Trust your visual instincts over the label.",
      "sectionIntro": "Run the Ten-Pace Test to ensure a print supports your structure rather than breaking it.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_leo__moon_pisces__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "quiet grandeur + blurred edges + one molten flash",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on quiet grandeur + blurred edges + one molten flash.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Anchor your choices in physical weight and thermal warmth. Pick up a garment and assess its density in your hand. If the weave feels flimsy or synthetic, drop it immediately. Your guiding equation is quiet grandeur + blurred edges + one molten flash. Build this physical reality by pairing a heavy, draped overcoat over a completely soft, unstructured knit, then adding a single dense piece of polished hardware at the collar. This creates a solid anchor point of light against the yielding fabric.\n\nConstruct your wardrobe slowly and deliberately. Sourcing dense, warm materials takes time, so do not rush to fill gaps with inferior alternatives. You must learn to rely on immediate, visceral reactions when assessing a new garment. Pick it up and wait for the physical verdict. If your stomach tightens, or if the cloth feels even slightly hollow in your hands, leave it on the rail and walk out of the shop. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise these structural principles before you purchase another garment.",
      "tests": [
        "trust your gut and walk away"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Seek materials that create quiet grandeur through soft accumulation. Your wardrobe demands warm fibres. Run the melt test on every new garment. Crush the material in your fist. If it springs back stiffly, leave it. It must melt into your palm. Use your grip to gauge quality. Visuals deceive, but mass reveals reality. Rely on {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Layer {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Select {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Anchor silhouettes with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. Constructing blurred edges prepares the ground for one molten flash. Memorise the hierarchy below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to isolate the fibres that construct your foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed alpaca",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "enveloping winter coats and oversized cardigans"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fluid modal jersey",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers that follow the body without ever gripping it"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed cotton flannel",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "shirts and loungewear that feel like a remembered embrace"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "The melt test is your baseline. Clench the fabric in your fist. If it holds sharp creases or fights back, it fails. {texture_bad_1} often commits this crime. It builds stiff cages instead of yielding to your shape. Reject {texture_bad_2} the moment it feels crisp against your neck or refuses to hold a warm drape. Avoid {texture_bad_3} when it carries a rigid, reflective seal instead of a soft, matt finish. These rigid textiles disrupt your quiet grandeur. They refuse to soften. You require textiles that collapse and pool. Let the piece hang over your bare arm. If it does not immediately relax and melt into your skin, leave it on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Identify and eliminate any fabric that builds a cage instead of following your form.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Seek out the exact intersection of {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Start every combination with {texture_good_1}. When you evaluate a new piece, drape it over your bare arm. It must soften and surrender to your body heat, pooling heavily rather than holding its own rigid shape. If it fights your movement, leave it on the hanger. This heavy, yielding drape establishes your quiet grandeur. Pair these warm, matt surfaces with just enough polish to break the visual silence.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the physical tension between your most reliable surfaces.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette runs entirely warm. Trust your eye on this rule. Build your foundation using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Assign {core_colour_3} to your structured coats and trousers. Treat {core_colour_4} as your earthy neutral base. Introduce {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as a single deliberate accent to establish quiet grandeur. Deploy your soft note sparingly near the face to ease the contrast of a sharp collar. Reject stark optic white, harsh neon, and icy pastel immediately. Defaulting to an unbroken block of dark garments looks like you stopped getting dressed halfway to the door. Break up that heavy mass by adding a jumper in {core_colour_1}, a scarf in {accent_colour_1}, or a thick belt in {core_colour_2}.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your colours to build a working foundation that serves you without hesitation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bitter chocolate",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Dark mahogany",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Blackened indigo",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep forest green",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Burnt umber",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Washed black",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Burnt amber",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rich cognac",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Misty taupe",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "head-to-toe black reads like you gave up on the way out the door",
          "fix": "break it up with a camel layer, a deep wine scarf, or a rich cognac belt"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, let quiet grandeur lead your decisions. Build the foundation from heavy silk crepe in warm tones of bitter chocolate. Support this draped base by keeping the perimeters soft. Avoid rigid tailoring. Instead, look for boiled wool garments that pool slightly at the wrist. Cut through the dark mahogany fabric with a single strike of yellow gold. Reach for an unpolished brass cuff or a bright gold ring. Rely entirely on your hands to judge the metal. Mirrors deceive. Density always tells the truth. If the metal lacks density, leave it on the tray. A quick dash for a morning espresso demands the exact same washed silk as a vital client pitch.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your working hours as the ultimate testing ground for your aesthetic foundation.",
      "tests": [
        "walking the dog deserves the same standard as a meeting (Moss)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In intimate, low-light settings, let blurred edges lead. Rely on the heavy drape of washed silk or cloud-soft lambswool in deep, warm tones like dark mahogany and bitter chocolate. Avoid stiff construction. Handle the garment to measure its heft. If it feels rigid, put it back. Trust your hands. Pouring a glass of water in your kitchen at midnight demands the exact same standard as a private dinner. Choose heavy silk crepe that absorbs shadows rather than reflects them. Keep the silhouette soft.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the proportions required for low light and close proximity.",
      "tests": [
        "walking the dog deserves the same standard as a meeting (Moss)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Buying paracetamol at the corner chemist does not excuse a drop in quality. Taking the terrier out in the rain requires the same strict execution you apply to a closed-door board meeting. Ensure every layer stays warm against the skin. Reach for washed silk in bitter chocolate or a dense cut of cloud-soft lambswool dyed dark mahogany. Lift the wool to evaluate the drape. If the piece feels thin or stiff, drop it. Never suspend your rules for convenience. Always anchor your choices in quiet grandeur + blurred edges + one molten flash.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat mundane routines as a strict testing ground for your standards.",
      "tests": [
        "walking the dog deserves the same standard as a meeting (Moss)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your hardware must run warm. Build your collection around {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Seek out quiet grandeur in your jewellery. Pair the blurred edges of your clothing with mixed hardware finishes. High-gloss silver creates a sharp, distracting glare against soft {core_colour_2} textiles. Stick to matt and brushed textures to maintain strict visual cohesion. Mix these muted finishes freely, but entirely avoid {excluded_finish}. Always lift a chain or buckle before you buy it. Sight deceives, but absolute mass never lies. If a fastening feels light, put it back. Keep your metals heavy to secure the look.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select metals that melt into your textiles rather than fighting them.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select your stones by their internal depth rather than surface glare. Look for {stone_1} and {stone_2} that hold a warm, slow light. Avoid anything that flashes or sparkles aggressively. Highly polished, mirror-like settings create jarring, hard lines against soft fibres. Fix this by insisting on matt or brushed metal mounts to maintain those blurred edges. Trust your hands to measure quality. Lift the jewellery before you evaluate it in a mirror. Appearances mislead. Density sets the standard. You need dense, substantial pieces that ground your outfit through sheer gravity.",
      "sectionIntro": "Choose stones for their density and quiet light, treating hardware as a grounding weight rather than a mere decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the {metal_1} chain from the counter and weigh it in your palm. Sight tricks the eye. Gravity provides the definitive answer. Evaluate density before you buy. A hollow cast ruins the effect of quiet grandeur. Highly reflective silver casts a harsh glare against warm garments dyed in {core_colour_1}. That intense shine disrupts your palette. Fix this by selecting matt or lightly brushed hardware instead. A softer surface creates blurred edges against your collarbone and maintains the cohesive temperature of your wardrobe.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess every piece of hardware by testing its raw physical density.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your accessories exist to provide that crucial one molten flash. They deliberately interrupt your base of quiet grandeur and bring finality to your blurred edges. Restrict your additions to a maximum of one or two strong pieces per look. Stand before the glass and strip away the secondary ring or the competing chain before you step outside. A solitary metallic element commands far more focus than a crowded arrangement. Apply this strict discipline to handbags. Demand full-grain leather construction. Look for a warm, entirely matt body disrupted by a single polished flash. Lift the item by its top strap. Measure the raw heft of the skin. A correct choice relies on solid weight rather than a rigid cardboard lining to dictate its structure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Curate your additions ruthlessly to serve their specific structural function.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, matt body with one polished flash"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Handle your scarves as pure texture. Look for silk with a completely matt finish. The surface must absorb light rather than reflect it. Drape a bitter chocolate or dark mahogany square around your neck. If the material sits stiffly, drop it. You require absolute fluidity to build those blurred edges. Apply the subtraction rule before stepping outside. If a thick gold chain already sits at your collar, remove the silk. One weighty element does the work. Multiple pieces cancel each other out. Always keep the warm tones directly against your skin.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your accessories as physical tools of subtraction and focus.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select keepsake jewellery to establish quiet grandeur. Look for solid, aged brass featuring a molten gold accent. Mix your finishes deliberately. Combine a matt brass cuff with a polished gold ring. Trust your hands to verify the quality. Weigh the metals. If an item lacks gravity, reject it. Keep the overall temperature decidedly warm. Before leaving, execute the subtraction test. Look at your reflection and take off the piece doing too much work. One heavy metal element is enough.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply rigorous physical discipline to your final layer of adornment.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged brass with a molten gold accent, mixed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "To build quiet grandeur, insist on low-contrast tonal variations over stark graphics. Let your tailored pieces pull their pattern directly from the loom, relying on the structural depth of {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2}. Fluid garments require an equally restrained approach. They should feature subtle dye shifts rather than stamped prints. Apply a simple visual test. Step back from the mirror and soften your focus. A successful pattern will blur into texture and disappear into the warm palette of the fabric. If the motif remains sharp and highly visible, it destroys your required blurred edges. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. These read as flat interruptions on the surface of the cloth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every print through the lens of woven depth and structural shadow.",
      "tests": [
        "step back and soften focus (blur into texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the soft focus test. Hang any {recommended_pattern_1} garment on a door and take five deliberate steps back. Relax your eyes until the room goes slightly out of focus. The print must dissolve entirely into a warm surface texture. If the individual shapes remain sharp and distinct, walk away. You require blurred edges to guarantee genuine quiet grandeur. Trust this visual reaction above all else. If the design forces your eye to read separate elements, it fails.",
      "sectionIntro": "Execute this distance test to ensure your prints dissolve perfectly into pure texture.",
      "tests": [
        "step back and soften focus (blur into texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_libra__moon_aquarius__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "balanced proportions + mobile layers + one refined touch",
    "closing": "Trust your tactile instincts to calibrate your wardrobe for balanced proportions + mobile layers + one refined touch.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your physical instinct is adaptability. When you pick up a garment, test its mobility. Pull the fabric between your hands to check the give. If it restricts your shoulders or binds at the waist, put it down. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not. Your wardrobe is not a static archive. Build it slowly, deploy it fast, and let your daily combinations drift by your immediate mood. Rely on cool tones to ground your choices, allowing mixed metals and matt finishes to sit harmoniously together.\n\nYour dressing rhythm relies on a simple equation. Memorise this formula: balanced proportions + mobile layers + one refined touch. Picture a pair of straight-leg wool trousers paired with an open silk shirt over a fine cotton vest, finished with a single silver signet ring. This works because every element gives you room to breathe and shift. Before you buy anything new, apply the seam test. Run your thumb along the interior shoulder seam. If the thread scratches or feels bulky against your skin, the garment fails. True quality rests silently against your collarbone.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master these physical baselines to evaluate garments without second-guessing yourself.",
      "tests": [
        "the seam test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build mobile layers with fabrics that perform. Start with {texture_good_1} for shirting that holds clean boundaries, worn over {texture_good_2} to keep sharp lines close to the body. Ground your balanced proportions with {texture_good_3} for trousers that drop cleanly and resist creasing. Finish with {texture_good_4} for outerwear that blocks wind but weighs nothing. Always run the recovery test. Crush a fistful of the fabric tightly for five seconds and let go. If it stays crushed, leave it on the rail. You need materials that snap back to a cool, flat surface instantly. Here is your hierarchy of reliable materials.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify the fabrics that give your clothes structural memory and constant movement.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the recovery test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Avoid {texture_bad_1} when it feels brittle between your fingers. Scrunch a sleeve and release it. If the creases refuse to drop out instantly, the material will distort your silhouette within an hour. Leave {texture_bad_2} on the hanger if it drags or catches on rough skin. Your styling demands one refined touch. Cheap textiles sabotage that goal immediately. Inspect {texture_bad_3} for a slippery, sweating finish against your neck. If it repels air and traps heat, walk away.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify poor materials by how they fail in your hands.",
      "tests": [
        "the recovery test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to anchor your mobile layers. This pairing provides structure without rigidness. Add {texture_good_1} for a cool contrast. Test the material in your grip. Twist a section of the textile tightly and let go. If the wrinkles remain stamped in place, drop the garment. You require resilient elements to map out your proportions accurately. Listen to the tactile feedback of a textile snapping back into shape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your wardrobe with a reliable tactile pairing.",
      "tests": [
        "the recovery test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your temperature is strictly cool. Build the base using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Rely on {core_colour_3} as your true white substitute. Keep {core_colour_4} as your structural dark neutral. Bring in {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} when you need a single deliberate accent. Deploy your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly. Pass over mustard, rust, and warm olive green entirely. Watch out for the beige-out. Stacking pale values leaves an outfit looking unfinished rather than minimal. Rescue it by grounding the look with your {core_colour_4} anchor piece or your {accent_colour_1} detail. Let a sudden fabric change, like worsted wool paired with crisp cotton poplin, restore the depth. Apply your formula of balanced proportions and mobile layers. Finish with one refined touch.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish a strict foundation of cool tones to create a wardrobe you can assemble without thinking.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Stark navy",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
