    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories deliver that one refined touch to your outfits. They secure the balanced proportions and anchor the mobile layers you build your wardrobe upon. Limit yourself to one or two deliberate pieces per look. Begin with silk scarves. Seek out a crepe de chine square with a strictly matt surface. Put it through the function test before leaving the house. Tie the knot tightly against a worsted wool collar and check if it holds its shape when you look over your shoulder. If the fabric slips or requires constant readjustment, take it off. The accessory must serve a physical purpose, acting as a functional anchor rather than a purely decorative afterthought. Stick to cool tones like stark navy and icy grey.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply strict mechanical standards to every accessory you add.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Build your fine jewellery collection with thin bands of mixed gold and silver. Pair polished rims with matt brushed surfaces. Let these contrasting metals rest against a cool icy grey sleeve. Apply the function test before you buy. Drag the chain or ring across worsted wool. If the metal catches the yarn or restricts movement through mobile layers, drop it immediately. Mirrors reflect a static image. The dense, cold reality of solid metal resting against your skin provides immediate feedback. Rely on this physical sensation above any visual styling. Select items that maintain balanced proportions without needing constant adjustment.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess your metalwork through physical touch and strict functionality.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin mixed gold and silver, mixed polished and brushed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select a small structured bag in kid suede or smooth leather to secure your essentials. Pick a top-handle silhouette finished with fine mixed hardware. Set the piece against stark navy or icy grey worsted wool to verify the cool tones integrate seamlessly. Before you commit, test its pure physical function. Load the bag with your daily items, pick it up by the handle, and carry it for a few paces. Assess how it behaves alongside mobile layers. If the clasp sticks, the strap slips, or the structure collapses and ruins the balanced proportions of the silhouette, reject it. If the bag requires constant adjustment to execute its basic job, leave it on the table.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply a strict practical exit test to your carried accessories to finalise the look.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede or smooth leather top-handle, fine mixed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the function test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Maintain balanced proportions by splitting your motifs according to the cut. Demand {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} for structured tailoring. Reserve {recommended_pattern_3} and {recommended_pattern_4} for shirts and flowing shapes. Calibrate your contrast to suit the context. Scale up the graphic geometry for sharp environments. Soften the lines into low-contrast weaves for relaxed situations. Evaluate every print by looking at the cloth from a metre and a half away across a table. It must read as a sharp texture rather than a buzzing distraction. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. Leave {avoid_pattern_2} on the rack. Keep the dyes grounded in a strictly cool palette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the geometry of your garments before they scramble your structure.",
      "tests": [
        "the desk test (read as clean texture at arm's length and a half)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Test a new pattern by draping the garment over a chair and observing the boundaries of the motif. At a distance, {recommended_pattern_1} must blur into a clean texture. Step back another pace and watch how the edges soften. If the print remains sharp and legible from across the room, leave it on the rail. You need patterns that integrate seamlessly into mobile layers rather than fighting for attention. Keep your temperature cool and let the scale of the motif act as a structural element. Use this assessment to preserve balanced proportions across your overall silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the desk test to measure the scale and clarity of any print.",
      "tests": [
        "the desk test (read as clean texture at arm's length and a half)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_libra__moon_cancer__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "balanced proportions + hidden depth + one refined touch",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on balanced proportions + hidden depth + one refined touch.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your compass is the sensation of cool, dense fluid against the skin. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate guide. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. When you construct a wardrobe, build slowly. Sift through racks with your hands, searching for tightly woven cloths that pour rather than grip. Apply the melt test. If a garment sits stiffly as a separate structure over your frame rather than dissolving into a single seamless silhouette, put it back. You want pieces that integrate with your body immediately. Once you assemble these foundations, deploy fast. You reach for your garments and put them on without a second thought.\n\nThe target is always balanced proportions + hidden depth + one refined touch. Picture a fluid, high-waisted worsted trouser falling in a straight column to an unlined leather loafer. The balanced proportions come from a precisely tailored hem meeting a flat vamp. The hidden depth is the heavy silk pocket lining you feel but nobody sees. The one refined touch is a single piece of dense, matt hardware resting against your wrist. Look for woven fabrics that absorb light rather than reflecting it. This approach strips away distraction. You dress with precision, relying on immaculate cut and substantial cloth instead of unnecessary volume.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise these core principles. They are the structural foundation of your wardrobe, the absolute rules you will use to filter out noise.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Building a quiet, cool-toned wardrobe relies on materials that carry hidden depth. Squeeze every garment you consider. Gather the fabric in your fist and hold it tightly for three seconds. If it retains sharp wrinkles or fights your grip, drop it. The cloth must collapse softly into a heavy, matt puddle in your palm. Demand {texture_good_1} for winter layers that compress and bounce back seamlessly. Choose {texture_good_2} for shoes and belts that mould to your stride and patinate over time. Build balanced proportions using {texture_good_3} for tailored coats that hold clean lines for years. Finally, introduce one refined touch with {texture_good_4} for linings that offer immediate, fluid movement. Prioritise the materials ranked below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the tactile foundation of your style by filtering for these specific materials.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
        {
          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Pull a stray thread from {texture_bad_1} and touch a match to it. If the fibre shrivels into a hard plastic bead rather than crumbling to ash, walk away. Synthetics suffocate the skin and destroy the cool, muted finish your pieces require. Run your palm across {texture_bad_2}. If the surface feels slick, traps heat, or squeaks under pressure, leave it on the rail. You require hidden depth in your materials, never a flat artificial sheen. Cheap blends reflect light harshly and drape poorly against the body. Rely on your fingers to evaluate the truth of a weave. If a piece feels rigid, greasy, or thin, it will fail you in motion.",
      "sectionIntro": "Eliminate compromises by testing materials rigorously before they ever touch your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "To hit your textural sweet spot, pair {texture_good_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Evaluate the synergy by layering them together. A worthy combination yields entirely, refusing to hold a stiff crease where the fabrics meet. Reject any cloth that stands rigid on the hanger. You require textiles that provide hidden depth through their drape. Combine a matt, cool-toned trouser with a soft shirt. The contrast between a muted, light-absorbing surface and a pliant finish does the heavy lifting. Close your eyes and gauge the combined weight in your hands. If the ensemble feels brittle or crisp, walk away.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your wardrobe strictly through touch.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Assemble your colours like a toolkit for building proportions. Anchor your wardrobe in {core_colour_1}, {core_colour_2}, and {core_colour_3}. Use {core_colour_4} as your crisp white substitute. Keep the overall temperature strictly cool. Inject depth with a deliberate accent of {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Deploy the relief tone strictly as a soft note used sparingly. Skip hot saturated red, stark optic white, and harsh neon. Watch out for the comfort collapse. When every component yields, you simply end up wearing pyjamas. Fix this error by putting back exactly one sharp edge. Break up those yielding pieces with a structured lapel, a softly creased trouser, or a stiff leather holdall.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your palette to build intentional visual boundaries and command your visual footprint.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Inky navy",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep teal",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
