      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the sofa drift: soften every piece far enough and one day you are simply in loungewear",
          "fix": "restore exactly one line: a rolled but real lapel, a trouser with a soft crease, or a firm leather bag against all that give"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, hidden depth dictates your strategy. Let an even scale provide the structural foundation, anchored by a single sharp detail. Evaluate your tailoring with a strict standard. If sitting through a three-hour board meeting reveals a digging waistband or a restrictive shoulder, discard the item immediately. Office environments never require suffering for an aesthetic. Select a cool slate wool jacket or a charcoal cashmere rollneck. Ensure every fabric surface remains entirely matt. Let the internal construction perform the hard work. Trust your physical senses. If a seam pinches while you type, leave that garment at home.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your office environment as a strict test of structural integrity and physical ease.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close quarters and low light, hidden depth takes precedence. Build an ensemble on dark, cool tones like midnight silk or deep forest cashmere. Trust your hands to judge the cloth. Mirrors deceive, but the friction against your skin tells the truth. If a fabric binds or scratches, discard it. A private dinner does not ask for stiffness to maintain formality. Let a single matt silver ring catch the dim light against a heavy brushed wool sleeve. Avoid excessive statements. Limit your palette and let the raw materials do the work.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the intimate environment by drawing attention to tactile details rather than broad visual strokes.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Test your daily baseline. A Tuesday morning trip to the local chemist for paracetamol never suspends your standard, nor does it ask for stiff discomfort. Grab dove grey trousers and an inky navy cashmere knit. Trust your hands when pulling clothes from the wardrobe. Evaluate every item by its drape before putting it on. If a sleeve restricts your movement while you queue for a prescription, discard it. Your daily execution is simply balanced proportions + hidden depth + one refined touch. Keep the entire palette cool. Anchor the outfit with full-grain leather loafers and a matt silver watch.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your everyday routine as an exacting test of your baseline habits.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your metal strategy runs cool. Look for {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} to secure your garments. Pick the hardware up and evaluate its physical mass. The eye is easily tricked, but genuine density never lies. High-shine metal acts as a sharp, distracting glare against soft, muted fabric. A gleaming {excluded_finish} creates visual noise. Stick to brushed or matt surfaces to keep the composition grounded. Every buckle or zip must serve as a functional anchor. Aim for balanced proportions across all structural details to ensure quiet cohesion.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware by its physical density and its muted finish.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select {stone_1}, {stone_2}, or {stone_3} in cool tones to ground your aesthetic. Press the gem against your wrist to gauge its temperature. A genuine mineral stays cold against the skin long after you pick it up. Let this sheer physical reality direct your final decision. Treat your settings with the same rigorous scrutiny. A glossy, mirror-like surface creates a harsh glare that fractures a subdued wardrobe. Drop the high-shine items entirely. Anchor your choices in brushed or matt finishes to bind the elements together and maintain the essential hidden depth of your style.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your jewellery by its sheer density and subdued finish.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the {metal_1} piece and listen to it clink against a wooden table. A hollow ring signals cheap construction. You want heavy objects that sit firmly and silently against your collarbone. Avoid high-glare, mirrored surfaces. A glossy finish flashes aggressively against your subdued, cool palette. This harsh contrast disrupts your balanced proportions. Select a matt finish or a brushed texture instead. A muted surface absorbs light rather than reflecting it. This keeps the layers cohesive and grounds your garments with actual substance.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test every piece of metal for density and finish before you put it on.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories supply the one refined touch needed to complete your silhouette. They serve to anchor your balanced proportions and underscore your hidden depth. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with handbags. Look for full-grain leather finished with brushed, matt hardware. Trust your hands to evaluate the material. Pick the bag up and apply the ripple test. Press your thumb firmly into the surface. The hide must gather and radiate outward in fine, natural waves around the pressure point. This proves the skin is whole and structurally sound. Corrected or treated surfaces simply dent and remain flat. Rely on this tactile feedback to ensure every piece carries the correct structural weight.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish your accessory strategy to ensure every finishing element aligns with your core physical criteria.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Turn to scarves to master balanced proportions. Pick up a length of deep teal silk or dove grey fine wool. Avoid high-shine satin. Demand a completely matt finish that absorbs cool light. Put the fabric through a gravity test. Drape it over a bare forearm and drop your arm swiftly. The material must pool into heavy, silent folds instantly. If it holds a stiff peak or rustles, leave it on the shelf. Rely on this fluid descent over any printed label. This immediate surrender proves the weave contains genuine hidden depth. A perfectly muted, carefully secured scarf provides exactly one refined touch.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess every accessory through strict physical criteria, stripping away visual distractions.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Secure your trousers with medium full-grain leather belts featuring a simple matt buckle. Let your keepsake jewellery provide hidden depth. Choose cool, aged silver and oxidised metals that sink into the shadows. Put on your chosen pieces and run the glare test. Stand in natural daylight and observe your outfit in the mirror. If a harsh reflection or an overly polished ring sends a visual shockwave through your silhouette, remove it immediately. Every item must quietly support your balanced proportions.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your look with purposeful additions and test the entire composition before you leave.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Ground your structured tailoring in woven patterns. Fluid garments take their motif from the dye. Insist on low-contrast tonal designs to build hidden depth. Secure balanced proportions between the scale of the weave and the cut of the fabric. Seek out {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} in your cool palette. Completely reject {avoid_pattern_1}. Create a strict pass-over list. Skip anything printed on stiff synthetics, high-contrast block designs, and heavily saturated graphics. As the light drops, the design must dissolve into a cool, moving texture rather than a rigid shape. Trust your immediate sensory reaction over the hanger appeal. A printed surface distracts, but the genuine drape of the cloth provides the absolute truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Pattern introduces rhythm to your garments without breaking the strict parameters of your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Subject every print to the dusk test. Hang the garment across the room and turn down the lamps. A successful {recommended_pattern_1} will lose its sharp edges as the room dims. The shapes must dissolve into a quiet, cool shadow. If the motif remains stark in low light, leave it on the rail. You require patterns that collapse into hidden depth. They must read as a rich, unified surface from ten paces away. Evaluate the visual weight carefully. The design must respect balanced proportions, never pulling the eye out of alignment.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply a strict lighting test to ensure every print remains subdued.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    }
