    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim environments, cool tones ensure your balanced proportions lead. Visual clutter disappears in low light. A stark navy worsted wool trouser paired with an icy grey fine ribbed merino knit does the necessary work. Evaluate the drape and density of the cloth. If you cannot sit comfortably through a long dinner without pulling at a hem or adjusting a restrictive waistband, take the garment off. Physical discomfort serves no practical purpose. Keep your metals mixed. Pair a high-shine silver watch case with a matt yellow gold ring. This tangible friction provides sufficient detail when shadows deepen.",
      "sectionIntro": "Low lighting and close proximity demand garments that stand up to immediate physical scrutiny.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A frantic morning dash for a train does not justify abandoning your physical equilibrium. Construct your standard uniform using garments that move fluidly from early morning tasks to late evening transit. Reach for crisp cotton poplin and technical nylon in a strictly cool palette. Combine icy grey layers with a mix of heavy silver and fine gold rings. Your aesthetic must survive mundane friction. Remember your baseline equation is always balanced proportions + cool composure + one refined touch. If a stark navy trouser feels too rigid to wear while loading boxes into a boot, drop it immediately. Clothes must serve your physical schedule. Test every single piece against this concrete reality.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your ordinary daily routine as the primary testing ground for your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your hardware strategy offers absolute freedom. Mix {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} across your jewellery and garment zips without hesitation. Choose matt or high-shine finishes as required. Ensure every clasp or buckle supports your balanced proportions. Gauge the heft of a watch or chain in your bare hands to confirm its substance. Heavy metal anchors the silhouette. Avoid faux-tarnished bronze, beaten copper, and pre-aged surfaces. They introduce rusticated clutter into an otherwise sharp aesthetic. Rely instead on brilliant {metal_1}, solid {metal_2}, and gleaming {metal_3}. These uncompromised pure elements solidify your cool composure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the hardware that punctuates your garments and anchors your jewellery.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Look for a dense structure when selecting your stones. You are building cool composure. A piece must feel significant in your hand before it touches your skin. Lift the ring and assess its density. Favour icy selections like {stone_1} or {stone_2}. Avoid rough, unpolished cuts that introduce visual noise and ruin your balanced proportions. Keep your settings firmly in the present. Frame your stones strictly in high-shine finishes and pristine mirror chrome. If the setting feels hollow or looks deliberately weathered, put it back. Select {stone_3} in a sharp, modern casing instead.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your stones and settings for sheer physical density before you ever wear them.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Investigate the underside of a belt buckle or a watch case. If the metal is stamped hollow to save weight, it will shatter your cool composure. Steer clear of artificially aged brass and hammered copper, which register as visual clutter. Demand pristine, solid surfaces instead. Focus on mirror chrome, polished white gold, or brilliant {metal_1}. When you incorporate {stone_1}, press it against your skin to verify its cold, heavy reality. Absolute density dictates quality, ensuring your metals always support balanced proportions.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate hardware through physical contact before making a final decision.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Anchor your silhouette in balanced proportions. Set the mood with cool composure. Finish the garment with one refined touch. Restrict your textiles and hardware to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with silk scarves. Seek out a crepe de chine square with a completely matt finish. Apply the focal test to every addition. If the accessory introduces a complex print, its texture must stay flat. Do not let two competing elements fight for attention. Trust your physical instinct when selecting these final pieces. A photograph deceives the eye. The actual drag and weight of the fabric in your bare hands delivers the absolute truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your finishing elements by testing their tactile weight and structural limits.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Filter your fine jewellery through a strict detail limit. If a piece attempts a complex shape and a high polish simultaneously, put it back in the tray. It must offer exactly one clear detail. Stack thin bands of silver and gold on the same finger. Layer a brushed silver pendant over a polished gold chain. This free approach to mixed metals and matt finishes anchors your cool composure. Evaluate an item by touch. Roll the rings in your palm before wearing them to confirm their substance. Keep every band thin to preserve balanced proportions against an icy grey sleeve.",
      "sectionIntro": "Curate the hardware that finishes the garment.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin mixed gold and silver, mixed polished and brushed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Source a small structured bag for your daily carry. Look for a kid suede or smooth leather top-handle. Avoid slouchy shapes. Demand fine mixed hardware that bridges your silver and gold elements. Enforce cool composure by matching this structure against worsted wool or technical nylon. Before stepping outside, conduct a final review. Scan your entire silhouette and isolate the primary focal point. If the smooth leather competes with the mixed metals, the outfit broadcasts too many messages. Remove the loudest piece. Secure balanced proportions by keeping the visual focus singular. Grasp the hardware. If the top-handle feels flimsy in your grip, drop it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your accessory configuration with a structured carry and a strict edit.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede or smooth leather top-handle, fine mixed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Build balanced proportions using adaptable contrast. Scale the intensity of your motifs up or down to suit the day. In your tailored garments, draw pattern purely from the woven fibres. In fluid layers like a technical nylon shell, take pattern from the surface dye. Apply the straight-edge test to every motif. Step back three metres from the glass. The lines must remain entirely crisp and true. If the shapes blur or bleed into the background, drop the garment. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. Their lack of definition undermines your structure. Instead, secure your foundation with {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2}. These selections hold their exact shape, ensuring cool composure through strict geometry.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as an architectural element, deploying it to build structure rather than distract the eye.",
      "tests": [
        "the straight-edge test (lines stay crisp and true at three metres)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Assess the internal geometry of any {recommended_pattern_1} you consider. The shapes must keep their sharp outlines across the entire surface of the fabric, wrapping cleanly around seams without breaking. Demand balanced proportions between the negative space and the dye. A vague or misaligned print destroys structural clarity and shatters your cool composure. Inspect the intersections closely. You require absolute visual definition to maintain your framework.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use the straight-edge test to evaluate any printed or woven motif.",
      "tests": [
        "the straight-edge test (lines stay crisp and true at three metres)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_libra__moon_scorpio__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "balanced proportions + quiet undercurrent + one refined touch",
    "closing": "Let your physical intuition bypass the mirror entirely, anchoring every choice you make in balanced proportions + quiet undercurrent + one refined touch.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Calibrate your wardrobe to the sensation of frictionless weight. When you pull on a garment, it should settle over your shoulders with a silent, heavy drape. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Your operational blueprint is balanced proportions + quiet undercurrent + one refined touch. Picture a structured overcoat layered over a fine-gauge knit, anchored by a sleek leather loafer. The silhouette remains centred and grounded, while a single sharp line on a shoe or bag elevates the entire combination. Keep the temperature strictly cool, stripping away excess visual clutter until only the pure cut remains.\n\nConstruct this sartorial foundation slowly over years. Invest in structural integrity first, then deploy these garments instantly on dark winter mornings without a second thought. To ensure a piece belongs in your wardrobe, subject it to the melt test. Put the garment on, stand before a mirror, and physically drop your shoulders. The fabric must melt seamlessly into your frame, absorbing completely into your natural posture rather than imposing its own shape. If the item sits rigidly apart from your body, leave it on the rack. Seek a perfectly matt finish that absorbs light and proves its worth through sheer material quality.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation, the strict physical rules of engagement for selecting garments that serve your specific architecture.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Keep your palette cool and build your wardrobe on materials that provide a quiet undercurrent and maintain balanced proportions. Reach for {texture_good_1} when selecting knitwear and winter layers. These garments must compress in your grip and bounce back immediately. For bags, shoes, and belts, select {texture_good_2} that moulds to your routine and patinates with wear. Anchor your structure with {texture_good_3} in tailored coats and blazers to guarantee clean lines that last for years. Introduce {texture_good_4} in blouses and linings to add one refined touch of fluid, unforced movement. Before buying any piece, apply the wrist test. Drag the fabric across the sensitive skin of your inner wrist. If it bites or feels synthetic, leave it on the rail. Let the nerves in your skin make the final decision.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every garment by its physical substance before you consider its cut.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
