    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At the desk, let light movement lead. Build the base with crisp cotton poplin and worsted wool. These fabrics must sit cleanly on the body without restriction. Support this daily agility with weightless layers. Add a fine ribbed merino knit over a stark navy shift. Mix your metals freely to break up uniform surfaces. Combine a steel watch with a brass cuff. Apply the queue test. If you cannot stand for twenty minutes waiting for a prescription without adjusting a collar or tugging at a hem, leave the piece on the hanger. Finish the profile with one pearl of light. A single polished silver stud near the jaw or a cool reflective pendant against icy grey technical nylon provides the necessary spark.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your work attire as a strict functional toolkit.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "For intimate evening settings, let light movement dictate your choices. Rely on the immediate drape of silk crepe or fine cashmere. Stiff construction traps you in low light. Pick up the garment and gauge how it shifts in your hands. Trust the physical feedback of the cloth against your skin. Appearance deceives, but the reality of the weave never will. Mix silver and gold hardware freely, letting the metals catch the cool ambient glow. Pair a matt technical nylon shell with high-polish rings. Apply the distraction check before you leave. Sitting through a two-hour dinner wearing your chosen outfit should not require suffering for the aesthetic. If the collar pinches, leave it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Close-quarters settings demand absolute physical ease, stripping away visual noise to focus entirely on how a garment feels in the dark.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "An impromptu errand for groceries does not grant permission to drop your standards. Dress for a brisk walk down a cool, damp street just as critically as an evening appointment. Reach for fine gauge knitwear and fluid gabardine. Rely on the tactile feedback of your own grip. Reflections flatter, but physical mass remains absolute. Mimic carrying a shopping basket before you leave the house. If a sleeve restricts your reach, discard the garment. Pair a matt silver watch with a polished platinum chain. The environment changes, but your baseline requires absolute consistency. Ensure every outfit is anchored by weightless layers + light movement + one pearl of light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Enforce your style rules on the most mundane days, treating everyday errands as a physical proving ground.",
      "tests": [
        "the pharmacy line: a trip to the pharmacy does not require suffering for the aesthetic (Slate)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your cool temperature gives you total freedom to combine metals. Mix {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} across your zips, buckles, and jewellery. A {metal_1} ring sits perfectly alongside a {metal_2} watch casing. Keep your finishes varied but strictly modern. Artificially aged hardware, hammered surfaces, and antiqued patinas create visual clutter against a sharp, present-tense wardrobe. Anchor your choices in highly polished finishes and mirror shine. Avoid {excluded_finish} entirely. When evaluating a new piece of hardware, pick it up in your hand. A gleaming surface often misleads, but the sheer physical density of a solid buckle provides an honest assessment. Heavy, substantial hardware offers the necessary anchor for your garments, ensuring they maintain their light movement.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat hardware as the structural anchor of your wardrobe, testing every clasp and zip for physical substance.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Anchor your light movement with solid, clear stones. Choose a brilliant {stone_1} or a cool {stone_2} to sit against your skin. Lift the jewellery in your palm. Glossy cuts distract the eye, but weight confirms the quality. Trust your hands to locate authentic pieces. Steer clear of textured or deliberately tarnished settings. Those muddy treatments dilute a precise aesthetic. Instead, keep your mounts clean and highly polished. Unblemished metal provides sharp clarity, ensuring your stones cut cleanly through your silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select stones that act as precise anchors for your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Weigh every {metal_1} piece individually. Your eyes gloss over cheap construction, but your muscles register the deficit. You build outfits around weightless layers, which means your accents must offer real structural density. Reject any simulated wear or fake oxidisation. These forced vintage effects act as visual sediment, dragging down your cool palette. Keep your hardware sharp and immediate. Choose high-shine reflective surfaces, polished details, and {stone_1} to create light movement. When you hold an item, it must feel solid enough to drop cleanly into place.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this physical check to verify the reality of your hardware.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You have assembled your weightless layers and ensured there is adequate light movement in the silhouette. Now, you must supply the final element. Your accessories provide that crucial one pearl of light. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look to maintain a cool, balanced aesthetic. Start building this collection with silk scarves, specifically a crepe de chine square with a strictly matt finish. Assess every addition using your own physical intuition. Glass reflects an illusion, but weight offers proof. Subject your choices to the subtraction test. Strip away the final item you put on. If the resulting shape feels instantly less constrained and the fabric breathes better, leave that piece on the table.",
      "sectionIntro": "Introduce the accessory strategy by anchoring it to the final step of their style formula, defining strict limits on quantity, and teaching them to edit their choices through physical sensation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Mix thin gold and silver chains without hesitation. Combine polished silver rings with brushed gold pendants. Keep the tone consistently cool across your icy grey wardrobe. Grip your jewellery firmly to confirm its quality. Optics fail us daily. True heaviness grounds the piece. If a metal chain drags heavily on your collar, drop it. Your weightless layers demand delicate shapes. Execute the removal check before stepping out. Put on every ring and necklace you intend to wear. Stop. Remove the thickest item. The remaining fine jewellery must feel like air against your collarbone.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select fine jewellery that acts as a literal extension of your body rather than an anchor.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin mixed gold and silver, mixed polished and brushed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your silhouette with a small structured bag. Pick it up and evaluate the construction. Demand kid suede or smooth leather in a neat top-handle shape. Check the closures for fine mixed hardware, which gives you complete freedom across your cool palette. Finish dressing by auditing your selections. Inspect the final assembly and unclip the single piece doing too much work. If a bulky clasp or a heavy frame drags down your weightless layers, leave that item behind. Rely on your grip to assess the leather. If the object feels cumbersome to carry, it will ruin the physical balance of the garments.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your outfit by choosing a structural anchor and aggressively editing the result.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede or smooth leather top-handle, fine mixed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Dictate pattern rules by the structure of the garment. Tailored pieces require woven-in geometry. Fluid pieces demand patterns that shift and breathe. Adapt your contrast to the item. Drop the scale down to tonal threads for quiet utility, or push it to graphic edges for a sharp anchor. Build a strict pass-over list. Leave {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} on the rack. Seek out {recommended_pattern_1} in structured pieces and {recommended_pattern_2} in softer shirts. Apply the motion check to every print. Hang the piece and swing it. A successful print reads as a soft, pleasant texture the moment you introduce light movement. If the design stiffens the fabric visually, drop it. Always keep the underlying dye temperatures cool.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the rhythm of your wardrobe by controlling how pattern behaves on the body.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the Ten-Pace Blur Test to evaluate any printed garment. Hang the piece across the room and narrow your eyes. A passing {recommended_pattern_1} will melt into a continuous wash of colour in motion. It should never read as a rigid graphic. If the lines remain sharp from ten feet away, leave the item on the rack. The print must surrender to your light movement. Treat this distance check as a reliable guide. Elaborate motifs distract up close. Choose prints that blur into cool shadows when you step back.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this optical check to ensure your prints support your structure rather than fighting it.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_pisces__moon_cancer__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "weightless layers + hidden depth + one pearl of light",
    "closing": "Navigate every garment by touch, relying on your body to construct weightless layers + hidden depth + one pearl of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Find your baseline in the sensation of absolute weightlessness. Trust your hands when shopping. Look for garments that feel like cool water slipping through your fingers. If a fabric drags against your skin, put the item back on the rack. Your core style formula is weightless layers + hidden depth + one pearl of light. Picture a sheer translucent blouse layered under a dense, heavy outer coat, finished with a single luminous pin resting at the collarbone. This structural contrast builds a foundation that demands zero attention.\n\nBuild your wardrobe slowly, curating each piece with strict intention. Deploy these garments with steady precision. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Apply the melt test to every piece you try on. When you slip a garment over your shoulders, it must immediately dissolve into your frame, becoming indistinguishable from your own posture. If a collar stands rigid against your neck or you have to pull a hem into alignment, the garment fails the test. You require absolute integration between the textile and your body.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish your stylistic foundation and the physical tests required to execute it.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe on fabrics that deliver weightless layers and a muted finish. Trust your fingers over a printed label. Pick up a garment and apply the collapse test. Gather the fabric in your fist and drop it onto a hard surface. It must fall into a soft pool rather than a stiff mound. Look for {texture_good_1} in knitwear that compresses and bounces back from your grip. Build your structure with {texture_good_3} for tailored coats that hold clean lines. Add hidden depth with {texture_good_4} for linings that glide over your skin. Ground these pieces with {texture_good_2} for bags and belts that mould to your life. Memorise the materials below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the core materials that build your wardrobe from the inside out.",
