        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the all-earth sink: brown on olive on bark, all matt and all heavy, can swallow you whole",
          "fix": "lift it: an oatmeal cream layer at the collar, one piece of polished leather, or the washed blue relief"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let fast movement dictate your attire at work. Anchor your core with a deep teal boiled wool jacket. Support this momentum by introducing weightless layers of washed silk underneath. A midday exit for coffee does not justify dropping your silhouette. Keep the tailored outerwear on. Let the crisp drape of dove grey heavy silk crepe trousers hold a strict vertical line. Pin a single piece of cool platinum to your collar to serve as your one pearl of light. Keep the rest of your palette strictly muted and matt. Reject loud prints. Rely on the sharp cut of the garments to direct your day.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply strict structural discipline to your working environment.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim, low-light spaces, fast movement leads your choices. Let heavy silk crepe fall directly against the skin. Avoid rigid fabrics that stand away from the collarbone. Pick up a deep teal slip, drop it onto a chair, and watch how it collapses into a liquid pool. Stepping outside after dark requires the same strict visual logic. Keep the dove grey boiled wool draped over your shoulders exactly as you wore it indoors. Rely on cool silver reflecting ambient bulbs to draw the eye. Plunge bare arms into cloud-soft lambswool to gauge the drape before venturing into the night.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess your garments for close quarters and low light.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat a Tuesday morning run to the post office with the exact same structural precision you apply to a scheduled appointment. Casual errands offer no excuse to compromise your lines. Reach for a boiled wool sweater in dove grey. Pair it with trousers that drop cleanly to the shoe. The visual temperature must remain strictly cool. Your daily routine relies on weightless layers + fast movement + one pearl of light. Assemble this sequence every morning. Check the drape of your washed silk shirt before stepping outside. Ensure the fabric falls without restriction. A matt silver watch provides the only necessary focus. Maintain this uniform without exception.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your standard to the unremarkable hours.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your hardware strategy relies on cool dominance. Anchor your weightless layers with {metal_1} and {metal_2}. Always handle the metal before buying. Lift the chain or the belt buckle. The visual finish might trick you, but the pure heft of the piece reveals its quality. Avoid sharp, reflective {excluded_finish} surfaces. A mirror-like shine cuts harshly against soft cool fabrics and disrupts fast movement. You must insist on a brushed or matt finish. This keeps the entire profile unified.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select hardware that grounds your silhouette without shouting for attention.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Your stones must anchor your weightless layers without stalling their momentum. Lift the setting in your open palm. Sight can be manipulated, but mass cannot. A piece might appear substantial, but if it feels hollow or flimsy, put it back. Seek out the cool, quiet density of {stone_1} or the solid opacity of {stone_2}. Avoid highly faceted, glittering cuts. A mirror-bright metallic polish acts as a harsh disruption against your muted garments. Secure the look by demanding brushed or matt settings to maintain fast movement from fabric to hardware.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones as structural anchors that hold the architecture of your garments in place.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift {metal_1} in your bare hand. Rely entirely on the physical sensation of density over any optical trick. Gleaming, high-shine finishes create a severe distraction next to muted {core_colour_1}. This sharp glare interrupts the fast movement of a cohesive outfit. Keep your hardware strictly subdued. Choose a completely matt or deliberately brushed surface to maintain a cool temperature and integrate quietly with those weightless layers. If {stone_1} feels suspiciously light when you weigh it in your palm, leave it on the shelf.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test the physical weight and finish of every piece before you put it on.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments provide weightless layers. Their tailoring allows fast movement. Accessories step in to deliver one pearl of light. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Apply the one-ember test to every addition. Stand back and ask if the item acts as a solitary point of cool illumination against your muted fabrics. If the accessory demands immediate attention over the whole outfit, take it off. Begin with handbags. Seek out full-grain leather finished with brushed matt hardware. Run your fingers over the metal. It must scatter the room light rather than shine.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hardware and details demand strict curation to protect the balance of your wardrobe.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Source scarves in fine wool or washed silk. Always demand a strictly matt finish. When you loop the fabric around your neck, it must drape cleanly to support fast movement. Subject each piece to a strict focal check. Lay the textile against a boiled wool jacket and look at the overall effect. The scarf should act as a single, quiet spark of cool tone. It functions as a solitary glowing ember, never a blazing bonfire of pattern. If the design competes with the garment beneath it, drop it. These weightless layers exist to finish a silhouette, not to dominate the frame.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess every accessory by how it feels in your hands and how it reacts to light.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Secure those weightless layers with a medium full-grain leather belt. Inspect the hardware. The buckle must remain completely matt. When selecting keepsake jewellery, demand aged silver and oxidised finishes. The darkened crevices of a tarnished pendant belong with cool tones like dove grey. Before you finish dressing, scan your hands and neck to locate the brightest reflection. Strip away any secondary metal that catches the eye. You want exactly one solitary spark resting against the muted textiles, never a scattered fire. This deliberate restraint guarantees fast movement and prevents bulky hardware from disrupting the silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your finishing hardware and apply a strict final edit.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Keep your tailored garments anchored in low-contrast {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2}. Let your fluid pieces, those cut for fast movement, take on the softer edges of {recommended_pattern_3}. Maintain an exceptionally low, tonal contrast across every print. Sharp graphic divisions disrupt the quiet surface of your clothing. Reject any piece relying on {avoid_pattern_1}. Pass over anything that breaks your muted finish. Subject every print to the firelight test. Take the fabric into dim evening illumination. A successful pattern must deepen its cool tones by lamplight, growing richer under the ambient glow rather than washing out.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat print as a structural decision, testing every graphic against the drape and cut of the cloth.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the firelight test to {recommended_pattern_1}. Hang the piece in a dark room and switch on a single dim bulb. Step back three paces. The print must lose its sharp edges and deepen into the cool, muted base fabric. Any stark contrast fails here. If the motif refuses to blur in the amber shadows, it will ruin the cohesion of weightless layers. True quality demands a pattern that melts under low lighting. This visual shift ensures the garment always supports fast movement.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every print to a strict lighting test before adding it to your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_pisces__moon_virgo__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "weightless layers + honest fabric + one pearl of light",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on weightless layers + honest fabric + one pearl of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Dress by touch first. Feel the air moving through the weave of a garment before you check the mirror. Your core formula is weightless layers + honest fabric + one pearl of light. Picture a sheer cotton gauze shirt worn unbuttoned over a dense silk slip dress, anchored by a single luminous pendant catching the cool light. This is your baseline. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. If the material feels stiff or suffocating, leave it on the rail.\n\nBuild your collection deliberately, then adapt your outfits rapidly to match the morning. You need pieces that shift seamlessly from a damp pavement to a dry indoor climate. Subject every new garment to the fall test. Pick the item up by the shoulders and drop it onto a table. Watch how the cloth collapses. It should pool fluidly, not hold an empty, rigid shape. If a sleeve stands up by itself, it will fight your movements. Mix matt finishes with subtle reflections to give the silhouette life.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this foundational logic before you touch another garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the fall test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe relies on honest fabric to build balanced silhouettes. Trust your hands over the mirror. Execute the edge test on every prospective purchase. Grip the hem tightly between your fingers. If the textile feels spongy or pushes back against your pressure, leave it on the hanger. You need pliable materials to construct your weightless layers. Seek {texture_good_1} for shirting that establishes clean architectural boundaries. Rely on {texture_good_2} for close base layers that guarantee sharp, easy movement. Pick up {texture_good_3} for trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day. Finish with {texture_good_4} for mobile outerwear that blocks cool air while weighing little. Stock your wardrobe from the list below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to filter your wardrobe before your eyes even register the garment.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the edge test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Drop anything that catches on your skin or traps heat. If a textile refuses to breathe, leave it on the rack. {texture_bad_1} often feels slick and dead in the fingers, lacking the dry snap of a proper worsted. When examining a seam, check the internal volume. If the stitching feels hollow or bulky, the garment will fail to adapt to your movement. {texture_bad_2} presents a similar trap, resisting your body instead of yielding. You anchor your look with one pearl of light, and a cheap, stifling surface kills that cool temperature immediately. {texture_bad_3} might pass a visual check, but clammy friction against your wrist will always expose poor quality.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn the physical traps that betray a weak textile before you even try it on.",
      "tests": [
        "the edge test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Force {sweet_spot_keyword_1} against {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to generate physical traction. This clash creates your foundation. Construct weightless layers using a cool {texture_good_1} over denser weaves to build volume without heat. Assess the final seam to test the boundary. A crisp finish holds absolute shape exactly where it ends, yielding nothing to external pressure. Avoid limp surfaces. Structure must always press against soft utility to keep the silhouette active.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your signature friction by pitting contrasting finishes against one another.",
      "tests": [
        "the edge test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette temperature is strictly cool. Build the base using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Anchor these neutrals with the structural depth of {core_colour_4}. Rely on {core_colour_3} as your absolute white substitute. Pass over mustard, rust, and warm olive green entirely. Use your soft relief tone sparingly as a quiet visual pause. Deploy {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} purely as isolated strikes of intent. Beware the frostbite trap. Stacking slate over slate projects blankness instead of strict discipline. Force a disruption into the flat space. Punctuate an honest fabric with a reflective metal bracelet, a glossed leather boot, or a single sharp strike of intense colour.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your palette by trusting temperature and recognising your anchors.",
