          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin mixed gold and silver, mixed polished and brushed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Carry a small structured bag to ground the silhouette. Choose kid suede or smooth leather in a cool colour like icy grey. A top-handle shape imposes order on weightless layers. Check the closures and clasps. Fine mixed hardware provides a sharp flash of silver and gold. Feel the structure with your hands. The architecture of the bag must hold its own shape perfectly when empty. Finally, apply the one-signal test before leaving. Stand back and look. You should see just one distinct gleam lifting the honest fabric. If two metallic or textured details fight for your eye, remove the weakest one immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finish the composition by adding structure and running a final visual check.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede or smooth leather top-handle, fine mixed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored garments require the rigid geometry of {recommended_pattern_1}. Fluid pieces demand the softer tracking of {recommended_pattern_2}. Adapt your contrast scale to the environment. Rely on tonal low-contrast weaves for foundation pieces, then dial up the definition when the setting shifts. Apply the straight-edge test to every printed garment. Step back three metres and review the piece. If the lines blur or lose their crisp track, leave it on the rack. True patterns hold their structure across a space. This discipline protects your system. Assemble weightless layers strictly from cool palettes. Ensure the foundation relies on honest fabric. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. Polish the completed architecture with one pearl of light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as an architectural tool rather than mere decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the straight-edge test (lines stay crisp and true at three metres)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Suspend the garment across the room and inspect the boundaries of the design. If a {recommended_pattern_1} blurs into a hazy smudge at a distance, reject it. You require razor-sharp borders between elements, particularly when deploying a cool anchor like {core_colour_1}. Rub the material to confirm you are holding honest fabric. A successful print maintains strict geometry regardless of perspective. If the dye bleeds or the edges soften, the item fails. Sharp boundaries give you the exact structure required to stack weightless layers without losing focus.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every printed piece to the three-metre precision test.",
      "tests": [
        "the straight-edge test (lines stay crisp and true at three metres)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_sagittarius__moon_gemini__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "expansive colour + light movement + one theatrical finish",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on expansive colour + light movement + one theatrical finish.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your compass is adaptability. Pick up a garment and test how it travels. If the fabric feels stiff or restricts your breath, leave it on the rack. You are dressing to shift seamlessly between spaces and groups. Anchor your choices in warm palettes that invite connection. Build your outfits around a strict formula: expansive colour + light movement + one theatrical finish. Picture a generous silk overcoat layered above a fluid linen tunic, anchored by soft leather trousers, and topped with an exaggerated, sculptural collar. The fabrics must breathe with you.\n\nLet your wardrobe drift by mood. Collect pieces intuitively as your days demand them. Before leaving the house, apply the half-mirror test. Stand close to the glass and examine the reflection from your shoulders upward. If your theatrical finish obscures your jawline or the layered collars feel heavy, remove one piece. The garments should frame your face, never swallow it. Mix matt and polished finishes freely across your body. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this foundational logic to anchor your physical instincts before you assemble an outfit.",
      "tests": [
        "the half-mirror test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe relies on fabrics that catch warm light and breathe with you. Build your foundation on expansive colour and light movement. To achieve this, rely on {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Layer with {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Ground your outfits in {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth, and finish with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. Before buying, apply the wrist-flick test. Snap the fabric lightly over your forearm. If it falls back in a liquid, silent collapse, keep it. If it holds its shape rigidly, leave it on the rack. Rely entirely on your hands to gauge the textile's truth. Choose from the list below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your materials by choosing fabrics that yield to your shape and invite contact.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
