          "fix": "give it one anchor: a sharply tailored blazer, a structured flat, or the gentle navy piece worn where the eye lands first"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let expansive colour lead your professional wear, supported by soft drape and heavy hardware. Wash a tunic in dark mahogany to establish the baseline. Heavy silk crepe provides the required light movement to soften strict corporate tailoring. A quick mid-morning errand for an espresso does not demand stripping away your warm climate. Pull a boiled wool jacket over the silk. Anchor the lapel with a mixed metal clustered pin to serve as your one theatrical finish. Ground the silhouette in bitter chocolate leather boots. Evaluate a garment by feeling the fall of cloud-soft lambswool against your collarbone. Reflections flatter falsely. The pull of the cloth dictates the truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish a strict hierarchy of elements for your professional environment.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, visual details fade. Here, light movement leads. Heavy silk crepe shifting over a dark mahogany sleeve registers immediately in dim rooms. Let density guide you when shadows obscure the cut. Combine a bitter chocolate boiled wool coat with a washed silk shirt for intimate dinners. Let textural choices invite others into your shared space. Mix your metals freely. A matt silver ring worn beside polished gold reflects sparse candlelight. Stepping out onto a dim patio does not mean dropping your warm atmosphere. Pull on cloud-soft lambswool instead of stiff canvas. Pick up every piece before wearing it. Select fabrics that react to the air.",
      "sectionIntro": "Adapt your strategy for intimate evening settings by prioritising tactile truth over visual detail.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Running basic errands does not require shedding your chosen silhouette. Treat Tuesday mornings exactly like Saturday evenings. Let the fabric's natural drop confirm your choice. Lift the material. A dark mahogany boiled wool cardigan must fall without stiffness. If a washed silk shirt clings or resists, drop it. Your baseline remains expansive colour + light movement + one theatrical finish. Apply this to mundane chores. Combine a bitter chocolate lambswool sweater with a mixed stack of brass and silver rings. Seek warm stones like sunstone. Keep every layer fluid. Do not save superior textiles for specific calendar dates. Buying stamps at the post office demands the exact same attention to scale and proportion as a formal gathering.",
      "sectionIntro": "Maintain your physical baseline regardless of the day's itinerary.",
      "tests": [
        "a walk to the bakery does not require abandoning your atmosphere (Mist)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your strategy relies on total freedom. Mix {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} across your jewellery to anchor any expansive colour palette. Ensure the overall temperature remains warm and approachable. Evaluate every clasp and chain by picking the item up. A shining facet offers false promises, but the solid heft in your palm confirms its quality. Guard against the trap of artificially weathered metals. Hammered copper and antiqued brass create distracting visual noise that drags down a contemporary wardrobe. Strip away this clutter by insisting on flawless polished gold, highly polished silver, and mirror chrome. Blend these reflective elements with {excluded_finish} textures to balance your look.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your hardware by demanding physical substance.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Anchor your expansive colour palettes with stones that possess deep internal clarity. Seek out {stone_1} and {stone_2}. Lift the piece to test its weight before you wear it. Mass always reveals the true quality of a setting. If it feels hollow, put it back. Warm tones in your garments require clean, decisive hardware. Steer clear of manufactured heritage. Pitted brass and chemically aged metals drag down your silhouettes, reading as visual noise against your fluid layers. Pull your jewellery into the present tense by demanding highly reflective finishes, polished silver, bright gold, and brilliant chrome. A single dense setting of {stone_3} provides the exact anchoring required.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your stones and hardware as literal weights to ground your fluid silhouettes.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the piece off the display tray. Feel the mass to verify the object's worth. Assess the heft of a {metal_1} cuff or a {stone_1} ring before you wear it. If it feels hollow, leave it on the glass counter. Avoid manufactured weathering completely. Artificially darkened crevices and faux-vintage treatments read as immediate clutter against expansive colour. Keep your hardware free of fake history. Anchor your warm palette with clean, unweathered finishes that rely purely on their actual density.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply a strict physical test to every piece of hardware.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Start with expansive colour. Build upon that base with light movement. Anchor the combination with one theatrical finish. Accessories carry this final responsibility. Keep your selection deliberate. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Execute the too-much test on every outfit. Stack your chosen items, move your arms, and observe the drag. If the hardware fights your natural motion, remove the last thing you added. Assess the friction and mass directly instead of relying on the mirror. Open your collection with eyewear. Look for acetate frames featuring a warm, mixed finish. Let the frames hold the focus while the rest of your silhouette flows freely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your final layer by testing the physical weight and drag of your hardware.",
      "rankedItems": [
