      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored pieces pull their pattern from woven geometry, while fluid garments require soft, organic motifs. Scale your contrast to the room. Wear low-contrast tonal weaves for subtle days, and dial up the graphic impact when the environment shifts. Look for {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} to anchor structural layers. Keep {recommended_pattern_3} for soft cuts. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely, as they flatten your warm palette. Subject every print to a quick visual sweep. You want a pleasant overall impression rather than a specific shouting motif. Build the shape with expansive colour, verify the cloth delivers light movement, and secure the proportion with one theatrical finish. The weave itself must confirm the visual promise.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your prints by letting the structure of the garment dictate the scale of the motif.",
      "tests": [
        "the glance test (a pleasant impression rather than a specific shouting motif)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the glance test before you buy any printed garment. Step back from the mirror, narrow your eyes, and take in the whole shape. Look for a wash of warm, expansive colour that blurs into an inviting, pleasant impression. If you instantly register the exact, sharp outlines within a {recommended_pattern_1}, put the piece back on the rack. The motif is shouting. You want the print to dissolve slightly as the fabric shifts. This gentle visual blur creates light movement over your silhouette, rather than freezing it in place. Let the pattern act as a background rhythm to support your heavier styling choices.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this visual check to filter out patterns that overpower your frame.",
