    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Mix {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} with absolute freedom across your hardware and jewellery. Your warm palette requires careful texture management. High-shine metals look sharp and distracting next to muted fabrics. Stick to matt and brushed finishes to keep the look cohesive. Block {excluded_finish} entirely. Test every piece of hardware before wearing it. Hold the item in your bare hand to confirm its density. A dense, heavy buckle provides the exact hidden depth necessary to anchor your wardrobe.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat every buckle, zip, and clasp as a deliberate structural choice.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select your jewellery by physical density. Weigh each piece in your palm to assess its heft. Genuine mass provides the absolute measure of quality. Seek out stones like {stone_1} and {stone_2}. They deliver the hidden depth needed to ground your wardrobe. Keep the hardware surrounding them subdued. High-gloss finishes clash harshly against warm, muted textiles. They create a stark distraction. Demand matt or brushed settings across your mixed metals to ensure every piece integrates seamlessly.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select stones and hardware that anchor your wardrobe through physical density rather than surface shine.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate a piece of {metal_1} by its pure physical drag. Let gravity prove the item's worth. If the chain or cuff feels hollow, leave it behind. Substantial mass proves the piece possesses hidden depth. Examine the surface treatment next. A high-shine polish creates a sharp glare that disrupts soft, muted garments. Avoid this clash entirely. Select matt and brushed finishes to keep your hardware grounded and cohesive. Heavy, subdued textures anchor a warm palette perfectly.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware by weight and finish before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments establish expansive colour in warm tones and build hidden depth. Accessories exist solely to deliver your one theatrical finish. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look to maintain balance. Begin with handbags. Select supple full-grain leather anchored by brushed matt hardware. Place the bag on a hard counter to perform the ripple test. Watch how the material settles. If the structure remains stiff and refuses to yield, reject the item entirely. The leather must collapse and ripple softly under its own weight.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your accessory strategy by applying strict physical tests to every piece you carry.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Source scarves exclusively in washed silk or fine wool. Every piece must carry a strictly matt surface. Anchor these textiles in bitter chocolate and dark mahogany. This creates the hidden depth necessary for your wardrobe. Always test the material before committing. Hold the scarf by a single corner and flick your wrist upwards. Watch the wave travel down the length of the cloth. A correct piece will roll in a continuous, heavy motion right to the hem. If the textile stutters or snaps abruptly, put it down. Keep the temperature warm across every colour you select to maintain harmony.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your scarves strictly by their structural integrity and surface.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your garments with medium full-grain leather belts. Insist on a completely matt buckle. This quiet detail establishes the hidden depth your wardrobe demands without pulling focus. Treat your keepsake jewellery with the same physical scrutiny. Select aged silver and oxidised metals over highly polished alternatives. These tarnished finishes ground warm fabrics perfectly. Before stepping outside, check the accessory's physical impact on your silhouette. If an oxidised ring or heavy leather strap sends a jarring shockwave through your washed silk, take it off. Every element must settle quietly into the whole.",
      "sectionIntro": "Secure the final elements of your look with precision, and test their physical impact.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Your tailored pieces extract their architecture from a muted {recommended_pattern_1}. Your fluid garments borrow their drape from a softly woven {recommended_pattern_2}. Enforce a strict low-contrast tonal rule across every printed or woven surface. The eye must trace the textile before it registers the motif. This approach guarantees hidden depth without demanding external attention. Pass over stark graphics, sharp borders, and {avoid_pattern_2}. Leave {avoid_pattern_1} permanently on the hanger. Evaluate any new printed garment under fading evening light to verify it will settle into a warm, moving texture instead of flattening out completely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as an architectural tool to build subtle structure, not as a surface decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Run every patterned piece through the dusk test. Evaluate the {recommended_pattern_1} in low evening light. At three paces, the motif must melt into a soft, warm blur. If the lines remain harsh across a collar or lapel, put the item back. You need prints that diffuse in the dark. This visual shift provides the hidden depth required for your aesthetic. When you find a design that loses its sharp edges as the room dims, buy it. Always verify how a pattern behaves away from glaring overhead bulbs. A successful weave acts as a shifting shadow, never a rigid stamp.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every pattern to a strict test of low-light legibility before adding it to your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_sagittarius__moon_taurus__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "expansive colour + sensory comfort + one theatrical finish",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on expansive colour + sensory comfort + one theatrical finish.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your physical instincts when assembling a look. Gauge the weight and warmth of the fabric against your skin. Apply the gravity test. Lift the garment and drop it onto a wooden chair. Flimsy fabrics float and collapse into a weak pile. A true piece hits the surface with an immediate, heavy thud. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not. Build your wardrobe slowly and adapt daily. Drift by mood rather than rigid schedules. Let the weather and your community guide the silhouette of the day.\n\nYour absolute baseline is expansive colour + sensory comfort + one theatrical finish. Picture a heavy knitted wool jumper in a rich, warm tone worn over soft cotton trousers. Anchor that practical base with a chunky brass ring or a heavily textured brocade jacket. Mix your metals freely, and combine high-shine details with completely matt fabrics. The tension between practical comfort and that single theatrical element creates a look that serves both you and the people you spend your time with. Keep your hands in your pockets. Let the clothes do the work.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is the architectural foundation of your style, the daily physical rules you must learn to trust.",
      "tests": [
        "the fall test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe relies on materials that deliver sensory comfort without collapsing. Build your foundation using {texture_good_1} for shirting that maintains clean architectural boundaries. Layer this over {texture_good_2} to keep sharp lines and easy movement right against your skin. Anchor the lower half with {texture_good_3} for trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day. Top it with {texture_good_4} to block the wind in lightweight mobile outerwear. Apply the edge test before you buy. Pinch the hem between your thumb and index finger. It must feel substantial enough to hold a warm expansive colour and anchor your one theatrical finish, yet pliable enough to yield immediately to your grip. If the edge fights back, drop the garment. Trust your hands to find these exact targets.",
      "sectionIntro": "Focus your hands on materials that guarantee physical ease while holding the clean structure of your garments.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the edge test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Do not buy {texture_bad_1} blindly. Test the memory of the cloth directly. Crush a sleeve in your fist. If the fold stays sharp and refuses to soften, it fails. You require warm, approachable textiles that invite connection, ensuring uninterrupted sensory comfort. {texture_bad_2} is equally hostile. Roll the fabric in your fingers. If it squeaks or traps heat, drop it immediately. Rely on physical friction to veto bad materials. Cameras mask cheap construction, but touch exposes it instantly. {texture_bad_3} might look appealing in photographs, but its brittle weave acts like a physical barrier. Reject any material that demands strict posture or restricts your ability to gather with your people.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to recognise the textiles that betray your physical needs.",
      "tests": [
        "the edge test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to build a tactile foundation. Then introduce {texture_good_1} as your one theatrical finish. Test the boundary of any new shirt. Grip the hem and flick it. If the bottom edge snaps into a stiff, rigid line, leave the piece on the rail. You require materials that adapt and yield to your movements. A warm palette relies on this physical fluidity to feel alive. Trust your hands to verify the drape. Static reflections hide the truth. Step around the fitting room to ensure the fabric drops cleanly.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your signature texture combinations and test their structural limits before you buy.",
      "tests": [
        "the edge test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette relies entirely on a warm temperature. Build the bulk of your wardrobe using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} as your primary base. Reach for {core_colour_3} whenever you need a white substitute. Deploy {core_colour_4} as a bridge neutral to link disparate garments. Bring in expansive colour using {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} for your deliberate accents. Treat your relief tone purely as a soft note, deploying it sparingly to break up heavy combinations. Leave pale pastel, neon brights, and flat blue-grey on the rack. Avoid a total absence of pigment. A completely greyscale outfit looks like a void instead of deliberate restraint. Wake the combination up by adding a hard reflection, a high-shine cuff, a glossy boot, or a single strike of saturated dye.",
      "sectionIntro": "Govern your wardrobe by giving every pigment a precise job.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Warm taupe",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft cream",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sand beige",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Warm stone",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Olive drab",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Espresso brown",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rust orange",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Ochre gold",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Pale clay",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "total ice: unbroken grey on grey can read as absence rather than composure",
          "fix": "add the polished signal, a mirror-finish cuff, a patent boot, or one line of electric colour"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let expansive colour lead your choices in the office, supported by the grounding weight of worsted wool or crisp cotton poplin. Build your base from warm taupe and camel. Step away from the mirror and close your eyes. Trust your body over the glass. Ignore the flat reflection and evaluate the cloth in motion. Test every garment before you buy it. Ask yourself if you would gladly wear these exact trousers out into the rain to grab the Sunday paper. If the fabric feels too rigid for a wet morning errand, leave the piece on the hanger. Add a single heavy brass or matt silver ring. Keep your jewellery mixed and adaptable.",
      "sectionIntro": "Approach your working day as a space for practical dressing, not a performance.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close quarters with low light, sensory comfort takes the absolute lead. Dim lighting neutralises colour, so physical texture must do the heavy lifting. Close your eyes and run your fingers across a camel worsted wool trouser or a warm taupe fine ribbed merino jumper. Gauge how it yields to your collarbone. Walking to the corner shop in the cold merits the identical soft baseline as hosting a packed dining table. Let a mixed cluster of yellow gold and sterling silver rings catch the faint glow of a shared meal. Require the subtle friction of crisp cotton poplin to anchor your base layers. If the weave feels rigid in your grip, drop it immediately. Prioritise threads that adapt entirely to your form rather than dictating a stiff silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master close-quarters dressing by letting your physical intuition dictate the rules.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A mundane run to the post office is the primary testing ground for your garments. Buying milk on a Tuesday requires the exact same foundational care as a scheduled gathering. Build these daily outfits around durable wool and soft cotton in warm shades. Let the fabrics breathe and move with your community engagements. If a piece restricts your reach while picking up groceries, discard it. Maintain your baseline by applying expansive colour + sensory comfort + one theatrical finish to every morning choice. Pair a technical nylon jacket with a heavy woven scarf and mixed metal rings. Trust your immediate tactile reaction when pulling items from the hanger. If the garment demands constant adjustment, abandon it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Ground your daily routine in strict tactile standards and refuse to compromise for mundane errands.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Treat your hardware as structural anchors. You have total freedom to combine {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} in a single outfit. Because you rely on expansive colour, your metals must provide crisp punctuation rather than rustic noise. Artificially distressed copper and oxidised brass act as messy distractions. Anchor your choices in pristine, highly reflective surfaces. Pick the buckle or chain up to judge its quality. Measure the true value in grams. Substantial items sink firmly into your palm. If the item lacks heavy, satisfying heft, put it back on the shelf. Mix your finishes freely across a warm palette, but entirely omit {excluded_finish} to maintain an unbroken baseline of sensory comfort.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate metals as structural tools, not decorative afterthoughts.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Treat a cut of {stone_1} or {stone_2} as a warm, concentrated anchor for your expansive colour. Lift the jewellery from the display to test its heft. Ignore the faceting and evaluate the pure mass. If the object feels light or hollow, walk away. Leave antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal in the display case. These faux-weathered textures generate visual static that contradicts a sharp, modern aesthetic. House your gems in polished silver, platinum, white gold, or mirror chrome. These highly reflective surfaces provide a crisp boundary that amplifies the stone. Maintain your baseline of sensory comfort by ensuring these dense objects rest completely flush along the collarbone or wrist.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware using physical density and precise reflection as your primary filters.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the piece off the display tray. Gauge the density in your palm before you check the tag. Price tags communicate marketing, while sheer weight indicates authentic craftsmanship. Trust the heft in your hand as your deciding metric. If the item feels hollow, put it back. Avoid pitted finishes that interrupt the clean lines of your base layers. They distract from the warm tones in your garments. Demand a smooth, polished gleam instead. When you ground your expansive colour with solid, weighty {metal_1}, you create a deliberate foundation rather than a flimsy afterthought.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply a strict physical test to ensure your hardware carries genuine value.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments establish expansive colour and deliver absolute sensory comfort. Accessories secure your one theatrical finish. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with eyewear. Seek out thick acetate frames offering mixed finishes and warm tones. Trust your hands to judge the materials. Pick up the glasses and assess their heft. Evaluate them using the one-signal test. The item must communicate a single structural intention. If the frame relies on chaotic embellishments rather than robust architecture, reject it. True weight reveals proper construction. Let physical density guide your selection.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use accessories as the definitive structural additions that anchor your entire wardrobe.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "acetate frame, mixed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Select a technical nylon crossbody in warm taupe. Check the strap and shell to ensure they deliver absolute sensory comfort. Examine the hardware next. You require brushed metal zips anchored by exactly one polished ring. Audit the hardware for visual discipline. Count the bright points. If the bag provides a single isolated reflection against the matt fabric, it passes. If multiple zips shine aggressively, reject the item. Mix your metals freely in these details, perhaps combining brushed brass zips with a polished steel ring. Controlling the reflections on your accessories ensures the expansive colour of your primary garments takes priority.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your functional carrying pieces by demanding strict hardware limits and absolute tactile reliability.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "technical nylon crossbody, brushed metal zips, one polished ring"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your expansive colour with a clean leather boot. Seek out smooth calfskin with a plain toe and a simple zip. Reject heavy buckles or contrasting welts. Rely on your immediate physical response. Assess the footbed blindly. The actual balance of the heel cannot be faked. Before stepping out, check the overall hierarchy. Scan your warm taupe layers to locate the most prominent visual element. If your footwear fights for attention against a textured worsted wool coat, change your shoes. Ensure your outfit offers one clear, undivided message to the people around you.",
      "sectionIntro": "Ground your wardrobe with structured footwear and apply a strict visual check before leaving.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "clean leather boot, clean"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-signal test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored jackets pull their structural rhythm from {recommended_pattern_1}. Fluid knitwear takes {recommended_pattern_2}. Choose adaptable contrast levels that shift seamlessly between different environments. Anchor your motifs in warm dyes. Let prints channel expansive colour. Maintain tactile softness to guarantee strict sensory comfort in the cloth itself. Test the geometry of your garments across a room. The motifs must hold a rigid border from a distance. If the shapes bleed together, discard the piece. Reject {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. Pass over stiff overlay prints, jarring scales, and any motif that distorts across your shoulders.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat print as architecture rather than decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the straight-edge test (lines stay crisp and true at three metres)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate the fidelity of {recommended_pattern_1} from across the shop. Hang the shirt on a door frame and walk backwards three full metres. The printed boundaries must hold their true shape. If the lines bleed into an indistinct blur, put the item back on the rack. A textile can provide incredible sensory comfort, but if the motif dissolves from a distance, it ruins the structural integrity of the piece. Look for sharp, permanent edges in every matt print. This clarity anchors every warm foundation you build.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this strict distance check to verify visual integrity in your prints.",
      "tests": [
        "the straight-edge test (lines stay crisp and true at three metres)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_scorpio__moon_gemini__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "close drape + light movement + one warm point of light",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on close drape + light movement + one warm point of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your physical instincts demand equilibrium. When assessing a garment, trust the weight in your hands to guide you. Look for materials that yield to your frame without clinging. Your anchoring logic is always close drape + light movement + one warm point of light. Picture a dense knit resting cleanly against the collarbone, paired with a fluid trouser leg that shifts smoothly as you step, finished by a single luminous accent resting near your throat. This configuration ensures you remain grounded yet entirely adaptable.\n\nBuild your collection slowly to guarantee absolute versatility across your week, then deploy your outfits fast when the morning demands action. When evaluating new garments, put them through the flight test. Ask yourself if you could wear the piece on a long-haul journey, sleep in the seat, and step onto the tarmac ready to work. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. If a collar digs into your neck or a seam restricts your shoulder, the garment fails. Leave it on the rack.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this core logic to build a wardrobe that functions without friction.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe on matt textiles that deliver light movement and a close drape. Trust your hands. Apply the drop test. Throw the fabric lightly into the air and watch how it settles. If it plummets heavily or holds rigid shapes, leave it. Look for {texture_good_1} to give your shirting clean architectural boundaries and pure separation. Rely on {texture_good_2} for close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement. Select {texture_good_3} for trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day. Finish with {texture_good_4} for lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little. This creates the matt canvas for your one warm point of light. Use the following hierarchy to select your core materials.",
      "sectionIntro": "Your physical comfort dictates your visual success, so test every fabric with your hands before it touches your skin.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Pick up a garment and toss it into the air. Watch how it drops. If it holds a stiff shape on descent, leave it on the hanger. Your wardrobe relies on a close drape, and rigid fabrics will constantly fight your physical geometry. Avoid {texture_bad_1} entirely. It creates a bulky shell that refuses to settle against your body. Squeeze a handful of {texture_bad_2}. If the fibres feel slick or trap heat instantly, put the piece down. Keep your visual temperature warm by rejecting reflective synthetics or any fabric treated with a stiff, matt coating. Trust the density of the weave. Hollow fibres deceive the eye, but genuine mass never fails you.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to instantly reject fabrics that disrupt your physical baseline.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Anchor your styling in the friction between {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Layer them directly. Test the mobility of any {texture_good_1} piece by pulling the fabric gently on the bias. You require light movement. The garment must drift and settle back, ensuring a close drape over your frame. Ground this descending fluidity with a matt finish. Keep your overall temperature warm to balance the pairing. Motion reveals the truth of the garment.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your materials vigorously to lock in your exact textural balance.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor your palette in a strictly warm temperature. Ensure the finish remains matt. Construct the base using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Swap stark white for {core_colour_3}. Rely on {core_colour_4} as a bridge neutral to connect contrasting items. Deploy {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as your sole deliberate accent. Apply your relief tone sparingly as a soft note. Every shade chosen must support close drape. Pass over pale pastels, neon brights, and blue-grey colours entirely. Watch for the hard shell trap. When your schedule speeds up, do not grab rigid armour or stiff utility jackets. Swap the technical shell for a brushed cotton layer that travels just as fast but wraps your frame securely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your colour palette as a strict system of utility.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Warm taupe",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
