    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, close drape takes the lead. Build your foundation with crisp cotton poplin and worsted wool cut to sit cleanly near the body. Let your other principles play a supporting role. Introduce a solitary warm metallic detail at the collar or wrist to act as your one warm point of light. Prioritise light movement over rigid construction. Test every seam by reaching for a high shelf or sitting in a low office chair. A frantic morning commute does not require surrendering your crisp tailoring. Anchor your choices in camel tones. Drop any restrictive blazers back on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assemble your office options by testing every piece for strict lines and physical ease.",
      "tests": [
        "a school run or a corner shop dash does not require surrendering your softness (Cove)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim lighting, close drape must lead. Low illumination flattens shape. Rely on fine ribbed merino and worsted wool to outline your proportions without clinging. Layer a warm taupe base with mixed metals. A matt gold chain or a brushed silver cuff resting on camel knitwear collects the ambient glow. Keep the fibres tactile against your skin. An impromptu evening out requires no surrender of your soft merino. Dress for the physical sensation of the fabric. Trust the worsted wool to keep its structure while you sit, guaranteeing light movement throughout the night.",
      "sectionIntro": "Construct your evening silhouettes for close quarters and low lighting.",
      "tests": [
        "a school run or a corner shop dash does not require surrendering your softness (Cove)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A quick errand at the local chemist gives you no excuse to drop your tactile standards. Never abandon your soft fabrics for the sake of speed. Base every look upon your mandatory equation of close drape + light movement + one warm point of light. Pull on a fine ribbed merino sweater in warm taupe. Pair it with technical nylon trousers. Keep the textile surface entirely matt. Add a singular brass ring. Reach for crisp cotton poplin shirting when the temperature shifts. Rely on your immediate sensory response to evaluate the garment. If the weave feels rigid across your shoulders, leave it on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your mundane daily routines with the exact same material rigour as significant events.",
      "tests": [
        "a school run or a corner shop dash does not require surrendering your softness (Cove)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Split your metals into two distinct tiers. Personal jewellery resting against your skin demands {personal_metal_1} or {personal_metal_2}. Structural hardware like bag clasps and coat zips requires {structural_metal_1} or {structural_metal_2}. This dual approach secures close drape on the body while allowing light movement and a warm undertone throughout the silhouette. Apply a tactile assessment when sourcing pieces. Lift the buckle in your hands to gauge its genuine mass. If the item feels hollow, abandon it. Avoid artificially aged metals like hammered copper or antiqued brass. These read as clutter against your present-tense garments. Keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome instead. Steer clear of {excluded_finish} surfaces entirely, ensuring your metallic finishes remain strictly matt.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish strict boundaries between the metals you wear against your skin and the hardware that holds your garments together.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Anchor your close drape with dense minerals like {stone_1} and {stone_2}. Lift the setting in your palm to test the heft. Avoid beaten copper and faux-oxidised brass. Artificially aged finishes register as visual clutter. Ground your warm palette and matt textiles with bright hardware. Rely entirely on polished silver, solid platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome. These sharp metals secure light movement without disrupting your balanced silhouette. Let these stones act as your one warm point of light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select stones and metals as structural tools to anchor your daily uniform.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Trust your hands over your eyes. Lift every ring or bracelet off the display. If it lacks absolute density, drop it. Avoid heavily patinated or artificially weathered finishes entirely. Deliberately aged surfaces act as visual debris that interrupts a modern foundation. Instead, secure your pieces in clean, unblemished {metal_1} or a dense {stone_1}. This smooth surface provides a grounding weight that catches warm reflections. Let this solid hardware anchor garments built for light movement while you establish a close drape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware by physical weight before you commit.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories supply the one warm point of light in your formula. Once garments deliver close drape and yield light movement, textiles complete the sequence. Commit to one or two strong pieces per look. Always execute the take-off test. Put on your items, step back, and remove the last piece you added. This ensures your additions remain deliberate. Begin with silk scarves. Select a crepe de chine square or a slim band with a strictly matt finish. Gauge the fabric with your fingers. Genuine crepe carries a faint granular bite that grips the collar. Rely on this tactile feedback as your definitive guide. If a textile reflects room glare or slides freely, drop it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Accessories define the boundaries of your silhouette, demanding strict curation to serve as intentional anchors rather than distractions.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square or slim band, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Subject fine jewellery to a rigorous edit. Put on your thin chain and small drops in brushed silver. Look in the mirror. If a piece disrupts the fluid line of your silhouette or demands attention over your own jawbone, remove it at once. The finish must remain matt to catch a warm reflection without glare. Every item must encourage close drape around the collar. Bulky pieces drag downwards. Look for delicate construction that guarantees continuous light movement as you turn your head. Pick up the metal. If it feels thick or unyielding, leave it in the box.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your final additions using strict material criteria.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin chain and small drops, brushed silver"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your silhouette with a small structured bag. Select a top-handle shape in warm kid suede, finished with fine matt hardware. The dense hide absorbs glare and provides a muted texture that grounds the light movement of your garments. Trust the physical density of the handle in your grip. Before stepping out, strip away the final item you put on. If the outfit loses its structure, return the piece. If the visual noise settles, leave the item on the table. Focus on maintaining a close drape across your entire frame.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your accessories by grounding your silhouette and testing your restraint.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede top-handle, fine matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Scale your contrast to the environment. Build your foundation on adaptive designs that shift smoothly from low to medium visibility depending on the setting. Let tailored jackets derive their pattern from the weave itself. Assign fluid shirts the task of carrying a printed motif. Look for fabrics that offer light movement, allowing the ink to breathe. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. Choose a warm, matt {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2} instead. Run the passing test. Walk past a glass window and check the reflection. A successful print dissolves into a gentle, shifting texture as you move, never hanging like a stiff graphic. Ensure garments maintain close drape. If the fabric wears like a flat canvas, leave it behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master how to scale and select motifs without letting the print wear you.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "To check any {recommended_pattern_1}, apply the motion test. Put the garment on and walk briskly past a large mirror. Watch the reflection briefly. The print must blur into a gentle, continuous grain as you walk. If it remains rigidly legible or flashes with hard edges, leave the piece on the rail. Your wardrobe demands light movement to function. A successful design dissolves into a warm, matt field when your body shifts. Keep the spacing tight enough that the boundaries melt together from three paces away. If you stop walking and the lines demand focus, the item fails.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the motion blur check to verify if a print serves your structural needs.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_scorpio__moon_aquarius__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "close drape + mobile layers + one warm point of light",
    "closing": "Let tactile gravity and physical weight serve as your ultimate compass, always pointing you back to close drape + mobile layers + one warm point of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your hands to find the quietest garments on the rail. Close your eyes and feel for fabrics that absorb light rather than reflect it. You are looking for a matt finish and a weight that settles against the skin. Build this collection slowly. Acquire pieces through careful iteration. When you put a garment on, apply the breath test. Take a deep inhalation. If the fabric restricts your ribcage or forces a change in your natural posture to accommodate the cut, reject the item. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Breath does not.\n\nYour core style formula is close drape + mobile layers + one warm point of light. Put this together with a fine gauge cashmere rollneck that traces the line of your torso. Add an unlined camel hair overcoat left open to shift as you move. Anchor it with a solitary gold cuff resting against the matt sleeve. Check every combination against these three mechanics. If the base layer stands stiffly away from the body, the outerwear locks you in place, or the metal finish lacks that singular warm gleam, change the garments until the equilibrium is restored.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat this as the structural foundation of your wardrobe, the central logic you return to when an outfit feels wrong.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Test ventilation before buying anything new. Press the textile to your mouth and blow outwards. If air hits your palm, the fabric breathes. If it traps the air, drop it. Let this tactile feedback guide your sourcing. Look for {texture_good_1} in your winter knitwear to create a close drape that compresses and bounces back. Choose {texture_good_2} for your bags and belts, allowing the surface to mould to your grip and develop a matt patina over time. Source {texture_good_3} for tailored coats to hold clean lines for years. Use {texture_good_4} for blouses to build fluid, mobile layers under heavier jackets. Complete the structure with one warm point of light in your metal hardware. These are your reliable tools.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your wardrobe strictly from materials that respond to your body heat and movement.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
