    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Reject anything that traps heat or snaps back against the body. When you pick up {texture_bad_1}, scrunch it in your fist. If it crinkles like a sweet wrapper and feels slick with an artificial sheen, leave it on the rail. It will ruin a close drape by sitting stiffly over your frame. Assess {texture_bad_2} for airflow by holding it against a steaming cup. If the vapour hits a solid wall and condenses, the material will suffocate your skin. Avoid anything that demands constant adjustment. If {texture_bad_3} clings with static or catches on the piece underneath, it interrupts your mobile layers. Rely strictly on tactile evidence over the label.",
      "sectionIntro": "Identify the materials that actively fight your body and ruin your silhouette.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Anchor your wardrobe in the strict tension between {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Pair a heavy matt wool trouser with a fluid {texture_good_1} shirt. Drape the fabric over your forearm and walk a few steps. If the material swings stiffly instead of rippling, drop the piece immediately. You require materials that yield to the body. Seek dense construction that delivers close drape without suffocating the skin. Guide your muted finishes towards a warm palette to keep the overall effect grounded.",
      "sectionIntro": "Combine contrasting textiles to anchor your wardrobe in physical reality.",
      "tests": [
        "the breath test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Keep your colours warm to support your structure. Establish your opaque groundwork with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Look for {core_colour_3} and {core_colour_4} as intermediate links to unite your mobile layers. Deploy {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as your single deliberate accent. Let the relief tone enter as a soft note used sparingly. Pass over Icy electric blue, Neon brights, and Fleeting trend pastels. Beware the dissolution trap. Stacking sheer layers without a foundation makes your silhouette vanish. Fix this by restoring definition with close drape. Slide a bias-cut slip that maps your shape underneath, or position a fitted layer nearest the skin to rebuild your outline.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your palette as a set of architectural materials, building definition from the skin outward.",
