    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "In the office, close drape leads the combination. Build the foundation with brushed wool or fine cashmere sitting near the collarbone in rich toffee. Support this inner structure with mobile layers that swing freely over the body. Provide illumination with one warm point of light, like a solitary glint of amber or brass. Apply strict continuity to your entire wardrobe. Drafting emails at a back desk requires the exact same tailored precision in your camel trousers as a board presentation. Evaluate garments by their physical weight in your palms. Aesthetics deceive, but heavy cloth tells the truth. Keep your dual metals grounded, letting a matt silver ring sit beside a muted gold watch.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your formula to the working week by leading with structure and relying on the physical weight of your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In low light, shadows blur sharp edges. Reach for matt silk and heavy, dark amber knits. Grip the garment. It must feel substantial, never flimsy. Warm tones perform best in dim rooms. Wear brushed cashmere near the skin to maintain your close drape. Treat evening wear with strict realism. A quiet dinner at home demands the same exact sartorial standard as a private tasting menu. Reject stiff items. Choose mobile layers that trace the shoulder. Mix brushed silver and matt gold at the wrist to catch the candlelight as your one warm point of light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your evening wear entirely on how the fabric behaves in dim rooms.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Build your morning routine around the strict application of close drape + mobile layers + one warm point of light. Do not lower your standard for a mundane walk to the pharmacy. A quick errand for gardening supplies deserves the exact same muted finishes and precise fit as any high-stakes meeting. Choose an unlined brushed wool coat over a matt silk blouse in a warm rust hue. Let the inner fabric sit firmly against the body. Fasten a piece of dual-register metal jewellery to the wrist. Gauge the tension of the seams against your frame. Photographs deceive, but the physical drag of quality cloth never does. Let that tactile gravity anchor your daily choices.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your morning routine as the uncompromising baseline for your entire wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "a hardware store run deserves the same clean fit as a Monday meeting (Flint)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your hardware strategy separates the jewellery touching your skin from the fasteners building your garments. Keep personal pieces restricted to {personal_metal_1} and {personal_metal_2}. For structural elements like zip pulls and bag clasps, source {structural_metal_1} and {structural_metal_2}. Brilliant mirror finishes create a harsh, distracting glare against your warm textiles. Fix this visual friction by insisting on matt or heavily brushed surfaces that blend quietly into your foundations. Ban {excluded_finish} altogether. Test every buckle or heavy chain by lifting it in your palm. Hollow metal betrays itself immediately. Trust your fingers to reject cheap casting. Heavy, solid zips give structure to your mobile layers, while substantial pendants sit perfectly flat across your close drape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Your hardware strategy divides strictly between the pieces you wear and the fasteners that construct your clothing.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Anchor your mobile layers with stones that hold their ground through density rather than sparkle. Select {stone_1} and {stone_2} for their opaque, clouded depth. Gleaming, highly faceted gems look unpleasantly sharp and distracting next to your soft muted colours. Rely on tumbled, brushed, or matt surfaces to maintain a cohesive, warm finish. Evaluate any new piece by lifting it from the display. Assess the raw weight in your hand. Your stones must carry enough gravity to pull a cashmere collar into place. A substantial piece of {stone_3} provides one warm point of light, giving the eye a solid anchor without demanding attention through sharp glare.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate stones by their physical density rather than their sparkle to select pieces that truly ground your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift every piece of {metal_1} before you put it on. Weight reveals quality instantly. If a ring or cuff feels light and hollow, leave it behind. Solid hardware provides the gravity required to ground your mobile layers and keep them from floating away. Avoid mirror-like surfaces that clash harshly with the soft fibres of your wardrobe. Opt exclusively for matt and brushed textures to maintain aesthetic cohesion. Let a dense piece of {stone_1} sit quietly over a knit that maintains close drape. This physical density ensures your hardware aligns with the quiet, warm register of your entire closet.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply these tactile rules to anchor your jewellery.",
      "tests": [
