          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Burgundy",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Plum",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Misty blue-green",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the sofa drift: soften every piece far enough and one day you are simply in loungewear",
          "fix": "restore exactly one line: a rolled but real lapel, a trouser with a soft crease, or a firm leather bag against all that give"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, structure takes the lead. Establish strict physical boundaries using the firm edge of a full-grain leather briefcase or the severe cut of a jacket. Let the remaining elements play a quiet, supporting role. Keep hidden depth entirely private. A silk lining or brushed wool interior exists strictly for your own physical validation. Assess a blazer by lifting it off the hanger. If it lacks internal architecture, reject it. Trust your hands to gauge the heft of a cloth before it touches your shoulders. Anchor the warm, matt colour palette in camel and rich toffee. Finish the composition with yellow gold or brass and a touch of quiet depth at the cuff. Dress exclusively to protect your own focus.",
      "sectionIntro": "Dress for the working day by establishing strict physical boundaries.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim lighting and close quarters, a touch of quiet depth takes the lead. Rely on your physical intuition to select your evening pieces. Let the fabric speak for itself in low light. Select rich toffee silk and thick camel cashmere that absorb ambient light rather than reflect it. Keep your warm yellow gold jewellery matt and close to the skin. Retreat from ostentatious displays, and focus strictly on how the cloth drapes over your shoulders. Evaluate every item by its weave and finish. Reject anything that feels flimsy or requires constant adjustment. Keep your silhouette strictly self-contained, ensuring every piece possesses genuine hidden depth to ground the evening.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the low-light environment by strictly controlling what others experience at close range.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A damp morning walk to fetch the newspaper requires an unyielding standard. This routine demands an identical level of care as any formal event. Button a warm camel brushed wool coat over a simple silk shirt just to buy cough syrup at the pharmacy. Grip the handle of a rich toffee full-grain leather bag. Let the raw heft anchor your posture before you step outside. Your daily dress relies entirely on structure + hidden depth + a touch of quiet depth. Reject the temptation to lower your guard for mundane tasks. Pull on a heavy cashmere sweater and ensure the matt fibres hold their shape against your frame.",
      "sectionIntro": "Approach your everyday errands as a strict testing ground for your physical instincts.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your metal strategy sits firmly in the warm spectrum. Anchor your garments with {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Lift the clasp or zip in your palm. Gauge the quality by feeling the pull in your hand. Heavy, solid metal confirms the piece possesses the structure and hidden depth you require. Avoid high-glare surfaces entirely. A highly polished {excluded_finish} buckle cuts a sharp, distracting line against warm, matt cloth. Fix this by demanding brushed or antiqued hardware that melts into the textile, keeping the garment cohesive.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test every piece of hardware for structural integrity and visual cohesion.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Anchor your structure with opaque materials that hold warmth, like {stone_1} and {stone_2}. Lift the jewellery in your palm to test its value. Let pure mass dictate the purchase. A proper stone sits heavy against your collarbone. Avoid highly reflective polished chrome or glaring silver. These high-shine finishes clash aggressively against a muted palette and break your visual continuity. Stick strictly to matt and brushed metal settings to maintain a cohesive surface. This treatment lets the hidden depth of your chosen stones take focus.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select stones that ground your structure rather than fight for attention.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift a {metal_1} buckle or a piece of {stone_1} jewellery and let it rest in your palm. Rely on your hands to evaluate the item. A substantial object confirms its own quality. Avoid high-gloss finishes entirely. A highly polished metal creates a sharp, distracting glare against warm, muted garments like a {core_colour_1} coat. Stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the styling cohesive. These subdued surfaces ensure your hardware provides solid structure and genuine hidden depth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your metals and stones by feel before you evaluate them by sight.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You have established structure and secured hidden depth in your garments. Now finalize the composition with a touch of quiet depth. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with handbags. Select full-grain leather or thick, warm suede equipped with matt brushed hardware. Put every new addition through the shake test before you buy it. Hold the bag by its handle and give it a firm, sudden shake. A superior skin will send a slow, heavy wave down its length. Weak synthetics will merely flutter and snap. Trust your hands. Movement reveals the truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this final filter to your accessories to ensure they serve the look rather than distract from it.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Treat scarves as the final layer of structure for your shoulders. Demand generous silk or fine woven wool in a warm camel or rich toffee. Apply the drape test before bringing the piece home. Place the fabric over a hard surface and watch how the edges settle. The material must collapse into heavy pools rather than jutting out in stiff peaks. Rely entirely on tactile feedback. Seek out strictly matt finishes. A shiny surface creates unwanted glare, whereas a matt weave creates hidden depth inside the folded cloth. Reject anything sparse. The heft must settle securely against your neck.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply rigorous physical standards to the fabric you drape around your collar.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your trousers with wide full-grain leather belts. Look for a matt brushed buckle to establish a warm, muted finish. Treat your keepsake jewellery the same way. Choose a deep carnelian stone set in oxidised brass or aged silver. These specific pieces provide structure and contain hidden depth. Run the momentum test before you step out. Walk three swift paces and halt. If a pendant swings wildly or a belt buckle pulls your waistband into sharp creases, the item fails. Remove the piece immediately to preserve your self-contained silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Lock down your silhouette with hardware that performs a deliberate physical job.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Let your tailored jackets and trousers draw their pattern from woven structure. Keep your fluid garments anchored in low-contrast, tonal prints. Trust your physical instincts to judge the balance. Assess the motif in low light to guarantee it softens appropriately. Ensure the design allows your eye to settle into a warm, moving texture rather than catching on jarring edges. Seek out {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} to build hidden depth. Step away from stark graphics. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. Keep the overall approach muted. Rely on the actual weave to provide visual interest rather than harsh colour breaks.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the geometry of your garments by evaluating every motif against the requirements of physical weave and tonal restraint.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Subject your garments to the dusk test. Hang a jacket featuring {recommended_pattern_1} across the room as the daylight fades. Step back and squint. Trust your physical reaction to the blur. A successful print dissolves into a warm haze, losing its distinct edges entirely. If the motif remains sharply legible in the shadows, leave it on the rail. You require prints that settle into the background to anchor the structure of your silhouette. This visual softening guarantees the cloth retains its hidden depth. Retreat from high contrasts. The fabric must yield to the twilight and blend smoothly. This optical check ensures every piece remains contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this optical check to ensure your prints serve your core style.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_scorpio__moon_libra__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "close drape + cool composure + one warm point of light",
    "closing": "Trust the weight of your garments to lead your hands directly toward close drape + cool composure + one warm point of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the physical drop of a garment against your skin. This is your sensory compass. If a piece stands away from your frame or feels rigid, leave it on the hanger. Your core style formula is close drape + cool composure + one warm point of light. Picture a dense woven top resting cleanly over tailored trousers, finished with a single, warm glint of light near the collarbone. The fabric must fall near the body without clinging. It must look composed and finished before you even think about adding extras.\n\nBuild your foundation slowly. Scrutinise every seam and hem. Deploy your outfits fast, trusting your hands to pull components that already align. Drift by mood when selecting your finishing details. You must apply the melt test to every new acquisition. Put the piece on and wait for the material to settle. The garment must yield to your frame, softening into a clean line that mirrors your exact posture. If the construction feels rigid or acts like a separate shell built around you, take it off. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this blueprint to build a wardrobe that relies on physical instinct and exact balance.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "To build cool composure, your materials must carry physical weight and absolute integrity. Look for {texture_good_1} in your winter layers. It must compress under your fingers and bounce back instantly. Find {texture_good_3} for your tailored blazers to hold clean lines for years. Seek {texture_good_4} for blouses that offer close drape and fluid movement over your collarbones. Ground these garments with {texture_good_2} in your footwear and belts, letting the grain patinate and mould to your grip. Always run the wrist test. Hold the material against the thin skin of your inner arm for ten seconds. If it scratches or traps heat, drop it immediately. Let your nerves deliver the final verdict. Hunt for the specific textures below.",
