    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Master your silhouette through strict close drape. Secure that cool composure. Finally, anchor the outfit with exactly one warm point of light. Keep the additions minimal, allowing only one or two strong pieces per look. Start by assessing your handbags. Look for thick full-grain leather constructed with brushed matt hardware. Let your touch confirm the quality. Apply the ripple test directly to the material. Press your thumb hard across the unstitched hide. You want to see heavy, slow waves form under the pressure. If the skin breaks into tight, shallow creases, drop the bag and walk away. Ignore the brand name. True structural integrity speaks through the leather itself.",
      "sectionIntro": "Mastering accessories demands strict editing and a ruthless reliance on physical touch over visual appeal.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Look exclusively for scarves in silk or fine wool. Subject every piece to the drop test. Gather the fabric in both hands and release it onto a solid surface. Watch how the material settles. A proper textile in warm camel or rich toffee falls instantly into heavy, fluid folds. A poor imitation will trap air and sit stiffly. Rely on your fingers to gauge this density. The right material anchors the garment without adding bulk. Avoid high sheen entirely. Choose a completely matt finish to maintain cool composure. Fold the length tight and knot it at the collarbone to secure that close drape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your secondary textiles by hand to separate true density from empty volume.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your waist with a medium full-grain leather belt. Look for a warm camel tone and insist on a strictly matt buckle. For keepsake jewellery, select oxidised, aged silver. Run your thumb over the blackened grooves of an old ring. Ground your cool composure in these muted finishes. Evaluate the close drape of the metal against your collarbone. Finish by executing the focal check. Stand back and remove any accessory that breaks the quiet, unified surface of your silhouette. Keep your hardware restricted to one warm point of light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this final protocol to select and audit your concluding details.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored garments take their pattern from the weave itself. Fluid pieces take theirs from the dye. Enforce a strict low-contrast tonal rule for every motif to secure cool composure. Select {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2}. Skip {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. Apply the dusk test. If the print does not settle into a warm, moving texture as the light drops, leave it on the rail. Feel the yarn to confirm its grade. Woven density proves the true quality. Ensure the fabric providing close drape uses pattern only to enhance the matt finish, never to break it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as an extension of the physical weave, not a surface decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Carry any {recommended_pattern_1} into a dimly lit space and retreat ten paces. Watch the fabric closely. The individual lines must dissolve. The surface should settle into a warm, moving texture rather than a rigid graphic block. If the design stays sharp in the shadows, drop the garment. A successful motif behaves like a matt vibration across the cloth. This subtle blurring secures cool composure. Ignore the harsh overhead lighting of the fitting room. When the colour melts into deep shadow, the piece is right.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this specific lighting test to ensure your chosen pattern dissolves into the correct texture.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_scorpio__moon_virgo__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "close drape + honest fabric + one warm point of light",
    "closing": "Let your physical boundaries define the silhouette, guided always by close drape + honest fabric + one warm point of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the physical weight of a garment against your collarbone and the friction under your fingers. Your physical instinct is pure function. If a jacket restricts your reach or requires constant adjusting, drop it immediately. Your baseline is close drape + honest fabric + one warm point of light. Picture a densely knitted jumper that follows the line of your ribs, tucked into sturdy woven trousers, and finished by a solitary muted pendant catching the ambient glare. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.\n\nCurate your collection slowly. Evaluate every seam and hem over time. Once the garments are yours, deploy them fast. Dress according to your immediate internal requirements and drift by mood. Run the flight test on every new prospect. Grip the fabric and ask yourself if you could sprint across a departures hall, hoist a heavy bag, and sit for six hours without a twisted sleeve or a digging waistband. If the piece demands delicate handling or limits your stride, leave it behind. You dress entirely for your own physical reality.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your structural foundation and your primary filtering mechanism.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Seek out an honest fabric that supports a close drape and sets the stage for one warm point of light. Rely on direct tactile feedback when selecting these core materials. Look for matt finishes that absorb the surrounding glare. Put every potential purchase through a pack check. Stuff the garment into a crowded holdall for a long journey. If it emerges uncreased and ready for immediate wear, keep it. Secure {texture_good_1} for shirting with strict architectural boundaries. Choose {texture_good_2} for base layers that hold sharp lines close to your body. Select {texture_good_3} for trousers that resist creasing through heavy movement. Finish your layering with {texture_good_4} to block wind without adding dead weight. Start your selection with the ranked list below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to identify the specific materials that support your daily structural requirements.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Leave {texture_bad_1} on the rack. It generates static, refusing a close drape and clinging poorly to the skin. Pass over {texture_bad_2} when it feels slippery and hollow between your fingers. These materials lack the warm resilience you require. Apply a crush gauge to every new piece. Compress a sleeve tightly in your fist for ten seconds and release it. If the item retains deep creases, it will never survive being packed in a travel case. Visual presentations deceive the eye, but a tactile response gives you exact data. Touch does not lie.",
      "sectionIntro": "Identify the materials that undermine your structural baseline.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Judge a piece by its drag and tension in your hands before putting it on. Visuals distort the truth. The heavy drop of a material reveals its true quality. Test every piece against an endurance metric. Fold the item tightly, press it down, and check the recovery. If it traps a rigid fold or restricts your reach, drop it. You require close drape to build a self-contained silhouette. Combine {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to establish this functional base. Keep the surface strictly matt. Layer in {texture_good_1} when you need slight variation, and finish the combination with a single warm detail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Lock in your baseline textures and eliminate anything that fails to perform under pressure.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your spectrum must remain unequivocally warm. Anchor your base in {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Substitute blinding whites with {core_colour_3}. Use {core_colour_4} to bridge gaps between contrasting pieces. Reserve {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} as deliberate accents. Treat your relief tone purely as a quiet note used sparingly to soften edges. Skip icy pastel, neon brights, and cold blue-grey entirely. Combine these tones with close drape to build your silhouette. Catch the armour reflex. When days accelerate, avoid grabbing rigid tactical coats or stiff utilitarian outerwear. Drop the carapace. Trade that rigid barrier for a sueded cotton layer that matches your momentum and provides genuine comfort.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assemble your palette with intent, using tone as a strict boundary for your physical choices.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Warm taupe",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft cream",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sand beige",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Warm stone",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Olive drab",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Espresso brown",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rust orange",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Ochre gold",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Pale clay",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the hard shell: reaching for armour, technical jackets, and stiff utility layers when life speeds up",
          "fix": "swap the shell for a brushed cotton layer that moves just as fast and holds you besides"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, let honest fabric take the lead. Worsted wool trousers and crisp cotton poplin shirts establish a self-contained baseline. Rely on close drape across the shoulder to maintain this structure. Sitting in a budget meeting does not require collapsing your silhouette into shapeless corporate garments. Maintain your form. Finish the attire by introducing a single warm brass or matt gold accent at the wrist. Trust your hands. If the cloth feels flimsy, leave it on the rack.",
      "sectionIntro": "Construct your working garments around structure rather than decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "paying a utility bill does not require collapsing your silhouette (Blaze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "When the lighting drops in a private dining room, let close drape lead. Low ambient bulbs absorb subtle textures. Pick up a fine ribbed merino sweater or a worsted wool jacket. Gauge the density in the weave directly. Let your tactile senses govern your choices because physical weight never deceives you. Keep your silhouette sharp even in solitude. Drafting an email at the kitchen counter does not demand collapsing your outline into an oversized jersey. Build a warm taupe or camel base. Anchor the neck with a matt gold chain or a bronze pendant. These dual-register warm metals catch just enough ambient glow in dim spaces without breaking your self-contained perimeter.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply these rules when adapting your style for intimate evening spaces.",
      "tests": [
        "paying a utility bill does not require collapsing your silhouette (Blaze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Standing in line at the post office does not require collapsing your outline. Treat an ordinary Tuesday morning errand with strict exactitude. Reach for a worsted wool trouser in camel or a crisp cotton poplin shirt in warm taupe. Pick up the garment and test the seams. Expect a completely matt surface. Your baseline expectation remains close drape + honest fabric + one warm point of light, regardless of the destination. Keep a muted bronze or rose gold ring as that singular detail. A mundane task never justifies abandoning your boundaries.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hold your ordinary Tuesday routines to the exact same rigorous standard you apply to a formal obligation.",
      "tests": [
        "paying a utility bill does not require collapsing your silhouette (Blaze)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Divide your hardware into two strict categories. Keep {personal_metal_1} and {personal_metal_2} directly against the skin. Treat these personal metals as solitary components that sit flush against honest fabric. For the functional zips, shoe buckles, and bag clasps, use {structural_metal_1} and {structural_metal_2}. Ensure the underlying temperature remains warm across your entire wardrobe. Exclude {excluded_finish} from all garments and jewellery to maintain a matt, self-contained aesthetic. Test every buckle and zip in your hands. Pick the garment up. An external finish can easily trick the eye, but absolute solid mass is undeniable. Avoid hammered copper, antiqued brass, and any artificially aged metal. Fake patina creates visual clutter against a present-tense style. Keep strictly to pure silver, platinum, white gold, or mirror chrome for your hardware.",
      "sectionIntro": "Manage your hardware strictly by separating what touches your skin from what holds your garments together.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select stones that sit heavy against the skin. Pick the piece up and let it rest in your palm. Surface treatments manipulate light, but gravity grounds your choice. Choose {stone_1} and {stone_2} for their opaque, matt finish. Anchor your honest fabric with a warm, strict geometry, opting for flat slab cuts over faceted clusters. Artificial aging and hammered textures read as distracting clutter against a contained wardrobe. Keep to purely reflective, highly polished settings to frame {stone_3} sharply.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware through strict criteria of density and precise geometry to ground your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Drop every piece of {metal_1} into your palm before you wear it. Your grip measures reality. Refuse any piece that lacks absolute physical heft. Trust this gravitational pull. When placing hardware against any honest fabric, refuse manufactured history. Beaten copper, treated brass, and artificially tarnished alloys disrupt your focus. Leave them on the tray. Build your foundation with brilliant silver, dense platinum, white gold, or high-gloss chrome instead. These clear, unmarked finishes respect a self-contained approach and provide a warm contrast to matt textiles.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test every piece of hardware in your hands before it touches your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your foundation relies on honest fabric. Your silhouette demands close drape. Accessories provide the finish, delivering exactly one warm point of light. Limit yourself to a single structural piece per look. Begin with the wrist. Secure a watch with a brushed steel case. Select a leather or steel strap with a matt brushed finish. Apply a strip-back protocol before leaving the house. Unclasp the watch and leave it on the table. If your fine ribbed merino knit and camel trousers suddenly feel empty, your base is too weak. You have used the hardware as a crutch. Put the watch back on only when the garments can stand alone. Trust your hands to feel the difference.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is how you anchor your clothing with hardware.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Watch",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "brushed steel case, leather or steel strap, matt brushed"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Belts must serve the structural needs of the outfit. Look for medium width straps cut from vegetable-tanned leather. Fasten them with a matt brushed buckle. The metal hardware should reflect your dual register approach. Alternate between warm brass and muted steel depending on the trousers. Feel the heft of the strap. Trust your physical senses. The visual presentation will deceive you, but the genuine weight of the material provides facts. A reliable belt anchors the waist without interrupting the close drape. If the hardware catches the eye before the garment does, conduct a hardware audit. Unbuckle the strap and leave it on the table. An accessory must sit quietly alongside your honest fabric. It must remain self-contained rather than demanding attention.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your proportions with hardware that serves the garment.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "vegetable-tanned leather, medium width, matt brushed buckle"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Source an honest fabric for your primary bag. Pick up a heavy canvas and leather tote, or evaluate a firm briefcase. Inspect the zips, rings, and buckles closely. They demand strictly matt hardware, executed in subdued steel or a warm brass. Finish your process with an isolation check. Stand at the mirror and physically remove your most prominent addition. If your self-contained shape remains fully intact without it, abandon the removed item on the table. It was simply generating visual noise rather than serving a true mechanical function.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your final practical additions and verify your structural boundaries with a strict physical test.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "canvas and leather tote or briefcase, matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the take-off test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Test every pattern on your body. Tailored garments take their visual rhythm from the physical weave. Fluid pieces accept printed motifs. Adapt your contrast levels to the day. Shift between low-contrast tonal weaves for structured situations and distinct contrast when the environment allows it. Stand in front of a mirror and walk. The design must resolve into a soft, pleasant texture in motion rather than a stiff graphic block. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. Favour {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} instead. Base these choices in honest fabric. Maintain close drape. Let the matt surface dominate, leaving room for exactly one warm point of light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your visual noise by grounding every pattern in physical movement.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the Ten-Pace Motion Test. Stand across the room from a mirror and walk briskly towards the glass. Watch how {recommended_pattern_1} behaves. It must dissolve into an agreeable texture as you move. A passing print will blur into a warm wash of colour rather than remaining a sharp graphic. The design must function strictly as honest fabric. It must drape cleanly without projecting a rigid shape of its own. Avoid anything that forces a viewer to decode a complex motif. If the design stays loud and legible while you walk, leave it on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this physical test to evaluate whether a print serves your structure or fights against it.",
      "tests": [
        "the passing test (reads as soft, pleasant texture in motion)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_taurus__moon_pisces__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "soft structure + blurred edges + a touch of quiet depth",
    "closing": "Trust your hands to steer you past rigid interference and directly towards soft structure + blurred edges + a touch of quiet depth.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Ground your clothing choices in touch and friction. Seek out garments that feel substantial in the hand but sit completely silently on the body. Keep your overall temperature warm, and demand strict adherence to your core formula of soft structure + blurred edges + a touch of quiet depth. Picture a relaxed, unlined jacket draped over a fine-gauge top, paired with fluid tailored trousers that break gently over a simple slip-on shoe. The pieces must interact smoothly. If a collar feels stiff against your neck or a shoulder pad dictates your movement, put the item back on the rail.\n\nBuild your wardrobe slowly and deliberately. Maintain a strictly self-contained approach to dressing. Rely entirely on the melt test for every new addition. When you put on a garment, wait ten seconds. The material must yield to your body heat, softening into your exact posture rather than enforcing its own rigid shape. If a piece stands away from your frame or requires constant physical adjustment, reject it. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. A garment's ability to dissolve into your physical form does not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the physical and visual rules that dictate how your clothes must behave.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Look for textiles that absorb light to create a matt finish and offer a warm touch against the skin. Build your foundation with {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight, and {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Apply the exhalation test before you purchase. Press the fabric to your lips and blow outwards. If the air moves easily through the fibres, the garment will drape properly to give you soft structure and blurred edges. Turn to {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth, and {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every seam. Let tactile feedback guide you, and hunt for the specific materials ranked below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the textiles that will build your foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed alpaca",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "enveloping winter coats and oversized cardigans"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fluid modal jersey",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers that follow the body without ever gripping it"
        },
