    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, soft structure leads. Establish a clear, self-contained framework in your tailoring. Support this primary shape with blurred edges at the collar or cuff, and ground the outfit with a touch of quiet depth in bitter chocolate or dark mahogany. Apply the desktop test to every piece. Organising mundane paperwork does not require flattening your physical form into rigid, lifeless office wear. Depend on your hands to verify the right drape. Hangers lie, but the heavy fall of silk crepe or the dense warmth of boiled wool tells the truth. Avoid stiff collars and high-contrast patterns. Select warm, matt finishes.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your working hours as a physical practice, relying on your garments as functional tools rather than rigid corporate costumes.",
      "tests": [
        "paying a utility bill does not require collapsing your silhouette (Blaze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "When moving into low light and close quarters, let soft structure dictate your choices. Choose heavy silk crepe in dark mahogany or washed silk in bitter chocolate. The fabric must drape without clinging. Look for a matt gold pendant or a smoky quartz ring to gather the dim lighting. Let your fingers evaluate the garments. Mirrors mislead. Textile density does not. Paying the evening tab at a local restaurant does not mean letting your shape collapse into unconsidered loungewear. Keep your self-contained lines intact even when dressing down for the night. Maintain the muted finish of the cloth and let the deep warm tones do the work.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the transition into low light by letting your hands dictate the drape.",
      "tests": [
        "paying a utility bill does not require collapsing your silhouette (Blaze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Running errands does not mean abandoning your silhouette. Keep your standard intact for mundane routines. Your baseline is always soft structure + blurred edges + a touch of quiet depth. Assemble your daily layers using warm tones and matt textiles. Reach for a heavy silk crepe shirt in dark mahogany. Pair it with cloud-soft lambswool trousers. Let the textiles drape closely to your frame. Exploit the dense weight of the material to maintain its shape while you wait in a queue. Do not downgrade to harsh synthetics or stiff cottons. Anchor the outfit with simple brushed gold hardware.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your foundational rules to ordinary tasks without dropping your standard.",
      "tests": [
        "paying a utility bill does not require collapsing your silhouette (Blaze)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your hardware strategy is strictly warm. Root your choices in {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. A high-shine, polished surface clashes severely with your warm, muted garments. Anchor the details with matt and brushed textures to maintain visual cohesion. Look for blurred edges on every buckle to match the soft structure of your tailoring. Lift the item and gauge its heft in your palm, whether it is a simple zip or heavy jewellery. Surface finishes trick the eye, but the absolute gravity of a solid {metal_1} piece remains constant. Avoid {excluded_finish} entirely to keep your metals grounded and self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Assess every clasp and buckle as a critical architectural element of your styling.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Handle the stone directly. Reflections distort reality, but pure mass acts as a reliable metric. Your hardware must carry a dense, heavy presence to ground the soft structure of your clothing. Look for {stone_1} and {stone_2}. These materials pull light inward rather than scattering it outward. They maintain a strictly self-contained, warm presence. Avoid faceted, brilliant cuts entirely. High-shine polish creates a sharp, distracting glare against your muted colours. Insist on matt and softly brushed textures to keep the aesthetic perfectly cohesive and preserve the blurred edges of your silhouette. A smooth cabochon of {stone_3} provides immense gravity without breaking focus.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select stones that absorb light rather than refracting it, demanding dense substance over surface shine.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Test any piece of {metal_1} by tossing it lightly in the air. Ignore the visual presentation. Downward pull is the only fact that matters. Demand profound physical density from your accessories. Heavy hardware grounds a warm wardrobe. Polished, high-shine metal creates a harsh glare that ruins a muted aesthetic. It appears glaringly aggressive next to soft colours. Prevent this clash by selecting a flat matt surface or a brushed finish. This approach keeps the focus inward and protects your blurred edges.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn how to assess your hardware through touch alone.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You have built the soft structure. You have established the blurred edges. Now use your hardware and leather to secure a touch of quiet depth. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Start with handbags. Look for full-grain leather or thick suede finished with warm, matt brushed hardware. Execute the wave test. Suspend the bag by its strap and jolt it once. The material must undulate and fall back into place heavily. If the leather stays rigid, leave it on the shelf. Rely on motion for your final verdict. Stillness hides flaws. Kinetic response reveals the actual quality. Anchor the aesthetic with dark mahogany and bitter chocolate details.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your finishing elements with strict physical discipline.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Subject every scarf to the drop check. Release the fabric above a table and watch it hit the surface. It must pool into slow, fluid waves. If the textile holds a rigid fold or forms a hollow tent, reject it immediately. Look for generous silk or fine wool with a completely matt finish. Prioritise blurred edges over sharp, machined hems to maintain a self-contained profile. Anchor these pieces in warm shades that match your primary metals. Grip the textile to verify the drape. A successful piece delivers soft structure through weight, never stiffness.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply absolute physical criteria when selecting textiles to wrap around the neck.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor the waist with a wide full-grain leather belt featuring a matt brushed buckle. Select keepsake jewellery that feels deliberately grounded. Pick a deep stone set in warm oxidised brass. To finish, evaluate the visual surface tension of your outfit. Put on the final piece and study the impact. If the item creates a sudden focal point that breaks your soft structure, take it off immediately. Every addition must sink quietly into the overall silhouette without causing a disturbance. Maintain blurred edges, rejecting any sharp reflection that bounces outward.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your proportions and verify your accessories with a single mechanical test.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the ripple test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Your tailored pieces take their pattern strictly from the weave itself. Rely on {recommended_pattern_1} or a muted {recommended_pattern_2} to establish soft structure. Fluid garments behave differently. Introduce blurred edges through a tonal {recommended_pattern_3}. Your contrast rule dictates low-contrast, tonal relationships only. High-contrast graphics belong in another wardrobe entirely. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and any sharp {avoid_pattern_2}. Apply the twilight review to every printed garment you consider. Examine the fabric in dim lighting. The motif must settle into a warm, moving texture. If the design stays stark and demanding, drop the hanger and move on.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate pattern as a subtle extension of the cloth, never a separate graphic layer.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Execute the distance check on {recommended_pattern_1}. Hang the garment in a shadowed room, step back three paces, and squint. The print must not register as distinct, hard shapes. You are looking for blurred edges. The design should settle into a warm, moving texture that only reveals its intricacy up close. If the motif remains sharp from afar, leave it on the rack. Your aesthetic requires soft structure, not rigid geometry. The pattern must melt into the weave and stay strictly self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test every pattern for its ability to soften and recede before you buy it.",
      "tests": [
        "the dusk test (settle into a warm, moving texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_taurus__moon_leo__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "structure + athletic space + a touch of quiet depth",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on structure + athletic space + a touch of quiet depth.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the sheer physical weight of a garment in your hands as your primary compass. Pick it up and feel the density of the weave. Your baseline is structure + athletic space + a touch of quiet depth. Picture a heavy, warm camel cashmere crewneck layered over flat-front wool flannel trousers, cut with enough room through the thigh to let you move freely. Finish it with soft suede loafers. The look relies entirely on the precise cut of the cloth and the undeniable quality of the fibres. Ignore the label. If the fabric feels thin or rigid, drop it.\n\nBuild your wardrobe slowly, investing only in pieces that meet your exact physical criteria. Once owned, deploy them fast and forget about them. Test every potential new item against your body. If you put something on and instantly feel a sudden urge to adjust a collar or tug at a restrictive hem, take it off immediately. Trust your gut reaction to a garment's restriction and walk away. A piece must sit securely on your frame while giving you complete physical freedom. If a jacket forces you to hold your shoulders tightly to maintain its shape, it fails. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight and construction do not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this framework to strip away the noise and evaluate every garment with absolute physical precision.",
      "tests": [
        "trust your gut and walk away"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Seek out materials that hold their shape while leaving room to move. Build structure with {texture_good_3} for coats and blazers that keep a clean line season after season. Layer it over {texture_good_1} knitwear that compresses and bounces back in your grip, giving you athletic space to breathe. For bags and shoes, run the patina test. Ask yourself if the {texture_good_2} will soften and darken where your hands touch it daily, gaining a touch of quiet depth over time rather than peeling or cracking. Ground these sturdy foundations with a lining or blouse in {texture_good_4} for fluid movement. Trust your fingers to find fabrics that absorb warm light into a muted, matt surface.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the materials that build your foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
