    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Trust your fingers to recognise failure before a garment touches your shoulders. Pick up {texture_bad_1}. If it feels slick, rigid, or traps heat, it destroys any sense of athletic space. Drop it. Test {texture_bad_2} by rolling the fabric between your thumb and index finger. If it feels hollow, it lacks the density needed for a balanced drape. Assess the ageing potential of every piece. Ask your hands if the item will slowly gather a warm, matt character over the years, or if it will simply degrade into a shiny mess. Materials like {texture_bad_3} fail this instantly. Their surfaces crack and fray instead of settling into a touch of quiet depth. Labels deceive. Grams confirm the truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to physically reject materials that compromise your foundation.",
      "tests": [
        "the patina test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Anchor your wardrobe in the tension between {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Assess how an item absorbs life. Look for surfaces that map daily friction and grow richer over years of wear, rather than degrading. A {texture_good_1} garment must soften and mould to your physical form. Run your hands over the material. It must feel substantial enough to carve out athletic space, yet remain entirely muted and matt. Avoid anything glossy or rigid. Rely on warm, yielding elements that trace your daily habits and develop a touch of quiet depth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the exact combination of surfaces that grounds your daily uniform.",
      "tests": [
        "the patina test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette runs inherently warm, demanding a matt finish. Root your wardrobe in {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. These form your foundation. Rely on {core_colour_3} and {core_colour_4} as bridge neutrals to connect distinct layers. This base builds essential structure. Apply {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} strictly as your single deliberate accent. Treat your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly. Pass over icy electric blue, neon brights, and fleeting trend pastels. Avoid the trap of an unbroken dark monochrome column. Break that heavy visual block using a cashmere scarf in {accent_colour_1} or a thick full-grain leather belt in {core_colour_2} to maintain athletic space and a touch of quiet depth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your palette by assigning every hue a strict job.",
