    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "You need materials that hold sharp edges. Avoid {texture_bad_1}. Squeeze the fabric tightly for five seconds and let go. If the wrinkles remain, it fails the tension check. It will sag at the joints by noon. Reject {texture_bad_2}. Drag your fingernail across the surface. If the threads snag or shed fibres, put the hanger back. Steer clear of {texture_bad_3}. Rub the weave between your thumb and forefinger. If it feels slick or synthetic, it will trap heat. Your wardrobe relies on rigid geometry. Materials that drape weakly or pill after a single wear destroy that architecture. Rely on your hands to weed out these liabilities.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to reject fabrics that fail your hands before they ever touch your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the recovery test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Anchor your wardrobe on the friction between {sweet_spot_keyword_1} and {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. This combination demands a precise fit and guarantees sharp edges. Before buying, grip a sleeve tightly. Release your hold and watch the fibres. If the item holds the crease and fails to snap back into shape, discard the option. It will fail you within an hour of wear. Introduce {texture_good_1} to keep the surface entirely matt. Your clothes must do the work of maintaining their structure so you do not have to.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the exact combination of fibres that builds your structural foundation.",
      "tests": [
        "the recovery test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette operates on a strictly neutral temperature. Build the framework using {core_colour_1} as your dark base. Layer {core_colour_2} and {core_colour_3} for lighter blocks, then bridge those shifts with {core_colour_4}. Treat {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} as rigid tools to highlight sharp edges. Bring in the soft relief tone purely to break up visual bulk. Ignore neon brights, glitter finishes, and sugary pastels. Beware the beige-out trap. Stacking garments of identical pale values produces an unfinished look. Cut through this flat haze by introducing a solid {core_colour_1} item or a stark {accent_colour_1} strike. Shift the fabric surface to restore depth, keeping all finishes muted and matt. Rely on tactile feedback to evaluate the final combination. Photographs distort colour. Heavy cloth speaks clearly.",
      "sectionIntro": "Map your colours by their exact structural function, applying them as deliberate tools rather than arbitrary choices.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Graphite",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
