    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Test {texture_bad_1} by crushing a handful of the cloth in your fist. Release your grip and watch the reaction. If the material holds deep wrinkles instead of springing back into shape, leave it on the hanger. Your wardrobe relies on dependable form to anchor one meticulous detail, and limp textiles muddy the read. Run your bare palm down {texture_bad_2}. If it drags against the skin or traps unnatural heat, drop it. A self-contained style requires fibres that breathe and hold their lines. Avoid {texture_bad_3} if the finish looks artificially glossy under shop lighting. You need a neutral, matt surface that serves the wearer rather than reflecting the room.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to drop materials that fail the body's baseline checks.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist-flick test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Anchor your wardrobe in the friction of {sweet_spot_keyword_1} worn directly against {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. This pairing guarantees essential softness while maintaining rigid architecture. Subject every new sleeve to the stretch test. Pull the elbow slightly away from your body. The cloth must recover its clean line immediately. If the material bags or collapses into formlessness, leave it on the rail. Relying heavily upon {texture_good_1} ensures the cut holds its form. Keep all surfaces completely matt. You remain entirely self-contained.",
      "sectionIntro": "Lock in your core textural pairing to ensure your clothes carry their own weight.",
      "tests": [
