    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Hang the garment across the room. Step back and squint until your vision blurs. A successful {recommended_pattern_1} must pass this glance test. It should dissolve into a subtle texture with a neutral temperature, never shouting its specific motif at the viewer. You want an impression that integrates flawlessly with a precise fit rather than overwhelming the shape. Look for patterns that read as a quiet hum of thread. If the print distracts from the inherent softness of the fabric, put the item back on the rack. Your aim is self-contained harmony. Let the scale of the design remain modest. Trust your physical reaction to the visual weight. If your eyes dart around the cloth to decode the shapes, the pattern fails the test.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the distance blur test to ensure your patterns serve the garment rather than dominate it.",
      "tests": [
        "the glance test (a pleasant impression rather than a specific shouting motif)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_virgo__moon_sagittarius__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "precise fit + fast movement + one meticulous detail",
    "closing": "Let the physical resistance of the fabric command your choices, trusting your body to intuitively deliver precise fit + fast movement + one meticulous detail.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust physical friction as your primary instinct compass. Put the garment on and move. If the fabric catches on your shoulders or restricts your stride, take it off. Looks lie. Restriction does not. Build your wardrobe slowly to serve a flexible routine, and drift your silhouette by the daily context. Apply the combination test before you acquire anything new. Throw the item on the bed next to three pieces you already own. If it refuses to merge with a neutral knit or a matt jacket, leave it in the shop.\n\nYour baseline equation is precise fit + fast movement + one meticulous detail. Memorise it. Picture a lightweight wool blazer tailored close to the ribs. Layer it over a fine-gauge merino sweater that breathes as you walk. Anchor the outfit with a single brushed steel watch face. The clothing provides the structure, and you supply the speed. Keep the overall finish muted so the tailoring speaks first. Trust your hands to find the correct weight, and reject anything that requires constant adjustment.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation and physical compass, the rules you must apply before you acquire or wear any garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the combination test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe on materials that deliver precise fit and fast movement. Trust your hands when shopping. Looks lie. Weight does not. Perform the snap test. Pull the fabric taut and release it. If it snaps back sharply into place, it will support your active geometry. Seek out {texture_good_1} for shirting that maintains clean architectural boundaries. Rely on {texture_good_2} for base layers that give you sharp lines without restricting motion. For trousers that resist creasing through long hours, choose {texture_good_3}. Finish with {texture_good_4} for lightweight outerwear that blocks wind. These fibres hold a muted, neutral finish. They act as the blank canvas required to support one meticulous detail. Master this hierarchy.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate fabric by how it moves and holds a shape.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "You rely on fast movement throughout the day. Avoid any textile that catches, drags, or dictates your posture. Apply the tension test to every new garment. Grip the hem firmly and stretch the weave. If it sags or ripples lifelessly upon release, leave it on the hanger. {texture_bad_1} clings awkwardly to the skin and restricts your stride. {texture_bad_2} generates friction against other layers, trapping heat and breaking a clean shape. {texture_bad_3} pills rapidly, creating a coarse surface that disrupts your lines. Trust tactile feedback over visual appeal. A sluggish return to form guarantees structural failure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to eliminate the textiles that actively work against your body before you even try them on.",
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Keep edges rigid. Your core pairing contrasts {sweet_spot_keyword_1} against {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Introduce {texture_good_1} to anchor the base. You require textiles with aggressive memory to maintain a precise fit. Scrutinise the sleeve cuff. Crush the material in your fist. If the fabric holds the wrinkles or hesitates to smooth out, leave it on the rack. It must recoil instantly. Demand matt surfaces and heavy metal zips to construct the silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Combine your textiles to guarantee a rigid structure.",
      "tests": [
        "the snap test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your overall temperature is exactly neutral. Construct your foundation with {core_colour_1} as a dark structural base. Balance it with the flat neutrality of {core_colour_2} and the grounding depth of {core_colour_3}. Apply {core_colour_4} to bridge these elements seamlessly. Introduce {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as a single deliberate focal point. Deploy your soft relief tone sparingly when the eye requires a brief rest. Rely on a precise fit to ensure these combinations communicate pure intention. Walk past neon brights, sugary pastels, and glitter finishes. Avoid the trap of a flat monochromatic block that leaves you uninspired by noon. Break the visual expanse by adding a crisp white poplin collar, a structural silver ring, or a sharp geometric sneaker. Trust physical instinct over artificial lighting. Cameras deceive. Verify true hue outdoors.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your palette as a strict structural tool to define shape and direct the eye.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Graphite",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft stone",
          "role": "cool_base"
