    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, precise fit leads. It dictates the silhouette, allowing fast movement to follow naturally as you navigate the day. Support these structural choices with one meticulous detail, perhaps a matt silver watch case or an unassuming platinum tie bar. Establish a neutral base using oatmeal and soft stone. Always evaluate your tailoring with the friction check. If those worsted wool trousers feel too rigid to climb a flight of stairs at a dead sprint, put them back on the hanger. Shop mirrors deceive. Joint mobility gives you the absolute truth. Rely on your instincts to select garments that serve corporate environments and transit corridors with the exact same standard.",
      "sectionIntro": "Demand as much from your workday clothing as you do from your schedule.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In low lighting, a precise fit becomes your primary tool. Close quarters require garments that sit flush without constant adjustment. Keep your colours strictly neutral. Select fine ribbed merino or a dense cotton knit that conforms directly to your frame. Examine how the cloth acts when you sit down. Bend your knees. If the material resists your posture, drop it. Reaching across a candlelit table demands a sleeve that yields softly. Hold all eveningwear to that exact gentle standard. Rely on matt steel cuffs or plain silver rings. Dim spaces easily hide poorly cut seams. Trust the friction against your skin instead.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test garments for close quarters by relying on touch over sight.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Grip the collar of your crisp cotton poplin shirt. Let the tension of the weave guide you. If a technical nylon jacket constricts your arms, leave it on the rack. Anchor your choices around worsted wool in soft stone and oatmeal. Ensure your colour temperature remains strictly neutral. Keep all finishes matt. Choose a brushed steel watch case over high polish. Picking up a prescription from the chemist does not suspend your rules. A damp Tuesday dash for the papers deserves the exact same adaptive standard. Your daily baseline is always precise fit + fast movement + one meticulous detail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your routine errands with the exact same rigour you apply to a major event.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your hardware requires a cool dominant strategy. Focus entirely on {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Maintaining a neutral temperature demands discipline. Hammered copper and antiqued alloys inject messy visual noise into a sharp, modern aesthetic. Rely strictly on pristine, unaged cool metals to maintain visual clarity. Steer clear of any {excluded_finish} finish. Lift a {metal_1} buckle off the table before you buy it. A plated surface fools the eye, but the dense heft of solid hardware never lies. Let this tactile weight guide your purchases. Dense metal grounds clothing engineered for fast movement. Secure a precise fit with a heavy {metal_2} zip pull.",
      "sectionIntro": "Set your standard for hardware by testing the raw, physical weight of the metal.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Evaluate your jewellery by physical density rather than visual appeal. Keep a neutral colour temperature across your hardware. Look for solid, opaque structures that hold light softly, grounding your collection with {stone_1} and {stone_2}. Pick the item up and feel its gravity in your palm. Store lighting deceives. Mass provides the absolute truth. Your accessories must sit flush against the skin to permit fast movement. Avoid artificially aged materials. Cracked resin, porous lava bead, and untreated composites create visual clutter. Discard those distractions. Keep to smooth, unblemished mineral surfaces.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your hardware with stones that carry actual density and metals that reflect light cleanly.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Hold the {metal_1} buckle or {stone_1} setting in your bare hand. Judge its density. Glossy photographs easily deceive. Pure gravity reveals the truth. Heavy hardware grounds your clothing and sits flush against technical nylon. Avoid artificially aged finishes entirely. Scratched zinc and brushed patina inject unwanted vintage degradation into a sharp system. Rely on immaculate mirror chrome and highly polished {metal_1} instead. Clean, dense finishes support fast movement. Flimsy pieces only slow you down.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every new piece of hardware by how it behaves in your hand.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories execute the final step of your method. You have secured a precise fit. You have ensured fast movement. Now you introduce one meticulous detail. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with silk scarves. Seek out a crepe de chine square or a slim band in a matt finish. Subject these items to the knot test. Tie the fabric, move quickly across the room, and check your collar. If the silk spins out of alignment and forces you to manually drag it back to centre, discard the piece. True utility means the shape holds its ground within a neutral palette. Do not tolerate constant adjustments.",
      "sectionIntro": "This section dictates how to anchor your clothing with finishing touches and textiles.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square or slim band, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Evaluate fine jewellery through physical friction. Drag the thin chain around your neck. If the clasp catches on your skin or requires a mirror to right itself, leave it behind. Choose small drops cast in brushed silver to anchor a neutral palette. The metal must remain cool and the finish must remain matt. Demand a precise fit at the collarbone. The piece must slide cleanly back to a balanced resting position during fast movement.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your secondary hardware to support an active frame.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin chain and small drops, brushed silver"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Secure a small structured bag in kid suede. Pick a top-handle shape in soft stone or oatmeal to keep the overall temperature neutral. Look for fine matt hardware in platinum or pale steel. A rigid short strap guarantees a precise fit against your hip. Test the piece by rotating your torso sharply. If the suede drags against your worsted wool coat or the bag swings wide, take it off. Your gear must support fast movement. Drop any item that throws off your physical balance.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject your final additions to strict physical checks.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede top-handle, fine matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the rotation test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Your pattern strategy depends entirely on the garment. Tailored pieces take their geometry directly from the physical weave. Fluid pieces handle printed motifs that distort with fast movement. Keep your contrast adaptable. A versatile approach means shifting from a muted, neutral weave to a clearly defined graphic depending on the context. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. Pick up {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2} instead. Trust your tactile read when inspecting the cloth. Ignore the mannequin. Weight provides the only reliable metric. Apply the distance check. Step back ten feet and snap your eyes open. If the motif collapses into a confusing smudge in that first split second, drop the piece. Anchor the look with a precise fit to ensure the design remains sharp.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate the geometry of the fabric before you introduce visual complexity.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the split-second reflex test before purchasing any patterned garment. Hang the piece across the room, close your eyes, and open them for a single moment. If your {recommended_pattern_1} dissolves into a confusing blur, leave it on the rail. A precise fit demands visual clarity. You require prints that maintain their defined edges during fast movement. Examine the weave of worsted wool or the surface of technical nylon. The geometry must register instantly. If the motif looks muddy from a distance, it will look chaotic in motion. Trust this immediate visual processing as the final verdict.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use this distance check to filter out chaotic prints.",
      "tests": [
        "the blink test (not muddy or confusing in the first split second from ten feet)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_virgo__moon_taurus__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "precise fit + sensory comfort + one meticulous detail",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on precise fit + sensory comfort + one meticulous detail.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the weight of the fabric against your skin as your primary filter. Your wardrobe relies on an unyielding baseline of structure and softness. Run your hand over the seam of a neutral cashmere jumper. Look for the tension of a dense weave that holds its shape. Your guiding equation is precise fit + sensory comfort + one meticulous detail. Picture a tailored wool coat that falls exactly to the calf, worn over a fine gauge silk knit, finished with a single piece of matt steel jewellery. The garments do the work. They enclose you in a private, self-contained architecture.\n\nBuild your wardrobe methodically over time. Acquire garments as permanent tools, allowing you to dress in seconds without hesitation. Before you commit to any piece, apply the wrist test. Drape the fabric over your forearm and check the physical weight against your own bones. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. If the material feels like an imposition or an intrusion, leave it on the hanger. You need clothing that operates quietly on your behalf.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your permanent foundation, the physical rules governing how you build and evaluate your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Subject every new piece to the breath test. Press the cloth against your mouth and exhale slowly. If the barrier feels stifling or traps the air, leave it on the rail. Your wardrobe relies entirely on sensory comfort, requiring materials that respect your neutral temperature. Choose {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Find {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that provide shelter without restriction. Rely on {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth to guarantee a precise fit. Finish your layers with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. Let the tactile response of the fibres override any label.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to evaluate every fibre before you let it touch your skin.",
      "rankedItems": [
