    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Once you establish a precise fit and guarantee sensory comfort in a neutral garment, your accessories provide the required one meticulous detail. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Put every item through your personal archive test. Pick it up and ask if the raw materials justify keeping it in a sealed box for thirty years. Trust your physical grip over a mirror reflection. Density cannot be faked. Apply this rigorous standard to handbags. Look for full-grain leather or thick suede finished with matt brushed hardware. If the strap feels hollow or the metal rings thin, leave the bag on the shelf.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use accessories to anchor your garments, trusting the physical weight of the materials to guide your selection.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Turn your attention to scarves. Select generous cuts of silk or fine wool with a completely matt surface. Avoid any weave that throws a shine. Prioritise absolute sensory comfort against the skin of your neck. Apply the legacy standard before purchasing. Ask yourself if you would fold this exact yardage of neutral pewter grey cloth into a cedar trunk to pass down in three decades. If the textile feels thin or the hem looks rushed, leave it on the rail. You need dense, light-absorbing materials that hold their drape. Rely on the physical tension of the fibres to guide your choice.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the same strict physical standards to your secondary items.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your trousers with a wide full-grain leather belt. Inspect the hardware closely. You require a matt brushed buckle that integrates quietly into your neutral garments. For your core jewellery, select a deep stone set in aged silver or brass that has been oxidised. Evaluate the density of the metal in your palm. A heavy casing delivers grounding sensory comfort against the skin. Guarantee a precise fit for every ring or cuff you choose to wear. Apply the relic filter before you leave the shop. Place your thumb over the cold stone. If the object feels like an inherited private possession meant solely for your own satisfaction, keep it. If it feels like temporary public decoration, remove it immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Audit your final hardware and strip away anything that feels like a costume.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Keep all pattern contrast strictly low and tonal to support a neutral foundation. Your tailored pieces take their pattern from structural weaves like {recommended_pattern_1}. Your fluid garments draw their depth from subtle variations like {recommended_pattern_2}. Maintain a precise fit across both categories so the garment provides the architecture. Pass over heavy blocks of colour, harsh graphic borders, and anything resembling {avoid_pattern_1}. Always execute the shadow check before buying. Hold the textile under a dim bulb. The motif must melt into a soft texture. If the design holds a sharp line in low light, leave it on the rack. This strict visual discipline ensures the cloth delivers pure sensory comfort.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate pattern as an architectural element rather than a surface decoration.",
      "tests": [
        "the lamplight test (melt into a soft texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Subject your {recommended_pattern_1} to a long-distance evaluation. Hang the piece across the room, turn on a single dim lamp, and step back. The motif must lose its hard boundaries and blur into a soft, hazy surface. If the shapes remain distinct in the gloom, the contrast is too high. You need absolute sensory comfort in your clothing. A sharp print acts as visual noise that breaks your self-contained focus. Require the design to settle into a quiet, neutral wash. The pattern must surrender its geometry and become an indistinct {core_colour_1} shadow.",
      "sectionIntro": "Run the lamplight test on every print to gauge its true contrast.",
      "tests": [
        "the lamplight test (melt into a soft texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_gemini__moon_aries__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "crisp separation + sharp edges + one clever contrast",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on crisp separation + sharp edges + one clever contrast.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your physical compass is structural alignment. Trust the sensation of garments settling exactly where they should without constant adjustment. If a piece drags across your shoulders or restricts your stride, drop it. Your anchor is your formula: crisp separation + sharp edges + one clever contrast. Picture a heavily structured tailored coat worn over a fluid, lightweight long-sleeved layer, finished with an angular, flat-soled boot. You are looking for clear boundaries between individual items. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't.\n\nAssemble your core pieces slowly and deliberately. Deploy them rapidly each morning to match your current objective. When evaluating a new garment, apply the treaty test. Ask yourself if this item negotiates a strict settlement between sharp architecture and pure utility. If it requires pulling, pinning or coaxing to sit right, the negotiation has failed. Keep the overall temperature of your selections firmly cool. Let the crisp precision of the cut do the work. Avoid garments that blur the lines of your silhouette. You need distinct, separate items to maintain a balanced grip on your wardrobe.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation. Memorise these rules and use them to test every garment you pick up.",
      "tests": [
        "the treaty test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "To build a wardrobe rooted in crisp separation, you need fabrics that hold their boundaries. Apply the two-hands test to every piece. Pull the material between your fingers. It must snap back with sharp edges, never collapsing into mush. Rely on the tension of the weave. Seek out {texture_good_1} for shirting to maintain strict geometry. Layer {texture_good_2} close to the skin for base layers that stretch without losing shape. Anchor the look in a cool palette with {texture_good_3} for trousers that fall cleanly and refuse to crease. Build lightweight outerwear from {texture_good_4} to repel the wind. These materials let you execute one clever contrast by layering them against each other. Focus your search on the materials below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to read the structural integrity of a garment with your hands before you put it on.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
