    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Avoid {texture_bad_1}. It catches on the skin and turns a clean silhouette into static cling. Reject {texture_bad_2} entirely. Grip the material with both fists and give the cloth a hard pull. If the weave distorts or collapses into a shapeless puddle, leave it on the rack. You require fabrics that hold their own shape. {texture_bad_3} fails this test immediately. It sags at the hems and blurs your sharp edges, destroying any chance of a cool, structured finish. Rely on your fingers to detect when a surface feels structurally weak before you even try it on.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify the materials that undermine your lines before they reach your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Look for textiles that establish crisp separation against the body. Pick up an item and roll the cloth firmly over your knuckles. You are feeling for {sweet_spot_keyword_1} that snaps back when crushed, paired directly against {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Your sweet spot demands sharp edges to function properly. If a weave feels muddy or limp in your grip, drop it. A cool surface like {texture_good_1} succeeds here because it dictates a rigid line. Keep your finishes mixed, placing a matt textile directly against a highly polished one. Let your hands confirm the density before you ever get dressed.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish your tactile baseline by testing how textiles behave under pressure.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette temperature remains entirely cool. Construct your daily base with {core_colour_1} worsted wool and {core_colour_2} crisp cotton poplin. Rely on {core_colour_3} as your bright substitute, letting {core_colour_4} technical nylon provide dark structure. Deliver a deliberate strike by deploying {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Apply your relief tone strictly as a soft note used sparingly. Pass over mustard, rust, and warm olive green entirely. Trust your hands to evaluate dye quality. Deep saturation carries a tangible physical density. Avoid the styling seesaw, where you acquire a haul of floaty gauze shirts one month and shift entirely to rigid utility trousers the next. Re-weave your approach instead. Keep one item from the other hand active in every outfit, always. This guarantees your sharp edges remain visible.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control your colours to engineer deliberate structure into every outfit.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Stark navy",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Icy grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
