    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, sharp edges lead. Build the foundation with worsted wool trousers and crisp poplin shirting that slice a clean line. Support this severe geometry by layering a technical nylon shell under a tailored blazer to execute one clever contrast. Test the garments before you leave for the office. Never abandon your lines. Even an empty boardroom at the end of the day demands a severe silhouette. If the clothes lose their rigid shape under artificial light, change them. Rely on the cool tones of stark navy and icy grey to establish order. A matt silver watch case worn alongside a gold ring interrupts the strictness. Keep the tailoring absolute and ensure crisp separation between your layers.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat the office as a strict proving ground for your geometry.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "When low light dims the finer details, let sharp edges take the lead. An icy grey worsted wool jacket must cut a precise line over a stark navy merino knit. Trust your hands to gauge the heft of the wool before putting it on. Sensation confirms what shadows hide. A quiet dinner in a dark restaurant still demands a deliberate outline. Mix a polished silver cuff with matt steel rings to catch the faint lighting, providing one clever contrast. Keep the entire palette strictly cool. Avoid anything soft or formless that blurs into the background. Test the collar of a crisp cotton poplin shirt. If the points wilt under a lapel, losing their crisp separation, drop the garment entirely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evening settings strip away visual information, so your structure must do the heavy lifting in the dark.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Build your morning choices around worsted wool trousers and a fine ribbed merino top. Anchor the look with heavy silver and matt brass hardware. Rely on the heaviness of the cloth when assessing your layers. Check the physical tension of the fabric rather than just looking in the mirror. Maintain this discipline during mundane tasks. Buying painkillers at the local chemist does not excuse soft jogging bottoms. A quick trip to the post office still requires distinct lines and careful tailoring. Keep the baseline colours anchored in cool stark navy and icy grey. Your daily uniform functions on a strict equation. You must achieve crisp separation + sharp edges + one clever contrast. Pair structured technical nylon outerwear with a woven silk scarf to secure that final detail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your baseline routine as a strict discipline, holding the standard when no one is watching.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your cool palette requires a deliberate approach to hardware. You have the freedom to mix {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} across your watch, buckles, and rings. Reject {excluded_finish} components entirely. Cast aside any metal manufactured to mimic age, as faux-vintage treatments register as messy distractions. Fix this by insisting on flawless, high-shine hardware to create one clever contrast against woven fabrics. Rely on gleaming silver, icy white gold, pure platinum, and mirror-grade chrome to enforce sharp edges. When assessing any new clasp or chain, pick it up and weigh it in your palm. A heavy gauge confirms quality. Only keep pieces that possess undeniable physical density to maintain crisp separation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Audit your metals by their weight and their modern precision.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Focus on stones that maintain crisp separation from their settings. Keep the colour profile of your gems distinctly cool. Look for the clarity of {stone_1} or the dense saturation of {stone_2}. Lift the piece before buying. If a ring feels suspiciously light, leave it on the glass counter. Avoid pairing these stones with oxidized bands, as darkened copper looks like debris next to modern gem cuts. Correct this by demanding flawless settings. Keep to highly reflective silver, bright white gold, or mirror chrome to define the sharp edges in your overall geometry. Use a single striking stone to provide one clever contrast against a strict tailored sleeve.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware by its physical density and light interaction.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Pick up the {metal_1} jewellery and test its heft in your palm. A solid item must possess enough mass to physically ground your clothing. Steer clear of hammered surfaces and deliberately distressed finishes. These uneven treatments register as visual noise and ruin your crisp separation. Instead, demand flawless metalwork. Stick to cool, mirror-polished surfaces or completely matt items to maintain absolute precision and sharp edges. Combining these two textures provides one clever contrast.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate the physical density of your hardware before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
