  "venus_capricorn__moon_aquarius__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "enduring structure + mobile layers + one living texture",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on enduring structure + mobile layers + one living texture.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Evaluate a garment by its density and drape. Build slowly over years so you can deploy fast each morning. When assessing a new piece, trust the weight on your forearm. Drape the fabric over your bare wrist before you even step into a fitting room. If it feels rigid or lacks a yielding, warm touch against your skin, leave it on the hanger. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not. A piece must possess an inherent gravity to anchor your wardrobe.\n\nConstruct your outfits using your core style formula of enduring structure + mobile layers + one living texture. Picture a sharply tailored outer coat, a pliant mid-layer that shifts as you step, and a tactile knitted scarf to trap the air. This combination creates a matt, balanced silhouette. Rely on the tension between strict architecture and fluid movement. Every element must pull its weight without raising its voice. Avoid the temptation to complicate the shape. Your foundation relies on strict precision, ensuring the finished result functions flawlessly.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the physical rules of your wardrobe foundation.",
      "tests": [
        "the wrist test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "To build a wardrobe of enduring structure and mobile layers, you need fabrics that obey your hands. Demand a matt, warm finish from every thread. When evaluating a new garment, apply the collapse test. Pick the item up and drop it onto a hard table. If it holds a stiff shape, leave it on the rack. If it falls into a heavy, yielding pool, it passes. Seek out {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Choose {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Rely on {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Finally, use {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. These specific materials guarantee your requirement for one living texture, forming the hierarchy below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every potential garment to strict tactile testing before adding it to your wardrobe.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
