    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "During intimate evening settings, ensure enduring structure anchors your shape. Dim lighting obscures subtle hues. Base your choices in heavy silk crepe or washed silk dyed in bitter chocolate. These fibres capture a warm ambient glow. Select matt gold and silver jewellery to catch low light without glaring reflections. Check every piece tactilely before dressing. The soft drape of dark mahogany boiled wool signifies true quality when shadows deepen. Hold firm to your baseline requirements at all times. A clumsy press at the laundry can bake unwanted stiffness into delicate fibres. If a service ruins the pliant nature of your clothes, find a new professional. A ruined drape destroys the item.",
      "sectionIntro": "Mastering close quarters requires strict attention to tactile reality when visual details fade.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip to the dry cleaner does not suspend your standards (Frost)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A morning errand offers no excuse for synthetic fleece. Keep your calculation absolute every day. You require enduring structure + mobile layers + one living texture. Build this baseline with bitter chocolate rigid cotton twill trousers. Add a dark mahogany washed silk shirt. Finish the combination with a cloud-soft lambswool cardigan. Assess your metals before stepping outside. Mix sterling silver rings with yellow gold hardware. Verify the surface finish of every piece. Everything must remain strictly matt. Squeeze the sleeve of your jumper. If the yarn feels hollow, return the garment to the hanger. Maintain this warm palette across all daylight hours.",
      "sectionIntro": "Enforce your material standards regardless of the daily itinerary.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip to the dry cleaner does not suspend your standards (Frost)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Operate a strict dual-register strategy for your metals. Confine personal jewellery worn against the skin to {personal_metal_1} or {personal_metal_2}. Shift to {structural_metal_1} and {structural_metal_2} for utility elements like zips, clasps, and shoe buckles. High-shine finishes create a sharp, distracting contrast against soft muted colours. A bright {excluded_finish} surface disrupts visual cohesion. Stick to matt and heavily brushed textures to anchor your warm palette. When evaluating a new watch or belt, test its mass in your palm. Visuals manipulate the eye, whereas heavy gravity confirms quality. Hollow or stamped metal will fail. Demand solid, cast hardware that provides a physical counterweight to the mobile layers you integrate into your outfit.",
      "sectionIntro": "Metals require deliberate division, treating jewellery and structural hardware as strictly separate disciplines.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Treat hardware as an enduring structure within your wardrobe. Lift an item and measure its heft unassisted. A photograph hides a hollow core, but a heavy drop exposes it. Opaque, dense pieces like {stone_1} and {stone_2} provide the necessary warmth to ground softer garments. Mirror-finish metal flashes abruptly and creates a harsh visual break against muted colours. Prevent this by insisting on matt or brushed settings. This approach ensures your stones integrate seamlessly into those mobile layers.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your garments with hardware that prioritises solid weight over surface glare.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Check the density of every {metal_1} clasp manually. Online images mimic density, yet only a physical assessment verifies the casting. Discard hollow chains and flimsy rings immediately. High-shine polish reflects sharp light and creates a jarring distraction against warm, muted {core_colour_1} fabrics. Refuse mirror finishes entirely. Demand brushed or matt surfaces to keep the piece integrated. A heavy, matt buckle provides the enduring structure necessary to anchor softer garments. Set {stone_1} into thick, brushed mounts to maintain this solid foundation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test every metal piece by its physical heft before it enters your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Accessories deliver the one living texture that completes your daily formula. Establish enduring structure first, integrate mobile layers, and rely on hardware to provide depth. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Begin with handbags. Demand full-grain leather paired with brushed matt hardware. Grip the strap and execute the heirloom test. Determine whether the object will gather a warm patina and remain relevant fifty years from now. If the surface feels hollow or synthetic, walk away.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your accessories as the final anchors of your daily uniform.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Expand your accessory selection through scarves. Construct your mobile layers using washed silk or fine wool. Look for a strictly matt finish. Leave shiny fabrics on the rail. Fold the material over your hand and consider whether the textile deserves careful preservation for decades. If the piece lacks that intrinsic value, do not buy it. Ground the look in warm tones like dark mahogany. The fabric must hang heavily without reflecting light. Mass dictates quality here. Test a cloud-soft lambswool wrap. If the yarn proves sparse, return it immediately.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your secondary accessories with the same ruthless physical criteria.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Provide enduring structure with a medium full-grain leather belt. Run your thumb over the hardware. You require a matt buckle, never a reflective surface. Complete the assembly with cast jewellery in aged silver and oxidised metals. Rest these muted pieces over warm, heavy fabrics. Let your fingers judge these objects. Reflections flatter falsely. Sheer density remains absolute. Finally, apply a strict longevity standard. Grip the belt and rings together, assessing whether they possess the permanence of inherited artifacts. If a piece feels like a temporary prop, remove it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your base with hardware and metals that pass the ultimate tactile threshold.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the keepsake test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Draw your pattern strategy directly from the garment's construction. Tailored shapes demand woven motifs. Fluid pieces take their cues entirely from the weave. Maintain a low-contrast, tonal approach to all prints to preserve a muted, warm finish. Build enduring structure with subtle {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2}. Treat these as solids from a distance. When choosing mobile layers, apply the lamplight test. Hold the patterned cloth near a soft bulb. The motif must melt gently into the fabric rather than snapping into sharp focus. This yields exactly one living texture without breaking the visual calm. Pass over high-contrast prints entirely. Reject {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} on sight. They fight the balanced silhouette. Let the raw textile guide your choice. The yarn itself holds the answer.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate patterns as architectural tools rather than visual distractions.",
      "tests": [
        "the lamplight test (melt into a soft texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Execute this low-light evaluation before committing to a purchase. Suspend the item from a hanger and extinguish the primary overhead lighting. Switch on a single warm table lamp. Step back three paces and evaluate {recommended_pattern_1}. The motif must lose its defined edges. It should melt into a blurred, indistinct surface rather than maintaining a crisp graphic outline. If the print remains legible from this distance, leave the piece on the rail. You need matt prints that behave like shadow or woven depth under dim conditions. This subtle diffusion provides the ideal foundation to support mobile layers, allowing fabrics to hang without visual friction. Rely on this environmental check completely. Digital screens flatten reality. Real-world illumination proves the cloth's worth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every print to a strict lighting test to determine its viability.",
      "tests": [
        "the lamplight test (melt into a soft texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_cancer__moon_gemini__fire_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "soft shelter + light movement + one sentimental keepsake",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on soft shelter + light movement + one sentimental keepsake.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your hands to find garments that move without friction. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. When evaluating a piece, close your eyes and test its drape. If it drags or binds, drop it. Your daily dressing relies on a precise equation of soft shelter + light movement + one sentimental keepsake. Picture this combination. You layer a dense, oversized cocoon coat over a fluid, ankle-grazing slip dress, finishing the look with a heavy, inherited pendant on a worn chain. The outer layer offers structural protection. The inner layer guarantees absolute freedom. The keepsake anchors the entire formula.\n\nBuild your collection deliberately, then deploy your choices fast, drifting by daily mood. True versatility demands impeccable construction. Apply the seam test. Turn every potential purchase inside out and run your bare hands over the interior bindings. If the internal stitching is rough, uneven, or abrasive, leave the item on the hanger. The unseen architecture must feel as resolved against your skin as the exterior appears to the world. Filter your choices for cool, muted garments with a matt finish that keep you comfortably self-contained. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn the structural logic of your wardrobe, using your physical senses to curate a collection that serves your exact requirements.",
      "tests": [
        "the seam test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your wardrobe around materials that provide soft shelter and allow for light movement. Seek out {texture_good_1} for shirting that creates clean boundaries against the skin. For base layers, choose {texture_good_2} to hold sharp lines while letting you move freely. Anchor the lower half with {texture_good_3}. It drops cleanly in trousers and resists creasing through a long day. Finish with {texture_good_4} in your outerwear to block the wind with almost zero weight. Before buying anything, apply the recovery test. Crush the fabric in your fist for five seconds and release it. If it holds a hard wrinkle, leave it on the rack. You need garments that spring back to a muted, cool surface instantly. Here are the core materials that pass the test.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify the materials that build your physical foundation and reject the ones that crease under pressure.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
