    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, dark drama takes the lead. Start your base with a sharp cut of worsted wool or crisp cotton poplin in warm taupe. These structured shapes hold up through long hours without collapsing. Support this primary structure with tactile ease against the skin. A fine ribbed merino roll-neck in camel keeps you grounded and focused, guaranteeing sensory comfort. Complete the outfit with one molten flash. A heavy gold cuff catches the light against a matt sleeve. Even a late desk shift demands a sharp worsted wool outline. Never let your tailoring soften into slouchy territory. Test the integrity of a trouser crease before you purchase. Fold the leg tightly. If the sharp line blurs, leave the item on the rack.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish your working hours by letting strong shapes drive the aesthetic.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, dark drama leads the execution. Pick up a crisp cotton poplin shirt in warm taupe and feel the dense weave. Trust your hands to verify the structure, as dim lighting easily disguises poor construction. Heavy cloth speaks the truth. Anchor the collar with a heavy, polished yellow gold chain to serve as your one molten flash. Test the outfit before you leave. Even a brief walk to a waiting taxi requires a sharp, intentional shape. Discard loose garments. Rely on the dense drop of worsted wool trousers to carry the line of your leg through the shadows, keeping your sensory comfort intact.",
      "sectionIntro": "Prepare for evening environments by letting heavy cloth define your shape.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat the post office queue and the supermarket aisle with strict mechanical discipline. Even a 2 AM drive to the petrol station for milk demands a deliberate shape. Your baseline remains constant across every environment. The mandate is always dark drama + sensory comfort + one molten flash. Anchor your morning routine in a heavy camel coat or a water-repellent technical nylon shell. Trust your skin to evaluate a garment before you wear it. If the weave feels abrasive or the collar restricts your movement, drop it immediately. Rely on this tactile feedback instead of the mirror. Finish the outfit with a polished brass belt buckle or a warm gold ring. A standard never drops just because the errand is trivial.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the exact same rigor to your mundane routines as you do to major events.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your strategy relies on a warm metal palette. Base your hardware on {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Reject {excluded_finish} surfaces. Avoid antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged hardware. These read as cluttered distractions against a clean, present-tense style. Keep strictly to polished {metal_1} and gleaming {metal_2}. Lift every chain, clasp, and ring to gauge its quality. Mass reveals the absolute truth. Trust the weight in your palm. A heavy {metal_3} buckle acts as your one molten flash, grounding your sensory comfort. A substantial zip brings necessary edge to your dark drama.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hardware dictates the structural integrity and light reflection of your entire wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "When integrating {stone_1} and {stone_2} into your collection, lift each piece in your palm. Vision plays tricks. Density provides the only reliable measure. A stone must feel substantial to ground the dark drama of your clothing. If it feels hollow or light, put it back. You require heft to achieve a polished finish. Avoid the trap of hammered surfaces or distressed settings. These introduce visual clutter that degrades a versatile aesthetic. Rely strictly on high-shine, pristine metal settings with a warm undertone to act as your one molten flash. The flawless surface of a smooth mount combined with the heavy density of {stone_3} creates tactile contrast. This preserves your baseline requirement for sensory comfort without sacrificing strict structural discipline.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your hardware purely through physical density and immaculate surface execution.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Pick up every buckle, zip, and chain. Do not trust your eyes to judge quality. Heft tells the truth. Trust your hands to evaluate the item. A solid {metal_1} closure provides the sensory comfort you require. Avoid oxidised rims and faux-vintage details. These components introduce unnecessary clutter against a precise silhouette. Demand a smooth, warm, highly reflective surface instead. This brilliant execution acts as your one molten flash, providing the exact voltage needed to illuminate a foundation of dark drama.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every piece of hardware to a strict physical evaluation before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your garments establish the dark drama and the essential sensory comfort. Accessories step in to deliver one molten flash. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Apply the final assessment by standing still and feeling the items against your skin. Let your skin dictate the final layer. Glass reflections lie to you, but actual weight does not. If the combination feels heavy rather than precise, remove the last thing you put on. Begin your selection with silk scarves. Seek out a narrow silk band. It must drape cleanly and bring a soft, warm glow to your neckline.",
      "sectionIntro": "Accessories secure the strict, polished finish of your foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk band, soft glow"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the too-much test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Select fine jewellery with strict precision. Look for a thin gold chain featuring a high polish. The metal must always read warm and serve as your one molten flash. Evaluate the piece by holding it in your palm. It should feel light enough to guarantee absolute sensory comfort against the neck. Test the visual weight before leaving the house. Fasten the chain against a camel knit. If the metal fights the dark drama of your clothing, the jewellery is too heavy. Take it off. The right piece registers strictly as a precise, gleaming edge against the skin.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this rigorous physical filter to select and test your metal.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin gold chain, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the too-much test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Look for a small structured bag. Pick a smooth leather crossbody in warm taupe or deep camel. Inspect the details carefully. The fine hardware requires a high shine in your warm metal lane, acting as a subtle iteration of your one molten flash. The strap must lie flat, preserving your foundation of sensory comfort rather than digging into your shoulder. Before finishing, review the entire silhouette. Strip away any single item that tips the scale from pure dark drama into mere costume. If the polished buckles on your bag fight your gold jewellery for dominance, leave the piece behind. Trust your hands to gauge the final equilibrium.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select your practical carry piece and apply a ruthless final edit.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "smooth leather crossbody, polished fine hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the too-much test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Filter every print through the glance test. A successful piece must register as an agreeable shift in tone from a distance, rather than a shouting motif. Tailored garments anchor {recommended_pattern_1} effectively. Let your fluid pieces take their movement from {recommended_pattern_2}. Because your approach adapts to shifting contexts, scale your contrast to match the room. Keep the lines tonal for subtle days, or push the contrast higher when a specific silhouette demands it. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. Look for {recommended_pattern_3} to introduce dark drama to a warm palette. Ensure the visual rhythm never disrupts your baseline of sensory comfort. Pair {recommended_pattern_4} with one molten flash of metal to unify the look.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as a calibrating tool, using scale and contrast to control where the eye lands.",
      "tests": [
        "the glance test (a pleasant impression rather than a specific shouting motif)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Step back from the hanger and let your eyes lose focus. A successful {recommended_pattern_1} must dissolve into a warm, pleasant haze, never reading as a rigid graphic shouting for dominance. If the motif requires intense scrutiny to decipher, it will overpower your balanced structure. Close your eyes and evaluate the weave. The cloth must provide immediate sensory comfort before the printed ink even registers. A heavy dye job that stiffens a shirt collar or lapel fails your requirements instantly, disrupting the dark drama. Patterns remain secondary to touch. Drape and texture never lie.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this visual check to calibrate your printed garments before purchase.",
      "tests": [
        "the glance test (a pleasant impression rather than a specific shouting motif)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_libra__moon_gemini__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "balanced proportions + light movement + one refined touch",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on balanced proportions + light movement + one refined touch.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust the shifting weight of fabric against your skin as your primary physical instinct. When you pick up a garment, gauge its drape. If it demands stiff posture or restricts your breath, put it down. Your foundation relies on balanced proportions + light movement + one refined touch. Picture an unstructured wool blazer in a cool wash layered over a fluid silk shell and wide trousers, grounded by a single slim chain. This combination works because the textiles drift easily with your body while the cut provides structure. Looks lie. Weight does not.\n\nBuild your wardrobe responsively. Acquire garments slowly, testing each new shape against your current collection. You can then assemble outfits quickly to match the mood of the community you are joining. Always apply the seam test before removing the tags. Run your thumb firmly along the interior shoulder binding. If the thread scratches or the tension bites into your skin when you reach forward, the item will disrupt your focus. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. When the construction yields to your frame, the garment belongs to you.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your physical baseline before you evaluate your reflection.",
      "tests": [
        "the seam test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your foundation relies on materials that guarantee light movement. Start with {texture_good_1} for shirting that provides pure separation between layers. Put this over {texture_good_2} for sharp, close-to-body base garments. For trousers, seek out {texture_good_3}. It must drape cleanly and survive the recovery test. Crush the hem in your fist for five seconds and release it. If the creases remain, leave the garment on the rack. The fabric must spring back instantly to maintain balanced proportions through an active day. Build lightweight mobile outerwear with {texture_good_4}. It blocks the wind and weighs little. Let the finish of this outer layer serve as your one refined touch. Trust your hands to verify these qualities before buying.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your physical foundation by selecting fabrics that respond cleanly to a long day.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
