    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Learn to spot poor materials by their physical failures. Pinch a fold of {texture_bad_1} and stretch it slightly. If the weave stays flat and lifeless when released, leave it on the rack. It will never yield the light movement you require. Avoid {texture_bad_2} entirely. It sits dead against the skin and traps heat instead of breathing with you. Run your fingertips across the face of {texture_bad_3} to check its surface tension. If it catches or drags, it lacks the crisp integrity you need. Rely on your tactile feedback to detect flaws before you ever approach a fitting room.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject poor materials before you ever try them on.",
      "tests": [
        "the recovery test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Pair {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to hit your textural target. Combine a crisp surface with a responsive knit to build balanced proportions and light movement. Twist the sleeve of a {texture_good_1} piece and let go. If the material stays bunched, put the item back on the rail. You require textiles that snap back immediately to hold their shape. A cool tone must run through these pairings. Mix matt finishes with high polish across your metals. You have full permission to blend silver and gold freely. This physical tension between smooth weaves and ribbed structures keeps you physically present for the people around you, rather than fussing with high-maintenance materials. Base your decisions on how the item behaves under pressure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the exact textural formula that anchors your daily dressing.",
      "tests": [
        "the recovery test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor your wardrobe with a strictly cool temperature. Establish your base using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Rely on {core_colour_3} as your white substitute, and deploy {core_colour_4} for dark components. Integrate {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} purely as your single deliberate accent. Treat your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly. Pass over Mustard, Rust, and Warm olive green immediately. They disrupt your spectrum. Watch out for the beige-out. This trap occurs when combining pieces at an identical pale value, making the outfit look unfinished rather than minimal. Intervene when a pairing falls flat. Rescue it with a {core_colour_4} anchor piece or a {accent_colour_2} addition. Let a shift in surface finish restore the depth, contrasting fine ribbed merino against technical nylon. Ensure the completed garments retain light movement to verify the combination works.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your wardrobe on a strict spectrum of cool tones, keeping every choice deliberate and assigned by a specific role.",
