    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Handle prospective items directly. Let the solid metal of heavy {metal_1} hardware confirm its quality before you look at the price. When selecting belt buckles or bag clasps, beware of highly polished, mirrored finishes. High-gloss reflections pierce right through muted, warm palettes and shatter your cohesive aesthetic. Instead, demand matt or heavily brushed {metal_1} surfaces. A dulled finish absorbs ambient light rather than bouncing it away, preserving the hidden depth of your garments without fighting for attention.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your hardware for physical substance and reject finishes that disrupt your palette.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your accessories provide the final element of your structure. Once you secure your close drape and build your hidden depth, you only require one warm point of light. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Put your chosen items on, then remove the extra cuff or competing chain. A single dominant object anchors an outfit far better than scattered details. Begin this discipline with handbags. Seek out full-grain leather or thick suede. Run your thumb over the zips and clasps. You need matt brushed hardware that sits quietly against the body, adding structure without noise.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply strict subtraction to your finishing touches and evaluate every object by its physical weight rather than its reflection.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Reach for generous silk or fine wool scarves with a strictly matt finish. Fold the fabric tightly against the collarbone to maintain the close drape. Test the material with your bare hands before committing. Dense camel cashmere compresses in your fist and springs back, while a flimsy synthetic collapses into nothing. When you finish dressing, look closely at your neckline. A solitary strong scarf anchoring a warm jacket is enough. This disciplined editing preserves your hidden depth and ensures a self-contained finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Filter your finishing layers with absolute physical discipline.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor the waist with a wide full-grain leather belt. Seek out a matt brushed buckle that sits heavy against your body. Treat keepsake jewellery with the exact same material scrutiny. Select a deep, warm amber stone set firmly in oxidised brass or aged silver. These solid pieces must provide hidden depth to your silhouette. Evaluate your final arrangement before leaving the house. If two reflective surfaces compete for dominance, remove one. Keeping your focus self-contained means letting a single heavy ring or a solid belt buckle stand alone without competition as your one warm point of light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your silhouette by anchoring it with physical weight and stripping away the excess.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "remove the earring doing too much / one strong piece is enough"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Restrict your tailored garments to structured weaves like {recommended_pattern_1}. Let your fluid pieces carry subtle {recommended_pattern_2} or {recommended_pattern_3}. Demand low-contrast, tonal variations. Pass over sharp graphics. Leave {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} on the rail. Assess the fabric from a distance. If the motif jumps out aggressively, put the garment down. True hidden depth requires the design to read as a continuous, matt texture from across the room. Choose patterns that complement your close drape, maintaining a warm and entirely self-contained finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as an extension of texture, using it to build weight without visual distraction.",
      "tests": [
        "step back and soften focus (blur into texture)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Hang the garment on a rail and step back three paces. Squint until the edges blur. If the lines remain stark and sharp, leave the item behind. You need {recommended_pattern_1} to dissolve into a single, textured surface. This optical shift guarantees hidden depth without breaking your self-contained silhouette. Test the material between your fingers. If the weight supports that close drape, the pattern will read as a warm, matt solid rather than a graphic distraction.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test every pattern from a distance to ensure it dissolves into pure texture.",
      "tests": [
        "step back and soften focus (blur into texture)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_sagittarius__moon_aries__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "expansive colour + sharp edges + one theatrical finish",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on expansive colour + sharp edges + one theatrical finish.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your hands to find the heaviest, most saturated fabric on the rail. Let warmth guide your selections. Build your wardrobe slowly and methodically, but deploy your combinations fast by morning instinct. Feel the garment for rigid seams and dense weaves before you consider putting it on. If a piece feels flimsy or looks hesitant, drop it. Your compass relies on undeniable physical presence.\n\nYour exact requirement is expansive colour + sharp edges + one theatrical finish. Picture a severely tailored heavy wool overcoat in a vivid dye, worn over knife-pleated trousers and anchored by high-gloss sculptural boots. Subject every combination to the radius test. Stand still and gauge whether your silhouette projects enough structural volume to hit the absolute boundary of your physical reach. If the impact recedes inward, the outfit fails. Demand garments that push outward with absolute polished clarity.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this foundational logic before you evaluate another garment.",
      "tests": [
        "the radius test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your foundation on materials that take a hard press and hold a saturated, warm dye. The requirement is strict. Begin with {texture_good_1} for shirting that snaps visually and anchors expansive colour. Cut your tailoring from {texture_good_2}, ensuring the silhouette stays rigid without begging for a steamer. Add one theatrical finish through {texture_good_3} on your accessories to throw maximum light back into the space. Layer {texture_good_4} underneath for linings that gleam. Before you buy anything, apply the bounce test. Crush a handful of the cloth and release it. If it collapses sluggishly, leave it on the rail. If it springs back instantly with structural tension, take it to the till.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise materials that hold a defined shape and bounce light back into the environment.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "sharp shirting that holds a crease and snaps visually"
        },
        {
          "name": "Sharp wool twill",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "knife-edge tailoring that never begs for a steamer"
        },
        {
          "name": "Patent leather",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "statement footwear and accessories that reflect maximum light"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk satin",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "slip dresses and linings that gleam under low light"
        },
        {
          "name": "Techno gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "wrinkle-resistant trousers and jackets that keep a rigid shape"
        },
        {
          "name": "High-shine taffeta",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "evening pieces that bounce light and cut a clear silhouette"
        },
        {
          "name": "Polished calfskin",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "footwear and accessories with a slick, radiant surface"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the bounce test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Avoid {texture_bad_1}. Pick it up and snap the cloth between your thumb and forefinger. If the material absorbs the shock and hangs lifelessly, it will drag your sharp edges down into a shapeless slump. Reject {texture_bad_2} the moment it touches your skin. If it catches on your knuckles, feels thin, or lacks a warm, solid tension in your grip, drop it immediately. These weak fibres collapse under pressure. Put {texture_bad_3} back on the rack if it rubs with a matt, powdery friction. Trust your fingers to detect this failure. Appearance deceives, but structural integrity reveals the exact truth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject the textiles that will betray your structure before you even try them on.",
      "tests": [
        "the bounce test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Avoid anything that yields too quickly. Anchor {sweet_spot_keyword_1} directly against {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. This combination guarantees the sharp edges you require. Always check the tension of a garment before wearing it. Pull the seam of {texture_good_1} tight. It must snap back into place immediately. Fabric that droops will fail you. You need strict resilience to carry warm dyes and heavy hardware. Base your decisions purely on this tactile feedback. A polished surface relies entirely on an unyielding foundation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the strict interaction between your materials to lock in your proportions.",
      "tests": [
        "the bounce test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your spectrum is fundamentally warm. Construct the base using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}. Sub in {core_colour_3} as your strict white alternative. Ground the scheme with {core_colour_4}. Introduce {accent_colour_1} and {accent_colour_2} as your sole deliberate focal points. Apply your relief tone sparingly to temper the high contrast. Leave murky pastels, icy grey, and dusty sage on the rack. Step away from uninterrupted, light-absorbing dark layers that flatten your intensity. Shatter that flat block with a massive, gleaming metallic cuff or a vividly saturated shoe to maintain your sharp edges.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your palette as a strict blueprint for visual impact.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Deep bronze",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Golden camel",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Warm ivory",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rich terracotta",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Warm sand",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Toasted chestnut",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Jet black",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fire engine red",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Hot tangerine",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brilliant marigold",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Washed peach",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "a restrictive dark monochrome look that stifles your presence",
          "fix": "break the silhouette with a massive polished gold cuff or a bright poppy red shoe"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Let sharp edges lead your weekday attire. Anchor the look with a heavy wool twill blazer or a crisp cotton poplin shirt. Support this tailoring with warm tones like deep bronze and golden camel. Operating behind a desk does not mean you must shed your tailored silhouette for a slouchy knit. Keep the structural items on. Bring in a theatrical element through highly polished accessories. Mix heavy gold and bright silver rings on the same hand. Step into glossy patent leather loafers. Trust the weight of these materials. If a jacket sags over the back of your chair, discard it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your primary style directives to the workplace.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In low light and close quarters, let sharp edges dictate your choices. Vision blurs in dim rooms. Tactile boundaries must step in. Reach for heavy silk satin and rigid wool twill. Demand the fabric maintain strict lines against the body. Stack mixed gold and silver hardware at the wrist to catch sparse light. Maintain this physical discipline during private hours. A quiet evening at home does not require surrendering your form to a soft fleece. Wear a crisp cotton poplin shirt and warm deep bronze trousers. Gauge every garment by closing your eyes and evaluating its construction. If a lapel collapses in your grip, leave it on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Approach intimate settings by letting physical boundaries dictate your shape.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Buying a pint of milk does not excuse abandoning your geometry. Treat a trip to the post office as an exacting calibration exercise. Maintain warm tones even on an unremarkable Tuesday. Reach for heavy silk satin trousers in golden camel. Anchor them with a stiff wool twill coat in deep bronze. Stack chunky rings in mixed gold and silver. Evaluate the outfit before you step outside. A mundane errand never justifies a shapeless compromise. Every single day demands expansive colour + sharp edges + one theatrical finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your highest standards to your most mundane routines.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "You have complete freedom to mix your metals. Layer {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} together in a single outfit. Do not worry about matching a watch strap to a belt buckle. Focus entirely on the surface. Avoid hammered, antiqued, or oxidised treatments. They lack crispness. Stay strictly in polished, warm metal that catches the light from across the street. Anchor your expansive colour with this brilliant shine. Test every piece of hardware before you buy it. Pick it up. Visuals can deceive, but sheer density provides exact proof. If a {metal_2} clasp feels hollow in your palm, put it back. You need substantial, dense hardware to structure your look. Reject any {excluded_finish} pieces entirely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your hardware as the dense architectural framework that grounds your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Seek out the unyielding clarity of {stone_1} and the brilliant faceted surface of {stone_2}. Lift the setting in your palm. Trust the gravity of the piece in your hand to tell the truth. Let this mass guide your choices. Reject any piece with a cloudy or distressed surface. These finishes look exhausted and muddy against your expansive colour choices. Lock yourself strictly into highly polished, warm metals that throw brilliant glints from fifty paces. Precision cuts provide the sharp edges necessary to complete your silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your jewellery with stones that reflect absolute clarity and physical density.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Combine your alloys with total freedom, but verify their physical substance. Lift every {metal_1} cuff or {stone_1} pendant before you buy it. A glossy photograph means nothing compared to the unyielding heft of solid casting. Your hardware must possess enough mass to ground your expansive colour. If the item feels light, leave it on the tray. Next, inspect the surface treatment. Scratched or artificially dulled components read as sluggish. They drag down the crisp precision of your look. Reject them entirely. Insist on strictly polished, warm metal that acts as a flawless mirror.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this physical test to every piece of hardware before it enters your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "oxidised, hammered, or antiqued finishes look tired and lack crispness",
          "fix": "stay strictly in polished warm metal that catches the light from across the street"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your accessories deliver the final component of your formula. After anchoring the foundation, you require one theatrical finish. Restrict yourself to a single strong focal point to maintain maximum impact. Begin with statement jewellery. Look for a solid metal collar in a high polish finish. Mix your metals freely, setting warm bronze directly against brilliant white alloys. Trust your physical instinct when handling hardware. Apply the stage test before making a purchase. Ask yourself if the reflection and scale of the collar would read clearly to the back row of a dark auditorium. If the shape disappears from a distance, drop it and walk away.",
      "sectionIntro": "Mastering the final slot in your style formula through deliberate, high-impact hardware.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Statement jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "polished metal collar, high polish"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the stage test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Treat your footwear as the foundation for an expansive colour strategy. Demand patent leather with an absolute, uncompromising gloss. Subject the material to a flash test before making a purchase. Shine a harsh light directly onto the vamp. If the surface drinks the beam, put the item down. You require a slick finish that bounces glare immediately back into the room. A polished, warm golden camel shoe must actively reflect its surroundings. Seek out structural heels and severe pointed toes to guarantee your sharp edges remain intact. Reject anything scuffed, brushed, or porous. Trust your physical reaction to the shine. If the leather does not gleam, it fails.",
      "sectionIntro": "Demand structural reflection and strict geometry from your footwear.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Footwear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "patent leather, patent gloss"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the stage test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select eyewear sculpted from thick, high shine acetate. Pick up the frames. The plastic must feel dense and reflect light like polished glass. Avoid anything with a scuffed or matt surface. A high gloss finish acts as an anchor when you wear an expansive colour palette built on warm tones like deep bronze. Choose frames with precise, geometric cuts to maintain sharp edges across your profile. Check the silhouette from across the shop before you leave. Step back ten paces from the mirror. If the acetate blurs into your face or the shine disappears, the piece fails. The accessory must project its rigid geometry unmistakably.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finalise your accessories by testing their physical impact and structural integrity.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Eyewear",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "acetate frame, high shine"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the stage test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Let tailored garments anchor the rigid structure of {recommended_pattern_1}. Allow fluid pieces to carry the sweeping scale of {recommended_pattern_2}. Demand high-contrast graphic impact from every print you touch. Examine the borders of the motif up close. The design must maintain its sharp edges without any bleeding dye. If the shapes bleed into a muddy blur, abandon the piece. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} entirely. Rely instead on {recommended_pattern_3} to deliver a polished strike. Every successful pattern requires a foundation of warm, expansive colour to ground the visual weight. Trust your eyes to measure the strict contrast instantly.",
      "sectionIntro": "Control the scale and contrast of your prints to maintain absolute visual clarity.",
      "tests": [
        "the twenty foot rule (bold and entirely legible from twenty feet)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Evaluate every printed garment by hanging it at the far end of the room. Step back twenty feet and observe the fabric. If the {recommended_pattern_1} blurs into an indistinct wash, leave it on the rail. You demand sharp edges to maintain graphic clarity. A successful print never devolves into mud. The warm pigment must remain entirely legible from across the floor. Deploy expansive colour with absolute precision. If the motif dissolves into visual static at a distance, it fails the legibility test. Trust your own eyes as your ultimate compass. Up-close detail deceives, but distance reveals true impact.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply a strict distance test to ensure your patterns do not blur into obscurity.",
      "tests": [
        "the twenty foot rule (bold and entirely legible from twenty feet)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_pisces__moon_libra__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "weightless layers + cool composure + one pearl of light",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on weightless layers + cool composure + one pearl of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Feel the drape of the fabric across your shoulders. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. If a piece pulls, stiffens, or traps heat, put it down and walk away. Your foundational rule is weightless layers + cool composure + one pearl of light. Picture a fine-gauge knit resting lightly under a completely unlined tailored jacket, finished with a single point of illumination at the lapel. The garments must skim your frame without ever restricting your breath. Demand complete physical ease and total freedom of movement.\n\nBuild your collection methodically. Acquire pieces slowly, then deploy them with exact precision each morning. Before you accept any new garment, apply the host test. Ask yourself if your body is providing the structure for the item, or if the item is forcing its own rigid architecture onto your frame. Looks lie. Weight does not. A heavy, restrictive coat dictates your posture and distracts your focus. Reject it. Keep only the pieces that require you to inhabit them softly, allowing your own alignment to provide the true shape.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the physical baseline of your wardrobe before you attempt to build anything else.",
      "tests": [
        "the host test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe relies on materials that build cool composure without adding bulk. When you pull a piece from the rail, run the fabric over the inside of your wrist. Trust tactile feedback completely. If it feels rough against that sensitive skin, leave it. Look for {texture_good_1} in your winter knitwear. It must compress gently in your hands and bounce back into shape. For shoes and belts, choose {texture_good_2} that will mould to your grip and patinate softly over time. Structure your tailored outerwear with {texture_good_3}. A blazer in this cloth holds a clean, crisp line for years. Underneath it all, rely on {texture_good_4} for blouses and linings. This guarantees the weightless layers that glide smoothly over your frame. Only accept materials that pass this physical filter.",
      "sectionIntro": "Let your hands filter the rail before you even look at the garment.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
