    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close quarters and low lighting, cool composure leads. Reach for deep teal silk or dove grey brushed wool. The dim environment reduces visual contrast. Let the gentle sheen of a platinum band or a matt silver watch face catch the available glow. Paying a utility bill at the kitchen table offers no excuse for sloppy tailoring. Maintain strict lines in private spaces. Keep your edges defined with an unlined inky navy cardigan. Drop shapeless lounge garments entirely. Rely on pieces that hang cleanly over the body to construct your layered foundation.",
      "sectionIntro": "Adjust your approach for intimate settings and low light.",
      "tests": [
        "paying a utility bill does not require collapsing your silhouette (Blaze)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Standing in line at the pharmacy to collect a prescription does not justify melting your outline into unstructured fleece. Pull an inky navy cashmere sweater over deep teal silk. Apply your mandate verbatim. Your baseline remains weightless layers + cool composure + one pearl of light. Drop a matt white gold pendant against the dark fabric. Evaluate the fall of the hem. Rely on the drape of fine fibres to hold their shape over your frame. Let the cool metal deliver the necessary finish.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat the most mundane errands as opportunities to enforce strict visual discipline.",
      "tests": [
        "paying a utility bill does not require collapsing your silhouette (Blaze)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Anchor your metal strategy in a cool foundation of {metal_1} and {metal_2}. Use these tones against your skin to align with your natural temperature. Introduce {metal_3} sparingly in structural components like a watch casing or belt buckle. Pick the item up and assess its pure mass. Weight reveals cheap manufacturing long before the eye spots a flaw. Avoid {excluded_finish} pieces. A glaring surface cuts harshly across subdued colours and breaks your visual harmony. Insist on matt and brushed textures. This tames the reflection and forces the hardware to integrate smoothly with your clothing. Let your metals serve as quiet anchors, supporting a weightless, cool aesthetic without stealing focus.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your wardrobe with disciplined, tactile hardware choices.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Select {stone_1} and {stone_2} for their opaque density. Lift the raw stone in your open palm before you wear it. Rely on your physical senses as a strict guide. Gravity exposes fragile components. A heavy, solid stone anchors your weightless layers. It grounds the fabric and enforces your cool composure. Examine the metal setting around your {stone_3}. Avoid mirror-finish, highly polished silver. That fierce shine fractures the quiet surface of your muted textiles. Insist on a matt or brushed metal setting to keep the hardware cohesive. This treatment diffuses the reflection, leaving you with exactly one pearl of light.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones by their physical density and ensure their settings absorb rather than reflect light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift every piece of jewellery before fastening the clasp. Assess the heft without looking. Close your eyes and gauge the density. This physical heaviness anchors your weightless layers. Avoid highly reflective metals that shatter your muted palette. A gleaming {metal_1} pendant or high-shine {stone_1} ring screams against quiet textiles. Choose brushed and matt finishes instead. A subdued surface absorbs the environment rather than bouncing it back. This careful control of shine guarantees cool composure.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test the physical reality of your hardware before integrating it into your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "After assembling weightless layers and establishing a foundation of cool composure, accessories provide exactly one pearl of light. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look to maintain this balance. Start this discipline with handbags. Require full-grain leather structures finished with brushed matt hardware. Put every potential addition through the single-point test. Seek a steady, solitary gleam rather than a blinding flash. The finish on a muted buckle or a dark strap must rest quietly against your garments, offering just enough contrast to draw the eye without disrupting the silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the final stage of your outfit by selecting accessories that add deliberate focus without breaking your balanced foundation.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Select scarves spun from fine wool or raw silk, ensuring the finish remains strictly matt. These materials provide the exact drape required to build weightless layers. Apply the single-point rule when evaluating patterns. Look for a solitary, quiet strike of slate woven into a dark navy background. Reject any sprawling motifs that threaten your cool composure. Drop the textile onto your bare neck to gauge its friction. Skin contact provides the ultimate verdict. Reflections lie, but the sting of cheap thread cannot be hidden.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate soft accessories by their exact density, friction, and restraint.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Secure garments with medium full-grain leather belts featuring a strictly matt buckle. Choose keepsake jewellery cast in aged silver. Look for deeply oxidised metal. These additions enforce absolute cool composure. They must slide quietly under weightless layers. Rely on the heavy, cool bite of dense silver in your hand. An item's true worth rests entirely in its physical substance. Before stepping out, audit the complete ensemble. Scan the final arrangement for any metal catching too much glare. Strip away the single piece flashing where it should retreat.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select structural finishes and test the final arrangement by removing excess glare.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Ground your tailored wool coats in {recommended_pattern_1}. Let your fluid garments carry {recommended_pattern_2}. Keep the internal contrast low. Demand tonal shifts that blend into a single wash of cool colour from a distance. Maintain cool composure through strict restraint. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. They introduce visual noise that shatters the quiet surface of your clothing. Apply the low-light test before buying. Take the garment into a dim room and check that the motif deepens into the shadows rather than flattening out. Stroke the weave before your eyes evaluate the print. A masterfully applied motif feels completely integrated into the fibre itself. Avoid any harsh graphic lines that might slice through your weightless layers.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the precise application of motif to build depth without shouting.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Apply the shadow test to any {recommended_pattern_1}. Dim the lamps in the room and step back. Under low illumination, the contrast must melt away completely. A successful print dissolves into the background, reading as a subtle, matt texture rather than a jarring graphic. If the shapes still jump out at you in a darkened space, leave the garment on the hanger. You require patterns that retreat into the weave when the lights drop. This visual fading protects the structural integrity of the clothes. It ensures they construct weightless layers rather than collapsing into flat, stark lines.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every print to a strict physical trial before it earns a place on the hanger.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_scorpio__moon_scorpio__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "close drape + quiet undercurrent + one warm point of light",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on close drape + quiet undercurrent + one warm point of light.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your first diagnostic tool is always weight. Pick up a garment and feel how it drops from your hand. Look for pieces that sink heavily and settle close to the skin. Trust this tactile instinct as your primary guide. Looks lie. Weight does not. Build your wardrobe slowly, testing every seam and gauge. When you curate with this level of precision, you can deploy fast in the dark and drift by mood without ever losing your baseline. Your core formula is close drape + quiet undercurrent + one warm point of light. Picture a dense knitted sweater sitting flat against the collarbone, anchored by heavy woven trousers in a muted tone, finished with a single warm hardware detail resting against the skin.\n\nYou are building a self-contained system that requires zero adjustment once worn. Every item must move seamlessly with you, holding its shape without demanding attention. Seek a matt finish that absorbs ambient glare rather than reflecting it back. Keep the overall temperature consistently warm. When you test a piece against your skin, it should feel like a natural extension of your own form. If a garment feels hollow in your hands or stands stiffly away from your frame, drop it and leave the shop. If it interrupts your physical ease or requires constant pulling to lay flat, heed that immediate physical rejection and step away.",
      "sectionIntro": "This is your structural foundation, the strict physical criteria you must apply before bringing any garment into your life.",
      "tests": [
        "trust your gut and walk away"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Seek out textiles that serve a self-contained life. Your garments demand a quiet undercurrent of tangible quality. Apply the melt test before buying. Press your bare palm into the cloth. It must yield to your warmth, softening against the skin rather than resisting it. Base your material choices on this tactile response. Look for {texture_good_1} for knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back. Choose {texture_good_2} for bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate. Rely on {texture_good_3} for tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years. Use {texture_good_4} for blouses and linings that add fluid movement and maintain a close drape. These fibres build a matt canvas designed to anchor one warm point of light. Prioritise these materials in the order below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise materials that reward close inspection.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
        },
