          "name": "Linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "warmer-weather pieces whose natural wrinkle reads as authentic"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Crush the material in your closed hand. A successful close drape requires fabrics that surrender completely. Test every garment to see if it yields like heavy liquid. If it fights back with a hollow crunch or springs into rigid creases, discard it. Avoid {texture_bad_1} entirely. It carries a stiff, brittle tension that refuses to soften. Reject {texture_bad_2} because it traps heat and feels slick to the touch. {texture_bad_3} creates a harsh, unyielding shell that disrupts a warm finish. These inferior fibres possess a stubborn memory. They hold their own shape instead of taking yours. Leave them on the hanger.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject the materials that fail your framework.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Pair {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to build your core wardrobe. Drop the material over your bare forearm. It must yield to your shape immediately, collapsing softly to form a close drape. If it stands rigid, put it back on the rail. Your style thrives on this exact tension between heavy density and a completely fluid, matt surface. Pick up an item and gauge its drag. Visuals can deceive, but physical mass tells the truth. Let your fingers verify the density. Keep all tones warm and muted to lock these materials together.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your material combinations by trusting how they behave in your hands.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette requires a strictly warm temperature. Build your heavy coats and tailored trousers using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2} as your base. Layer {core_colour_3} and {core_colour_4} underneath for silk shirting and cashmere layers. Establish a quiet undercurrent by introducing {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} through a full-grain leather bag or a small silk square. Treat the relief tone as a soft note used sparingly around the collar. Pass over icy electric blue, neon brights, and fleeting trend pastels. Avoid the trap of a head-to-toe dark monochrome outfit, which reads like an abandoned morning routine. Break up a solid block of shadow with a {core_colour_2} brushed wool overcoat, a {accent_colour_1} cashmere scarf, or a {core_colour_4} full-grain leather belt.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your shades by treating them as distinct tactical roles.",
