    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "Lead with close drape for your working foundation. Reject stiff tailoring. Select brushed wool and camel silk that contour gracefully without rigid padding. Allow quiet, matt textures to support this shape. Ground the look with a solitary warm metal accent at the wrist or collar. A tweed blazer bound for the dry cleaner gives no excuse to suspend your standards. Even the most utilitarian office piece must pass a physical inspection. Hold the material and crumple the sleeve. If it feels hollow, leave it on the hanger. Prioritise your tactile reality over any corporate dress code.",
      "sectionIntro": "Construct a professional wardrobe that firmly enforces your tactile baseline.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip to the dry cleaner does not suspend your standards (Frost)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In dim lighting, let close drape guide your choices. Visual details vanish in the shadows. Texture takes the lead. Reach for camel silk or rich toffee cashmere. Keep the finish matt and your metals warm. Rely on yellow gold to catch whatever low illumination exists in a darkened room. The baseline remains absolute. You demand the same tactile quality at a secluded table as you do in daylight. If a piece feels stiff, drop it. Let the weight of the fabric dictate your selection.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply your tactile rules rigorously when the lights go down.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip to the dry cleaner does not suspend your standards (Frost)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "A Tuesday morning trip to collect a prescription is a rigorous trial for your garments. Pick up that camel cashmere sweater and gauge the knit. Rely on density. While sight can be tricked, heavy warmth offers undeniable proof. If the weave feels stiff, put it back. Build a self-contained world. Apply your baseline equation without exception: close drape + quiet undercurrent + one warm point of light. A rich toffee silk scarf tucked into a brushed wool coat does the work. Fasten the collar with a small, matt gold pin. Protect your inner environment from the noise outside.",
      "sectionIntro": "Maintain rigorous exactness in your daily routine.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip to the dry cleaner does not suspend your standards (Frost)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your metal strategy requires a warm foundation. Anchor your choices in {metal_1} and {metal_2}, reserving {metal_3} strictly for discreet functional elements like concealed zips. Highly polished hardware shatters the harmony of muted textiles. Harsh glare distracts from close drape. Fix this by demanding exclusively brushed and matt textures. Banish {excluded_finish} entirely. Assess every buckle and zip by hand. Solid hardware pulls the fabric firmly down to the body, while hollow alloys ruin the structure. Choose components with tangible heft to maintain a quiet undercurrent.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hardware is structural first and decorative second, demanding absolute physical substance.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "When choosing stones, rely on density and a muted finish to ground your attire. Lift the piece to evaluate it. True value registers in the palm. If a {stone_1} or {stone_2} feels hollow, put it back. You require heavy, opaque materials that reinforce your quiet undercurrent. Ensure every finish is entirely matt. High-gloss surfaces appear abrupt and jarring against warm, soft textiles like brushed wool. Keep the texture brushed. This ensures the hardware aligns seamlessly with your close drape and restrained tones.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate stones as structural anchors by testing their mass and surface finish.",
      "tests": [
