  "venus_virgo__moon_leo__earth_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "precise fit + athletic space + one meticulous detail",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on precise fit + athletic space + one meticulous detail.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Your sensory compass is physical equilibrium. Look for garments that distribute their weight evenly across your shoulders and hips. If a piece restricts or requires constant adjustment, drop it immediately. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight doesn't. Base your choices on the strict equation of precise fit + athletic space + one meticulous detail. Picture a tailored trouser cut with enough room in the thigh to sprint, paired with a dense knit crew neck, finished with a heavy, engineered watch case at the wrist.\n\nBuild your wardrobe slowly to ensure every new item links smoothly to the rest. Deploy it fast on the day. Keep your temperature entirely neutral, anchoring your choices in matt surfaces and a muted presentation. Apply the treaty test to every prospective purchase. Ask yourself if the garment forces you to barter your range of motion for a sharp outline. If you must negotiate terms with the seams just to sit down, the piece fails. Choose architecture that supports your balance.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish your mechanical baseline and learn the strict rules of engagement for your physical equilibrium.",
      "tests": [
        "the treaty test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Build your foundation on fabrics that guarantee a precise fit while providing athletic space. Pick up any garment and apply the stretch-and-release check. Grasp the cloth and pull gently in opposing directions. If it fights back with rigid resistance, drop it. Let your fingertips gauge the mechanical give of the weave. Choose {texture_good_1} for shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation. Rely on {texture_good_2} for close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement. Seek {texture_good_3} for trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day. Deploy {texture_good_4} for lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little, letting one meticulous detail anchor your matt, neutral uniform.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every material by how it reacts to physical tension.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Crisp cotton poplin",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "shirting with clean architectural boundaries and pure separation"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine ribbed merino",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "close-to-body base layers with sharp lines and easy movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Worsted wool",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "trousers that drape cleanly and resist creasing through a long day"
        },
        {
          "name": "Technical nylon",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "lightweight mobile outerwear that blocks wind and weighs little"
        },
        {
          "name": "Lightweight gabardine",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "transitional jackets with rigid structure and no heavy drag"
        },
        {
          "name": "Matt silk",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "a frictionless fluid layer added without bulk"
        },
        {
          "name": "Crisp linen",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "breathable separation over fluid drapes in warmer weather"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Reject materials that collapse under tension. Execute the knuckle check. Grip the material in both fists and pull outward. If {texture_bad_1} sags or loses its snap, leave it on the hanger. A precise fit requires absolute structural integrity. Cloth that stretches out of shape cannot maintain required boundaries. Pay attention to {texture_bad_2}. If it feels slick or greasy between your fingers, it will trap heat and drape weakly. You need cloth that holds its own architecture. If it feels flimsy or hollow in your grip, drop it outright.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to identify the materials that will actively sabotage your silhouette.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Take the fabric in both hands and apply firm outward pressure. The material must offer immediate resistance. Let your grip measure the density. A fitting room reflection might promise structural integrity, but the friction against your skin reveals the absolute truth. Seek out {sweet_spot_keyword_1} layered heavily against {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. You require this physical drag to lock down a precise fit while preserving enough athletic space for unrestricted movement. Anchor the combination by introducing {texture_good_1}. Keep every surface matt and muted. Ground the garments in a strictly neutral temperature, punctuated only by cool metal hardware.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your texture pairings around physical friction and structural resistance.",
      "tests": [
        "the two-hands test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Keep your overall temperature neutral. Build your foundation with {core_colour_1} as your dark base. Rely on {core_colour_2} and {core_colour_3} for your main blocks. Bridge them with {core_colour_4}. Deploy {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} as a single deliberate strike. Allow a soft note used sparingly to provide relief. Beware the wardrobe pendulum. Do not isolate your garments into a strict utility month followed by a fluid, draped month. Force a dialogue instead. Keep one rigid piece and one giving fabric in every combination to secure your athletic space. Leave neon brights, glitter finishes, and sugary pastels on the rail. Grab the garment and test the dye against your own hand. A matt cotton poplin reveals the true depth of the colour under harsh store lighting.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat your palette as a toolkit, measuring every shade by how it builds a complete garment.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Graphite",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft stone",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
