      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the seesaw: one month all floaty gauze, the next all crisp utility",
          "fix": "re-weave instead: keep one item from the other hand in every outfit, always"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At work, precise fit takes the lead. Anchor your presentation with a worsted wool blazer cut exactly to your shoulders. Build the supporting layers around this rigid structure. A crisp cotton poplin shirt must provide enough athletic space across the back to let you move without tension. Keep the temperature strictly neutral, relying on soft stone and oatmeal. Finish the combination with one meticulous detail, perhaps a brushed steel watch or a matt silver collar bar. Always enforce your baseline rule for shape. Your desk hours demand absolute definition. Pinch the cloth at your ribs. Trust the seam to hold its rigid line.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the structure of your working hours.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "When the lights drop in a quiet room, shadows swallow fine patterns. Your leading formula element here is a precise fit. Let the geometry of the garment handle the work while visibility fades. Rely on a fine ribbed merino jumper in soft stone or an oatmeal worsted wool trouser. Keep the colour palette entirely neutral. Avoid high shine. Choose matt silver hardware that catches a single glint of ambient light. Judge these pieces with your hands first. Dim lighting obscures weak construction, but the dense drape of heavy fabric always tells the truth. If a garment collapses into a formless pile the second you step into the dark, leave it behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the structural demands of low-light proximity.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Treat a mundane run for paracetamol exactly as you treat a scheduled event. Your standard does not suspend itself because the destination is a supermarket aisle. A midnight drive to the petrol station still demands a deliberate shape. Build every outfit around your core law. That constant anchor is precise fit + athletic space + one meticulous detail. Pull on worsted wool trousers and a crisp cotton poplin shirt in soft stone or oatmeal. Check the drape in the mirror to ensure the cut functions with your actual anatomy. Fasten a silver belt buckle with a matt finish to ground the strictly neutral palette. Do not slip into shapeless lounge clothes just because the hour is late.",
      "sectionIntro": "Maintain strict visual discipline across your most ordinary routines.",
      "tests": [
        "a midnight petrol station run still deserves a silhouette (Cinder)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Lock your hardware strategy into a cool, neutral dominance. Restrict every zip, watch case, and buckle strictly to {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3}. Banish antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal outright. These elements inject unwanted historical clutter into a present-tense system. Demand clean surfaces and reject any {excluded_finish} finish. Pick the hardware up before committing. An online photograph can hide cheap alloys, but the sheer, undeniable mass resting in your palm proves the grade. When your metals carry genuine weight, they perfectly anchor a precise fit and safeguard the athletic space your garments require to perform.",
      "sectionIntro": "Select hardware that anchors your wardrobe through absolute density and cool-toned discipline.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Treat your hardware as the final anchor of a precise fit. Start with clarity and density. Look for {stone_1} and {stone_2} that absorb neutral light with a matt, muted finish. Pick up the ring or pendant before wearing it. A faceted cut can distract the eye, but the unyielding heft of real stone confirms its worth. Trust this tangible weight as your primary guide to quality. Next, assess the setting. Clear away visual noise entirely. Anchor your stones in polished silver, platinum, white gold, or mirror chrome. These cool surfaces maintain the clean, athletic space you demand from your garments.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones and metals like precision equipment.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Pick up the item. Evaluate its literal gravity. A genuine {metal_1} watch case or piece of jewellery should drop into your palm with immediate force. If it feels hollow or unexpectedly light, leave it on the shelf. Ignore forced vintage finishes like tarnished brass and beaten copper. Those manufactured patinas create unnecessary friction against your neutral garments. Anchor your look with slick, unblemished white gold or mirror chrome instead. This heavy, clean hardware complements the precise fit your garments require.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every piece of hardware by its physical weight before you wear it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Your clothing establishes a precise fit and secures the required athletic space. Hardware and textiles provide the one meticulous detail that resolves the geometry. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Apply the departure check. Stop at the hallway mirror, scan the outfit, and take off the final item you put on. Begin your selection with silk scarves in a neutral tone. Look for a matt crepe de chine square or a slim band. Rub the fabric between your thumb and index finger. It must grip slightly, lacking any slippery gloss. Trust your hands. Your fingertips give an honest assessment of quality where an appealing pattern might mislead you. Weight and friction dictate the reality of the piece.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the final components of your style formula by applying strict limits and trusting your tactile instincts.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Silk scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "crepe de chine square or slim band, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Keep fine jewellery grounded in a precise fit against the collarbone. Look for a thin chain and small drops cast in brushed silver. The surface must be completely matt. Pick up the metal. Let the chain fall through your fingers and trust the cold density of it. Solid links prove their value through their downward pull. Anchor this muted metal against a fine ribbed merino sweater in oatmeal. Run the threshold assessment before heading out. Check your reflection to see if the silver demands attention. If the drops reflect any sharp glare, take them off. Your accessories must sit quietly inside your neutral wardrobe.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your physical frame with deliberate hardware.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Fine jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "thin chain and small drops, brushed silver"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Select a small structured bag. Pick up a kid suede top-handle design finished with fine matt hardware in brushed silver. Trust your hands to check the density. The suede must feel thick, and the structure must support itself without sagging. Choose a neutral shade like ash grey or mushroom. Wear it close to the body to guarantee a precise fit against your hip. Before stepping out, perform the boundary scan. Scan your reflection from collar to shoe. If any hardware or texture demands attention over the whole, remove it.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your daily carry and rigorously test the final balance.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Small structured bag",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "kid suede top-handle, fine matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the last-look test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Anchor your structured tailoring with {recommended_pattern_1}. Let your fluid, moving layers carry {recommended_pattern_2}. Keep your pattern contrast adaptable. Rely on tonal, low-contrast weaves for daily wear, and scale up the graphic weight when the context shifts. Trust your own sight to calibrate this distance. Hold any new jacket out at arm's length. It should register as a calm, flat block of neutral colour. Bring it right up to your face. The exact geometry of the yarn must only reveal itself now. This optical trick supports a precise fit, ensuring the cloth never overpowers the shape. Protect your required athletic space by keeping visual noise strictly controlled. Pass over anything that shouts. Drop {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2} straight back on the rail.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every woven motif to strict visual scrutiny before letting it near your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Hang your {recommended_pattern_1} on a door and take three large steps back. At this distance, the surface must blur into a calm, matt block of neutral colour. Walk forward. The design should only resolve into clear shapes when you are near enough to touch the cloth. If the motif projects across the room, leave it on the rack. You require garments that deliver a precise fit and preserve your athletic space, rather than overwhelming your frame with visual noise. A loud print ruins the muted finish you need. Let the subtle weave draw the eye only when someone is standing right next to you.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the distance test to weed out loud prints and protect your muted palette.",
      "tests": [
        "the arm's-length test (calm even texture far, rewarding weave close)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_taurus__moon_taurus__air_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "structure + sensory comfort + a touch of quiet depth",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on structure + sensory comfort + a touch of quiet depth.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Let your hands do the sorting before you even look in a mirror. Feel the weight of the weave and note how the fabric settles over your palm. You are building a wardrobe methodically over time. Curate pieces at a measured pace and rely on the physical sensation of quality to guide you. If a seam pulls awkwardly or a finish feels harsh against your skin, drop the item immediately. Trust your physical revulsion as your ultimate compass and walk away empty-handed. Looks lie. Weight does not.\n\nYour baseline equation is structure + sensory comfort + a touch of quiet depth. Picture a heavy overcoat with precise shoulders worn over a dense knit top, finished with a pair of sturdy flat shoes. The silhouette holds a crisp shape while the interior layers remain entirely forgiving. Every element feels matt and warm to the touch. Let the cut do the heavy lifting. Leave excess detailing behind and focus entirely on how the fabric moves with your frame. Avoid anything that restricts your breathing or requires constant adjustment.",
      "sectionIntro": "Commit this baseline blueprint to memory and use it to interrogate every garment you consider.",
      "tests": [
        "trust your gut and walk away"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your wardrobe relies on fabrics that deliver shape alongside deep physical ease. Look for warm, matt finishes that absorb light to give your garments a touch of quiet depth. Test every piece manually. Squeeze the sleeve of a {texture_good_1} jumper. It must compress heavily and spring back instantly. Run your fingers over {texture_good_2} accessories. They need to feel pliable enough to mould to your grip. Inspect the lapels of a {texture_good_3} coat. They must support clean lines without rigid stiffness. Against the skin, rely on the fluid weight of {texture_good_4} for movement. The rule is strictly tactile. Let your fingertips override the label. If the fibres fight back against your grip or emit a high, artificial squeak when rubbed together, put the hanger back.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise the materials that build your wardrobe before you even look at a label.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Cashmere",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "knitwear and winter layers that compress and bounce back"
        },
        {
          "name": "Full-grain leather",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "bags, shoes, and belts that mould to your life and patinate"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed wool and tweed",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "tailored coats and blazers that hold clean lines for years"
        },
        {
          "name": "Silk",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "blouses and linings that add fluid, effortless movement"
        },
        {
          "name": "Suede",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "shoes and accessories with quiet matt texture"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fine merino",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers soft against the skin and resilient through washes"
