  "venus_sagittarius__moon_pisces__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "expansive colour + blurred edges + one theatrical finish",
    "closing": "Your style guide is a map of your own instincts, built on expansive colour + blurred edges + one theatrical finish.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Trust your hands. If a fabric feels stiff or noisy, leave it on the hanger. Seek garments that feel warm to the touch and drop with a heavy, fluid grace. Your baseline equation is expansive colour + blurred edges + one theatrical finish. Picture a tailored trouser lacking a harsh front crease. Pair it with a soft woven top that drapes seamlessly across the shoulder. Anchor the look with a single oversized, sculptural accessory. The shapes remain yielding, but the resulting silhouette stays balanced and deliberate.\n\nBuild your collection slowly. Acquire pieces with ruthless precision over time, but dress quickly each morning. Before you step outside, run the host test. Look in the mirror and ask if your garments make you feel ready to welcome people into your own home. If a rigid collar or a tight waistband makes you feel like an anxious guest striving to impress, discard the item immediately. You require a matt, grounded certainty to function properly. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. Looks lie. Weight does not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this foundational logic to evaluate new garments and test your daily outfits.",
      "tests": [
        "the host test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Your foundation demands materials that anchor warm tones and create blurred edges. Introduce the melt test to every potential purchase. Crush the fabric in your fist. If it springs back with rigid resistance, put it back. True quality must yield and dissolve entirely into your palm. Look for {texture_good_1} in slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Choose {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Rely on {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Finish with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. Hunt down these specific fibres to guarantee a matt, grounded aesthetic.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your wardrobe from materials that submit completely to your touch.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed alpaca",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "enveloping winter coats and oversized cardigans"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fluid modal jersey",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers that follow the body without ever gripping it"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed cotton flannel",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "shirts and loungewear that feel like a remembered embrace"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Drop {texture_bad_1} immediately if it holds a rigid shape. Squeeze the sleeve and observe the release. A worthy material relaxes into soft, slow folds, whereas a failure snaps back into aggressive, sharp creases. Reject {texture_bad_2} entirely. It catches the light with a hard glare that shatters a muted, matt palette. Your clothing relies on expansive colour. Stiff synthetics break that harmony. They refuse to drape and create harsh shadows that clash with a warm aesthetic. Examine the garment with your eyes closed. If the textile feels like dry paper or cold plastic, leave it behind.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to reject materials that fight your body.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Pair {sweet_spot_keyword_1} against {sweet_spot_keyword_2} to establish your base. Evaluate {texture_good_1} by testing its pliability. It must yield and collapse back into soft folds rather than fighting your grip with rigid creases. Your aesthetic thrives on this yielding quality, grounded in warm tones and punctuated by one theatrical finish. Look for matt surfaces that absorb the ambient room lighting. Rely on physical touch to reject unyielding, structured synthetics.",
      "sectionIntro": "Mastering your signature tactile pairing requires strict physical testing.",
      "tests": [
        "the melt test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Your palette runs strictly warm. Build your foundation with {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_2}, grounding them in the structural depth of {core_colour_3} and the natural anchor of {core_colour_4}. Deploy a single deliberate accent using {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2}. Rely on your relief tone as a soft note used sparingly near the face to break up heavy blocks. Beware the heavy earth sink. Layering dark muted tones, all matt and all heavy, will swallow you whole. Lift this density by placing a light {core_colour_1} piece near the jawline, adding a supple leather belt, or introducing your relief tone to create blurred edges between garments. Pass over stark optic white, harsh neon, and icy pastel.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your wardrobe in your precise colour geometry.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Bitter chocolate",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Dark mahogany",
          "role": "warm_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Blackened indigo",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep forest green",
          "role": "earthy_green"
        },
        {
          "name": "Burnt umber",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Washed black",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Burnt amber",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Rich cognac",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Misty taupe",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the all-earth sink: brown on olive on bark, all matt and all heavy, can swallow you whole",
          "fix": "lift it: an oatmeal cream layer at the collar, one piece of polished leather, or the washed blue relief"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At the desk, let expansive colour lead. Build an unbroken column of warm bitter chocolate or dark mahogany. Support this base by softening your garment boundaries. Select heavy silk crepe that falls over the collarbone instead of a stiffly ironed cotton shirt. Provide one theatrical finish at the wrist using mixed metals in a matt finish. Test your downtime moments against this standard. A midday dash down to the street for an espresso does not demand dropping your balanced column for a shapeless fleece. Maintain your deliberate silhouette even when stepping away from the screen. Let physical touch judge the fabric every morning. Give preference to textiles with significant density that pool rather than peak to preserve those blurred edges.",
      "sectionIntro": "Translate your daily instincts into a professional context without compromising your core foundations.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close quarters, blurred edges must lead the approach. Rely on heavy silk crepe in warm bitter chocolate to soften the boundary between fabric and skin. Lamplight turns rigid lines harsh. Keep the drape intact without introducing sharpness. Evaluate the garment by watching how it falls across the shoulder. It must settle perfectly matt against the body. Choose dark mahogany boiled wool over structured outerwear for late dinners. Evaluate the textile closely. If the surface catches the indoor glow with a hard glare, put it back. Mix silver and gold chains without hesitation, ensuring every piece remains completely muted.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master low lighting and close proximity through strict tactile choices.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "Do not surrender your silhouette to stiff nylon or shapeless jersey just because you are standing in a queue at the local pharmacy. Rely on tactile instincts to find the correct daytime garments. Reach for heavy lambswool or a warm, matt washed silk shirt in bitter chocolate. These materials drop with gravity. Mix gold and silver rings freely against a dark mahogany sleeve. Maintain your strict standard across every ordinary hour. Your absolute requirement remains expansive colour + blurred edges + one theatrical finish. If a jacket feels rigid across the shoulders or demands constant adjustment, leave it behind. Your daily clothes must support physical action without friction.",
      "sectionIntro": "Build your daily foundation with the same rigorous standard you apply to a formal occasion.",
      "tests": [
        "a trip for milk does not require abandoning your silhouette (Tide)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "You have absolute freedom to stack and combine {metal_1}, {metal_2}, and {metal_3} across your jewellery and structural hardware. The only rule is texture. A highly polished, reflective metal cuts too sharply across soft, warm palettes and disrupts an expansive colour story. Prevent this jarring effect by anchoring your pieces exclusively in matt and brushed textures to maintain your blurred edges. Reject any piece with a {excluded_finish} treatment. Scrutinise every clasp and link physically. Lift the item and register its drop in your palm. Visuals can deceive, but actual gravitational heft confirms the quality. A heavy, brushed buckle grounds your garments, while hollow, lightweight components ruin the balance.",
      "sectionIntro": "Take strict control of your hardware, ensuring every piece grounds your aesthetic rather than distracting from it.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Look for dense, opaque specimens like {stone_1} and {stone_2}. These ground your warm wardrobe without catching sharp light. A faceted gem acts like a mirror and looks entirely jarring next to your muted garments. Choose cabochon or raw cuts to preserve your blurred edges and keep the outfit cohesive. Always verify the stone before committing to it. Hold it directly to check its density. A glossy surface often deceives the buyer, but true physical mass tells the strict truth. A proper mineral feels resolutely heavy in the hand.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your garments with hardware that respects your muted aesthetic rather than fighting it for attention.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Lift the {metal_1} or {stone_1} from the counter to measure its mass. If a piece feels hollow, leave it behind. Avoid highly polished finishes entirely. A bright mirror shine cuts sharply through soft layers and breaks the cohesion of your warm tones. Select matt and brushed hardware to preserve your blurred edges and provide one theatrical finish to your expansive colour choices.",
      "sectionIntro": "Test your hardware before it touches your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "Set your foundation with expansive colour. Soften your silhouette with blurred edges. Complete your formula using one theatrical finish. Accessories act as this final stage. Restrict yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Implement the one ember test. Treat your bitter chocolate and dark mahogany garments as a dark hearth. Your accessory must function as the single glowing coal radiating warm heat. Turn to handbags first. Demand full grain leather and brushed matt hardware. Reject rigid plastics and high shine clasps. Run your thumb across the material. The dense drop of genuine hide grounds an outfit through sheer physical weight.",
      "sectionIntro": "Use accessories to anchor your wardrobe with deliberate weight and clear intention.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather, brushed matt hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Source scarves in washed silk or fine lambswool. Keep the surface strictly matt to anchor blurred edges. Use the one ember principle for every piece before purchasing. Hold the textile up to natural daylight. You must locate a single spark of warm colour glowing deep within the dark mahogany or bitter chocolate fibres. If the dye looks completely flat and dead, drop the item. A successful accessory absorbs ambient glare while projecting its own internal heat.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master your secondary layers by scrutinising how their materials absorb and hold light.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor the waist with a strip of heavy full grain leather secured by a completely matt buckle. Mix your metals without hesitation. Pair aged silver and oxidised keepsake jewellery directly against warm dark mahogany fabrics to protect those blurred edges. Rely on the physical mass of these materials. Evaluate a piece by its solid drop in your palm rather than its reflection in the shop glass. Complete the look by checking your final theatrical finish. Step back from the mirror and remove any item that flashes too brightly. Strip away the excess hardware until you leave just a single point of heat to anchor the expansive colour base.",
      "sectionIntro": "Finish the look by selecting hardware that grounds your silhouette without breaking its boundaries.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "medium full-grain leather, matt buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "aged silver, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the one-ember test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Demand subtle tonal shifts. Tailored pieces take their pattern directly from the yarn. Look for {recommended_pattern_1} woven physically into the cloth. Fluid garments rely on printed {recommended_pattern_2} or {recommended_pattern_3}. Anchor your expansive colour with these careful selections. Let blurred edges govern how the shapes interact, ensuring the line between foreground and background dissolves seamlessly. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. Subject any patterned piece to the firelight test. Bring the garment near a warm lamp and watch the tones. The print must deepen and glow under the bulb. If the motif turns stark or flattens out, return it to the rail. The way a physical fabric absorbs warm lamplight provides the only true measure of its quality.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate every motif against a strict low-contrast rule, selecting structural weaves for tailoring and tonal prints for fluid layers.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "Take your {recommended_pattern_1} away from the shop window to examine it under realistic lighting. Hold the garment next to a low lamp or a lit candle and observe how the motif behaves. The print must deepen into the shadows and gain a rich, warm resonance. Reject anything that turns flat or stark without artificial glare. You need expansive colour that softens into the dark rather than fighting the gloom. A brightly lit mirror often deceives the buyer, but the way a dyed yarn reacts to dim lighting proves its actual worth.",
      "sectionIntro": "Subject every motif to a strict lighting check before you buy it.",
      "tests": [
        "the firelight test (deepen and warm by lamplight)"
      ]
    }
  },
