    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Tailored garments pull their pattern strictly from the structural weave. Fluid pieces take theirs from subtle tonal variations in the dye. Keep all contrast low. A pattern must never arrive before the garment itself. To guarantee quiet grandeur, subject the piece to the lamplight test. Hold the fabric under a dim, warm bulb. The motif must recede and melt into a soft texture. If the print remains sharp, reject it entirely. Seek out {recommended_pattern_1} and {recommended_pattern_2} to construct your wardrobe. Pass over {avoid_pattern_1} and {avoid_pattern_2}. True hidden depth relies on these tonal weaves, giving your pieces life without raising their volume.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat pattern as an architectural detail, an extension of the fabric itself rather than a surface decoration.",
