    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "Your approach to metal operates on two strict tracks. Reserve {personal_metal_1} and {personal_metal_2} for jewellery resting directly against your skin. Their warm tones anchor your palette. For clasps, zips, and buckles, rely entirely on {structural_metal_1} and {structural_metal_2}. This separation provides clean structure without competing focal points. Every piece of hardware must pass a physical check. Lift the component. Vision deceives. Mass reveals the truth. Reject hollow alloys. Highly polished finishes catch the light sharply and distract from understated garments. Fix this error by sticking exclusively to matt and brushed textures to keep the outfit cohesive. Ban {excluded_finish} entirely.",
      "sectionIntro": "Establish strict boundaries between the metals resting on your skin and the hardware securing your garments.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "Weigh the piece in your palm to test its heft. Judge the stone by its sheer gravitational pull. Seek out dense, opaque options like {stone_1} or {stone_2} that hold warmth inside rather than flashing it outward. A highly polished stone or a glaringly reflective metal creates a jarring distraction against your muted fabrics. Anchor your hardware with completely matt or gently brushed finishes to maintain visual cohesion. These materials provide the firm structure required to ground the inherent softness of your garments. Keep the scale contained and entirely deliberate.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your stones by their density and their capacity to absorb ambient light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Assess closures and chains by their pull against your fingers. Hardware must carry enough literal gravity to anchor the softness of your garments with grounded structure. A flimsy zip betrays the whole outfit. Watch out for blinding reflections. An overly gleaming edge clashes against warm, muted fabrics, breaking the visual cohesion. Stick strictly to brushed or matt {metal_1} to keep the integration seamless. Evaluate every buckle or clasp independently. If the item lacks substance, discard the entire garment.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply this physical test to evaluate hardware before bringing it into your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "high-shine, polished chrome silver looks sharp and distracting next to soft muted colours",
          "fix": "stick to matt and brushed textures to keep the look cohesive"
        }
      ]
    },
    "accessory_1": {
      "text": "You have anchored your garments in structure and softness. Now, use accessories to deliver a touch of quiet depth. Limit yourself to one or two strong pieces per look. Subject every item to the heirloom test. Assess whether the object possesses the dense, warm permanence required to be passed down decades from now. Rely on the uncompromising reality of physical materials. Apply this strict standard to handbags. Demand full-grain leather or thick suede. Inspect the metal closures and reject anything highly polished. Accept only matt brushed hardware. Genuine density confirms quality.",
      "sectionIntro": "Apply the same strict standards to your accessories as you do your garments, forcing every piece to earn its place through sheer physical weight.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Handbags",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "full-grain leather or thick suede, matt brushed hardware"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the heirloom test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_2": {
      "text": "Treat your scarves as the final layer of your self-contained presentation. Choose generous squares of matt silk or lengths of fine warm wool. These textiles bridge the strict lines of tailored structure with pure, tactile softness. Scrutinise the hand-rolled edges and the density of the weave. Grip the material and verify it possesses the integrity to outlive you, remaining immaculate enough to wrap in tissue for the next generation. If the textile feels flimsy or the surface catches too much light, abandon the purchase. Seek only muted, substantial fabrics in deep camel or warm ochre that ground your silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your textile accessories by demanding absolute material integrity.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Scarves",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "generous silk or fine wool, matt"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the heirloom test"
      ]
    },
    "accessory_3": {
      "text": "Anchor your waist with wide full-grain leather belts fastened by a matt brushed buckle. The thick hide provides necessary structure against the softness of your woven garments. For keepsake jewellery, seek out a deep stone set in oxidised silver or aged brass. These heavy metals ground your warm camel layers. Before you purchase anything new, apply the legacy check. Close your eyes and measure the metal against your skin. Ask yourself if it mimics a hefty artifact uncovered in a wooden box inherited decades ago. If the item feels hollow and shines like thin foil, drop it and walk away.",
      "sectionIntro": "Anchor your silhouette with heavy objects that finish the shape.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Belts",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "wide full-grain leather, matt brushed buckle"
        },
        {
          "name": "Keepsake jewellery",
          "role": "accessory category",
          "useCase": "deep stone set in aged silver or brass, oxidised"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the heirloom test"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_narrative": {
      "text": "Establish structure in your tailored garments by sourcing pattern entirely from the physical weave of the cloth. Allow pieces that deliver softness to carry {recommended_pattern_1} or {recommended_pattern_2}. Keep all internal contrast strictly low and tonal to preserve a muted finish. Always verify the underlying base remains warm. Ignore {avoid_pattern_1} entirely. Pass over anything resembling {avoid_pattern_2}. Subject every new print to the field test. The motifs must merge into a continuous surface, mimicking the natural texture of the ground observed from a high hill. Trust your fingers to evaluate the woven cloth before your eyes assess the print. Sight deceives. Touch remains absolute.",
      "sectionIntro": "Dictate your prints with strict boundaries to build texture rather than demanding attention.",
      "tests": [
        "the field test (settle into a natural texture like ground seen from a hill)"
      ]
    },
    "pattern_tip": {
      "text": "To execute the field test, drape the garment across a chair and step back. Blur your focus until {recommended_pattern_1} loses its distinct boundaries. The print must settle into a continuous, organic surface. Picture the terrain seen from a high ridge. You want the overall effect of a warm, distant landscape. If the shapes pop out or refuse to blend, reject the piece. You require a pattern that provides internal structure without sacrificing visual softness. It must retreat into a unified texture rather than projecting outwards. Trust your own perception to recognise this shift. If the motif reads clearly from across the room, bypass the garment.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the field test to evaluate any pattern before you bring it into your wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the field test (settle into a natural texture like ground seen from a hill)"
      ]
    }
  },
  "venus_libra__moon_virgo__water_dominant": {
    "coreFormula": "balanced proportions + honest fabric + one refined touch",
    "closing": "Trust your body to map the boundaries of your style, building every outfit through balanced proportions + honest fabric + one refined touch.",
    "style_core": {
      "text": "Evaluate every piece by its physical restriction. Trust this physical instinct as your ultimate compass. A garment must yield to your movement without losing its structure. Build your wardrobe methodically over the long term, but dress fast each morning. Let your daily uniform drift by mood and practical requirement. If a jacket pulls across your back when you reach forward, put it back on the rail. Assess the flight test before every purchase. If you cannot jog through a crowded transit hub and sit in a cramped seat without the fabric strangling you, reject it immediately.\n\nYour daily construction relies on a strict baseline. Memorise your core equation: balanced proportions + honest fabric + one refined touch. Anchor this concept in reality. Picture a heavy wool jumper sitting flush at the waist of straight denim jeans, finished with a sleek leather ankle boot. The silhouette provides room to breathe while the dense fibres hold their shape. Keep the overall temperature cool across your entire collection. You are combining practical utility with deliberate execution. Trust your hands when inspecting seams and hems. Looks lie. Weight does not.",
      "sectionIntro": "Memorise this foundational logic before you bring a single new garment into your house.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_good": {
      "text": "Evaluate a material by how it falls. Execute the drop test. Pick the garment up by the shoulders and release it onto the bed. Watch the descent. You need materials that settle into balanced proportions instead of freezing into rigid shapes. Anchor your cool colours using {texture_good_1} for slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight. Seek out {texture_good_2} for jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight. Choose {texture_good_3} for dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth. Build your outer layers with {texture_good_4} for unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge. An honest fabric performs instinctively. Rely on the priority list below.",
      "sectionIntro": "Train your hands to recognise honest fabric before you even look at the garment tag.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Washed silk",
          "role": "rank 1",
          "useCase": "slips and blouses softened until the sheen turns to candlelight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Cloud-soft lambswool",
          "role": "rank 2",
          "useCase": "jumpers and cardigans that shelter without weight"
        },
        {
          "name": "Heavy silk crepe",
          "role": "rank 3",
          "useCase": "dresses that trace the body with fluid, hidden depth"
        },
        {
          "name": "Boiled wool",
          "role": "rank 4",
          "useCase": "unstructured protective coats that stay soft at every edge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed alpaca",
          "role": "rank 5",
          "useCase": "enveloping winter coats and oversized cardigans"
        },
        {
          "name": "Fluid modal jersey",
          "role": "rank 6",
          "useCase": "base layers that follow the body without ever gripping it"
        },
        {
          "name": "Brushed cotton flannel",
          "role": "rank 7",
          "useCase": "shirts and loungewear that feel like a remembered embrace"
        }
      ],
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_bad": {
      "text": "Grab {texture_bad_1} and crush it in your fist. If it squeaks, holds sharp creases, or lacks a cool touch against your skin, drop it instantly. Your body demands materials that yield. Throw {texture_bad_2} across a table to gauge its density. If the item catches the air and drifts slowly downwards, leave it on the rack. Quality drops fast, but cheap blends float. Your style relies on one refined touch, a finish you can never achieve over a foundation that feels stiff or synthetic. Squeeze every fibre. If the textile fights your grip, walk away.",
      "sectionIntro": "Learn to recognise imposters before they touch your skin.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "textures_sweet_spot": {
      "text": "Merge {sweet_spot_keyword_1} with {sweet_spot_keyword_2}. Take an item cut from {texture_good_1} and bundle it into a ball. Ask yourself if it can survive ten hours crammed into a cabin bag and emerge wearable. If the cloth crushes permanently, leave it on the rail. An honest fabric works hard and recovers fast. Contrast a matt finish against a faint sheen to build visual depth. Keep the temperature cool. You need surfaces that perform under stress without demanding delicate care.",
      "sectionIntro": "Master the interaction between two surfaces to lock in your working wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "the flight test"
      ]
    },
    "palette_narrative": {
      "text": "Observe the shade in natural light. Your spectrum demands a cool temperature to establish visual clarity. Build the foundation using {core_colour_1} and {core_colour_3} as base neutrals. Keep {core_colour_2} ready as your structural dark neutral, and rely on {core_colour_4} to act as your white substitute. Bring in {accent_colour_1} or {accent_colour_2} solely as a single deliberate accent. Deploy the relief tone strictly as a soft note used sparingly. Bypass hard black, harsh neon, and heavy earth brown entirely. Watch for the hard shell trap. When life speeds up, you might start reaching for armour, technical jackets, and stiff utility layers. Swap the shell for a brushed cotton layer that moves just as fast and breathes easily. Combine this yielding garment with one refined touch to complete the outfit. Ensure balanced proportions govern the silhouette.",
      "sectionIntro": "Maintain absolute discipline over your hues, selecting only shades that serve your structure.",
      "rankedItems": [
        {
          "name": "Dove grey",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Inky navy",
          "role": "structural_dark"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep teal",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Oyster",
          "role": "white_substitute"
        },
        {
          "name": "Pale aqua",
          "role": "cool_base"
        },
        {
          "name": "Smoked mauve",
          "role": "warm_cool_bridge"
        },
        {
          "name": "Faded rose",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Deep berry",
          "role": "accent"
        },
        {
          "name": "Soft oatmeal",
          "role": "relief"
        }
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "the hard shell: reaching for armour, technical jackets, and stiff utility layers when life speeds up",
          "fix": "swap the shell for a brushed cotton layer that moves just as fast and holds you besides"
        }
      ]
    },
    "occasions_work": {
      "text": "At the office, let balanced proportions lead. A heavy silk crepe blouse tucked into wide-leg trousers sets a clear structural standard. Let an honest fabric act as the primary support system for this shape. Choose washed silk or boiled wool for their tactile integrity rather than delicate finishes. Finally, bring in one refined touch to complete the profile. Before commuting, apply the ripple test. Ask yourself if you would put on these exact trousers to dash out for the Sunday paper in the pouring rain. If they demand precious treatment or restrict movement, take them off. Office clothing must offer the exact same yielding comfort as your most familiar weekend jumpers. Stick to cool tones like dove grey and deep teal to set a calm visual baseline.",
      "sectionIntro": "Frame your office choices by establishing a clear structural hierarchy.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_intimate": {
      "text": "In close, low-light settings, your honest fabric takes the lead. When shadows obscure shape, touch supersedes sight. Layer deep teal washed silk under a dove grey cloud-soft lambswool cardigan. Mix your jewellery freely to catch the dim lighting. Pair a matt platinum band with polished gold hoops and a dark sapphire pendant. Apply the comfort baseline. Evening attire requires the identical gentle standard of ease as your weekend wear. If heavy silk crepe feels restrictive during dinner, discard it for the night. Keep your palette firmly cool and maintain your balanced proportions. Trust physical sensation over your reflection. If a garment pinches, leave it in the wardrobe.",
      "sectionIntro": "Navigate intimate evening occasions by prioritising physical sensation over the mirror.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "occasions_daily": {
      "text": "When you step out to run a sudden errand, demand the exact same baseline of care as you would for a formal meeting. Pull on a dove grey boiled wool jumper rather than a fleece zip-up. Slip a matt platinum band onto your finger before grabbing the house keys. Maintain your baseline. Your routine relies on a strict equation. Always execute balanced proportions + honest fabric + one refined touch every single time you cross the threshold. Let cool tones anchor these choices. Pair straight denim with a deep teal washed silk shirt for a sudden trip to the local pharmacy. Do not suspend your rules for mundane tasks.",
      "sectionIntro": "Treat a routine Tuesday morning with the exactitude you bring to a scheduled appointment.",
      "tests": [
        "a rainy Sunday paper run deserves the same gentle standard (Ripple)"
      ]
    },
    "hardware_metals": {
      "text": "You hold total freedom to mix metals. Wear {metal_1} at your cuffs alongside a {metal_2} watch and a {metal_3} belt buckle. Blend highly polished elements with {excluded_finish} surfaces freely. Always test jewellery and hardware by picking it up in your palm. Vision deceives. Mass reveals the truth. A heavy, solid metal grounds your silhouette and ensures balanced proportions. Do not buy artificially aged pieces. Antiqued brass and hammered copper create visual clutter against a crisp wardrobe. Fix this by sticking strictly to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome. These clean, cool metals act as the necessary rigid counterpoint to an honest fabric.",
      "sectionIntro": "Hardware provides the rigid anchor point for your entire wardrobe.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_stones": {
      "text": "When adding gems to an honest fabric, let density dictate your choices. Hold every piece in your palm before you wear it. A heavy {stone_1} or a cold {stone_2} must feel like a grounded physical object in your hand. Steer clear of simulated vintage settings and faux-tarnish mounts. These elements register as historical clutter against a crisp, modern aesthetic. Set your stones in stark, unblemished alloys to keep the overall temperature cool. Mix these finishes freely across the body to maintain balanced proportions without looking rigid. Let the solid mass of a dense {stone_3} act as your one refined touch.",
      "sectionIntro": "Evaluate your gems by their physical density and how they catch the light.",
      "tests": [
        "pick it up: looks lie, weight doesn't (the pick-it-up weight test)"
      ],
      "traps": [
        {
          "failure": "antiqued brass, hammered copper, and artificially aged metal read as clutter against a present-tense style",
          "fix": "keep to polished silver, platinum, white gold, and mirror chrome"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hardware_tip": {
      "text": "Assess hardware solely by its heft. Pick up any {metal_1} or {stone_1} piece and gauge its weight. If a ring or clasp feels hollow, leave it on the shelf. You anchor your wardrobe with balanced proportions, so demand the exact same structural integrity from your accessories. Reject intentionally distressed surfaces and dull, oxidised chains. These textures register as visual noise against a cool palette. Instead, confine your selections to gleaming, unblemished items. When you build a foundation of honest fabric, your finishing details must be razor-sharp and perfectly clear.",
      "sectionIntro": "Lift the piece to understand its true value.",
      "tests": [
